<HEADLINE>
NASCAR DRIVERS, CREW CHIEFS PRAISE TMS, DEBATE GROOVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The DirecTV 500 brought out a record 12
cautions Sunday, but, for a change, no one left Texas Motor
Speedway blaming the track design.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good racetrack,'' said Larry McReynolds, crew chief
for the No. 31 Lowe's Chevrolet driven by Mike Skinner. ``It caught
a lot of slack the first couple of years, but the good thing about
it is those guys \RTMS officials\S responded to everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at this racetrack, as much as it is a little ways
away from home \RNorth Carolina\S, we need to be here two times a
year.''
</P>
<P>
   In a race that lasted 3 hours, 49 minutes, accidents eliminated
six cars and hobbled several others running at the end, including
those of Dale Jarrett and Jeff Gordon. But the track escaped
unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers were unanimous in attributing the dozen yellow flags, a
NASCAR Winston Cup season high, to ``one of those racin' deals.''
In other words, wrecks happen.
</P>
<P>
   TMS requires white-knuckle driving. Speeds at the 1.5-mile
superspeedway top 190 mph, leaving little margin for error.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of aggressive driving,'' said Jimmy Makar,
crew chief for the No. 18 Interstate Batteries Pontiac driven by
Bobby Labonte. ``Track position was so important that you couldn't
really give up anything, and I think people were just taking a
little more than they were giving. You can't do that here. It
doesn't take much to get yourself in trouble here, because you're
running so fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Drivers are split on whether TMS has created a second groove.
</P>
<P>
   The race set a track record with 29 lead changes among 17
drivers. Last year, there were 24 lead changes involving 11
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could run high or low and pass people on the outside. We've
never really been able to do that here before,'' said Terry
Labonte, driver of the No. 5 Kellogg's Chevrolet. ``It was pretty
much two grooves. The pavement is a little bit older, and it kind
of lets you have two lines.''
</P>
<P>
   But with only one Busch Grand National/Winston Cup weekend a
year, drivers said it will take some time before the pavement will
be broken in enough to allow passing on the outside, especially
between turns 1 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a one-groove track, but it's getting better,'' said
Todd Bodine, who drives the No. 66 Phillips 66 Chevrolet in the
Busch Series. ``It's going to take five or six years ... for this
place to get the groove more out to where the other grooves can
come in.''
</P>
<P>
   Drivers were ready to raise the white flag on TMS after the
first two years. They complained of dangerous turns and a slippery
surface.
</P>
<P>
   A $3 million makeover, which included repaving and redesigns of
Turns 1 and 4, has allowed drivers to shut up and race the past two
years. Owner Jack Roush, who has won two of the four Winston Cup
races at TMS, calls the track ``friendlier'' now.
</P>
<P>
   It also is faster.
</P>
<P>
   During the final few laps Sunday, race winner Dale Earnhardt Jr.
was running lap times that would have qualified him in the top 15.
That has prompted some to call for a slow down.
</P>
<P>
   At the sport's fastest tracks, Daytona and Talladega, NASCAR
mandates speed-reducing restrictor plates, which impede the flow of
air and fuel from the carburetor to the combustion chambers. Speeds
at TMS, Atlanta and Charlotte now rival those at Daytona and
Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten to the point now, even with the increased speeds,
that we can race here, and that's a much better feeling from a
driver's perspective,'' said Jarrett, the defending points champion
who finished 33rd Sunday. ``But I still say that here, as at a
number of other places, if we could somehow figure out how to slow
the cars down that we'll see even better racing yet.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
