<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE AT FIRST SIGHT FOR FANS, KAPLER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Gabe Kapler made connections Monday, some of
which went far beyond him putting wood to horsehide. By the fourth
inning, fans sitting in Home Run Porch were chanting, ``Juan Who.''
By the next inning, female fans were appreciative of Kapler for
something else. ``Nice butt,'' was their chant.
</P>
<P>
   Under the circumstances _ replacing Juan, and all _ the heir
apparent right fielder had the greatest debut in Texas Rangers
history, but as the legacy of Mr. Gonzalez tells us, there's more
to it than just crunching numbers or having masculine appeal.
</P>
<P>
   One game in a Rangers uniform and the 24-year-old Kapler opened
not only a new season but also a new era in Arlington by
immediately achieving something that eluded Gonzalez for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Gabe is loved by all.
</P>
<P>
   Introduce yourself with back-to-back home runs on the first
three pitches you see, and what else would you expect? OK, fine _
that's a natural response for those doubters who want to remind all
honeymooners that it's a long, long season.
</P>
<P>
   But then again, a refresher course in Gonzalez history should
not be necessary. For 10 years, Juan did what Kapler did Monday,
but at no time did he ever make an emotional connection with fans
at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The same paying customers who worship at the shin guards of a
Pudge Rodriguez treated Gonzalez like a beached jellyfish. They
poked at him with a stick. And Juan poked back. Ten years of this
made for a rather curious and uncomfortable relationship, almost
unheard of for a player of superstar status.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the way it was with Juan. And why over the long
haul it might be different with Kapler, even if his offensive
production is merely average, as opposed to the eruption Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry that much about expectations because I think I
know what the fans expect,'' said Kapler, following the Rangers'
10-4 victory against the White Sox before an announced Opening Day
house of 49,332. ``The fans come to see someone who plays hard, who
hustles, and who does little things to help the team win. I can
promise them that every game. That's one area where I will never
let down the team or the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   And yes, Kapler had given some thought to a two-home run,
three-hit, three-RBI kind of debut for the Rangers and a standing
ovation almost every time he turned around.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my wildest dream I thought about it,'' said Kapler,
smiling. But he also added, ``Maybe I didn't necessarily expect
this, but I do expect special things from myself. I have those kind
of goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates had witnessed that throughout spring training. As
had Rudy Jaramillo, the Rangers' hitting coach. Oates pulled aside
Kapler before Monday's opener to remind the newcomer that he could
``own'' all of right field at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Gabe that the way he plays the game, they will love him
out there,'' Oates said. ``He's just so gung-ho about everything.
I'm not so sure a bad day would have hurt him with the fans because
they could still see what he was all about. But to have this kind
of day, it will do nothing but boost Gabe.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two weeks of spring training, Kapler had been on
an offensive tear in Florida after a month and a half of extensive
bat instruction from Jaramillo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything Gabe did last season (in Detroit) he now does just
the opposite,'' Jaramillo said. ``We tore down his swing and his
mental approach to hitting, and started all over. That shows you
what kind of kid he is, that he immediately trusted me enough to
let that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapler's workload in Florida became immense because of the extra
hours put in with Jaramillo. ``But you can't ever give him too
much,'' Jaramillo said. ``He always wants more. He's a worker and a
hustler, and I really liked the way the fans fell in love with him
today. They saw the Gabe Kapler we've been seeing.''
</P>
<P>
   One press-box joke Monday centered on Kapler being part of the
Gonzalez trade with Detroit last November. ``Do you mean the
Rangers got five other players, too?'' But while pitchers Justin
Thompson and Francisco Cordero were listed as the key acquisitions,
it was Kapler who would be coming in to play the same position as
Gonzalez. And this after a somewhat disappointing rookie season
with the Tigers _ a .245 average with 18 homers and 49 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think today's game, to open this way, was huge for the
team,'' Kapler said, ``and Juan Gonzalez himself didn't have that
much to do with it. But there are the questions floating around out
there about how much offense we lost since last season, and how
much we could make up. So to come out today, and do this, that's
very motivational, in my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   It was like old times _ four home-run balls divided between
Kapler and Rodriguez accounted for seven of the runs. Pudge got
another MVP campaign started with a bang, while Kapler got a new
start in a new town after making a very positive impression in
spring training with everyone, particularly his new teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was curious how long it would take the fans to react to
Gabe,'' shortstop Royce Clayton said. ``As it turned out, the wait
wasn't long, was it?'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
