<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS' LATE-SEASON BLOOM TOO LATE FOR PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ If this is the second half of the season, then it comes
as no surprise that the Dallas Mavericks are making a mad dash
toward next season.
</P>
<P>
   In six of the past eight seasons, the Mavericks have posted a
better record in the second half of the season than they did in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks will carry a 17-15 record in the second half of
the season into Tuesday's 7:30 p.m. tilt against the Sacramento
Kings at Reunion Arena. By contrast, the Mavericks were 15-26 at
the midway point of this season. The Mavericks won't be going to
the playoffs for the 10th consecutive season.
</P>
<P>
   During last year's lockout-shortened season the pattern was
similar _ a slow start and a fast finish that ultimately gave
Mavericks fans false hopes going into the off-season. That includes
a 9-9 record after April 1 of a season that ultimately ended with a
19-31 record.
</P>
<P>
   This year five of the Mavericks' final nine games are against
teams that have qualified for the playoffs _ Sacramento, Portland,
Seattle, Minnesota and the Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   The other four games are against Denver, Vancouver, Houston and
the Los Angeles Clippers _ teams that have been eliminated from
playoff contention.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their seemingly annual reservations in the NBA Draft
Lottery, the Mavericks still have goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thirty-five-plus wins would be a good goal,'' guard Erick
Strickland said. ``Hopefully you'd like to win the rest of them,
but we got some tough games, so we've just got to stay mentally
tough.'' SWEET 16
</P>
<P>
   For a team that has never had a winning record on the road, the
Mavericks appear comfortable playing away from Reunion Arena this
season.
</P>
<P>
   With three road games remaining, the Mavericks have a 16-22 road
record, sixth-best in team history, and two victories away from
ranking fourth all-time.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 victories also is as many games as the Mavericks have won
on their own court.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's different, but we play well on the road,'' guard Erick
Strickland said. ``But even in the past we were in a lot of the
games on the road; we just couldn't win them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this year we've been able to close a little more than we
have in past and learn how to win through adversity. We know we're
not going to get many calls, but we've fought through that and just
found a way to win.''
</P>
<P>
   And about those 19 home losses?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy,'' Strickland said. ``But hey, that's just how it
is. Hopefully we can do better about that and finish the season off
strong.'' DAVIS PURSUES RECORD
</P>
<P>
   Hubert Davis said he doesn't care much about records, but he is
close to owning one.
</P>
<P>
   With nine games remaining, Davis leads the NBA in 3-point
shooting at 51 percent. The NBA single-season record is 52.4
percent, set during the 1994-'95 season by Steve Kerr of the
Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has made 79 of 155 3-pointers this season. If the
eight-year veteran hits 16 of 26 3-pointers or better, he will
break Kerr's record. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
