</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS ROUT EXPOS IN OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL -- The first thing the Dodgers did in the offseason was
create balance in the lineup. Lefty hitting Shawn Green fit the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   And the first thing the Dodgers did this season is show off that
balance.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dodgers' inaugural game under Bob Daly's watch, Kevin
Brown pitched six effective innings and the middle of the order
drove in eight runs as the Dodgers opened the season with a 10-4
beating of the Montreal Expos in front of a soldout crowd of 51,249
at Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros led the offensive assault with his second career
grand slam, which highlighted a five-run seventh inning. Gary
Sheffield had two hits, including a two-run triple, and Todd
Hundley homered and had three hits. Shawn Green's lone RBI came on
a walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have guys on base it makes your job a lot easier,''
Sheffield said. ``When you start doing that right off the bat, it
relaxes you for later on in the season. It was a great game for us,
and I hope the cycle of not scoring runs for Kevin is changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson wanted to jump into his newfound deep
bullpen, and he plucked out newcomer Terry Adams to pitch the final
three innings and record the save. Dustin Hermanson took the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like when a plan comes together,'' Johnson said with a wide
grin. ``(Brown) wanted to go back out there and kind of fought me
on it, but I had a fresh pen. It made it easier when we added (five
runs) on. He said, `You got the right guy out of there.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, there were handshakes and congratulations in the
manager's office from Daly. And not many were thinking about
Montreal's Vladimir Guerrero, who had a pair of homers and four
RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to keep him happy,'' Johnson said. ``I've got to
keep him happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Games like this is the way to do it. There's plenty of folks who
road the disastrous wave of the last two seasons in the clubhouse
to point out that 161 games remain, but this opener offers hope
because of the way the Dodgers' offense pounced on mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos made four errors that led to four unearned runs, but
the Dodgers still needed a pair of key hits.
</P>
<P>
   In a four-run fifth inning, a pair of throwing errors led to
Sheffield's triple and a 5-1 lead. Two innings later Expos third
baseman Michael Barrett, with two errors in hand, failed to make a
play on Mark Grudzielanek's grounder a few feet to his left. It
went as a base hit, but put reliever Anthony Telford in a game.
After a Sheffield single and Green walk, Karros smacked his grand
slam down the left field line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We capitalized on their mistakes,'' said Karros, who passed
Steve Garvey and is second on Los Angeles' all-time homer list with
212. ``We were given a lot of opportunities. Hundley had a big hit,
Sheff had two big hits, Green got the walk and I got the hit. It's
not like we came out and rolled them over. We were given a lot of
opportunities, but when you're given opportunities you have to take
advantage of them and we did.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the eight RBI, the No. 3 through No. 6 spots in
the order were a combined 6 for 17, hit two homers and scored four
runs. The offensive production was exactly what the club hoped for
when it sent Raul Mondesi to Toronto in exchange for Green in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Last season the imbalanced Dodgers failed to reach double digits
in runs until the 22nd game of the season. They reached the mark
only 11 times.
</P>
<P>
   And don't think the striking power and balance of the middle of
the lineup doesn't comfort the pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier to make mistakes and get by with bad pitches
and not pitch great when you have an offensive effort behind you
like that,'' said Brown, who struck out seven and allowed three
runs in improving to 3-2 on opening day. ``You definitely want to
pitch better, but I'll take the win. I think we're a lot better
balanced this year from the standpoint we've got a healthy of Todd
Hundley from the left side being a threat. We have Shawn Green,
who's real well-rounded, and last year we were a little right-side
heavy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
