<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT IN WESTPORT DEATHS OFFERS TO PLEAD GUILTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ It has been almost a year since police found
in a house five men shot to death at different times and left where
they fell.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Beach was arrested a day after that, on April 6. Police
said Beach murdered the men from March 28 to April 1, and he soon
faced the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Now Beach, 57, has offered to plead guilty and serve life
without parole _ if prosecutors will drop the death penalty. His
lawyers filed the offer Feb. 28 in Jackson County Circuit Court.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday defense lawyer Cynthia Short said that from the start,
Beach had been ready to pay for his crimes and wanted to plead
guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under this plea agreement,'' she noted, ``he would die in the
penitentiary.''
</P>
<P>
   County Prosecutor Bob Beaird said he had no plans to drop the
death penalty. Beaird said he would meet this week with dozens of
family members of the victims and inform them of the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Most family members have supported execution, Beaird said. Two
reached by telephone Monday declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Brandy Sales, the daughter of victim Kenneth Gulley Jr., said
that she would think about the offer but that this week was a
difficult time. The anniversary of the death carries its own pain,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The murder victims were Gulley, 45, the stepson of Beach's
brother; Michael Davis, 32, Beach's stepson, who lived at the
house; Mark Nelson, 28, who also lived at the house; Christopher
Conrad, 27, of Overland Park; and Jerry Nickerson, 56, of Kansas
City. Beach knew all five men.
</P>
<P>
   Police entered Beach's rented house at 4275 Jefferson St. in the
Old Westport neighborhood after one of Gulley's brothers, Dennis
Gulley, went to the home to find his brother, broke in and found a
body. Before Beach was captured the next day, police said, he
phoned a man and told him Dennis Gulley would be killed next.
</P>
<P>
   Officers arrested Beach at a hotel near his home, and he has
been incarcerated since then. He's charged with five counts each of
first-degree murder and armed criminal action.
</P>
<P>
   Jury selection is scheduled to begin Aug. 30. Beach's lawyers
have said in court filings that they will use a mental illness
defense if the case goes to trial.
</P>
<P>
   During the period of the murders, they wrote, Beach twice tried
to kill himself with alcohol and pills. He also drove into the
country with a hose before backing out of a plan to kill himself
with car exhaust, lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Several months before the murders, Beach started behaving
strangely, defense lawyers wrote, but ``no one appreciated the
depth of his depression or the depth of his irrational thinking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
