<SLUG> BC-BLOCK-ADVERTISING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
H&AMP;R BLOCK SHOPS AROUND FOR ADVERTISING AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ H&AMP;R Block Co. is putting its $100 million
global advertising account up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   The account has been at Young &AMP; Rubicam, Chicago, since 1996,
but the departure of two key executives at that agency who oversaw
the Block account triggered the decision to initiate an agency
review.
</P>
<P>
   To help in the process, Block has hired Los Angeles consultant
Select Resources International to help find the right agency.
</P>
<P>
   Recent Select Resources clients include Hewlett-Packard, BMW and
Starbucks. Block and Select Resources hope to announce the agency
by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   David Byers, who has been Block's chief marketing officer for
about 10 months, said as the company had aggressively made
acquisitions and diversified, it began seeing a need for a new
marketing partner.
</P>
<P>
   In the last couple of years the company has spent billions on
acquisitions, giving it 94 financial services centers across the
United States, mortgage services, and one of the 10 largest
accounting firms in the United States. And having spent billions on
its acquisitions to become a full-service financial services
company, Block now plans to dramatically boost its global
advertising, from about $30 million worldwide last year to $100
million this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a number of issues that we were working on with all
the Young &AMP; Rubicam companies...but I don't know that it was moving
along at the pace we needed,'' Byers said.
</P>
<P>
   Then the worldwide creative director on the account and the
worldwide account director left, sparking the decision to move
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Breen, president and chief executive officer of Young &AMP;
Rubicam, Chicago, said he was disappointed by Block's decision.
Although the agency had been invited to participate in the review,
Breen said a final decision hadn't been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young &AMP; Rubicam helped H&AMP;R Block achieve four consecutive
record-breaking years for its business,'' Breen said. ``They've
been happy with our efforts....In fact, the current work we've done
for them has effectively repositioned the company in a stylish,
contemporary and relevant way, and has been well-received by both
consumers and the media.''
</P>
<P>
   On the staffing issues, Breen said that although the agency
regretted losing two key persons, more than 70 others also worked
on the account.
</P>
<P>
   But Gary F. Prestopino, an analyst with Tucker Anthony Cleary
Gull in Chicago who follows H&AMP;R Block, said the company had too
much at stake to risk anything but a full-bore marketing effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've seen a number of changes and a positioning of the
company as a total financial services provider using the tax client
as leverage to sell those products, so it probably makes a lot of
sense to take a step back and ask, `Is there a better
mousetrap?' &UR; '' Prestopino said.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's fairly common for a new head marketing person to
initiate an agency review soon after joining a company, Byers said
that wasn't the case here.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the intent had been to make a change when I came in,''
Byers said, ``I'm aggressive enough that we would have made that
change immediately.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
