<HEADLINE>
MIAMI COUNTY, KAN., PLANNERS TO HEAR DEVELOPMENT PROPOSAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUCYRUS, KAN. _ The Miami County, Kan., Planning Commission will
hear a proposal tonight to turn 10,000 acres near Bucyrus, Kan.,
into a planned development to protect it from haphazard growth.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Osborn, whose company Osborn Properties owns about 5
percent of the property, is proposing the plan. The idea, Osborn
said, is to create a plan that would bring orderly growth to an
area of a county that is growing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about preventing sprawl by controlling where growth
goes and where the density is,'' said Osborn, who recently
presented his ideas to Miami County commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   The plan marries two new planning concepts, Osborn said. Around
the unincorporated community of Bucyrus, the plan calls for using
new urbanism, putting community and retail development within
walking distance of homes.
</P>
<P>
   In the areas outside Bucyrus, the plan would incorporate ``rural
by design,'' a concept that tries to preserve the rural feeling in
a housing development.
</P>
<P>
   That is achieved with lot setbacks of 100 feet or more,
incorporating walking and biking trails instead of standard
concrete sidewalks and eliminating a lot of curbs and gutters that
define suburban areas and create drainage problems downstream,
Osborn said. The plan also calls for keeping 40 percent of the
space undeveloped and keeping property lines from reaching streams.
</P>
<P>
   Osborn, whose family owns several parcels of land in Miami
County, is the son of Jim Osborn, who helped found Home Office
Reference Laboratory, now LabOne, and Osborn Laboratories. Both
companies do laboratory testing for insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   The county has done a good job of creating zoning regulations
that favor development around the towns in the county like Paola
and Louisburg, Osborn said. But development will eventually come to
the Bucyrus area. Instead of having something that looks just like
a south Johnson County development, the proposal would give Miami
County the chance to develop something that may not exist anywhere
in the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While his company owns only a small part of the property, Osborn
has explained his idea to owners of some of the larger land pieces
within the 10,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consensus is we need a plan to have controlled
development,'' Osborn said. ``We know eventually development will
come here.''
</P>
<P>
   The presentation tonight is to gauge reaction from the planning
group to determine whether to proceed with the concept, Osborn
said. The plan would require revisions in the county's zoning
regulations, and there is a need for extensive public discussion,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Davis, chief building official for Miami County, said the
area has become a desirable place to develop and the county's land
values are showing that. He said some of the county's residents
worry about the area losing its rural nature.
</P>
<P>
   Osborn believes his plan would create growth that is sensitive
to those feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it doesn't happen right away, at least we would be
preserving the area with a good plan so when growth gets there, it
is not haphazard,'' Osborn said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
