<SLUG> BC-AWG-LABOR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSOCIATED WHOLESALE GROCERS CONTINUES OPERATIONS DURING LAYOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, MO. _ Associated Wholesale Grocers Inc. continued
operating its distribution centers Monday, using outside companies
as the Teamsters union kicked its boycott into gear.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was the second day since Associated laid off about 640
warehouse and transportation workers at its Kansas City, Kan.,
distribution center. Nearly 700 employees in Springfield, Mo., also
were laid off after a three-year Teamsters contract expired Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   An Associated official said he expected Kansas City, Kan.,
warehouse operations, run now by CS Integrated (Kansas) LLC, to be
normal later this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``As of (Monday), this is a 2-day-old company in the
warehouse,'' said Jerry Garland, Associated's executive vice
president of marketing. ``We have 450 new employees in the
warehouse, many of whom are still learning the job. We believe, by
the middle of this week, we'll be back on schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   A Teamsters official said pickets monitoring the trucks leaving
Associated's distribution center said deliveries fell far short of
normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a typical Sunday night and Monday morning, you'll have 150
to 200 trailerloads leaving AWG,'' said Jim Williams, recording
secretary of Teamsters Local 955. ``Our people counted 34
trailerloads leaving during that period.''
</P>
<P>
   A CS Integrated spokesman said he expected the normal number of
loads to be shipped out by the end of Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a little bit behind and delayed,'' said Hal Leddy, a
spokesman for CS Integrated, based in New Jersey. ``But I'm
expecting that from here on, day by day, things will be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Leddy said CS Integrated was still taking job applications. The
company is operating with new hires, temporary workers and 85 to 90
former Associated employees.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Davidson, Local 955 president, said those former
Associated employees were not workers who lost their jobs this past
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of our members is still out and reporting for picket
duty and handbilling,'' he said. ``If they have former employees,
it's people AWG fired years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams of the Teamsters union said operations were not as
normal as Associated and CS Integrated were indicating. Several
trucks that left the distribution center returned 20 minutes later,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would mean that they're leaving AWG empty, because you
can't run a load in 20 minutes,'' Williams said. ``They're trying
to make it look like they're operating normally.''
</P>
<P>
   Garland denied that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard that rumor, but I can assure you that any trucks
leaving AWG have groceries in them,'' he said. ``I don't think we'd
be quite that naive as to return a truck 20 minutes later with the
same trailer number.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been reports that truck deliveries to some Associated
stores have been several hours late. There also have been scattered
reports of Associated-supplied stores in the area being out of
certain items because of a ``warehouse shortage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that has anything to do with what's going on at
AWG,'' Garland said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, however, that retail grocery sales reportedly were
strong late last week and over the weekend. Part of that was
attributable to concerns over Associated's outsourcing plans and
dispute with the Teamsters, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Associated, a cooperative with 850 stores in 10 states, supplies
Price Chopper, Country Mart, Sun Fresh, Apple Market, Thriftway and
Hen House stores in the Kansas City area. An official with Four B.
Corp., which operates more than two dozen area grocery stores
supplied by Associated, could not be reached for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Teamsters continued picketing Associated's
distribution centers in Kansas City, Kan., and Springfield,
contending that more than 1,200 employees have been locked out. The
company said it did not consider the situation a lockout because
those employees were given layoff notices two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said Local 955 had four pickets at Associated's two
entrances at its Kansas City, Kan., facility. There are others
there in support, without picket signs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The union Monday sent members to start handbilling eight area
stores supplied by Associated, seeking customer support. Williams
said that effort would expand this week to more stores.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred former Associated employees Monday filed for
unemployment benefits. The Kansas Department of Human Resources
used the union hall of United Auto Workers Local 31 near General
Motors Corp.'s Farfax plant.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the waiting period for getting benefits was three
weeks. The weekly benefit is slightly more than $300, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 0033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
