<HEADER>
A6438 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CLINTON-CHINA-SFCHRON     04-04 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS WTO WOULD AID FREEDOM IN CHINA
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ President Clinton, arguing that America must reject
``irrational attachments to the animosities of yesterday,'' pushed
strongly for Congress to approve the normalization of trade
relations with China in a speech Monday before a trade-friendly
gathering of Silicon Valley leaders and centrist Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want America's economy to continue to grow, and if you
want your country to continue to be a force for peace, and freedom
and prosperity ... we have to be willing to shoulder our burden for
the future,'' Clinton told a crowd of about 300 Democratic
Leadership Council members, business and political leaders,
including Gov. Gray Davis, and eBay CEO Meg Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   ``And ironically,'' he said, ``we will be one of the greatest
beneficiaries by doing what is right for China and the rest of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The president delivered his speech at the futuristic Tech Museum
of Innovation in San Jose _ part of a two-day fund-raising and
political trip to the Bay Area. Granting China permanent normal
trade relations status before its entry to the World Trade
Organization would benefit American workers and the cause of
freedom in China, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do this, 20 years from now we will wonder why we ever
had a serious debate about it,'' Clinton told the audience, which
gave him a warm reception. ``If we don't do it, 20 years from now
we'll still be kicking ourselves for being so dumb.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's push came as the White House announced that 200
high-tech heavyweights _ including CEOs of Silicon Valley giants
such as Sun Microsystems, Sybase, Nortel Networks and Qualcomm _
have signed a letter expressing their strong support for a
U.S-China trade pact, calling it ``an absolute priority'' for their
industry.
</P>
<P>
   They were joined by a bipartisan group of 42 governors _
including Davis _ who Monday also urged congressional approval of
the trade measure. Both Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive
GOP nominee for president, and his brother Jeb Bush, the Florida
governor, also signed their support for the measure.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., also announced her support of
normal trade relations as the best way to create more American jobs
and ``bring about freedom'' in China.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress refuses to normalize trade relations, China could,
under WTO rules, refuse to grant the same market access to U.S.
companies that it gives to everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech leaders fear this would give competitors in Europe and
Asia a huge advantage in one of the world's largest markets.
</P>
<P>
   The president's choice of a high-tech venue for his high-profile
appeal on the China trade issue was no coincidence. The wishes of
tech executives _ who have pushed hard for more open trade with
China _ have held increasing sway on Capitol Hill, where the
industry has dramatically increased its political donations _ and
its clout.
</P>
<P>
   And the president, who has visited the Bay Area twice this year
to collect technology donations, picked up $1 million in campaign
contributions for the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee
Sunday night at a South Bay fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the president's intense political lobbying effort
this week was not aimed at Republicans, who generally support
opening China trade _ but at a number of House Democrats who
maintain concerns about labor's opposition and human rights abuses
there.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told tech leaders that the more than 270 trade
agreements signed by the United States in the past seven years have
contributed to economic boom in the country.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged ``the trade issue has become symbolic about
people's general unease about globalization,'' including issues
such as child labor and abuse of workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow, these trade agreements have become a lightning rod
for everybody's dissatisfaction with everything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The vote by Congress ``is on an agreement that lowers no
American trade barriers, lowers no American tariffs, grants no
great access to China to any part of the America economy,'' Clinton
said. But Chinese tariffs ``will fall by more than half over five
years in every sector, from telecommunications to automobiles to
agriculture,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, China will agree to play by the same
trading rules that we follow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that ``China is a one-party state, that it
does not tolerate opposition, that it still denies its citizens the
fundamental rights'' of freedom of speech and religion, Clinton
said the trade pact is ``the most intelligent thing we can do to
increase the chances that China will become more open, more
democratic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the answer is to allow them in,'' said Clinton, ``and
to let liberty spread from within.''
</P>
<P>
   The president noted, for example, that the number of Internet
addresses alone in China is expected to boom to 20 million this
year. ``We know how much the Internet has changed America ...
imagine how much it will change China,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton said the United Status must ``continue to push China
in every way we can to improve and observe human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   But the president warned there would be dire implications should
Congress turn down the trade agreements with China.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main consequences would be to hurt America economically
and to dramatically strain our relations with China at a time when
we need to maintain a positive ability to impact their conduct,''
he said, pounding the podium, adding the trade pacts are critical
``to get the leaders in that country to imagine the greatness of
their country in future terms, not yesterday's terms.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
