<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OWL-ENDANGERED-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENVIRONMENTAL GROUPS PETITION TO LIST CALIFORNIA SPOTTED OWL
AS  ENDANGERED
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By GLEN MARTIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Claiming that efforts to protect the California
spotted owl have failed abysmally, a coalition of environmental
groups is petitioning the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service Tuesday to
list the reclusive deep-woods bird under the U.S. Endangered
Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   If the owl is listed, it could greatly reduce logging in
California, and it would also restrict other activities in forested
areas of the state, including development, livestock grazing,
recreation and mining.
</P>
<P>
   The California spotted owl, native to the Sierra Nevada and
southern California's coastal mountains, is a kissing cousin of the
northern spotted owl, which is found in the coastal ranges of
northern California, Oregon, Washington and British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The northern spotted owl, listed as threatened by the U.S. Fish
and Wildlife Service in 1990, was the subject of an epic battle
between environmentalists and the logging industry. Ultimately, the
listing resulted in timber harvest reductions in some national
forests.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists said federal protection for the California
spotted owl is overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were about 6,000 northern spotted owls when they were
listed,'' said Noah Greenwald, a forest ecologist with the
Albuquerque-based Center for Biological Diversity, one of the lead
groups in the coalition. ``By best estimates, there are only around
2,000 California spotted owls left.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service will now have 90 days to
determine if a listing warrants consideration. If the agency
chooses to consider the petition, it will undertake a one-year
review of the owl's status, then decide whether or not to list it.
</P>
<P>
   There are three subspecies of spotted owls. Along with the
northern and the California varieties, there is also the Mexican
spotted owl, which lives in Arizona, New Mexico and northern
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   All are virtually identical in appearance: relatively large,
round-headed owls with spotted breasts that live in old-growth
timber and subsist on rodents.
</P>
<P>
   All three owls have declined in numbers across their range.
Research has indicated that logging of the birds' favored
old-growth habitat has contributed to the downturn.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to avoid a listing for the California owl _ and the
concomitant economic effects it would have _ the U.S. Forest
Service issued ``interim guidelines'' in 1993 for managing national
forests known to harbor the bird.
</P>
<P>
   But three studies, two conducted by the Forest Service and one
undertaken by a Humboldt State University ornithologist, concluded
that owl populations have declined significantly since the interim
guidelines were adopted.
</P>
<P>
   Greenwald said owl populations have declined between 7 and 10
percent in the Lassen, El Dorado and Sierra national forests.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Watson, the California and Nevada regional director for the
Wilderness Society, an environmental group that originally endorsed
the Forest Service's interim rules, said his organization now
supports a listing under the Endangered Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guidelines were a step in the right direction, but a lot
of time has passed and a (permanent protection) plan has yet to
emerge,'' he said. ``You can't wait around forever. A petition is
warranted.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson said that the petition may goad federal agencies into
adopting tough protections for the owl under a pending management
plan for the Sierra Nevada, obviating the need for a listing.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial foresters are condemning the petition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is more about a plea for fund-raising and
membership support for (the environmentalists') anti-forestry
campaign than it is about what is best for the California spotted
owl,'' said Chris Nance, a spokesman for the California Forestry
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Nance said a 1992 Forest Service study shows that California
spotted owls are well-distributed throughout their historic range.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, we have to be careful where we point fingers,'' he
said. ``In the eight years since 1992, logging in the West has been
reduced by 92 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   John C. Robinson, a wildlife biologist with the forest service's
California regional headquarters, said that owl populations have
declined by ``a statistically significant'' degree.
</P>
<P>
   However, said Robinson, it is unlikely that a single factor _
such as logging _ is wholly responsible for the drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably a number of reasons, including (loss of)
habitat quality, weather, and perhaps to a certain extent,
intrusion by barred owls,'' he said. (Barred owls are a species
from eastern North America that is invading spotted owl habitat.)
</P>
<P>
   Spotted owl numbers also go up or down in response to prey
availability, said Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   He also said there may have been some ``holes'' in the spotted
owl reports that are cited as supporting evidence for the petition.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, owls that may have moved out of their established
territories were counted as dead by the researchers, when (the
owls) may actually have been alive and breeding elsewhere,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 0037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
