<HEADLINE>
NATO TROOPS SEIZE A TOP SERB FACING WAR CRIME CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS with updates, revisions thruout.) 
 (rk) 
 By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands _ After years of criticism for not
bringing top war criminals to justice, NATO troops Monday arrested
Momcilo Krajisnik, one of the most important Serb leaders in the
Bosnian war, on charges of war crimes, including genocide.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said in announcing the arrest that Krajisnik, a
close ally of the Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic, was the
most senior of 39 war crime suspects now in custody. Diplomats have
described Krajisnik as a fanatic politician who sometimes equaled
Karadzic in power, and through his business deals helped finance
the ``ethnic cleansing'' campaign in the 1992-95 Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   Krajisnik was immediately flown to The Hague where he will stand
trial before the International Tribunal, which charged him with
every war crime in its statute for his role as a principal
strategist behind hundreds of civilian massacres. Conviction would
mean a maximum life sentence for Krajisnik, 55, who is expected to
enter a plea this week.
</P>
<P>
   Although his impending indictment was reported in the Serbian
press three months before it was handed up secretly in February, it
was not clear why French troops with the SFOR peacekeeping force
decided to arrest him now.
</P>
<P>
   But given the long-running failure of NATO forces to bring war
criminals to trial, Krajisnik clearly was not expecting his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and tribunal officials said Krajisnik was at his elderly
par- ents' home in Pale when French troops blew open the door with
explo- sives shortly after 3 a.m. Monday. They briefly detained his
parents, tied the hands of his two sons and hustled Mr. Krajisnik,
still in his pajamas, out the door.In New York, Richard Holbrooke,
the U.S. ambassador at the United Nations, said in an interview,
``This is possibly the most important day since the Dayton
agreement on Bosnia,'' adding that ``Krajisnik was a very important
person after all. He was the former co-president of Bosnia, he was
the head of the Bosnia Serb delegation at Dayton.'' Holbrooke was
the author of the Dayton peace accord on the Bosnian war in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The removal of Krajisnik from the country, which is long
overdue but couldn't happen until he was indicted, removes from
Bosnia the leading public opponent of the Dayton agreement. The
other opponent, Karadzic, has been in hiding for four years,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   During the talks in Dayton, Krajisnik drew attention for his
rig- id, separatist views and his opposi- tion to the accords. But
his arrest does not affect the accords, diplo- mats said, because
it was Slobodan Milosevic, then president of Serbia, who excluded
the Bosnian Serbs and signed for the Serb side.
</P>
<P>
   Following the arrest, the chief prosecutor for the tribunal,
Carla del Ponte, called once more for the cap- ture of Karadzic and
said the two men should stand trial jointly be- cause they were
charged with the same heinous crimes. The tribunal is clearly
pressing NATO to make that trial a reality by arresting Kara- dzic,
who was indicted in 1995 on charges of genocide.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment against Krajis-H nik listed some 40 towns and
vil- lages from where Muslims and Croats were driven by force. It
also listed hundreds people who were massacred. It also specified
11 pris- on camps where non-Serbs were de- tained and tortured,
executed or de- ported under orders from Kra-H jisnik and other top
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the war he was second only to Karadzic and shared command
over Bosnian military and police,'' said Paul Risley, the spokesman
for del Ponte. ``The decisions he participated in, resulted in the
deaths of thousands of Bosnians and in the deportations and ethnic
cleansing of hundred of thousands.''
</P>
<P>
   The pressure on NATO to arrest key figures accused of genocide
in the Balkans has been growing since last spring, after Louise
Arbour, then the international tribunal's prosecutor, began
complaining publicly about the lack of cooperation she had received
from Western governments.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Arbour began to receive the help she sought from
British, German and U.S. military intelligence agencies, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said that ``this puts pressure on everyone else, is a
strong warning, and a strong assertion of renewed determination by
NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Ponte, who succeeded Arbour, said the tribunals'
investigators have stepped up their work in turn, and expect to
bring as many as 50 more indictments of senior officials
responsible for crimes of genocide, murder and ``ethnic
cleansing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Del Ponte has intensified the demand on the nations of NATO for
intelligence support and military action against suspected war
criminals in the Balkans. She called Monday for those nations ``to
insist on the apprehension and surrender of all other indicted''
war criminals, and in particular Karadzic.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors' demands helped stiffen NATO's spine, U.S.
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Krajisnik, an executive of Yugoslavia's biggest power company
before the nation war, has long been Karadzic's political tool.
Dealing in arms during the Balkans war, he also played a shrewd
enough hand to emerge as the titular political leader of Bosnia's
Serbs in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Out of office since 1998, he still wielded political control in
concert with Karadzic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Krajisnik is a big fish,'' the State Department spokesman,
James Rubin, said in an interview Monday. ``And we expect his
arrest to rattle Karadzic's cage.''
</P>
<P>
   In Brussels, Lord Robertson, the NATO secretary general, warned
other war crimes suspects: ``The net is closing. It is time to turn
your- selves in.''
</P>
<P>
   Krajisnik held a series of polit- ical posts after helping
Karadzic found the Serb nationalist party known as SDS in the
1980s. As one of the SDS leaders, he became speaker of the Bosnian
Serb assem- bly and was a member of the Bosni- an Serb Security
Council. His roles gave him shared control over the military and
the police. He was Karadzic's top aide for much of the Bosnian war,
and after Karadzic was indicted publicly and could no longer have
an official function, Krajisnik succeeded him. Krajisnik served as
the Serbian representative in the post- settlement presidency of
the Bosnian Federation from 1996-98 without be- ing challenged by
the NATO-led peacekeeping troops that arrested him Monday.
</P>
<P>
   French officers were reluctant to  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  act
against prominent Serbs in and around Pale, in the zone French
forces command under NATO's ban- ner..
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one question being asked behind the scenes here was why
France suddenly agreed to capture a senior Bosnian Serb official.
Al- though most NATO personnel in Bos- nia deliberately avoided
encounter- ing indicted individuals until 1997, France held out
until recently. This prompted open talk among British and U.S.
military officials that France was pro-Serb and that the French
sector of Bosnia was a safe haven for indicted Serbs. Of the 18
NATO arrests made since 1997, the French military had arrested only
two low-level men, and only in the last three months.
</P>
<P>
   By some accounts here, several recently publicized incidents
point- ing to cooperation between French and Serbian intelligence
may have embarrassed Paris and brought the turnabout that led to
the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Dutch officials also said that del Ponte, an experienced and
tough prosecutor in Switzerland before joining the tribunal last
year, has made it a priority to enlist French cooperation. She has
called on sev- eral ministers in Paris recently. President Jacques
Chirac visited the tribunal here in February while on a state visit
to the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like the French at last may have pulled the plug on
wanted Serbs in Bosnia,'' said one Dutch official. ``Some even went
skiing in the French sector, but people must be getting quite
nervous over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, 70 suspects are known to be under indictment by the
tribunal; other sealed indictments may also exist. Of those
suspects, 39 are now in custody, including Krajisnik.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his critics in the region believe that Krajisnik's time
had come because he remained an im- portant obstacle to Western at-
tempts to make progress in the peace effort in Bosnia and allow
Muslim and other refugees to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found him to be the most per- sistent extremist and
xenophobic in- dividual with whom I had to deal,'' said Jacques
Klein, the head of the U.N. mission in Bosnia. ``He has this
xenophobic kind of ha- tred.''
</P>
</TEXT>
