<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 I DON'T SEE ANY STATUES OF LAWYERS  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thank God Willie Mays didn't whine that his statue wasn't big
enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Say Hey Kid, as it turns out, is a lot more gracious than
the Say Nay Kid.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney for the late Joe DiMaggio has threatened legal
action if San Francisco honors DiMaggio by giving his name to North
Beach Playground, where Joe played ball as a kid.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney, Morris Engelberg, is the Say Nay Kid. Even though
he's an old coot, he acts like an immature kid. He says Joe wanted
something bigger named for him _ the Bay Bridge or the airport.
</P>
<P>
   All Willie (Say Hey) Mays got was a large statue at the new
ballpark, and he didn't start talking about a lawsuit unless we
named that large pool of water next to San Francisco the Say Hey
Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Willie Brown and Supervisor Gavin Newsom, so far, are
caving in to the threats.
</P>
<P>
   What is this, Petaluma? This city can't afford to battle that
attorney twerp in court?
</P>
<P>
   And would the Great DiMaggio really have been offended to have
all those scruffy kids playing ball on Joe D Field?
</P>
<P>
   Memo to Mayor Willie and Gavin: Name the playground after Joe,
let his mouthpiece sue and expose himself to international
ridicule. If you don't, I'm going to sue the city for cowardice.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio got knocked to the dirt by about 1,000 chin-high
fastballs, and not once did he run whimpering to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   AND LITTLE STU Miller didn't whine when I referred to him in
Saturday's column as a diminutive lefty.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, the former Giants' pitcher once blown off the mound at
Candlestick, is a rightie.
</P>
<P>
   Honest mistake. In baseball, except for Stu, all little pitchers
are lefties. Bobby Shantz, Whitey Ford, Billy Pierce, Danny Boone,
Harvey Haddix. And all little lefties are crafty.
</P>
<P>
   But I should've known, since Miller is not Stuey and all small
crafty lefties have names ending in y.
</P>
<P>
   RECENT ITEM told of a male meter maid whose three-wheeler got
smacked by a bad guy in a stolen car, who also hit a taxi.
</P>
<P>
   In the account I got, the taxi driver chased the bad guy and
held him, then the bad guy's pals made threats, so cabbie let bad
guy go.
</P>
<P>
   In reality: Cabbie did nothing, while his  &UR; passenger  &LR; gave
chase. The passenger was a local financial writer, Jon Rhine.
</P>
<P>
   And as Rhine made the tackle and struggled with the bad guy, who
tried to bite him, at least a dozen bystanders did nothing. The
cabbie alertly kept the meter running, costing our hero an extra
$8.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that Rhine is a serial vigilante. He has chased bad
guys on at least three other occasions over the years. And never
once did anyone say so much as ``Thanks.''
</P>
<P>
   Yo, John: Thanks.
</P>
<P>
   TRAIN PAIN: My travel guru Seymour Seitz took the train to
Sacramento for the weekend, but come 8:40 Sunday morning, time to
return, no train.
</P>
<P>
   Mighty Amtrak was an hour late because the driver of the train
crew's pickup van forgot to spring forward.
</P>
<P>
   And a Caltrain ballpark special last Wednesday (ballpark preview
day) was a disaster _ overcrowded, chaotic, many near fights, etc.
Veteran conductor Jeffery Craig Papp tried to defuse the tension by
issuing apologies for the screwup of the Joint Powers Board.
</P>
<P>
   He announced that the train would be passing the JPB building,
``So here's your chance to moon 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   For his efforts, Papp has been suspended.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR TAX dollars at work: Contra Costa County bought disposable
cameras and gave 'em to homeless folk, then put the photos on
display, calling the exhibition ``Putting a Face on Homelessness.''
</P>
<P>
   One official said, ``They were really empowered by the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Blarney, says homeless advocate Susan Prather. Their faces are
all over the streets as it is. How about some real programs to get
their faces off the streets?
</P>
<P>
   So Prather mailed a camera to each county supervisor (except
one) and to two other key county officials. Her instructions: Take
a picture of yourself for an exhibit titled ``Picture the
Bureaucracy: Faces of the Hopeless and Ineffective.''
</P>
<P>
   STROLLING SUNNY Berkeley, Tom Turner stopped at a
cookies-and-lemonade stand run by two 8-year-old girls.
</P>
<P>
   When the group in front of Tom bought the last cookies, one of
the girls whipped out her cell phone. ``Mom, we've run out of
cookies. Can you bring some more?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
