<SLUG> BC-BREAST-CANCER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SIMPLE TESTS FOR BREAST CANCER MAY SPARE WOMEN CHEMOTHERAPY  &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Two little-known biological signposts of breast
cancer that can be picked up in simple tests may spare thousands of
women the need for debilitating chemotherapy, scientists reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A new study found strong evidence that the testing can predict
which women who have surgery and radiation to remove an early-stage
breast tumor should also be treated with cancer-killing drugs to
cut the risk of a recurrence. A recurrence often brings a much
worse prognosis than the initial cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted by a German research team, was outlined at
the annual meeting of the American Association for Cancer Research
in San Francisco, where the main focus Monday was on new ways to
gauge the risks of breast cancer. Breast cancer is the
second-leading cancer killer of American women after lung cancer
and the most frequently diagnosed form of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers said they hope to translate recent gains in
understanding the molecular workings of cancer into better clinical
practice, particularly by targeting therapies to patients who
really need it while sparing others the sometimes awful side
effects.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the 180,000 U.S. women newly diagnosed with breast
cancer each year have tumors of less than 2 centimers and the
cancer has not spread to the lymph nodes.
</P>
<P>
   For more than roughly 2 out of 3 of these node-negative
patients, surgery and radiation eliminate the cancer for good. But
the tumor comes back in the other 30 percent of cases _ forcing
many women to opt for so-called ``adjuvant chemotherapy'' as a
precautionary measure.
</P>
<P>
   But measuring levels of two cancer-related proteins _ known as
uPA and PAI-1 _ can dramatically sharpen the odds of making the
proper choice.
</P>
<P>
   The tests are inexpensive, costing about $20 in Europe, where
they are widely used. But authorities have had little evidence to
justify widespread use in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Tests come in different forms for different types of tumors.
Some are licensed for routine use in the United States already,
while others are expected to be cleared by the end of the year,
depending on how persuasive the evidence turns out to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new data is going to help a lot,'' said John Berryman,
manager for information services and regulatory affairs at
test-maker American Diagnostica Inc. in Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Lead author Anita Prechtl of the Technical University of Berlin
found that the two tumor markers ``consistently demonstrated a
correlation with both duration of disease-free survival and overall
survival.''
</P>
<P>
   She followed 556 patients for about 32 months on average.
Results showed that about 55 percent of patients could be
classified as having a very low risk of relapse based on low
measured levels of uPA, short for urokinase-type plasminogen
activator, and PAI-1, an inhibitor of the same protein.
</P>
<P>
   Fully 93 percent of the low-risk patients had no recurrence
without the cancer-killing drug therapy. Conversely, in those
patients found to have high risk for recurrence, giving a standard
form of chemotherapy reduced the probability of relapse by nearly
44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors emphasized that cancer may return after being absent for
many years, suggesting the need for a much longer study than what
was presented Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In other presentations, cancer researchers shed new light on
such diverse issues as the efficacy of radical surgery and the
everyday dietary risks of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   A research team at the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn., found
that surgically removing both breasts as a way to prevent cancer _
so-called bilateral prophylactic mastectomy _ reduced the risk
significantly even in women with genetic mutations that make them
especially vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Previous research had shown that prophylactic surgery can work
even if the woman has a family history of cancer, but Monday's was
the first to document a link to women with the genetic mutations.
</P>
<P>
   For those without the more frightening known risks, scientists
offered new grounds for making some fairly modest changes in diet.
</P>
<P>
   Research into the risks of eating meat have found that the
danger lies mainly in how it is cooked _ not in the meat itself.
That is because of probable carcinogens found in charred, well-done
meat cooked at high heat, such as on an open-flame grill.
</P>
<P>
   Data is not conclusive, and the dietary risks are thought to be
relatively modest overall even for frequent barbecuers. But given
the preliminary evidence, consumers might be wise to avoid eating a
lot of charred meat if they can help it, said Rashmi Sinha of the
National Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
