<SLUG> BC-CHRONICLE-SALE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TRIAL TO DETERMINE FATE OF CHRONICLE SALE  &HT;     By HARRIET CHIANG 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Hearst Corp. and former mayoral candidate
Clint Reilly agreed Monday to proceed directly to a full trial on
Reilly's legal effort to block the pending sale of The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which bypasses a hearing on a preliminary
injunction, means that Hearst's long-delayed purchase of the
newspaper will be postponed at least until after the full trial is
held in May.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement keeps in place a temporary restraining order
issued Thursday by U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker after he
expressed concerns about Hearst's imminent sale of the San
Francisco Examiner to the Fang family, which owns the Independent.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the preliminary injunction hearing on April 13, the
two sides will prepare for a trial beginning May 1 where the judge
will decide whether or not to permanently block the sale. The
nonjury trial is expected to last one to two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Shulman, one of Reilly's attorneys, said the agreement
came at the suggestion of representatives for Hearst and The
Chronicle after the judge granted Reilly's request to delay the
sale until the scheduled April 13 hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the judge's ruling last Thursday, I think they perceived
that they'd lose the preliminary injunction hearing,'' Shulman
said. ``They said they wanted an early trial, and we said fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Examiner Publisher Tim White said a trial will give the
newspapers an opportunity to present a full case to the judge. ``I
think, in some ways, it's a relief to have something definitive on
the horizon,'' said White, who will become publisher of The
Chronicle if the deal goes through.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least there's finally a finish line in sight for this
marathon,'' said Chronicle Executive Editor Matthew Wilson. ``We
want this over with so that we can focus all of our energies on
building an even stronger newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hearst and Reilly were hammering out an agreement to go to
trial, Reilly posted a $100,000 bond that had been ordered by
Walker to cover any losses that could be proven by Hearst and The
Chronicle if Walker's temporary restraining order were overturned.
</P>
<P>
   Walker's order came after an attorney for The Chronicle said
that the newspapers' owners were losing almost $100,000 in interest
income every day the sale is delayed.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's developments did not come as a surprise to antitrust
experts, who said that it is not unusual in cases involving a
pending merger to try to get to trial as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is money,'' said Laurence Popofsky, a veteran San
Francisco antitrust lawyer. ``And these transactions live and die
in the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than fuss with a preliminary hearing and still face the
prospect of a trial sometime in the future, the newspaper owners
can present their strongest case, call in witnesses and obtain a
decision in a relatively short period of time, Popofsky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of legal controversy where the premium for
the defendant is to get to the guts of right and wrong as soon as
possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge rules against Reilly, the newspaper owners say, the
sale of The Chronicle and Examiner will immediately be completed.
Reilly could file an appeal, but antitrust lawyers say there is no
guarantee that Walker or the appellate court would agree to further
delay the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good way to put a final end to this apparently endless
saga,'' said Stephen Barnett, a law professor at Berkeley's Boalt
Hall School of Law who has followed newspaper antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's lawsuit appears to be the only roadblock to the sale,
which would dramatically reshape the newspaper market in the Bay
Area. The Justice Department has already approved the acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   For 35 years, the San Francisco Chronicle and Examiner have
published under a joint operating agreement, which provides that
the two newspapers share business and publishing facilities but
maintain separate editorial staffs.
</P>
<P>
   After owners of The Chronicle put the paper on the market,
Hearst announced in August that it was purchasing the morning
newspaper for a reported $660 million and selling the Examiner,
which as the afternoon newspaper had seen its circulation plummet
to 108,968.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Hearst agreed to sell the Examiner to the Fang
family.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of its deal with Pan Asia Venture Capital Corp.,
a publishing company owned by the Fangs, Hearst has agreed to keep
the Examiner running and pay all costs during a four-month
transition period.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst will pay $16 million for the balance of the first year
and up to $25 million for each of the next two years to keep the
Examiner operating.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly filed his original lawsuit in January, arguing that
Hearst's purchase of The Chronicle would give the newspaper chain
an illegal monopoly on the local newspaper market. After Hearst
announced the sale of the Examiner to the Fangs, Reilly went back
to court seeking an order to delay the deal, which he called a
``sham.''
</P>
<P>
   In his pleadings, Reilly relied on expert witnesses who said
that it would take a subsidy of $250 million over five years to
keep the Examiner in business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
