<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENTER FIELD BELONGS TO ANDERSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- It took the trade of one of his best friends, but
Garret Anderson has found a home.
</P>
<P>
   From a personal standpoint, Anderson was sad to see Jim Edmonds
traded to the Cardinals last month. But from a professional
standpoint, it entrenched Anderson in center field.
</P>
<P>
   Last season Anderson played mostly center field, but only
because Edmonds was hurt. In 1998, Anderson played right field
because Tim Salmon was hurt. Before that he was a left fielder.
Without the trade of Edmonds this spring, Anderson would have seen
some time as the DH.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm an every-day player and not a DH,'' Anderson said.
``I'm glad I didn't have to go in there (to manager Mike Scioscia's
office) and say something. I know I've earned the right to play out
there every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that's different now is that the outfield
situation is settled. We don't have too many outfielders anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Not unless Edgard Clemente is considered a candidate to
eventually challenge for a starting spot. The Angels are high on
Clemente and his best position is center field. And all the teams
that previously were interested in Edmonds -- Mariners, Yankees,
A's -- still need an outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is a free agent at the end of the season, but the San
Fernando Valley native would like to stay in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely would like to stay here,'' Anderson said. ``But
it's not a decision I can make. It's more a matter of what the
front office wants to do. I learned at an early age, if they want
you, they'll find a way to keep you. If they don't want you, you're
gone. So I've learned to take care of my own business on the field
and everything else will take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The only question regarding Scioscia's opening-night lineup was
the catching spot, and he went with Bengie Molina over Matt
Walbeck. Molina became the Angels' seventh opening-night catcher in
eight seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bengie is going to get a little more of an opportunity early
on to see what he can do,'' Scioscia said. ``I talked to Matt and
he took it very well. He's a competitor and wants to play every
day. But he understands.''
</P>
<P>
   Molina got a chance to make Scioscia look good early in Monday's
game. The Yankees' Chuck Knoblauch led off the game, and tried to
steal second on the first pitch to Derek Jeter. Molina threw
Knoblauch out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real exciting for me,'' Molina, 25, said of getting the
opening-night start. ``It's a dream come true for me. There are no
words to describe it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels honored their all-time team in pregame ceremonies
Monday. Commemorating their 40th season, the fans voted on the
club's website, www.angelsbaseball.com.
</P>
<P>
   Those in attendance Monday were second baseman Bobby Grich,
third baseman Doug DeCinces, catcher Bob Boone, left fielder Brian
Downing, right fielder Reggie Jackson, right-handed starter Mike
Witt, left-handed starter Frank Tanana and reliever Troy Percival.
Those not in attendance were manager/shortstop Jim Fregosi, first
baseman Rod Carew, center fielder Jim Edmonds, right-handed starter
Nolan Ryan, left-handed starter Chuck Finley and DH Don Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Ramon Ortiz (small tear in shoulder tissue) threw in the
bullpen Monday and will make his next rehab start Thursday in
Arizona in a minor league camp game. He's on track to make his
season debut April 11. ... Pitcher Tim Belcher, recovering from
off-season elbow surgery, will throw a two-inning simulated game
today and again later in the homestand. Belcher expects to go on a
rehab assignme nt after the Angels begin their first road trip
April 14. ... Mo Vaughn, who held a players-only team meeting on
opening night last season and did the same in Boston while with the
Red Sox, did not hold a meeting before Monday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS VS. N.Y. YANKEES
</P>
<P>
   Time: 7:05 at Edison Field
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: FSN; KCTD-1540, KIK-FM-94.3, XPRS-1090
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: Kent Bottenfield, an 18-game winner and N.L. All-Star
last season with the Cardinals, will make his first regular-season
start for the Angels tonight against the Yankees' Roger Clemens.
Clemens has a career mark of 25-8 with a 2.49 ERA against the
Angels. Tonight's start will be Bottenfield's first against the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   -- Joe Haakenson
</P>
