<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6453 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-STANFORD-PRESIDENT-SF     04-04 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STANFORD-PRESIDENT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 STANFORD NAMES ENTREPRENEUR PRESIDENT  &HT;     By TANYA SCHEVITZ and BILL WORKMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ Stanford University officials named Provost
John L. Hennessy the campus' 10th president Monday, making him the
first entrepreneur and computer scientist to lead a major research
university and positioning Stanford to take a leading role in the
new economy.
</P>
<P>
   The founder of a seminal Silicon Valley microprocessor company
that apparently made him millions, Hennessy, 47, has also served as
chairman of Stanford's computer sciences department and dean of the
School of Engineering. He replaces Gerhard Casper, 61, who
announced last fall that he would step down after eight years as
president to return to teaching.
</P>
<P>
   Hennessy, who has been at Stanford since 1977, acknowledged that
he does not have a smooth road ahead of him when he takes the post
on September 1.
</P>
<P>
   His appointment comes only days after a federal jury in San Jose
concluded that a former Stanford University medical school
researcher was fired in retaliation for her complaints of sex
discrimination and awarded her $540,000. He must also mop up after
the failed merger of Stanford's hospital with the University of
California at San Francisco that was dissolved on April 1 after
racking up huge losses.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Hennessy has been increasingly depicted as
sensitive to the issues of women on the faculty. As provost, he has
already initiated a schedule of taking female faculty members
individually to lunch to discuss their careers.
</P>
<P>
   `'We need to engage all of our faculty and staff about how to
make a better working environment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said he must work to build on the academic
program that Casper undertook, including strengthening of the
undergraduate program and continuing Stanford's ``ability to
attract the best faculty, the best staff and the best students,
given the cost of living in the Bay Area,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Ikenberry, president of the American Council on
Education, the nation's leading higher education association, said
Hennessy is well-prepared to handle the challenges of running a
world-class institution with 14,219 students and 1,640 faculty.
</P>
<P>
   ``His strong point will be that none of those will be new issues
for him. He will have lived those issues and dealt with them as
provost,'' Ikenberry said. ``He enjoys a very strong reputation
nationally.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Casper said, he has admired Hennessy's ``clarity,
intellectual vigor and honesty.''
</P>
<P>
   As provost, Hennessy has been the chief academic and budget
officer, overseeing the university's $1.6 billion academic
operating budget and its $6.2 billion endowment.
</P>
<P>
   He has also taken on some of the tough issues facing the
university, including soaring housing costs and the need to
reexamine faculty and staff compensation. In addition, he is
leading the searches for new deans for the schools of medicine and
education and for undergraduate admission.
</P>
<P>
   Yale University President Richard Levin, a 1968 Stanford
graduate, said it is a ``healthy sign'' that Stanford chose an
insider as president and said it will give the new president a
``flying start.''
</P>
<P>
   With a Ph.D. in computer science and his business experience as
cofounder of MIPS Computer Systems in 1984, Hennessy is expected to
bring a strong focus on technology into the classrooms and
strengthen Stanford's position in the booming high-tech economy.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Diefendorff, editor and chief of the Sunnyvale-based
Microprocessor Report, said that Hennessy is one of the early
pioneers of a microprocessing design that changed the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Hennessy has also authored one of the most heavily used computer
architecture books, worked until recently as the chief architect of
Silicon Graphics Computer Systems and continues to consult for the
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``John is clearly a technologist at heart,'' Diefendorff said.
``He is one of the icons of Silicon Valley and the computer
microprocessor industry. From that perspective, you can only
believe he can only strengthen Stanford's role there.''
</P>
<P>
   As dean, Hennessy engineered an online master's degree in
electrical engineering in 1998, making Stanford the first major
research university to do so. And he has used the Internet
extensively to support students in his classes.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford graduates have founded several successful startups,
including Silicon Graphics, Sun Microsystems and Cisco Systems. The
university was also the incubator for Yahoo, created by two
Stanford undergraduates, Jerry Yang and David Philo, who studied
under Hennessy.
</P>
<P>
   Yang said Hennessy has always had a vision of how the university
and the industry work together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the environment where there is a healthy interchange
of ideas between the university and industry has been one that John
supports,'' Yang said.
</P>
<P>
   Hennessy's ties to Silicon Valley may give him a leg up in
raising money for the university. He was instrumental in pulling in
the university's biggest ever donation, $150 million last October
from Silicon Graphics and Netscape cofounder Jim Clark, to fund a
biomedical engineering and sciences center.
</P>
<P>
   Hennessy, who lives in Atherton with his wife and two sons, is
reputed to have made his fortune when he sold MIPS to Silicon
Graphics for $200 million in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview with the Chronicle of Higher Education,
Hennessy would not reveal his net worth, but conceded he could
``get away with being on a few boards and doing nothing else.''
</P>
<P>
   For him, that means working at Stanford. Although university
officials did not disclose Hennessy's new salary, his predecessor
made $379,622 in 1997-98, according to the Chronicle of Higher
Education.
</P>
<P>
   `'If you have enough financial independence, then you can do
what you really love and not worry that you're missing the next dot
com,'' Hennessy said.
</P>
<P>
   But no one expects Hennessy's engineering background to signal
that Stanford is ``about to become MIT west,'' said John
Bravman(cq) &LR; , Stanford's vice provost for undergraduate education.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, said Bravman, ``this is the time to have someone (as
president) who is deeply connected to the whole new economy, and
who also appreciates the breadth of what we do here at the
university.''
</P>
<P>
   Hennessy was one of about 400 applicants considered for the job
during the five-month search. Just who the other finalists for the
presidency were could not be determined Monday, with the 17-member
search committee maintaining a discreet silence.
</P>
<P>
   Among those rumored to have been leading candidates were Nan
Keohane, president of Duke University, also a Stanford graduate;
William Brody, president of Johns Hopkins University, and U.S.
Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala.
</P>
<P>
   Another name that emerged immediately after Casper's
announcement he was resigning was that of Condoleezza Rice, a
senior researcher at Stanford's Hoover Institution, Republican
George W. Bush's foreign policy adviser and Hennessy's predecessor
as provost.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rice said Monday that she was never a candidate for the
Stanford job. ``I love Stanford, but when I left I made clear that
my future was in foreign policy, and everyone respected my
statement.''
</P>
<P>
   In selecting a provost to step up to the president's job, the
trustees returned to what had become almost a routine procedure of
promoting provosts into the top spot before Casper's arrival on
campus in 1992. The two presidents immediately prior to Casper,
Donald Kennedy and Richard W. Lyman, had both been provosts.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Levin, Stanford's student body president, said Hennessy's
appointment is ``a huge win for students.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As provost, John Hennessy cared very much what students had to
say, and we look forward now to working with him as president,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
