<HEADLINE>
NO RUSH GETTING BLAKE INTO LINEUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -- With the Kings already in the playoffs, they are
using caution in bringing back captain Rob Blake from a bruised
left knee suffered in Saturday's game against the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Blake did not play Monday night against the Coyotes, remaining
in Los Angeles to undergo test. He will be reevaluated again today
and could rejoin the team for Wednesday's game in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want him here, but it is important to get him health,''
coach Andy Murray said. ``Rob has had an outstanding season and he
is so important to our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake, who has had a history of injuries, has been healthy all
season with the exception of two games in January with a strained
groin.
</P>
<P>
   If he is not ready to go, Blake is expected to play Friday
against the defendng Stanley Cup champion Dallas Stars at Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   In other injury news, Nelson Emerson, who broke the index finger
on his left hand just four games after coming over from Atlanta,
has the arm in a cast, but surgery has been ruled out for now.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson was whacked across the left hand by Philadelphia's
Daymond Langkow on March 23. When the hand swelled doctors thought
Emerson might need a pin in the finger to stabilize the joint.
</P>
<P>
   Ziggy Palffy, sidelined since a sprained right shoulder March15
against the Might Ducks, remains in Los Angeles and is skating
daily at the club's training facility in El Segundo. The Kings do
not know whether Palffy will be back before the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Big Hit: Although the Coyotes were on the verge of clinching a
playoff spot, most of the talk at America West Arena focused on the
crushing hit by Phoenix's Dallas Drake last Saturday on Edmonton's
Boyd Devereaux.
</P>
<P>
   The Oilers are seeking a suspension for Drake, who they claim
left is feet to apply a shoulder to the head of Devereaux, who
suffered a concussion. The Coyotes rallied from a three-goal
deficit after the hit, but lost 4-3 in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel for him, but it is part of the game,'' said Drake, who
scored the Coyotes' first goal Monday. ``I hear he is getting
better and I am happy for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick Whistles: The Kings came in 1-3 against Phoenix, but won
the last meeting 5-2. Phoenix is tied with Detroit for the league
lead with eight 40-point scorers, but has scored an NHL-low 36
power play goals. ....
</P>
</TEXT>
