<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CLEAVES ACHIEVES A SLIVER OF THE DREAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (UPDATES thruout with game result.) 
 (ms) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The day before Monday night's national
championship game against Florida, Tom Izzo, the Michigan State
coach, made one of the more startling statements of the tournament.
He said Mateen Cleaves, his senior point guard, was as significant
to Michigan State basketball as Magic Johnson had been.
</P>
<P>
   Eyebrows arched. Magic was one of the great point guards in
National Basketball Association history. Magic transformed the
position. Magic and Larry Bird crystallized the melting-pot nature
of college basketball and carried that goodwill into the pro game
right when the National Basketball Association really needed it.
</P>
<P>
   Izzo wasn't saying that Cleaves was as good as Magic. He was
saying that Cleaves was as significant to the Spartans in the late
1990s as Johnson was in the late 70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's only one Magic,'' Izzo said. ``I just think
that Mateen Cleaves has been the next closest thing because of his
personality, because of his will to win. A lot of players have it,
but Mateen shares it with everybody. He is the reason we are a
great family. Great players make all the people around then better.
They might take them from good to great, from average to good. For
us, Mateen makes our coaching staff better, he makes our players
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Izzo knew that if Michigan State was to win its first
championship since Johnson led them in 1979, Cleaves would have to
be everything Izzo said he was.
</P>
<P>
   In the 89-76 national championship victory, A.J. Granger and
Morris Peterson would be the most valuable players, bailing the
Spartans out with clutch basket after clutch bas- ket. But Cleaves,
who finished with 18 points, four assists and just two turn- overs,
was the emotional engine. He displayed skill in the first half and
heart in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves missed his first shot but then set the tone for Michigan
State's formula for beating the Florida press. He outran a double
team and scored. A possession later, Cleaves, employing the same
strategy, beat the double team and scored again. With 16 minutes 39
seconds left in the half and Michigan State leading by 11-9,
Cleaves left the game. His re- placement was Jason Richardson, a
6-foot-6-inch guard from Saginaw, Mich., who thrives in the
fullcourt up- tempo game forced by Florida. In Cleaves's absence,
Richardson flour- ished. He scored six points, but more than the
points, the understudy forced Florida to reconsider its full-H
court pressure.
</P>
<P>
   When Cleaves returned 3:11 later, Michigan State led by 17-11.
Just when the Florida defense was get- ting comfortable with giving
Cleaves breathing room, the all-American pulled through.
</P>
<P>
   His 3-pointer with 9:51 left gave the Spartans a 24-17 lead; his
3 with 8:49 remaining boosted the lead to 29-20. Finally, Cleaves's
3 with 1:12 left in the half gave Michigan State a 43-32 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half, Cleaves's bas- kets may have saved the game.
Flor- ida had just scored four straight points and pulled within
48-41. Cleaves broke the press and dribbled the length of the court
to score.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves came to Michigan State as a highly-touted
football-basketball player from nearby Flint, a city that has
turned out a large number of outstanding high school, college and
professional athletes. Each season has been better than the one
before, from an injury-riddled freshman year when the Spartans went
to the National Invitational Tournament, to a better sophomore
season, to last year's run to the Final Four, which ended with a
semifinal loss to Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves said his freshman season set the tone for the rest of
his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lowest point in my career was when we went to the NIT,''
Cleaves said. ``There's nothing wrong with that tournament, but
just to sit back and watch TV and watch these teams in the NCAA
tournament, to see all the media, watching how much fun they were
having, seeing the smiles of guys, then watching the Final Four. I
promised myself back then: `I'm going to play in that NCAA
tournament; I'm not going to the NIT anymore.'''
</P>
<P>
   So how good is Cleaves, really? Is he NBA caliber? He certainly
isn't the traditional player with obvious gifts. He doesn't have a
terrifying shot or an unstoppable penetration move. At 6 feet 1
inch, Cleaves is more likely to be posted up than post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been a guy that wanted the stats, never been a guy
who wanted the accolades,'' he said. ``I just want to win. Whatever
you do, win. A lot of guys tease me a lot, they say I cheat when we
play cards, but I just want to win. The name of the game is win.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Wisconsin last Saturday, Cleaves' line was atrocious: 1
point. NBA personnel who watched the game weren't deterred. Chris
Wallace, the Boston Celtics general manager, is a Cleaves fan.
``You look at his statistics against Wisconsin _ nothing to be
excited about _ but they won and he played a key role in them
winning,'' Wallace said. ``He is a tremendous leader, has excellent
intangibles and he has a hardened, winning edge.''
</P>
<P>
   With Magic Johnson and Steve Smith watching, Cleaves showed the
hardness and the edge. At 50-44, Cleaves dribbled the length of the
court and was fouled. Cleaves, ap- parently not hearing the
whistle, kept going. His right ankle got tan- gled with Teddy
Dupay's foot; he tumbled and suffered a severe sprain. With 16:18
left in the season, he had to leave the game with his team clinging
to a 50-44 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves, severely limping, re- turned to a thunderous ovation ,
with 11:11 left and Michigan State lead- ing, 58-49.
</P>
<P>
   His first play was a turnover on a fast break; his second a
fullcourt outlet to Peterson for a basket. With Cleaves playing on
one leg, Michigan State went on a 21-9 run and put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves didn't score, Cleaves did- n't pass. Michigan State won
a na- tional championship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 0102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
