<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6460 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-NCAA-FINAL-ART-NY     04-04 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-FINAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN STATE KEEP ITS PROMISE ON THE WAY TO A NATIONAL TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT38,39 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Adds photo note) 
(ms) 
 BY JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Mateen Cleaves had returned for his senior year
for this national championship stage and those pearl white nets
dangling beneath two baskets. Monday night he grimaced and screamed
his way through a virtuoso performance in the spotlight and then
smiled sweetly and clipped down the nylon as his final bow as a
senior.
</P>
<P>
   He had plenty of help from his Michigan State teammates who had
vowed to be back hours after being defeated by Duke last year in
the national semifinals. His best friend from his hometown of
Flint, Mich., Morris Peterson, rained in 21 points from distances
that were often barely inbounds. Another senior, willowy A.J.
Granger, snaked through the lanes for 19 points worth of tip-ins
and point-blank jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Michigan State's 89-76 victory over young
Florida was Cleaves-willed, Cleaves-orchestrated and as fine a
one-man show a college basketball player could perform. The point
guard who missed the first 13 games of the season with a stress
fracture to his right foot poured all his talent into an 18-point
on 7-of-11 shooting and four-assist outing.
</P>
<P>
   He blunted the Gators runs at every turn so his old team could
beat the precocious one and forced a precocious coach, Florida's
34-year-old Billy Donovan, to wait his turn behind a beloved one,
Michigan State's Tom Izzo. And so finally a wacky, unpredictable
tournament came to a true and just end: the best team in the nation
rightfully crowned.
</P>
<P>
   Only once did it look like it wouldn't _ Florida burst out in
the second half intent on cutting into Michigan State's 11-point
lead. The Gators pounded the ball into Udonis Haslem and Brent
Wright, then Mike Miller drained a 3-pointer to cut the lead to
47-41. But Cleaves refused to let the young Gators to get a grip on
the momentum.
</P>
<P>
   He sliced through the Florida press for a layup; he nailed a
3-pointer - his 18th point - and put the Spartans back up by 50-44.
With 16:18 left, Cleaves was trying to stop Florida's surge again.
He caught a pass on the fly at midcourt and was slapped on the
wrist by Brett Nelson. Cleaves, however, continued to the basket
and tangled with the Gators' Teddy Dupay and was hammered to the
floor. He crawled along the baseline, grabbed his lower leg and
after several minute delay was pulled from the game and taken back
to the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates repelled another Florida surge in his absence -
Mike Chappell and Granger banging in clutch 3-pointers. When a big
screen in the RCA dome showed Cleaves making his way back to the
court, the crowd of 43,116 roared. When Cleaves re-entered the game
with 11:51 minutes left and his team up 58-50, even the Gators fans
applauded politely perhaps knowing the end was at hand. The Gators
never got closer.
</P>
<P>
   For Michigan State, the vision of a national title appeared a
year ago at a hotel in Florida. The Spartans had just been beaten
by Duke in the Final Four semifinals, and Izzo gathered his guys in
a crowded room and told them they would be back.
</P>
<P>
   For Florida, the national championship apparition visited just
three weeks ago on a basketball floor in Winston-Salem, N.C. The
Gators were about to be bounced in the first round by Butler in
overtime when Miller hit a runner with three-tenths of a second
left to snatch a 68-67 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Just as this Michigan State team envisioned a championship, the
Spartans had some history on their side _ Magic Johnson led them to
a championship in 1979. Just as Florida was late to embrace its
title possibilities, the Gators' basketball program was a newcomer
to this spring spectacle. In 1994, the Gators made their only prior
Final Four appearance, and this was the school's first ever
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   In taking a 43-32 lead into halftime, Michigan State, the lone
top seed to make the Final Four, showed how age and experience
forged a tough-minded and deliberate team. Three seniors - Cleaves,
Peterson and Granger _ and two juniors, Charlie Bell and Andre
Hutson, looked every bit ready to uphold their refuse-to-lose
motto.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators, who had a sole senior and played seven freshmen and
sophomores at least 10 minutes a game, wanted to treat the 94-foot
court like a motor speedway and run over the Spartans.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan said his Florida team's helter-skelter style was
intended to take the ``fear and anxiety'' out of every possession
so his players would not treat a second of a 40-minute game like
it's ``life or death.'' But the Spartans showed early that they
were prepared for the full-court pressure when Peterson threw the
ball over the hawking defenders to a streaking Cleaves for easy
back-to-back layups and an 11-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Spartans not only did not commit a turnover into 12
minutes into the game, but Cleaves, their floor leader, led them to
53 percent shooting and a team-high 13 points on 5-of-8 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   As they have all season, Florida got a boost from its bench -
especially 3-point bomber, freshman Brett Nelson. The Gators first
five off the bench averaged 31.9 points a game in the regular
season and have upped it to 36.6 in the tournament. When the Gators
second unit entered the game with 13 minutes left, Nelson dropped
two 23-footers from top of the key to cut the Spartans lead to
21-17.
</P>
<P>
   But Izzo, too, dispatched his bench effectively. Freshman Jason
Richardson scored six points off the bench and helped ignite a 14-5
Spartan run that gave Michigan State a 35-22 lead.
</P>
<P>
   By playing stifling man-to-man defense and pounding the boards,
Michigan State also was able to control the tempo of the game. They
allowed their opponents an average of 59 points a game and led the
nation in rebounding margin, 11.7 a game.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators saw why as the Spartan defense held them to 40
percent shooting as Michigan State staked out the ground under the
basket as their own. Granger and the 6-3 Bell were especially
effective. Granger had four rebounds and scored nine points while
Bell, a tenacious jumper pulled down seven first-half rebounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 0106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
