<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN STATE TOPS FLORIDA, WINS NATIONAL TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-FLORIDA-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Florida sopohomore guard Teddy Dupay describes
his team's playing style this way: ``I bet if you're way up in the
arena, it probably looks like a bunch of ants running around after
you pull up a rock.''
</P>
<P>
   But rocks crush ants like scissors cut paper. And the Gators'
remarkable NCAA Tournament ran into an avalanche of boulders
disguised in Michigan State uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Even with two of their Flintstones _ Morris Peterson (foul
trouble) and Mateen Cleaves (sprained right ankle) _ missing a key
second-half stretch, Michigan State showed its flinty side. The
Spartans played Florida's game better than Florida in recording an
89-76 national championship victory Monday night before 43,116 in
the RCA Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it has sunk in yet what we've done,'' Michigan
State coach Tom Izzo said. ``It was a team effort. We had a lot of
guys do a lot of things. All of our subs played well.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State (32-7) now has a second national championship
trophy to match the hardware won by the 1979 Magic Johnson team.
Florida, playing in its first national championship game, finished
29-8.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, who finished with 21 points, went to the bench with
his third foul at 17:23. Just over a minute later, Cleaves _ who
had sliced through Florida's pressure defense with no impediments _
sprained his right ankle. As he hobbled to the locker room, it
appeared the Gators were ready for feeding time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Cleaves went down, we knew we had to start making our
run, but we were never able to get it going,'' said Florida
sophomore forward Mike Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was definitely going to get back out there,'' Cleaves said.
``The trainer just told me it was going to be sore.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans played with the resolve and dedication of a room
full of Trappist monks. They turned Florida's strengths _ pressure
defense and waves of production from the bench _ into their
strengths. Especially with Peterson and Cleaves off the court.
</P>
<P>
   But Charlie Bell (nine points, five assists), A.J. Granger (19
points, nine rebounds) and reserve Mike Chappell (five points) made
sure that Florida never got closer than six points in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see a team press them all year long, and that's
probably for a good reason,'' Donovan said. ``We didn't take away
the things we needed to. The press was effective in the second
half. Every time we made a run, they answered. That's a sign of a
great team with great leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves, who finished with 18 points and four assists, and
Peterson returned with 11:51 remaining. Peterson, seeing his good
friend hobbled and limping, took over. He scored 14 points,
including three stone-cold 3-pointers, over a six-minute period.
His final three boosted Michigan State's lead to 82-62 with 5:18
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Four of Michigan State's first eight field goals were the result
of slicing through Florida's full-court pressure. Cleaves had two
layups and an assist on an Andre Hutson basket. And the Spartans'
first turnover didn't occur until the 8:05 mark when Brett Nelson
poked the ball free from Cleaves. And all that resulted in was a
Gators turnover on the ensuing possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great game plan against their press,'' Cleaves said.
``We wanted me to cut through the middle and get me the ball. We
attacked it. We set up a formation that was easy for us to break
the press.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final 10 minutes of its last three NCAA Tournament
victories (Duke, Oklahoma State, North Carolina), the Gators
outscored those teams by 25 points (66-43), outshot them 47 percent
to 32 percent and outrebounded 39-23. But that witching hour never
came for the Spartans.
</P>
<P>
   With 10 minutes remaining, Michigan State had a 62-50 lead,
courtesy of Granger's follow shot. Over the last 10 minutes,
Michigan State turned the Gators into geckos.
</P>
<P>
   Izzo, 45, who was a Spartans assistant for a dozen years before
getting his current job, wants to have a picture taken with his old
boss, former Michigan State coach Jud Heathcote. Izzo said he wants
each of them holding the trophies of their respective championship
teams, to depict bridging the gap between 1979 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
   For the Spartans, Michigan State 89, Florida 76 was a
championship game worth framing. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
