<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN STATE GETS MAD, THEN GRABS TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The last thing Florida should have done, the very
last thing, was injure Michigan State All-American Mateen Cleaves.
Instead of giving the Gators a chance to win, it actually sealed
their doom. Because when Teddy Dupay and Cleaves collided and
Cleaves landed awkwardly and sprained his right ankle and hobbled
to the lockerroom _ all it really did was make Michigan State mad.
</P>
<P>
   Tough, talented and wise, the Spartans are the best team in the
nation under normal circumstances. Once they got mad, they
overwhelmed the Gators with inspiring resolve, timely shooting and
a granite defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he went out, we kind of knew how bad he was hurt,''
forward A.J. Granger said after the Spartans won the NCAA
championship Monday with an 89-76 victory over Florida before
43,116 in the RCA Dome. ``We rallied together in the huddle. We
looked at each other and said, `Let's do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves and Dupay tangled on a fast break with just over 16
minutes remaining and the Spartans leading 50-44. After they broke
free of each other, Cleaves landed hard and immediately grabbed his
right ankle. He was engulfed in medical and support personnel. He
eventually hobbled to the lockerroom. During his 4:30 absence, the
Spartans not only increased their led by three points, they
smothered Florida with an aggressive, immovable defense. The Gators
would make just five baskets over the next nine minutes as Michigan
State extended its six-point lead to 20.
</P>
<P>
   The victory will resonate throughout the state. The epicenter of
celebration, of course, is Michigan State's campus in Lansing,
which has waited 21 years for a title. The man who delivered the
1979 crown, Magic Johnson, attended Monday's game and joined the
Spartans afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very special to see him support us,'' Cleaves said. ``We
wanted to get a win for him.''
</P>
<P>
   They also will rejoice in Iron Mountain, in Michigan's Upper
Peninsula, where Spartans coach Tom Izzo and San Francisco 49ers
coach Steve Mariucci were high school classmates. They have
remained best friends and have had a longstanding bet: would Izzo
win a national title before Mariucci won a Super Bowl? Mariucci
lost.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, they're celebrating in Flint, the industrial town 60
miles northwest of Detroit. Home of General Motors and the United
Auto Workers' union, Flint now has something to show the nation
besides decay and (ital)Roger and Me(end ital). The Spartans' soul
_ Cleaves, Morris Peterson and Charlie Bell _ comes from Flint.
</P>
<P>
   ``People outside of Flint see Flint as a bad, run-down city,''
Peterson said. ``Flint is a great city. Through all of the negative
things, Flint has taken pride in in athletics. We've brought some
glory back to Flint.''
</P>
<P>
   All three Flintstones, as they're called, were instrumental in
the Spartans' victory. Cleaves had 18 points and four assists and
shredded Florida's pressure defense; he was named Final Four MVP.
Bell was quiet but effective, with nine points, eight rebounds and
five assists. He ran the offense flawlessly when Cleaves went down
_ just as he did during Cleaves' 13-game absence (broken foot) at
the beginning of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation was not any different than the beginning of the
year,'' Bell said. ``For half the year, I ran the team when Mateen
was injured. I feel very comfortable running the point. We had
adversity all year and tonight was no different. We are a team, and
that's why we're still standing.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson _ Mo Pete, as he's called _ again showed why he is the
best pressure player in the country. After struggling in the first
half, he scored 16 points in the second and buried the Gators with
a series of 3-pointers. In six tournament games, Peterson scored 75
of his 105 points in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   But no one was more important than Granger, who made 7-of-11
shots , scored 19 points and grabbed nine rebounds. He also hit
three 3-pointers, each arriving just when the Spartans needed it
most.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called Granger the X factor,'' Florida coach Billy Donovan
said. ``We could not allow him to step out and make 3-point
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans not only broke Florida's press, they attacked it.
Usually, Cleaves pushed the issue, but he had help from Bell,
Granger and Peterson. Even center Andre Hutson helped a few times.
Together, they burst past the first wave of defenders, then either
took the ball to the rim or passed to open teammates for jumpers.
The Spartans used this approach to make seven of their first 10
shots and score 17 points in five minutes. It was a near-perfect
display: Michigan State did not commit a turnover for 12 minutes
and grabbed a lead it would not relinquish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used a 1-4 set, and we made one pass and then let me cut
(to the middle of the court),'' Cleaves said. ``If we had (an
advantage in) numbers, (coach Tom Izzo) said to attack.''
</P>
</TEXT>
