<HEADER>
A6467 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     04-04 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FranBlinebury
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
INDIANAPOLIS _ They are a relic from the past, a product of another
time, like the butter churn, the Pony Express and the tankful of
gasoline that doesn't cost a sultan's riches.
</P>
<P>
   They are a running, jumping, up-in-your-face anachronism that
was built for the long haul rather than the quick fix.
</P>
<P>
   In this era of teen-agers dancing straight from the high school
prom into the NBA or using the university campus as no more than an
ivy-covered takeoff strip to jet toward the riches of a pro career,
they are a college basketball team that is the equivalent of newly
discovered drawings on the wall of a cave _ both old and exciting.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State won the national championship Monday night with a
starting lineup that consisted of three seniors and two juniors who
grew together, who lost together, who suffered together and
ultimately came together in a thoroughly complete and utterly
satisfying 89-76 triumph over Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans are three longtime friends _ Mateen Cleaves, Morris
Peterson and Charlie Bell _ from the hardscrabble streets of what
was once the thriving town of Flint, Mich. They worked to build
this dream, this accomplishment, this special memory the way their
parents and neighbors used to build cars at the old Ford plants
that have long since shuttered their doors _ by toiling long hours
and for years.
</P>
<P>
   The Flintstones, as they came to be known, had a job to finish.
</P>
<P>
   Yabba dabba done.
</P>
<P>
   They might as well have been running an assembly line.
</P>
<P>
   They were led by Cleaves, the firecracker of a point guard who
was never going to let them come up short of their goal. He had
turned his back on a chance to jump to the NBA after his junior
season and had put so much of himself into reaching this point. He
hit seven of 11 shots, including a trio from 3-point range, to fire
in 18 points straight between the eyes of the Gators.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves is their voice, their emotion, the ignition spark that
turns over their engine, and he was not going to be denied, not
going to be stopped. He went down hard to the floor with 16:18 left
in the game after a particularly rough run-in with Florida's Teddy
Dupay and wound up crawling along the baseline toward the Spartans'
bench before being helped to the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   But you knew he would come back, even if the trainers had to tie
him to the saddle and prop him up like El Cid returning to battle,
and in less than five minutes, Cleaves was out on the floor again,
limping with a high sprain in his right ankle.
</P>
<P>
   They were led by Peterson, the sharp, smooth, slender fellow who
is built like a stiletto and sticks just as deep and deadly.
Peterson, playing with the emotional burden of his grandmother's
death last week, pumped in 15 of his team-leading 21 points in the
second half to continually keep those Gator jaws from snapping shut
on his team.
</P>
<P>
   They were led by Bell, the junior-class member of the
Flintstones, who scored nine points but managed to get his 6-3
frame on the boards all night long for eight rebounds and dealt
five assists.
</P>
<P>
   They were led by A.J. Granger, the senior who will graduate next
month and then get married in June. He went on an early honeymoon
cruise with 19 points _ 3-for-5 on treys _ and was the X-factor
that repeatedly confused and made the Florida defense pay.
</P>
<P>
   If you're counting, that's four leaders, and, truth be told,
there were more. For this was a team that came back to the Final
Four for the second straight year to finish the task it started a
year ago when it lost to Duke in St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   This was the team of the future in Florida _ five freshmen and
four sophomores _ that met the team of this night, this game, this
chance.
</P>
<P>
   They came from behind three straight times in the NCAAs, against
Utah, Syracuse and Iowa State, survived Wisconsin's coma ball, then
ran Florida right out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a bunch of guys who will always be special, because we
were always in it together,'' said Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this shouldn't be regarded as a throwback or one of the
first antiques from the 20th century. Maybe in this time of one- or
two-year wonders blowing through campus faster than a thunderstorm,
the way to build a real champion is to do it the Spartan way _
without an overall No. 1 NBA draft pick but with parts that are
complementary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team will have five- and 10- and 20-year reunions,'' said
coach Tom Izzo. ``People at Michigan State will remember this team
for how it played.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more for how it persevered.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
