<HEADLINE>
LOCAL TECH ISSUES TAKE IT ON THE CHIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``a'' national news file.) 
By JASON Z. COHEN AND CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Investors moved their money away from the new
economy stocks of the Nasdaq on Monday and toward the stalwarts of
the Dow Jones industrial average, continuing a market correction
that began last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq exchange, where shares of scores of local technology
companies are traded, sustained its largest single-day point drop
to date Monday. The fate of local firms in the sell-off mirrored
that of the rest of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Chatsworth-based MRV Communications, which manufactures
components for the fiber-optic networks that make up the
infrastructure of the Internet, had the region's largest decline
Monday, losing 19.65 percent of its value.
</P>
<P>
   Semiconductors were down 7.4 percent, according to Anthony
O'Bryan, a market analyst with A.G. Edwards Inc. Locally, Vitesse
Semiconductor Inc. of Camarillo and Semtech Corp. of Newbury Park,
both semiconductor manufacturers, had only moderate losses Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ross Gerber, manager of the Woodland Hills office of Sun America
Securities, said Monday's decline ``was not a bad day in the stock
markets. The drop was in selected high-risk securities. ... Even
with a correction in the Nasdaq, it would be hard for me to believe
that people who invest today won't be happy in two to three
years.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the recent volatility is because uninformed investors
sell their shares after seeing other investors dump their shares,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's sell-off was precipitated by the breakdown in talks
between representatives of Microsoft and the U.S. Justice
Department, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just kind of a shock to the market,'' O'Bryan said.
``It just gave people an excuse to restart the correction in the
tech stocks because Microsoft was such a big player in that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft case was a fairly predictable catalyst for
Monday's decline, said Richard Barnett, director of equities for
Beverly Hills-based City National Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Added Barnett: ``These declines are very healthy. Prices can't
continue to increase. It brings rationality back to the market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
