<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEAVES THE MAGICIAN HAS FIRM GRASP ON TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The Muslim name that his activist parents gave
him means ``firm and unshakable.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in the beginning, it seems, they knew.
</P>
<P>
   On the night that he had dreamed about all his life, Michigan
State's Mateen Cleaves, raised to be a leader, took his dream by
his poised hands and transformed it into an NCAA basketball
championship Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Just like Magic.
</P>
<P>
   It was 21 years ago that another Michigan State born-leader, a
magician named Earvin Johnson, unshakably carried the Spartans to
their last NCAA tournament title.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's known as a winner,'' Cleaves had said. ``I just want to
be known as a national champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Expected to be up to their shorts in Gators, the Spartans blew
through the Florida press and made a mockery of the notion that
their opponents' depth would be a telling factor.
</P>
<P>
   The dominant factor in the 89-76 victory, as it turns out, was
Cleaves.
</P>
<P>
   The senior from Flint, Mich., painted the complexion of the game
from the beginning. He drove the paint. He shredded the Gators'
full-court pressure. When a sprained ankle finally slowed him down
four minutes into the second half, Cleaves had 18 points, and the
partisan Michigan State crowd could sense what was happening.
</P>
<P>
   A sign among the Spartans fans read, ``Party like it's 1979.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a great competitor,'' Florida coach Billy Donovan
said of the new magician, Cleaves. ``He has a tremendous will to
win, as he showed all season.''
</P>
<P>
   Scoring and shooting, however, were not supposed to be Cleaves'
paramount skills. Through his first five games of this NCAA
Tournament, Cleaves had been shooting only 37.5 percent from the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think it was their defense tonight,'' the
Gators' Teddy Dupay said later. ``I think so often that's what they
get credit for. But offensively is where they hurt us tonight. They
scored pretty much at will.''
</P>
<P>
   And where there was a will Monday night, there was usually a
Mateen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy has the heart of a lion,'' winning coach Tom Izzo
said. ``He has worked for this for four years.''
</P>
<P>
   There are few Final Four teams in recent years who have seemed
more prepared. The Spartans' 13-point winning margin _ it once rose
to 20 _ is the largest since Duke overwhelmed Michigan's alleged
Fab Five by 20 in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   An even more ringing statement about the job that Izzo did,
however, is that in Saturday's semifinals, the Spartans had every
answer for a startlingly different, doggedly defensive Wisconsin
team.
</P>
<P>
   Izzo had less than 48 hours to prepare for the hip-shooting,
free-subbing Gators.
</P>
<P>
   But what he had, Donovan clearly lacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference was they're seniors,'' the Florida coach said.
``Mateen Cleaves, Morris Peterson and A.J. Granger all stepped up,
made plays, made shots and opened the game up for them.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the Spartans had passed this way. Cleaves' boyhood
dream at that time was snuffed in the 1999 Final Four semis by
Duke. After two All-American seasons at point guard, Cleaves was
roundly expected to turn pro after that Final Four loss.
</P>
<P>
   But there was unfinished business.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave up a lot of money to come back,'' Izzo said. ``People
should appreciate him for the great kid that he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as storybook as it gets for Mateen. He has lived his
dream.''
</P>
<P>
   For four years, he has been the Michigan State program's heart
and soul. But leading a team to its dreams was what Frances and
Herb Cleaves had in mind for their son 22 years ago, when they
pushed his baby stroller with them to civil-rights rallies and
school-board meetings and wherever there was a cause over which to
be concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was what I came back for,'' Cleaves said. ``This was the
dream.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
