<HEADER>
A6471 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BKC-CLEAVES-MVP-TEX     04-04 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CLEAVES-MVP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARTANS' CLEAVES WAS SIMPLY MAGICAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ There is a seven-inch height difference between
Mateen Cleaves and Earvin ``Magic'' Johnson. And Cleaves' style is
bullish while Johnson was elegant and well, magical.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday night, a 21-year gap was closed between the 6-foot-2
Cleaves and the 6-9 Johnson when Michigan State won its second
national championship with an 89-76 victory against Florida.
Cleaves, who played 31 minutes against Florida's relentless
pressure defense, was named the Final Four's Most Outstanding
Player.
</P>
<P>
   The senior guard finished with 18 points. A less than 40-percent
shooter in the NCAA Tournament, he was an uncharacteristic 7-of-11
from the field, including 3-for-3 on 3-pointers. It was his
leadership as much as his statistics, however, which again willed
the Spartans to victory.
</P>
<P>
   With 16:18 remaining, shortly after scoring his final basket,
Cleaves injured his right ankle. He limped to the locker room with
his team leading, 50-44. When he returned with 11:51 left, Michigan
State was leading, 58-50. He played the rest of the game, often
limping up and down the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in a lot of pain. I tried to walk on it and I couldn't
put any more pressure on it. We added some tape and a brace on it.
I started to cry a little bit, but luckily I was able to get back
out there and play,'' Cleaves said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's the greatest leader in school history,'' Michigan
State coach Tom Izzo said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Which includes a guy named Magic Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Johnson led the Spartans to their first national title
in a memorable championship-game matchup with Indiana State's Larry
Bird. Johnson was named the tournament's most outstanding player in
1979.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves announced at a pretournament pep rally in East Lansing,
Mich., that the Spartans would win the national championship. He
helped make good on that boast Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mateen has the heart of a lion,'' said Michigan State senior
Morris Peterson, a childhood friend of Cleaves. ``There's nothing
he can't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves and the Spartans solved Florida's vaunted full-court
press with ease most of the night. The Spartans passed over it, or
in-bounded the ball to their big men, who then passed to Cleaves
for what amounted to fast-break opportunities. Florida had just one
steal off its press in the first 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleaves is a great point guard and he showed that tonight,''
Florida sophomore forward Mike Miller said. ``He did a good job of
running his team against our press and he hit some big shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves missed the first 13 games of the season because of a
stress fracture in his right foot. After he returned, the Spartans
won 23 of their past 26 games. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
