<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-FLAMES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL TIES DAD; FLAMES KNOT STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Calgary Flames played like a desperate hockey team,
the Stars couldn't stand prosperity, and a night that should have
belonged to Brett Hull ended the way it started: All even.
</P>
<P>
   At the 7:48 mark of the second period, Hull blasted a vintage
one-timer past Calgary goalie Fred Brathwaite, nailing down career
goal No. 610 and tying his Hall of Fame father, Bobby, for ninth
all-time on the NHL's goals list.
</P>
<P>
   The goal supplied the Stars a 2-0 lead, a raucous home crowd and
610 reasons to finish off the 11th-place Flames. But Calgary's
desperation and the Stars' inability to clear their zone accounted
for two hard-luck third-period goals against Stars backup goalie
Manny Fernandez, who made 34 saves. But he was bombarded by 17
shots in the third period and overtime when the Stars managed six
shots.
</P>
<P>
   Each team traded chances in the extra period. Joe Nieuwendyk
missed wide left on a breakaway, and when the smoke cleared from a
wild, end-to-end affair, the Stars and Flames were tied, 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We allowed this game to get tied because we didn't stay with
the program,'' coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``We decided the
territorial game that we played the first two periods wasn't good
enough, and we decided we were going to start making plays. We had
full control of the hockey game and then we allowed them back in.''
</P>
<P>
   Which was a shame considering Hull's long-awaited
accomplishment. Goal No. 610 left only a smoking net and a burned
goaltender. It was long in coming, but Hull's blast from the lower
right circle ate up Brathwaite the way a wicked Nolan Ryan fastball
used to freeze batters into submission.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was another blown lead in the third, but \Rthe goal\S is a
good feeling. I didn't know if it was ever going to happen, but
it's nice that it's here now,'' Hull said. ``It's quite an honor.
He's a Hall of Fame player. They voted for the Top 50 greatest
players he was No. 8 and, not only that, he is my father.''
</P>
<P>
   His 24th goal in one of the most grueling seasons of his 13-year
career was vintage Hull. Hitchcock rolled out a new power-play line
of Hull, Nieuwendyk and Mike Modano. It clicked. Hull drifted into
the lower right circle and Nieuwendyk, from below the goal line,
flicked a one-touch pass from Modano onto Hull's cocked stick.
</P>
<P>
   Hull let it rip and Brathwaite had no chance to catch up to it.
Brett notched his 610th in 937 games, while Bobby did it in 1,063.
Bobby also had 303 goals from 1972-79 while playing for Winnipeg of
the World Hockey Association. Brett is now three goals shy of
catching Mario Lemieux.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have grown up and be a part of what he \RBobby Hull\S did
and then to go on and be able to achieve that for myself is a great
accomplishment I feel very proud of,'' Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   Modano's 38th goal of the season gave the Stars a 1-0 lead on
their first of five first-period power plays. He blistered a
one-timer from the top of the right circle that carried some mean
English and curved around a Calgary defenseman and beat Braithwaite
high to the far corner for a 1-0 lead at the 6:09 mark.
</P>
<P>
   With nothing to gain, the Stars seemingly lost focus and strayed
from their suffocating forecheck and were sloppy in their own end.
The Flames capitalized with an onslaught on Fernandez, whose busy
night also included some spectacular saves.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Shantz cut the Stars' lead in half at the 8:27 mark of the
third period when he deflected in Phil Housley's blast from the
point. Housley tied it when his centering pass from below the goal
line caught the back side of Fernandez's stick blade and trickled
into the net with less than seven minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard, it's two goals I would like to take back,
unfortunately,'' Fernandez said. ``We're stuck with a tie, but it's
better than a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars played their second game without Sergei Zubov, out
with a sprained ligament in his right knee. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
