<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6473 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-04 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
INDIANAPOLIS _ Their eyes met from across the room. Victims of
love.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those early moments in Monday night's NCAA
championship game, one of those supposedly tense and treacherous
times when the game still was close and Michigan State guard Mateen
Cleaves still could walk without a limp.
</P>
<P>
   But as Cleaves finished doing one of those Most Outstanding
Player things of his, blasting through the Florida press, faking,
spinning and flicking in a layup that hardly made the net flinch,
he seemed to make all the pressure fade with a simple smile.
</P>
<P>
   Only one other player to wear Spartans green has ever been able
to show such calm on this kind of stage. And there was that one
player watching from about 20 rows up. There was Magic Johnson
shaking with pride in his MSU sweatshirt, pumping his fist and
pointing down to this Mini-Him of sorts wearing jersey No. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves, who stands 6-2 going on 5-11, glanced up at Johnson and
opened his mouth wide. He smiled and pointed back at Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Hero, say hello to Mini-Hero. Magic, wave at Mini-Magic.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those scenes that seemed almost too choreographed
to be real, much like this whole night. But it was indeed real and
it was wonderful because sometimes a player can possess a game as
radiant as the style with which he plays it.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, two players can be so gifted. Sometimes, one can come
along 21 years after the first.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans hadn't seen this kind of night since 1979, when
Johnson flashed the same type of game and showed the same kind of
dominance by simply being on the floor and being so calm amid the
madness.
</P>
<P>
   It might be trite. It might be corny. But guess what. Sometimes
the hero does come home, sometimes the good guys win in the end,
patience is a virtue, history repeats itself, dreams do come true,
and all that other stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, everything CBS wants in made-for-television drama
does not have to be contrived. It can be real.
</P>
<P>
   So there was the hero from Flint on Monday night, the one with
the darting eyes and bouncy game like we had seen a generation
before. There was Cleaves, who hung around for his senior season
for the most remarkable of reasons _ because he wanted to bring
home the championship to ol' State.
</P>
<P>
   The Florida Gators had come into the RCA Dome with both barrels
of their 21st-century attack blasting. But there was Cleaves
weaving and passing, breaking down the Gators' will as often as
their press with that circa-1979 style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleaves is really tough,'' Gators guard Teddy Dupay said. ``We
could never match him.''
</P>
<P>
   There were the confused and tormented looks on so many Gators'
faces even in the first half as they wondered what was going wrong
with all their big plans.
</P>
<P>
   And then, there was the obligatory riveting drama _ Cleaves
crumbling to the floor and suffering a freaky ankle sprain early in
the second half.
</P>
<P>
   You could almost hear the director barking instructions from the
truck: ``Cut to Cleaves' mom! Cut to Cleaves' mom!''
</P>
<P>
   And there was Mom, a look of concern on her face, one hand
holding a green-and-white pompom, the other covering her mouth in
shock.
</P>
<P>
   There were the Gators beginning to cut into the Spartans' lead.
Cut to a shot of the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   And there was Cleaves, limping back onto the floor and telling
his coach he was ready to go back into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was as storybook as it gets for Mateen,'' MSU coach Tom
Izzo said.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes storybook is wonderful. Cleaves never scored another
point after re-entering the game with 11:51 remaining, but he ran
the show and stole it.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-point lead became a romp. The story ended with Cleaves
(18 points, four assists) standing there facing the Spartans'
stands, hopping on one leg, his arms pumping back and forth, his
head swiveling from one side to the other.
</P>
<P>
   And there was Magic just a few feet away, applauding Mini-Him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might sound strange because (Johnson) is 6-8 and I'm real
little,'' Cleaves said. ``But he's the guy I always looked up to. I
wanted to be just like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Guess what. He was.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
