<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYMINGTON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYMINGTON FINANCES AT
 TACKED
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 BY JERRY KAMMER 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Former Gov. Fife Sy mington acknowledged Monday that
six of his real estate projects were foundering at a time that he
was telling lenders that he had become a multimillionaire because
of those projects' success.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Manning, the attorney who is pursuing Symington in U.S.
Bank ruptcy Court for six union pension funds, used a methodical,
daylong interrogation to attack the 1990 Symington financial
statement that forms the core of the 3-week-old trial.
</P>
<P>
   The pension funds are asking Judge George Nielsen to reject
Symington's attempt to shed his debt on a $10 million loan. With
interest, they estimate the tab at more than $18 million.
</P>
<P>
   The funds claim that Symington used bogus financial statements
not only to get the 1990 loan but also to persuade Arizona voters
that he was a successful businessman who could put the state's
financial house in order.
</P>
<P>
   Symington became governor in 1991 after winning a runoff against
Demo crat Terry Goddard. He was re-elected in 1994, the year before
he declared personal bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Symington, who developed 16 com mercial properties, lost all of
them in the Phoenix area real estate down turn of the late 1980s
and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Manning abandoned the battering ram attack with which
he began questioning Symington on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he laid patient siege to Symington's finances, aiming
to demonstrate that Symington tricked the pension funds into making
the loan that financed the Mercado project in downtown Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Symington acknowledged that in the months before the 1990 loan
he:
</P>
<P>
   Tried to sell his share in a Scottsdale building for $600,000
while giving the pension funds a financial state ment that claimed
its value was $2.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Hired lawyers to advise him on taking six projects into
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Lost all the tenants in a Missouri Avenue office building that
his finan cial statement said was fully occu pied.
</P>
<P>
   During questioning, Symington maintained a patrician calm as he
insisted that those admissions signi fied nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Symington shrugged off Manning's list of failures. The
bankruptcy talk, for example, merely was intended to consider a
possible strategy for pressuring lenders to back off, he said. He
noted that none of the projects went into bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The former governor claimed that his financial statement gave
the pension funds plenty of information to see that he was
vulnerable to the sort of real estate recession that ultimately
forced him into personal bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Denying that he tried to deceive the pension funds, Symington
said that they made no attempt to understand his complex financial
situation. He claims that such questioning would have had little
meaning anyway, because the funds had committed themselves to make
the loan three years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Symington noted that his financial statement reported loans
totaling $178 million at a time when the Phoenix area real estate
market was lurching toward recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe my financial statement shows I was highly leveraged
in a very difficult market,'' the ex-gover nor said.
</P>
<P>
   Invoking a key point of his defense, Symington blamed the
pension funds for not taking a careful look behind his numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had taken time to look and ask questions, they would
have known that I was being buffetted by the market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The trial's outcome could hinge on two hotly contested issues.
</P>
<P>
   The first issue derives from federal bankruptcy law, which
states that the funds can keep Symington on the hook only if they
prove that they acted reasonably in making the loan. That means
that the funds have to defeat Symington's claim that they did
little more with his financial statement than stuff it in their
file.
</P>
<P>
   The second issue derives from a 1987 written agreement in which
the pen sion funds committed to making the loan. Symington says
that agreement, for which he paid $110,000, locked the funds in.
</P>
<P>
   Manning argues that the agreement allowed the pension funds to
back out of the loan if they had the sort of information that
Symington failed to reveal in his financial statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He flat lied to us, and he knows it,'' Manning said after the
court session.
</P>
<P>
   Manning gained ground in court Monday as he noted Symington's
efforts to shore up the loan on a Mesa shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   Symington's records show that his staff feared that if the loan
went into default, the pension funds might have grounds to back out
of the loan.
</P>
<P>
   Manning and Symington sparred over the meaning of a pledge that
Symington gave the pension funds just before receiving the loan. Sy
mington declared that he knew of no ``material adverse change'' in
his financial statement, which reported a $12 million net worth.
</P>
<P>
   Symington said he stood by the statement because he understood
the 1987 agreement to define that term as meaning insolvency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was still solvent and had a viable business,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
