<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6479 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-MICHST-SENIORS-HN     04-04 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MICHST-SENIORS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
INDIANAPOLIS _ When Michigan State's season ended with a loss to
Duke in the national semifinals one year ago, Mateen Cleaves,
Morris Peterson and A.J. Granger made a pact.
<TEXT>
<P>
   They would not leave Michigan State without a national
championship in their senior season.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Cleaves' foot injury that kept him out for 12 games
early in the season, and his ankle injury Monday night in the
national title game, it all came to pass. Behind Cleaves, Peterson
and Granger _ the team's three senior leaders _ the Spartans beat
Florida 89-76.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my God, this is what I came back for,'' said Cleaves, who
thought about leaving college early to enter the NBA but decided to
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the difference was their seniors,'' said Florida
coach Billy Donovan. ``They stepped up and made plays and made
shots every time we'd cut the lead to six or eight points in the
second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson had 21 points, Granger 19 and Cleaves 18, despite
missing part of the second half after twisting his ankle with 16
minutes left in the game. He returned at far less than full speed
with about 12 minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy has the heart of a lion,'' Michigan State coach Tom
Izzo said of Cleaves. ``He has worked for this for four years, and
I knew he wasn't going to let this stop him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take my hat off to our seniors. They came in four years ago,
and we made some promises. Now we have answered those promises.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves was injured after he was fouled by Florida's Teddy
Dupay, landing on Dupay and twisting his ankle. Cleaves was helped
to the dressing room with the Spartans ahead 50-44.
</P>
<P>
   By the time his ankle was taped and he returned with 12 minutes
left, the Spartans were ahead 60-50. During the time Cleaves was
out and shortly thereafter, Granger and Peterson took the game
over.
</P>
<P>
   Granger and Peterson led the Spartans to dazzling 60 percent
shooting from the field (15-of-25) and from 3-point range
(6-of-10).
</P>
<P>
   Granger had nine points in the half, while Peterson had 15
points on 3-of-5 shooting from 3-point range. With Cleaves in the
locker room getting medical attention on his ankle, Granger and
Peterson scored 16 straight points for the Spartans.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan said that before the game, he considered Granger the
X-factor Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called him that going in because we knew that Cleaves and
Peterson were going to probably play well and do a good job
handling our press,'' said Donovan. ``We knew we could not allow
Granger to step out and make 3-point shots. We lost because of what
they did behind the 3-point arc (11-of-22).''
</P>
<P>
   Granger, the least heralded of the three Michigan State seniors,
had no problem accepting the designation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather be that guy, because if you're not in the spotlight
you're going to get more open shots,'' said Granger, who also led
the Spartans with nine rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, Cleaves was instrumental in helping the
Spartans break the Florida press. Twice, Cleaves beat the defense
downcourt and scored on easy layups. Michigan State led 43-32 at
the half, with eight points coming directly from baskets after
breaking Florida's press.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we attacked their press well tonight and pushed the
ball up the floor,'' said Izzo. ``We got some easy baskets early. I
don't know if that broke them or not. We had four turnovers in the
first half.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans turned the ball over 10 times in the second half,
but one subplot in the game spoke plenty about the way they handled
Florida's pressure. Michigan State scored 16 points off turnovers,
while Florida scored 14.
</P>
<P>
   That was one of the main reasons the Michigan State seniors were
able to leave with the title they had dreamed about since last
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to be remembered as champions,'' Granger said. ``No
one remembers who came in second.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
