<HEADER>
A6480 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-LAPD-RAMPART-LADN     04-04 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAPD-RAMPART-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARKS REJECTS IMMUNITY PLANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The union representing Los Angeles police officers
Monday called for a moratorium on any administrative actions
against officers who come forward to break the code of silence and
tell of corruption at the Rampart Division.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Chief Bernard C. Parks issued a scathing
rejection of a proposal last week from District Attorney Gil
Garcetti on a similar offer of confidentiality to officers willing
to provide evidence about the expanding corruption probe.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing his dispute with Garcetti, Parks said the county's
chief prosecutor failed to consult with him or the department
before making his proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no potential positive benefit to the citizens of this
city when this offer is viewed in the context of identifying and
removing corrupt police officers from the department and restoring
faith in the criminal justice system,'' Parks said in his report to
the Police Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather it is a bold declaration of noncooperation ... that
prevents the (LAPD) from its legal obligation to hold officers
accountable for illegal actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Garcetti said he would have no comment on Parks'
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The two have been at odds for more than a month after Garcetti
accused Parks of refusing to allow detectives to cooperate with
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Parks would not accept the Police Protective League's
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``These calls for anonymity and amnesty do not provide a
legitimate path to justice,'' said Cmdr. Dave Kalish, a department
spokesman. ``These proposals are not necessary and clearly send the
wrong message and could very well hamper ongoing investigative
efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Hunt, president of the Los Angeles Police Protective League,
however, argued that the Rampart scandal is an extraordinary event
in the history of the LAPD and requires extraordinary steps to
resolve the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not talking about protecting criminals,,'' Hunt said.
``If they did something wrong, they should be filed on. We are
talking about that if there is a code of silence, let's give people
a chance to break it without further recriminations. Other
governmental institutions provide for whistle-blowers to uncover
wrongdoing and so should the LAPD.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was contained in a letter to the Police Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Commission President Gerald Chaleff said he wanted to review it
before commenting.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Mayor Richard Riordan's office said Riordan would
have no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Cindy Miscikowski, who chairs the City Council's
Public Safety Committee overseeing the LAPD, said she believes the
League proposal has merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a sense that there will be nonretribution, it
might encourage some officers to come forward,'' Miscikowski said.
``I have a feeling that this could be a pressure point, and a lot
of people would come forward. We have to give it a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunt said his proposal calls for the Police Commission to
instruct Inspector General Jeffrey Eglash to deal with the
officers, rather than the District Attorney's Office. Eglash did
not return telephone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's the inspector general acting as an agent for the
Police Commission, we believe an officer can be protected from
reprisals,'' Hunt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a blue wall of silence, we want it torn down. To
assure the public of our officers' complete forthrightness and high
degree of integrity and to assure officers they won't suffer
reprisals, this moratorium is essential.''
</P>
<P>
   Kalish said Parks is concerned that both the Garcetti plan and
League proposal would hamper police investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some cases, these officers might be co-conspirators and are
looking to avoid punishment,'' Kalish said. ``Besides, we have a
number of officers who already have come forward and are providing
information to detectives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
