r a BC-UCLA-AFFIRM-LADN     04-04 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UCLA-AFFIRM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA LAGS SYSTEM IN ADMITTING MINORITIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HARRISON SHEPPARD 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Three years after the University of California
dropped race as a factor in admission, the number of minorities
accepted statewide has nearly bounced back to affirmative action
levels _ except at the two most prestigious campuses, UCLA and
Berkeley, according to figures released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA sent out 10,752 letters of acceptance to high school
seniors for the fall 2000 freshman class, an increase of 4.4
percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   The number of African-American, Chicano/Latino and American
Indian students receiving acceptances was 1,544, an increase of 9.4
percent over the previous year. The only minority group
experiencing a decline was African-Americans, with 315 acceptance
letters going out, down from 329 the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the last year the UC system considered race in
undergraduate admissions, the number of minority students accepted
at UCLA was 2,121.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, the UC system admitted 7,336 minority students, out
of nearly 42,000 total admissions for the fall 2000 freshman class.
That's 100 more than were admitted for fall 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Asian applicants who were offered admissions
dropped slightly, from 14,358 to 14,306. Asians, who did not get
preferential treatment under affirmative action, account for 34
percent of offers systemwide and lead UC Berkeley's freshman class
with 40 percent of admission offers. The numbers of other
minorities admitted to Berkeley this year are still well below 1997
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Most of UCLA's acceptance and rejection letters arrived at
students' homes Saturday, the last of the UC bunch. The arrivals
ended a period described by high school seniors as one of
anticipation and dread.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I'd be the one running out to get the mail,'' said
Karina Quintero, a senior at Francis Polytechnic High School who
was accepted to UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   When the thick envelope arrived with the UCLA seal on the
outside, ``I just couldn't believe it. I was looking at the
envelope and I was overwhelmed with joy,'' said Quintero, 18, of
Pacoima.
</P>
<P>
   Quintero and several other local UCLA-bound minority students
said Monday that they are glad they were accepted based on their
merits alone, and not based on their ethnic background.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always of the opinion that I didn't want to get into a
school just because I was a female Hispanic,'' said Sandra
Hernandez, 17, a North Hollywood High School senior who was
accepted by UCLA but rejected by UC Berkeley. ``I wanted to be
something more than that. I don't think it would've felt right
knowing I got into Berkeley over somebody who was more qualified
than I was just because of that factor.''
</P>
<P>
   But a representative of the Los Angeles-based Mexican American
Legal Defense and Educational Fund said many disadvantaged minority
students are being denied a quality education under the policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think students are being hurt,'' said Theresa Bustillos,
MALDEF's vice president of legal programs. ``If you don't have the
diversity and you don't have (minority) students going to every
campus, then that's hurting very qualified minority students and
that's bad for the future of this state.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, she said, more minority students have ended up at
junior colleges or not attending college at all.
</P>
<P>
   But on the positive side, she believes the state has been paying
more attention to educating minority students at the K-12 level to
make sure they are better prepared for college.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the UC regents decided to reject a 17-year practice of
using affirmative action goals in admission. The following year,
California voters reinforced that decision, passing Proposition
209, which prohibited state agencies from making race-based
decisions. The first year of the new policy, 1998, saw a 36 percent
drop in minority admissions at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Admissions at California State University campuses were not
directly affected by Proposition 209 because the CSU system never
used race as a factor in admissions.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA Admissions Director Rae Lee Siporin said the increase in
Latino students admitted this year and decrease in African-American
students aresimply a reflection of California's demographics: The
Latino population has been growing rapidly, while the
African-American population has not.
</P>
<P>
   According to U.S. Census Bureau estimates, California's Latino
population was 10.1 million in 1998, an increase of more than 31
percent since 1990. By comparison, the African-American population
was 2.45 million in 1998, an increase of only 6.6 percent since
1990.
</P>
<P>
   Siporin said the school has also been working harder in the past
few years to reach out to minority students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working to increase the Latino population and
interest in the university because historically not a huge number
of Latino students have gone on to four years,'' Siporin said.
``We've been trying to make everything more accessible to and of
interest to the Latino population.''
</P>
<P>
   Students have until May 1 to indicate their college choice.
Typically, about 42 percent of the accepted students decide to
attend UCLA, Siporin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 0200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
