<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6482 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKC-NCAAFINAL-HNS &LR;      04-04 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAAFINAL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
INDIANAPOLIS _ For four years, he had longed for the spotlight,
even demanded it at times. Finally, Mateen Cleaves was where he
wanted to be. The man in charge. All eyes on him.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But for a brief moment Monday night, the spotlight was not on
Cleaves' dream. It was on his severely sprained ankle as he limped
to the locker room with a national championship on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, however, the Michigan State senior was back,
and the spotlight returned to what proved to be his immeasurable
heart.
</P>
<P>
   Providing an emotional lift in the last 12 minutes to match his
fantastic play through the first three-fifths of the game, Cleaves
all but willed Michigan State to a rousing 89-76 win over Florida
in a fast-paced NCAA Tournament final Monday night at the RCA Dome.
</P>
<P>
   On crutches following the game, Cleaves said he had no doubt he
would return to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was definitely going to come back,'' said Cleaves, who was
named the Most Outstanding Player of the Final Four. ``I told the
trainer that they would have to amputate my leg to keep me from
going back in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot of pain when I went down. I tried to walk, but I
really couldn't put any pressure on it. Back in the locker room, I
dropped a couple of tears. I was a little sad about it. But they
taped it up good, and luckily I was able to come back and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State (32-7), whose 13-point margin of victory was the
largest in a title game since Duke beat Michigan by 20 points in
1992, claimed its first championship since Magic Johnson led the
Spartans to the crown in 1979. Florida, which was playing in its
first NCAA championship game, finished the season with a 29-8 mark,
equaling the most wins in school history.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves scored all 18 of his points before hurting his ankle,
but he was still invaluable to the Spartans _ from the moment the
sellout crowd of 43,116 spotted him on the jumbo screen making his
way back to the court until the final minute, when the outcome was
decided and he could leap for joy on only one leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy's got the heart of a lion _ not just for one year but
for four years,'' said fifth-year Michigan State coach Tom Izzo.
``I love him because he's what the whole university embodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The three seniors I don't know what I can say to make
everybody know how much they mean to me. They've done a great job
in helping build this program.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans' senior trio of Cleaves, Morris Peterson and A.J.
Granger combined for 68 points, and each hit three 3-pointers as
Michigan State went 11-for-22 from long range and shredded the
Gators' defense by making 55.9 percent of its shots from the field
(33-of-59).
</P>
<P>
   Peterson, who led the Spartans with 21 points, continued his
second-half dominance, scoring 15 after the break. All of those
came after he returned to the game with the limping Cleaves at the
11:51 mark, Michigan State holding on to a slim 50-44 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Barely a minute after Peterson left the game with his third
foul, the collective heart of the Spartans faithful stopped beating
as Cleaves took a nasty spill that resulted in a twisted ankle with
16:18 to play.
</P>
<P>
   It was a wild sequence that started underneath the Florida
basket when Donnell Harvey grabbed an offensive rebound but had his
shot blocked by Aloysius Anagonye. With bodies falling to the floor
in the paint, Anagonye found a streaking Cleaves around midcourt.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves was fouled there by Brett Nelson, but he couldn't hear
the whistle above the roar of the crowd. Cleaves continued to drive
for the layup, hand-fighting with Teddy Dupay the whole way.
</P>
<P>
   After throwing the ball into the basket, Cleaves came down
awkwardly, his ankle tangled with Dupay's. Minutes later, when he
was finally able to limp up the arena tunnel, Michigan State held a
six-point lead, and its two best players were on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   The first indication the Spartans would not wilt came on the
possession immediately after Cleaves' injury. David Chappell
stroked a 3-pointer to get the lead to nine points, but that lift
was erased over the next few minutes before Cleaves and Peterson
returned.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as Peterson hit the floor, he went to work. He sneaked
out on a one-man fast break for a layup, broke the Florida press
and picked up a three-point play with another layup, then drilled
three 3-pointers, the last of which gave Michigan State an 82-62
lead and was the final nail in the coffin for the Gators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I have to get yelled at at halftime or something,'' said
Peterson, who scored 31 of his 41 points in the Final Four after
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Florida, which got a game-high 27 points on 10-of-12 shooting
from Udonis Haslem, should have known it was in trouble at the
half, as it went into the locker room facing a 43-32 deficit. The
Spartans had handled Florida's much-ballyhooed press with ease,
turning the ball over only four times to the Gators' eight in the
first 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators' pressure forced 10 turnovers in the second half, but
they never seemed to be in the ballgame. And the couple of times
they did make a move, Michigan State came up big.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we made a run, they answered,'' said Florida coach
Billy Donovan, who at 34 failed in his attempt to become the
third-youngest coach to win a national championship. ``To me that's
the sign of a great basketball team.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
