<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6483 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT &LR;      04-04 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEILL AND SPENCER GIVE YANKEES VICTORY OVER ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Orlando Hernandez has always seemed to find
tranquillity in big games, in those situations when he is in the
vortex of trouble in the most significant situations, in the
playoffs, in the World Series. On opening day.
</P>
<P>
   Having drawn the assignment of pitching the first game of the
New York Yankees' season, Hernandez found that calmness and kept
his team close long enough for Paul O'Neill and Shane Spencer to
hit home runs in a 3-2 victory over the Anaheim Angels. The Yankees
have opened their season on the West Coast the last four years, and
this was the first time they came away with a victory. Hernandez
allowed a run and eight hits, walking three and striking out four.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Rivera, who came into the game not having allowed a run
since last July 21, a stretch of 30 2/3 innings, had his streak end
Monday night when he gave up a run-scoring single to Mo Vaughn in
the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Yankees were in the clubhouse more than three hours
before Monday's game, some of them already in their full workout
uniforms. With lots of time to kill before batting practice, they
watched baseball on television. Bernie Williams, Chuck Knoblauch
and a dozen others shouted at the highlights of Andres Galarraga's
home run in Atlanta, and of Tony Batista's game-winning blow in
Toronto. Mel Stottlemyre has been in the professional game nearly
40 years and he watched, too. He woke up Monday morning, he said,
and ``I found myself craving it.''
</P>
<P>
   If the tension of competition lures them, then they were all
drawn into their own game by the fifth inning. Anaheim's Tim Salmon
had slugged a home run in the second inning, and the Angels led,
1-0. In the fifth, manager Joe Torre rose out of his seat and
leaned against the railing in the front of the Yankees' dugout. The
situation was getting serious.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had runners at first and second and one out and Darin
Erstad popped up weakly toward left, flipping his bat away
disconsolately. But shortstop Derek Jeter, chasing the fly well
onto the grass, peeled away thinking that Spencer in left field
would catch the ball. Spencer pulled up, figuring Jeter would make
the catch. The ball fell, the bases were loaded with one out and
Anaheim had a chance to seize control of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez threw a fastball high on his first pitch to the next
batter, Adam Kennedy. Stottlemyre jogged to the mound to calm
Hernandez, saying something that caused the pitcher to laugh. The
right-hander had seemed out of rhythm in the early innings, cutting
off his delivery prematurely when throwing a couple of breaking
balls, and he did not have much zip on his fastball. But he had to
navigate his way through this mess.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez jammed Kennedy with a fastball, the second baseman
barely lifting a blooper at third baseman Scott Brosius, who made
the easy catch with the runners hustling back to the bases _ and
Hernandez screaming at him to let the ball fall. If Brosius had
done so, he almost certainly could thrown home or to second to
start a double play, for Kennedy had barely moved from the batter's
box.
</P>
<P>
   From El Duque's perspective, the defense behind him had given
away two outs and now Vaughn was walking to the plate, a grand slam
waiting to happen. Hernandez had struck out Vaughn in his first two
at-bats with off-speed pitches _ once whiffing him with a 67 mph
curveball after throwing mostly fastballs _ and with the count one
ball and two strikes, Hernandez threw his hardest fastball to that
point, 90 mph, Vaughn leaning back. Two balls and two strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Again, Hernandez followed that fastball with a changeup, and
Vaughn swung over the top, missing and killing the threat.
Hernandez has been much more relaxed this spring, teammates have
noticed, but as he came off the mound after that inning, he was
yelling to himself, his head and hands bouncing with the syllables.
The momentum had turned.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter returned to the dugout after the inning, met briefly with
Spencer and Torre to review the muffed pop-up and then pulled on
his helmet to lead off the inning. Jeter pulled a single into the
hole at shortstop, bringing O'Neill to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had two hits in the first five innings, but as they
have done so often in the last three years, they had worn down the
opposing pitcher, Ken Hill, with their patient and pesky approach.
The first 14 batters to hit for the Yankees had taken the first
pitch, and it wasn't until Hill threw his 64th pitch _ to Tino
Martinez _ that any Yankee swung and missed. The Anaheim
right-hander, who threw into the sixth inning only one time all
spring, required 57 pitches in the first three innings, breathing
heavily at the end of that frame.
</P>
<P>
   He was approaching 100 pitches and threw O'Neill what was
supposed to be a sinking fastball. But the ball remained over the
plate and O'Neill, a low-ball hitter, smashed it. At the sound of
contact, Ricky Ledee threw his arms into the air in the Yankees
dugout, where the rest of the players rushed forward to see
O'Neill's ball land over the center field wall, an estimated 430
feet from home plate. The Yankees led, 2-1; Hill was relieved two
batters later.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer, given a chance to be a regular member of the lineup
this season, bashed a home run in the seventh, pushing the Yankees'
advantage to two runs. Vaughn came to bat again in the seventh, two
outs and a runner at first base, and Hernandez's next-to-last pitch
of the night was his hardest, a 91 mph fastball. Vaughn swung and
missed that for strike two, then grounded out weakly on the next
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez strolled off the field. The marathon has begun,
Stottlemyre said before the game, and El Duque ran the first leg. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
