<HEADLINE>
KINGS LOSE GAME, MAYBE SMOLINSKI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Kings' first game after clinching a playoff spot
had no Rob Blake, no Stephane Fiset and no real letdown.
</P>
<P>
   And though their 2-1 loss Monday night against Phoenix clinched
a playoff spot for the Coyotes, the Kings maintained their momentum
for the first round that begins next week.
</P>
<P>
   Without Blake, who remained in Los Angeles with a bruised knee,
Jere Karalahti stepped in and provided a spark.
</P>
<P>
   Without Fiset, who played perhaps his best game of the season in
Saturday's clincher against the Mighty Ducks, the Kings turned to
Jamie Storr, who faced 30 shots in the first two periods alone.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until rookie Trevor Letowski ripped a shot past Storr
with 11:06 in the third period that the Coyotes took the lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes' victory moved them to within a point of the Kings
(37-31-11) for the fifth spot in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever finishes fifth is expected to face the mighty Detroit
Red Wings in the first round. The number six team probably will
face Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix, which plays its next two games at home before finishing
at home Sunday at Dallas, has one more victory than the Kings, but
three more losses.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings move on to Vancouver, where they play Wednesday night
against the Canucks. Then it's back home Friday night for the
Stars, and the final game of the regular season Sunday in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The team, however, could be playing without second line center
Bryan Smolinski, who suffered a knee injury in the final minutes
during a collision with the Coyotes' Travis Green.
</P>
<P>
   With injuries this season to captain Keith Tkachuk, Letowski has
19 goals this season, including seven in the third period alone.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was the first in four games for the Kings at America
West Arena. The Kings dropped all three meetings at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes were coming off a demoralizing loss Saturday at
Edmonton, their chief competition for the sixth spot in the West
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 3-0, Phoenix scored three goals late in the third
period only to lose in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the Kings, who last month overtook Phoenix in the
conference and the Pacific Division, the Coyotes had 18 shots
against Storr in the first period but did not score.
</P>
<P>
   The game was scoreless until Murray's 28th goal of the season at
the 4:16 mark of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Center Jozef Stumpel, who has worked well with Murray since
Ziggy Palffy went down with a sprained right shoulder, skated into
the Coyotes zone and took the Phoenix defense with him.
</P>
<P>
   Murray hustled past Greg Adams on the right and Stumpel gave him
the puck. Murray fired at Sean Burke's weak side and beat him over
the right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes were 0 for 3 on the power play in the first
period,including a 5 on 3 advantage in the first three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   After a loud meeting by coach Bob Francis between periods, the
Coyotes started to pick up their game midway through the second.
</P>
<P>
   At the 10:30 mark, Benoit Hogue circled the Kings defense and
passed in front to Dallas Drake for the tying goal.
</P>
<P>
   For Drake, who has been widely criticized for a hit last
Saturday on Edmonton's Bob Devereaux, it was his 14th goal of the
season and 300th NHL point.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix slowly took control of the period.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings Luc Robitaille had an excellent scoring chance with
six minutes left, but defenseman Lyle Odelein dropped to the ice
and stopped the puck with his chest.
</P>
<P>
   With 2:32 remaining in the period, the Coyotes had a great
chance to take the lead. Letowski had two open looks at the net,
but both shots were blocked by Storr.
</P>
