<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS KEEP HOPES ALIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- If not for his bright red hair Jorgen Jonsson would
gone virtually unoticed since he was acquired by the Mighty Ducks
from the New York Islanders on March 11. The quiet 27-year old
Swedish center had only one assist in his first nine games with
Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   But Jonsson made the crowd of 15,759 at The Pond take notice
Monday night when he did more than his share to keep the Ducks'
fading playoff hopes alive in a 3-1 victory over the Nashville
Predators.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim had controlled virtually all of the first two periods,
but the Ducks were locked in a 1-1 tie when Jonsson scored on a
sharp angle from along the right boards at 18:26 to give them a
much-needed lift, and the lead, heading into the final period.
</P>
<P>
   Then early in the third he jumped off the bench and carried the
puck quickly into the Nashville zone. He pulled up in the high slot
and slipped a nice pass to Kip Miller in the left circle, who beat
Nashville's Mike Dunham on the stick side with Anaheim's first shot
of the period at 1:50.
</P>
<P>
   The two points doubled Jonsson's Anaheim point total and they
were the difference in a game that was much too close for the
Ducks' comfort. Anaheim outshot the outhit the Predators, outshot
them 33-17 and outchanced them by a wide margin.
</P>
<P>
   But the pesky Predators hung around just long enough to make
things interesting, thanks to the outstanding play of Dunham.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was a must coming in, but it became even more
important when San Jose defeated Edmonton 1-0. That result was
another a blow to the Ducks' best chance of making the playoffs
(catching San Jose), but Anaheim's win keeps it within striking
distance of both the eighth-place Sharks and seventh-place Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   If the Ducks (33-34-12-2) were to win their remaining three
games, the Sharks will need four points in their last three to
assure the Ducks can't pass them, while the Oilers would need three
in their final three games.
</P>
<P>
   It took the Kings over 24 minutes to get a shot on goal on
Saturday. Nashville needed only 18 seconds, but the Predators also
took an early penalty and the Ducks made them pay the price.
</P>
<P>
   Drake Berehowsky was called for holding Teemu Selanne's stick 52
seconds into the game and it was Selanne who set up Anaheim's first
goal. From behind the net the winger found Steve Rucchin wide open
in the slot and the center easily beat Dunham at 1:40. The goal was
Rucchin's 17th of the season, but his first in eight games.
</P>
<P>
   While Hebert wasn't serious tested in the opening period, Dunham
kept his team in the game by stopping Antti Aalto from close range
after a Predators turnover and Ladislav Kohn on a two-on-one. The
Nashville goalie also got a good break when the puck bounced over
Selanne's stick with the net wide open.
</P>
<P>
   The game was beginning to look more and more like a repeat of
Saturday's loss in Los Angeles, especially when Cliff Ronning
slipped a backhander through Hebert's pads at 8:10 to tie the game,
1-1, shortly after Dunham and the Predators had survived a flurry
that included chances by Paul Kariya, Mike Leclerc and Kohn.
</P>
<P>
   Dunham stopped Kariya while the Ducks were on the power play,
but then Jonsson finally made his mark with the Ducks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
