<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS--LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS FALL SHORT IN OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Mo Vaughn had waited all winter for the opportunity
he had in Monday night's season-opener against the defending World
Series champion New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   After an off-season of rehabilitating his severely sprained left
ankle, and regaining a passion for the game, the Angels first
baseman found himself where he wanted to be -- standing at
homeplate with the game on his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   But Vaughn, batting with the bases loaded, two out and the
Angels clinging to a 1-0 lead in the fifth inning, struck out
against Yankees pitcher Orlando Hernandez. Vaughn struck out three
times and was 0 for 4 before his RBI single in the ninth inning cut
the Yankees' lead to 3-2. But it wasn't enough as Mariano Rivera
got Tim Salmon on a fly to right with the tying run on second base,
finishing the 3-2 Yankees victory before a sellout crowd of 42,704
at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' Paul O'Neill took advantage of his opportunity only
moments after Vaughn's fifth-inning strikeout, hitting a two-run
homer off Angels starter Ken Hill for a 2-1 Yankees lead in the
sixth inning. One inning later, Shane Spencer homered off Angels
reliever Kent Mercker for a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hill (0-1) pitched well in defeat, giving up two runs and four
hits in 5 1/3 innings. Hernandez (1-0) was better, allowing one run
-- on a home run by Salmon -- and eight hits in seven innings. The
Angels out-hit the Yankees, 10-6.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon had given the Angels a 1-0 lead, hitting Hernandez's
first pitch of the second inning into the bullpen beyond the
left-field fence. It was the third opening-day homer for Salmon in
his career.
</P>
<P>
   Hill made the lead stand up early on, and he got plenty of help
from his catcher, Bengie Molina. Through four innings, the Yankees
had two hits -- a single by Chuck Knoblauch to lead off the game,
and a single by O'Neill leading off the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   But Molina threw out both Knoblauch and O'Neill trying to steal,
thwarting any potential Yankees rally. Through five innings, those
two hits were all that Hill allowed.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that Hill is the ace of the rotation after elbow
troubles and a 4-11 record last season has had many observers
predicting a miserable season for the club. But Scioscia has been
optimistic about his team's chances this year from the moment he
first donned perwinkle blue.
</P>
<P>
   Last season the Angels finished in last place after too many
injuries to key players and internal strife, but Scioscia said that
is no reason to predict the same in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the Braves in '91 or the Dodgers in '88, both
teams were fourth place the year before,'' Scioscia said. ``So it's
possible. People say we don't have the pitching. Well, I'm looking
at the other side of the coin. History has proven it can be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm basing my optimism on is the arms are better than a
lot of people give 'em credit for. And our offense stacks up with
anybody's.''
</P>
<P>
   That offense had a chance to break open the game in the fifth
inning against Hernandez. Scott Spiezio opened the inning with an
infield single and one out later, Gary DiSarcina singled Spiezio to
second.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad followed with a popup to shallow left field, where
at the last moment shortstop Derek Jeter moved away from the ball.
The left fielder Spencer had no play and the Angels had the bases
loaded with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Kennedy, who doubled in his previous at-bat, hit a weak
popup to Scott Brosius at third for the second out of the inning,
bringing up Vaughn. But Vaughn, who struck in his first two
at-bats, struck out for the third time to end the threat. He
grounded out to first in his fourth at-bat, then singled home
DiSarcina with two out in the ninth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
