<HEADLINE>
KINGS LOSE GAME AND SMOLINSKI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Kings didn't want to lose, but it was more
important not to lose players.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they are looking at going the rest of the way without
second-line center Bryan Smolinski, who sprained his right knee in
the final 16 seconds of Monday's 2-1 loss to the Phoenix Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski, who made a dramatic defensive play Saturday in the
Kings' playoff clinching victory over the Mighty Ducks, was struck
on the side of the leg when the Coyotes' Travis Green fell to the
ice.
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski will return to Los Angeles today, but coach Andy
Murray said it was the kind of injury - a sprained medial
collateral ligament - that would sideline a player six weeks during
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so disappointing,'' said Luc Robitaille. ``But now
we have to find someone else to do the job. There is too much at
stake.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory clinched a playoff spot for Phoenix, which had
dropped behind the Kings after a seven-game losing streak. Now, the
Coyotes are just two points behind the Kings for the fifth spot in
the Western Conference and the unhappy prospect of playing Detroit
in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings already are playing without Ziggy Palffy (sprained
right shoulder), who should be back for the playoffs and Nelson
Emerson (broken left index finger), who probably won't.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Rob Blake also did not make the trip due to a bruised
left knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so close to the end and now these injuries,'' said
Jozef Stumpel, who assisted on Glen Murray's second-period goal.
``We'll be okay, but we sure are getting tested.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings also played without goalie Stephane Fiset, who played
perhaps his best game of the season in Saturday's clincher. The
Kings turned to Jamie Storr, who faced 30 shots in the first two
periods alone and 33 overall.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until rookie Trevor Letowski ripped a shot past Storr
with 11:06 in the third period that the Coyotes took the lead.
</P>
<P>
   With injuries this season to captain Keith Tkachuk, Letowski has
19 goals this season, including seven in the third period alone.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix, which plays its next two games at home before finishing
Sunday in Dallas has one more victory than the Kings, but three
more losses.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings move on to Vancouver, where they play Wednesday night
against the Canucks. Then it's back home for the Stars on Friday
night and the final game of thr regular season Sunday at Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The loss also was the first in four games for the Kings at
America West Arena. The Kings dropped all three meetings at Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes were coming off a demoralizing loss last Saturday at
Edmonton, their chief competition for the sixth spot in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 3-0, Phoenix scored three goals late in the third
period only to lose in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the Kings, who last month overtook Phoenix in the
conference and the Pacific Division, had 18 shots against Storr in
the first period but did not score.
</P>
<P>
   The game was scoreless until Murray's 28th goal of the season at
4:16 of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Center Jozef Stumpel, who has worked well with Murray since
Ziggy Palffy went down with a sprained right shoulder, skated into
the Coyotes zone and took the Phoenix defense with him.
</P>
<P>
   Murray hustled past Greg Adams on the right and Stumpel gave him
the puck. Murray fired at Sean Burke's weak side and beat him over
the right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes were 0 for 3 on the power play in the first
period,including a 5-on-3 advantage in the first three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   After a loud meeting by coach Bob Francis between periods, the
Coyotes started to pickup their game midway through the second.
</P>
<P>
   At the 10:30 mark, Benoit Hogue circled the Kings defense and
passed in front to Dallas Drake for the tying goal.
</P>
<P>
   For Drake, who has been widely criticized for a hit last
Saturday on Edmonton's Bob Devereaux, it was his 14th goal of the
season and 300th NHL point.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix slowly took control of the period. The Kings Luc
Robitaille had an excellent scoring chance with six minutes left,
but defenseman Lyle Odelein dropped to the ice and stopped the puck
with his chest.
</P>
<P>
   With 2:32 remaining in the period, the Coyotes had a great
chance to take the lead. Letowski had two open looks at the net,
but both shots were blocked by Storr.
</P>
