<HEADLINE>
OPENING NIGHT AT EDISON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ 5 p.m.: Seven members of the Angels' all-time
team Bobby Grich, Doug DeCinces, Mike Witt, Brian Downing, Bob
Boone, Frank Tanana and Reggie Jackson are supposed to be present
at an interview room for a press conference. But the only people
present are impatient members of the media.
</P>
<P>
   5:15: Five gentlemen from the Angels' distinguished group Grich,
DeCinces, Witt, Downing and Tanana finally are brought in by the
team's communication director, Tim Mead. Where's Reggie?
</P>
<P>
   5:20: Grich reflects on his greatest Angel moment going 5 for 5
one Sunday afternoon against the New York Yankees. ``After I hit a
home run against Ron Guidry, I was given a standing ovation and
came out and tipped my hat to the crowd,'' recalls Grich. ``I'll
never forget that golden moment because there was a beautiful girl
in a red dress in the second row.'' The one-time Long Beach single
guy once had quite a notoriously passionate eye for the ladies. But
these days he's lapsed into the less humdrum life of doting
husband/papa/golf feign in Coto de Caza out in Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   5:30: Bob Boone shows up, and actually says that the 1982 and
1986 Western Division-winning teams had some of the greatest
personnel in the history of baseball. And the guy said it with the
straightest of faces.
</P>
<P>
   6:15: Reggie Jackson is spotted! He's in front of the Yankees'
dugout doing what he does best these days networking. I didn't
bother to ask him why he missed the press conference because, well,
it's never been one of my overwhelming compulsions in life to talk
to Reggie Jackson, even when he was a somebody.
</P>
<P>
   7:00: I run into Tony Tavares, and Michael Eisner's
man-in-waiting with the Angels says, ``I'm sure we're going to hit
well. We'll go as far as our pitching will take us.'' I simply
didn't have the nerve to inform Mr. Tavares in the bliss of early
April that the Angel pitching won't take the team into October.
</P>
<P>
   7:40: They're singing the National Anthem, an American Bald
Eagle named Challenger is set to descend on the infield, and I'll
play Regis and give you a million dollars if you can figure out
what Long Beach figure is a commanding presence in the middle of
the Edison Field diamond. Give up? Why, of course, it is none other
than that ol' Long Beach mayoral candidate, Ski Demski,
resplendent, as always, in his flowing Santa Claus beard as he
oversees the unfurling of one of his 300-feet American flags.
</P>
<P>
   7:44: Play ball. The temperature is a mild 70 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   7:45: Surprise. New York Yankee leadoff batter Chuck Knoblauch
singles.
</P>
<P>
   7:46: Surprise. Knoblauch is caught stealing by the new Angels
catcher, Bengie Molina.
</P>
<P>
   7:52: Surprise. Angels starter Ken Hill gets out of the inning
without yielding a run to the mighty Yankees. Hey, who says the
Angels' pitching is lousy?
</P>
<P>
   7:56: Darin Erstad opens with a single.
</P>
<P>
   8:03: Mo Vaughn makes it through the first inning this time
without tearing up his ankle, but he doesn't make it through
without whiffing on a textbook change up thrown by Orlando ``El
Duque'' Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   8:15: Can you believe it? Ken Hill has a shutout going after two
innings!
</P>
<P>
   8:18: Rockets explode! The crowd explodes. Tim Salmon slams El
Duque's first pitch 430 feet over the left-field wall. How about
those Angels! They actually have a 1-0 lead against the defending
world champions.
</P>
<P>
   8:35: Wow. Ken Hill has made it through three innings, giving up
only that measly hit to Knoblauch. And to think I've been
questioning the quality of Angel pitching.
</P>
<P>
   8:44: The Angels' self-professed Big RBI Man, Mo Vaughn, isn't.
He strikes out again on an El Duque change after Adam Kennedy
doubles.
</P>
<P>
   8:50: Bengie Molina guns out another Yankee base runner, the
not-so-fleet Paul O'Neill. No wonder the Angels dumped Todd Greene.
</P>
<P>
   8:51: Ken Hill still is working on a shutout. And four innings
are in the book!
</P>
<P>
   9:04: Mo Vaughn is charged with first Angel error of the season
when first base umpire Terry Craft claims his misguided throw pulls
Ken Hill off first base on a grounder by Shane Spencer. TV replays
indicate Hill's foot touches the bag ahead of Spencer. Why wasn't
the new Angel manager, Mike Scioscia, out there arguing?
</P>
<P>
   9:09: Mo Vaughn flags down Knoblauch's check-swing grounder, and
makes another lousy throw to Hill that this time Terry Craft
acknowledges arrives in time to assure Hill of five shutout
innings.
</P>
<P>
   9:20: Derek Jeter gives up on Gary DeSarcina's pop fly to short
left ield, figuring Shane Spencer will catch it. But Spencer also
shies away, and suddenly the Angels have the bases loaded with a
chance to break open the game.
</P>
<P>
   9:22: An opportunity for redemption for Mo Vaughn. Alas, El
Duque strikes him out for the third time in five innings. The
Angels have seven hits off the cagey Yankee right-ander, but,
ominously, they have only that one run produced by Salmon. They
also have stranded five base runners, four by Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   9:31: Finally, form prevails. Hill, as he's known to do after a
few innings, falters. After Jeter singles, O'Neill homers, and, as
quickly as you can say Mo Vaughn, the Yankees silence the capacity
crowd and take a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   9:35: Hill is replaced by Kent Mercker, who gets the Angels out
of the innings without any further damage.
</P>
<P>
   9:56: Angels threatening again with runners on first and second,
and Bengie Molina facing Hernandez. But Bengie fares as feebly as
Vaughn, popping up weakly to Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   9:59: Shane Spencer's home run gives the Yankees a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   10:10: Poor Mo Vaughn. He strands still another base runner, but
at least this time he doesn't strike out. He grounds out to Tino
Martinez at first base. It doesn't look good for the home town
heroes, as deadline prohibitions arrive. El Duque is cruising and
the Yankees are only an inning away from Mariano Rivera. The Angels
seem destined for the first of what figures to be many losses this
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
