<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS FALL SHORT IN OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM - Mo Vaughn had waited all winter for the opportunity he
had in Monday night's season opener against the defending World
Series champion New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   After an offseason of rehabilitating his severely sprained left
ankle, and regaining a passion for the game, the Angels first
baseman found himself where he wanted to be - standing at home
plate with the game on his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   But Vaughn, batting with the bases loaded, two out and the
Angels clinging to a 1-0 lead in the fifth inning, struck out
against Yankees pitcher Orlando Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn struck out three times and was 0 for 4 before his RBI
single in the ninth inning cut the Yankees' lead to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't enough as Mariano Rivera got Tim Salmon on a fly
to right with the tying run on second base, finishing the 3-2
Yankees victory before a sellout crowd of 42,704 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' Paul O'Neill took advantage of his opportunity only
moments after Vaughn's fifth-inning strikeout, hitting a two-run
home run off Angels starter Ken Hill for a 2-1 Yankees lead in the
sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   One inning later, Shane Spencer homered off Angels reliever Kent
Mercker for a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Hill (0-1) pitched well in defeat, giving up two runs and four
hits in 5 innings. Hernandez (1-0) was better, allowing one run -
on a home run by Salmon - and eight hits in seven innings. The
Angels outhit the Yankees 10-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a lot of good things, the only bad thing was we didn't
win the ballgame,'' said Angels manager Mike Scioscia.
</P>
<P>
   And Hernandez had as much to do with that as anybody.
</P>
<P>
   His funky delivery, ability to change speeds and throw at
different arm angles had the Angels hitters on their heels all
night. Particularly Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   ``His ball doesn't stay in the zone long,'' Vaughn said. ``He
makes his pitches. Some guys hit the ball hard, but they hit 'em
foul. Not a lot of guys throw the baseball like he threw tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn already had struck out twice against Hernandez before
facing him in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He changed up every at-bat,'' said Vaughn. ``He was as sharp
as I've ever seen him. Over the course of the game I think I swung
at one bad ball. Everything was on the corners. He threw strikes,
but you couldn't pick up a pattern.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Be careful,'' Hernandez said he told himself when facing
Vaughn in the fifth. ``Make your pitches because Mo Vaughn is one
of the best hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon had given the Angels a 1-0 lead, hitting Hernandez's
first pitch of the second inning into the bullpen beyond the
left-field fence. It was the third opening-day homer for Salmon in
his career.
</P>
<P>
   Hill made the lead stand up early on, and he got plenty of help
from his catcher, Bengie Molina. Through four innings, the Yankees
had two hits - a single by Chuck Knoblauch to lead off the game,
and a single by O'Neill leading off the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   But Molina threw out both Knoblauch and O'Neill trying to steal,
thwarting any potential Yankees rally. Through five innings, those
two hits were all that Hill allowed.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth inning, it appeared Hill had a 1-2-3 inning. But a
bad call by first-base ump Terry Craft extended the inning. And
even though Hill got out of that inning, it took its toll on him in
the next inning, when O'Neill homered after an infield single by
Derek Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have gone longer,'' Hill said of his 5 innings. ``But
that play at first cost me another 10 bullets.''
</P>
<P>
   The fifth inning that began so promising started with Scott
Spiezio's infield single.
</P>
<P>
   One out later, Gary DiSarcina singled Spiezio to second. Darin
Erstad, who had three hits, followed with a popup to shallow left
field, where at the last moment shortstop Jeter moved away from the
ball. Left fielder Spencer had no play and the Angels had the bases
loaded with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Kennedy (Cal State Northridge), who doubled in his previous
at-bat, hit a weak popup to Scott Brosius at third for the second
out of the inning, bringing up Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   But Vaughn, who struck in his first two at-bats, struck out for
the third time to end the threat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 0301EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
