<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS KEEP SLIM HOPES ALIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM - If not for his bright red hair, Jorgen Jonsson would
have gone virtually unnoticed since he was acquired by the Mighty
Ducks from the New York Islanders on March 11.
</P>
<P>
   The quiet 27-year-old Swedish center had only one assist in his
first nine games with Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   But Jonsson made the crowd of 15,759 at the Pond take notice
Monday night when he helped keep the Ducks' fading playoff hopes
alive by scoring the game-winning goal and setting up another in a
3-1 victory over the Nashville Predators.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim had controlled virtually all of the first two periods,
but the Ducks were locked in a 1-1 tie when Jonsson scored on a
sharp angle from along the right boards at 18:26 to give them a
much-needed lift, and the lead, heading into the final period.
</P>
<P>
   Then early in the third he jumped off the bench and carried the
puck quickly into the Nashville zone.
</P>
<P>
   He pulled up in the high slot and slipped a nice pass to Kip
Miller in the left circle. Miller beat Nashville's Mike Dunham on
the stick side with Anaheim's first shot of the period at 1:50.
</P>
<P>
   Jonsson, according to Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg, hadn't been
playing poorly, but the former Islander admitted he has been
pressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' he said when asked if was bothered by his lack of
production since his arrival in Anaheim. ``It's been a long time
since I've had a good game in terms of points. It gets to your
mind, you wonder what you are doing wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge goal,'' said Hartsburg of Jonsson's 12th of the
season - he scored the first 11 for the Islanders. ``Going into the
third period tied after playing so well would have been edgy.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Ducks were aware that eighth-place San Jose had
defeated Edmonton, but they didn't let up in the final period, or
most of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim outshot the Predators 34-17, outhit and outchanced them.
And thanks to Jonsson they scored just enough despite some
outstanding goaltending by Dunham.
</P>
<P>
   ``We managed to score tonight,'' said defenseman Oleg Tverdosvky
of the Ducks, who had been limited to one goal in seven of their
previous 14 games. ``It's simple, you score you win.''
</P>
<P>
   Three goals were more than enough for Guy Hebert, who said, ``I
probably could get used to games like this, the more the merrier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys are doing an unbelievable job out there,'' added the
Anaheim goalie. ``I'd have to go back to maybe recreation hockey
when the last time I was facing just 15-16 shots a game.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was a must coming in, but it became even more
important when San Jose defeated Edmonton 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   That result was another a blow to the Ducks' best chance of
making the playoffs (catching San Jose), but Anaheim's win keeps it
within striking distance of both the eighth-place Sharks and
seventh-place Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   It also kept the team's spirits up heading into games in Chicago
on Wednesday and Nashville on Friday. Anaheim completes the regular
season Sunday against the Kings at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still exciting to be on the cusp of the playoffs,'' said
Hebert. ``I would rather playing with a ray of hope than be one of
the teams that has already been eliminated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 0302EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
