<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-SPOON-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS' NATIONAL HOLIDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG SPOON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If sports fans ruled the government, Monday would've been a
national holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Since it wasn't, I left the office early, grabbed some extra
batteries for the TV remote and settled into my easy chair for the
best six hours of sports entertainment since the Super Bowl pregame
show.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers opened their season in Montreal at 4:30 p.m.
Michigan State and Florida met in the NCAA basketball championship
game beginning at 6. The Angels opened at home against the Yankees
at 7:30, the same time the Kings started their game in Phoenix and
the Ducks dropped the puck at home against Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Five games, all televised on different stations. Opening Day in
one sport, Closing Day in another and two hockey games with playoff
implications.
</P>
<P>
   Boy, this is a tough job sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   First observation, made about 5:15 p.m. while glued to Channel
5: The Dodgers aren't real solid up the middle. Of course, they
don't have to be to beat the Expos. The problem will be beating the
Diamondbacks and Giants in a National League West race that appears
to be up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers will try to get by this season with 35-year-old
Kevin Elster at shortstop. Hope he gets to ground balls better than
he did Monday night. Watching the guy flop around on the Olympic
Stadium artificial turf on ground balls up the middle was almost as
painful as watching 37-year-old Devon White bobble the balls that
get past Elster.
</P>
<P>
   None of that mattered by the time Eric Karros' grand slam in the
seventh inning put the Dodgers ahead to stay in a game they won
easily, 10-4. Time to click over to the NCAA game.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Packer, who's been announcing games since God created CBS,
was drooling all over himself before the game ever started.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is not about the few who will make it to the NBA,
but about the hundreds trying to get their MBA's,'' Packer screamed
during the pregame show.
</P>
<P>
   You mean college athletes go to class?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Michigan State showed early that it was too big and too
strong for Florida, no matter how quick the Gators thought they
were. Teams like Florida and Wisconsin gave the Final Four some
drama, but did anyone really think the Spartans would not come out
on top?
</P>
<P>
   By halftime Michigan State led, 43-32. Early in the second half
Mateen Cleaves sprained an ankle, but he limped back onto the court
moments later. How inspirational. The Spartans barely needeed him,
especially with A.J. Granger burying jumpers and Morris Peterson
beating the Gators back on the fast break.
</P>
<P>
   A quick click over to KCAL revealed a film clip introducing the
Angels-Yankees game. Some overzealous film editor decided to string
together old and new clips of Angels moments with shots of Babe
Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong with this picture?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on Fox Sports Net 2, the Ducks were already ahead of
Nashville, 1-0. Too little too late? Anaheim entered the game three
points out of a playoff spot with four games remaining. That's what
happens when you let 99 percent of the league into the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Back on CBS, Michigan State wrapped up an 89-76 win for the
national title. A limping Cleaves still had plenty of spring left
as the Spartans prepared to cut down the nets. OK, back to
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got a strong outing by Ken Hill and some fancy
footwork afield by Mo Vaughn to take a 1-0 lead over the Yankees
through five innings. Too bad the game lasts nine. In the sixth,
Paul O'Neil hit a two-run homer for a 2-1 Yankees lead.
</P>
<P>
   Silly me. I remained optimistic anyway. Must be all that Opening
Day euphoria. It's enough to make one take only a brief check of
the hockey scores (Kings tied 1-1, Ducks leading 2-1).
</P>
<P>
   Still, I had to keep reminding myself it's early. Real early. A
baseball season that began at 2 a.m. in Tokyo last week will last
for dozens of summer nights and thousands of clicks on that old
remote.
</P>
<P>
   Time for some more AAA batteries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
