<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-SIDE-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS FANS DON'T EXPECT MUCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ To mark their 40th anniversary, the Angels
splayed a mural of their all-time team across the outfield fence
and invited the players to Edison Field to be honored in front of
Monday night's season-opening crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Chuck Finley was not available. He's preparing to
pitch today for Cleveland. Jim Edmonds also sent his regards. He
was playing center field for St. Louis on Monday. Don Baylor might
have been in an Angel uniform, too, but he's running the Cubs --- a
matter of dollars (Disney's) and sense (Baylor's).
</P>
<P>
   Their presence might have given Angels fans something to look
forward to once the game started. Instead, those who were brave
enough to wear Angels jerseys or caps --- they were outnumbered by
Yankee fans about 4 to 1 --- seemed resigned to another season of
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   If Yankee fans came to the park with visions of another World
Series championship, Angels fans were already willing to say
fuhgedaboudit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been an Angel fan for 25 years, so I've had to deal with
this 22 times,'' said Scott Vandenberg, a firefighter from Cypress.
I don't think the pitching is very good. If they can out-slug
people, maybe they'll do OK but I'm a dreamer.''
</P>
<P>
   The failure to make a substantial offer to Finley, a career
Angel and fan favorite, is what bothered several fans. Particularly
since the staff ace is now Ken Hill, who won four games last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife said the baby was kicking her on the way here,'' said
Vince Defabiis of Upland, who attended the game with his pregnant
wife, Cami. ``I think it was nervous that Hill was pitching
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The expectations inside the clubhouse are quite different than
outside it, insisted Angels manager Mike Scioscia, who's embarking
on his first major-league season as manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you said the word --- external,'' said Scioscia, when
asked about the low expectations. ``Nobody in our organization,
from the front office to the clubhouse, doesn't believe that this
is a championship caliber team.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the salary-cutting moves the Angels have made since last
summer --- dumping Omar Olivares, Randy Velarde, Edmonds and Finley
--- they spared no expense for the pre-game ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Three-hundred Edison employees unfurled a 300-foot wide American
flag. (The seamstress may want to stick around; the pitching staff
figures to need work soon.) The red glare of fireworks accompanied
the national anthem, sung by Mandie Pinto.
</P>
<P>
   Most impressive, however, was the finale when an American bald
eagle named Challenger --- perhaps as close as the Angels get to
one all year --- descended from the upper deck and landed safely on
the pitcher's mound.
</P>
<P>
   This was a marked improvement from the last such Disney stunt,
when at a Mighty Ducks opener a few years ago, the team's mascot,
Wild Wing, descended from the rafters of the Pond through a shower
of fireworks only to catch on fire. Duck l'orange, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   This time the wings were OK. Now, it seems, all the Angels need
is a prayer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
