<SLUG> BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTACKING THE PEOPLE'S ABILITY TO GOVERN THEMSELVES 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the 
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has a national reputation for First
Amendment commentary. His e-mail address is
levendos(AT-sign)trib.com.) 
(gm) 
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   It
takes a piggish amount of arrogance to attempt to limit the free
speech rights of the people. But most of Congress is up to it _ as
well as many state legislators, mayors and governors.
<TEXT>
<P>
   On March 29, the U.S. Senate was only four votes shy of passing
a flag desecration amendment that would have limited the First
Amendment protections of the Bill of Rights. The U.S. House had
already passed the amendment last June with 15 more votes than
necessary to achieve the required two-thirds vote.
</P>
<P>
   Flag desecration or flag burning in a political context is both
an act of dissent and a statement. Clearly, though many who object
to flag burning deny it, the act speaks volumes. It is one way that
those who protest U.S. foreign policy or U.S. acts of war can
startle the media into paying attention to their cause or dissent,
and thereby get their message to the people.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the 20th century, the U.S. Supreme Court recognized
that some actions are also speech or even predominantly speech.
Symbolic speech the court calls them. Protest marches are speech;
picket lines are a form of speech; raising a red flag is a form of
speech; wearing black arm bands to protest the Vietnam War was
speech; waving an American flag when our soldiers return home and
march down New York City's Fifth Avenue is speech; and so, in
contrast, is burning the flag a form of speech.
</P>
<P>
   The First Amendment protects the right of a speaker to support a
war in which this nation is engaged. It also protects the right of
a speaker to criticize that same war. If waving a flag in support
of a war is protected speech, then burning it to show one's
disagreement with the war must also be protected speech. That's the
essence of the First Amendment and the meaning of the U.S.
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The 63 members of the Senate and the 305 members of the House
who would hog our right of speech and dissent seem to have an
extremely myopic vision of our right to freedom of speech.
</P>
<P>
   Their vision certainly doesn't take into account the
constitutional history of the First Amendment and the U.S.
Constitution. Nor does this myopia take into account the founding
fathers' grand experiment _ a people given the power to govern
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Article I, Section 6 of the U.S. Constitution makes an absolute
statement about free speech _ not unlike the founders' clear
meaning of the First Amendment: ``The Senators and Representatives
... for any speech or debate in either House, they shall not be
questioned in any other place.'' That means no matter what a
senator or representative says about any citizen of the United
States or anyone else, or about any government action, they cannot
be brought into a court of law. They cannot be sued for slander or
arrested for sedition if what they say is spoken on the floor of
the House or Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Had the flag amendment passed and been ratified by two-thirds of
the states, any senator could still burn a flag on the Senate floor
and not be taken to jail for this symbolic speech.
</P>
<P>
   The overarching concept of self-governance means that the people
must have all the rights of debate and speech that their elected
representatives have under the Constitution. That's why the First
Amendment reads, in part: ``Congress shall make no law ...
abridging the freedom of speech, or of the press.''
</P>
<P>
   Self-governance is precisely the reason that political speech
enjoys the greatest protection under the Constitution. And flag
burning as dissenting political speech must continue to be
protected.
</P>
<P>
   By what foggy notion of liberty and democracy can our elected
officials seek to take away a portion of that right and yet retain
it for themselves?
</P>
<P>
   A number of state legislatures have been attempting to restrict
the Internet to only that material which is deemed appropriate for
children to view or read. Anything considered ``inappropriate'' or
``harmful'' to children would be banned from the World Wide Web.
Fortunately, all these Internet laws have been struck down as an
unconstitutional infringements on freedom of speech and freedom of
the press.
</P>
<P>
   These elected officials may be too near-sighted to see that the
Internet is the most democratic form of mass communication ever
invented. Or, they may be afraid of its inherent power.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with access to the Internet can be a publisher and have
thousands of readers. Being an Internet publisher doesn't require
wealth, only knowledge and the ability to communicate. As such,
this new form of communication _ the people's mass communication
system _ jeopardizes the elitist power structure. And that is the
real reason politicians want to control it and limit what can be
communicated through this medium.
</P>
<P>
   New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has finally realized that
his attacks on the Brooklyn Museum of Art for showing a
controversial British art exhibit were bound to fail. Last week,
his administration settled out of court with the museum and
reinstated city funding to the institution.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's numerous attacks on freedom of speech have shown he
is deficient in his understanding of the First Amendment and the
protections it provides to speech, art, music and books.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent opinion, Judge Guido Calabresi of the Second U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals, a former Yale School dean, criticized the
number of First Amendment lawsuits filed against Giuliani's
administration. He wrote, ``We would be ostriches if we failed to
take judicial notice of the heavy stream of First Amendment
litigation generation by New York City in recent years.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is another elected official who acts as if the people
should have a much narrower and more limited right of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   And the Republican Party's choice for presidential candidate,
George W. Bush, the governor of Texas, has an abysmal First
Amendment record in his state. He has had protesters arrested for
peacefully demonstrating against his administration's policies and
proposed legislation at the state capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The public sidewalk outside the governor's mansion has a long
tradition of being a forum for rallies, demonstrations, and even
press conferences. Not any more. Bush doesn't like criticism.
Therefore, the citizens of Texas are not allowed to express or hear
other points of view concerning state public policies in front of
the mansion where many of those policies originate.
</P>
<P>
   It takes unmitigated gall for an elected official to think he or
she has the right to take away or restrict the rights of the
people, rights essential for self-governing _ the right to discuss
and debate public policy, the right to dissent, the right of free
expression.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, arrogance instead of respect for the people's
rights seems to have become the new currency in American politics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-03-00 1540EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
