<P>
   BARBECUE-CANCER (Undated) _ With barbecue season just around the
corner, scientists are offering new evidence that grilled, charred
and fried meat may pose a risk of breast cancer. The culprit
appears to be a compound called PhIP, produced when meat is cooked
at high temperatures. Rats fed high doses of PhIP develop tumors in
</P>
<P>
   their mammary glands, studies have shown. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   HEARTBURN (Undated)_ In the right concentration, the acid in
your stomach is powerful enough to dissolve a penny. It can also
wreak havoc in your throat, as millions of sufferers of heartburn
know. Most people treat heartburn on their own, spending a total of
$1 billion a year on over-the-counter remedies such as Tums and
Maalox. But many people still wonder when it's appropriate to see a
doctor. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MAYOR-INVESTMENTS (San Francisco) _ San Francisco Mayor Willie
Brown plunged into the stock market in 1999 and made a killing on a
series of initial public offerings involving high-tech stocks, city
records show. In a disclosure statement, Brown said that he had
amassed a stock portfolio worth as much as $970,000 through a
series of purchases of 16 different stocks, including 14 computer
or Internet companies. By CHUCK FINNIE and LANCE WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-SALE (San Francisco) _ A federal judge fast-forwarded
the future of San Francisco's daily newspapers when he set a May 1
trial on former mayoral candidate Clint Reilly's antitrust suit to
block Hearst Corp. from buying the San Francisco Chronicle. U.S.
District Judge Vaughn Walker on Monday set the date for a full
trial after attorneys for Hearst proposed skipping an April 13
hearing on Reilly's request for a preliminary injunction blocking
the sale pending an unscheduled trial, which could have been months
off. By SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-SHANGHAI (San Francisco) _ When United Airlines Flight
858 from Shanghai touched down Monday at San Francisco
International Airport, it became the first direct, nonstop service
by a U.S. carrier between San Francisco, America's capital of
high-technology, and Shanghai, China's business capital and largest
city. By DAVID ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-FALCONE (Undated) _ ``Falcone,'' the long-overdue mob drama
from CBS, holds its own without caveats as engrossing television.
The drama manages to avoid being derivative, even though it's a
series (a miniseries, maybe) based on a movie (``Donnie Brasco''),
based on the real life of undercover FBI agent Joe Pistone. By MARK
McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ADIRONDACKS-HIKING (Keene Valley, N.Y.) _ There's no telling
what to expect in the Adirondacks in late winter. This year, ski
poles turned out to be our most treasured equipment as we set out
on the Phelps Trail toward our lodging for the night. The warm
weather and earlier rains had transformed trickling creeks into
free-flowing, rushing streams, and the poles helped with balance in
stepping atop rocks that provided only slippery footholds across
the dangerously cold water. By MARIANNE COMFORT.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPEAN-RAILS (London) _ Easy-to-use passes, such as the
Britrail pass in the United Kingdom and Eurail pass on the
continent, make train travel in Europe convenient and enjoyable.
Rail passes provide unlimited rail trips for the number of travel
days indicated on the pass. Supplements, necessary to ride the
Premier trains, are covered or discounted with the rail passes. By
JULIE COOPER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ I'm a criminal. The deadline for
returning U.S. Census forms passed on Saturday and my ``short
form'' is still sitting on my desk next to my tax returns. The
government definitely will get my tax returns. I'm scared of the
IRS. I'm not scared of the Census Bureau, which has given us an
extension to April 11 and probably won't prosecute anyone who
misses that deadline. So I don't know when I'll mail back that
form. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   DNA-TESTING (San Francisco) _ DNA testing is the key that can
unlock the door to the truth in many of the toughest cases before
our courts. With the technology available in many cases to prove or
disprove guilt scientifically, the questions left to politicians,
law enforcement authorities and legal scholars are these: When do
we set aside what our very fallible eyes and ears tell us and rely
on the reports of technicians? By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
