<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0405-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    All toilets are not created equal
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Roger the plumber is my new best friend; he
keeps me flush(ing) as did his father before him. This morning,
he's wedged into the downstairs bathroom preparing to do battle
with a 1950-vintage, emerald green
</P>
<P>
   American Standard that won't quit running unless its handle is
jiggled rhythmically to one complete chorus of ``Mairzy Doats.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Toilets,'' he mutters and shakes his head, ``can't live with
'em...can't live without 'em.'' Socrates never said it better.
</P>
<P>
   Americans love flush toilets and will not be deprived of their
convenience _ at any cost. Do-it-yourselfers willingly spend hours
kneeling in abject reverence before a broken one, replacing
this...sealing that. Praying.
</P>
<P>
   Swearing. And for the rest of us, those whose kids took all
their tools off to college with them, there is Roger.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Congress, a day late and a dollar short as usual,
mandated that in an effort to conserve resources, all new toilets
retailed in the U.S.of A. were to use only 1.6 gallons of water per
flush which immediately resulted in
</P>
<P>
   suburban unrest _ as well as a lot of flushing. Three per visit,
to be exact, or your bathroom ended up on the auto club's condemned
list.
</P>
<P>
   Americans, however, did not take this deprivation lying (or
sitting, as the case may be) down. We did what we had to do and
turned into a nation of toilet smugglers _ with a twist.
</P>
<P>
   Companies in the U.S. are still allowed to manufacture the
high-flush models _ but only for export. Our toilets are going to
Canada, and we're having to bring them back one at a time as
contraband. It's a legend in the making _
</P>
<P>
   kind of like rum-runners during Prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep,'' the story will go in the re-telling, ``I remember when
Granddaddy was running them high-flushers from
</P>
<P>
   Windsor to Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Crapper, a 19th-century Englishman, left an indelible
mark on the plumbing business. His fame as well as his manhole
covers, are widespread. Homage for his weighty contribution to
human comfort and sanitation is paid
</P>
<P>
   world-wide, even in south Florida where some of my friends have
organized a Thomas Crapper society with regular meetings and
tee-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   I suspect alcohol may have been involved.
</P>
<P>
   But just to set the record straight, Crapper, though credited
with manufacturing and installing some thirty lavatories with
cedarwood seats in Sandringham House much to the delight of Queen
Victoria, was not, I'm sorry to
</P>
<P>
   say, the father of the original flush toilet. That was Sir John
Harington.
</P>
<P>
   Sir John was a naughty boy who had been banished from the royal
presence for translating and circulating among the young ladies at
court, salacious parts of Ariosto's epic poem, ``Orlando Furioso.''
It was somewhere around the same time (1591) that he invented the
flush toilet and installed one for Queen Elizabeth in her palace at
Richmond, Surrey. Without doubt, this pleased Elizabeth and allowed
Harington to slink back into her good graces.
</P>
<P>
   Crapper, on the other hand, may very well have been the inventor
of the syphonic ``short-flush'' that is now so dear to the hearts
(and occasionally nether regions) of the American Congress. Because
of a piece of legislation
</P>
<P>
   enacted by London authorities in 1870, to preserve vast amounts
of water being wasted in ``water-closets'' (the more dignified
British term for toilet, and believe it or not, the one that got
Jack Paar and his ``Tonight Show'' bumped off television for saying
it back in 1960), plumbers were ordered to build water-waste
preventers into their cisterns.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Crapper's syphon mechanism: user pulls chain on
wall-mounted cistern, water flushes bowl, and then stops. Simple
operation - one moving part. It was progress where man desired it
most _ in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon, Roger yells up the stairs that ``Old Green'' is
working just fine. No more ``Mairzy Doats.'' I thank him profusely
and silently mutter a little prayer asking that he never give up
plumbing for e-trading.
</P>
<P>
   A high-flush beats a low one every time - whatever the game.
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
