<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Underinflated tires steal dollars down the road
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's just awful. How can a $10 bill not even come
close to filling your gas tank halfway? Sadly, it's today's
reality. Wasn't it yesterday _ well, OK, last summer _ that your 10
spot would bring most fuel gauge needles well past the halfway
mark, maybe even all the way up?
</P>
<P>
   But we have to deal with the present. What are we to do?
</P>
<P>
   Short of selling our gas-guzzling buggies and running out to
purchase cars like Honda's Insight, Toyota's Prius or even a diesel
Volkswagen New Beetle, we can take baby steps to increase our
vehicles' fuel efficiency. But with gas prices expected to rise to
the high side of $1.50 before summer and already approaching $2 in
many areas, something is better than nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The first and simplest place to begin is with your vehicle's
tire pressure. The U.S. Energy Department in 1995 estimated we
wasted 4 million gallons of gasoline daily because of underinflated
tires. Factor in today's number of vehicles, and we are talking
about serious waste.
</P>
<P>
   An underinflated tire _ besides being the leading cause of tire
failure _ can rob you of as much as 10 percent of your fuel
economy, says Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber Co.'s chief engineer of
product design, Bill Egan. That may not sound like a lot, but let's
look at the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Say you drive one of those big sport-utility vehicles. They get
11 or 12 miles to a gallon stopping and going in city traffic.
Let's assume you drive 100 miles per day. We'll assume that your
vehicle runs on regular-grade fuel. So now we have you driving 500
miles a week just going to work and running daily errands. We'll
add another 100 miles for weekend travel. So now we are looking at
600 miles per week or 31,200 miles per year.
</P>
<P>
   Divide 31,200 by 12 miles per gallon, and you get 2,600 gallons
of annual fuel usage _ and we didn't even send you off on a
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Regular gas at $1.50 means that you spend $3,900 per year for
fuel. If underinflated tires can rob you of as much as 10 percent
in fuel economy, that means the same SUV now gets only gets 10.8
miles per gallon. You now use 2,889 gallons of gas, which adds up
to $4,333 in fuel costs, or an additional $433.
</P>
<P>
   That 10 percent number, according to Goodyear's chief engineer
for light trucks, Mike Kolowski, was based on data for passenger
cars. The bigger the tire, the more potential for rolling
resistance, and the more an underinflated tire can help guzzle gas.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that you can pick up a quality tire pressure
gauge for much less than the cost of a half a tank of gas. You'll
have to check your tire pressure. The proper pressure can be found
on a sticker inside your door sill, sometimes on the fuel door
filler or in your owners manual. Some stations now charge for air,
but many still have free air. Even if you spend 50 cents on air,
proper pressure still equates to pennies saved and dollars earned.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
