r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN05-COX     04-04 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Do fish feel pain? Sure; as did those snared by PETA prank
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ I'm torn. I could go either way on this one _ with
PETA, or with its ethical archrival, PETGIF.
</P>
<P>
   That would be People for the Ethical Treatment of Guys in
Flannel.
</P>
<P>
   The issue: Brutality against fish. But first, the treatment of
fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   This week my sympathy goes to them after People for the Ethical
Treatment of Animals pulled off an April Fools prank that succeeded
beyond PETA's wildest estimations.
</P>
<P>
   The hook: PETA announced, and several newspapers reported, that
it would put tranquilizers into Lake Palestine before Saturday's
Red Man Cowboy Division Fishing Tournament. The fish would doze
while fishermen grew red, PETA said.
</P>
<P>
   The line: The tournament happened to be on April 1. PETA listed
``April Phule'' as a press contact.
</P>
<P>
   The sinker: A variety of people took the bait, principally
officials at the Texas Parks and Wildlife Department and the Upper
Neches River Municipal Water Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The manager of the latter accused PETA of ``borderline
terroristic methods.'' Park rangers were mobilized to catch anyone
dumping sleep aids into a 25,500-acre reservoir containing 40
billion gallons of water.
</P>
<P>
   Tranquilizing that pond would take enough Sominex to fill three
Exxon Valdezes.
</P>
<P>
   Phuled you, said PETA.
</P>
<P>
   After a ``gotcha'' press release trickled forth, I spoke by
phone to the person behind the prank.
</P>
<P>
   Her name is Dawn Carr. She's devoted four years of her life to
sparing the feelings of fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fish, like all animals, can feel pain, and tricking them into
impaling themselves on hooks is hardly sporting,'' said Carr.
</P>
<P>
   ``It only takes a brief look at a trout on the end of the hook
to know that he would far prefer not to be in this predicament,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   I must say, Carr has good points. The first _ the sporting
notion. Imagine if, say, a giant beyond the clouds dangled lottery
tickets over a Texas sidewalk, and then snatched their takers out
of this life sphere before they could scratch. Sporting?
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the pain thing. Hook through jaw: Discomfort?
Mild, burning sensation? Erotic pleasure?
</P>
<P>
   Well, to some guys in flannel, yes. The latter.
</P>
<P>
   Before I go too far out in this current, I must acknowledge the
flannel in my lineage _ dedicated fly fishermen, hip-waders at the
ready. They love the smell of salmon eggs in the morning: the smell
of victory.
</P>
<P>
   I was with them for a time. I enjoyed catching fish. The thing I
didn't enjoy, I came to realize, was killing fish. In fact, the
killing so dampened the catching (catch-and-release seemed
pointless) that I stopped. I hiked instead.
</P>
<P>
   With hunting, fishing combines to provide one of society's key
social delineators. In my family, one son loves to catch and eat
fish, and one wouldn't so much as give a fish wrong directions. He
also won't wear or eat any animal flesh.
</P>
<P>
   As is a father's function, I am torn between the two
predispositions. I oppose animal cruelty. But my Rockport shoes
once said ``moo.'' So, too, with that cherished baseball glove.
</P>
<P>
   As for hunting, I can't imagine any joy that could come with
shooting dead a majestic beast. But I'm in no position to judge
because the pig that became that prized football of mine looked
majestic to its mama.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that though I don't like to see animals
killed, I manage to pay others to do my killing. So, what of Mrs.
Paul's? Queen of fish sticks, or matron of genocide?
</P>
<P>
   Torn, that's me. Let's eat.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
