r l BC-TEST-DRIVE05-COX     04-04 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST-DRIVE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BMW M5 makes splashy return
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After a five-year absence, the M5 sport sedan's return
to the BMW lineup is made with more than enough credentials to earn
the category's No. 1 rating.
</P>
<P>
   The car it supplants, in most reviewers' estimation, is the BMW
540i six-speed sedan, so it's really a family affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to claim that the 540i six-speed was the best sports
sedan money could buy,'' says Automobile magazine. ``But that was
before BMW unveiled the M5.''
</P>
<P>
   What's not to like about the M5? It has quietly stylish good
looks, tremendous performance and enough luxury/high-tech touches
to compete effectively in those areas with domestic, Japanese and
other European cars. It really needs no options, but a car with a
base price of $69,400 _ plus a $2,100 gas-guzzler penalty _ had
better be equipped not well, but totally.
</P>
<P>
   The M5 is a driver's car, with precise steering,
stomp-'em-and-stop brakes, a slick six-speed transmission and a
400-horsepower V-8 with 369 pounds-feet of torque at a relatively
mild 3,800 engine revolutions per minute.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers translate into sheer fun in the city, on the
highway or at the performance driving center at Spartanburg, S.C.,
where BMW offers a free two-day course to M5 buyers. Only there or
on other closed courses can the M5 be fully utilized. It has a
zero-to-60 mph rating of about five seconds and a computer-limited
top speed of 155 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Innovations and other nice touches include a variable-redline
tachometer that raises the suggested limit from 4,000 rpm to about
6,500 rpm as the engine warms, a stability control system combining
traction control with anti-lock brakes, and a tire pressure warning
system.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the M5's appeal and driving experience, however,
is the V-8 engine. It docilely burbles along in traffic, growls
when aroused and loafs quietly _ well, rather quietly _ at cruising
speed in the top gears. But its sudden response, even in fifth or
sixth gear, is amazing.
</P>
<P>
   The laudatory adjectives can go on and on, with conclusions
typically matching that of Car and Driver magazine, which summed it
up pretty well: ``The sport sedan may never have been more
elegantly _ or potently _ expressed.''
</P>
<P>
   That's for now, of course, because it was just yesterday that
the same was said of the 540i.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 2000 BMW M5 rear-drive sports sedan
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $72,070 (base: $69,400; includes $2,100
gas-guzzler tax)
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 5.0-liter V-8 engine with 32 valves (400
horsepower), six-speed manual overdrive transmission
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: two-stage dual front air bags, front
side-impact air bags, front head-protection system air bags,
automatic height-adjusting front safety belts, power anti-lock disc
brakes, stability control system
</P>
<P>
   Options on test vehicle: none
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 13 mpg premium unleaded city, 21 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
