<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Wednesday, April 5, 2000 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ When the history of pandering is written,
perhaps Al Gore's swoon for Miami's anti-Castro zealots will rate
no more than a heavy footnote. But whether it is ultimately judged
one of the great grovels or just a standard political one, the vice
president's pander is especially pernicious. (Teepen, Cox News
Service.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ MIAMI _ There seemingly is no end to the
hideous soap opera surrounding the 6-year-old Cuban political pawn
Elian Gonzalez. There will be an end, of course, and the sooner the
better. But for the time being, it gets more ugly by the hour.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ Roger the plumber is my new best friend; he
keeps me flush(ing) as did his father before him. This morning,
he's wedged into the downstairs bathroom preparing to do battle
with a 1950-vintage, emerald green American Standard that won't
quit running unless its handle is jiggled rhythmically to one
complete chorus of ``Mairzy Doats.'' ``Toilets,'' he mutters and
shakes his head, ``can't live with 'em ... can't live without
'em.'' Socrates never said it better. (Schuett, Cox News Service)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _The issue: Brutality against fish.
But first, the treatment of fishermen. This week my sympathy goes
to them after People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals pulled
off an April Fools prank that succeeded beyond PETA's wildest
estimations. (John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED
