</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6602 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NUTSNBOLTS05-COX     04-04 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTSNBOLTS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Make safety a top priority in backyard play equipment
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When I was a kid growing up in Dayton, the only
question I had about a backyard swing set was how high could I
swing before the legs of the swing set pulled up out of the ground
and the whole thing tipped over.
</P>
<P>
   Now that I've gotten old and boring, the first things I check
when I see backyard play equipment are the safety features. Like
the nosy lady from across the street, I think safety first and fun
second.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing you know I'll be screaming at some kid, ``Put down
that stick before you put somebody's eye out!''
</P>
<P>
   LOOK OUT FOR FALL ZONES
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Consumer Products Safety Commission _ keeper of all the
statistics designed to scare you out of getting out of bed _ says
about 200,000 children a year are treated in U.S. hospital
emergency rooms for playground equipment-related injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those children are hurt in public parks, but about
51,000 of them are hurt at home.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the injuries are the result of falls, so it's important
to surround backyard play equipment with a soft surface for those
landings.
</P>
<P>
   Swings sets should never go on uncovered concrete or asphalt.
Even a grassy lawn will quickly become trampled and hard.
</P>
<P>
   The protective surface material should cover an area that
extends 6 feet in all directions from stationary equipment such as
climbing towers or slides. The protected area also should extend 6
feet to the sides of swing supports.
</P>
<P>
   Measure the distance from the ground to the point where swings
attach to their support bars. The protected area should extend
twice that distance in front of and behind the swings.
</P>
<P>
   The most common materials for a protective ground cover are
shredded-bark mulch, wood chips, fine sand and fine gravel.
</P>
<P>
   Wood chips or shredded-bark mulch are good choices because
they're effective, relatively inexpensive, fairly easy to maintain
and a little less messy than sand.
</P>
<P>
   Shredded tire mulch is even easier to maintain, but it's
expensive and hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Consumer Products Safety Commission, a
9-inch-thick layer of shredded-bark mulch or wood chips should
prevent a life-threatening head injury in a fall of up to 10 feet.
The same depth of fine gravel gives protection from a 7-foot fall,
and 9 inches of fine sand protects from a 5-foot fall.
</P>
<P>
   One way to keep the ground covering in place is to surround the
play area with a wooden border. Pairs of 6-by-6-inch landscape
timbers held together with galvanized landscape spikes hold in
ground covers up to 12 inches deep.
</P>
<P>
   MAINTENANCE IS AN ONGOING PROCESS
</P>
<P>
   Wooden equipment should be inspected at least once a year.
</P>
<P>
   Remove any splinters and sand rough spots. Check the structure
for loose nails, screws and bolts.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure all guardrail posts are secure. Gaps between parts
should be less than 3 1/2 inches or greater than 9 inches so that a
child's head cannot become stuck.
</P>
<P>
   Wood that is exposed to outdoor weather must be sealed regularly
to protect it from water damage. Most wooden play equipment is made
of wood treated to prevent insect infestation, but treated lumber
still must be sealed.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden playground equipment that sits in direct sun probably
should be sealed more often than equipment that sits in shade, but
most equipment should be sealed every second or third year.
</P>
<P>
   Throw a bucket of water on the equipment after at least three
days with no rain. If the water soaks in instead of beading, it's
time to reseal.
</P>
<P>
   Use a penetrating sealer of the type used for decks. The sealer
should include an ultraviolet radiation screen and a mildew
inhibiter.
</P>
<P>
   Plan to inspect metal swing sets at least twice a year.
</P>
<P>
   These problems should be corrected immediately:
</P>
<P>
   _ Loose or worn hardware or any part that projects or protrudes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Any rope or cord, such as a jump rope, attached to or left
near the equipment. Clothing with drawstrings also present a
strangulation hazard, and strangulation is the main cause of death
in playground accidents.
</P>
<P>
   _ Exposed equipment footings such as concrete blocks or metal
anchors that have pulled loose from the ground partially or
completely.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rusted joints or tubing. Sand rust spots and paint with
rust-resistant paint.
</P>
<P>
   _ Missing or damaged components such as handholds and swing
seats.
</P>
<P>
   _ Open S-hooks. Squeeze the open ends of S-hooks shut with a
pair of pliers or enclose them in plastic sleeves to prevent
snagging clothing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pinch and crush points. Look closely at all the moving parts
for swing components such as gliders and seesaws. Any joint where
fingers or limbs could be compressed should be inaccessible. If you
can't ensure safety, get rid of the component.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD'S AGE DETERMINES CHOICE
</P>
<P>
   If you're considering buying new play equipment, the No. 1
variable in choosing appropriate products is the age of your child.
</P>
<P>
   If you're buying for a pre-schooler or toddler, your best choice
might be a plastic play set. They come in a variety of
configurations from small playhouses to larger sets with swings and
slides.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic play sets are usually easy to assemble; some just slide
out of a box ready to go. They're small enough that the falling
hazard is reduced.
</P>
<P>
   But they're rather expensive for their size, and children will
lose interest in them when they get a little older.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden play sets can grow with the child. You add components as
the child's interests grow. Also wooden play sets make an
attractive addition to a back yard.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden play equipment can be quite expensive, though. Assembly
can be handled by an experienced home carpenter working with a
helper, but many homeowners buying elaborate sets opt for
professional installation.
</P>
<P>
   Though metal swing sets are not as glamorous as wood, they
generally are good values. A set with as many play components as
your children can imagine probably will cost less than $300.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their relative cheapness, one option is to buy a
metal swing set and simply dismantle it in a few years as it wears
out or the children
</P>
<P>
   outgrow it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
