<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6643 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-EUROPEAN-RAILS-HNS &LR;      04-04 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPEAN-RAILS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PASSES MAKE RAIL TRAVEL IN EUROPE EASY AS A WHISTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JULIE COOPER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Yellow Submarine stands at the ready at Waterloo
Station, all set to whisk passengers through the Chunnel to Europe.
No underwater skills necessary _ this is the Eurostar train.
</P>
<P>
   This train just happens to be painted up to promote the
re-release of the Beatles' feature-length cartoon ``Yellow
Submarine.'' Here are Blue Meanies alongside the Fab Four of John,
Paul, George and Ringo. Inside, the plush seats of first class give
no indication that this is anything but a great way to travel in
style.
</P>
<P>
   Security is as tight here as it is for an international airport
departure. Within 30 minutes of settling in, though, we are on our
way to Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Busy executives break the silence of the train on cell phones,
talking business and personal lives. Tea and coffee are served by
smiling attendants. Then there is breakfast, a choice of hot or
cold. There are wide seats, a handy table that is roomy enough for
a briefcase full of work or a meal tray, and scenic Britain just
outside the window.
</P>
<P>
   It takes about 20 minutes to travel the 32 miles of the Chunnel,
under the English Channel, just enough time to polish off the hot
breakfast served by the train attendant. Maximum speed is 186 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging in France, the weather is overcast, but the sun breaks
through as the morning wears on and we make a stop at Lille.
</P>
<P>
   Eurostar trans-Channel travel began in November 1994, and
reports indicate that more than 900,000 North American passengers
have used these fast and convenient trains between London, Paris
and Brussels. In 1999, more than 200,000 Americans took the train.
</P>
<P>
   For this group of railroading travel writers, Brussels is merely
a stop for lunch; then it is back on the train for the 90-minute
trip to Paris. Popping out of the train station like gophers, we
are herded a few blocks away to a restaurant, then back to catch
the 3:40 train to Paris-Nord.
</P>
<P>
   This is probably how international business is conducted between
Belgium and France: a quick dash to the neighboring country for a
meeting, lunch and back on the train. You're home in time for
dinner.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, more than 60 percent of passengers on the Thalys (a
made-up word for the rail system) are leisure travelers, according
to Michel Jadot, a spokesman for the European rail line. Thalys is
a service of Belgian, French, German and Dutch rails to facilitate
travel in Northern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thalys is moving south, east and west,'' Jadot said. Special
trains serve Disneyland Paris and ski regions in Europe. Regular
runs include Amsterdam, Rotterdam and Antwerp in the Netherlands;
and Koln and Dusseldorf, Germany; and between Brussels and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   The five-hour trip from Brussels to Frankfurt is expected to be
cut in half by 2002 with the addition of new dedicated lines. The
privately owned rail line aims to serve 12 million passengers by
2010.
</P>
<P>
   Cee Cee Drummond works for the New York office of Rail Europe.
On this cross-continent trip, she is showing more than telling
about the trains and the countries that Rail Europe serves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think clients that we have today do so much research for the
trip,'' Drummond said during a ride on the high-speed train from
Paris to Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers consult friends, the Internet and guidebooks before
booking trips to Europe, Drummond said. ``We do about 85 percent of
our business through travel agents,'' she said of the $230 million
generated by Rail Europe sales.
</P>
<P>
   The typical Rail Europe customer is not a first-time visitor to
Europe, Drummond said. He or she is a repeat traveler, 45 to 55
years old, college educated, who may have seen Europe from a motor
coach tour a few years before. This time out, the traveler plans to
see two to three European countries.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the booming youth market made up of backpackers
who hop the trains for summer travel after college. Drummond said
that the Eurail Flexipass is the most popular, allowing unlimited
first-class travel in 17 countries for either 10 days or 15 days.
</P>
<P>
   My six-day Europass, for example, cost $368 and allows travel in
France, Germany, Italy, Spain and Switzerland. Travel in Britain is
not covered with under Europass, but rather with the separate
BritRail passes. Rail passes must be purchased in the United States
before the traveler leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Rail passes provide unlimited rail trips for the number of
travel days indicated on the pass. Supplements, necessary to ride
the Premier trains, are covered or discounted with the rail passes.
</P>
<P>
   Seat reservations are also required for Premier trains such as
the Eurostar, French TGV, Italy's Cisalpino and Artesia (between
France and Italy). ``If you've paid for a supplement on a train,
that includes your seat reservation and there are no additional
fees required,'' Drummond said.
</P>
<P>
   While riding the rails no longer has the romantic allure shown
in old movies, Europe's rail comes pretty close.
</P>
<P>
   For Rose and Richard Huber of San Jose, Calif., a 21-day rail
pass from Eurail is just the ticket. We met on the deck of the
Compagnie Generale de Navigation steamer on Lake Geneva for a
cruise to Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
   Both Eurail and Swissrail passes are valid on CGN boats. The
Hubers, who own an electronics business, were return visitors to
Europe _ some 30 years after their first visit. This time, they had
flown into Munich, Germany, and were taking trains across Western
Europe on a 21-day pass. The plan was to end the trip at
Oktoberfest.
</P>
<P>
   Like walking ads for a European vacation, the Hubers said they
rented a car on a 1968 European vacation. A few years later, Mrs.
Huber joined an escorted bus tour with a friend. Ten years ago, the
Hubers made a train trip.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with rail passes in hand, the Hubers were crossing borders,
taking city tours and traveling with no particular itinerary in
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like the freedom of Eurail,'' Mrs. Huber said, taking in
the bright, blue sky on the deck of the Swiss steamship. ``The
trains are all clean and beautiful.'' And they hadn't even sampled
the Premier trains.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO:
</P>
<P>
   For information on rail passes in Europe and Britain, see your
travel agent or contact Rail Europe, www.raileurope.com. Phone
888-382-7245 for a 48-page ``Europe on Track'' 2000 brochure.
</P>
<P>
   Rail passess are available for single countries, regions (Easter
Europe, Scandinavia, Balkans), or all of Europe (five-country
Europass or 18-country Eurailpass).
</P>
</TEXT>
