<HEADER>
A6655 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-(TRIMS     04-04 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIGNATION OF JAPAN'S CABINET PAVES WAY FOR NEW PRIME MINISTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
(See also JAPAN-OBUCHI-REACT) 
(js) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japan's Cabinet resigned en masse Tuesday, setting the
stage for a rapid political succession two days after a
life-threatening stroke incapacitated Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation, which was made formal in a brief, final Cabinet
meeting Tuesday evening, is expected to lead to the nomination of a
candidate to succeed Obuchi by the governing Liberal Democratic
Party as early as Wednesday morning. A parliamentary vote to ratify
the party's choice, who is widely reported to be the Liberal
Democrat's second-ranking official, Yoshiro Mori, would be held
almost immediately afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   With tears streaking down his cheeks as he spoke during a late
afternoon new conference, the caretaker prime minister, Mikio Aoki,
said the dissolution of the government was made ``based on the
judgment of the doctors and from the viewpoint that we should not
allow even one moment's political vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   The news came amid persistent reports throughout the day that
Obuchi's condition was steadily worsening and that the prime
minister was already brain dead by mid-afternoon. Aoki denied this,
saying he was ``very upset'' at the media for passing on what he
said were unsubstantiated rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians close to the transition process and several Japanese
political analysts said Tuesday that the party had used the
extraordinary 22-hour news blackout surrounding Obuchi's
hospitalization early Sunday, and the carefully stage-managed
process since, to quietly engineer the selection of Mori, the
party's secretary-general, as its unopposed candidate for prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   The secretive handling of the news of Obuchi's hospitalization
and the back-room machinations drew strong, renewed criticisms
Tuesday from several quarters. Many Japanese said the process
revealed a side of their country that was neither altogether modern
nor democratic.
</P>
<P>
   Mori was reportedly selected in part because of his reputed
strong loyalty to Obuchi. Even more decisive, however, were his
close ties to the ruling party's major coalition partner, the
Buddhist-backed New Komeito Party.
</P>
<P>
   Mori's ratification by the parliament, or Diet, is already
considered a foregone conclusion, political analysts said Tuesday,
because the governing coalition led by the Liberal Democratic Party
enjoys far more than the simple legislative majority needed to
approve the choice.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question about the choice,'' said Kozo Watanabe,
deputy speaker of the lower house of the Diet. ``In a matter of a
few hours, the central commission of the L.D.P. will announce Mr.
Mori's selection, and their junior coalition partners will support
it. In that event, we will have a new prime minister before the
parliament tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Many commentators said Tuesday, however, that by choosing Mori _
a burly, raspy voiced politician not especially known for his
personal popularity or campaigning skills _ the Liberal Democratic
Party was taking a huge risk in difficult national elections that,
because of Obuchi's stroke, are now expected to be held before the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The choice spoke volumes, they said, about some unusual
imperatives in Japanese politics like loyalty to partners and
allies in a crunch _ in this case to Obuchi's memory and to the New
Komeito Party _ rather than short-term gain, or even survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not that the L.D.P. lacks people who could enjoy
popularity, there is Mr. Kono and Mr. Kato, both of whom would
probably be more popular,'' said Masumi Ishikawa, a professor of
politics at Nigata University of International and Information
Studies, and a former senior political correspondent of the Asahi
Shimbun newspaper. ``But the L.D.P. is basing its decision on who
has a good relationship with Komeito. They are not thinking of the
reaction of the people of Japan, and this behavior is very
strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Yohei Kono, the foreign minister, and Koichi Kato, a former
chief Cabinet secretary, were both thought to aspire to the prime
minister's job.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, many analysts were already describing the Liberal
Democratic Party's choice of Mori on the basis of the New Komeito
Party's comfort as a recipe for electoral difficulties, because the
coalition between the two parties has been deeply unpopular since
it was formed last October. Opinion polls have consistently shown
that Japanese voters disapprove of having a party with religious
affiliations in the government.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The new government will have to dissipate growing criticism of
the secretive, seemingly antiquated mechanics of a succession in
which Aoki was allowed to become caretaker merely on the basis of
an unsubstantiated conversation with the stricken prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   The way in which Mori was selected contributed further to the
appearance of a process dominated by consultations between
all-powerful party barons who assiduously kept the public in the
dark while deciding the nation's course.
</P>
<P>
   Some longtime political insiders spoke Tuesday with almost
reverential approval of the off-stage consultations that produced
Mori as Obuchi's successor, describing it as a confirmation of the
efficiency of Japan's political system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Aoki's reaction to Obuchi's collapse was very tactful,''
said Watanabe, the lower house deputy speaker. ``If he had waited a
week or 10 days after Mr. Obuchi collapsed, somebody else could
have raised their hand as a candidate, and there could be some
chaos. But by the time Mr. Aoki announced the condition of Mr.
Obuchi, it was already virtually decided who would take over.''
</P>
<P>
   But for independent politicians and commentators, and indeed
much of the public, the baronial succession process gave way to a
field day of introspection about how, 55 years after World War II,
Japan has remained a democracy largely in name rather than in
spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although Japanese politicians keep saying `minshushugi' there
is no spirit of democracy in this country,'' said Kaoru Okano, a
political commentator who is a former president of Meiji University
in Tokyo, using the Japanese word for democracy. ``There are
statesman and politicians in the west. In Japan there is a third
category, wheeler-dealer.''
</P>
<P>
   Okano said that the current crisis had revealed Japan to be
dominated by this latter category.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Other commentators said the failure of the country's leaders to
operate in a more open manner and include the people in their
decision making had contributed to widespread public distrust of
politicians and disillusionment with politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process of choosing a successor has revealed itself as not
very democratic, and is indeed very closed,'' said Shusei Tanaka, a
political scientist at Fukuyama University in Hiroshima. ``I have
the feeling that whoever comes out of this coalition will probably
be the same, and the people of Japan feel much the same way. The
feeling is that even if the prime minister changes, the policies
won't. We are in need of dramatic reforms of Japanese politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
