<P>
   JAPAN-OBUCHI-REACT (Tokyo) _ The stroke that put a sudden end to
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's tenure _ and focused world attention
yet again on the back-room horse-trading that determines how this
country, the world's second-largest in terms of economic muscle,
functions politically _ has elicited little more than a shrug from
most Japanese. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-RIGHTS (Moscow) _ After a visit to the region, U.N. Human
Rights Commissioner Mary Robinson criticized Russia for human
rights violations in Chechnya and urged an investigation. By
Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-LAUNDER (Geneva) _ On the first indictment in the
money-laundering case against Nigeria's former military leader,
Gen. Sani Abacha. This is Switzerland's biggest such case,
investigating more than $600 million, according to Swiss Federal
Police. By Elizabeth Olson.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-POVERTY (United Nations) _ After years of treading
carefully around the issue of why some countries stay poor and get
poorer, the United Nations on Tuesday laid much of the blame
squarely on the countries themselves. While not ignoring the
problem of reduced foreign aid, the report by the U.N. Development
Program said that three-quarters of countries have estimated their
needs but very few have concrete plans of their own on what to do
about them. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
