and his Miami relatives' battle to keep him in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 2:30 p.m. EST.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HORMONE-REPLACEMENT (Undated) _ Women in a large study of
the effects of hormone replacement therapy have been told that
researchers have found a slight increase in risk for heart attacks,
stroke and blood clots. The study is not being halted but adds more
fuel to recent debate over whether estrogen therapy actually helps
the heart. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-DEALER (New York) _ The owner of New York City's oldest gun
dealership talks about federal and state regulation and the
National Rifle Association. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES  &LR; _ Washington
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `w' news category)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-DRUGS (Washington) _ Democrats are intensifying their
push for the extension of Medicare to cover prescription drug costs
for the elderly. The issue will be one of the most important in the
national election, with elderly voters a critical swing vote. By
Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   (This story is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' news category)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-MARKET (Tokyo) _ A look at what's behind the surprisingly
resilient Japanese stock market, which has outperformed the U.S.
market over the last year despite Japan's lapse into another
recession in late 1999, rising government debts and now the change
in leadership following the prime minister's stroke. By Stephanie
Strom.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SUITS (Undated) _ Looking at the private antitrust
suits that may now be filed following the legal decision against
Microsoft. With other developments. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   EMAIL-MONITORS (Undated) _ Hundreds of companies are looking at
their employee's e-mail on a routine basis. And their numbers are
soaring. ``The market for e-mail monitoring has basically doubled
in size over the last year,'' said Abner Germanow, a research
manager at the International Data Corp. But the monitoring raises a
number of questions about ethics and privacy.
</P>
<P>
   DOTCOM-FAMILIES (Undated) _ In the dot-com world, peopled
largely by 20-somethings and 30-whatevers, an increasing number of
chief executives are turning to their fathers and mothers to tap
into the one qualification the nerdiest whiz kid lacks by
definition: experience. By Amy Zipkin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-1900 (Paris) _ The art world has not escaped the tyranny
of round numbers this year. Exhibitions in Amsterdam, London and
Paris are currently celebrating the art of 1900. The aim of this
year's shows, though, is not to present great art as such but to
convey something of the mood of the times. And there was indeed
much going on in 1900, nowhere more than in Paris. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   ANGLER-ARTIST (New York) _ Sidney A. Neff, who calls himself a
piscatorial bibliophile, has taken his personal library of rare
books on fishing and, using the book binder's art he took up 20
years ago, transformed them into desktop fishing expeditions. By
picking up one of Neff's works, the ``reader'' literally opens a
series of doors to explore an elegantly tooled world of trout,
insects, and iris-lined river banks, all wrought in dyed African
leathers, Japanese paper, and gold. By Andrew C. Revkin.
</P>
<P>
   (This story was scheduled yesterday but later eliminated.)
</P>
<P>
   HUMAN-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Human Resources'' slowly and
deliberately spirals its ingenuous hero down a treacherous rabbit
hole of duplicity and corporate politics at a French factory, and
eventually threatens to put him and his father on opposite sides of
a war between management and labor. This film, directed by Laurent
Cantet, explores class differences, corporate behavior, labor
relations and father-son strife with an unusual depth and subtlety.
By Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ Column: On Argentine wines. By Frank J.
Prial.
</P>
