<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DEATH-PENALTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BILLS TO STOP EXECUTING THE INNOCENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, April 4:
</P>
<P>
   The battle to reform administration of the nation's deeply
flawed death-penalty system gained momentum last week with the
introduction of legislation in the House that would provide
important new safeguards to lessen the chance of executing innocent
people. The enlightened measure, the Innocence Protection Act,
would require preservation of biological evidence, make DNA testing
available to federal and state inmates, and set national standards
to ensure competent lawyers for indigent defendants accused of
capital crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsored by Ray LaHood, R-Ill., and William Delahunt, D-Mass.,
the measure parallels a bill that Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.,
introduced in the Senate in February. Lending critical support is
Gov. George Ryan of Illinois, a Republican, who declared a
moratorium on executions in his state in January because of its
``shameful record of convicting innocent people and putting them on
death row.''
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee chairman, Henry Hyde, praised the
bill as a ``very reasonable treatment of a very difficult and
delicate issue'' and promised a prompt hearing _ a pledge the
Senate Judiciary chairman, Orrin Hatch, should match. Both
supporters and opponents of the death penalty should be able to
agree on a measure reducing the risk of executing the innocent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
