A6663 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-JAPAN-NYT &LR;      04-04 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-JAPAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AN ABRUPT TRANSITION IN JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, April 4:
</P>
<P>
   Japan is suffering from a leadership crisis far deeper than the
sudden disability of Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi. A new prime
minister will soon be named to replace Obuchi, who was left in a
coma by a stroke over the weekend and is not expected to recover.
But none of the current contenders are likely to have the political
clout or daring needed to energize Japan's creaky government
machinery or to jolt its economy out of an almost decade-long
recession.
</P>
<P>
   Dismissed as a colorless hack when he took office almost two
years ago, Obuchi scored some successes. He carried out a badly
needed banking bailout, applied the kind of powerful fiscal
stimulus that had long been sought by Japan's major trading
partners, including Washington, and in the process modestly revived
the political fortunes of his sagging Liberal Democratic Party. But
he failed to follow up these initial economic achievements with the
kind of bold deregulation needed to rationalize Japan's banking and
business systems and to stimulate a resurgence of consumer demand.
As a result, Japan's economy is once again contracting and the
Liberal Democrats remain dependent on coalition partners who make
it hard to provide effective, consistent governance.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's political system appears particularly threadbare at
times of unexpected turbulence, whether they involve natural
disasters like the latest volcanic eruptions of Mount Usu, or human
tragedies like Obuchi's illness. For more than 24 hours the
Japanese public was fed misleading information disguising the
gravity of Obuchi's condition. Then came a hasty announcement that
power was being passed, on a caretaker basis, to a cabinet
official, Mikio Aoki, who appears to lack the political stature to
hold the job on his own.
</P>
<P>
   That will leave it to the Liberal Democrats' powerful faction
leaders to choose among several more formidable contenders. The top
candidates now seem to be Yoshiro Mori, the party's secretary
general, and Yohei Kono, the foreign minister. The winner will
probably serve only a few weeks before facing the voters in new
elections now expected before the Group of 8 economic summit
meeting in Okinawa in July. The Japanese people should use that
election to demand that their political leaders show more courage
in devising bold economic reforms that can lead Japan out of its
prolonged and costly recession.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 1251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6664 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MICROSOFT-NYT &LR;      04-04 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MICROSOFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MICROSOFT'S ILLEGAL MONOPOLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, April 4:
</P>
<P>
   With settlement talks having broken down, the judge overseeing
the government's antitrust case against Microsoft issued a stinging
ruling Monday that Microsoft had violated the antitrust laws by
abusing its monopoly position over Windows, the operating system
that controls the vast majority of personal computers. The ruling,
which supported most but not all of the government's accusations,
deserves wide credence. It was carefully grounded in antitrust
doctrine and the facts presented at trial.
</P>
<P>
   Now the judge, Thomas Penfield Jackson, moves on to the far
harder task of concocting a remedy. Here he will find no completely
satisfactory options.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson embraced the core of the government's case, ruling that
Microsoft illegally used its monopoly over Windows to get most
consumers to use its browser, the software that connects computers
to the Internet, rather than Netscape's. Microsoft's aim was far
more devious than a mere attempt to sell browser software. Browsers
can potentially replace Windows as the platform from which
computers run word processors and other application programs. So
Microsoft's decision to incorporate its browser in Windows and to
prohibit manufacturers from substituting anyone else's browser was
designed not to benefit consumers, the ultimate test of antitrust
doctrine, but to insulate Windows from competitive challenge. That,
Jackson ruled, violated the antitrust laws. Microsoft is counting
on the conservative justices on the appeals court to reverse
Jackson and give it more leeway to design products as it likes.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also ruled that Microsoft violated the antitrust laws
by proposing to carve up software markets with competitors and by
using its market power to steer the biggest Internet providers away
from Netscape. But he did not rule, as the government asked,
against less troubling contracts that Microsoft wrote with other
partners to discourage their customers from using Netscape's
browser.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for Jackson in devising an acceptable remedy is that
the government has failed to produce decisive evidence that
Microsoft's illegal tactics have as yet seriously harmed consumers.
Yes, Microsoft's tactics kept the price for Windows a bit too high
and squelched innovation in operating systems. But by how much, and
with what impact? The uncertainty leaves Jackson with two somewhat
unsatisfying solutions.
</P>
<P>
   He could focus on so-called conduct remedies for some of the
ways Microsoft unfairly drove out competition. Microsoft might, for
example, be required to publish promptly and completely all the
technical data that software companies need to make their programs
work smoothly with Windows. But these remedies would require
permanent government oversight of the software industry _ a
potential nightmare in a fast-moving, technically complicated
industry. Besides, conduct remedies do nothing to address the
government's core accusation: that Microsoft's illegal acts
eliminated potential competition in the market for operating
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson might be tempted, then, to impose structural remedies.
He might require Microsoft to license Windows to several other
companies that would be free to modify it and compete against
Microsoft. That way consumers could choose a version of Windows
based on price, customer service and perhaps features. But some
experts believe customers would flock only to Microsoft's version,
because only Bill Gates employs the experts who wrote the program
and know it best.
</P>
<P>
   The other structural remedy would go the final step _ breaking
up Microsoft into three or so separate companies, with Microsoft
personnel divided among them. The advantage of this remedy is that
it would break Microsoft's monopoly choke hold and avoid the need
for constant government oversight. But Jackson, let alone the more
conservative justices on the appeals court, may choke on that
drastic a remedy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 1252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6686 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-DIVISIONS-BOS &LR;      04-04 1559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIVISIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN KOSOVO _ A DIVISION OF LAND, A DIVISION OF PEOPLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MITROVICA, Yugoslavia _ Cesko Refika, 63, lives on the north
side of this old industrial city in what may be the most heavily
protected apartment building in the world, surrounded by hundreds
of French soldiers, not to mention nine tanks.
</P>
<P>
   And she is terrified.
</P>
<P>
   She has fled her home five times, staying briefly with relatives
on the south side, only to return again under armed guard. Her home
is surrounded by hostile Serbs, she cannot sleep, and her two young
grandchildren cry constantly. Last month, someone fired a
rocket-propelled grenade into a neighbor's apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why she comes back, the old Albanian woman shrugged,
saying, ``I have nowhere to go.''
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, Oliver Ivanovic talked about how his Serb
neighbors are under siege by ethnic Albanians who want to kill
them, and by international peacekeepers he says are unable or
unwilling to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The international community has to do more to protect Serbs,''
said Ivanovic, the Serb community leader and a former executive in
a mineral company. ``There are 16,000 Serbs left in Mitrovica, but
4,000 have been expelled and there are Albanian extremists who want
to kill or expel the rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitrovica (Mee-trow-VEE-cha) is the belly of the beast, the nub
of the problem in Kosovo. This drab, shabby city of about 80,000 is
so bitterly and literally divided that one despairs for the United
Nations' ambitious plan to transform this Serbian province into
something resembling a stable, multi-ethnic democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Divided by the Ibar River, separated by Kosovo Force, or KFOR,
peacekeepers, Serbs live on the north side, ethnic Albanians on the
south. They snarl at each other, occasionally erupting in murderous
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Mitrovica is a bastion of extremism. The middle ground is the
bridge, a desolate expanse of barbed wire guarded mostly by French
soldiers that is the only thing keeping the two sides from
slaughtering each other. It has replaced the Berlin Wall and
Belfast's Peace Line as Europe's greatest monument to division and
intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Like the woman in the Old Testament who agreed to let Solomon
cut a baby in half rather than share it with someone else, the
Serbs are content to abide by the partition of Mitrovica, seeing it
as their Alamo, their last stand in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But about 700 Albanian families are demanding to return to their
homes on the north side, which Serbs seized during and after
Yugoslavia's campaign to drive ethnic Albanians from Kosovo, and
the NATO bombing last year that stopped it.
</P>
<P>
   Mitrovica presents international peacekeepers with their biggest
challenge, and its de facto partition makes a mockery of the UN
mission to nurture a multi-ethnic society. But a difficult task has
been made even harder by disagreements over how best to keep the
lid on boiling tensions.
</P>
<P>
   Some soldiers, including Americans, accuse the French Army,
which controls the sector, of being soft on the Serbs, by not
disarming them and showing them who's boss. Some say the French
harbor a historical sympathy for the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   But the KFOR commander, General Klaus Reinhardt, a German,
defends the French troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The French have the hardest job,'' he said in an interview,
bristling at suggestions that other nations have lost confidence in
the French. ``They never got a chance to prove they are impartial.
They do a dangerous job, and they do it well.''
</P>
<P>
   Some American soldiers who have been to Mitrovica said the
problem is not that the French are biased toward the Serbs, but
that the French believe the best way to keep the peace is to make
the Serbs feel safe. Sometimes that means looking the other way
when weapons are found.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a philosophical difference,'' said US Army Sergeant
Joshua Themann. ``I'd say most of KFOR thinks you should go in
there and take every weapon you can find. The French don't share
that view. They think if you're not hostile, things will settle
down. We think just the opposite, that unless you confront and take
weapons, it will get worse.''
</P>
<P>
   But while American soldiers seem more than willing to confront
extremists, their superiors are more skittish. When American
soldiers met violent resistance from Serbs during house-to-house
searches for weapons in February, the Pentagon ordered US troops
out of the area. Reinhardt said he sent the American troops back in
a day later to prove that the Serbs could not dictate who would be
assigned in the area. But it was a token gesture, and the Americans
have not gone back since.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the heavy lifting to the French. Dozens of their
soldiers have been hurt, some seriously, in clashes with both
sides, and Albanians have repeatedly tried to kill them.
</P>
<P>
   Lieutenant Matthieu Mabin, 25, a French soldier, acknowledged he
was sympathetic to Serbs, but not to the extent that he would favor
them over Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy for the Serbs,'' said Mabin, standing outside
one of three apartment buildings on the north side where the French
soldiers guarded returning Albanians. ``The Albanians have a future
because we're here. The Serbs are very afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   International police units dispatched here by the United
Nations, meanwhile, are critical of the KFOR in general and the
French in particular. J.D. Lucky, a Texan who was in charge of
policing in North Mitrovica, said that French troops looked on and
did nothing to help as he was set upon and beaten by a Serb mob in
February. For his trouble, Lucky was transferred.
</P>
<P>
   His replacement, John Adams, an inspector from the Royal Ulster
Constabulary, Northern Ireland's police force, which is among the
world's most experienced in policing a divided society, held the
job for less than a month.
</P>
<P>
   The day after Adams gave an interview to the Globe and several
other newspapers in which he criticized the French troops, he, too,
was summarily transferred by UN administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Reinhardt was unapologetic about the discipline meted out to the
police commanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody in the police doesn't like what we're doing, they
should talk to me, not to you,'' Reinhardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said the situation in Mitrovica needs a police response
more than a heavy-handed military one. But he said the UN is not
backing the police, prefering to defer to KFOR.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's lacking here is a determination to show who is in
charge,'' said Adams. He said the police force in Mitrovica, which
numbers 500 officers, needs to be three times larger.
</P>
<P>
   The police and military, meanwhile, appear to be singing from
different hymn sheets. Adams said he had intelligence reports
showing that many of those causing trouble on the Serb side are
taking orders from Belgrade, where the regime of the Yugoslav
president, Slobodan Milosevic, sees the destabilization of
Mitrovica as a way to undermine the international effort throughout
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But Reinhardt, contradicting not just Adams but US officials and
his direct superior, NATO supreme commander General Wesley Clark,
said there is no evidence that Belgrade is directing Serb
troublemakers in Mitrovica.
</P>
<P>
   Mitrovica is home to extremists on both sides. On the south
side, Emin Xhinovci, a former rebel with the Kosovo Liberation
Army, runs a cafe he named after Adolf Hitler. French troops forced
him to take down a sign that had a swastika. But the soldiers could
do nothing to alter Xhinovci's appearance. He has dyed his hair jet
black, combed it to one side, and trimmed his mustache so that he
resembles Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem odd that an ethnic Albanian would idolize someone
who carried out genocide against Jews and various minorities, but
the Nazis also occupied Serbia and killed Serbs, and any enemy of
the Serbs is a friend of Xhinovci's.
</P>
<P>
   Just over the bridge, on the north side, Serbian men with
walkie-talkies sit in the Dolce Vita bar, smoking cigarettes,
drinking beer, and looking out the window for Albanians who dare to
try to come back. They sometimes beat up journalists, whom they see
as biased against them. When French troops went after the
walkie-talkie men last week, they were greeted with a shower of
stones.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place reminds me of home,'' said Adams, ``but we don't
have the level of hatred in Northern Ireland that exists here.
These people really, really hate each other.''
</P>
<P>
   While there is no shortage of thugs on either side, there are
also many ordinary people like the sleepless, beleaguered Mrs.
Refika and Olivera Josifovic, who don't wish harm on anyone and
just want to be allowed to live in peace.
</P>
<P>
   Josifovic, 35, a Serb, used to live next to the bridge, but
moved in with her brother in the Zvecan section farther north when
the war ended and the bridge became the epicenter of communal
hatred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the war, I worked with Albanians, and we would go to
each other's homes, but now I don't have contact with them,'' she
said, holding her 9-month-old son, Marko, in a Serb community
center.
</P>
<P>
   She accepts that partition is necessary ``at least until things
get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Does she think things will get better?
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope so,'' she said, turning to look at her smiling son. ``I
hope I live, for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 1315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6687 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS &LR;      04-04 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON, WE HAVE A PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching a diva meltdown is like witnessing the implosion of a
grand old building: in an instant, a once-great and mighty
structure is reduced to rubble and dust.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the destruction of a building is a methodical,
meticulously planned event _ it's supposed to happen. Divas, on the
other hand, just come undone, unraveling before our eyes with a
myriad of tantrums, tribulations, and troubles until there's isn't
much left. It happened to Billie Holiday, it happened to Judy
Garland. And, some believe, it may be happening to Whitney Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I'm not implying that Houston will wind up destitute,
shattered, and gone too soon like Holiday and Garland, who finally
checked out at 44 and 47 respectively. But, recent reports seem to
indicate that Houston, 36, is spiraling out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Houston _ depending on whose story you believe _ either bowed
out of or was fired from an appearance on the last week's Academy
Awards. At one preshow run-through, Houston was allegedly ``out of
it,'' and at another rehearsal, she reportedly missed her cues,
sang the wrong song, and generally seemed ``discombobulated,''
according to what one source told gossip maven Liz Smith. Burt
Bacharach, one of the show's musical directors, is said to have
told Houston, ``Just leave. It's not going to work out,'' 48 hours
before showtime. (She was replaced by country singer Faith Hill.)
</P>
<P>
   And even as tongues were still wagging about Houston's Oscar
no-show, word came of her bizarre behavior during an interview with
Jane magazine. According to writer Tony Romando, the notoriously
tardy Houston arrived four hours late, claiming she had a dental
emergency. And during the interview, she ``was extremely unfocused,
had trouble keeping her eyes open, and kept singing and playing an
imaginary piano on the table,'' he said. She also compared meeting
the president to hanging out with a junkie, and referred to the
jeweler who made the gold and diamond bracelet adorning her wrist
as ``this Jew guy on Diamond Row.''
</P>
<P>
   Quipped Romando about Houston's demeanor, ``I guess laughing gas
can do that to you.'' Could be. But there's nothing funny about
what's been happening to Houston. It's just sad.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a strange year for Houston. In January she was
detained at an airport in Hawaii after 15.2 grams of marijuana were
found in her bag; she was late-hour scratch from this year's Rock
and Roll Hall of Fame induction ceremony where she was supposed to
honor her mentor, Arista's Clive Davis; and there's even continued
debate over whether, during the Grammys, she flipped the bird (some
say she merely shook her fist) at Rosie O'Donnell when the comedian
made a thinly veiled crack about Houston's Hawaii troubles.
</P>
<P>
   All this has been keeping Houston's publicists busy, issuing
statement after statement to explain their client's recent
exploits. But nothing can erase the perception that Houston has
become that most frightening of creatures _ the diva run-amok.
</P>
<P>
   These disturbing reports come at an inopportune time for the
singer. After less-than-stellar initial sales in 1998 for her
latest album, ``My Love is Your Love,'' the CD rebounded big-time
on the strength of brilliant dance remixes of ``Heartbreak Hotel''
and especially, ``It's Not Right But It's Okay.'' With her career
regaining its momentum, Houston doesn't need bad press. Despite the
old axiom, sometimes there is such a thing as bad publicity.
</P>
<P>
   While she still has some of the best pipes in the business _ you
can fault her choice of material, but her voice is extraordinary _
Houston is a long way from the squeaky-clean image cultivated for
her when her career began 15 years ago. Whereas people once watched
Houston to marvel at her considerable talent and beauty, now just
as many folks probably want to see her because she might do
something unseemly or outrageous, if she even bothers to show up.
These days, watching Houston is like attending a stock car race _
there's always potential for a spectacular crash.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Houston's having a bad spell, and there's more to the
official reports of the singer's sore throats and bouts of
exhaustion than the subterfuge of her publicists. She's hardly the
first star to be combative, belligerent, and difficult. After all,
she is a diva, and that is what divas do. But it's high-time for
someone to rein Houston in _ not just to save her career and
reputation, but perhaps the singer herself.
</P>
<P>
   Remember back in 1992 when Houston inexplicably married
oft-troubled singer Bobby Brown, and many believed such an
association would tarnish her reputation? Now, it seems, the two
may have been better matched than any of us then realized.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
