<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PALERMO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T BELIEVE WHAT THEY SAY ABOUT SICILIAN CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIE C. FRANKLIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALERMO, Italy _ When it comes to advice on traveling and
safety, Palermo seems to rank as one of the most dangerous
destinations in the world, right up there with Haiti, Colombia, and
Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   Filthy, dirty city, one acquaintance told my husband and me
before we left for a recent 10-day trip to Italy, most of which we
spent in Sicily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pericoloso'' (dangerous), said our friends from the north of
Italy. ``Mafioso,'' they added, just to make sure we got the point.
The most skilled pickpockets in the world are there, the guidebooks
warned. Take off your gold, leave the camera in the hotel room. (Mi
scusi? Why would I possibly want to be in bella Italia, and leave
my camera at the hotel?)
</P>
<P>
   Worst traffic on the planet, said the American we met on the
Amalfi coast just days before our journey south to Sicily. Drivers
refuse to yield to stop signs, he said; worse, unruly motorcyclists
drive on the sidewalks. You take your life in your hands when you
walk in Palermo, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mama mia! Were we ``patzo'' to want to visit Palermo?
</P>
<P>
   Crazy we were not, but we sure were curious to see Palermo with
our own eyes. And so, after four magical days in the tranquil and
sophisticated tourist town of Taormina, we boarded the train at
Messina for the 3 1/2-hour ride west to Palermo, the capital of
Sicily.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, our stay was brief, only 36 hours, but surely our
observations are as valid as anyone else's.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what my husband and I will remember about Palermo:
</P>
<P>
   --The pleasant couple who drove us from the train station to a
hotel, which they recommended to us, in the center of this bustling
city. That act of random kindness saved us several hours and a
whole lot of stress.
</P>
<P>
   --The roped-off Via Liberta, a wide and well-used pedestrian
boulevard in the center of Palermo's Old Square, an architecturally
rich and beautiful part of the city.
</P>
<P>
   --The sophisticated men and women who strolled the
pedestrian-only street, arm-in-arm, greeting friends with a kiss on
one cheek and then the other, pushing designer baby strollers, and
being pulled by their yuppie dogs.
</P>
<P>
   --Our charming horse-and-buggy ride through the Quattro Canti di
Citta; the shimmering blue Mediterranean Sea filled with cruise
ships and cargo barges in the bustling Bay of Palermo, the largest
port in Sicily.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, it probably would have been prudent to spend
three or more days in Palermo, a cosmopolitan city with quite a bit
to do. With more time, we would have ventured to the Palazzo
Abbatellis and the Museo Regionale Archeologic, two of Italy's most
renowned museums and home to important collections of ancient and
modern art. We would have also visited Museo Internazionale delle
Marionette, Palermo's well-known puppet museum. And we would have
taken a day trip seven miles east to the popular beach town of
Mondello.
</P>
<P>
   Here's my point: Travel is as much about expanding our awareness
_ of our world, our neighbors, ourselves _ as it is about getting
on and off planes, checking in and out of hotels, and eating at
restaurants and seeing the sights recommended by the guidebook or
by a friend. To truly expand our awareness, we must make our own
impressions about a place. When Gulliver travels to Lilliput and
Brobdingnag and tells the reader that ``nothing is great or little
than by comparison,'' he means that only by contrasting ourselves
to others can we really figure out who we really are.
</P>
<P>
   Why travel if not to compare our lives, history, culture, and
cuisine with others? What better way is there to really know
yourself? You must decide where to journey and why. Yes, read the
guidebooks; yes, talk to friends; but don't go to a place just
because it's in vogue, or stay away from a destination because
someone else didn't enjoy their time there.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: What others had led us to believe we would find
in Palermo, and what we actually found.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being mowed down by drivers who impulsively careen
onto sidewalks to avoid traffic jams, we saw cars parked neatly
along side streets. Contrary to what we had heard _ that there were
no traffic lights in Palermo _ we found both streetlights, and
drivers who obeyed them. It was possible to be a pedestrian in
Palermo and safely cross the street.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of finding a dirty, unattractive city here in Sicily's
northwest corner, we found a picturesque older town, bordered on
one side by the sparkling blue Mediterranean Sea, and on the other
by the snow-capped mountain peaks of Monte Pellegrino.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being upset by the sight of dirty, begging children
in the streets, we found children eager to speak English with two
Americans while the kids took a break from their pick-up
neighborhood soccer game.
</P>
<P>
   Don't misunderstand me. I'm not specifically advising you to go
to Palermo. What I am advising is that, after reading the
guidebooks and talking with friends, remember this: The adventure
of travel, the excitement that comes when you venture someplace
new, is entirely up to you.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
