u f BC-RUSSIA-YUKOS-BOS &LR;      04-04 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YUKOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN OIL GIANT FORCED TO CLEAN UP ITS ACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEFTEYUGANSK, Russia _ Times have changed for Yukos oil _ or so
it says.
</P>
<P>
   In Yukos's heyday, the giant oil company was one of Russia's
most powerful and politically connected corporations. But to
foreign investors, it was also an example of what was wrong with
doing business in this vast country.
</P>
<P>
   Critics accused Yukos's executives of using their political ties
to make themselves fabulously rich while evading taxes, hiding
profits, and using dirty tricks to keep stockholders from sharing
the wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Yukos's executives appeared to be willing to try anything to
prevent investors from having a say. Last year, minority
shareholders showed up for an important meeting to find a notice
taped to the door informing them that the session had been moved to
a town 100 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   But since President Vladimir V. Putin came to power in December,
Yukos has lost the allies in government it had under Boris N.
Yeltsin and also expects to lose the tax breaks, government
contracts, and other privileges it once enjoyed. Instead, the
company hopes to regain its position by running an efficient
business _ or at least selling that image.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, the company has posted healthy profits, cut
costs, paid delinquent taxes, and promised stockholders millions of
dollars in dividends. In an effort to spruce up its image, it also
flew groups of reporters out to its oil fields to witness the
progress.
</P>
<P>
   On the Priobskoye oil field in western Siberia last month, Yukos
showed off Russian employees and foreign partners working together
on towering rigs in subzero cold. It has brought in the French
company Schlumberger, a leading oil-field services company, to help
increase output and efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Mikhail Khodorkovsky, Yukos's chief executive officer, said in
an interview that he wants to bring ``efficiency and transparency''
to the company.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, the company has hired the US accounting
firm PricewaterhouseCoopers to audit its books. Khodorkovsky also
promised that independent directors, including foreigners, will be
appointed to the board and that executives will hold frequent
meetings with investors.
</P>
<P>
   The changes have produced results, Yukos said.
</P>
<P>
   It has slashed its operating costs to $3.70 per barrel of oil,
down from $12 in 1998, helping the company post a pre-tax profit of
$600 million last year. Shareholders have been promised $100
million in dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Has this former bad boy of Russian capitalism really gone
straight?
</P>
<P>
   Troika-Dialog, a Moscow-based investment bank that holds a
minority stake in Yukos, is not persuaded. In a recent report, the
bank called Khodorkovsky's efforts to clean up Yukos's image ``spin
control masquerading as corporate governance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For many investors, Yukos is the epitome of shareholder abuse
in Russia _ no mean feat,'' the report read.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Yukos's impressive profits were attributable to
higher oil prices, while the company's low production costs were
the result of Russia's devaluation of the ruble in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yukos is effectively playing the game that everyone else is
playing now, which is `be nice to investors.' But they still have a
lot to do to prove this isn't just hot air,'' said Jim Henderson,
an oil and gas analyst at Renaissance Capital, a Moscow-based
brokerage. ``It is not as if they said: `Ooh, we've been naughty
and now we had better be good.' It is in their own interests to do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Russia becomes prosperous and stable depends largely on
companies like Yukos, one of eight major oil companies here.
</P>
<P>
   The oil industry dominates Russia's economy. Fuel and energy
taxes provide 40 percent of the national budget. Oil and gas
exports account for 47 percent of foreign currency reserves.
</P>
<P>
   If the industry can generate wealth for its employees and
investors, not just its executives, the economy should flourish. If
the industry can't, or won't, then Russia's explosive mix of a
small wealthy class and a majority mired in poverty could
destabilize the country.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Yukos's history gives ample cause for caution.
</P>
<P>
   Khodorkovsky, the chief executive, is one of Russia's
``oligarchs,'' a group of financiers who used their political
connections after the Soviet breakup to buy the crown jewels of
Russia's economy _ oil and gas companies, nickel mines, aluminum
smelters, television stations _ at prices well below their value.
</P>
<P>
   Boris Berezovky, perhaps the most influential of the oligarchs,
boasted in a 1996 interview that he and six other men controlled
half of Russia's economy, and that they had financed the reelection
of former president Yeltsin and had been dictating government
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Under Yeltsin, the oligarchs were able to use their clout to
avoid taxes, manipulate legislation to their benefit, and increase
their stranglehold over the economy.
</P>
<P>
   In Putin's Kremlin, Berezovsky still has influence. But
Khodorkovsky has lost his allies.
</P>
<P>
   That has made it necessary to live down the reputation Russia's
oil giants gained for manipulating their finances to cheat
shareholders. The biggest blow to Yukos's reputation resulted from
a scandal involving the financier Kenneth Dart, a US-born
billionaire who in 1994 renounced his citizenship and moved to the
Cayman Islands.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Dart, who held minority shares in three Yukos
subsidiaries, publicly accused the company's executives of cheating
minority investors. Yukos responded by excluding Dart from a series
of shareholder meetings where it issued new stock and sold it
cheaply to Yukos-owned companies in Cyprus, diluting Dart's stake.
</P>
<P>
   Khodorkovsky does not deny the charge, but said he acted because
Dart was resisting plans to streamline the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't start this dirty game, but I was ready to answer in
kind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After a yearlong battle in the courts and the press, the two
sides settled their dispute in December when Yukos agreed to buy
out Dart's shares for a reported $120 million. (He is believed to
have invested significantly more, but his representatives refused
to say how much.)
</P>
<P>
   Khodorkovsky has accused the Western media of an anti-Russian
bias for taking Dart's side.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was all very unpleasant because during the battle with
Dart there was a lot of Russophobia in the Western media,
particularly in America,'' Khodorkovsky said.
</P>
<P>
   But Western investors are not alone to have clashed with Yukos.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Petukhov was mayor of Nefteyugansk, a Siberian outpost
where Yukos has its largest production company. A harsh Yukos
critic, the mayor led protests outside its headquarters after the
company cut salaries and stopped paying local taxes. In a letter to
the federal government in June 1998, Petukhov accused Yukos of
``cynical actions and murderous politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, he was shot dead while walking to work.
</P>
<P>
   Yukos officials, who accused Petukhov of corruption, denied any
involvement, but many people in Nefteyugansk suspected the oil
company. The crime has never been solved.
</P>
<P>
   The company's relations with the town have improved. Yukos has
paid all its taxes, contributed computers to city schools, and
helped finance the building of a church.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 1320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
