<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6691 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-FALCONE-HNS &LR;      04-04 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALCONE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     `FALCONE' STANDS ON ITS OWN AS WORTHY DRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The comparisons to ``The Sopranos,'' the scheduling that recalls
``Roots,'' the way a national tragedy kept it off the air last fall
_ all that can wait for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Falcone,'' the long-overdue mob drama from CBS that began
Tuesday night, holds its own without caveats as engrossing
television. The drama manages to avoid being derivative, even
though it's a series (a miniseries, maybe) based on a movie
(``Donnie Brasco''), based on the real life of undercover FBI agent
Joe Pistone.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Gedrick (``The Last Don,'' ``Murder One,'' ``Iron Eagle''
and ``Ally McBeal'') plays Pistone _ Joe Falcone to his ``mob
pals'' in New York City. When we pick up the story, Falcone has
already ingratiated himself in a cell of la famiglia, befriending
Sonny Napoli (Titus Welliver of ``Mind Prey'' and ``Brooklyn
South,'' in a wonderfully revelatory performance).
</P>
<P>
   The tension grows as Falcone faces constant challenges about his
loyalty, and an intramural mob war looms. The plot's effects are
heightened when we remember that a real person went through this.
</P>
<P>
   But the real tension comes from within Falcone's other family,
which includes his wife, Maggie (Amy Carlson of ``Another World''),
and their two children. They don't know the specifics of his other
life. They don't know what he's doing for the Feds. All they know
is that it takes him away from home for weeks at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the (show's) future, I can see family life being every bit
as important as the mob life,'' said executive producer Mark
Johnson, who was also a producer for ``Donnie Brasco.''
</P>
<P>
   The new series ``is about a man who is so strongly compromised
in every relationship he has, yet has chosen his life _ and
secretly enjoys it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The show first garnered notice last spring for not making it on
the air. CBS President Les Moonves said he knew ``Falcone'' was a
good drama when it crossed his desk in April. Yes, good drama _ but
the wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   It was post-Columbine. Immediate post-Columbine, a week after
the school shooting in a Denver suburb. Moonves said he had a
``visceral'' reaction to the violence (an ice-pick murder has since
been toned down). The show was shelved.
</P>
<P>
   Now the program CBS didn't want to air is being presented as
event television. Using a scheduling strategy for a drama not seen
on network TV since ABC's ``Roots'' aired on eight consecutive
nights in January 1977, ``Falcone'' will be ``stripped'' _ running
on eight nights over nine days.
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour pilot will be followed by one-hour installments
airing at 10 p.m. Wednesday through Saturday and Monday, April 10,
through Wednesday, April 12. (CBS is airing a live teleplay, ``Fail
Safe,'' on Sunday night.)
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Kahl, the network's senior vice president for program
planning and scheduling, said CBS didn't have a natural time slot
for the show, and wanted to put some promotional effort behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really liked the show, and we kind of said to ourselves,
`What can we do a little differently ... so it wouldn't fall into
the mid-season pitfalls?''' he said. ``How can we call a little
extra attention to that show so it doesn't fall into the same
trap?''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who spent the downtime from ``Falcone'' producing the
feature movies ``Galaxy Quest'' and ``My Dog Skip,'' relishes the
show's change of fortune. ``I'm thrilled we are doing it this
way,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Although each episode can stand on its own, there's a serial
effect that is amplified by the nightly airings: ``As written, one
show feeds off the next. We do pick up where the last one left
off.''
</P>
<P>
   But remember: Although the success of ``The Sopranos'' certainly
piqued the interest of CBS, this is not a clone show. The moral
center is different. The feel is different. The executive producer
said it came naturally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have to consciously be different,'' Johnson said.
``Like everyone else, I am a huge fan of `The Sopranos' ... (but)
ours is a different show. Ours does not have the black humor. We
didn't have it in the movie, and we didn't have it in the show
itself. It is about a completely different character.''
</P>
<P>
   Another difference: There is no cable-only profanity. Still, the
dialogue rings true, with one notable exception.
</P>
<P>
   When a mobster asks another mob guy in the hospital how he
feels, there are a lot of things he can say. ``Like a bag of poop''
is just not one of them. Sorry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize he said that,'' Johnson said. ``I have no
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, there are a couple of ``Sopranos'' crossovers. For
example, Louis Lombardi, who plays FBI agent Skip Alari on the HBO
series, is small-timer Ernie Bello on ``Falcone.''
</P>
<P>
   And Lillo Brancato Jr., who as Matt Bevilaqua got blown away a
few weeks ago, plays Sonny's pal Lucky on ``Falcone.'' Our guess is
his fate won't live up to his nickname.
</P>
<P>
   Put aside all those tangential issues surrounding this
compelling drama. ``Falcone'' is not ``The Sopranos,'' or
``Roots,'' or just a scheduling guinea pig. It stands on its own
just fine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
