<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6693 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-04 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STAND UP AND DON'T BE COUNTED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I'm a criminal. The deadline for returning U.S.
Census forms passed on Saturday and my ``short form'' is still
sitting on my desk next to my tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   The government definitely will get my tax returns. I'm scared of
the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not scared of the Census Bureau, which has given us an
extension to April 11 and probably won't prosecute anyone who
misses that deadline. So I don't know when I'll mail back that
form.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 40 percent of the American public isn't returning
census forms. Some are simply procrastinators or losers who can't
keep federal forms separate from Ed McMahon's letters in the mail
pile.
</P>
<P>
   I partly fall in that group, but also partly in a group that
consciously resists returning the forms. In other words, I
consciously resist going through the pile of junk mail to find that
census form.
</P>
<P>
   You might as well ask me to get up from the dinner table and
have a nice conversation with someone reading a script to persuade
me to change phone services. You might as well ask me to put my
credit card and Social Security numbers on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The census comes every 10 years, and this isn't the decade to be
asking people personal questions.
</P>
<P>
   Some conservative radio talk show hosts have advocated
resistance to the census and the supposedly intrusive questions
about income and indoor plumbing posed by the all-powerful federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   They have it backwards. The government can't be all that
powerful if it needs to find out if you have a toilet or a
telephone. So much for all those conspiracy theories that have the
Feds watching us while we're on the john and listening to all our
conversations.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't mind filling out the long form's questions about
indoor plumbing. Of course, there is some shame involved. I'm
ashamed I don't have outdoor plumbing. That's what determines
status in the San Francisco area _ outdoor plumbing like a hot tub
and a Port-a-Potty for workers building additions on the house.
</P>
<P>
   There's only one set of questions on the short form I find
troublesome, the questions about race. Despite a large number of
boxes to check (11 different ones for Asians), there simply aren't
enough choices to fit America.
</P>
<P>
   Let's be real honest, I hate checking a box marked ``white.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just so boring, bland and doesn't quite match the way I'd
describe myself, which is all-American, half-crazed, half-Irish
swamp Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   Being white definitely has its advantages, such as during
traffic stops, police sweeps or visits to the loan departments of
banks. But nobody wants to check a box marked ``white.'' You might
as well check ``can't jump,'' ``can't dance'' or ``white shoes and
white belt.''
</P>
<P>
   And according to the Census Bureau, if you check two boxes, say
``black'' and ``white,'' you'll be counted as black. In other
words, they're following the same definition of race created by
racists in the South.
</P>
<P>
   A national census (or ``enumeration'') is mentioned five
paragraphs into the Constitution as the basis for determining
representation. If a census were important enough to mention that
high up in the Constitution, perhaps we should go along with it.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, though, the census seemed tangled up in issues of
race and legitimacy. The Constitution leaves the specific questions
on the census to Congress, but does mention counting ``free
persons,'' excluding ``Indians not taxed,'' and counting all other
persons as ``three-fifths.''
</P>
<P>
   No, the Founding Fathers didn't get off to a good start,
counting each slave as three-fifths of a human being. Maybe there's
some poetic justice in the fact that 200 years later only
three-fifths of the human beings in the country are responding to
the census.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrants are scared of being harassed by the Immigration and
Naturalization Service. Conservatives don't like government
intrusion in service of redistribution of wealth _ or distribution
of services, as liberals would have it.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of plain people don't like giving their income or
answering questions like the one on the long form about whether
they have difficulty ``learning, remembering, concentrating?''
</P>
<P>
   What?
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Secretary of Commerce William Daley says information on the
value of your home will help determine the adequacy of housing for
the elderly, and information about military service will help plan
the location of veterans hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   As if housing for the elderly ever will be adequate. As if the
government is actually opening VA hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   No one believes the Census Bureau when it says our answers will
remain confidential. After all, this is America.
</P>
<P>
   The president released private letters from a woman he allegedly
made passes at. The mayor of New York released juvenile records for
a guy shot and killed by the police. College transcripts for George
W. Bush and Al Gore were spread all over the newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not advocating that people violate the law and refuse to
respond to the census. I doubt the Feds will be telling the
tabloids you don't have a phone or indoor plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   I'm definitely returning my census forms, but only to keep the
Census Bureau from sending an enumerator to my house. I can tell a
Jehovah's Witness to get lost, but I don't think I can tell a
census guy I'm not really white.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
