<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6694 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECHNO-MICROSOFT-BOS &LR;      04-04 1595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-MICROSOFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTING UNIVERSE HAS CHANGED DURING MICROSOFT CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In 1997, when the US Justice Department asked a federal court
to slap Microsoft Corp. with a $1 million-a-day fine for illegal
practices, the company's number two executive, Steve Ballmer,
replied: ``I say to heck with (US Attorney General) Janet Reno.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, 2 1/2 years later, Microsoft's bold confidence has been
shaken not only by the beatings it has taken but also by the rapid
changes in the technology world that make it harder for any one
company to be as dominant as Microsoft has been.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's harsh ruling on Nov. 5, which
denounced Microsoft's business practices, forced the company into
four months of negotiations aimed at settling the case. But
settlement talks died and Jackson has found Microsoft guilty as
charged. No one doubts the software giant will appeal.
</P>
<P>
   So Microsoft's renewed determination to win in the courtroom
comes as the company has already lost the first major battle and is
virtually certain to lose the next.
</P>
<P>
   And just as the legal battlefield has been reshaped over the
past 29 months, so has the competitive landscape of the computer
industry. These changes will permanently alter Microsoft's role in
the industry, whatever the outcome of the antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, when the case began, many thought the future of
computing would be resolved by the browser wars. And Microsoft's
move against Netscape was viewed ominously by those who feared the
Redmond, Wash. company was gaining a lock on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But even then, there were ample evidences of other rising
technologies. That year, 3Com Inc. sold a million of its handheld
Palm Pilot handheld computers, devices that didn't use any
Microsoft software. Already, about 70 million people worldwide were
using the Internet, a computerized communications system run with
non-Microsoft software.
</P>
<P>
   And hobbyists and computer science students were beginning to
sing the praises of a new kind of computer operating system called
Linux _ sophisticated, powerful, and available at no cost. Unlike
Windows, Linux is ``open source'' software. That means its raw code
is freely available, so programmers can modify it at will. And
Linux is completely independent of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   None of these changes have harmed Microsoft's ability to make
money. The company earned $7.8 billion in profits in the fiscal
year ending last June. And its core market for personal computers
continues to grow rapidly. The Chicago market research firm
eTForecasts projects that over 200 million PCs will be sold
worldwide in 2005, up from 125 million this year. The majority of
these machines will rely on Microsoft operating systems and
applications software. If Microsoft isn't dismantled by the federal
courts, years of robust earnings lie ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But the Microsoft of 1997 seemed unstoppable. Not only did it
boast overwhelming dominance on the desktop, it also appeared
poised to extend its power to every other area of computing.
Indeed, that fear was at the heart of the government's decision to
prosecute.
</P>
<P>
   But today, it's a different world. ``You have dramatic shifts in
the industry every 18 months to two years,'' says Microsoft
spokesman Jim Cullinan. Because of those changes, he says,
Microsoft's role in the industry was bound to change _ lawsuit or
no lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Part of it is simply the inevitable backlash felt by any
institution that's perceived as extremely powerful. Bob Young,
chairman of Red Hat Software Inc., the leading supplier of Linux
operating systems, can tell the difference simply by listening to
people who greet him on the street. ``They say, `We're just
generally pulling for you guys,' '' says Young. ``There's sort of
the sense (that) people are tired of being dictated to by
Microsoft, and they want successful alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   From near-total obscurity in 1997, Linux now commands a quarter
of the market for server operating systems, second only to
Microsoft Windows NT. Part of Linux's success, says Young, is due
to the perception of Microsoft as a corporate bully.
</P>
<P>
   Young also credits the government's antitrust case, saying that
it prevented Microsoft from attacking Red Hat with the sort of
heavy-handed tactics the company has used against other rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that it was easier to strike the
relationships we've been able to build with (computer makers)
Compaq, IBM, and Dell as a result of Microsoft not being as
aggressive as they have been documented as being in the past,''
says Young.
</P>
<P>
   And yet he believes that even if Microsoft hadn't faced the
lawsuit, there'd still be a Linux boom. The reason, says Young, is
the rise of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet and open source are tightly linked,'' says Young.
Like Linux, the raw programming or source code for every key
Internet system is public information. As companies began building
Internet-based communications and business systems, they became
accustomed to the freedom and flexibility that comes with access to
the source code. And so corporate computer users were happy to
embrace an operating system based on the same philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Irving Wladawsky-Berger, the Linux chieftain at IBM Corp.,
shares Young's view. Despite Microsoft's efforts to control
Internet browsers, Wladawsky-Berger says there's no way any firm
can dominate a system as open as the Internet. ``The world economy
is so much bigger than a browser,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   As Young predicted, IBM has embraced Linux and other types of
open source software because they're a perfect fit for the open,
decentralized design of the Internet itself. For example, Windows
is basically limited to running on computers with microprocessors
based on Intel Corp.'s Pentium design. Linux, on the other hand,
will run on everything IBM makes, from laptops to mainframes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's lingua franca,'' says Wladawsky-Berger _ a universal
language for all kinds of smart machines.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is just beginning to have an impact on other
software markets dominated by Microsoft. The company's most
profitable product is its Office software suite, with word
processor, spreadsheet, personal information manager, and other
features. But little by little, people are starting to use
Internet-based software as a substitute for some of these
functions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a kind of liberation going on,'' says Geoff Ralston,
vice president for communications services at Yahoo Inc. Ralston is
in charge of a variety of Yahoo services that let people collect
their e-mail or schedule their appointments from any
Internet-connected computer, using software running on a Yahoo
server instead of the desktop machine.
</P>
<P>
   Ralston scoffs at the idea that Web-based applications like his
will ever substitute for traditional PC software. But it has
altered the way people store and access personal information.
Instead of keeping it solely on a Windows PC at work or at home,
the data is also stored on a remote computer located somewhere in
the Internet's ``cloud'' of interconnected servers. ``Suddenly,
everything is available to you all the time,'' Ralston says.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the same will apply to other popular software products. Sun
Microsystems Inc. plans a service called StarPortal that will give
users access to a full-fledged suite of office software, stored and
run on a remote server rather than the local computer. Microsoft
plans to offer the same service. If the concept catches on, it
could mean a dramatic decrease in sales of traditional software
packages _ an unsettling prospect for the leader in that market.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has never been the leader in handheld computing. That
industry was founded by Apple Computer Inc.'s ill-fated Newton
device, but blossomed when 3Com Inc. introduced the Palm Pilot in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's been trying to catch up ever since. But its
feature-laden Windows CE system left consumers cold. Meanwhile,
consumers have snapped up 6 million Palm devices, and a company
called Handspring is now selling less expensive models that use the
same underlying software.
</P>
<P>
   Palm's chief competitive officer Michael Mace says that
Microsoft and other rivals have failed because they try to apply
old software thinking to this new market. ``They've tried to design
a handheld as a miniature PC,'' says Mace. ``What you get is a bad
PC . . . and a bad handheld.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft vows to keep on trying. The company is launching a new
version of its Windows CE technology next month. But already, Palm
has achieved the kind of loyal customer base that Microsoft has
built up in desktop computers. Meanwhile, Palm and other companies
are rushing to add Internet browsing capability to the millions of
cellular phones sold each year. Again, it's a vast new market where
Microsoft isn't in the running.
</P>
<P>
   If Microsoft is left intact by the federal government, it will
remain one of the world's biggest and most powerful companies. But
in a striking illustration of how much the world has changed,
Microsoft last week lost its place as the world's most valuable
publicly traded corporation. That crown was snatched by Cisco
Systems Inc., builder of the underlying hardware and software that
makes the Internet work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The network has become the predominant issue in today's
marketplace,'' Cullinan admits. Microsoft is one of the biggest
nodes on that global network. But at the end game of the antitrust
trial, it's merely one among many.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6695 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-ADIRONDACKS-HIKING-2T     04-04 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADIRONDACKS-HIKING-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HIKING TO THE ADIRONDACK PEAKS ON THE CUSP OF SPRING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE COMFORT  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEENE VALLEY, N.Y. _ There's no telling what to expect in the
Adirondacks in late winter.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, we were treated to several inches of fresh powder for
an annual snowshoeing weekend at Grace Camp and Camp Peggy O'Brien
in the heart of the High Peaks region. This year, on similar dates
on the calendar, hiking boots and crampons for occasional icy
patches turned out to be more practical for trails that had melted
and re-frozen over the previous few days.
</P>
<P>
   Getting ready for the trip, it was unclear what we should even
pack for the 3 1/2-mile trek to the cabins, the two-night stay and
then a day of climbing some of the tallest peaks in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Record-breaking high temperatures and rain had melted all of the
snow in lower elevations, but our band of hikers was experienced
enough to know to expect anything at higher elevations. Indeed, as
late as mid-week an average of one foot of snow still lay on the
ground of the High Peaks region.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, traces of snow covered more and more of the brown
grass the further we drove north from Albany. By the time we pulled
into the parking area in Keene Valley called the Garden, the
scenery was mostly white under a sky that had brightened, for a
short while, from dark gray to a clear blue.
</P>
<P>
   Making a quick assessment at the trailhead, we determined that
with sturdy boots we could safely tread the route packed down by
dozens of previous hikers. But we stuffed crampons inside our
backpacks in case of icy patches near the peaks, and we strapped
snowshoes on the outsides in case a prediction of a couple of
inches of new snow proved too conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us recalled the pleasant surprise last year of walking
in on nearly bare earth and then awakening the next morning to
several inches of powder that built up to 18 inches by the end of
the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   This year, though, ski poles turned out to be our most treasured
equipment as we set out on the Phelps Trail toward our lodging for
the night. The warm weather and earlier rains had transformed
trickling creeks into free-flowing, rushing streams, and the poles
helped with balance in stepping atop rocks that provided only
slippery footholds across the dangerously cold water.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, near the afternoon's destination, the only way to
avoid a good foot-soaking was shimmying across a slick log while
clutching a second, parallel dead tree trunk.
</P>
<P>
   Hiking in on the cusp of two seasons brought some rewards as
well, though. Slender daggers of ice that had melted and refrozen
at the tips into glasslike bells hung over some of the taller
rocks, interrupting the flow of the newly freed streams.
</P>
<P>
   Lower Wolf Jaw, one of the 46 tallest Adirondack peaks that
would be obscured by full foliage in the spring or summer, appeared
in full view most of the way. And the higher we climbed the gently
graded trail, the heavier the dusting of snow that adorned the
hemlock trees.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly beyond the tricky stream passage, we veered off the main
trail to cross Johns Brook _ thankfully over a bridge this time _
and to enter property owned by the Adirondack Mountain Club.
</P>
<P>
   It was here in the 1920s that the club, which promotes
preservation of the Adirondacks and low-impact recreation in the
park, purchased land and two existing camps from club member Homer
Brown. Some of the earliest snowshoe and ski climbs in the High
Peaks started from this property in the late 1920s, according to
``With Wilderness at Heart,'' a history of the club published for
its 75th anniversary in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Our destination, Grace Camp, originally had been built closer to
the brook and named for Brown's wife. It burned to the ground in
1967, the cause never determined, and was replaced in time for the
1968 summer season, according to the historical account. New
environmental sensibilities prompted the club to move the camp 180
feet farther from Johns Brook in 1991 to its current location. The
one-room camp, which sleeps six, was modernized two years later,
with the interior gutted and renovated to increase floor space and
glass area.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a quarter-mile away on the same property, other
friends were staying at Camp Peggy O'Brien, a larger two-room cabin
that accommodates up to 12 people. This camp replaced the club's
deteriorating decades-old Winter Camp in 1988, and was named for an
active club member who had died a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Even more rustic accommodations are available in a nearby
lean-to and state-designated campsite. The thought of being open to
the whims of winter in these settings really builds up appreciation
for the Grace Camp's warmth, the mattresses on the beds, the
propane lights, the indoor clothes line for drying wet clothing,
and, the most deluxe feature, the foam covering for the
otherwise-cold outhouse toilet seat.
</P>
<P>
   (In the spring through fall, the club operates and staffs Johns
Brooks Lodge on the other side of the brook. A night's stay in the
hostel-like accommodations includes a full breakfast; a trail lunch
and family-style dinner are available for an additional fee. Like
Grace Camp and Camp Peggy O'Brien, the lodge is usually booked so
far in advance that it is wise to make reservations in the spring
for the following winter.)
</P>
<P>
   (MORE MORE)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KEENE VALLEY, N.Y.: xxx the following winter.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tim, Sandra, Mark and I arrived at Grace Camp before the other
two weekend occupants and knew enough to claim the bottom tiers of
the triple bunk beds. Heat can rise to near-sauna temperatures from
the wood-burning stove, once it gets stoked.
</P>
<P>
   It was only mid-afternoon, so we sat down on the benches at the
rustic wooden kitchen table and dug into our backpacks for
sandwiches and fruit for a late lunch before heading back on the
trail for a short hike while the sunlight lingered. There would be
plenty of time later to settle in and divide up chores: fill a pail
of water from the brook and heat it to a rolling boil on the
propane stovetop to make it potable; store perishable food in the
latched metal storage box on the covered porch that serves as a
refrigerator in the winter; fill the heat stove with some of the
firewood piled in another box on the porch.
</P>
<P>
   Trail signs posted within a mile of the two camps indicate that
several of the Adirondacks' highest summits are less than three
miles away. No wonder many aspiring 46ers, hikers intent on
climbing all of the highest 46 peaks, start their treks from here.
</P>
<P>
   Even the notoriously long walk in and then climb up Mount Marcy
becomes an 11-mile round trip from here, instead of the 17-mile day
trip required when starting out and returning to the Garden parking
area.
</P>
<P>
   With so many choices of trails for the full Saturday ahead, our
larger group of 16 hikers split into two. One decided to venture up
Upper Wolf Jaw, about a three-mile climb, and then, if stamina
permitted, continue on for another mile to Armstrong. My hiking
buddy, Tim, and I joined the other group led by an aspiring winter
46er, who wanted to add the 4,827-foot Basin to the list of peaks
scaled during the winter months.
</P>
<P>
   Several in that group already had been to that summit at least
once, so they were anxious for some variety. They devised a route
that started out on a maintained trail over a suspension bridge
then veered off to begin the increasingly steeper climb up Chicken
Coop Brook before rejoining the trail again for the steepest ascent
to the peak.
</P>
<P>
   Those who had brought along maps and compasses _ and knew how to
use them _ became our guides, since low-level clouds obscured any
nearby peaks that might have provided other hints on direction.
</P>
<P>
   The previous year, some of us had snowshoed up neighboring
Saddleback in several inches of powder, working hard to break trail
on the way up and then sliding on our feet, as if with skis, on the
steepest parts of the descent.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the deep holes in the snow around the trees indicated
that a few feet of snow remained on the ground. But a series of
melting and re-freezing had packed down the snow enough for easy
treading with hiking boots, leaving enough snow to cover the fallen
branches and roots that could trip an unwary hiker in other
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The scenery along the way featured ice in all of its beautiful
and treacherous forms: a thick, solid layer of chunks of frozen
snow built up behind a tree that had fallen across Johns Brook;
blue, glazed ice coating the trail near the peak; and a
greenish-hued frozen cascade tumbling over a tall rock face.
</P>
<P>
   The weather noticeably changed as we gained elevation and left
behind the shelter of tall evergreens. Crampons, sharp spikes
strapped onto the soles of boots, came out of day packs to dig
footholds into crustier snow and ice. Outer parkas were zipped up
as shields against the windy, damp air at the top, which was
enshrouded in a cloud. The mist blocked the views of Marcy and
Haystack accessible on clearer days, which was just as well since
the gray veil also prevented truly seeing how far the drop-offs
were beyond the ice patches I cautiously crawled over.
</P>
<P>
   Ever eager for adventure, my hiking companions chose to try yet
another route off the mountain, along Basin Brook, and then to
bushwhack alongside the opposite side of Johns Brook from the
established trail. This latter part of the trek brought the
discovery of an abandoned cabin not far from the camps yet far
enough from any regular route to remain hidden from most hikers.
</P>
<P>
   Our adventures were pretty well concluded, with just the hike
back to the cars left for Sunday morning. Light snow that had
fallen throughout the late afternoon and early evening turned to
freezing rain and wet snow by the time we set out. The streams were
still high, but we knew now where to cross the trickier sections;
the trail was turning mushy, disappointing the skiers passing us on
their way in.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the snowshoes had remained strapped to packs throughout
the trip. But we had been prepared for anything late winter in the
Adirondacks was ready to deliver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
