<HEADER>
A6699 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECHNO-QUIET-BOS &LR;      04-04 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-QUIET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO DO SOME YELLING ABOUT THE `QUIET PERIOD' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was going to be a darned interesting story about a
start-up's fund-raising experience. We did the interviews. We got
all the juicy details on its next-generation TV services, its
money, and its financial backers.
</P>
<P>
   Then the chief executive talked to his lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   He called back and said he shouldn't have spoken to us because
(gasp) his company is in the dread and oh-so-mysterious ``quiet
period.'' If we wrote the story, he claimed, he'd be in trouble
with the feds. Worse, if a story appeared where he seemed to be
touting his IPO _ which is slated to happen not this month, but
``sometime this year'' _ it might derail his stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   We'll still write that story, of course. But the incident
brought to a head the frustrating mythology of so-called quiet
periods, which are being overused in this heyday of high-tech stock
offerings, nervous chief executives, and overly zealous lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the facts. First, there is absolutely no rule in the
Securities and Exchange Commission's books about quiet periods. In
fact, no such words show up anywhere in securities law.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to quiet periods, observes Stuart Cable, a partner
at Goodwin, Procter &AMP; Hoar in Boston, ``Much of what you're dealing
with is lore, rather than law.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true. All of the rules related to the quiet period have
been written by lawyers, who are paid worrywarts. They all agree on
one central rule: that companies should clam up as soon as they
agree with their investment bankers to do an initial public stock
offering. The period lasts from then until the day their stock
starts trading, which is usually around 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   That's understandable. The point is _ and always has been _ that
companies should not be talking up their stock, or priming the
market, in advance of an offering. That means they shouldn't be
seeking press, urging their buddies to invest, making forecasts
that aren't in the IPO papers, or suddenly doubling their
advertising budget.
</P>
<P>
   It does not mean they should fail to respond to routine
questions about their operations, executives, and prospects during
that time. Nor does it mean that every corporate maneuver,
investment, or buyout thereafter begets a quiet period.
</P>
<P>
   Two wildly successful local companies, Akamai Technologies Inc.
and Sycamore Networks Inc., recently declined to talk to the Globe,
citing quiet periods. Sycamore was doing a secondary stock
offering, Akamai wrapping up a previously announced acquisition
(which was not the subject of the story).
</P>
<P>
   Neither of these are great reasons to shut off the flow of
information. Lawyers say a secondary offering requires less
solemnity than the IPO. An acquisition shouldn't spark a quiet
period, they say, unless the company's finances will be
significantly impacted by the event.
</P>
<P>
   Says Lynnette Fallon, a partner at Palmer &AMP; Dodge in Boston:
``There's no quiet period that gets triggered by an acquisition.''
</P>
<P>
   Fallon says companies are under gag orders simply because some
lawyers and executives are very conservative. They'd rather say
nothing than risk trouble. They're all fearful after the mistakes
of Webvan Group Inc., a Silicon Valley online grocery start-up,
which gave interviews to Forbes Magazine and to TheStreet.com
before its IPO last year. The SEC stepped in, in that case, and
called for a ``cooling-off period,'' delaying the IPO for one
month.
</P>
<P>
   Says Fallon: ``There's a lot of market fear. No one wants to be
the one that gets delayed.''
</P>
<P>
   But once a company is public _ like highfliers Akamai and
Sycamore _ there are far fewer excuses not to answer the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Cable tells his clients that ``normal corporate news,''
unrelated to a stock sale, is ``natural, desirable, and entirely
consistent with the objective of disclosure to the public which
underlies the federal securities laws.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the SEC itself pushes for maximum disclosure to average
investors. The regulators have been pushing companies to stop
giving details to Wall Street analysts that they won't give to the
public, or to reporters who are writing to inform the general
public.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: Unless a company's a few months from going public,
the quiet-period excuse is pure fiction. Why should the growing
ranks of ``insiders'' _ company executives and their families, the
lawyers, venture capitals, and Wall Streeters _ hoard information
that ordinary investors should have, too?
</P>
<P>
   They shouldn't. And it's time they grow up and act like the real
companies they profess to be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHAT'S A 'QUIET PERIOD'? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A ``quiet period'' is not required by law but is based on
lawyers' recommendations. It starts the day a company agrees with
its underwriters to go public and ends the day the company's stock
starts trading _ typically about 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   During the quiet period, lawyers tell clients:
</P>
<P>
   --Don't suddenly increase your advertising plans.
</P>
<P>
   --Put one person in charge of all information that goes out of
the company in response to questions.
</P>
<P>
   --No employee, officer, or director should encourage anyone to
buy the stock.
</P>
<P>
   --No employee, officer, or director should divulge forecasts or
other company information not in the IPO prospectus to people
outside the company.
</P>
<P>
   --Respond to legitimate inquiries for facts on the firm's
financial condition and business operations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
-------- &QC; 
 &QL; 
IPO watch &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are some initial public offerings scheduled for this week:
</P>
<P>
   Exelixis Inc.- San Francisco, 9.1 million shares, priced $10-12,
managed by Goldman Sachs; Industry: Other Services.
</P>
<P>
   GoAmerica Inc.- Hackensack, N.J., 10 million shares, priced
$14-16, managed by Bear Stearns &AMP; Co; Industry: Communications.
</P>
<P>
   HealthStream Inc.- Nashville, Tenn., 5 million shares, priced
$11-13, managed by Robertson, Stephens; Industry: Other Services.
</P>
<P>
   i3 Mobile Inc.- Stamford, Conn., 4.4 million shares, priced
$14-16, managed by Deutsche Bank Alex Brown; Industry: Business
Services and Software.
</P>
<P>
   LivePerson Inc.- New York, 4 million shares, priced $13-15,
managed by Chase Bank Hambrecht &AMP; Quist; Industry: Business
Services and Software.
</P>
<P>
   Numerical Technologies Inc.- San Jose, Calif., 5.5 million
shares, priced $11-13, managed by Credit Suisse First Boston;
Industry: Business Services and Software.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Beth Healy is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached by
e-mail at bhealy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
