</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUGH-CITY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS BOSTON A CITY OF NEGATIVITY? 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Perhaps this cradle of culture has become a bastion of
bashing. Maybe this city that prides itself on higher education and
high-tech is guilty of a less-savory reputation for low blows.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the hypothesis has assumed at least some renewed
relevance since Celtics coach Rick Pitino put Boston on notice _
and on the psychiatrist's couch _ with his harangue March 1
following a 104-102 loss to the Toronto Raptors at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   Despondent that the slumping Celtics had been beaten on Vince
Carter's implausible last-second 3-pointer and infuriated that he
had been subjected to jeers for his team and cheers for the
opposition in his own building, Pitino chastised the city, his most
volatile charge being, ``All this negativity that's in this town
sucks.''
</P>
<P>
   More remarkably, Pitino _ who changes opinions the way some
people do TV channels _ did not retreat from his stance. He
insisted the following day, ``I have no problem with anything I
said, not even this minuscule amount.'' He closed his right thumb
and forefinger for illustration and added, ``Everything I said was
the gospel truth according to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But is it the gospel truth, period?
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Pitino's comments are grist for
self-examination _ even self-guilt, a cherished Boston tradition.
Is this city a citadel of cynicism? Is it any more demanding, or
insufferable, than other metropolitan playpens celebrated for their
passion?
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it a tough town?'' said University of Connecticut and
former Northeastern basketball coach Jim Calhoun. ``Yeah, it's a
tough town. It's a very judgmental town because they love their
teams. And when you have love, there are two parts _ the other part
is hate. The one thing you have to do in Boston is succeed. And if
you do, they'll put you on top of the Pru.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you don't, just hope they don't expect you to jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sense in Boston that it's almost something to take
pride in to be nasty,'' said Patriots quarterback Drew Bledsoe, who
believes the city has a lot in common with other places in that
regard.
</P>
<P>
   The hectic lifestyle is not conducive to patience; it's tough to
make the mortgage, it's a challenge just to get from here to there,
and by the time harried patrons reach the game, they almost demand
instant gratification as a salve for daily life's indignities.
Anything less is considered a personal affront. That intolerance
has been stoked by the droughts of the local franchises: The
Celtics haven't won a world championship since 1986, the Bruins
since 1972, the Red Sox since 1918, the Patriots since the dawn of
time.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, failure seems to have become almost a medallion of
public pride; mass masochism is the prevailing sentiment even on
those occasions when a World Series, Super Bowl, NBA Finals, or
Stanley Cup Finals becomes Boston's destination. Of a far more
disturbing nature, the city long had a reputation for being
inhospitable toward minority athletes. Although the climate is said
to be improving, the hangover lingers.
</P>
<P>
   Sports reportage sometimes can be mistaken for war
correspondence. With the proliferation, if not saturation, of media
outlets and the resulting competition, controversy can become the
coin of the realm. But for all that attention, Boston is a
metropolis that sometimes seems to exalt small-town priorities. A
case in point is the professional franchises' struggles for
upgraded facilities, which, in this arena of political football,
often get treated like local zoning board debates over installing a
fire hydrant at the street corner. The Red Sox are still playing in
Fenway Park, amid the ghosts _ and some of the dirt _ from its 1912
construction. In their efforts to replace it with a more
commercially viable replica, they must tiptpoe through a minefield
of environmentalists and antiquarians, among others. Patriots owner
Bob Kraft's campaign for an urban stadium was summarily rebuffed,
and the intransigence of Massachusetts Speaker of the House Thomas
Finneran almost chased Kraft to Hartford before a compromise was
forged to keep the team in Foxborough. The Bruins and Celtics were
consigned to the cobwebs of Boston Garden for some three extra
decades before their pleas for better accommodations were answered.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's just plain meanness, as evidenced at the
FleetCenter Wednesday during the McDonald's All American High
School Basketball Game. Some among the crowd of 18,264 took the
opportunity afforded by the presence of 7-foot-6-inch Neil
Fingleton of Holy Name in Worcester _ a native of England and a
relative newcomer to the sport _ to chant, ``This isn't a circus,''
and ``Freak.'' When Fingleton missed a dunk, he was booed
mercilessly, prompting Celtics forward Paul Pierce to echo his
coach's comments of four weeks before: ``The fans of Boston are
terrible. They booed the kid from Boston _ he's only 16.''
</P>
<P>
   So how bad are things? Is this indeed a town without pity? Or,
in the final analysis, is it worth the aggravation? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Location, location, location &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blame it on the cursed, eclectic weather. Or the relentless
congestion of the megalopolis from Boston to New York to
Philadelphia. Or the unforgiving economy.
</P>
<P>
   In the Midwest, they worry about holding the door open for the
next person as opposed to slamming it in someone's face to get a
better spot in line. On the West Coast, the major concerns seem to
be what sunblock to use and when the surf will be up.
</P>
<P>
   Not in the Northeast. Generally, there is no escape. So the game
becomes the surrogate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The East is tougher,'' said Celtics guard Kenny Anderson, who
also has played in New Jersey, Portland, and Charlotte. ``It's
tougher to make a living. You've worked (hard) all day, it's a
hassle getting to the games, maybe there's a crisis at home . . .
''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, ``There's more a sense of urgency,'' said former
Rangers and Bruins defenseman Brad Park. ``People here have less
patience. It's `I want to be entertained and I want to be
entertained now.' ''
</P>
<P>
   With no excuses accepted. ``East Coast fans,'' said John
Davidson, an analyst on Rangers telecasts for MSG and an NHL
commentator for ABC, ``are not good at hiding their emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidson remembers experiencing culture shock during his
goaltending days when he was dealt from pardon-me St. Louis to the
crucible of New York in 1975. During warmups before his first
exhibition game, Davidson was besieged with vile expletives by a
customer behind his net. His curiosity could endure only so much.
He turned to identify this roughneck who had taken such an instant
disliking to him. ``It was a woman,'' said Davidson with a laugh.
``About 40. I thought, `Oh my God, what have I gotten myself into?'
''
</P>
<P>
   He'd gotten himself into the cacophonous corridor of the
Northeast, the Boston-New-York-Philadelphia axis.
</P>
<P>
   Boston isn't necessarily as loud as its bigger brethren, but it
has a distinctive, intimidating voice nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Former Red Sox reliever Dick Radatz considers it ``the greatest
place to play if you win and the toughest if you lose. It's like a
way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Radatz has seen that life from both sides. During four years as
the American League's premier reliever, he was a veritable oasis on
some dreadful Sox teams, a civic icon. As a rookie in 1962, Radatz
didn't allow a run in his first 20-plus innings. Then he was
brought into a bases-loaded, two-out jam in a Fenway tie against
the Yankees. Bill Skowron managed to get his bat on one of The
Monster's fastballs, mustering a feeble dribbler that found its way
through the infield, scoring the tying and winning runs. As he left
the mound, a stunned Radatz was booed. When he arrived, shaken, in
the dugout, third baseman Frank Malzone turned to him and said,
``Tough town, huh, kid?''
</P>
<P>
   Tough because, as ex-Patriot quarterback Steve Grogan observes,
the constituents ``can get a little impatient when things are not
going well, more than anyplace else.'' So much so that, he said,
``I've seen it drive some guys out of town before their time.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Red Sox general manager Lou Gorman, now executive
consultant for public affairs with the team, thinks that's because
the complaints often cross the line into foul territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many players resented it when it got personal,'' said Gorman.
``(Their feeling was), `If I strike out four times, criticize me.
But don't call me names.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
