<SLUG> BC-BBA-SEATTLE-MOYER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNHERALDED LEFTY MOYER IS NO. 1 IN SEATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ There's always been a thin line between a crafty
veteran and a No. 1 starter. After 11 years pitching for six teams,
Seattle's Jamie Moyer has learned to feel comfortable in both
roles.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his career, Moyer is an Opening Day
starter. Tuesday night, at Safeco Field, he'll oppose two-time Cy
Young Award winner Pedro Martinez and the Red Sox. It may sound
like a mismatch, but the Sox know better. Moyer has a 52-24 record
since July 1996, when he was traded to Boston for outfielder Darren
Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   If you recall, Moyer isn't one of those guys who tries to
overpower hitters. He will change speeds, throw sinkers, and use
anything else he can think of to befuddle batters.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer was 2-0 with a 1.80 ERA against Boston last year.
Lifetime, he is 5-3 against the Sox in 11 starts.
</P>
<P>
   When the Mariners opened Safeco Field last July, Moyer was the
starting pitcher but not the loser in a 3-2 setback against San
Diego. He didn't hesitate when asked to pitch this year's opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider it a big honor just to have the opportunity,'' said
Moyer. ``Especially since the last time I pitched an opener was
back in the eighth grade. I plan to go out and pitch and have fun
with it. But at the same time be competitive and give it my all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken me a long time to learn my craft. Why? I don't
know. Gaining confidence is a big thing. People having confidence
in you is a big thing, too. Over a period of time I learned a lot
and I matured a lot as a pitcher and a person. Since coming over
here, it's all come together.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer first made it to the majors with the Cubs in 1986. After
three seasons, he moved on to Texas, then St. Louis, Baltimore,
Boston, and Seattle. His overall record as both a starter and
reliever is 118-101.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer developed his unique style through trial and error.
Control is the key. Last year, he walked two or fewer batters in 29
of 32 starts. He averaged 1.9 walks per nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer's education started at Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming up in the Cubs organization, people had faith in me,
but I couldn't put up the numbers,'' said Moyer.
</P>
<P>
   Then he pitched in the heat of Texas and St. Louis before moving
on to homer havens in Baltimore, Boston, and Seattle. Instead of
wearing down, he became one of baseball's best pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   His winning percentage since 1996 (70.2) is bettered only by
Martinez (71.3).
</P>
<P>
   Moyer said his experiences at Fenway and the recently demolished
Kingdome forced him to make adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Fenway, you ideally like them to hit to center field or
right field,'' he said. ``Everybody likes to hit for the Wall. But
I quickly learned that in my style of pitching, I had to keep the
ball on the ground and try to utilize my defense. It was the same
way when I went to the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always have to make adjustments. In the Kingdome, the ball
seemed to carry better to right in the power alley. The solution
was the same even though it was turf. Keep the ball down and stay
away from the big inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they call Safeco a pitcher's park. I don't know about
that. We haven't even played a whole year here. Everything I know
is on last year's games. I will say if a ball is hit well, the
batter will be rewarded. But there are no cheap home runs here.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariners manager Lou Piniella says there was never a doubt in
his mind about his Opening Day starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good group of young men,'' said Piniella. ``They're
professional. They work hard. The attitude and the chemistry have
been good. ``He's just the best we have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
