u a BC-PARRISH-LANDSCAPE-ART     04-04 1696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARRISH-LANDSCAPE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (a and e coding)  
 A PAINTING IN THE BANK  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDSOR, Vt. _ It hangs in a nondescript spot behind the
tellers' desk, with no plaque, no label, no fanfare. If you didn't
crane your neck, you might not even notice it _ let alone realize
that this painting of a tree, hanging in a bank, is worth hundreds
of thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But try to take the Maxfield Parrish painting from this little
branch office and _ as one art gallery discovered last winter _
you'll face the wrath of a town.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the affection Windsor's 4,000 residents hold for the
early 20th-century illustrator. And such is their determination to
keep the painting, even if they have to fight the waves of
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Famous in his own time, when his whimsical figures and classical
scenes graced magazine covers, Parrish's pricey originals now hang
in posh hotels and movie stars' homes. But nowhere is he better
loved than in Windsor, where he's seen as a link to a cherished
past.
</P>
<P>
   From the height of his career to his death in 1966, Parrish
lived in an artists' colony in the woodsy hills of Plainfield, N.H.
But he conducted his business in Windsor, a small town of brick and
Colonial homes just across the Connecticut River, in the shadow of
Mt. Ascutney.
</P>
<P>
   For all the time he spent there, only one true artifact remains:
the landscape painting he gave employees of the Windsor County
National Bank in the early 1950s. He wanted to thank them for the
help they gave him, month after month, balancing his accounts.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed a clear-cut gesture of gratitude at the time, but
then, it was a simpler time. When Parrish gave the painting to
``the girls'' at the bank, Windsor County National was locally
owned and had just two branches. In 1967, it was bought by Vermont
National Bank, which itself was recently taken over by the larger
Burlington-based Chittenden National Bank.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of big mergers and financial conglomerates, the
painting on the wall has become the subject of new debate. And the
question of who owns it _ a succession of banks, or of people _
remains, to Windsor's residents, disturbingly unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   Chittenden's president, Paul Perrault, is doing his best to
reassure them. He pledged last week that ``that painting is going
to stay right there in that office.''
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to the more delicate question of ownership,
Perrault won't be pinned down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a question that needs an answer,'' he said.
``Does it have to have an owner?''
</P>
<P>
   Such was the state of affairs last week, when the latest bank
merger turned official and complete. To a small town, this was a
big deal: accounts were switched, new checkbooks were distributed,
Vermont National Bank signs came down, Chittenden signs went up.
</P>
<P>
   And a group of aging residents known as The Trust, afraid for
the painting's future, held a closed-door meeting with their
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The Trust, which claims ownership of the Parrish painting and
seeks to keep it in Windsor, is composed of 11 former bank
employees, most of them now retired, many of them old enough to
remember when Parrish himself came into the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Those were golden years in Windsor, a West Vermont town whose
legacy outweighs its size. In the 18th century, the Vermont
Constitution was signed here. In the 19th, a new wave of industrial
production was born in Windsor factories. And in the 20th, Windsor
was a commercial capital for an artists' and writers' community,
the famous Cornish Colony founded in New Hampshire by sculptor
Augustus Saint-Gaudens.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire may have had the landscape they loved, but Vermont
had the commerce. So artists would regularly cross the local
covered bridge, beneath a sign that still warns, ``Walk Your Horses
Or Pay Two Dollars Fine,'' and go to Windsor's post office, stores,
and banks.
</P>
<P>
   Like everything in small-town life, banking back then was a
social event, said Wesley Hrydziusko, a teller at Windsor County
National Bank in the late 1950s. ``Even if people didn't have any
bank business, they'd just stop in and chew the fat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But of all of the bank's favored customers, Parrish was among
the most beloved, Hrydziusko said. When employees saw his Cadillac
roll slowly up the street and pull up at the post office _ as it
did every six weeks or so _ they knew they were due for a visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute he showed in the doorway, he was greeted all over
the place,'' Hrydziusko said.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish wore neat, dapper clothes and had a shock of white hair,
Hrydrziusko said. And he always told a stream of jokes, and carried
a stack of checks. Bank officials would escort him into the
cashier's office as workers settled his accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1950s, to thank them for their help, Parrish gave
the employees a painting, titled ``New Hampshire: Thy Beloved
Hills.'' The image had been commissioned as a poster to promote New
Hampshire tourism, said John Dryfhout, chief curator at the
Saint-Gaudens National Historic Site in Cornish. But the original
painting was Parrish's to sell or give away. And it had the
trademark Parrish qualities: an ethereal, luminous glow, and the
electric-blue color the artist had copyrighted as ``Parrish blue.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, the painting hung prominently behind the tellers'
desk. When Vermont National took over and built a new branch office
down the road _ a neoclassical sort of structure, with thin columns
and a portico out front _ the painting was placed in a similar
spot.
</P>
<P>
   But the bank eventually moved it to a side wall, to make room
for a promotional display. The bank was trying to standardize its
look, one former employee said, and the painting didn't fit the
motif.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was there, and Windsor's residents were satisfied.
Over the years, the painting has become part of the local
landscape, said Pam Sullivan, 55, who works in a store that sells
Parrish's artwork on tote bags, night lights, and soap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who have been there a long time just see it as
part of the bank,'' she said. ``It's just been there. It would be
like moving the mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the painting has been a constant even as Windsor has
changed _ as factories closed, businesses left, and commerce
started moving in the other direction, from Vermont to New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   But of late, Windsor has been trying to revive itself, with a
new crop of artisans, museums, and promotions. And it still has
civic pride _ a lot of it _ as residents proved in February 1999,
when the Parrish painting almost disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Windsor Police Lieutenant Vincent Jordan remembers the morning
well; it was 7 a.m., toward the end of his night shift, when he got
the frantic call. It was a former bank employee, who had been
tipped off by a current one: Vermont National planned to sell the
painting, for $150,000, to the Currier Gallery of Art in
Manchester, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   The gallery had asked if the bank would sponsor an exhibit of
Parrish's work, said gallery spokesman David Juvet. The bank had
declined, Juvet said, but had offered to sell the painting instead.
The gallery arranged to pick it up on a Tuesday morning, Jordan
said, before the bank opened, at 8 a.m..
</P>
<P>
   But employees, past and present, didn't think it was the bank's
to sell. And they had what they considered proof: a letter from
Parrish's son, Maxfield Parrish Jr., which seemed to state the
artist's intent.
</P>
<P>
   Bank employees, the son wrote, ``made a visit by dad to the bank
a social occasion instead of a necessary chore. He appreciated it,
hence the presence there of this painting in the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan rushed to the bank and told gallery officials that the
painting's ownership was under dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, quite frankly, I really couldn't let the painting
leave the town,'' he said. ``I negotiated a stoppage of action.
Either that, or I take it back, and we hang it in the police
station.''
</P>
<P>
   The bank and gallery backed down, and the painting stayed. But
for weeks afterward, the town was in a tizzy. People threatened
lawsuits and boycotts. Bank officials issued an apology. And a
cadre of former employees banded together, hired a lawyer, and
formed the Trust _ filing legal documents asserting their ownership
claim.
</P>
<P>
   In the year since, the Trust and the bank have shared a cordial
detente. But, as many townspeople are quick to point out, the bank
has never given up its ownership claim. The matter has never been
litigated or settled, said Jonathan Springer, the Trust's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   And many residents say they're always ready for a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll guard it with our lives,'' said Barbara Rhoad, 60, a
lifelong Windsor resident who remembers Parrish from her childhood
days. ``We're not a money-type people. That isn't important. It's a
gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Trust's latest fit of consternation was overblown,
Springer insists; it stemmed from confusion about the Chittenden
merger.
</P>
<P>
   And Perrault, the bank president, said that while he intends to
get the painting ``spiffed up,'' he also plans to keep it where it
is.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, we don't need to have a big,
drawn-out battle about who owns it,'' Perrault said. ``I think
everyone's in agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but townspeople still don't feel secure, judging by
the hushed conversations in kitchens and living rooms. People still
speculate about why the painting hangs on the side wall _ does the
bank want someone to steal it? _ and talk about better places to
display it. They wonder about the bank's intentions. Some even
hatch half-serious plots about jumping over the counter and
whisking the painting away for safekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   And while the painting seems secure for now, Lieutenant Jordan
has considered the possibilities. So every night when he's on duty,
he drives by the bank and peeks in the window, just to check.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to keep an eye on it,'' he said. ``Make sure it's still
hanging on the wall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
