<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JOY OF CUSHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Linda Engley was curious about a word she'd come across in a
recent Globe Magazine column. ``What you will never see when you're
cushing in front of the TV,'' wrote John Yemma, ``is a major report
on, say, a crystal-clear afternoon in October.''
</P>
<P>
   Cushing? wondered Engley. ``Is this a real word? My abridged OED
doesn't list it.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the first time Yemma had used cushing: Last fall he
wrote of the newest luxury, the well-appointed home office, ``It's
not for cushing, vegging, lounging, cribbing, or kicking back.''
</P>
<P>
   But is it a ``real'' word? Yes, in the sense that several layers
of editors assumed readers would get it; it's obviously a verb
formed from cushy, which means ``soft, comfortable, easy'' and is
often, these days, shortened to cush: ``The winner gets a cush spot
in the quarterfinal round.'' There's also a noun cush, short for
cushion or cushioning: ``Lexus needs more cush for the tush,'' read
one headline.
</P>
<P>
   But cush as a verb, meaning ``to luxuriate, or make luxurious,''
is still very rare. A Lexis-Nexus search turned up a 1986 report
about Chrysler's ``cushing up the interior'' of the new Dodge Ram
pickup truck. And the earliest citation available _ a San Francisco
Chronicle piece in praise of three-day weekends _ quoted a Mill
Valley dentist, back in 1992, using the word: ``It allows me time
to run my errands, cush out, and have a whole different perspective
on life.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that Californians were cushing first. The
unexpected twist, when it comes to cush, is that its two meanings
may have quite different origins. Cushy though your cushions may
be, the words, some etymologists say, are not related.
</P>
<P>
   Cushion is not in dispute; as a noun, it goes back to Middle
English, which spelled it dozens of different ways (quishin,
cuisshin, whishin, cusshyn, coussin, for starters). The derivation
goes back to Latin coxa, hip or thigh, presumably the parts most in
need of cushioning. Cushy, however, remains an enigma. It's first
recorded in a 1915 letter from a soldier, and some authorities
(including the Oxford English Dictionary) say it's an Anglo-Indian
word, borrowed by British colonials from the Hindustani khush,
pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Others believe the source is more likely to be a different Indic
language, Romany, where the word is kushto, ``good.'' Some
reluctantly allow that it could be a slurring of cushiony, and Eric
Partridge's massive slang dictionary cites the dialect word cushie
_ ``soft, flabby'' _ as a possible source.
</P>
<P>
   But the American Heritage Dictionary editors think nobody's made
an airtight case. A usage note in the third edition (1992) opines
that the Anglo-Indian theory has scanty evidence, then throws
couchee (French for ``lying down; a bed'') into the mix. Recent as
it is, we may never know where cushy comes from.
</P>
<P>
   As for where it's going, that's our call. What is cushing for?
``I've used the word to mean something a little classier than
vegging,'' says Yemma. ``Vegging, to me, sounds brain dead. Cushing
is more joyful: It's sitting on that newly reupholstered chair with
a good reading light while listening to a great new CD with the sun
coming through the window, and an evening ahead with fresh scallops
and shrimp and mussels in the refrigerator and nice sheets to climb
into later.''
</P>
<P>
   If you like the sound of cushing, join the fun. It's not in the
dictionaries yet, but if the people want it, it will settle in and
stay a while.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Jan Freeman's e-mail address is freeman(at)globe.com; write to her
at The Boston Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378. Please
include a hometown and phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 1332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
