<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALCONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALCONE A NEARLY FLAT EXAMPLE OF MOB TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
FALCONE 
Starring: Jason Gedrick, Amy Carlson, Titus Welliver, Eric Roberts 
On: CBS 
Time: Tuesday from 9 to 11 p.m., followed by hourlong installments
at 10 p.m. through April 12, skipping only Sunday, April 9. 
Rated: TV14 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that we know the earth is as round as Michael Clark Duncan's
head, and Christopher Columbus has his own holiday, we don't have
much patience for flat. And so goes Mob TV after ``The Sopranos,''
now that we've taken David Chase's trip through the
multi-dimensional world of New Jersey's &UR;  &LR; made men and their
blood-stained car trunks. Who has time for a capo without a shrink?
</P>
<P>
   ``Falcone,'' a new series premiering Tuesday, is actually better
than flat, but only by a degree or two. It's based on the exploits
of real-life undercover FBI agent Joe Pistone, a family man who
submerged himself in the New York mob. The story made an excellent
movie, ``Donnie Brasco,'' and it's a rich premise for a TV series,
as a moral man gets blood on his hands and neglects his family in
the name of a greater good. Is he a hero, or a workaholic? Is he
secretly turned on by the criminal world he's infiltrating? And
will the mean boys with the guns ever discover his true identity?
</P>
<P>
   ``Falcone,'' named after Joe's mob alias, skips in and out of
these questions, and it's a fun ride at first. The series is
tightly plotted, and the twists create moments of satisfying
intrigue, particularly when members of the Volonte family nearly
find out Joe's masquerade. But juicy plot turns alone cannot fuel a
series for long, especially when they repeat themselves, and the
limitations of ``Falcone'' become clearer in its second and third
episodes. Soon you realize that the mob will almost catch Joe in
every episode, and that Joe's wife may never do more than throw
worried looks at the camera again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Other problems: The script is laden with overfamiliar
gangster-crew lingo that becomes tiresome. The noir look, now
predictible in TV crime dramas, is not artfully done. And the
casting is significantly off base. Pistone, played by Johnny Depp
in ``Donnie Brasco,'' is given an overly sensitive spin by Jason
Gedrick, the hunky actor recently seen cleaning Ally McBeal's
exhaust pipe in a car wash. Gedrick, also known from ``Murder One''
and ``EZ Streets,'' is likable, and he could easily carry a series,
but he's too likable in ``Falcone'' to be believable. What
self-respecting mobster would let this softy in on all his evil
plans?
</P>
<P>
   As ladder-climbing mob captain Sonny Napoli, Titus Welliver is
more effective, especially as the series progresses and we see his
cool crumble in explosions of rage. Along with his unusual name,
Welliver has a curiously compelling face, and his hard eyes seem to
whisper evil. On the other hand, his crew members aren't
distinctive, although ``Sopranos'' fans will recognize Lillo
Brancato Jr., who played the idiotic wannabe recently whacked by
Pussy and Tony. Only a raving Eric Roberts, who plays the mob boss
living in a psychiatric hospital, brings true electricity to the
proceedings, but he appears but a handful of times in the first
four episodes. He also adds a blackly comic element sorely missing
elsewhere on the show.
</P>
<P>
   In a risky move, CBS is airing the series as if it were a
miniseries event. Following the two-hour premiere, it will air in
nightly hourlong installments at 10 p.m. through April 12, skipping
only Sunday. The importance of that last date? It's the season
finale of ``The Sopranos.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
