<HEADLINE>
INFREQUENT-TRAVELER SMILES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those who travel infrequently may find themselves strangers in a
strange land as they puzzle their way through airports, hotels, and
car rentals. Sometimes their actions can be humorous _ to others
anyway (and, in retrospect, to themselves). Here are some of the
tribulations of inexperienced travelers who entered their stories
in Enterprise Rent-A-Car's Infrequent Flyer Rewards contest:
</P>
<P>
   --Debbie Bunten of Dohlonega, Ga., tried to heat her sandwich in
a hotel room safe, thinking it was a microwave. (She won the
contest grand prize _ a Chevrolet Tracker.)
</P>
<P>
   --Eliza Wolk of Ashland, Ore., dashed from her hotel room upon
spying a complimentary terry-cloth robe on the bed. A bellhop had
to assure her that no one else was staying in the room.
</P>
<P>
   --Charlotte Bender of Elyra, Ohio, was thrilled to see her name
in lights and a car waiting for her at an airport rental car lot.
Only one problem: The hoopla was for another C. Bender, who
belonged to the company's gold card club, and an embarrassed
Charlotte had to turn over the car to its rightful renter.
</P>
<P>
   --Other examples: Finding their hotel beds turned down, North
Carolina youngsters placed a hysterical call to their parents,
fearing someone had robbed their room. A roller-coaster fan just
loved her plane's emergency landing on a snow-packed runway but was
disappointed to learn all flights don't end that way. And a flight
attendant had to stifle her laughter when a man began yelling for
her into the air vent, thinking it was the intercom.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, those of us who travel more frequently are immune
from such embarrassing actions, right? Well . . . there was the
London trip that began with me bringing the wrong passport to Logan
Airport and ended with me spilling the contents of my carry-on bag
all over the floor at Heathrow Airport. But enough about that.
</P>
<P>
   (The contest judge was travel guru Arthur Frommer. For
Enterprise's latest offering, the ``Promote Yourself Career
Contest,'' visit www.enterprise.com.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Which is the nation's highest capital? (Answer at
end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``You may have the Universe if I may have Italy.'' _
Giuseppe Verdi. &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: McGillicuddy City, N.D., was formerly called Granville.
But it changed its name three years ago when it won a contest
sponsored by Dr. McGillicuddy's Imported Schnapps. (McGillicuddy
City, population 275, will celebrate its third birthday July 14-16
with street dancing, parades, trail rides, and more. Check out
www.drmcgillicuddy.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Today's loopy law: It is illegal for two men to carry a bathtub
across the town green in Longmeadow, Mass. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hollywood down under: Fox Studios Australia, located in the heart
of Sydney, has opened to the public and is expected to attract more
than 2.7 million visitors a year. ``Titanic _ The Experience'' is a
lurching, heart-stopping re-creation _ with audience participation
_ of the filming of the last moments of the ill-fated liner.
Meanwhile, Bent Street is headquarters for dining, shopping, and
entertainment. Tickets cost $24.50 US for adults and $15 for
children. For more information on Australia, visit
www.australia.com or call 800-333-0262 for a free vacation planning
kit. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Event to remember: The Great Gilroy Garlic Festival Recipe Contest
and Cook-Off will take place in Gilroy, Calif., lovingly known as
the garlic capital of the world, on July 29. Contest rules are
available at www.gilroygarlicfestival.com or by sending a
self-addressed, stamped envelope to Great Gilroy Garlic Festival
Recipe Contest and Cook-Off; Gilroy Garlic Festival Association
Inc.; PO Box 2311; Gilroy, CA 95021-2311. Entries must be
postmarked by May 1. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Denver may be the Mile High City, but the
nation's highest capital is 6,996 feet high _ Santa Fe, located in
the Sangre de Cristo Mountains. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Compiled from wire service reports, news releases, books,
magazines, Web sites, and the deepest recesses of the author's
mind. Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpenter(at)globe.com. Include
your name and community.)
</P>
</TEXT>
