<HEADLINE>
WHEREFORE ART ROMEO AND JULIET? IN VERONA! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERONA, Italy _ Under a sunny sky Verona seems to glow rosily,
romantically. And the air here seems unusually pure and zesty, like
the first sip of champagne at a wedding party.
</P>
<P>
   The many time-mellowed, red-tile-roofed and pink brick buildings
certainly contribute to the city's rosy coloration. The
invigorating quality of its air can be explained by the fact that
the jagged hills on the horizon are the Dolomites, foothills of the
Alps. But nothing _ or rather no one _ contributes as much to the
atmosphere of high-octane romance as those star-crossed loversRomeo
and Juliet.
</P>
<P>
   A jewel of a place, Verona is one of the best-preserved medieval
cities in northern Italy. It has magnificent churches and palaces,
a first-rate art museum, and an unusually beautiful main plaza. The
numerous ancient monuments include a well-preserved Roman
amphitheater, still in use and second in size only to the Colisseum
in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   For a lot of visitors, however, Verona's only must-see
attractions are the sites associated with Romeo and Juliet,
including what are purported to be their homes and her tomb. That
there are such sites is a tribute to the power of literature (not
to mention the shrewdness of tourist offices) since there is no
real evidence that the two ever existed other than in writerly
imaginations.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare's ``Tragedy of Romeo and Juliet'' was written around
1595. It was based on a romantic tale set in Italy and in
circulation in various forms since the 13th century but with plot
devices, such as two lovers dying after drinking from the same
poisoned cup, found in classical Greek literature. The feuding
Montagues and Capulets of Shakespeare's play did have real-life
counterparts in the Montecchis and Capuletis, two prominent
13th-century Verona families on different sides in the bitter power
struggle between the pope and the Holy Roman emperor, a dispute
that split the city and the region into warring factions.
</P>
<P>
   What is now known as Juliet's House was supposedly once owned by
the Capuletis, but whether a ``Giuletta'' ever lived there no one
can say. Anyway, she is certainly there now in the form of a bronze
statue of a pretty but downcast maiden that visitors love to pose
with.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, there is a balcony. The house on Via Capello is built
around an inner courtyard overlooked by a second-story stone
balcony. The small courtyard is frequently jammed with
camera-toting international tourists, and couples from Milan,
Berlin, Tokyo, Marseilles, Sheffield, and Boston happily line up to
reenact the balcony scene. ``Wherefore art thou, Romeo? . . . Hans?
. . . Pierre? . . . Guido? . . . Hideo? . . . Joe?''
</P>
<P>
   If tradition can be trusted, Romeo lived just a few streets away
from Juliet in a still standing but decrepit medieval house on Via
Delle Arche Scaligere. Because of its poor condition, the house, a
former Montecchi residence, isn't open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Juliet's so-called tomb _ an empty sarcophagus of dubious
provenance _ is in the crypt of the chapel of a former monastery at
the intersection of streets named Shakespeare and Capuleti. The
interior of the tomb, which looks rather like a stone bathtub, is
usually littered with scraps of paper. These are notes to Juliet,
ranging in tone from romantic to skeptical. (``Wherefore art thou,
Juliet?'' is a common sentiment.)
</P>
<P>
   Whether looking for the shadowy traces of the two lovers or
exploring Verona's very real artistic and architectural treasures,
the place to start is Piazza Bra, the main square. Just inside the
line of the 14th-century walls and accessed by a monumental
archway, Piazza Bra is one of the most pleasant and impressive town
squares in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   In the center of the piazza is a lushly-planted public garden, a
green oasis in the brick-red town. Facing the square on two sides
are several palaces, including Palazzo Barbieri, which houses
municipal offices. A third side is lined with cafes fronting on a
wide and curving sidewalk, known as the Listone, where the citizens
of Verona like to promenade in the early  &UR; evening &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The Piazza Bras's fourth side is dominated by the enormous mass
of the Roman amphitheater or arena. Built in the first century AD,
the arena _ which has 44 tiers of seating and could accommodate the
entire Roman town _ has long been Verona's pride. In the 17th
century a special town council was established to preserve and
restore it. The scene of chariot races and gladitorial spectacles
in Roman times, the arena is now used for large-scale grand opera
productions, naturally including ``Romeo and Juliet.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Verona's other Roman monuments still in use are two city
gates, Porta Borsari and Porta Leona; and also Ponte Pietra (Stone
Bridge), a sturdy but graceful five-arched bridge over the Adige
River, which loops protectively around the town. Frequently
repaired over the centuries with different kinds of stone, the
bridge has an engaging piebald appearance and is much photographed.
</P>
<P>
   The site of the forum, the Roman seat of government, is now
Verona's second main square, Piazza della Erbe. The scene of a
daily fruit, vegetable, and flower market, this piazza is a lively
and atmospheric spot, just steps from Juliet's House. Her statue is
often decorated with bouquets of fresh flowers bought at the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Verona has many magnificent churches but the one that definitely
shouldn't be missed is the basilica of San Zeno Maggiore. Built in
the 13th century to house the shrine of Verona's patron saint, a
fourth-century bishop, this is one of the most ornate Romanesque
churches in northern Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The interior of San Zeno is richly decorated and has a large
rose window representing the Wheel of Fortune. The shape of the
window is artfully echoed in the halo of the Virgin Mary in the
superb 15th-century altarpiece by Mantegna.
</P>
<P>
   The bronze panels on the doors of the basilica's west entrance,
some dating from the 11th century, illustrate Bible stories and
incidents in the life of St. Zeno with crudely executed but
powerful images.
</P>
<P>
   The saint's tomb is in a vaulted crypt beneath the basilica.
However, Zeno's presence seems strongest in a side chapel that
contains a charming 14th-century wooden statue of him. Grinning
broadly, the old bishop is benevolence personified.
</P>
<P>
   In the 13th and 14th centuries, the powerful Scaligero family
ruled Verona from Castelvecchio, a sprawling brick fortress on the
banks of the Adige. An impressive castle with well-preserved
towers, turrets, ramparts, and moats, Castelvecchio is now the
town's principal art museum.
</P>
<P>
   The museum galleries are arranged in such a way as to also show
the highlights of the castle, which has sweeping views over the
town and river. The large art collection includes paintings by
Bellini, Veronese, and Tintoretto. Grouped in one gallery are a
number of beautiful madonnas by gifted but anonymous medieval
craftsmen. As you might expect in a castle, there is a display of
swords and armor, most dating from the high Renaissance and often
beautifully ornamented.
</P>
<P>
   Linked to the castle is Ponte Scaligero, a medieval bridge over
the Adige. Built of brick in the same fortress style as
Castelvecchio, it too has ramparts, turrets, and arrow slits. But
the old bridge is pretty and peaceful these days, its defensive
nooks and crannies popular trysting places for real-life Romeos and
Juliets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
