<HEADLINE>
ITALY REAWAKENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Italy is going to be one hot spot this year.
</P>
<P>
   For Christians, this is a Jubilee Year, celebrating the 2,000th
anniversary of the birth of Jesus, and for Catholics, a Jubilee
Year is especially important. Since the Middle Ages the Catholic
Church has been holding a special Jubilee every 25 years during
which pilgrims seek atonement and spiritual renewal by visiting
holy sites in Rome and elsewhere in Italy. One highlight will be a
World Youth Day observance from Aug. 5-20.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Italy, and especially in Rome, there has been a
reawakening in the country with the renovation, refurbishment, and
reopening of museums, historic churches, and sites. Rome alone has
refurbished more than 700 monuments, works of art, and sites.
</P>
<P>
   For tourists in general, travel agents are reporting that
Tuscany is fast replacing Provence as the chic getaway. The January
issue of Andrew Harper's Hideaway Report is devoted to Florence and
Tuscany. Harper reports the best months to visit for both weather
and to avoid the crowds are May and October. (For subscription
information, call 800-235-9622 or visit www.hideawayreport.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Tom Souza of Central Holidays reports their bookings have been
up 15 to 20 percent so far this year, and the heaviest booking
season is yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   The company says it is offering its most comprehensive tour
program ever for Italy and is including new programs for Tuscany
with optional house or villa rentals. Travel agents have details or
call 800-935-5000.
</P>
<P>
   Alitalia has also produced a ``Complete Vacation Catalog'' about
Italy. For a copy, call 888-340-8562.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly two of the more enjoyable things about Italy are its
food and wine. The Parker Co. in Lynn not only specializes in villa
rentals, but also has food and wine tours throughout Italy. The
company's Italian cooking school tours begin at $2,650 a person and
include air fare from Boston, hotels, classes, most meals, and
more. For information, call 800-280-2811 or visit
www.theparkercompany.com.
</P>
<P>
   For travelers planning a trip to Italy, there are a number of
Web sites. Among them: the Italian National Tourist Board Jubilee
site at www.piuitalia2000.it; the Italian National Tourist Board
official site at www.enit.it; the Vatican Site at www.vatican.va;
the Pilgrims organization in Rome at www.
</P>
<P>
   operaromanapellegrinaggi.it; a general site on the Jubilee at
www.giubileoroma.com; and a site on religious events at
www.ecclesia2000.com/
</P>
<P>
   appuntamentigiubileo.
</P>
<P>
   Another handy item for planning a trip is a copy of ``Hello
Italy! Italian Hotels $50-$99 A Night For Two.'' The book is $18.95
and is available in stores or from the publisher, Wilson
Publishing; call 323-939-0821 or, on the Web, visit
www.HelloEurope.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Shroud on view &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While every church in Italy is expected to hold special events,
the Cathedral of Turin will gain a lot of attention. From Aug. 26
to Oct. 26 it will display the Holy Shroud of Turin, a cloth said
to have been used to wrap Jesus' body after the crucifixion. While
the shroud's authenticity has been questioned, believers say it
bears the imprint of Jesus' body. The shroud is in fragments and
has been kept hidden for decades at a time. It was on display in
1978 and again for a few weeks in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The free exhibition will be open daily, although some times will
be reserved for the sick and disabled.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Food festival &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Homestead Resort in Hot Springs, Va., will hold its sixth
Annual Food &AMP; Wine Spectacular April 6-8. It will feature culinary
delights prepared by some of Virginia's best chefs and American,
New Zealand, and Australian wines from 41 wineries. For
information, call 800-838-1766.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Free night &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For travelers 55 and older, visiting family or friends on Easter
just got more affordable. Candlewood Suites Senior Value Program is
offering guests 55 and older Easter night free when they pay for a
night before or after the holiday. The program also applies to
other holidays such as Mother's Day, Father's Day, Memorial Day,
Independence Day, Labor Day, Thanksgiving, Christmas, and New
Year's Day. And the company says a first-time stay _ anytime _
counts as yet another ``holiday.'' For information, call
888-CANDLEWOOD.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Indy 500 tickets &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guaranteed seats for this year's Indy 500 are featured on a
four-day package from Spectacular Sport Specials. The package is
$1,474 a person double occupancy and includes accommodations,
tickets for the May 28 race, a ticket for the drivers' meeting, a
meal, tours, and more. For information, call 800-451-5772.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell exhibit &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Norman Rockwell Museum in Stockbridge, Mass., is presenting
``In Rockwell We Trust,'' an exhibit that explores the role
Rockwell played in American advertising as a celebrity spokesman
for a wide assortment of products.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit continues through Aug. 27. For information, call
413-298-4100, ext. 220.
</P>
