<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNA-TESTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DNA TESTING: GOOD OR BAD FOR JUSTICE? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Eyewitnesses may be uncertain. Lawyers may
bungle. Cops may err. But a $10,000 Zeiss microscope is as close to
infallible as you can get.
</P>
<P>
   Besides a world of hurt, criminals often leave behind traces of
themselves _ blood, hair and semen _ that can be used to convict
them or to clear others falsely accused of their misdeeds. DNA
testing is the key that can unlock the door to the truth in many of
the toughest cases before our courts.
</P>
<P>
   With the technology available in many cases to prove or disprove
guilt scientifically, the questions left to politicians, law
enforcement authorities and legal scholars are these:
</P>
<P>
   When do we set aside what our very fallible eyes and ears tell
us and rely on the reports of technicians? When is it in the
interests of justice to shift the responsibility for passing
judgment from ourselves to laboratory equipment?
</P>
<P>
   Barry Scheck, one of the famed crew of attorneys who persuaded a
jury that O.J. Simpson was innocent, says the time to make a
wholesale move to DNA testing is now.
</P>
<P>
   Scheck's Innocence Project at the Cardozo Law School in New York
has played a prominent role in the freeing of more than 60
prisoners in the United States on grounds of actual innocence.
</P>
<P>
   With Peter Neufeld and Jim Dwyer, Scheck is the author of a book
that makes a case for readily available post-conviction DNA
testing, ``Actual Innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   An astonishing compendium of stories about miscarriages of
justice, the book looks into the causes and effects of defects in a
criminal justice system that, as of last summer, had sent at least
64 people to prison and death row for crimes committed by others.
</P>
<P>
   One was Ron Williamson, who played baseball in the minor league
organizations of both the Oakland A's and the New York Yankees.
Williamson was sentenced to death for a 1982 rape and murder. Last
April, he was freed by DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are thousands of people across the country who could
prove their innocence with DNA testing,'' Scheck said.
</P>
<P>
   Only two states require post-conviction DNA testing, Illinois
and New York. That will soon change. Bills are now before
legislators in many other states, including California, where a
measure by state Sen. John Burton, a San Francisco Democrat, is to
go to the Senate Public Safety Committee on April 11. The bill
would grant convicts the right to DNA testing provided they
demonstrate that important new evidence has been found.
</P>
<P>
   The tests are expensive _ up to $9,000 in complex cases _ but
the Burton bill would require courts to pay for testing in the
cases of indigent convicts.
</P>
<P>
   In the Alameda County District Attorney's Office, one of the
region's most experienced and respected prosecutors, Rockne Harmon,
has been handling his office's reconsideration of some of its
oldest unsolved cases.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon, part of the prosecution team in the O.J. case, relies on
DNA testing heavily, but his agenda is very different from
Scheck's. He's trying to put people in jail. In the last 18 months,
Alameda County has reopened more than a dozen unsolved cases going
back an average of 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon doesn't think DNA testing is a blanket answer to
questions of guilt or innocence. Biological testing is of limited
use, he said, because it can't ``touch the whole body of
evidence.'' It will never explain away compelling conventional
evidence, such as the presence of the rape suspect's wallet in the
victim's car.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon also contends that while the tool is basically a good
one, its proponents really want DNA testing to help further a
hidden agenda: undermining the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   That view is shared by Ed Blake, a forensic scientist who has
consulted on perhaps more DNA cases than anyone in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Blake, of Richmond, Calif., thinks a post-conviction DNA testing
law like the one Burton is carrying ``is probably the most
important criminal justice legislation in 30 or 40 years.''
</P>
<P>
   His fear _ a major one _ is that such legislation will be
misused if not crafted carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't say in a law that anyone convicted has an open book
for claiming this kind of work has to be done,'' Blake said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the public gets the perception the defense attorneys are
abusing the process, the public will demand laws to prevent the
whole process from happening at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake called Burton's bill ``very reasonable,'' except for its
failure to say what constituted ``reasonable notice'' when a DNA
challenge was to be mounted. Defense attorneys will exploit that,
he predicted, by demanding DNA tests shortly before scheduled
executions, merely to delay them.
</P>
<P>
   Hastings Law School professor Rory Little, a former federal
prosecutor and onetime top assistant to U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno, also qualified his praise of the bill by pointing out that it
was silent on another important question: What happens next if the
DNA testing looks like it might exonerate the defendant _ and in
what court does it occur?
</P>
<P>
   Charles Weisselberg, a law professor at the University of
California at Berkeley, argued that the Burton bill should include
a provision designed to preserve evidence to make it available for
future DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   As for the alleged hidden agenda of some testing proponents,
Stanford Law School professor Robert Weisberg pleaded guilty. DNA
testing ``certainly is'' a collateral attack on the death penalty,
he acknowledged, but one worth making.
</P>
<P>
   ``The twist on this,'' he said, ``is that in the long term it
might re-enforce the popularity of the death penalty, because it
might eliminate the problem of factually innocent people being
executed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
