u f BC-TECHNO-ROUND-BOS &LR;      04-04 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-ROUND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTOGRAPHY IN THE ROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the cooler things to happen to photography in the digital
age has been the emergence of 360-degree pictures. They create a
``you are there'' experience for viewers, who use their computer
mouse to control what part of a panorama they see.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year or so, the technology has quickly found a host
of uses, such as remote tours of homes for sale and interactive
entertainment. You can use your computer to pick which room or part
of an event or scene you want to see and zoom in as if you were
standing there watching with your own eyes.
</P>
<P>
   While the pictures can be incredibly fun to look at, they can
also be a bear to make, requiring expensive equipment and complex
efforts to stitch together two or more pictures into a continuous
image.
</P>
<P>
   A firm that just moved its headquarters from Manhattan to
Westborough, Mass., however, is starting to roll out what it
promotes as a fast, cheap, one-click way to create ``interactive
images'' _ and a way to move quickly into real-time 360-degree
video for people who have powerful enough Net connections.
</P>
<P>
   The company, Cyclovision Technologies Inc., has just renamed
itself Remote Reality. It makes extensive use of technology
developed at Columbia University's computer science labs, including
seven patented or patent-pending inventions.
</P>
<P>
   To understand how its system works, try to imagine you are
looking up the stem of a martini glass to the reflections on the
underside of the cup. If you could counter-distort and greatly
magnify the images, you would have a way of looking at almost the
entire room.
</P>
<P>
   What Remote Reality now sells is a $500 lens that does just
that. The device has a convex mirror, about the size of a hamburger
bun, mounted by a pen-size stem to the front of the lens. It fits
most digital cameras, including Agfa, Nikon, and Olympus models.
You also have to buy a $300-a-year software license for converting
the images into a usable form.
</P>
<P>
   To take pictures, instead of looking through the camera and
aiming at a point in front of you, you aim the lens up at the
ceiling or sky to take in the whole scene.
</P>
<P>
   Through a fairly simple software process, pictures can be edited
and posted on the Web within minutes. And they can be downloaded in
a second or two with a broadband-speed connection. It might take up
to a minute, however, for a dial-up modem, because an individual
image may easily contain 2 megabits of data.
</P>
<P>
   Once the image is on your computer, you have everything you need
to see and rotate it because Remote Reality runs on so-called Java
applets rather than a special plug-in program you have to download
from a Web page.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, the company plans field tests of a streaming video
product it expects to become available this fall. That will open
the door for people who have broadband-speed Net connections to
watch sports events, concerts, or street scenes in interesting
places as if they were standing there.
</P>
<P>
   The video system uses digital compression that can make images a
little herky-jerky. Without using billions of pixels, there is only
so far you can zoom in before the picture starts looking like bad
satellite surveillance of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, you could easily spend $25,000 on digital
cameras and associated software to create 360-degree images. You
could also take years off your life enduring the frustration of
making usable pictures. Both the price and complexity have since
plunged, though possibly not far enough for the average amateur
photographer.
</P>
<P>
   A leader in the field to date has been Silicon Valley-based
Interactive Pictures Corp. or Ipix, whose system requires taking
two images with a 180-degree fisheye lens to create one panorama.
It can cost as little as $330 if you already have a digital camera.
</P>
<P>
   However, you have to pay Ipix a fee for every image you make,
like buying Polaroid film _ about $1.25 a pop for the consumer
product and a lot more for professional systems. If the light
levels in the two images are starkly different _ a picture at
Fenway Park, for instance, showing the sun-dappled field and the
gloomy grandstand _ getting the images to synch up can be vexing.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have paid Remote Reality your annual software licensing
fee (which includes upgrades), you can take all of the images you
want, including plenty of bad practice shots to get the hang of it.
</P>
<P>
   Remote Reality's president, Jeb S. Hurley, is so convinced
people will love the product that he left a job running a $1
billion division of Eastman Kodak to take over the 14-person
company last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``You turn photography into an experience, as opposed to a mere
presentation of images,'' Hurley said. ``I think Web advertisers
are going to love this because they are really thirsty for
something more compelling than click-through banner ads.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Hurley's demonstrations shows the inside of a Lexus. You
get all the same visual information you could get from looking at
five or six sequential pictures of the dashboard, passenger seat,
rear window, and driver's seat.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to explain without seeing it yourself, but trust your
reporter: When you sit in front of the computer scrolling around
the inside of the car in a continuous loop, you can really imagine
you are sitting on the gearshift.
</P>
<P>
   The potential applications for 360-degree photography and
videography are huge, going beyond entertainment and advertising to
include videoconferencing, military surveillance, one-camera video
security systems for office lobbies, and interactive photographs
for Web news sites that put you in the journalist's shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Once millions of people finally have broadband-speed Net access,
it is easy to imagine that something as common as sending a
relative a picture of your new home will take on a totally
different meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of sending her some snapshots of the porch and the
kitchen and the kids' room, you would zap her a file that would
make her feel that she was standing there with you. As Hurley puts
it, with 360-degree pictures, ``You begin to change the very way
you think about an image.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Peter J. Howe is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached by
e-mail at howe(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
