<HEADLINE>
HOW LOW WILL TECH STOCKS GO? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How will you know when technology stocks hit bottom?
</P>
<P>
   That was the question on investors' minds Monday as they watched
the Nasdaq plunge into the abyss. The technology-heavy index lost
350 points, or 7.6 percent of its value, the most brutal day yet in
a correction that has been underway for the past week.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's selloff was prompted by the breakdown of the
government's talks with Microsoft Corp., which like all trigger
events, was more an excuse than a reason for the carnage that
followed.
</P>
<P>
   With their lofty valuations, tech stocks were vulnerable to a
major correction. The only issue was when, not if.
</P>
<P>
   Predicting where a new floor will be established is never an
easy task, especially in times of such violent mood swings. But
with traditional stocks, there are at least some yardsticks you can
use to measure.
</P>
<P>
   Take a stock like FleetBoston Financial Corp. A few weeks ago we
argued that it was undervalued because it had fallen to a level
that struck us as a bargain price. Ours was not a brilliant call.
We looked at the bank's earnings, projections for future earnings,
and the multiple of earnings the stock was selling for _ about 8 _
and concluded that barring a collapse in the economy, Fleet had to
be worth more than the $27 per share it then commanded.
</P>
<P>
   Others made the same judgment and Fleet has since rebounded to
$40.
</P>
<P>
   But when you try to bring that same kind of analysis to the
newest of the new economy stocks, you hit an obvious problem: There
is very little measure. ``A lot of these stocks don't have much of
a foundation,'' said Jim Weiss, chief of equities at State Street
Research.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the past year's hottest stocks were companies with no
earnings and very modest sales. They rose on expectations and
hopes. When investors were optimistic that was more than enough. In
the current rout, expectations and hopes aren't much to fall back
on.
</P>
<P>
   Consider another local stock, Navisite. The Andover company
specializes in hosting, a form of computer outsourcing. A brand-new
company, Navisite had $9 million in sales in its most recent
quarter to go along with losses of $11 million.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, those numbers were enough to drive Navisite's
stock to $327 per share and a market value of about $8 billion.
Monday Navisite closed at $95, a decline _ which we can measure _
of 70 percent from the top.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai Technologies, another high-flier, reached a peak of $327
per share at the end of last year. The Cambridge Internet company
had sales of $2.7 million and losses of $29 million in its most
recent quarter. Monday Akamai closed at $119, a decline from the
peak of 63 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The magnitude of speculation in these stocks was pervasive,''
said Ned Riley, chief investment strategist for State Street Global
Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger, more established tech stocks have not been spared in
this downturn. But profitable firms like EMC Corp. and Cisco
Systems have held up much better than their start-up counterparts.
In tough times, it seems, earnings actually do matter.
</P>
<P>
   Tech fans point out that nothing fundamental has changed between
this week and last week. Technology still has a bright future, they
say, and investors will get a glimpse of that future in the next
few weeks as corporations report their first-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think those earnings will be very good,'' said Alan
Lowenstein, manager of the John Hancock Technology Fund. Lowenstein
is also hopeful that the Nasdaq's troubles may slow down the pace
of initial public offerings. With less money going into brand-new
companies, Lowenstein reasons, existing tech stocks may reap some
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two years, anyone who bet that fallen technology
stocks would stay down has lost his shirt and his money. Investors
have used the periodic tech corrections to load up on more
technology stocks. Maybe they will do that again this time.
</P>
<P>
   But if they don't, and they are forced to grope around in search
of a bottom, they may wish they had some more reliable markers to
rely on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
