<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-B2B-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOW THE CROWD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Feeling left out of the business-to-business bonanza?
</P>
<P>
   Well, just wave a magic wand and call yourself a B2B company!
</P>
<P>
   Lately, everyone from ancient software firms to ailing Web
stores has been making the leap to business-to-business e-commerce.
Never mind that few so-called B2B firms do much Internet business.
And some have yet to sign on customers and investors.
</P>
<P>
   If you have been looking for a narrow definition of B2B, the
Net's latest rage, you won't find it. But here's a good starting
point. It's any business that sells to other businesses online or
helps them sell on the Web or . . .
</P>
<P>
   You get the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Blame investors for the B2B hype. After abandoning unprofitable
and free-spending virtual retailers, they raced toward seemingly
sexier ventures such as Chemdex Corp., which sells laboratory
supplies to researchers.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Companies that weren't B2B scrambled to become part
of the B2B trend. Last month, Lands' End, a catalog and online
retailer, raised its B2B banner, announcing plans to supply
companies with branded apparel and luggage through its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Lands' End in B2B land are a host of cash-hungry virtual
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Send.com, a California software retailer that couldn't make a
profit selling to regular shoppers, is now targeting businesses.
And last week, MotherNature.com, an online vitamin retailer that
has been trimming costs, said it would pursue a B2B strategy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How do you keep a curious employee from nosing through the
corporate network and into his company's salary database? And how
do you give a preferred client a larger helping of Internet options
than a regular customer?
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, corporations are turning to software firms such as
Marlborough-based Gradient Technologies Inc. to help them set
different levels of network access for employees, vendors, and
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We determine who (the users) are, and give them appropriate
information'' said Tracy Mansolillo, a Gradient spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gradient's NetCrusader technology was named ``The
Best of Security Solutions'' at the Internet Commerce Expo in
Boston. The company's customers include Citibank, Kaiser
Permanente, and Penn State University.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1989, closely held Gradient also has been helping its
corporate customers track people who click into their Web sites.
The function has become more important as hackers continue to break
into corporate sites, swiping valuable information and embarrassing
executives.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As demand for Web site builders skyrockets, many of their
corporate customers are complaining about long delays, huge fees,
and arrogant consultants, a new survey has found.
</P>
<P>
   Executives told Forrester Research that some service providers
refused smaller projects, put off work, jumped ship, and demanded
equity in their firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``They offered me either more than I wanted or not exactly what
I wanted,'' an executive with a publishing company told Forrester.
``They have an attitute that I should be grateful to buy their
services.''
</P>
<P>
   Attracting a large share of the gripes were hot developers of
integrated software systems, according to the survey of 50
executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clients chase integrators the way teenagers chase rock
stars,'' explained Christine Ferrusi Ross, a Forrester analyst.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The .nu guys on the domain block are beginning to rattle their
more established .com colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   The first spat involves Expedia.com, a big online travel service
spun off last year by Microsoft Corp., and cybersquatter
Expedia.nu.
</P>
<P>
   Expedia Inc., which owns the trademark for the word Expedia, has
challenged the Swedish company that registered the domain name
Expedia.nu. The fight will be arbitrated by the World Intellectual
Property Association, part of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the skirmish is .NU Domain Ltd., which has been handing
out domain names such as Microsoft.nu, Harvard.nu, and Amazon.nu to
anyone with a few bucks.
</P>
<P>
   At the company's Web site, www.nunames.com, users can buy new
domain names for less than $100 a pop. Still available: Gillette.nu
and Procterandgamble.nu.
</P>
<P>
   Just remember that the UN is watching.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
