<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6732 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TOUGH-CITY-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     04-04 1460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUGH-CITY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... me names.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yet not one of more than 20 past and present athletes and
executives interviewed would trade his Boston experience. The
demands may be greater, but they go with the territory. And it
beats the alternative. An adoring public may be the ideal, but a
caring public is better than an ignoring public.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Boston, New York, Philadelphia, and Montreal,'' said
Rangers center Tim Taylor, a former Bruin and Detroit Red Wing,
``you'd better be prepared to know that when things don't go well,
you're going to have to deal with the pressure. And when things go
well, there's nothing like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Grogan said, ``You succeed here and there's a lot of perks.
Pedro Martinez owns this town because he's the best. I don't think
it would be the same way if he were in Kansas City or Minnesota or
Montreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Martinez's Red Sox predecessor, Yankee starter Roger
Clemens, who endured a relationship of extremes with Boston fans
before he bolted to Toronto, has no complaints _ or claims none.
``I wouldn't say it was difficult, because I enjoyed playing in
that environment,'' he said. ``They're caring fans and they come
out and support you.''
</P>
<P>
   Or savage you. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Our little town &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun, a Bay Stater born and bred who still considers himself
a Bostonian 15 years after relocating to Storrs, Conn., believes
size matters in a sociological sense. ``When I call Boston `the old
town,' '' he said, ``I mean that because it is a town. It has that
intimacy.''
</P>
<P>
   The sports definition of ``intimacy'' can be translated as
``lack of alternatives for abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``New York can be (harsh), but it's a huge market,'' said
Gorman. ``There are 8 million other things to do. But here
everything seems to get regurgitated more than anyplace else.
Everybody has an opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   And isn't shy about changing it without warning. ``There were
many games where I was almost booed out of the stadium,'' said
Grogan. ``Then I did something at the end, we won, and suddenly, I
was the hero.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a microcosm of his 16-year career, during which Grogan
experienced the cycle of rejection, rebirth, and redemption.
``There were a couple of times I thought about bailing out,'' he
said. ``But I never asked for a trade. I liked the city, so I stuck
with it and wound up on their good side again.''
</P>
<P>
   That's more than can be said for some past minority athletes.
</P>
<P>
   During the Celtics' glory days of the 1950s and '60s, Bill
Russell was a hero who led them to an unparalleled 11 NBA
championships in 13 years. Off the court, his home was vandalized
when he settled in suburban Reading. After his retirement, Russell
maintained an icy distance from the city and only recently has
there been a rapprochement.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Hall of Famer-to-be Kirby Puckett rejected a more
lucrative free agent offer from Boston and stayed in Minnesota.
While Puckett's agent, Ron Shapiro, maintained that his client
``really liked Boston,'' there were some undercurrents of social
tension in the outfielder's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took my wife along to help figure out what we wanted,'' said
Puckett then. ``I know that when Tonya goes to the Metrodome, she
is going to be safe. That's not true at other ballparks.''
</P>
<P>
   The scrutiny also was uncomfortable. ``I felt like a fugitive,''
said Puckett. ``If I saw someone coming, I had a feeling someone
was going to call something in on me.''
</P>
<P>
   But past and present Red Sox coach Tommy Harper, ostracized in
1984 when he confirmed that the team implicitly condoned the
segregationist spring training policies of the Winter Haven (Fla.)
Elks Club _ which invited only white members of the team to
socialize _ was pleased by the melting pot he saw upon his return
to camp this year in Fort Myers, Fla. ``This is like night and
day,'' said Harper. ``This is a different atmosphere altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the perception dies hard. Al Skinner experiences it as he
tries to rebuild the Boston College basketball program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city of Boston has had its share of problems as far as
minority students are concerned,'' he said last month. ``We
recognize the evolution the city has made. But that still lingers.
Those are the things you deal with. It's not just BC. But the city
of Boston has to take some responsibility for what exists.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
The sky is falling &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   M.L. Carr, the former Celtics player and coach and current
executive, remembers a ragged stretch on the court back in 1981.
``They let us know we weren't performing at the level we should
be,'' he said. The Celtics at the time were in the midst of the NBA
Finals against the Houston Rockets, a series they went on to win in
six games for the franchise's 14th world championship.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Cashman, a winger on the Big, Bad Bruins who's now an
assistant coach in Philadelphia, assumed that Stanley Cup crowns in
1970 and '72 would sate the masses. Quite the contrary. ``After two
Cups,'' he said, ``it was almost automatic that we were expected to
win again. It was a lot tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   And last season, after the Patriots roared to a 6-2 start that
put them in prime playoff position, there was a sense of doom about
the upcoming game against the Jets. Sure enough, in a
self-fulfilling prophecy, they lost that game, staggered to an
also-ran 8-8 finish, and cost coach Pete Carroll his job.
</P>
<P>
   And that's how Boston reacts when things are going well.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the dismal showings of the Bruins and Celtics, they
really have something to harp on. But the targets seem to accept it
as due punishment, Pitino's scolding notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're allowed to boo,'' said Bruins coach Pat Burns, who
previously coached in the hockey hotbeds of Toronto and Montreal.
``They pay $80 or $90 and the players don't (perform), they're
allowed to boo.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics' fabled tradition doesn't do them any favors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of history,'' said forward Eric Williams. ``All
that winning. The people still remember. The kids grow up with
that. They're spoiled from all the banners. Is it fair? Life's not
fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, star forward _ and frequent villain _ Antoine Walker
rates Boston ``a great basketball town. When you're the top guy and
the team isn't doing as well as people thought it would, there's
going to be finger-pointing. I like that kind of pressure. That's
good pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   From afar, former Bruins center Adam Oates of the Washington
Capitals considers the issue nonsense. ``Pitino was out of line as
far as I'm concerned,'' he said. ``Look at the product. It sucks,
and it's because of him. . . . Professional athletes in Boston are
spoiled. A lot of guys just aren't honest with themselves.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
You talk too much &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maybe self-delusion is a form of self-defense. There's nowhere
to hide in a city with a merciless media contingent that seemingly
grows by the minute with the advent of talk radio and the flood of
Web sites to supplement the two metropolitan and sundry suburban
newspapers, plus the electronic ganglia of television and
microphone cords.
</P>
<P>
   Butch Hobson's first game as Red Sox manager was against the
Yankees in 1992. Afterward, his office was overflowing with 100
journalists. After the media exodus, Gorman dropped by and asked,
``What did you think?''
</P>
<P>
   Hobson responded with near dread, ``Is it like this every
night?''
</P>
<P>
   Gorman replied, ``It's not quite that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   But almost. That's why Gorman classifies this media coverage as
``the most intense of any city in the country. The talk shows are
probably more (influential) than any other place than New York.
There's tremendous coverage. Sometimes it's unfair, but you have to
be willing to accept it as part of being in this market. I didn't
mind it as long as it didn't get too personal.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Patriots general manager Patrick Sullivan believes it
did, that some reporters had an inexplicable vendetta against his
father, late team founder Billy Sullivan. ``What differentiates it
here,'' said Sullivan, ``is that the media isn't content to report
the story, but wants to be part of it.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
For the record &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the end, what matters is the bottom line; everything else is
peripheral.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think every city's tough,'' said Walker. ``Everything is
based on wins and losses.''
</P>
<P>
   `Twas ever thus, as Harry Sinden, the former Bruins coach and
longtime general manager, can testify. ``Pitino is not wrong,'' he
said, ``but it has to do with the team's performance. I wouldn't
say (the negativity) is any worse here. I just don't see a heck of
a lot of difference here than anyplace else.''
</P>
<P>
   For some Bostonians, that may be the real insult. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Shira Springer, Nick Cafardo, Gordon Edes, and Nancy
Marrapese-Burrell of the Globe staff contributed to this report. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
