<HEADLINE>
SOME KNOCKOUT COMPETITION EXPECTED THIS WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The European Champions League graduates to the knockout phase
this week, recalling the origins of the competition. The event has
become an ambiguous conglomeration of summer qualifying rounds and
round-robin group play, leading to the quarterfinals, which revert
to good old home-and-home elimination.
</P>
<P>
   And the Real Madrid-Manchester United match should be a classic.
Manchester United is the world's most glamorous and richest club,
but Real Madrid is probably the most popular club in history. Real
made its reputation by opening its doors to the great Hungarian
dissident players in the 1950s and, under the on-field direction of
Argentine Alfredo Di Stefano, won the first five European Champions
Cup titles.
</P>
<P>
   Real Madrid also symbolized Franco-style fascism, though this
association has been filled with contradictions, not the least of
which is the monarchical implications of the name ``Real'' (Royal).
But the club has long embraced the values of capitalism, and is
worth more than nearly all other clubs.
</P>
<P>
   But sporting clubs now are becoming transparent enough to be
assigned values. Manchester United is considered the richest,
recently being assessed at $1.66 billion _ a significant increase
on the $1.06 billion offered by Rupert Murdoch's media conglomerate
last year. The club last week announced pre-tax profits of $19.5
million for the past six months, which should increase the yearly
take to $44.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Other European clubs are following the lead of English clubs and
going public.
</P>
<P>
   And it is more than coincidental that SS Lazio is among
Manchester United's challengers, since the Rome club became the
first Italian team to be quoted. Lazio president Sergio Cragnotti
has revived a team that has only one Serie A title. Now, Lazio is
in contention for three championships _ Serie A, the Coppa Italia,
and the European Champions Cup, and coach Sven-Goran Eriksson told
the Swedish daily Expressen ``we have everything to take all
three.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, which meets Valencia Wednesday, is coming off a 1-0
victory over Juventus, which rejuvenated the Serie A ``scudetto''
race. A glancing header by Diego ``El Cholo'' Simeone provided the
difference as Lazio pulled within 3 points of Juve with six weeks
left in the season. When the Milan Borsa opened Monday, Lazio's
stock value had increased by 10.86 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, though, is that an immense amount of capital is
needed to field teams deep enough to withstand the crowded
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Three Spanish teams have advanced to the final eight of the
European competition. Barcelona, which meets Chelsea Wednesday, is
making a run at the Primera Liga title after crushing Valencia,
3-0, on goals by Dutchmen Patrick Kluivert (two) and Winston Bogard
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish soccer appears to be adjusting to modern times better
than some of its more populous neighbors. The Liga has absorbed an
enormous influx of foreign players, maintained its reputation for
wide-open offensive play, and continues to produce young talent.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Spain defeated Italy, 2-0, for the first time in 22
years. And, the Spain Under-23 team also stopped the Italians, 3-0.
Young players such as Valencia midfielder Gerard could be heading
to Serie A, but there appear to be plenty of replacements.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Return of Hurtado
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution earned a point in a 2-2 tie at Los Angeles, but
might have fared even better had Eduardo Hurtado arrived. Hurtado
is expected to return from Ecuador this week after his family
experienced visa problems. Alex Aguinaga and Agustin Delgado, his
teammates with Ecuador's national team, had a smooth return after a
2-0 win over Venezuela in Quito Wednesday. They rejoined their club
team in Mexico City and helped Necaxa take a 4-0 victory over
Atlante. Delgado, who appears to be a young version of Hurtado,
scored three goals . . . Bruno Schneider, the leading scorer in
Eastern Massachusetts high school soccer the last three years,
suffered a leg injury during a tryout last week with Blackburn
Rovers. Schneider, 17, who has American and European citizenship,
is scheduled to return to England for training this month . . .
Former Revolution midfielder Jair has been called to the Cape
Verdean national team for a World Cup qualifier against Algeria
Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
