<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GODOLPHIN IS A STABLE OUTFIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is only a matter of time before Godolphin Racing Inc., the
thoroughbred stable of Sheik Maktoum al Maktoum and Sheik Mohammed
al Maktoum, becomes a major force in American racing.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of the horses owned by the ruling family of
Dubai, which includes Sheik Hamdan al Maktoum, who owns the
Shadwell Estate Co. Ltd. breeding operation and also races under
his own name, and a fourth brother, Marwan, was sensational at the
Dubai World Cup March 27. Granted, Dubai World Cup Day amounts to a
home game for the sheiks, but they still won five of the six races
on the $11.75 million card, and had several other runners hit the
board.
</P>
<P>
   Sheik Maktoum, the ruler of Dubai; Sheik Hamdan, the minister of
finance, Sheik Mohammed, the minister of defense, and Sheik Marwan,
the youngest of the brothers, are the four sons of the late ruler,
Sheik Rashid bin Said al Maktoum. It was the idea of Sheik
Mohammed, a horseman who specialized in Arabians, to take
thoroughbreds from England, train them in Dubai, and return them to
England to race. Godolphin, which was established in 1994, quickly
outgrew England, became international, and Mohammed began the Dubai
World Cup in 1996. Money is not a problem in oil-rich Dubai, a
member of the United Arab Emirates, and Sheik Mohammed is
determined that his horses make an inpact in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The results of Dubai World Cup Day offer an example of how
powerful Godolphin is right now. Dubai Millennium captured the $6
million World Cup, the world's richest race, by 6 lengths over
Behrens, the best America had to offer. Sheik Mohammed was so
confident in the ability of the 4-year-old Dubai Millennium that he
changed his name from Yaazer when he was age 2 because the sheik
felt confident he would win the first World Cup of the new
millennium. A son of Seeking the Gold, Dubai Millennium has won
eight of nine career starts, earned $4.2 million, and is considered
the best horse in training. The remainder of his campaign will be
directed toward the $4 million Breeders' Cup Classic, at Churchill
Downs Nov. 4.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Godolphin colorbearers Rhythm Band ($2 million Duty
Free at 9 furlongs on turf); Fantastic Light ($2 million Sheema
Classic at 12 furlongs on turf), and China Visit ($500,000 United
Arab Emirates Derby at 9 furlongs on the dirt), won on Dubai World
Cup Day. Plus, Conflict, owned by Marwan al Maktoum, won the
$250,000 Godolphin Mile. Only in the $1 million Golden Shaheen, a
6-furlong dash, did a shipper break through, as Big Jag, arguably
the best of the American sprinters, scored by 4 lengths. Even then,
Godolphin's Bertolini was second.
</P>
<P>
   The strength of Godolphin has been steadily building. Among the
best horses the stable has raced in the past are Lammtarra, who won
the Epsom Derby, King George the VI, and Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe
in 1995, the first to accomplish that triple since the legendary
Mill Reef in 1971; Swain, second in the World Cup and third in the
Breeders' Cup in 1998; Daylami, who won last year's Breeder's Cup
Turf; and Almutawakel, who won last year's World Cup. However, the
outfit never has had the depth it now enjoys.
</P>
<P>
   Godolphin took its first shot at the Kentucky Derby last year.
The stable purchased Worldly Manner, who was trained by Bob Baffert
and owned by John and Betty Mabee, for $5 million after he won the
Del Mar Futurity. Managed by Simon Crisford, the spokesman for
Godolphin, and trained by Saeed bin Suroor, the hands-on trainer,
Worldy Manner was prepared for the Rose Run in Dubai. He ran a
great mile in the Derby, looming a threat in Godolphin's bright
blue colors as the field turned for home, but he ran out of gas and
faded to fifth.
</P>
<P>
   This year Godolphin intends to send China Visit, and, perhaps,
Chief Seattle, who was purchased after he ran second in both the
Champagne and the Breeders' Cup, to Louisville to contest the first
jewel of the Triple Crown. China Visit, a son of Red Ransom, has
run only twice, breaking his maiden at Deauville last August.
Conventional wisdom says he's too lightly raced to win the Derby.
Frankly, he'd have to be a monster to do so. Chief Seattle, a son
of Seattle Slew, would be a serious player, but he has been
training, without racing, in Dubai since February.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sheik Maktoum (who bred China Visit at Gainsborough Farm in
Kentucky) is keen to go for the Kentucky Derby with his homebred
colt,'' said Crisford. ``We are hoping that Chief Seattle will also
be able to take part.''
</P>
<P>
   Godolphin was criticized last year for not giving Worldly
Manner, who appeared like a horse not ready to run the distance, a
prep race in the United States before the Derby. The stable now has
decided if it doesn't want to prep its horses in America, maybe
American horses will prep in Dubai. After the World Cup, Sheik
Mohammed announced that the purse of next year's UAE Derby will be
raised to $2 million, making it the richest Derby in the world.
``Our aim is to make the meeting better each year,'' said Sheik
Mohammed. ``By increasing the prize money for the Emirates Derby,
we expect to have an even stronger field for the race in 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   While it appears that Godolphin will be up against it at
Churchill Downs on the first Saturday in May, consider this: It is
sending 30 2-year-olds to train at Santa Anita this month. The
juveniles will be trained by Eoin Harty, a protege of Baffert. The
decision to ship to California was based on the quality of
2-year-old racing on the West Coast, and the similarity in climate
between California and Dubai. ``We feel that California is the
right place for Godolphin's training base, and we look forward to
competing in 2-year-old races in California, and throughout North
America,'' said Crisford.
</P>
<P>
   Godolphin is not yet ready to dominate American racing, but the
clock is ticking.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Material from publicity departments at various racetracks was
used to prepare this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
