<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-BADDELEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUGUSTA WELCOMES 19-YEAR-OLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ He is not out of place amid the azaleas, the pine
trees, and the giants of the game. Make no mistake, Aaron Baddeley
fits into the Augusta National landscape like a green blade of
grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the plan,'' said Dale Lynch. ``This is no dream.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan called for a Masters berth in 2000? OK, conceded Lynch,
perhaps they figured that Baddeley would be part of the world golf
stage by age 21. Silly them, because the amateur from Australia
turned 19 three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we looked at the whole picture when he was younger and
he's been doing the mental preparation all along,'' said Lynch, who
has nurtured Baddeley's golf game since the two were introduced six
years ago. And this rare exemption into the Masters, Lynch
emphasized, is another step in the progress. ``No matter what
happens this week, he'll gain from it. This is a long-term plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, however, some valuable dividends have been cashed
in to support their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Age 14. Baddeley received a letter from Jack Nicklaus, who had
heard great things about the youngster. Work hard, wrote Nicklaus,
and stay focused. Later that year, Baddeley won the club
championship at Croydon Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   Age 15. He became the youngest player to make a cut in an
Australasia Tour event.
</P>
<P>
   Age 16. His first competition in the United States was a rousing
success, with runner-up finishes at the World Junior and US Junior
Amateur.
</P>
<P>
   Age 17. A pairing with Gary Player in the Greg Norman
Invitational in Australia. Sort of a publicity stunt, with the
youngest and the oldest. But Player turned up the intensity by
saying of Baddeley: ``The best young player I ever saw was Jack
Nicklaus. I think this young man _ and I don't say this lightly _
has the ability Jack Nicklaus had at the same age.''
</P>
<P>
   Age 18. A friendly round with Phil Mickelson at Greyhawk in
Arizona. The graceful lefthander shoots 71. The kid with the plan
shoots 67 and wins $40.
</P>
<P>
   Age 18. Baddeley became the first amateur in 40 years to win the
Australian Open, and the nation could barely contain itself. ``A
supernova emerged,'' gushed Peter Thomson, a five-time British Open
champ and Australian legend.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, the investment was ready to be cashed in. Wrong.
Baddeley would remain an amateur.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the matter?'' said Player. ``Don't you like money?''
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, money is very important. But not so important
that it disrupts The Plan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was hours after the Australian Open, and the Baddeley family
was celebrating with friends. Craig Spence, a veteran pro on the
Australasia Tour, was part of the festivities, and when he heard
Jo-ann Baddeley say how wild things were, Spence said, ``Wait till
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, the next morning chaos kicked in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aaron had a mobile phone, (father) Ron had a mobile phone, and
there was a hotel phone, too _ all three rang constantly,'' said
the mother.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing of Aaron Baddeley had begun, and the usual
suspects were out in front. Nike. Titleist. IMG. Newspapers.
Magazines. Cable sports shows. The Masters called in its first
exemption to an amateur in 25 years, even though the good news came
at 7:30 in the morning and woke him up.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that wasn't as bad as the call from the folks at The
International, a PGA Tour stop in August. Obviously
misunderstanding the time difference, they called at 2:30 in the
morning. ``They were very apologetic,'' said Ron, ``and we had a
nice talk.'' But they made no commitment, for there are decisions
still to be made.
</P>
<P>
   Such as when to turn pro.
</P>
<P>
   There's no rush, said Ron Baddeley, who recently sold his auto
parts store. He understands what is at stake here, but he is more
father than manager. Financial concerns take a back seat to the
human frailties that can fracture a young man's spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why Aaron didn't turn pro after stunning the golf world
last winter, the father invoked the name of Justin Rose, the
17-year-old Briton who surprised with a fourth-place finish at the
1998 British Open and turned pro the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost weep for him,'' said Ron Baddeley, knowing that Rose
had barely made a nickel as a pro. That explains why the father
pulled his son aside following the first round of the Bay Hill
Invitational three weeks ago. Aaron had played a near-flawless
round _ save for three balls hit into the water at the par-5 sixth
hole. The round of 75 had the young Aussie hanging his head.
</P>
<P>
   Did they talk about his mechanics?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not with me,'' said the father. ``I'm not a golfer. I'm
just telling him to enjoy, to stop putting too much pressure on
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unlike fellow phenoms such as Tiger Woods and Sergio Garcia,
Baddeley did not swing a club while in diapers. He didn't start
playing until he was 12, which raises the question: How did he get
so good, so fast?
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked so hard. I quit cricket and would practice hours
every night,'' said Aaron. ``I asked a club professional, `How do
you get better?' And he told me to `hit balls till your hand
started bleeding.' So I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Too much, thought Ron, so a few years ago the father laid down
the law: There would be no golf on Sundays because the kid needed a
break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys are too fanatical,'' said Lynch, ``but Aaron knows
where that fine line is between working on something and leaving it
alone and trusting it.''
</P>
<P>
   They decided 1999 was a good time to test the game at another
level, so Baddeley returned to the United States. He was second at
the Northeast Amateur, then second in the Western Open in Chicago.
Everything was going to plan, until Baddeley missed making it into
match play at last summer's US Amateur at Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very disappointing,'' said Lynch, ``but it actually
worked out in our favor. We got to work on his swing and what was
wrong with it. We never would have won the Australian Open had we
not worked on the swing.''
</P>
<P>
   The win at the Open came in dramatic fashion, for Baddeley
played in the final group with Colin Montgomerie. The kid shot 69,
Montgomerie 71.While othersled the cheers, perhaps the most telling
quote was delivered by Baddeley himself: ``If Tiger Woods is the
best player in the world, then I've got to be better than Tiger.
Tiger's the benchmark, and I want to be better than the
benchmark.''
</P>
<P>
   Baddeley made the cut at the Honda Classic, missed it at Bay
Hill, and has already played seven practice rounds at Augusta.
Other exemptions will be accepted, but there is no official word on
when he will turn pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I can play with these guys,'' said Baddeley, and
you'd be hard pressed to find anyone to disagree. There is,
however, a test to his maturity that will come when Ron and Jo-ann
return home and let him fend for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time,'' said Jo-ann. ``He is ready.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 1349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
