u s BC-HKC-NDAKOTA-BOS &LR;      04-04 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-NDAKOTA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH DAKOTA GLAD TO BE BACK IN FROZEN FOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saturday night was turning into Sunday morning a little more
than a week ago, and there was University of North Dakota hockey
coach Dean Blais in the middle of a downtown Minneapolis hotel
lobby answering the urging of the Fighting Sioux faithful and
dancing an impromptu jig.
</P>
<P>
   Happy times were here again in the land of the Fighting Sioux.
</P>
<P>
   They were headed back to the Frozen Four _ the NCAA's hockey
championships _ where they will try to repeat the success they had
last time North Dakota made a stand in the finals, without some of
the off-ice wildness that came along with the journey.
</P>
<P>
   North Dakota knocked off Niagara, 4-1, in the West Regional to
punch its ticket to Providence and this week's Frozen Four. North
Dakota plays Maine Thursday at 2 in one semifinal. Boston College
meets St. Lawrence at 7 in the other.
</P>
<P>
   The Fighting Sioux had a bit of a tough time just getting to the
Frozen Four when they won it last time around in 1997. A World War
II fighter plane slid down the runway when its landing gear didn't
work and that closed the airport back home and the Sioux were a day
late getting into Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen it all,'' said Peter Armbrust, then a freshman
forward and now North Dakota's captain.
</P>
<P>
   They had a much rougher time of it shortly upon returning to
Grand Forks. What should have been a high time for celebrating a
6-4 title-game win over Boston University, quickly became a time
for sandbagging and trying to hold off high waters.
</P>
<P>
   The Red River flooded that spring and the university's hockey
players, along with the rest of the community, went to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two or three days after we got back from winning it all, we
started sandbagging all over town.'' Armbrust said. ``You'd drive
around and listen to the radio and they'd tell you where to go.
They called off school and we basically tried to save the town. We
did that for a couple of weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The water won.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said get out of here,'' Armbrust said. ``You packed all
your stuff as quick as you could. Usually it's an hour to Fargo and
it was three hours. The interstate was flooded and it was basically
a line of cars for 70 miles. It was pretty crazy. We got back up
here a month after the flood and the town was totally torn up.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the team's drama has been confined mostly to the
rink. And while the past couple of regular seasons have been super,
the postseasons have been super frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the Fighting Sioux have been among the top-ranked
teams in the nation. Each year they had a bye in the NCAAs, meaning
they got to stay in the West and only had to win one game to get to
the Frozen Four. Each year, they lost the game.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Sioux were 30-7-1 and looking to come to the
FleetCenter and try to become the first team since BU in 1972 to
repeat as national champions. They lost to Michigan in the
regionals in Ann Arbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were up, 3-1, or something and ended up blowing it,''
Armbrust said. ``I don't know how. Everyone was saying it was
basically our year. It was a shoo-in for us. I don't know if we
necessariy believed it. But the games we should have shown up for
and played our best hockey, we didn't. It wasn't that we were
overconfident or thought they were going to hand us the
championship. We didn't play well the night we should have. It was
terrible, looking at the seniors' faces and seeing the dejection.
We had such a great team, we couldn't believe we had lost it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Sioux were even better and were 32-5-2 and
planned a trip to Anaheim, Calif., to get their title back. And
lost to BC, 3-1, in Madison, Wisc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hungry coming into the playoffs, real hungry, and we
thought it would be our year especially after losing the year
before,'' Armbrust said. ``We ran into Boston College and they just
outplayed us. It was the same old thing, not being able to send
those seniors out on a winning note. You kind of question your
game. Maybe you could have done something more. I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the likes of Lee Goren and Armbrust and Jason Ulmer
and Brad DeFauw are the seniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost a lot of guys and we had some stuff to prove, that we
could do the same things that the team last year did,'' said Goren,
who was drafted in the third round by the Bruins in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The past three years, North Dakota won the WCHA regular season
title. The last two years the Sioux then lost in the WCHA playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   This year, they took the other route. They finished second to
Wisconsin in the regular season and then won the league playoffs
and carried momentum into the Regionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to tell the young guys, try to explain to them how
terrible it is to get to the NCAAs and not play your best hockey,''
Armbrust said. ``To have a chance and blow it. We don't have as
talented a team as last year but I think we work harder and we're
having a lot more fun this year. We don't feel the pressure we did
the last two years where everyone expects us to win.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of tough losses at Wisconsin in the middle of January
may have helped as much as anything. North Dakota scored two goals
in the last seven minutes to tie the first night and then lost in
overtime. Then scored three in the last five minutes to tie the
next night. And lost in OT again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a kick in the teeth and cost us the league
championship,'' Armbrust said. ``That could have been it. We could
have thrown in the towel. But coach talked about how we played a
couple of great games. He pointed out how we played great hockey
and big deal if we don't win the league, try to win the league
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Won those. Won in the Regionals.
</P>
<P>
   Now they're back in the Frozen Four. Won this the last time they
were here, too. Something's got to give, since Maine won it all
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Sioux will try to play loose again. Have some fun.
</P>
<P>
   And give Dean Blais a reason to dance another jig or two before
the weekend's over in Providence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
