u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-GARCIAPARR     04-04 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-GARCIAPARRA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA STOPS SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As he begins his fourth season with the Red Sox,
absent much of the controversy that cast shadows over his first
three openers here, Nomar Garciaparra sounded almost Zenlike Monday
about what lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know what to expect in the game,'' said the
26-year-old shortstop, who in three seasons has been American
League Rookie of the Year, runner-up for MVP in Year Two, and AL
batting champion in Year Three. ``Every year is different.
Everything is different. Who knows why things happen? They just
happen, because that's part of the game, part of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the Sox begin their 100th season seldom have expectations
soared as high as they have for the Olde Towne Team, due in great
measure to the presence of the pitcher, Pedro Martinez, who will
attempt to win his third straight opener since coming to the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, who complained regularly the last two seasons about
how lightly the Sox were regarded, is scornful of the
opinion-makers who now sing the team's praises.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cracks me up,'' he said. ``Somebody who put us down as much
as we were put down, now they're saying we're good, but in the back
of their minds they think we're horrible. They're just waiting with
an `I told you so' attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Martinez was masterful, marvelous, and mythic in
pitching the Red Sox to their second straight berth in the playoffs
as the wild-card entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to say,'' Martinez said Monday. ``There's a
lot to do. That season is gone. That money is in the bank, what
they paid me for that season. It's up to me to do what I have to do
this season. I don't have a ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, asked if he thought it was fair to expect Martinez
to match his performance of last season, shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he goes out to pitch, you know you have to back him up,
put up some runs, play good defense,'' he said. ``You can't expect
him to go out there and strike out everybody. Sure, it happened
last year, and if it happens again, great, but you can't go out
there with the approach that it will.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox begin this season against former Sox lefthander Jamie
Moyer with a new center fielder, Carl Everett, their 13th
consecutive different Opening Day right fielder, Darren Lewis, and
a 41-year-old designated hitter, Gary Gaetti, whose knees set off
metal detectors in airports.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Hatteberg, who was the Opening Day catcher a year ago, is
on the bench, supplanted by Jason Varitek. Jeff Frye, who opened at
second base last season, is still on the club, barely. Jose
Offerman, who was the DH last season, is at second, with Frye a
$2.5 million backup. Bret Saberhagen, who was the No. 2 starter
behind Martinez, is back in Florida, attempting to engineer yet
another medical miracle, while last year's closer, Tom Gordon, and
aspiring starter Juan Pena are both sitting out the year with elbow
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   New faces in the rotation include Ramon Martinez, starting his
first full season with the Sox; lefty Jeff Fassero, who last season
pitched the opener for the Mariners before falling off the map; and
lefty Pete Schourek, two years after pitching the last game of the
1998 playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have been uncommonly successful in openers, winning
three in a row, six of seven, and eight of their last 10. They're
also coming off a spring training in which their 11-19 record was
tied with the rebuilding Florida Marlins and those perennial
stinkers, the Milwaukee Brewers, for worst in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not concerned about it,'' Garciaparra said. ``When you
have a veteran ball club, sometimes you're not as concerned about
the results as you are about getting yourself ready for April. With
a not-so-veteran team, a young team, guys are trying to make the
team and ready from the first day of camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra missed 27 games with assorted elbow, groin,
hamstring, and wrist injuries last season. He began camp this
spring by spraining a ligament in his right knee when he planted
his foot on a routine infield drill and the soft dirt gave way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weird things happen,'' Garciaparra said, speaking not only
about himself but Pena, who was struck in the right wrist by a line
drive and apparently tore the ligament in his elbow. ``Think about
how you talk about the weirdest injuries that happen. You can get
hurt stepping out of your car.''
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, he said, he doesn't make it a goal to stay
healthy. He just plays hard and hopes for the best.
</P>
<P>
   He has been around long enough that he feels at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I feel like a veteran? I guess in the sense that I'm
comfortable in my surroundings, I know what my surroundings are,''
said Garciaparra. ``I know how to get to Fenway and home from
Fenway. I know where the parking lot is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the personalities on this team. I know what needs to be
done. I'm not going to go and call team meetings, but the guys you
know, and have built relationships with, I know I can go over and
say something to them. Before, I didn't know how guys would
react.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, at least at the outset, is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I can just go out there and play,'' he said. ``This has
been the first spring with no controversy. Think about it. First
year, `Oh my God, he's playing shortstop (instead of John
Valentin).' Second year, `He had a good rookie year, but now will
he (stink),' and the Mo (Vaughn) thing. Third year, `Oh my God,
Mo's not here.'
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, it's `Hi, what's up?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Now Pedro will offer the first response.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
