<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-CRIMES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN SPORTS, LAW MEET, PROSECUTORS MUST WALK A FINE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH RANALLI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nola Foulson is probably the only person ever to read Red Sox
slugger Ted Williams's book ``The Science of Hitting'' for its
legal insights.
</P>
<P>
   Foulson, the district attorney for Sedgwick County, Kansas, also
spent scores of hours last fall watching ESPN and CNN-Sports
Illustrated into the early morning, and not because she
particularly likes baseball, or any other sport for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I would just as soon watch grass grow,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, like other prosecutors across North America, Foulson
was struggling with the hazy boundary separating rule-breaking from
lawbreaking in contact sports, a debate that has raged anew since
Boston Bruin Marty McSorley was charged with assault in Canada last
month for smashing another player in the head with his hockey
stick.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically at least, prosecutors have broad power and
discretion to bring criminal charges against violent sports
conduct. Even a hard cross-check in hockey or a beanball in
baseball could be interpreted as an assault under the laws of
Canada and most of the 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   Yet legal experts say prosecutors who must play referee often
find themselves making judgment calls without a rulebook. Athletes,
meanwhile, are given little or no guidance about what separates
conduct that could land them in the showers from conduct that could
land them in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly can be a very dangerous situation,'' said
attorney Randy Chapman, former chairman of the Massachusetts Bar
Association's Criminal Justice Section. ``Prosecutors have broad
discretion. That's the slippery slope everyone is concerned
about.''
</P>
<P>
   In Foulson's case, she had to decide last spring whether to
bring charges against Wichita State University pitcher Ben
Christensen, who it appeared had intentionally thrown a pitch at an
opponent during warm-ups.
</P>
<P>
   The opposing player, Anthony Molina of Evansville University,
recently filed a $150,000 civil lawsuit alleging that he suffered
facial fractures, retinal damage, and permanent vision impairment
when the ball struck him in the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Foulson found that a ``brushback'' pitch _ even
between innings, thrown at a batter who might be improperly
``timing'' warm-up pitches _ was essentially part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   In her six-page report explaining why Christensen wasn't charged
criminally, she quoted no less an authority than Williams, who
wrote in his book that major league pitchers would sometimes brush
him back if he got too close to the plate during warm-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Foulson found that ``brushback'' pitches were tolerated under
NCAA rules and that Christensen did not intend to hit Molina.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Foulson said she probably would have brought charges against
McSorley, which illustrates just how fine a line prosecutors walk
when sports and law intersect.
</P>
<P>
   In the waning moments of the Bruins' Feb. 21 game against the
Vancouver Canucks, McSorley hit Canucks winger Donald Brashear in
the head with his stick, sending Brashear crashing backward, his
head striking the ice. Brashear suffered a Grade 3 concussion, the
most severe kind.
</P>
<P>
   McSorley, who said he meant to hit Brashear in the upper arm and
provoke a fight, was suspended for the last 23 games of the season
and lost $72,000 in salary. Because he is 36 and nearing the end of
his career, it's likely McSorley may never play in the NHL again.
</P>
<P>
   When prosecutors in British Columbia brought assault charges
against McSorley, however, many cried foul, including the NHL's
chief legal officer, Bruins president and general manager Harry
Sinden, and McSorley's defense lawyer, Paul Kelly, of the Boston
firm of Foley Hoag &AMP; Eliot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law enforcement should never have been involved in this
case,'' said Kelly, a former longtime federal prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   But equally vocal was a chorus of politicians, judges, and
prosecutors in Canada and the United States, including Suffolk
(Mass.) County District Attorney Ralph C. Martin II, who said he
``probably'' would have charged McSorley if the incident had been
at the FleetCenter in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   To some observers, the debate over the McSorley case points up
just how unevenly prosecutions are brought for conduct that occurs
during sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   Why, for instance, was McSorley prosecuted and not Christensen?
Just as the NCAA tolerates inside pitching, Kelly said, the NHL has
long tolerated fighting and tough-guy ``enforcer'' players like
McSorley and Brashear, who had fought earlier in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer Mike Tyson, who unlike McSorley had a criminal record, was
not prosecuted for biting off part of Evander Holyfield's ear
during their 1997 heavyweight championship fight.
</P>
<P>
   But Tony Limon, a high school basketball player in San Antonio,
was sentenced to five years in state prison for breaking an
opponent's nose with an elbow last year, and a 15-year-old Chicago
boy is facing charges of aggravated battery for a hit from behind
he made during a high school hockey game that left another player
paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors such as Las Vegas District Attorney Stuart Bell,
whose office declined to prosecute Tyson, say a myriad of factors
go into a decision whether to prosecute, including how much
professional players implicitly ``consent'' to rough conduct in
their particular sport; whether the victimized player is willing to
press charges; and whether there is another forum for punishment,
such as a league or government agency.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Las Vegas police declined to charge Tyson criminally,
Bell said, was that the Nevada Athletic Commission was already
conducting its own probe.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous attempts by both federal and state lawmakers to
regulate sports violence have failed over the past 20 years. Kelly
said the lack of clear legal standards for prosecutors or police to
follow confuses players and allows outside factors such as
community pressure to dictate decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said his own research in the McSorley case has shown that
most prosecutions have been brought against visiting players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you should leave it solely in the hands of
judges and ambitious prosecutors,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors in Canada, known as ``crown attorneys,'' have even
more power than their US counterparts, said prominent Ontario
defense lawyer Richard J. Bosada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our crown attorneys have a tendency to respond to community
views,'' Bosada said. ``That's the unfairness of it. The crown
attorney's personality is often a factor, and community feeling is
a factor, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal researchers say a much larger percentage of prosecutions
for on-field behavior take place in Canada _ where baseball player
Dave Winfield was arrested and charged with cruelty to animals when
his warm-up throw killed a seagull in Toronto in 1983. The charge
was dropped the next day.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, there have been numerous criminal cases brought
against NHL players, including several Bruins, but none has been
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   One NHL player, Minnesota's Dino Ciccarelli, did plead guilty to
assault charges in 1988 and was sentenced to one day in jail.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, McSorley would be the first player ever found
guilty by a jury of assault.
</P>
<P>
   Some commentators have called the McSorley prosecution an
important ``message'' to younger players in an era where sports
violence appears to be on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one NHL player, the New Jersey Devils' Scott
Niedermayer, doesn't appear to be listening.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the NHL suspended Niedermayer for 10 games _ worth
more than $150,000 in salary _ for a two-handed chop with his stick
to the top of the helmet of Florida Panthers forward Peter Worrell
during a game. Worrell was not seriously hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching the game at home when it happened,'' said
Bergen County District Attorney William H. Schmidt. ``Certainly it
crossed the pale as conduct that warranted some action by the NHL.
But it did not rise for us to . . . an indictable offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NHL needs to and should police their own sport. In most
instances, law enforcement authorities should not be involved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
