<SLUG> BC-FUNDING-HARSHBARGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARSHBARGER TAKES REINS IN CAMPAIGN-FINANCE REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ What timing. Six months after taking the reins of
Common Cause, a granddaddy of good-government groups, Bay State
transplant Scott Harshbarger finds himself riding high on the
hottest horse in Washington, the drive for campaign-finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   It's probably just a coincidence that both parties' presumptive
presidential nominees, plus some of Congress's strongest defenders
of the current money system, became born-again reformers just after
Harshbarger arrived in town. In fact, the Democrat who narrowly
lost the governor's race in 1998 says with self-deprecation that he
still doesn't get all his phone calls returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hershberger? Hamburger? It's back to the days of having to
spell my name,'' said Harshbarger, who, as Massachusetts attorney
general from 1990 to 1998, led high-profile campaigns against
tobacco, guns, legalized gambling, and domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this new job _ president of Common Cause _ could be
Harshbarger's greatest challenge and opportunity. His mandate is to
energize and restore status to the 30-year-old citizens' lobby that
by most measures is showing its age. His mission is to lead Common
Cause in a year when, thanks largely to Arizona Senator John
McCain's assault on special interests, its signature issue _
getting big money out of politics _ has captured the public
imagination and has a chance to move in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an extraordinary moment for Common Cause,'' said Fred
Wertheimer, who headed the group for a more than a decade. ``The
issue of campaign finance reform is attracting unprecedented
national attention, and Common Cause has been there from the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiercely independent, Common Cause never has had a partisan as
president, and Harshbarger is taking pains to erase his Democratic
brand and play no favorites in the presidential race. This week he
called Vice President Al Gore's new proposal to ban unlimited
donations of so-called soft money and create a $7.1 billion
endowment to fund candidates ``a good, solid response'' to
campaign-finance abuses. But, Harshbarger added, he still has
doubts about Gore's sincerity and credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``The words are right, but how is Gore different from Bill
Clinton, how does what he says effect the 1996 presidential money
scandals, which were the biggest in history, and why should you
believe him on this issue at all?'' Harshbarger asked.
</P>
<P>
   He's no more charitable to Texas Governor George W. Bush.
Harshbarger says Bush adopted ``a phony reform proposal'' to beat
McCain in the GOP primaries and ``is not even in the same
ballpark'' with Gore because he defends soft money. And the sudden
interest by Senate Republicans in tinkering with the campaign
finance laws is aimed less at change and more at giving senators
political cover in the November elections, Harshbarger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, it's a little hard to believe (Gore and Bush)
are going to pick up the reform mantle,'' Harshbarger said. ``On
the other hand, it proves they see what McCain and (Bill) Bradley
saw: that campaign-finance reform is a really salient issue in the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   If Harshbarger harbors ambitions for elective office _ another
run for governor in 2002, perhaps _ standing on a national platform
and exposing political hypocrisy isn't likely to help him win
friends in the Democratic establishment. Representative Martin
Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat who probably has his own eye on a
higher prize, said using Common Cause as a political stepping stone
``won't work'' for Harshbarger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been accused of being holier-than-thou all of my
political career, and there is no point in being different now,''
said Harshbarger, insisting he likes what he's doing and ``the last
thing on my mind'' is running for office. ``As a practical matter,
it's our job to call them as we see them.''
</P>
<P>
   The job, which was offered to him by Derek Bok, Common Cause's
chairman and the former president of Harvard University, is a good
fit for Harshbarger. He said it allows him to stay in public life
and in touch with the kind of ethics issues that interested him
most as general counsel of the Massachusetts Ethics Commission, as
Middlesex district attorney, and as attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   It also gave him a needed change of venue after a very
disappointing defeat in the governor's race, a bout of
post-election depression, and some career uncertainly for a
58-year-old ``former'' office-holder with a lawyer wife and empty
nest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting a little distance was important, so I wasn't
constantly thinking about what could have been, or what might have
been,'' said Harshbarger, who commuted to Boston each weekend last
fall but now has rented an apartment in Washington. ``I vowed I
wouldn't say anything about (Gov.) Paul Cellucci _ he won, that's
the ballgame, that's the way it is _ and besides, nobody really
wanted to hear my opinion, and nobody wants to hear you whine.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Washington was a culture shock. As a candidate,
Harshbarger said he was tuned in to the public's cynical view that
government is at best irrelevant and at worst tainted and corrupt.
Inside the Capital Beltway, Harshbarger found elected officials
tone deaf to the cry that Washington is the captive of special
interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unbelievable disconnect,'' Harshbarger said during an
interview in his spacious downtown office. ``People in Washington
see the world totally differently from people anywhere else in the
country. The feeling here is `the public is wrong. That's not the
way we do business here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A second surprise, Harshbarger said, was to find the community
of public-interest activists, supposedly led by Common Cause,
arguing about agenda, divided over tactics, and nursing old
grudges. How on earth were they going to win a war against the
powerful lobbyists on K Street, Harshbarger wondered, if the
reformers were fighting among themselves?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why the other side can sleep at night,'' Harshbarger
said, recalling the industry's divide-and-conquer strategy that
defeated antitobacco legislation in 1998. ``They know their best
chance is to throw red meat out there and get the reform groups to
yell at each other and refuse to talk to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Miller, executive director of Public Campaign, said Common
Cause was mostly to blame for the bad blood because ``like an
800-pound gorilla,'' it got accustomed over 30 years to throwing
its weight around and disregarding newer advocacy groups like hers.
``Scott has put out the peace flag, and I think it's working,''
Miller said. ``People are feeling a lot more generous these days
toward Common Cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger said one of his goals is to broaden the Washington
coalition of clean-government types to include civil-rights and
public-health groups and to mobilize more activists at the grass
roots. Another is to grow Common Cause's 200,000 membership and $10
million budget because both have been static for years. A third is
to use the Internet, a larger staff, and Harshbarger's
communication skills to raise the visibility of the organization
and make the arcane subject of campaign finance accessible to a
larger audience.
</P>
<P>
   He's already getting attention in some unexpected places.
Conservative radio talk-show host Rush Limbaugh recently gave
Harshbarger credit for questioning Gore's reformer credentials.
``He didn't criticize me, and he quoted me twice,'' Harshbarger
said, amazed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
