<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, April 5:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-POLITICS (Tokyo) _ Yoshiro Mori, secretary general of
governing party, is expected to become prime minister on Wednesday.
Cabinet resigns to pave the way. Also, analysis on how the
transition has been handled. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-OBUCHI-REACT (Tokyo) _ Their prime minister was lying in
the intensive care unit of a local hospital, kept alive by a
respirator. The media were full of stories about how their elected
representatives had lied about the gravity of his condition in
order to put in place a succession plan before critics could raise
their voices. The very legitimacy and credibility of their
political system had been thrown into question. But the Japanese
people barely shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-RIGHTS (Moscow) _ After visit to region, U.N. Human
Rights Commissioner Mary Robinson says there have been serious
human rights violations in Chechnya. By Patrick Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-POVERTY (United Nations) _ After years of treading
carefully around the issue of why some countries stay poor and get
poorer, the United Nations on Tuesday laid much of the blame
squarely on the countries themselves. While not ignoring the
problem of reduced foreign aid, the report by the U.N. Development
Program said that three-quarters of countries have estimated their
needs, but very few have concrete plans of their own on what to do
about them. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-STATUS (Washington) _ Census Bureau Director Kenneth
Prewitt holds a news briefing on the status of Census 2000
operations. Half of forms had been mailed back as of Friday
evening; the percentage is probably up to about 57 percent now. By
David Stout.
</P>
<P>
   ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS (Washington) _ The House passes a bill to set
up a national organ transplant system, replacing a regional system.
By Eric Schmitt. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-RIDGE (Harrisburg, Pa.) _ A look at George W. Bush's
relationship to Gov. Tom Ridge, a potential running mate. By Frank
Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-SOCSEC (Philadelphia) _ Vice President Gore proposes
changes to Social Security to pay women more money. Women who leave
the paid work force to raise children typically receive about $600
a year less than they would if they stayed employed the whole time.
He also proposes more money for widows. By James Dao. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News and notes from the hustings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (dateline to kum) _ Developing. Waiting for Cuba's
decision on the departure for the U.S. of Elian Gonzalez's father.
Talks continue in Miami. Vice President Gore says the father should
be allowed to take his son home ``if the father says on free soil
that he believes that the son should go back to Cuba with him.'' He
says a family court should have a role though. By Rick Bragg (in
Miami) and/or Neil A. Lewis. (in Washington)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-DIPLO (Washington) _ A working profile of the Cuban
Interest Section, as the diplomats prepare for Elian's father to
arrive in Washington. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HORMONE-REPLACEMENT (Undated) _ Women in a large study of
the effects of hormone replacement therapy have been told that
researchers have found a slight increase in risk for heart attacks,
stroke and blood clots. The study is not being halted but adds more
fuel to recent debate over whether estrogen therapy actually helps
the heart. Researchers said women should talk with doctors and
discuss treatment if they are taking the therapy in hopes of
reducing heart attack risk. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   EMAIL-MONITORS (Undated) _ Hundreds of companies are looking at
their employee's e-mail on a routine basis. And their numbers are
soaring. ``The market for e-mail monitoring has basically doubled
in size over the last year,'' said Abner Germanow, a research
manager at the International Data Corp. Company managers give a
variety reasons for installing such software. Some are on the
lookout for oversized e-mail attachments that clog their networks.
Others seek to dissuade employees from using their systems for
personal activities. And others want to make sure employees aren't
sending harassing e-mail messages that could get the company into
legal trouble. Whatever the reason, the snooping raises a number of
questions about ethics and privacy. By Lisa Guernsey.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SUITS (Undated) _ Looking at the private antitrust
suits that may now be filed given the legal decision against
Microsoft. Plus other Microsoft antitrust developments. By Steve
Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Technology stocks were lower in
mid-afternoon. At 1:45 p.m., the Nasdaq composite was down 331
points, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 186 points.
Treasury prices were higher. Crude oil was at $25.78 a barrel.
European markets were mixed: London down 0.12 percent, Frankfurt up
1.37 percent. The Nikkei closed down 0.64 percent. Hong Kong's
market was closed for a holiday. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-LIQUIDITY (Undated) _ A look at the liquidity questions
hanging over a growing number of Internet companies, including
CDNow and Peapod, raising questions about their viability. By Saul
Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   COKE-INVEST (Undated) _ Coca-Cola holds analysts' meeting. By
Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   KRISPY-IPO (Undated) _ Krispy Kreme prices its IPO. By Patrick
McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column. By Nancy
Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-MARKET (Tokyo) _ A look at what's behind the surprisingly
resilient Japanese stock market, which has outperformed the United
States market over the last year, despite Japan's lapse into
another recession in late 1999, rising government debts and now,
the change in leadership following the prime minister's stroke. By
Stephanie Strom.
</P>
