<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUDGE SETS TRIAL FOR SUIT SEEKING TO BLOCK NEWSPAPER SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SETH ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A federal judge fast-forwarded the future of San
Francisco's daily newspapers by setting a May 1 trial on and
antitrust lawsuit that seeks to block the Hearst Corp. from buying
the San Francisco Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker on Monday set the date for a
full trial after lawyers for Hearst proposed skipping an April 13
hearing on the plaintiff's request for a preliminary injunction
blocking the sale until a trial is held, which could have been
months off.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was filed by Clint Reilly, a political consultant
who launched an unsuccessful campaign for mayor last year. The
lawsuit contends that the purchase of the locally owned Chronicle
would lead to New York-based Hearst's owning the only metropolitan
daily paper in San Francisco and would create an illegal monopoly
that would raise advertising and subscription prices.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst has agreed to sell the afternoon Examiner, the company's
flagship newspaper, to the publisher of the Independent, a free
tabloid published three times a week.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst and the Chronicle Publishing Co. have called Reilly's
lawsuit baseless, saying Hearst's plan to buy the morning Chronicle
and sell the Examiner would restore economic competition between
daily papers in San Francisco for the first time in 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   Walker last Thursday entered a temporary restraining order that
barred the sale until the April 13 hearing. Reilly on Monday posted
a required $100,000 bond to cover potential damages to Hearst and
Chronicle Publishing if his claims fail.
</P>
<P>
   Although the restraining order expires before May 1, Hearst
agreed not to complete its purchase of the Chronicle until Walker
ruled on the trial.
</P>
<P>
   For both sides, the expedited trial avoids a potentially sticky
preliminary injunction and speeds a resolution to the future of the
Chronicle and Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is excellent news,'' said Timothy O. White, editor and
publisher of the Examiner. ``We're delighted that Judge Walker
recognized the urgency of this matter and was willing to be
accommodating and hold a trial on such short notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph M. Alioto, Reilly's attorney, also was pleased. ``We are
more than happy about going directly to trial,'' he said. ``It's
great for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Each side predicted it would win at trial.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst has agreed to pay $660 million cash for the Chronicle,
Northern California's largest daily newspaper. The Chronicle's
daily circulation is 465,535, while the Examiner's is 108,968.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst separately agreed to transfer ownership of the Examiner
to the publisher of the Independent and provide a $66 million
subsidy over three years to cover costs of publishing the
newspaper. No purchaser was willing to buy the Examiner without a
substantial subsidy, Hearst has said in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1965, the Examiner and the Chronicle have published under
a joint operating agreement, an exception to antitrust laws that
lets them combine business operations and split revenue, while
maintaining separate editorial staffs.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is allowed under the Newspaper Preservation Act,
which was intended to keep alive newspapers with dwindling
circulation so communities would have the benefit of multiple
editorial voices.
</P>
<P>
   In granting the temporary restraining order last week, Walker
ruled that Reilly had initially raised serious legal questions
about whether the proposed newspaper sales complied with antitrust
laws and met the goals of the act.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Justice Department has said that it had no
objections to the sales, and expected them to result in competing
newspapers, Walker said the department's ruling was not binding on
the courts.
</P>
</TEXT>
