<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6749 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-BLACK-AND-WHITE-REVIE     04-04 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-AND-WHITE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROSSING COLOR LINES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For most of its running length, ``Black and White'' is an
enjoyable, seemingly improvisatory mess about rich white kids who
want to be black, African-American gangsters who long to go legit,
athletes in trouble, angry undercover cops, earnest documentarians
and their gay husbands, and Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   It's fun to watch this highly varied assortment of curious,
dissatisfied individuals try on one another's poses and personae,
forcing their way into unfamiliar lifestyles and generally
reinventing themselves as they go along. There's a jazzy energy _
although the film is set to an insistent hip-hop beat _ to all the
sex and threat and giddy misbehavior, which is nicely underscored
by a general air of boundary-breaking acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   But after a while, writer-director James Toback finds it
necessary to impose some narrative order on all of the multiculti
shenanigans. And while the plot threads he bothers to tie up are
not uninteresting, they play as artificially as they inarguably are
against the film's vibrant mosaic of spontaneous behavior.
</P>
<P>
   While the films' white folks move fluidly, if often
outlandishly, across contemporary New York's racial lines, the
African-Americans' efforts to achieve traditional success, while
spectacularly effective, are realistically fraught with more
difficulty and peril. The main plotline involves Rich Bower (played
by Wu-Tang Clan impresario Oli ``Power'' Grant), a Staten Island
crime lord who'd love to focus his energies on a music career, if
only he could convince frightened white recording studio owners to
let his crew cut a record.
</P>
<P>
   Rich's spectacular river-view condo is the site of an ongoing
party, where invited celebrities like Tyson and Method Man mingle
with teen-age crashers (Bijou Phillips leads that pack) from Park
Avenue and with the equally enthralled Sam (Brooke Shields), a
documentary filmmaker who just thinks privileged kids' fascination
with black culture is, well, fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   The film's funniest encounters are between Sam, her husband
Terry (Downey in his thousand-and-first impersonation of a flirty
homosexual) and the self-mockingly charming Tyson, who humorously
manages to steal every scene he's in. (``I'm on parole, brother,
please,'' is a typical, exquisitely timed response to one of
Terry's outrageous come-ons).
</P>
<P>
   The film's other designated sportsman, New York Knick Allan
Houston, plays a character who's in a more urgent legal bind. His
Dean, a straight-arrow college basketball star and childhood friend
of Rich's, is entrapped and blackmailed by undercover cop Mark (Ben
Stiller) into setting his friend up for a bust. Complicating this
tortured situation is the fact that Mark has a past with Dean's
girlfriend Greta, a sociology grad played by, of all people,
supermodel Claudia Schiffer (talk about no boundaries).
</P>
<P>
   There are many other subplots and relationships, none of them
particularly any more persuasive than those just illuminated, but
they're intelligently enough detailed to sustain your attention.
And this being a Toback film (his last one was the snarky ``Two
Girls and a Guy''), sex is a pretty prominent factor here. A lot of
that has its basis in stereotypical racial assumptions, but again
Toback brings solid, observational verity to the encounters that,
more often than not, give them a believable erotic charge.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, ``Black and White'' isn't too sure about how to
characterize what Toback sees as the blending state of contemporary
racial politics. But when it's not trying to understand or explain
and just _ as the kids put it these days _ representing, this
flawed but intriguing movie manages to say quite a bit. &QL; 
________ &QL; 
The film: ``Black and White'' (R; sex, language, nudity, violence,
drug use). &QL; 
The stars: Oli ``Power'' Grant, Ben Stiller, Allan Houston, Brooke
Shields, Robert Downey Jr., Mike Tyson, Bijou Phillips, Claudia
Schiffer, Elijah Wood, Jared Leto, Joe Pantoliano. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Written and directed by James Toback. Produced
by Michael Mailer, Daniel Bigel and Ron Rotholz. Released by Screen
Gems. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 40 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
