r l BC-CANCER-FIGHT-LADN &LR;      04-04 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-FIGHT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT WITHOUT A FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Retransmitted with Sidebar slugged Take Charge) 
By PHIL DAVIS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bruce Paltrow refused to submit to the cancer that burrowed
rapidly into his throat, penetrated lymph nodes and snaked around
his carotid artery.
</P>
<P>
   The film and television producer and his family plunged into the
mysterious world of cancer treatments with a literal lust for life.
They studied all the options and asked their physicians lots of
questions. Paltrow chose aggressive surgery, doubled the standard
radiation treatment and sought alternative therapies from
acupuncture to vitamins.
</P>
<P>
   The assault drove the throat cancer into remission.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a fistfight,'' said Paltrow, father of Academy
Award-winning actress Gwyneth Paltrow. ``You have to go forward,
attack it _ do everything you can to win.''
</P>
<P>
   That philosophy won't work for everyone. But the attitude will.
</P>
<P>
   Paltrow is part of a growing trend of assertive medical
consumers. Dr. David Feinberg, a psychiatrist at the University of
California, Los Angeles, predicts that within two years a wave of
assertive, informed patients will transform the medical profession,
bring foreign terms such as customer service and satisfaction into
the medical vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   Feinberg, co-author of ``Don't Let Your HMO Kill You''
(Routledge; $14.95), is one of the leaders of this charge. His book
is one of several appearing on bookstore shelves that advises
patients how to manage their managed-care plan.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals are already responding to the trend. UCLA's new $600
million medical center will feature warm, sunlit corridors, tasty
food and in-room family areas instead of cold, uncomfortable
waiting rooms. The hospital design is a nod to a future when
patients will have a choice on where to spend their health-care
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   HBO addresses this patient call to arms with a 2 1/2-hour
television documentary, ``Cancer: Evolution to Revolution,'' that
shows cancer patients how to take an active, aggressive role in the
treatment of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are expecting more from their doctors,'' said Joseph
Lovett, the veteran television health journalist who produced and
directed the HBO special. ``This show is not about miracle cures.
It's about knowing how to get involved, finding the latest
treatments as they develop and having as many options as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is also fueling change. Medical Web sites _
government, non-profit and commercial _ make it easy for patients
to get enough information to pose intelligent questions. Doctors no
longer control all the knowledge. In fact, there is so much
information out there, most physicians can't keep up with it all.
</P>
<P>
   This health-care revolution has been a long time coming. The old
fee-for- services system sent health-care costs skyrocketing. HMOs
stepped into the picture in the early 1990s, promising _ and
failing _ to control costs. Feinberg said patients were left out of
the loop because insurers and doctors were accountable only to
employers.
</P>
<P>
   Patients didn't fit into the picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average patient asks four questions in a 10-minute
visit,'' Feinberg said. ``The typical physician interrupts within
19 seconds. There's not a lot of communication going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Feinberg said that companies such as Xerox that give employees a
medical allowance and let them shop for their own health plan, are
on the forefront of a new wave of medical care. Things tend to
improve when the person providing the service is directly
accountable to the customer, not to a disinterested third party
(like an employer).
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Peter Clarke, a University of Southern California physician
and co-author of ``Surviving Modern Medicine'' (Rutgers University
Press; $18), said a patient needs information and a psychological
edge to gain control of the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``From an economic viewpoint, the supply side can treat
customers indifferently and get away with it,'' Clarke said. ``The
antidote to that is to be proactive. They don't need to be
adversarial or confrontational, but they do need to be active on
their behalf.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
