A6758 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AIRLINE-SHANGHAI-HNS &LR;      04-04 0393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-SHANGHAI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSINESSES WELCOME DIRECT AIR LINK TO SHANGHAI 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When United Airlines Flight 858 from Shanghai
touched down Monday at the San Francisco International Airport,
there were compelling business reasons for the airport to welcome
its arrival.
</P>
<P>
   The air link is an important milestone. It marks the first
direct, nonstop service by a U.S. carrier between San Francisco,
America's capital of high-technology, and Shanghai, China's
business capital and most populous city.
</P>
<P>
   ``This reflects the great economic connection between Shanghai
and San Francisco,'' said John L. Martin, the airport director. ``I
fully expect China to be our fastest-growing market. Their economy
is improving; San Francisco's economy is booming.''
</P>
<P>
   The service is important to United, according to officials of
the Chicago-based airline. United is the leading carrier at the San
Francisco airport, where it has just over the half of the flights
and half of the passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco is our largest international gateway,'' said
Bill Roy, United's director at San Francisco. ``We expect a lot of
high-revenue customers on this route. Most of the Silicon Valley
companies have offices in China.''
</P>
<P>
   The new flights, Roy said, will reduce flying time between San
Francisco and Shanghai, an official sister-city, to about 11 hours.
Until now, counting a change of planes at Tokyo's Narita
International Airport, it was 17 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The Shanghai-San Francisco flights, now fives days a week, will
operate from the airport's new International Terminal when the $944
million structure opens Sept. 26.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the Pacific, Shanghai opened a new
international airport last year.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses lobbied Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater for
the Shanghai service, Martin said. Some of those companies are
members of the year-old SFO Bay Area Business Coalition, a
nonprofit advisory group.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition will continue to lobby the Department of
Transportation in hopes of increasing Shanghai service from five to
seven days a week, Martin said. The Transportation Department
allocates slots to selected airlines based on negotiations between
the United States and foreign countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
