<HEADLINE>
WINE OF THE WEEK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Friday, April 7) 
 
By MICHAEL LONSFORD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today is the 214th anniversary of the birth of William Rufus
Devane King, the 13th vice president of the United States. King
served only 46 days in office before dying of tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where was the oath of office administered? &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Today is also the 61st birthday of movie director Francis Ford
Coppola (The Godfather I, II and III, Apocalypse Now).
</P>
<P>
   With this week's featured wine, let me make you an offer you
can't refuse. Think of a wine that's fruity, light and perfumed.
Beaujolais, right? And who's the self-proclaimed ``king of
Beaujolais''? George DuBoeuf. So the 1998 DuBoeuf Fleurie _ 4 stars
_ is a fine example of the bright, fruit-driven style of ``cru''
Beaujolais. As Robert Duvall (might have) said, ``I love the smell
of strawberries in the morning!'' And with warm (OK, hot) weather
approaching, put a bottle of this Fleurie in the fridge for about
45 minutes and then chill out. It costs about $9.99.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the entire range of Beaujolais, DuBoeuf also
makes other wines, such as Macon-Villages, Pouilly-Fuisse and a
Cotes du Rhone-style red called Milenage.
</P>
<P>
   A: Havana. Because of his ill health, he was forced to spend the
winter of 1852-53 in Cuba. By a special act of Congress, King was
the only person to hold one of the two highest offices in the land
who was sworn in on foreign soil.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WINE RATING: &QL; 
 &QL; 
5 stars: Outstanding &QL; 
4 stars: Fine &QL; 
3 stars:Good &QL; 
2 stars: Fair &QL; 
1 star: Poor &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
