A6779 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-MAYOR-INVESTMENTS-HNS     04-04 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYOR-INVESTMENTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MAYOR BANKS ON TECH STOCKS, AND WINS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHUCK FINNIE and LANCE WILLIAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mayor Willie Brown plunged into the stock market
in 1999 and made a killing on a series of initial share offerings
of technology companies, city records show.
</P>
<P>
   In a financial disclosure report filed Monday with the San
Francisco Ethics Commission, Brown said that he had amassed a stock
portfolio worth as much as $970,000 through a series of purchases
made last fall at the height of his re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16 different stocks Brown bought, 14 were computer or
Internet companies. Seven of the investments appeared to have been
initial offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of Brown's stock picks were big winners, according to
a review of price data. The stocks in the mayor's portfolio, which
Brown said he had assembled in a series of buys between Oct. 1 and
Dec. 9, are worth more than double their purchase price, securities
data indicate.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, Brown turned a 280 percent profit on an Internet
stock he flipped after holding for only two days.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 9, Brown said he had bought between $1,000 and $10,000
worth of stock in a Microsoft spin-off called Expedia Inc., an
on-line travel service. The stock's initial offering price was $14.
On Nov. 11, when Brown sold, the stock was trading at $53 per
share.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has done even better with two other tech stocks he
acquired when they first went public and since has held onto:
McAfee Communication Corp., which makes software to guard against
computer viruses, and Cache Flow Inc., a company that markets
computer network equipment. Both stocks have more than tripled in
value since Brown bought them.
</P>
<P>
   Kandace Bender, Brown's press secretary, said the mayor did not
have a new financial guru guiding him in his stock market foray.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, he does not have a new financial adviser,'' she said.
``Like millions of Americans, he is kind of playing around on the
Internet and doing trading over the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   To guard against conflicts of interest, the state's Political
Reform Act requires public officials to file a report each year
outlining their investments and sources of income and gifts. The
law requires politicians only to estimate in general terms the
worth of their investments.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in his report, Brown put the value of his newly purchased
stocks at between $97,000 and $970,000.
</P>
<P>
   In other portions of the report, Brown said that he had sold the
Sacramento home where he had lived during his years as speaker of
the state Assembly. Real estate records show the house sold for
$207,000.
</P>
<P>
   The report also shows that for the fourth year in a row Brown
was paid more than $10,000 by a Los Angeles law firm where he
moonlighted while in the Assembly. The city Charter bars mayors
from holding outside jobs, but Brown has characterized the annual
payments from the Christensen, White law firm as part of a
multiyear buyout of his San Francisco law practice.
</P>
<P>
   Since Brown took office, Stephen Besser, a former partner in the
Los Angeles firm, has become a San Francisco city lobbyist, while
his wife, Jacqueline Besser, shares $102 million in city contracts
through a management consulting firm she formed in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Brown also reported receiving more than $10,000 in stock
dividends last year from Harbor Bay Realty Inc., a company owned by
Alameda developer Ron Cowan, Brown's friend and former law client.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said in his report that he had received no gifts at all
during his fourth year as mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of Brown's report involved his stock buying.
According to the reports, he was buying technology stocks in the
midst of the mayor's race, even as he and other mayoral candidates
debated policy responses to the region's blistering,
technology-based economic boom, which is creating multimillionaires
but also pushing affordable housing out of the reach of many.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
