   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-ELIAN _ MIAMI _ The Immigration and Naturalization Service
has put the immigrant status of 6-year-old Cuban rafter Elian
Gonzalez on the back-burner as the effort now shifts to placing the
boy in his father's custody if, and when Juan Miguel Gonzalez comes
to the United States ? which could be as early as today. But in
this 11th hour, will the Miami family give him up? And just how
does the INS plan to remove him from their home? What sort of
resistance will they run into in Miami's Cuban exile community?
Developing.(MWilliams, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-SIDE _ MIAMI _ Color story on the going-on in Miami.
Extended family in Miami is supposed to let INS know whether it
will agree to some sort of deal surrounding Elian, the 6-year-old
Cuban kid caught between his Miami relatives and his dad in Cuba.
So far, cousin Marilysis has collapsed, taken to hospital. And
Cuban radio hosts are advising people not to come out yet to
protest. (Douthat, Palm Beach Post). 15. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: We are monitoring from Washington, the status of Juan
Miguel Gonzalez's impending trip to the United States to pick up
his son, Elian. If, and when he comes to Washington, we will be
covering the story with photos. We will send out an updated budget
of stories at that time.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ The next important step in the
Microsoft antitrust suit won't take place in the courtroom, but in
two separate meeting rooms. The Justice Department and the 19 state
attorneys general must agree on what penalties to recommend to U.S.
District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, and Microsoft officials
must overcome what some call the take-no-prisoners ``Gates
culture'' to fashion a new settlement proposal more acceptable to
the government. (Glass, Cox News Service). 22.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.,
said Tuesday his Senate Commerce Committee would hold hearings on
the Microsoft case to assess its impact on consumers and on ``this
incredible engine that's driving America's economy?'' Including
reaction from Commerce Committee member Max Cleland, D-Ga., and
others in Congress. (Geewax).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   VISA-WAIVER _ A bill that would make the practice of visa
waivers to grant foreign visitors and businessmen temporary access
to the United States was approved Tuesday by the House Judiciary
Committee. (Schultz, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SEX-TRADE _ WASHINGTON _Three women, two from Russia and one
from Mexico, tell a congressional hearing Tuesday of being swept
into the international forced sex trade, which officials say
involve 700,000 women and children annually. Among the victims is a
Mexican woman who was rescued in South Florida after being kept
against her will in a mobile trailer-brothel. (Malone, Cox News
Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: The hearing began at 2 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS _ WASHINGTON _ The South is lagging again in census
returns, Census Director Ken Prewitt said Tuesday. He said the
Census Bureau planned a new round of promotional ads aimed at the
region. Prewitt also denounced ``cheap shots'' from prominent
politicians who have voiced privacy concerns abut the long form.
(Holmes, Cox News SXervice). 15.
</P>
