<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS: Columbia News Service provides feature stories from the
New York City area every week for your use as desired. There is no
cost to you. CNS stories are transmitted courtesy of the New York
Times Syndicate/New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   The stories are slugged BC-CNS-keyword and move in the ``l''
news category. They are edited by adjunct professors who work at
The New York Times, Daily News, Newsday and The Associated Press,
among other places. The stories are written by degree candidates at
the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. All we
ask is that you send us a tearsheet.
</P>
<P>
   So please, if you can, use our stories. Most of them are news
features that can be held until you have a pesky hole to fill.
</P>
<P>
   To send us a tearsheet:
</P>
<P>
   Columbia News Service
</P>
<P>
   Graduate School of Journalism
</P>
<P>
   Columbia University
</P>
<P>
   2950 Broadway
</P>
<P>
   New York, N.Y. 10027
</P>
<P>
   Professor Wayne Svoboda (212) 854-3837
</P>
<P>
   Columbia News Service
</P>
<P>
   E-mail ws52(AT)columbia.edu
</P>
<P>
   Web site:http://cns.jrn.columbia.edu
</P>
<P>
   This week's stories:
</P>
<P>
   VEGAN-SWEETS (New York) _ Some strict vegetarians avoid all
animal products, including milk, butter and even some kinds of
sugar. But that doesn't mean they have given up cakes, brownies or
other sweets.Bakers across the country are catering to the sweet
tooth of a growing population. By Sarah Treffinger. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-DATING-SERVICE (New York) _ At least two online services
are bringing together women in prison and lonely men on the
outside. It's a controversial activity, praised by some who fallen
in love and condemned by others who say they have fallen prey. By
Michael Goldman. (1250 words)
</P>
<P>
   WALL-STREET-HOMELESS (New York) _ Within steps of Wall Street,
where fortunes change hands every day, is a center that feeds and
supports hundreds of homeless men who are mentally or physically
ill. When the center was first proposed, the community opposed it,
but it has won over some neighbors, and now operates almost
invisibly in the midst of prosperity. By Michael Caronna. (750
words)
</P>
<P>
   TOMBSTONE-ART (New York) _ The notion of a cemetery as a bland
resting place with identical headstones is being challenged by an
architect who believes tombstones should more closely reflect the
lives of the people under them. So Hali Weiss is crafting
personalized remembrances, incorporating art, design and elements
from many religions. By Gus G. Sentementes. (950 words, with art
available at http://cns.jrn.columbia.edu)
</P>
<P>
   ASIAN-EYE-SURGERY (New York) _ Many Asian-Americans are having
surgery to create a double eyelid, what used to be called
`Westernization.` But increasingly, people are having the surgery
not to look more like Caucasians, but to look more like other
Asians. By Jean Lee Scheidnes. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   CHINESE-MUSICIAN (New York) _ In his native China, Wei Zhang was
widely known as the master of the sheng, an ancient and very
difficult wind instrument. But he chose to come to the United
States to incorporate jazz and rock into the ancient music of the
sheng, in an attempt to spread the knowledge of the instrument
worldwide. By C.M. Lanzillotti. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   BALLROOM-RESURGENCE (New York) _ Ballroom dancing is on the
upswing again, as more and more young people find it is an activity
that promotes friendship, fitness, and fun. By Jocelyn Anderson.
(750 words)
</P>
</TEXT>
