<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6814 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-BALLROOM-RESURGEN     04-04 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-BALLROOM-RESURGENCE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALLROOM DANCE STAYS ALIVE AS A DIFFERENT KIND OF SPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mp)  (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Jocelyn Anderson is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 
 By JOCELYN ANDERSON   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Get yourself around the room at least once!'' Lisa
Jo Sagolla calls out. She gazed out on auditorium where 26 pairs of
partners swayed or staggered, the graceful swan-like duos gliding
past the awkward duckling pairs. A quick-tempo jazz melody filled
the air.
</P>
<P>
   Two slow steps followed two quick steps, over and over and over
and over.
</P>
<P>
   The fox trot, after all, is a travelling dance. Sagolla's
dancing class dutifully circled the room, faces frozen in
concentration. Some even seemed confident enough to relax and enjoy
the movement.
</P>
<P>
   Sagolla's class at Columbia University is a part of the latest
revival of ballroom dance, which has waxed and waned a number of
times in the past 100 years. Ballroom competitions boomed in the
1920s, and Fred Astaire and Ginger Rogers electrified the public
with their moves in the post World War II era. In recent years,
ballroom has achieved enough prominence to point it toward the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Ballroom dance courses like Sagolla's report a boom in
registration, and even a Broadway musical, ``Swing!,'' along with
peppy Gap commercials, celebrates the smooth style of partner
dancing. And while it may be Grandma's passion, ballroom dance has
crossed the generational divide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Professional studios have always been around,'' said Sagolla.
``Now a whole new generation is becoming aware of it and young
people are doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Arthur Murray Dance Studio in Manhattan, Fred Kaviani,
the director, said enrollment has steadily grown from about 350
students last year to about 500 this year. Similarly, DanceSport
enrolls 200 new people each month, according to Candace Salas, the
studio manager. Currently, DanceSport instructs about 1,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Students are willing to pay as much as $80 an hour to learn
shake their hips to the salsa, glide across the floor in a waltz or
throw their partners in a jitterbug.
</P>
<P>
   Zee Onuf, a graduate student in art history, is taking dance at
Columbia with her fiance to prepare for their wedding _ ``so we
don't make total fools out of ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has this incredible elegance,'' Onuf said.
</P>
<P>
   More young dancers are attending competitions, too. The
Manhattan Amateur Classic, a yearly ballroom competition for the
New Jersey-New York-Connecticut area, has a division for juniors,
aged 6 to 18. About 90 junior couples from across the country
signed up this year, compared with 70 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sometimes watch the competitions on television,'' said Karen
Seong, a student in Sagolla's class. ``It's kind of goofy. I didn't
know they were that serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Sagolla said her 52-student class is always full. Students seem
to view ballroom dance as a safe way to meet potential dates, she
added.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are needing to reconnect,'' Sagolla said. ``A
generation of people grew up dancing apart now want physical
contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Daphna Locker, co-president of the Greater New York United
States Amateur Ballroom Dancers Association, cited fitness as
another bonus of ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to the gym to run on a treadmill is boring,'' Locker
said. ``Ballroom dancing, if nothing else, is a partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   Added dance teacher Amy Garcia of Fred Astaire Studios in
Manhattan: ``Physically you have to be using your body to its
fullest potential in terms of everything, flexibility and
endurance.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the ultimate testimony to ballroom's popularity over
time is its candidacy to enter the Olympics. Ballroom cleared the
first hurdle in 1997 when the International Olympic Committee
recognized it as an official sport. If the IOC now accepts it for
Olympic competition, judges will score the dancers in such
categories as technique and style. Analysts say, however, that
because of the IOC's slow pace, that may take several years.
</P>
<P>
   But Locker is confident that day will come, with ballroom's
traditional image as an art form already beginning to fade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people don't look at dancing as a sport,'' she said.
``That perception will have to change. I think that's coming
about.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
