<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6816 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-CNS-TOMBSTONE-ART &LR; (mp     04-04 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-TOMBSTONE-ART </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHITECT SEEKS A SOFTER TOMBSTONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mp)  (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Art for this story is available for downloading at
http://cns.jrn.columbia.edu) 
(Gus G. Sentementes is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By GUS G. SENTEMENTES   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With a slab of stone and the written word, Hali Weiss
is ready to take on the American way of death.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the design of our final resting places.
``Cemeteries today are horrible,'' said Weiss, an architect. ``The
idea of sameness in death emerged after the world wars. That notion
is convenient for cemeteries, where grave markers have to be a
certain size and graves must lie on a grid pattern'' to permit easy
grounds maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   What the traditional cemetery leaves out, Weiss said, are
stories _ those of the deceased and of the loved ones who visit the
final resting place. So, in 1992, Weiss founded Living Monuments
Inc. to try to change that.
</P>
<P>
   Her goal is to work with friends and relatives to create a
tombstone that tells more about the deceased than when they were
born and when they died. It's a process that is therapeutic and
meaningful for her clients, she said _ and, she adds, too rare in
the funeral industry.
</P>
<P>
   Many other monument companies ``don't work with families to
craft a distinctive design that helps the customer come to terms
with the loss of a loved one,'' Weiss said. ``It's usually just
roses on stone. With me, if someone ended up with roses as part of
the design, they'd have to come up with a reason why roses are
meaningful to the person they're memorializing.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss has patented one design, the Scroll of Life memorial,
which takes its influence from the Buddhist prayer wheels that
surround Buddhist temples. It features a rotating black granite
cylinder that is engraved with the short biography of the
deceased's life, which Weiss helps her customers to write. She even
developed a workbook, with the help of grief therapists, that asks
the bereaved to recall the personality and accomplishments of the
loved one they are trying to write about.
</P>
<P>
   Other reminders of the deceased can be incorporated into the
design: Weiss can include pictures on the cylinder through a
photographic masking process.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, who designs about 100 monuments a year, believes more
people will be looking for personalized funeral products in the
coming years. More than 77 million baby boomers will be turning 50
years old by 2015, and Weiss, a young boomer herself, believes that
more of them will take control of the death experience of their
parents and themselves _ the way they took control of the
childbirth experience in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Many of her clients are college-educated, upper-middle-class
people from various religious faiths. With prices starting at about
$2,000 and averaging $5,000 to $6,000, a Weiss memorial is more
expensive than conventional headstones and simple markers, which
typically range from $600 to $3,000 in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes clients aren't prepared for the process. ``I usually
meet with a customer four to six times. The client determines the
pace,'' said Weiss. ``But some people are overwhelmed at first and
don't come back for a few months.''
</P>
<P>
   The planning can bring up painful memories, too. Weiss remembers
one woman who wanted to design a memorial for her husband, who had
been dead for three years. The woman planned to take a picture of
the tree that they had been married under and then incorporate the
photograph into the memorial design, Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She couldn't bring herself to do it,'' Weiss said. ``She just
couldn't take a picture of the tree.'' The woman never completed
the monument.
</P>
<P>
   Another client, a woman in her 70s, won't wait for family
members to design a memorial for her after she dies. She has it
already planned with Weiss, selecting the Handprints design for her
memorial. A bronze cast of the customer's hands is made while the
customer is alive, and the handprints are then incorporated into
the memorial design. Weiss made bronze handprints not just of the
woman but also of her children, who are in their 30s. The woman is
keeping the bronze hand casts on a wall in her house until she dies
_ and then Weiss will complete the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   The personalized memorials have been a tough sell at some
cemeteries. Many have specific guidelines for grave markers and
memorials, and place restrictions on the size and material
composition of the memorial. Many only allow memorials and markers
made of stone, and bronze is often forbidden because thieves steal
it. Since her designs often go against the conventions of size and
materials, Weiss said she's constantly negotiating with cemeteries
to allow her memorials to stand.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the industry, while applauding Weiss's efforts to
humanize the funeral process, think memorials are destined to get
simpler.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a part of our society that is into conspicuous
consumption, and those are probably the people who don't mind
spending $5,000 for a personalized monument,'' said Lisa Carlson,
61, executive director the Funeral Consumers Alliance and an
outspoken critic of the American funeral industry. ``But there's
another portion of the boomers who are downwardly mobile. They're
going to find their meaning maybe in splitting up the cremated
remains among the relatives or spreading them somewhere the person
enjoyed being, like on a golf course or in a river.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you remember,'' she adds, ``the baby boomers were the ones
who made us recycle. The idea of pickling the body and sticking it
in the ground doesn't seem to be a good use of our resources.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
