u l BC-CNS-WALL-STREET-HOMEL     04-04 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-WALL-STREET-HOMELESS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMELESS CENTER SURVIVES UNNOTICED NEAR WALL STREET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mp)  (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(MICHAEL CARONNA is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By MICHAEL CARONNA   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Wall Street, the strut of men and women in
business suits tells the world that they are masters of their own
universe. But few notice the 100 or so homeless men who shuffle in
and out of a nearby unmarked doorway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to keep a low profile,'' said Joan Tappen, director of
outreach at John Heuss House, a drop-in center for mentally and
physically ill homeless men.
</P>
<P>
   When community members heard a rumor that a homeless center was
coming to their neighborhood more than a decade ago, they sued to
keep it out. But John Heuss House has managed to not only open and
survive, but to turn at least one enemy into an ally.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Huber was the owner of Delmonico's restaurant in 1985 when he
first heard about plans for the center. He imagined lines of
homeless people up and down the street, panhandling and driving
away customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had seen what was going on at 42nd Street and I was really
upset,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Together with the Bowling Green Association, Huber and other
local residents formed the Coalition to Advance Lower Manhattan and
sued to keep the John Heuss House out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position was basically `not in my backyard,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But when John Heuss House won the court case, the Rev. Win
Peacock of Trinity Church, which runs the center, invited Huber and
others to help direct the center.
</P>
<P>
   The experience, Huber said, taught him that the homeless men
weren't lazy; they were sick and needed help.
</P>
<P>
   Huber now donates extra food like cannoli cream cake and
Manhattan clam chowder to John Heuss House from his latest
restaurant, Captain's Ketch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He became one of our staunchest supporters,'' Tappen said.
</P>
<P>
   Located in a former restaurant at 42 Beaver St., John Heuss
House was founded 11 years ago by Trinity Church. It now prepares
breakfast and dinner for 100 men each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a French restaurant, I think,'' Tappen said pointing to
a wall of empty wine racks behind piles of cardboard boxes.
</P>
<P>
   As she spoke, about 30 men sat in groups on steel and plastic
chairs around small, square tables in the main room. They talked
quietly and ate underneath the ceiling's bare ducts and fluorescent
lights.
</P>
<P>
   It was 4 p.m. and the men were trickling back from appointments
arranged by the center with counselors, social workers and doctors.
Snacks of macaroni and cheese, cookies and chicken were laid out on
trays.
</P>
<P>
   All of the afternoon's food had been donated from local
restaurants, but breakfast and dinner is cooked in the center's
huge stainless steel kitchen _ another holdover from the days when
it was a place of power lunches.
</P>
<P>
   Most of today's clients are bused nightly to beds at church
shelters, but some stay behind at the drop-in center, making do
with several chairs pulled together.
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Polite, 32, sleeps on chairs in the center during the day
because he works at night. The chairs are uncomfortable, he said,
but if he weren't staying under Heuss House supervision, he would
``still be all screwed up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody here knows that this place is better than anyplace
else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he suffers from drug and mental problems, Polite has
landed a part-time night job and has resumed studying to be a
registered nurse since coming to John Heuss House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been all improvement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the success stories at John Heuss House escape the notice of
the rest of New York's financial district.
</P>
<P>
   Trading assistant Mike Dugan, 30, who was sitting in front of
the New Stock Exchange on break, said that in the seven years he
had worked there he had never heard about the homeless center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very surprising. I didn't think that they would put
something like that here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A block away, Bill Crowe, a 35-year Wall Street veteran, was
also unaware of the center.
</P>
<P>
   But he said with an air of indifference, ``Nothing surprises me
in New York anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
