<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-VEGAN-SWEETS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VEGANS HAVE A SWEET TOOTH, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  (mp)  (For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired)  
(Sarah Treffinger is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By SARAH TREFFINGER   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Birthday parties. Holidays. Weddings. When it comes
to such occasions, it's hard to imagine not clearing the table to
make room for dessert. But for the ever-growing vegan population,
the usual sweets just won't do.
</P>
<P>
   Vegans, or strict vegetarians, eat no animal products
whatsoever. Not only must they stay away from dairy products, they
must avoid treats made with certain brands of white sugar, which is
often processed with bone char. And they can forget about eating
anything with gelatin in it. A contingent of vegans also eliminate
honey from their diets.
</P>
<P>
   Now bakers across the nation hoping to tap this market are
offering treats that eschew animal products _ so that vegans don't
feel left out of any special occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Allison Rivers started her own vegan bakery business in the
Seattle area nearly three years ago just because so few vegan
treats were available in mainstream stores. Rivers specializes in
cookies and brownies, but she can also be persuaded to make wedding
cakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no other product out there that meets my standards
for what I choose to eat,'' said Rivers, who was a vegetarian for
11 years before going vegan three years ago. ``Ninety percent of my
diet is organic, and most of my products are organic.''
</P>
<P>
   These options are essential, said Tiffany Refior, who lives in
Montclair, N.J., and is listed on about.com as the guide to
vegetarian cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not having a wedding cake would be a big deal for some
people,'' Refior said. ``In that sense, they would feel left out of
the tradition. So they try to find bakers who can make something
that looks like a traditional cake, but is strictly vegan.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Simmons, a vegan baker in South Euclid, Ohio, said she
can customize a wedding cake to suit vegan specifications without
compromising the taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``When non-vegans eat my vegan chocolate cake, they don't
realize there's anything different about it,'' Simmons said. ``The
vegan white cake does taste a little different than a regular white
cake because of soy milk,'' she said, but ``it still tastes very
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Another vegan baker, Leena Isac of Penfield, N.Y., has received
four orders for vegan wedding cakes since January. A vegan herself,
Isac said she understands the rationale used by many brides and
grooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people go vegan for ethical reasons, so they don't
want to serve dead animals at their wedding,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Or other holidays, for that matter. Throughout the year _ and
especially around Valentine's Day _ Pangea Vegan Products of
Bethesda, Md., sells a gourmet Belgian chocolate assortment that is
popular among vegans nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``These chocolates contain no dairy, egg albumin, honey or other
ingredients that are unsuitable for the vegan lifestyle,'' said
Shari Kalina, a spokeswoman for Pangea.
</P>
<P>
   Having that option is a good thing, said Matt Ball, the
executive director of Vegan Outreach, an advocacy group based in
Pittsburgh, Pa. But he insisted it's not the most important thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that since there have been vegetarians throughout
history, there have always been people who have sought out
non-flesh-based meals,'' Ball said. ``I enjoy making a
`traditional' meal for Thanksgiving and Christmas, using seitan'' _
wheat gluten _ ``as a substitute for flesh. But even though I enjoy
`traditional' things, I have never felt that holidays were about
any particular food or material item.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
Graduate School of Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway,
New York, N.Y. 10027.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
