<SLUG> BC-CNS-CHINESE-MUSICIAN </SLUG>
  (mp) 
 MUSICIAN BRINGS THE SOUNDS OF CHINA TO THE U.S.   (For use by New
York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as desired)  
(C.M. Lanzillotti is a master's degree candidate at the Graduate
School of Journalism at Columbia University.) 
 By C.M. LANZILLOTTI   
 c.2000 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Atop a narrow flight of steps on the third floor of a
midtown New York building is a modestly stocked Chinese souvenir
shop, managed by one of the most famous musicians China has ever
known.
</P>
<P>
   But the musician, Wei Zhang, has given up a life of fame and
fortune to fulfill his musical dream: the fusion of his ancient
traditional-sounding wind instrument with jazz and rock.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang plays the sheng, one of the oldest wind instruments in the
world and one of the most difficult to play. In China, he was a
teacher at the prestigious Jianjin Conservatory of Music and played
to audiences around the country. But he came to the United States
three years ago at the invitation of the Tung Ching Chinese Center
for the Arts in New York, and decided to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to stay and learn about Western music,'' he says, and
plans to remain in the States a few more years. ``For 20 years I've
tried to modify my music _ I'm following the new Western styles to
bring it back because that's what young people in China like.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhang learned to play the sheng, a two-foot-tall instrument
consisting of 19 pipes and 24 fingerholes, when he was 11,
encouraged by his parents to find a vocation that was safe from the
purges of the Cultural Revolution. Now 43, he is one of fewer than
100 musicians who have mastered the instrument. Its history goes
back 4,500 years, and its sound is closest to that of a flute with
many pipes.
</P>
<P>
   He has performed at Lincoln Center, Carnegie Hall and many
universities but most often at the New York Chinese Cultural
Center, where he is a member. But to support himself and his goal
of combining the Western and Chinese sounds, he works at the
souvenir shop, where Chinese tourists come not only to buy relics
of America, but to meet someone they've only heard or seen on radio
or TV. But even in China, the instrument was a rarity.
</P>
<P>
   Sook San Ho, 25, a student from Singapore who is of Chinese
descent and grew up with a familiarity of both Eastern and Western
music, had never seen the sheng before seeing Zhang play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like it before,'' she says. ``It's
bulky and fat, unlike other wind instruments. Surprisingly good
music comes out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   She says it reminds her of the ``sounds of home.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhang's audiences are still overwhelmingly Chinese, said Chan
Suey Ping, 48, who has seen Zhang play at the Chinese Cultural
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Westerners probably don't know how to appreciate this
music,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But fans say the musician must nurture his Chinese audience in
the United States and then gain interest with Americans if he is
ever going to realize his dream of fusing Eastern and Western music
and making it popular.
</P>
<P>
   Nan Wang, 43, who has seen Zhang play at Queens College, says
the key is capturing the attention of young Chinese-Americans _ who
appreciate rock 'n' roll more than traditional tunes.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang says he wants to appeal to both Chinese and Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more Americans learn about my music,'' he says, ``the more
we can understand each other, and have a strengthening of ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Westerners are still very surprised by this instrument,''
he said. ``They've never seen it before, and they find it very
strange.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: There is no charge for use of this story, but please
send a tearsheet to Professor Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service,
