<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SAYS CUBAN BOY SHOULD BE GIVEN TO FATHER ON U.S. SOIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
(js) 
 By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In anticipation of the arrival of Elian Gonzalez's father in the
United States, Vice-President Al Gore said Tuesday that the father
should get custody of his son if he declares in this country that
Elian should go back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gore said that Elian and close family members from
Cuba should be granted permanent residency status in the United
States until a legal battle is resolved over the boy's future. But
Gore said his comments Tuesday were not a change from his earlier
stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the father says on free soil that he believes that the son
should go back to Cuba with him, that of course is likely to be
determinative, but he has to be allowed to say that free of
intimidation,'' Gore said on NBC's ``Today'' show. The father, Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, should have the chance to state his position in
family court, Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore re-asserted his previous position, saying that Elian, his
father and close family members should be given permanent residency
while the issue of where the boy belongs is settled in family
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, I have said that, at heart, this is a
custody matter that should be handled in a domestic relations court
with expertise in these matters,'' Gore said in a written statement
after his ``Today'' show appearance. ``This court's guiding
objective should be the best interest of the child _ not diplomacy,
not politics, not immigration precedents.''
</P>
<P>
   Both President Clinton and Attorney General Janet Reno endorse
the boy's return to Cuba as soon as possible with his father.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the presumed Democratic presidential candidate, has been
criticized by his likely Republican opponent, Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, over his handling of the Elian issue. Bush has accused the
vice president of switching positions on the issue _ and breaking
ranks with the White House _ in order to cull favor with
Cuban-Americans, an important voting bloc in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's statements Tuesday came a day after the State Department
issued visas for Gonzalez and five other Cubans that would allow
them to fly to the United States to reunite with Elian.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Elian was discovered by fishermen in an inner-tube
off the Florida coast, one of three survivors of a capsized refugee
boat. His mother and 10 other Cubans drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was given temporary residency and placed in the care of
his great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, in Miami. But like many
Cuban-Americans whose families fled President Fidel Castro's
communist regime, Lazaro Gonzalez does not want to see Elian
returned to Cuba. He has filed an appeal with a federal court in
Atlanta to compel the Immigration and Naturalization Service to
grant the boy an asylum hearing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Federal officials resumed negotiations with Lazaro Gonzalez
Tuesday to try to persuade him to surrender Elian to the boy's
father, at least temporarily, if the father comes to retrieve him.
As a condition of the handover, the father would have to stay in
the United States through the appeals process, Maria Cardona, an
INS spokeswoman, said.
</P>
<P>
   Castro said he would allow Elian's father to come to the United
States alone if he could bring the boy back immediately, or to come
with an entourage of 27 other Cubans if they had to wait through
the appeals process. The 28 visa applications were submitted on
Monday morning to the U.S. Interests Section in Havana. Officials
granted visas to Juan Miguel Gonzalez, his second wife, their
infant son, one of Elian's favorite cousins, the boy's kindergarten
teacher and a pediatrician.
</P>
<P>
   James P. Rubin, a State Department spokesman, said on Monday
night that the other 22 applications are being reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, lawyers for the boy's Miami relatives said
that even if Elian's father came to Miami, they would not let him
take custody because of potential ``psychological harm'' to the
boy. But on Monday morning, Kendall Coffey, a lawyer for the Miami
relatives, said that his clients would like to meet with the father
to discuss the issue ``as a family.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel Gonzalez could arrive in the United States as early
as Tuesday. So far, the Cuban government has not said whether the
father will have to wait until the State Department issued the
other 22 visas. Castro's proposed entourage includes Elian's
teachers, classmates and relatives, as well as psychiatrists and
other medical personnel and a high-ranking official, Ricardo
Alarcon..
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. Interests section in Havana will be submitting a list
of questions to the Cuban government concerning these requests for
visas to determine the merits of the individual cases,'' Rubin said
in a written statement on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 1548EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
