<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: The Sabbath: Make it what you will
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ I was sitting in church Sunday morning,
listening to the sermon and feeling pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the preacher was telling us about Jesus. And I
love to hear the story, the old, old story.
</P>
<P>
   For another, my two newest grandchildren _ both boys and both
born in January _ were at church as well, to the extent that they
were in the church nursery. You got to start somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   That's an old, old story in itself. Our small folk of
grandchildren, four in all, represents the fifth generation of my
family to attend services at the First Baptist Church of Lufkin. No
use to stop now.
</P>
<P>
   But, as I said, the subject was Jesus, from the Book of John,
sixth verse, recounting how He had healed a man on the Sabbath _
``Take up your bed and walk,'' Jesus commanded _ and, as a
consequence, had raised holy hell with the Jewish leaders.
</P>
<P>
   I had heard this story before. I think I've heard them all
before. Each time, though, if I listen, I'll get a little something
different from it.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the part of how the sick would sit beside a certain
pool of water, waiting for the surface to be stirred by an angel,
the signal that the water now contained healing powers.
</P>
<P>
   That's a bit beyond my comprehension. Best that I leave it to
those who better understand miracles, forms of which still happen
even unto today, some people will tell you. I wouldn't argue
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus singled out the individual that he did because, sick as he
was, the man had no way to drag himself into the water, crowded as
the banks were with others in need of healing.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it often works. Just when it seems you have lost all
hope, suddenly, everything turns out exactly as you dreamed it
would.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe something like that has happened to you. Maybe you called
it a miracle. Maybe you were right. I wouldn't argue otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus' problem with the Jewish leaders was that He had broken
the law. The law said you didn't work on the Sabbath. Healing was
work. The law was the law.
</P>
<P>
   Here's something I learned from the sermon that I didn't know
before: That the details of the law were such that if you so much
as dug your foot into the dirt while just sitting there, otherwise
doing nothing, that was considered a form of cultivating the soil
and you were guilty of breaking the law.
</P>
<P>
   When the religious leaders confronted Jesus on a similar issue,
what He said was this: ``The Sabbath was made for man, not man for
the Sabbath.'' I wouldn't even begin to argue with that. Neither
could they, which made them even madder.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus said so many wonderful things about human rights that were
perfect not only for the times in which He lived, but for all
times.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jefferson, as you may know, so admired the philosophy of
Jesus that he whittled down his Bible so that it included only His
words and stories. But he had to keep it hidden.
</P>
<P>
   Because in the time of Thomas Jefferson, it was against the law
to alter the Bible, and you could go to jail for doing so even in
the privacy of your own home.
</P>
<P>
   We've progressed somewhat. But even in our times, my wife _ good
church woman that she is _ won't attend a movie on Sunday for
anything. That's the way she was raised, that's the way she raised
our daughters and that's likely the way they'll raise our
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that my wife allows that it's OK to watch movies on
TV in the privacy of your own home.
</P>
<P>
   If that makes sense to you, you're likely as good a church
person as she is.
</P>
<P>
   What would Jesus do? I don't think He would argue with her
either.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of The Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. Mailing address is P.O. Box
151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915; e-mail, jmurray(AT)txucom.net;
website: www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
