<HEADLINE>
COPING WITH THE MARCH OF TECHNOLOGY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My husband has 250 laserdiscs and his player has almost quit
working. Where can we find a place to order a new player, since
laserdiscs are no longer made?
</P>
<P>
   _ S.F., Mansfield, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Sight &AMP; Sound, a used-laserdisc and DVD retailer in Waltham,
Mass., sells the Pioneer DV-919, a combined laserdisc- and
DVD-player, for $799.
</P>
<P>
   For ordering information, call (781) 894-8633 or visit the Web
site www.tiac.net/users/amadeus.
</P>
<P>
   There's still a trickle of new laserdisc releases in the United
States _ Sight &AMP; Sound has received ``Bowfinger,'' ``American Pie''
``General's Daughter'' and ``South Park: Bigger, Longer, and
Uncut'' this year.
</P>
<P>
   If you're looking for a laserdisc-only player, a Sight &AMP; Sound
employee said you can usually find them in pawn shops.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the movie ``Yours, Mine and Ours'' with Lucille Ball and
Henry Fonda out on video?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.J., Everman, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: That 1968 screwball comedy is currently in print, so you
should be able to order it from Blockbuster Video and other
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Blockbuster sells it for $11.99. If it isn't currently in stock,
special orders usually take four to six weeks to be shipped to the
store.
</P>
<P>
   You also can order the film on the Web at www.blockbuster.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
