<P>
   HOUSE-ABORTION (Washington) _ The House on Wednesday is expected
to pass a ban on certain late-term abortions for the third time in
four years. And President Clinton is expected to veto the measure,
as he did in 1996 and 1997. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-MEXICO (Washington) _ A long-standing battle over water
between Texas and Mexico is prompting angry farmers from the Lone
Star State to meet here this week with lawmakers and State
Department diplomats. The Texans will urge the officials to prod
Mexico into giving drought-stricken Rio Grande farmers water that
they say the nation owes them. By AUSTIN ZALKIN.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Undated) _ The father of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez is
expected to depart for the United States seeking to claim his son.
Vice President Al Gore says the father should be allowed to take
his son home ``if the father says on free soil that he believes
that the son should go back to Cuba with him.'' By ARMANDO
VILLAFRANCA and GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BARLOW-COLUMN (Undated) _ Why are companies like Intel and Ford
giving their employees free computers? Not only is it the cheapest
way to help their employees achieve computer literacy, but the
companies will probably wind up making money from the giveaways. By
JIM BARLOW.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ On April 26 the Supreme Court will
hear a provocative case _ whether the Boy Scouts may forbid gays
from becoming troop leaders? The legal issue may be a close call.
But the moral issue is not. It is whether the Scouts should be
exempt from public policy that forbids discrimination against
minorities. Fear should not be allowed to triumph over tolerance
and civil rights. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
