<HEADLINE>
SHAD ROE REQUIRES A SOFT TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARK BITTMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shad roe is something like foie gras: rich, filling
and delicious, as long as it is' prepared gently and not
overcooked. Too often, though, it is sauteed, and for so long that
it tastes as gritty as a bag of sand.
</P>
<P>
   With such a short season, from now through May, it deserves to
be cooked carefully. Shad, the largest members of the herring
family, migrate to the rivers of the East Coast every spring. It is
a big, bony fish (filleting it properly is an increasingly rare
skill), with moist flesh that is not unlike that of salmon. But its
huge egg sacs, which come in pairs held together by a thin
membrane, are the real attraction. They are filled with millions of
eggs, which if properly cooked are creamy and rich, almost like
fine organ meat. As a bonus, the exterior membrane becomes slightly
crisp.
</P>
<P>
   Most people try to saute shad roe, a process that too often
leaves the eggs separate and grainy. My technique is not sauteing,
nor quite poaching. I use a nonstick pan and cook the roe in a
little butter, but gently, just enough to guarantee good flavor and
a nicely browned crust. The cooking time is about three minutes on
a side, just long enough to firm up the roe to the equivalent of
medium-rare. You can cut into it to check the doneness, but you can
also tell by how firm it gets.
</P>
<P>
   Like most heavy, rich foods, shad roe is best finished with
something sharp, like capers, vinegar or mustard. The recipe here
produces a fast mustard sauce, but you can use the same technique
with a tablespoon or two of capers or vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most luxury ingredients, shad roe is not all that
expensive _ $6.99 for a large pair at Citarella last week. One pair
will serve two people.
</P>
<P>
   SHAD ROE WITH MUSTARD
</P>
<P>
   Total time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 large pair shad roe, about 12 ounces
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   Minced parsley for garnish, optional.
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat an 8- or 10-inch nonstick skillet over medium heat for a
minute or two, then add the butter. When butter melts, gently lay
the shad roe in the pan and sprinkle it with salt and pepper. Cook
for about 3 minutes, or until the underside is lightly browned.
</P>
<P>
   2. Turn very gently with a large spatula, and season the cooked
side. Cook another 3 minutes or so, again until the underside is
lightly browned. By this time the roe should be firm to the touch;
if it is still soft, cover the pan and cook a minute or two longer,
cut into it to check. When done, the center will be red and the
area surrounding it pink.
</P>
<P>
   3. Remove the roe to a warm plate, and stir in the mustard and \
cup of water. Raise the heat to high and stir with a wooden spoon
until the sauce is smooth and thick. Spoon over the roe, sprinkle
with parsley if you like and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Variation: For shad roe with bacon, omit the butter and begin by
cooking 4 thick slices of good bacon over medium heat until the fat
is rendered and the bacon is done; remove the bacon and keep warm.
Cook the roe in the bacon fat, as above. Serve the roe and bacon
with lemon wedges, garnished with parsley.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
