<HEADLINE>
`BLACK AND WHITE' TACKLES N.Y. CULTURE CLASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: C  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The title of James Toback's restless drama most obviously
comments on the collision and commingling of two cultures on the
streets of New York.
</P>
<P>
   A group of white high-school kids reject the affluence of their
upper-class existence and redefine themselves by appropriating the
elements of hip-hop street culture. These uptown teens dress down
and head downtown to hang with a group of gangstas, drug dealers
and aspiring rappers, who are trying to redefine their lives in the
opposite direction, out of the streets and into the world of
businessmen, deals and lawyer-speak.
</P>
<P>
   Toback thrives on the contradictions that define these
characters, setting them off with provocative bravado and a jagged,
in-your-face style.
</P>
<P>
   His performers _ Elijah Wood and pop-singer Bijou Phillips as
the leaders of the high-school wannabes and rap producer Oli
``Power'' Grant as a gangsta-turned-impresario _ are naturals. Even
better is mighty wild card Mike Tyson playing himself, musing about
his parole, flaring up at an unwanted flirtation, and doling out
dubious, lethal advice to Grant.
</P>
<P>
   Toback seems to have just discovered this cultural phenomenon
but he manages a surprising degree of easiness in the milieu,
finding his insights not in the clash but in the mix of opposites.
The scenes are driven with an immediacy and uncertainty, as if
anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   His camera bobs and weaves like an episode of ``NYPD Blue,'' his
actors riff in improvisations and busy ensemble scenes, and he
swirls it together in impressionistic chunks a la Robert Altman.
Problem is, he's no Altman.
</P>
<P>
   Rotating around this urban core like so many satellites are a
hackneyed collection of hangers-on, traitors and unwanted
trespassers. Ben Stiller is a suspicious, self-loathing sleaze;
Allan Houston is an opportunistic college basketball star in a jam;
and Claudia Schiffer drones glib sociological theories with all the
cred of a stumbling supermodel. Brooke Shields wanders through it
all as a pushy L.A. filmmaker verbalizing Toback's themes with a
pithy running commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Where the contradictions of the urban characters are charged
with a lived-in awareness and a ``take it as it is'' attitude,
these morally compromised figures feel designed to show that there
is no ``black and white,'' only shades of gray. But they're so
contrived that Toback undercuts any street credibility he may have
earned with his jittery, sexually charged cultural mix.
</P>
<P>
   Black and White. Directed and written by James Toback. Cast:
Robert Downey Jr., Bijou Phillips, Oli ``Power'' Grant, Raekwon,
Claudia Schiffer, Brooke Shields, Ben Stiller, Mike Tyson, Elijah
Wood. Screen Gems. 100 minutes. Rated R for nudity, violence and
language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 1612EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
