<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOOTER-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLLEGE STUDENTS COLLABORATE ON A BETTER SCOOTER FOR THE INFIRM
 &HT;    440&AMP;add. For release Sunday, April 9.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Someday, frail elderly and disabled people may ride
in a motorized scooter designed by three college students.
</P>
<P>
   The trio, all students of the Rhode Island School of Design,
took on the challenge of building a better scooter three years ago.
Their unique ``PentaRay Scooter'' recently received a Gold Award
from the American Society on Aging.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the PentaRay and the dozens of other
models on the market today is its five-wheel design, for which the
students are seeking a patent.
</P>
<P>
   By using five wheels instead of the more common four or six,
their scooter has a 2-inch smaller turning radius than any scooter
now available, said Mathew(cq) L. Chin, 22, of Branford, Conn. That
means it's more maneuverable in tight spaes.
</P>
<P>
   The developers claim other advantages for their machine, which
is not yet commercially available.
</P>
<P>
   They say the PentaRay has more traction than most front-wheel
design scooters because the drive train is in the middle,
underneath the seat. That gives the scooter a greater ability to
climb steep grades, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Other unique design features include a curved front column for
more leg room, ergonomically designed throttle levers that can be
used with either the thumb or fingers, and padded thigh rests to
give the user more support and protect the legs.
</P>
<P>
   Another feature is the design of the dial that controls the
scooter's maximum speed. Most such dials turn left or right like a
radio dial and require some manual dexterity. The PentaRay uses a
wheel that can be rolled forward or backward with the palm of the
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a more intuitive position and easier to use,'' Chin said.
</P>
<P>
   Storage pouches for small items such as a wallet and keys are
provided beneath the arm-rests. The pouches replace pockets, which
are difficult for seated people to reach.
</P>
<P>
   The guiding force behind the project was 22-year-old Jonathan
Friedman of Chicago, whose father was scooter-bound since Jonathan
was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of grew up with scooters in the house and moving them
around,'' Friedman said.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman enlisted Chin and Aaron von Eigen of Baltimore when the
three were sophomores. They were able to obtain grant money, which
is available to students in the health care design field, to help
cover the $2,000 cost of the project and help pay their school
bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of opportunity in this field,'' von Eigen said,
noting that as the Baby Boomer generation ages there will be more
need for products to assist them.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Before making the first of hundreds of design drawings, the
three spent several weeks researching the market and assessing what
techniques worked and which ones they thought they could improve.
</P>
<P>
   Their goal was to make a more maneuverable and powerful scooter,
and they wanted to make it nice-looking as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to meet the psychological needs of the users, not
just the physical needs,'' Chin said, adding that people should not
``feel like they are outcasts'' because they are in a scooter.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between a wheelchair and a scooter, von Eigen
chimed in, is that ``you're in a wheelchair, you ride a scooter,''
and that manifests itself in the way the user feels about himself
or herself and the way they are treated by others.
</P>
<P>
   For their work, the students, who are graduating this spring,
earned straight A's in their design classes. Now they face an
uncertain future.
</P>
<P>
   They have been discussing the possibility of marketing the
PentaRay with several scooter manufacturers, either as a complete
unit or incorporating various features into other scooters.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the prestigious ASA award ``will get us in the door''
with scooter manufacturers, Chin said.
</P>
<P>
   If they are able to market the PentaRay, they don't expect it to
be commercially available for at least two years. They predict it
would retail for about $3,000 to $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
