<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6838 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CENSUS-STATUS-ART-NYT     04-04 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-STATUS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS DIRECTOR SAYS RESPONSE TO HEAD COUNT IS DISAPPOINTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT12 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(HLW) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Americans are mailing in their census forms at a
rate well below what federal officials had hoped for, raising
concerns that getting an accurate population count will take longer
and cost more than it should, the chief of the Census Bureau said
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The nationwide response rate, 55 percent as of Monday versus the
61 percent that the bureau had anticipated by now, is ``not a good
indicator of civic responsibility in this country,'' Dr. Kenneth
Prewitt, the census director, said at a news briefing in which he
alternated between optimism and worry, exhortation and mild
scolding.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said he still hopes for a torrent of mail in the next
few days, so that the mail-in response target of 70 percent _ 5
percentage points higher than the mail-in rate from the 1990 census
_ can be reached by mid-April.
</P>
<P>
   After that, counters will go to households that did not respond,
at a cost estimated at $35 per visit. For each percentage point
that the response rate rises, 1.2 million fewer household visits
will be needed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The success of the census is in the hands of the American
people,'' Prewitt said, calling on his countrymen to ``reverse a
long tide of civic disengagement.''
</P>
<P>
   The census of 1990, which had a mail-response rate of 65
percent, is acknowledged to have undercounted the population by
several million, and census officials dearly want to avoid a
similar failure this time.
</P>
<P>
   Federal aid to schools, money to cities for anti-poverty
programs, the locations of new roads, sewers, banks and shopping
centers _ all those and many more features of American life are
linked one way or the other with census data, Prewitt reminded a
news conference on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   So is representation in Congress. Though Prewitt did not mention
it on Monday, many population experts believe that some states
missed out in the 1990 census because of an overall undercount of
several million people. California, which has 52 seats in the House
of Representatives, might well have 53 if the last census had been
more accurate.
</P>
<P>
   As in 1990 and before, states in the South and Southwest lagged
behind the rest of the country in response rates, Prewitt said.
South Carolina had a response rate of 47 percent, for instance, and
Mississippi 46 percent. The District of Columbia had a response
rate of 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty percent of the people in Texas, New Mexico and Oklahoma
responded, and 51 percent of those in Arizona. Alaska had the
lowest response rate among the states, 42 percent, but the
Commonwealth of Puerto Rico had by far the worst record: 33
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio had the highest response rate, 62 percent, followed by
Nebraska and Iowa at 61, then Michigan and Pennsylvania at 60
percent. California, which has so much to gain, or lose, depending
on the census results, had a 57 percent response rate.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said low response rates can be explained, at least in
part, by demographics and attitudes. States that have a high
proportion of hard-to-reach rural dwellers, or in which many people
distrust the government, tend to have low response rates.
</P>
<P>
   He said much of the mistrust, ``ill-founded but
understandable,'' is in the hearts of recent immigrants, who do not
understand or simply will not believe what is true under the law:
that information gleaned by the census is not passed on to law
enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt acknowledged some dismay at recent remarks by Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas, the presumptive Republican presidential
nominee, and Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the Republican leader,
expressing concern about possible invasions of privacy in questions
on the census long form, sent to one in six households.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the long form's more personal questions, about indoor
plumbing or disabled people in a household, are vital if deserving
Americans are to get the assistance they need, the director said.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau plans a barrage of ads in the days just ahead
in regions where response has been low. Anyone who lost a form can
still get one by calling 800-471-9424, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt found some reasons for optimism in the results to date.
The bureau's electronic scanners have worked almost flawlessly in
processing more than 25 million forms, he said, and 58,000 forms
have been done on the Internet _ something almost inconceivable a
few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he urged people who are visited by census takers not to
hide or be uncooperative. ``These are not federal bureaucrats,
these are Americans,'' he said. ``Neighbors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 1614EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6839 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT &LR;      04-04 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANGUEDOC GETS ITS DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ERIC ASIMOV    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Languedoc, which curls around the southern coast of France, is a
fount of French civilization, but as a winemaking region it hasn't
gotten much respect. On maps of wine regions, it is sometimes
simply labeled ``Other.'' But now, Languedoc is gaining credit for
its assortment of interesting, well-priced red wines.
</P>
<P>
   The bad rap used to be deserved. Languedoc produces an ocean of
insipid wine, most of it destined for blending. That, in a sense,
is liberating to the current generation of Languedoc winemakers,
who are free to re-evaluate just about everything, including
feverishly experimenting with different grapes.
</P>
<P>
   The region's traditional grape, carignan, may be the most widely
planted in France, mostly because of its sturdiness and high
yields. Often it is blended with other regional favorites, like
cinsault and grenache. Today, producers are supplementing these
grapes with Rhone varieties, like syrah and mourvedre, and even
grapes from Bordeaux, like cabernet sauvignon and merlot.
</P>
<P>
   But more important than the debate over grapes has been the
improvement in grape growing and winemaking techniques.
</P>
<P>
   With more modern techniques, winemakers are even succeeding with
the old grapes, producing delightful wines, like the Domaine de
Fontareche, that are fruity and easy to enjoy. On the other end of
the spectrum are concentrated, powerful wines like Prieure de
St.-Jean de Bebian. Either way, Languedoc will never just be
``Other'' again.
</P>
<P>
   PRIEURE DE ST. JEAN DE BEBIAN, COTEAUX DU LANGUEDOC, 1996 $30 &QL; 
Fruit and tar aromas, sweet flavors, very tannic.
</P>
<P>
   CHATEAU DES ESTANILLES, FAUGERES, 1996 $25, Complex, meaty
aroma, powerful and delicious.
</P>
<P>
   DOMAINE l'AIGUELIERE, MONTPEYROUX, COTEAUX DU LANGUEDOC, 1996
$14 &QL; 
Sweet cherry and earth aromas, simple but lively.
</P>
<P>
   CHATEAU DE LASCAUX, COTEAUX DU LANGUEDOC, 1998 $10 &QL; 
Fruity and fragrant like a Beaujolais, modest and likable.
</P>
<P>
   DOMAINE DE FONTARECHE, COTEAUX DU LANGUEDOC, 1997 $17 &QL; 
Sweet aromas of roasted fruit and herbs, mouth-filling texture.
</P>
<P>
   MAS CAL DEMOURA, COTEAUX DU LANGUEDOC, 1996 $13 &QL; 
Floral aroma, tastes of herbs and spices.
</P>
<P>
   Listed in order of preference. Prices are those paid in various
Manhattan wine shops.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 1614EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6840 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-STARTREK-AZR &LR;      04-04 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARTREK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN POLICY AND THE ENTERPRISE: TV'S `STAR TREK' OFFERS CRASH
COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MIGHT HAVE MISSED THIS.  MOVING IN THE
``E'' AND ``K''
 CATEGORIES.  ALSO CHANGING SPELLING OF ``KAHN'' TO ``KHAN'') 
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To analyze U.S. foreign policy, it takes a keen intellect, years
of study and a deep understanding of international affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, you could just watch ``Star Trek''.
</P>
<P>
   For more than three decades, the popular science fiction show
