<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6850 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-STOREBOUGHT-ART-NYT &LR;      04-04 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOREBOUGHT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVORY BEGINNINGS, SWEET ENDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent as NYT7 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ We're known as the chef's secret source,'' said Judi
Arnold, co-owner of Dufour Pastry Kitchens, bakers of hors
d'oeuvres that look as if a chef made them herself. ``We never
divulge the names of our clients. If I ever told which caterers,
hotels or clubs ... .'' Arnold didn't need to finish the sentence.
</P>
<P>
   But if I were serving one of Dufour's delicious little blue corn
empanadas filled with a gently spicy mixture of black beans,
jalapenos and cilantro at one of my dinner parties, I would tell
anyone who asked. This is not 1952, when women were judged on the
lightness of their cakes and the daintiness of their canapes.
People are lucky if they have time to cook the main course.
</P>
<P>
   There's no stigma in store-bought appetizers or desserts. If it
was a choice between seeking help from a professional or not having
friends to dinner, I would opt for a little strategic help. And I
wouldn't try to hide it.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some prepared foods in New York these days are so good,
I will even boast of having bought them. Others are so unusual that
they qualify as conversation pieces at a party. A careful shopper
can find sweets and savories to fit every meal from lasagna with
garlic bread to rack of lamb with potatoes Anna.
</P>
<P>
   These days, you can even buy individual hot souffles, made with
the richest dark chocolate, sold frozen and ready to bake. They are
available either in returnable ramekins or disposable foil ones for
$8 each at William Poll, 1051 Lexington Avenue, between 74th and
75th Streets in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to take more responsibility for the dessert, try
subtly flavored licorice meringue disks that can be topped with
raspberry sorbet and garnished with whipped cream. They are $2 each
at Payard Patisserie, 1032 Lexington Avenue, between 73rd and 74th
Streets.
</P>
<P>
   The licorice arrives as a surprise aftertaste and pairs
perfectly with Payard's sorbet. You supply the whipped cream, but
please don't do as an Upper East Side hostess who said whipping
cream was too much trouble and used the stuff that comes in the
can.
</P>
<P>
   No work beyond cutting is needed with a dacquoise, layers of
meringue and creamy, buttery filling, covered with toasted almonds.
A six-inch cake is $20 at Marquet Patisserie, 15 East 12th Street,
between Fifth Avenue and University Place; order two days in
advance.
</P>
<P>
   A dessert called caffe latte is one of the few whimsical sweets
whose taste matches its good looks: the handsome coffee cup with
handle, made of chocolate and filled with light but rich espresso
mousse. Good to the last drop. Each is $6 at Black Hound, 170
Second Avenue, between 10th and 11th Streets.
</P>
<P>
   Creme brulee is not hard to make, but Bouley Bakery sells a
silken version in a round of almond pastry that would be hard to
duplicate at home. Each one is ready to eat and $5 at the bakery,
120 West Broadway, between Duane and Reade Streets.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to buy old-fashioned petits fours, the only ones I
have ever eaten whose taste is worthy of their handsome looks are
from Divine Delights in San Francisco, available by e-mail
(divinede(at)wenet.net). They are filled with truffle creams,
butter creams and fruit fillings and enrobed in white chocolate
tinted different colors. A dozen are $25.50 from (800) 443-2836 or
(415) 382-7585.
</P>
<P>
   Hors d'oeuvres don't have to have the eye-catching appeal of
desserts; they just have to be easy to eat and flavorful. Quirky is
good, too, like the world's most elegant pigs in blankets, wrapped
in phyllo from William Poll and ready to bake. You could even pair
them with Poll's intriguing bake-and-serve kataifi (shredded
phyllo) wrapped around a piquant mixture of Parmigiano-Reggiano,
Swiss, feta, goat and mozzarella. Each tray of 12 to 14 pieces is
$25.
</P>
<P>
   Just as unusual are roasted carrots and potatoes to serve at
room temperature on toothpicks. The garnishes and the cooking
elevate them beyond homemade. The carrot chunks come with slices of
preserved lemons and bits of olives, a luscious blend of sweet,
acidic and salty.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchel London Foods, 22A East 65th Street, near Madison Avenue,
sells them for $10 a pound. Then, there are the potato chunks
roasted in some of the world's most delicious cooking fat _ chicken
_ that can also be served warmed. They are $7.95 a pound at Eli's
Manhattan, 1411 Third Avenue, at 80th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Toasted wedges of paratha, Indian flatbread suffused with
fenugreek leaves, also make an easy and unusual cocktail nibble.
The heated bread even perfumes your kitchen with the scents of
India. A package of four rounds, about the size of pitas, is $2.99
at Kalustyan, 123 Lexington Avenue, between 28th and 29th Streets.
</P>
<P>
   An Italian-style alternative worlds away from American-style
pizza is the pizza bianca from Sullivan Street Bakery, 73 Sullivan
Street, between Broome and Spring Streets. The thinnest, crispest
dough, not much thicker than a cracker, is scented with rosemary or
topped with thin slices of potatoes or mushrooms. Slices about the
size of a typical pizza slice are $1 to $2 and can be cut into
smaller strips for serving.
</P>
<P>
   As for those Dufour hors d'oeuvres __ earthy wild mushrooms with
crunchy walnuts creamy mascarpone enlivened with Roquefort,
Thai-flavored Chinese cabbage with peanuts or those black beans _
the only problem is that you will want to taste one of each in
ready-to-bake phyllo, puff pastry or tarts.
</P>
<P>
   They are $8.85 to $11 a dozen at Dufour Pastry Kitchens, 25
Ninth Avenue, at West 13th Street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
