<SLUG> BC-VISA-WAIVER05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VISA-LESS ENTRY PROGRAM MAY BE MADE PERMANENT
 &HT;    BY SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The practice of allowing foreigners to enter the
United States for a short stay without a visa could become a
permanent program, a House committee voted Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, visitors from 29 countries may enter the United
States by showing only a passport or other proof of identity.
Americans may also enter those countries under similar conditions.
The 1986 law that established the program on a temporary basis, and
has been extended several times, is scheduled to expire April 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``A permanent program will be a long-term benefit to the travel
and tourism industry,'' said Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, chairman of
the subcommittee on immigration and claims and the bill's primary
sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   A country is eligible for the U.S. visa wavier program if fewer
than 3 percent of its visa applications are rejected by the State
Department annually. In addition, any country that participates in
the program must offer American travelers similar privileges.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, approved Tuesday by the full Judiciary Committee on a
voice vote, also would require all countries participating in the
program to have machine-readable passports by October 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Smith noted that the ``principal argument against a permanent
visa program has been the failure of the (Immigration and
Naturalization Service) to establish a credible system for
calculating or estimating overstay rates.
</P>
<P>
   The bill includes a number of provisions that would help the INS
keep track of arrivals and departures of foreign travelers without
visas, such as an automated entry-exit database, by October 2001.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter addressed to the Judiciary Committee chairman, Rep.
Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the Justice Department said the legislation's
deadlines were ``overly ambitious'' and asked for more time to
implement the record keeping program.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, signed by Assistant Attorney General Robert Raben,
also asked the committee to consider a provision that would allow
the attorney general to temporarily suspend a country's
participation in the wavier program for law enforcement or national
security interests.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was approved after a brief debate about alleged
discriminatory practices associated with rejecting a country's
request to participate in the program.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sheila Jackson-Lee, D-Texas, a co-sponsor of the bill, said
U.S. officials may use a form of ``profiling'' to deny visa waivers
to people from developing countries or ``countries of color.'' She
said Nigeria was an example of a country whose citizens have not
been able to obtain visa in order to visit family or attend
funerals in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This program is racially biased, and has a racist system of
determination,'' said Rep. Mel Watt, D-N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Before the final vote, the committee adopted an amendment by
Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., that would prohibit the visa wavier
refusals on the basis of race, sex, sexual orientation and
disability.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Schultz's e-mail address is sues(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
