<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAND-BOILED-COFFEE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAND TOO HOT FOR THE FEET BUT JUST RIGHT FOR COFFEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo was sent as NYT5 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Making coffee may not be rocket science, but the way
it is done at Avra, a new Greek restaurant in Midtown, it looks
like an archaeological dig in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   Stavros Aktipis, the restaurant's managing partner, is using
what was originally a baptismal font as a coffee maker. It is
filled with sand, which is heated by a burner underneath rather
than by the sun.
</P>
<P>
   A Greek copper coffeepot, a briki, which has an hourglass shape
and a long handle, is filled partway with ground coffee, water and,
often, sugar and set into the hot sand until the mixture begins to
boil, about a minute. The pot is lifted out of the sand, stirred to
settle the coffee, and embedded again in the sand. The coffee is
allowed to come to a boil twice more.
</P>
<P>
   All Greek _ and Turkish _ coffee is boiled three times to
guarantee that it will be properly thick, with ample foam, or
kaimaki, on top. But Greek coffee is not often made in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   Aktipis said he saw this theatrical coffee-making method in a
few places in Greece. He speculated that the ancient Arabs might
have made coffee this way in the desert. After all, it is believed
that they started the custom of coffee drinking as we know it. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Avra is at 141 East 48th Street; (212) 759-8550. Sand-cooked
coffee is available for $2.75 a cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
