<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES FIVE COLOR PHOTOS, ONE B&AMP;W PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   SPIN THE BAHAMA-METER: There are 30 or so inhabited islands in
the Bahamas. Which one should you choose for a vacation? We've made
it easy, with numerous island descriptions and web sites to
investigate. (Includes 2-column photo from Harbour Island, 2-column
photo from Exuma, 2-column photo from Paradise Island, 2-column
photo from Grand Bahama, 18-pica photo from Nassau, 1-column B&AMP;W
photo from Bimini.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: DESTINATIONS: Modern-art aficionados are likely to find
the Coconut Grove Bed &AMP; Breakfast near Miami especially appealing.
Not only is it in a shaded corner of a historic district, but the
turn-of-the-century home belongs to a Grove artist, Annette
Rawlings, whose work has been exhibited in museums and galleries
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS: Van Gogh lovers, take note: Museums in
Detroit, Boston and Philadelphia have found a new theme for
exploring the artist's perennially popular works: ``Van Gogh: Face
to Face,'' the first exhibition to focus on his portraits.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES FOUR COLOR PHOTOS, ONE B&AMP;W PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   PORTRAIT OF A FILM ICON: Being Burt Lancaster wasn't as easy as
it looked. According to Kate Buford's new biography, ``Burt
Lancaster: An American Life,'' there was a lot more to the movie
star once known worldwide as ``Mr. Muscles and Teeth'' than there
seemed on the surface. (Includes 2-column B&AMP;W photo of Lancaster in
``From Here to Eternity'' and 6-pica color photo of book jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: KEYES PROFILE: Daniel Keyes, author of ``Flowers for
Algernon,'' has written a book detailing the creation of his
beloved novel. (Includes 6-pica color photo of Keyes.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: NONFICTION: `HOOK': Most of Donald E. Westlake's
characters in ``The Hook'' are stereotypes, but Westlake does them
well _ and he does desperation really well. The characters are
unsympathetic, which is all right, but they lack charm, and that's
not all right. (Includes 6-pica color photo of book jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PUBLISHING NOTES: A new reissue from James Agee and Walker
Evans reaffirms the notion that everything old is new again.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: `LENNON': The government's surveillance of rocker
John Lennon as detailed in Jon Wiener's new book is a fascinating
study.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS: Author David Frum looks at the '70s and
concludes that the lives we live today are rooted in social changes
that took place in the decade that saw us eating granola, listening
to James Taylor and Jimmy Buffett and sitting in gas lines.
(Includes 1-column color photo of columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES FOUR COLOR PHOTOS, ONE COLOR ILLUSTRATION
</P>
<P>
   SITTING IN SAFETY: Too big for most child car seats and too
small for standard seat belts, children from preschoolers to
third-graders are literally being put in harm's way. According to
recent pediatric and highway safety recommendations, children who
are under 9 years old and weigh less than 80 pounds should use
either a booster seat or a ``youth'' seat when riding in a car.
Experts say that at least half of the approximately 500 children a
year who died in auto accidents from 1994 to 1998 might have
survived if they had been properly restrained. (Includes 4-column
photo of a child looking at his siblings in car seats.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HIP MOVEMENTS: Belly-dancing classes help women accept
their bodies. (Includes a 2-column photo of a woman dancing.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ANALYZING BEAUTY: Beauty combines bone structure and skin,
facial reconstructive surgeons say. (Includes a 6-pica color photo
of actor George Clooney.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEALTH &AMP; MEDIA: A new magazine is aimed at women who want
to adopt a less-is-more philosophy. (Includes a 6-pica color photo
of the cover of Real Simple magazine.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ON THE WEB: A new Web site offers valuable assistance to
nursing moms. (Includes a 6-pica illustration of a computer.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: RESEARCH: Vigilence in the lab pays off for researchers
examining stress, blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WRESTLING (Available by 5 p.m., Wed., April 5) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE WILL INCLUDE SEVERAL COLOR PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLEMANIA: A look at what might be the biggest pay-per-view
event ever. It certainly is the longest. ``WrestleMania: All Day
Long'' presents the Federation fan with 12 hours of programming
covering each and every WrestleMania right up to and including this
year's live event.
</P>
