   GRAPEVINE: News, notes, gossip from the wrestling industry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFESTYLES (Available by 2 p.m., Thu., April 6) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE WILL INCLUDE SEVERAL COLOR PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   SPRING FASHION: It's not often that the design world has the
audacity to take as many delicious risks as it has for this year's
spring season. Here are the must-have items.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: THE EYES HAVE IT: Designers have exchanged the soft,
subtle shades of winter for bold, playful eyewear colors inspired
by fresh flowers, ripe fruit and evening sunsets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NASCAR (Available by 5 p.m., Thu., April 6) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE NASCAR: LAUGH TRACKS: Now that NASCAR has gone big-time
with a megabucks television deal, stock-car racing probably will
get more serious. But participants in the sport still enjoy
laughing at themselves. ``Racing is like dark comedy,'' driver Kyle
Petty said. ``You make fun of all the serious stuff. You make fun
of wrecks, just so you don't have to think about them.''
</P>
<P>
   WITH: ON THE RISE: A look at who's hot and who's not on the
NASCAR circuit.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: MAKING HEADLINES: A summary of NASCAR's top stories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: NASCAR Q&AMP;A: An interview with a leading figure in NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: POWER INDEX: A look at some of the hottest teams going
into Sunday's Goody's 500 at Martinsville Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: DRIVER STANDINGS/WINSTON CUP
</P>
<P>
   WITH: DRIVER STANDINGS/BUSCH SERIES
</P>
<P>
   WITH: WINSTON CUP MONEY LEADERS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOCUS (Available by 5 p.m., Fri., April 7) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE WILL INCLUDE SEVERAL COLOR PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   A SEASON ON THE LAND: More flue-cured tobacco is grown in Pitt
County, N.C., than anywhere else in the nation. The culture and the
economy are rooted in tending the leaf, and in the self-reliant way
of life such labor demands. Yet as court rulings, public opinion
and pressure from Washington alter the fortunes of tobacco, change
has made its way into the fields.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TOBACCO PRIMER: In their infancy, tobacco plants look like
tiny shamrocks. As many as a million plants have taken root in the
warmth of W.C. Moore's greenhouse. The green fuzz sprouting in the
seed crates doesn't look like much, but with an average price, the
half-million pounds of leaf it will grow into could net $850,000.
</P>
