<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAGEEXPRESS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 PageExpress budget for the week of April 3, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   PageExpress, a new service from The New York Times Syndicate,
consists of paginated pages built with content from Cox Newspapers
and The New York Times News Service. The pages are easy to retrieve
from a web site. You can use them just as they are or customize any
or all of the elements _ text, fonts, photos and graphics _ to suit
your needs.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on these pages, or to view a sample, use
your web browser to visit http://nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   For the password to download and use the pages, call Bob Farnell
at The New York Times Syndicate: 800-972-3550 or e-mail him at
farnellb &LR; nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Unless otherwise noted, pages are available after 2 p.m. Tue.,
April 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOOD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES THREE COLOR PHOTOS, THREE COLOR ILLUSTRATIONS
</P>
<P>
   VIVA LAS VEGANS: Welcome to the world of the vegans (pronounced
VEE-guns), the most hard-core of the various types of vegetarians.
They choose to free their dinner plates of animal products for a
variety of reasons: health, environmental, ethical. But, in taking
their stand, they make changes in their dining-out and grocery
selections. (Includes 5-column illustration showing three vegans
standing alongside several stalks of asparagus, 2-column
illustration of a vegan holding a carrot, 2-column illlustration of
a vegan relaxing on broccoli, 1-column photo of convenience foods
for Vegans.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: VEGAN COOKING TIPS
</P>
<P>
   WITH: MANY DIFFERENT KINDS OF VEGETARIANS
</P>
<P>
   WITH: NUTRITIONAL CONCERNS FOR VEGANS
</P>
<P>
   WITH: RECIPES: Recipes for TVP Tacos, No-Egg French Toast, Curry
Tofu with Cashews and Seitan Bordelaise.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: FOOD BRIEFS: Quisp is back, if you're willing to go online
to get it. (Includes a 6-pica photo of Quisp cereal.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: IN PRINT: A new book on cheese says Americans have caught
up to their European counterparts in the production of the dairy
product. (Includes 6-pica photo of book jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHEELS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES THREE COLOR PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   2001 FORD EXPLORER SPORT TRAC: Just when it seemed automakers
had filled every available niche in the pickup and sport-utility
vehicle classes, here comes Ford with exactly what you didn't know
you needed: the half-SUV, half-truck Explorer Sport Trac. It's got
the cabin of a Ford Explorer and a truncated cargo cage. (Includes
4-column photo of the 2001 Ford Explorer Sport Trac, 18-pica photo
of the Sport Trac's interior.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AT A GLANCE: Fact box previewing the 2001 Ford Explorer
two-wheel-drive Sport Trac.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: THE MECHANIC: As the escalating price of fuel continues to
chisel its way deeper into our wallets, the natural reaction of
many motorists is to find the cheapest gasoline available. I still
adhere to the rule that quality fuel is the best bargain in the
long run. (Includes 1-column photo of columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES FIVE COLOR PHOTOS, ONE COLOR ILLUSTRATION
</P>
<P>
   WIRED TOWN: A high-tech community in Arizona is using a
sophisticated network to bring neighbors together. DC Ranch, with
200 homes occupied and another 6,000 slated for construction, has
made high-speed Internet connections a standard feature of the
houses it sells. (Includes 3-column photo of a man working in his
home, 1-column photo of a computer and a big-screen television.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: GAME CORNER: Because so many video games using the ``Star
Wars'' license have already been made, you'd think a game that took
three years to develop would blow us out of our collective seats.
Unfortunately, LucasArts' new ``Star Wars'' game, ``Force
Commander'' doesn't do it. (Includes 2-column photo from ``Force
Commander.'')
</P>
<P>
   WITH: E-TRAVELER: Wedding jitters? Ease your marital fears with
a trip to the Web. (Includes 2-column illustration of honeymooners
driving away with a computer hanging out of their car.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECHNOBUDDY: The smart way to buy a computer is to treat a
computer system like a stereo outfit. Today you might buy a really
good set of speakers, then replace the amplifier in a year or so,
each time getting better stuff. (Includes 1-column photo of
columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: GADGETS: Morel Ltd., an Israeli company, won an Innovation
Award at this year's Consumer Electronics Show for a
grapefruit-sized home theater satellite speaker designed to blend
with modernistic decor. (Includes a 1-column photo of a speaker
module.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES FIVE COLOR PHOTOS, ONE B&AMP;W PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   SPIN THE BAHAMA-METER: There are 30 or so inhabited islands in
the Bahamas. Which one should you choose for a vacation? We've made
it easy, with numerous island descriptions and web sites to
investigate. (Includes 2-column photo from Harbour Island, 2-column
photo from Exuma, 2-column photo from Paradise Island, 2-column
photo from Grand Bahama, 18-pica photo from Nassau, 1-column B&AMP;W
photo from Bimini.
