<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6888 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-ELLERBEE-KIDSBOOKS-TE     04-04 1515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLERBEE-KIDSBOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BOOKS FOR KIDS, ELLERBEE SENDS STRONG MESSAGE: GET REAL, AND BE
YOURSELF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALYSON WARD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Casey Smith is a world-class journalist stuck in an
11-year-old's body _ an outspoken, opinionated loudmouth who wants
to right wrongs and ask all the tough questions. Megan O'Connor is
her popular and perpetually perky classmate _ a Mary Richards of
the preteen world whose sticky sweetness hides her backbone of
steel. Together the two are surviving their first year of middle
school, reviving the defunct-since-the-'80s school newspaper and
learning to get along with each other and their quirky newspaper
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Casey and Megan aren't real _ they're products of the
imaginative mind of world-class journalist Linda Ellerbee, and the
lead characters in her new series of novels for 8- to 12-year-olds
titled ``Get Real.'' Ellerbee, 55, whose life has taken some
unexpected turns from outspoken TV journalist to broadcast anchor
to TV producer and children's news show host, has now turned her
attention to promoting a simple message for kids: You don't have to
do what other people expect you to do. Be real.
</P>
<P>
   Ellerbee certainly looks ``real'' today. She's wearing jeans, a
black pullover shirt with a zipper and red Converse hightops. It's
the casual uniform of her series' hero, an 11-year-old girl with
bigger things than fashion on her mind. Ellerbee is in town as part
of a brief promotional tour plugging her books in major U.S.
cities. She's speaking to a Fort Worth audience of businesswomen
and their daughters, who look a bit like Casey and Megan. Ellerbee
is telling the dressed-up crowd at the Fort Worth Public Library a
little about her books but more about her own life.
</P>
<P>
   Ellerbee has two grown children, a daughter and a son. One plays
in a rock band and the other is a television producer.
</P>
<P>
   When she tells people this, Ellerbee explains, ``Invariably, the
next question is, `What instrument does your son play?'''
</P>
<P>
   So what instrument does her son play?
</P>
<P>
   Ellerbee smiles. ``My son is a first-rate television producer,''
she says. ``My daughter plays lead guitar in a rock band.''
</P>
<P>
   Going against expectations _ what other people expect you to do
_ has been the story of Ellerbee's life, and now she's making it a
challenge for children. The executive producer, writer and host of
Nickelodeon's ``Nick News'' spent years surprising people in her
work as a journalist _ first as a correspondent and anchor at NBC,
later as the writer and anchor of an ABC historical series, and in
her current role as a strong and intelligent voice in children's
television. Through her company, Lucky Duck productions, Ellerbee
has also produced weighty and informative specials for children and
adults, dealing with AIDS and the environment, politics and current
events. Her award-winning work has been sometimes controversial and
almost always right on target.
</P>
<P>
   Now her work at Nick has helped to bring her to something new
again: writing a series of books about smart kids, for smart kids
ages 8-12. Through ``Nick News,'' Ellerbee has spent years talking
to children and learning what they care about. She's learned, she
says, that kids are more intelligent than most adults give them
credit for. They care about the world around them and they want to
change it, whether they're publishing a newspaper or producing TV
shows or playing in a rock band. With the ``Get Real'' book series,
Ellerbee is showing them how they can.
</P>
<P>
   The first two ``Get Real'' books arrived in stores in March. The
series shows a group of offbeat and intelligent sixth-graders
solving mysteries and putting out a school newspaper that uncovers
every bit of scandal and controversy their small Massachusetts town
can provide.
</P>
<P>
   Casey and Megan are both good role models for her preteen
readers, Ellerbee says.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both strong girl characters; they're just very
different,'' she says. ``And often when we give young girls images
or messages of what they need to be, we give them only one kind of
message, and it's almost always the `Megan' message: It's OK to be
strong as long as you dress perfect and you're appealing and
people-pleasing. I wanted to give (readers) the message that it's
really OK to be who you are _ period _ end of story.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong girl characters help build strong girl readers, Ellerbee
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to help give girls role models their own age that
they could look at them and say, `Hmm, maybe I'm in there _ maybe
part of that one is me _ maybe I'm part of this one,' '' she says.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Ellerbee found her own role models in books. When
she grew up in the 1950s, she said, girls weren't expected to have
ideas and opinions and adventures. But when she found Jo March in
``Little Women'' and Nancy Drew _ young women who were expressing
their ideas and solving mysteries and cutting off their hair _ ``It
was a way for me to see a world of possibilities,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, in a culture so different from 1950s America,
Ellerbee says girls need strong role models desperately.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that around (age) 11, little girls' self-esteem starts
to drop,'' she says. ``Up until then, they feel powerful, they feel
they have voices _ and around 11, they start getting a message: If
you use those voices you won't be popular.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the theory psychologist Mary Pipher made popular with
``Reviving Ophelia,'' a 1994 book that discusses what Pipher calls
a ``girl-poisoning,'' sexist culture that erodes girls' spirit and
sense of value as they enter adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   Ellerbee says this problem is best solved by tearing down walls
between men and women _ and boys and girls. The ``Get Real'' series
is one of her personal strikes against those walls.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven-year-old Casey and Megan are strong in different ways,
but Casey is the one with adventure in her blood. In the first
``Get Real'' book, ``Girl Reporter Blows Lid Off Town!,'' Casey
uncovers a paper mill's illegal pollution of the river that runs
through her town. In the second book _ ``Girl Reporter Sinks
School!'' _ she figures out who's been selling answers to tests at
her school, and discovers the pressures that sometimes lead
students to cheat. These stories go straight into the school
newspaper, ``Real News,'' and the students learn they have the
right to ask questions and the power to change things.
</P>
<P>
   The books are about kids working together, taking action and
learning that the world isn't black and white. They're not strictly
about girl power.
</P>
<P>
   The girl characters in the ``Get Real'' series, she says, can
provide role models for boys, too. And there are plenty of smart,
adventurous boys in the series.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the idea that books ``about'' girls are books ``for''
girls is part of the cultural problem, Ellerbee says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee you no one says to (''Harry Potter'' series
author) J.K. Rowling, `Now, are these books only for boys?' '' she
says. ``And nobody ever said it to Mark Twain, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Children's television has led the way, Ellerbee says, in showing
that stories about girls can appeal to both sexes. Shows such as
Nickelodeon's ``Clarissa Explains It All'' and ``Alex Mack,'' with
female main characters, have attracted both male and female
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Books are now making the same progress. Boys are lining up to
buy Ellerbee's ``Get Real'' series as fast as girls, she says _
``which says to me that we have come a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``God knows that we (women) have all been given books with
little boy characters, and nobody thinks a thing about the fact
that little girls read `Tom Sawyer' or `Huck Finn' or `Harry
Potter,''' she says. ``But there's always been this myth that
little boys wouldn't read books where the lead characters were
girls. We've come to a place where that's finally changing; as long
as the characters themselves are strong, and the stories are good,
little boys will read them, too.''
</P>
<P>
   When she was growing up in Houston, Ellerbee said, girls didn't
talk about careers. ``It was always about who you were going to
marry _ were you going to be the architect's wife, or the doctor's
wife or the ditch-digger's wife?'' she says. ``The idea was that
who your husband is defines who you are. Here it is the year 2000,
and we know... that much of that still exists _ that many parents
still encourage their little boys to be doctors and their daughters
to be doctors' wives.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey and Megan probably both have higher goals than simply
marrying a doctor. But although Ellerbee especially hopes girls
find inspiration in her strong girl ``Get Real'' characters, she's
writing the books for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to write stories about kids who aren't perfect, who
make mistakes, who aren't always likable but who have a passion
about something,'' Ellerbee says.
</P>
<P>
   Boys and girls _ and even world-class journalists. All doing
what you might not expect them to.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 1705EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6889 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HUMAN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     04-04 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUMAN-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HUMAN RESOURCES': A WHITE-COLLAR INNOCENT IN BLUE-COLLAR
TERRITORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review) 
(jt) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Human Resources'' begins innocently enough as the story of an
eager beaver fresh out of business school who returns from Paris to
his home in the provinces to take a white-collar job at the factory
where his father has worked for 30 years. In these opening scenes,
Frank (Jalil Lespert), the pride of his blue-collar family, is a
veritable Boy Scout: a little overconfident perhaps but also a
model son and, once he lands a job in the factory's human resources
division, a dutiful, enthusiastic employee bursting with new ideas.
</P>
<P>
   But as ``Human Resources'' goes along, it slowly and
deliberately spirals its ingenuous hero down a treacherous rabbit
hole of duplicity and corporate politics that eventually threatens
to put Frank and his father (Jean-Claude Vallod) on opposite sides
of a war between management and labor. As it burrows into its
subject, this smart, coolheaded and ultimately wrenching film,
directed by Laurent Cantet, explores class differences, corporate
behavior, labor relations and father-son strife with an unusual
depth and subtlety. The story it tells might be described as a
naive young man's unsentimental education.
</P>
<P>
   As schematic as it becomes, ``Human Resources'' never loses its
poignant human dimension. It is so beautifully acted that the cast,
especially the nonprofessional actors playing the embattled factory
workers, seems plucked from the streets of a provincial French
town. Lespert brings just enough eager-beaver unctuousness to his
part so that Frank never seems heroic. Although the movie doesn't
stridently take sides, its sympathies tilt toward the workers.
</P>
<P>
   Frank's unhappy lesson in labor relations begins when he
suggests to his bosses that the workers be polled on the
desirability of a 35-hour workweek. What better way, he imagines,
could management demonstrate to the assembly-line workers that they
have a voice in how things are done? But the tough, grizzled union
representative, Amoux (Danielle Melador), immediately smells a rat.
Frank is devastated when the results of the survey become a
justification for more layoffs. When he discovers that his own
father is on the list of those to be dismissed, he is faced with
excruciating choices. His wildly impulsive responses only compound
the trouble.
</P>
<P>
   As anguished as ``Human Resources'' becomes, it is wise in the
ways of the workplace, and the movie could be read as a cautionary
primer for those entering the labor force. Frank is so eager to
prove himself that he initially ignores the chain of command and
steps on a few toes. He also learns that his relationship with his
friends on the assembly line is compromised by his new status, and
he finds himself resented and feared.
</P>
<P>
   Pathetically susceptible to the flattery and manipulation of his
boss (Lucien Longueville), he also learns you can't be on both
sides of a labor war. But his most painful lessons have to do with
being the son of a man who sacrificed to send him through college
so that he could become a white-collar manager and in effect the
enemy. The crowning irony of Frank's ``success'' is that it
alienates him from the father who made it possible. The movie's
dramatic climax is a father-son confrontation of stunning cruelty.
Although the movie stops short of outright tragedy, it is suffused
with a grief born of rifts that may never be mended.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HUMAN RESOURCES'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Laurent Cantet; written (in French, with English
subtitles) by Cantet with Gilles Marchand; directors of
photography, Matthieu Poirot Delpech and Claire Caroff; edited by
Robin Campillo; art director, Romain Denis; produced by Caroline
Benjo and Carole Scotta. Running time: 100 minutes. This film is
not rated.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Jalil Lespert (Frank), Jean-Claude Vallod (Father),
Chantal Barre (Mother), Veronique de Pandelaere (Sylvie), Michel
Begnez (Olivier), Lucien Longueville (Boss) and Amoux (Danielle
Melador).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 1706EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6891 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER05-COX     04-04 1983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Gore and Cuban boy
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore said Tuesday that Elian Gonzalez's father should be
allowed to take his son home ``if the father says on free soil that
he believes the son should go back to Cuba with him.'' Gore also
said a family court should be involved. In doing so, Gore denied
that he changed course last week when he broke with the
administration by saying the 6-year-old should be allowed to remain
in the United States with permanent residency status while his
custody case is heard in family court.
</P>
<P>
   A BUS WITHOUT THE `STRAIGHT TALK' LOGO
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a month after giving up his presidential effort, John
McCain was back on a campaign bus Tuesday urging New Yorkers to
elect his ``soul mate,'' Rudy Giuliani, to help reform big-money
politics. In Giuliani, ``I think I will have a staunch and strong
ally in the United States Senate for campaign finance reform,''
McCain told a town hall meeting of more than 100 people at an
American Legion post in Northport. Giuliani agreed with McCain on
campaign funding, even though Giuliani aims to raise $20 million,
some of it in soft donations, in his battle against Hillary Rodham
Clinton. ``I have to be competitive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   THE `MOTHERHOOD PENALTY'
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore said Tuesday that he would make Social Security more
fair for women who take time off from work to raise children. The
current Social Security formula is based on average earnings over
35 years of work. Because millions of women take several years to
raise their children, the typical woman works 27 years. Those years
raising children do not count toward Social Security earnings,
effectively creating a ``motherhood penalty.'' Gore said his
proposal would allow parents to take credit for up to five years of
earnings if they take that time to raise children. That would
increase Social Security benefits for those women by about $600 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   SOFT MONEY IN NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   Two watchdog groups, Common Cause and Democracy 21, filed a
complaint Tuesday with the Federal Election Commission charging
that special accounts established by the political parties to
benefit Democrat Hillary Rodham Clinton and Republican Rudy
Giuliani are illegal. The complaint targets accounts set up by the
Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee and the National
Republican Senatorial Committee to accept unlimited soft money
contributions from unions, corporations and individuals who are not
permitted to give directly to individual campaigns. The Democrats
said the accounts have been used in Senate elections for years. The
Republican committee did return calls from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   SPARE THE ROD
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning at a high school near Philadelphia on Tuesday,
George W. Bush promised to work for local control of education and
for a ``teacher protection'' law barring lawsuits against teachers
or principals who enforce reasonable discipline. ``I don't want to
be the federal superintendent of schools,'' he told a group of
teachers, parents, school administrators and student and community
leaders. ``I trust local people to make the right decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   BIG PROFIT FOR NONPROFIT
</P>
<P>
   A nonprofit group allied with the House Majority Whip Tom DeLay
(R-Texas) raised $1.3 million in 1998 from five donors, including
one that contributed $1 million, according to an investigation by
the Capitol Hill newspaper Roll Call and the Washington Post. Under
the tax code, the Virginia-based group, U.S. Family Network, run by
Robert Mills, a former campaign manager for DeLay, need not
publicly disclose the names of donors, though their contributions
are not tax-deductible. Public records show the group has lobbied
Congress for four years on issues such as school prayer, although
Roll Call reported that U.S. Family Network officials did not
formally register as lobbyists until February.
</P>
<P>
   DELAYED CRITICISM
</P>
<P>
   Roll Call also revealed some unsavory spending habits of the
U.S. Family Network, the right-leaning nonprofit group with close
ties to House Majority Whip Tom DeLay (R-Texas). Expenses shown on
the group's 1997 and 1998 tax forms include more than $100,000 in
salaries for former DeLay staffers and their families, as well as
$149,000 for a 15-year lease on an unspecified stadium skybox.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL TRAVEL RULED OUT
</P>
<P>
   The Fox News Channel reported that the Bush campaign has decided
for now that there will be no foreign travel for George W. There
were discussions about going to Europe, then to Latin America,
according to Fox. But, ``campaign advisers have decided that such a
trip might only call attention to the governor's lack of foreign
policy experience,'' Fox said. The cable channel also said that
Bush has stopped chatting off the record with reporters on the
campaign plane.
</P>
<P>
   PLENTY OF PENNSYLVANIA
</P>
<P>
   Six Pennsylvania Democrats are competing Tuesday for the chance
to challenge Republican Sen. Rick Santorum in November. But the
primary winner can expect an uphill battle in the fall: No Democrat
has won a full six-year Senate term in Pennsylvania in 38 years.
The primary was too close to call among Rep. Ron Klink, former
state Labor Secretary Thomas Foley and state Sen. Allyson Schwartz.
The three others failed to register beyond single digits in any
poll. Santorum had no competition on the Republican side.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL DIVIDE, DONATION DIVIDE
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore talked in Atlanta about getting technology into the
hands of those who can't afford it, then turned to fund-raising
among those who can afford it. ``Computers and an Internet hookup
are as vital to education in this century as a blackboard and chalk
were in the last generation,'' Gore told students and civil rights
group members at Morehouse College. But Cox Newspapers' Kathey
Pruitt reported that it was definitely the ``haves,'' not the
``have-nots,'' who spent the latter part of the evening with Gore.
He participated in a Democratic National Committee fund-raiser at a
home in Atlanta's fashionable Buckhead section, where the going
rate for entry was $100,000 a couple. The event was expected to
raise up to $2 million for the DNC.
</P>
<P>
   MAYBE THEY SHOULD COPYRIGHT THEIR SPEECHES?
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing a phrase George W. Bush, used a week ago, Al Gore said
in his Morehouse College speech in Atlanta on Monday that Americans
should consider bad schools a ``national emergency'' _ and insisted
he was the first to use the phrase. ``We need to treat the
existence of failing schools as a national emergency. I used that
phrase a year ago.'' Gore reiterated his promise to have every
classroom and library linked to the Internet by the end of his
first term. He also supports funding for computer-equipped
technology centers in poor communities.
</P>
<P>
   GIVE TILL IT HURTS?
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush and wife Laura donated $334,000 to charity in
1998, the same year he sold his interest in the Texas Rangers
baseball team. Al Gore and wife Tipper gave away a little more than
$15,000 in 1998, but it was a larger share of their taxable income.
The Gores' contributions amounted to almost 7 percent of their 1998
taxable income of about $224,000, while the Bushes' donations
represented just under 2 percent of their taxable income of $18.4
million. Bush got more than $14 million when he sold his interest
in the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   A WIN, A LOSS AND A TIE
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore had a double-digit lead over George W. Bush in a new New
York poll, while Bush had the advantage over Gore in a survey taken
in traditionally Republican Indiana. The two were tied in a new
poll that came out in Wisconsin. In New York: Marist College's
Institute for Public Opinion (4 percentage point error margin),
Gore up 49 percent to 38 percent. In Indiana: Indiana University
Center for Survey Research (4.5 percentage point error margin),
Bush up 54 percent to 36 percent. In Wisconsin: St. Norbert College
poll (4 percentage point margin error), 46 percent apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ONE-SIDED ETHNIC POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Democratic senatorial candidate Jon Corzine accused a
spurned would-be campaign worker of trying to blackmail him by
threatening to go public with more ``dirt'' about supposed slurs
against Italian-Americans. Meanwhile, Sen. Robert Torricelli
appeared with Corzine in Newark and made it clear he supports
Corzine over ex-Gov. Jim Florio. Corzine, of Italian extraction
himself, apologized last week for making joking remarks about
cement shoes to an Italian-American contractor. Corzine said the
threats came from Michael Cino, a co-chairman of an
Italian-American Democratic club who had sought a job with the
Corzine campaign for several months.
</P>
<P>
   A RIDGE TOO FAR
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman stood mute last week as George
W. Bush answered a question about whether she could be his running
mate. But Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge, when couldn't stop talking
about not talking when Bush was asked the same thing about him: ``I
just say this with great respect. First of all, it is the
governor's call, pure and simple, and the last thing in that very
important process he needs is other elected officials running
around saying, `Hey, I got a call, I got a call, I'm on the list.'
Secondly, it's not fair to the individuals, it won't be fair to the
person that the governor ultimately selects, so I'm just going to
lay it all out: I'm never going to tell you,'' Ridge added.
</P>
<P>
   HERE COMES THAT CONSPIRACY AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton said Rudy Giuliani is tapping into a
network of right-wing, non-New Yorkers to help pile up his
fund-raising lead in their Senate contest. ``He is playing on their
fears and sending out these direct-mail requests,'' said Clinton,
who has raised $12 million to Giuliani's $19 million. Giuliani's
fund-raising letters are ``more in line with the right wing of
America than the mainstream of New Yorkers,'' she said. Giuliani
campaign manager Bruce Teitelbaum responded: ``Mrs. Clinton is
obviously disappointed in her campaign and its ability to attract
more support, so now she's reverting to that old Clinton ruse of
blaming the vast right-wing conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ADVANTAGE TO THE UN-TERM-LIMITED
</P>
<P>
   Why would someone like Elaine Bloom, who has been a fixture in
the Florida House of Representatives, an outspoken Democrat who has
served at various times as deputy majority leader, speaker pro tem,
and chair of the health and tourism committees, give that up to run
an uphill campaign against popular 10-term Republican Rep. E. Clay
Shaw Jr.? Two words: term limits. In the early 1990s, 18 states
placed a limit in the early 1990s on the number of years that
legislators and many other state officials could serve. So
situations like Bloom's are a consequence that few of the advocates
foresaw when the term-limit measures were enacted.
</P>
<P>
   REMEMBER ASBESTOS?
</P>
<P>
   Asbestos legislation in Congress is the latest subject to find
its way into issue advertising in this year's campaigns. In
Minnesota, a coalition of labor, environmental and consumer groups,
along with trial lawyers, is behind a TV ad against Republican Sen.
Rod Grams. Grams co-sponsored a bill to set up a system to screen
asbestos victims and essentially allow only the seriously injured
to be compensated. The ad flashes a 1964 photo of Minneapolis plant
workers, a dozen of whom have since died from asbestos-related
disease, and accuses Grams of ``pushing legislation to let the
asbestos companies off the hook.'' Grams campaign manager Pat Fiske
would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from Cox staff and wire reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
