<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6892 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-CONGRESS05-     04-04 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-CONGRESS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCAIN PLANS MICROSOFT HEARINGS
 &HT;    With MICROSOFT. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate Commerce Committee Chairman John McCain and
other lawmakers called Tuesday for congressional hearings on the
Justice Department's antitrust case against Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is the role of Congress to assess two things,''
McCain, R-Ariz., said on NBC's ``Today'' show one day after U.S.
District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson ruled that Microsoft
broke federal antitrust laws. ``One, the impact on the consumer of
such action that might have to be taken on the part of Microsoft;
and, two, what is the impact on this incredible engine that's
driving America's economy?''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., a member of the Commerce Committee,
said he believed Congress should hold hearings to learn more about
Microsoft, but not to prepare for legislative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's legitimate to look into anything that impacts the public
to this extent,'' Cleland said. ``But I would want to keep the
hearings more in the realm of informational, because it's ticklish
for Congress to get involved with a subject that is in the process
of litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the case for now is being decided in the courts and in
private talks among litigants, several Republican lawmakers seemed
eager to get involved as advisers to Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Richard Armey of Texas urged Microsoft to
appeal the ruling because ``the government's case stands on the
shifting sands of a rapidly changing marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., said in a statement that the Justice
Department ``clearly wishes to destroy the world's most successful
software company.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Linder, R- Ga., agreed with that assessment and added
that Congress may eventually take action. ``I am afraid that this
ruling might ultimately necessitate congressional action to clarify
antitrust laws,'' he said. ``This may be the only way to curb the
excesses of the Justice Department's destructive barrage of
regulations. ``
</P>
<P>
   But reaction to the Microsoft ruling was not entirely along
partisan lines. For example, Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin
Hatch, R-Utah, a Microsoft critic, also promised hearings and said
in a statement that he ``was surprised that Microsoft did not heed
the advice of so many to seize the opportunity to admit to its
wrongdoings, recognize that the law does apply to Microsoft, and
put its past behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats were more inclined to support the Justice
Department, they were not united. Among the Democrats most
disappointed by the court's ruling was Sen. Patty Murray, who
represents Microsoft's home state of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, she said that ``if upheld, this ruling will
throw a wrench in the gears of competition.'' Murray added that
Microsoft ``will prevail because the government's attorneys have
not convincingly proven the case that Microsoft's actions harmed
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the presumed Republican
presidential nominee, refused to comment on Microsoft, saying, ``I
do not think it's appropriate to discuss the specifics of a matter
that is pending before the court.''
</P>
<P>
   His Democratic counterpart, Vice President Al Gore, issued no
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
