<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6894 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SERVING-SOUP-ART-2TAK     04-04 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERVING-SOUP-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUP MAGIC AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent as NYT2 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 (Dining)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The first course arrives like a spring still life, a
shallow white bowl containing a tangle of pea shoots and mint and
an artful scattering of fresh peas. Then the waiter appears,
bearing a shining copper saucepan filled with a hot, clear broth.
He gently pours it over the vegetables, and before your eyes the
dish comes to life: so fragrant, limpid and beautiful that it
hardly deserves such an ordinary name.
</P>
<P>
   Pea soup.
</P>
<P>
   It is a striking and unexpected beginning to a meal, and it owes
everything to a simple trick of presentation: a two-step process
that elevates the first course from commonplace to nearly haute
cuisine. Unlike many pleasures of restaurant dining, the technique
is perfect for entertaining at home.
</P>
<P>
   The garnishes can be arranged on the plates hours ahead, the
soup served hot at the table from a tureen or a pitcher, without
the risk of sloshing over a shallow rim on the way to the dining
room.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants everywhere are serving soup this way. In Manhattan,
Quince, Sea Grill, Cello, Palladin, Jean Georges and Thalia are
just a few of them. But no one is certain where the style
originated. Eberhard Muller, the chef and an owner of Lutece, said
he first saw it in Paris, possibly at L'Archestrate, a Michelin
three-star restaurant, which was owned by Alain Senderens.
</P>
<P>
   That was in the 1970s, when nouvelle cuisine was coming into
vogue, and classic tableside service from rolling carts was
replaced by dishes artfully placed on oversize dinnerware in the
kitchen. A few chefs like Senderens began putting only the garnish
in the dish, which was topped with a ladleful of soup at the table.
</P>
<P>
   Some Japanese chefs, like Tadashi Ono of Sono and Nao Sugiyama
of Sugiyama, have also become devotees of this style, but Ono said
it is not really Japanese. ``I learned it in France,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Lutece last winter, Muller's waiters spooned cauliflower
cream over a hillock of tiny cauliflower buds, glistening with
osetra caviar. At the Sea Grill in Rockefeller Center, diners who
order asparagus soup this spring are presented with a large bowl
laid out with a precious mound of sauteed morels, ramps, fava beans
and asparagus tips. Then a verdant asparagus puree is poured in.
Either dish would work beautifully at home.
</P>
<P>
   A little trickier is what Michael Otsuka has devised at Thalia:
a consomme of fresh tuna, ladled over slivers of raw tuna with
crisp Japanese vegetables. The broth cooks the fish no more than it
needs, which is perhaps better than if the entire dish had been
finished in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   But the presentation is less about efficiency than theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can present something pretty, almost festive, instead of a
plain white bowl, and it grabs the diner's attention, making it a
special occasion,'' said Morgen Jacobson, the chef at Quince. In
addition to clear pea soups, he also serves a silky Japanese
pumpkin soup over a green apple and salmon garnish.
</P>
<P>
   At a dinner party, the main advantage, apart from the visual
effect, is that soup can always be prepared in advance, often days
or weeks before, if there is space in the freezer. And the
garnishes can be arranged hours before company arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Something as simple as good homemade chicken soup can be ladled
over garnishes like slivers of avocado and pieces of crab meat
seasoned with lime juice and cilantro or over hedgehog mushrooms
and roasted garlic with bits of crackling pancetta. The soup is
greater than the sum of its parts.
</P>
<P>
   A mushroom or beef consomme or a gossamer vegetable puree,
zapped Thai-style, with lemon grass, ginger, lime and a splash of
chili oil, can be ladled over small shrimp seasoned with cilantro
and basil. Chili, garlic and bold herbs can always be used to
season the garnishes because the soup will dilute their impact.
</P>
<P>
   Because the garnishes are spare, no more than a tablespoon or
two for each guest, it is possible to indulge and add a few sauteed
morel mushrooms, shards of truffle, dicings of barely cooked fresh
foie gras or a ration of caviar. All ingredients, regardless of the
cost, should be arranged attractively in the bowls. Using shallow
soup plates will show off the garnish and guarantee that it will
not be submerged by the soup.
</P>
<P>
   ``You set up a small portion of the food and make it look
pretty, like it's ready to eat.'' Jacobson said. A little tepee can
be made of asparagus tips standing over a few plump morels, or a
rosette made of radish slices under tiny avocado cubes, with a tuft
of radish sprouts on top.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs also pay attention to textures, and many garnishes add
crunch. Try tossing in tiny croutons fried in olive oil with tender
diced mushrooms. Julienned radish, daikon, carrot, turnip or apple
can contribute a crisp note.
</P>
<P>
   Cold soups work well, too. Consider putting the diced garnish
for gazpacho in chilled bowls first, or serving dessert soup this
way, especially with ice cream as the garnish. ``If you try to put
a cold fruit soup in a bowl with some ice cream or sorbet in the
kitchen, it will melt by the time it comes to the table,'' Muller
said.
</P>
<P>
   And when it's a warm fruit soup, like the buttery pineapple rum
broth that Marc Murphy spoons over rum raisin ice cream at La
Fourchette, there's no other way. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ASPARAGUS EMULSION WITH MORELS AND FAVA BEANS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from the Sea Grill &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 45 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 pound slender to medium asparagus
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   6 small ramps, in {-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   16 medium morels, halved lengthwise and brushed clean inside
</P>
<P>
   4 pods fresh fava beans, shelled, blanched 2 minutes and peeled
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon chopped mint
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon minced chives
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced shallot
</P>
<P>
   1 small clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 sprigs fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   2{ cups chicken stock or water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flat-leaf parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh lemon juice. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Snap ends off asparagus. Remove tips, and reserve. Chop
stalks.
</P>
<P>
   2. Heat oil in skillet. Add ramps, and saute over medium-high
heat 1 minute. Add asparagus tips and morels. Saute 1{ minutes
longer. Add fava beans. Saute another minute or so. Season to taste
with salt and pepper. Add mint and chives, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. Melt butter in large saucepan. Add shallots, garlic and
rosemary, and cook over medium heat until soft but not brown, about
3 minutes. Add stock, bring to a simmer and discard rosemary. Add
chopped asparagus. Simmer 10 minutes, until asparagus is tender.
Add parsley. Transfer to blender, and puree mixture until very
smooth and frothy. Return to saucepan, add lemon juice, and season
to taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   4. To serve, place a mound of the asparagus tip and morel
mixture in each of four soup plates. Reheat puree. Serve soup
plates. At the table, ladle hot soup around each portion of
garnish.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SPRING PEA SOUP &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Quince &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2{ hours, plus chilling &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, trimmed, rinsed, halved but unpeeled
</P>
<P>
   1 head garlic, rinsed, halved horizontally but unpeeled
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   6{ cups well-seasoned chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   4 ribs celery, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   One-third pound peas, shelled, pods reserved
</P>
<P>
   3 sprigs fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   2 sprigs fresh tarragon
</P>
<P>
   Zest of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   12 sugar snap peas, cut in {-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1{ ounces fresh pea shoots (about 1 cup loosely packed)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons fresh lemon juice. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat oven to 450 degrees. Toss onion and garlic with 2
teaspoons olive oil, wrap in foil, and bake 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bring stock to simmer. Add celery and baked onion and garlic.
Simmer 25 minutes. Add half of shelled peas and the pea pods, with
2 sprigs mint, tarragon and half the lemon zest. Season to taste
with salt and pepper. Simmer, partly covered, 20 minutes. Set aside
one hour. Strain through fine strainer. Chill broth, about 4{ cups.
</P>
<P>
   3. Bring pot of well-salted water to boil. Blanch remaining peas
and sugar snaps about 2 minutes, until bright green. Drain, and
plunge in salted ice water. Drain, and dry on paper towel.
</P>
<P>
   4. Trim pea shoots to 1-inch lengths. Toss in a bowl with
blanched peas, sugar snaps, remaining lemon zest, salt, pepper, 2
teaspoons olive oil and finely slivered leaves of remaining mint
sprig. Set aside until ready to serve. Then toss again with lemon
juice.
</P>
<P>
   5. Place portion of pea and pea shoot mixture in center of each
of 6 bowls and serve. At the table, spoon cold pea broth over the
mixture, or reheat the broth and spoon hot broth over the garnish.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WARM PINEAPPLE-RUM SOUP WITH RUM RAISIN ICE CREAM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from La Fourchette &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 gold Hawaiian pineapple
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup dark brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 vanilla bean, split
</P>
<P>
   } cup dark rum
</P>
<P>
   1 pint rum raisin ice cream &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Remove crown from pineapple, quarter pineapple lengthwise,
cut off skin, and core. Dice flesh in {-inch cubes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Melt butter in a large skillet over high heat. Add the ginger
and the pineapple. Stir in the brown sugar. Cook until the sugar
melts. Add the vanilla, and continue cooking until the pineapple
starts to brown, about 10 minutes. Stir in the rum and } cup water.
Bring to a boil, and cook 2 minutes. Allow to cool 15 minutes. The
pineapple can be cooked in advance and set aside at room
temperature until serving time, then warmed briefly.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place a large scoop of ice cream in the center of six chilled
soup plates. Serve. At the table, spoon warm pineapple mixture,
with liquid, over ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   (af)
