<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6907 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SIX-NUMBERS-BOOK-REVI     04-04 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIX-NUMBERS-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JUST SIX NUMBERS': GETTING DOWN TO EARTH WITH THE ASTRONOMICAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Famous cosmology books that offer to explain the universe to the
astronomically inept like myself have always ended up disappointing
me. Stephen Hawking's ``Brief History of Time'' may have been the
least understood best seller of all time. Steven Weinberg's ``First
Three Minutes'' didn't sell as well as Hawking's book, but it
competed with it in the difficult-to-wrap-your-mind-around
sweepstakes. In light of that, I opened Martin Rees' ``Just Six
Numbers: The Deep Forces That Shape the Universe,'' another
astronomical overview for laymen, with some trepidation.
</P>
<P>
   I needn't have. Rees' book is not easy; portions of it are even
quite elusive. Still, it manages to be both a deep and an
accessible book, and it answers a lot of the questions produced by
natural wonderment.
</P>
<P>
   The main idea of ``Just Six Numbers'' is that the universe is
amazingly fine-tuned, and that if certain basic features were
mathematically just a little bit different, we wouldn't be here,
and neither would much else in the present universe. The force that
holds the atomic nucleus together _ Rees' epsilon _ is one example,
since, if it were just a bit larger or just a bit smaller, there
would be no stars. Or, if the force of gravity were only slightly
different, the universe would never have come into existence. Rees,
an English cosmologist who holds the title of astronomer royal at
Cambridge University, explains why these various numbers account
for the universe as it formed over the last 10 to 12 billion years
_ and he gives us some sense of what will happen to it in the
future (a prediction based on another of his six numbers).
</P>
<P>
   Most compelling, Rees also shows the deep and powerful
connections between ourselves and everything else, the way our
existence and the nature of the universe are part of one consistent
picture. Perhaps it is obvious to some that if the Andromeda Galaxy
weren't there, neither would we be, but to me that revelation
brought a mystical, almost spiritual frisson. We are, Rees tells
us, quite literally made of stardust. ``We cannot understand our
origins without the cosmic context,'' he writes at the beginning of
his cosmological-mathematical-philosophical rumination. If you
apply yourself at something more than a casual level to his
nontechnical, layman-friendly prose, you can pretty much understand
what he means even when the concepts get, as it were, pretty
stratospheric.
</P>
<P>
   Rees answers basic questions like this: Why could we exist only
in a very big universe? If the universe weren't something on the
order of 10 billion light years across, life on earth would be
impossible. This is because it took some 4.5 billion years for
human life to develop here on earth from the original single cell
organisms, and it took just as long for the earliest stars to have
produced the materials that make up our life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very hugeness of our universe, which seems at first to
signify how unimportant we are in the cosmic scheme, is actually
entailed by our existence!'' Rees exclaims. ``The expanse of space
is not an extravagant superfluity; it's a consequence of the
prolonged chain of events, extending back before our solar system
formed, that preceded our arrival on the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Rees then gives a capsule history of cosmic formation, showing
how the original element, hydrogen, transmuted into all of the
others, up to the biggest, most complex naturally occurring one,
uranium. ``Supernovae have created the `mix' of atoms that the
earth is made of and that are the building blocks for the intricate
chemistry of life,'' Rees writes. When they exploded, they showered
the universe with the debris that, eons later, ended up in the
gaseous swirl that, eons after that, formed the sun and the planets
of our solar system. This cosmic history explains why there is a
great deal of carbon and iron in the world but very little gold. It
is because the elements in their natural state exist in the same
proportions as they were created during the eventful life cycles of
the stars.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers that Rees introduces demonstrate the almost
fantastic concatenation of cosmic characteristics that enables us
to have come into being. Not everything here is crystal clear. The
concept of antimatter could have used a bit more explanation, for
example, and, I'm sorry to say that the theory of superstrings _
``that the various subnuclear particles are different modes of
vibration'' _ continues to elude me.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, despite several readings of the relevant passages, did I
quite understand the connection that Rees asserts between the force
that holds protons and neutrons together _ his epsilon _ which is
0.007, and the percentage of the mass of the helium atom that turns
into energy in the process of fusion, also 0.007. Perhaps a more
adept reader will have no trouble with this.
</P>
<P>
   Even I got the reason that the figure 0.007 is indispensable. If
it were stronger, protons would bind together so readily that all
the hydrogen in the universe would quickly mutate into heavier
elements, and without hydrogen the stars would be without the
nuclear energy that enabled them to create the other building
blocks of life. If it were weaker, then larger atoms would have
been unable to stay together, with the result, as Rees explains
this, that ``we would have a simple universe composed of hydrogen,
whose atom consists of one proton orbited by a single electron, and
no chemistry.''
</P>
<P>
   Near the end, Rees introduces some theological speculation. Does
the fine-tuning of the universe presuppose a universe-tuner, a
beneficent creator? His answer to that question has to do with the
possibility that there may be multiverses, separate universes that
``cooled down differently, ending up governed by different laws and
defined by different numbers.'' That is highly speculative, Rees
acknowledges, but the six numbers that he uses to describe the one
universe we can see are not speculative at all, and they have been
made accessible to ordinary intelligence by this marvelous little
book.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: `JUST SIX NUMBERS: The Deep Forces That Shape
the Universe'
</P>
<P>
   By Martin Rees
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 173 pages. Basic BooksNews Corp. $22.
</P>
<P>
   (dw)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 1732EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6909 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-RESTAURANTS-PRIVATE-R     04-04 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTAURANTS-PRIVATE-ROOMS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW IN RESTAURANTS, GRAND SECLUSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent as NYT8 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 (Dining)  
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The hostess hovered over the table, making sure her
green-bordered place cards with calligraphy were at the proper
settings. Nearby, in the glow of the fireplace, her guests mingled
over drinks.
</P>
<P>
   In the kitchen, the final touches were being put on the Chilean
sea bass that had been marinating in acacia honey and soy sauce.
When the five-course dinner was actually served, the setting and
mood had the elegance and intimacy of a Park Avenue apartment.
</P>
<P>
   But the candlelight dinner party Regine Traulsen and her
husband, William J. Diamond, gave recently was not in their home,
but in a private dining room at a restaurant, upstairs at Cello, on
the Upper East Side. Like more and more New Yorkers, the couple had
taken their entertaining to a new stage.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that private rooms were the exclusive domain of
the rich and well connected. Only a few of the best restaurants had
them _ Le Perigord, ``21,'' Le Cirque _ and they were out of reach
for the average diner.
</P>
<P>
   But today, restaurants at all levels are building private rooms
of all descriptions, from imitation manor houses, like Cello's, to
refitted bank vaults, like Vine's, in the financial district. And
New Yorkers, eager to entertain but short on time, are filling
them. Sometimes even before the restaurants have opened.
</P>
<P>
   Private dining rooms have taken on the cachet of the chef's
table in the kitchen. It's no wonder: some of the rooms are truly
remarkable. At Metrazur, the private room is perched above Grand
Central Terminal, eye-level with one of the enormous glittering
chandeliers.
</P>
<P>
   Guastavino's velvet room looks over the entire restaurant;
Lupa's private rooms are as intimate and charming as a Tuscan
farmhouse. Even older places like Le Bernardin are reconfiguring
their spaces to add them on (its new room is scheduled to open in
October).
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the novelty of the private rooms, entertaining in a
restaurant has another attraction: there's no opportunity for
guests to size up the hosts by address, decor or the contents of
the medicine cabinet. And the hosts gain all the pleasure of a
party, from setting up the guest list to planning the menu and the
wine, with none of the pain of cooking and cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike at a party in the main restaurant, the host can
control virtually every aspect _ personalized menu cards and table
settings, family linens, the selection of music and even how loud
it's played.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can live in a dungeon and entertain like you're in a
country manor,'' said Adam D. Tihany, the restaurant designer. His
firm designed Le Cirque 2000 and Jean Georges, both with private
rooms (library-like at Le Cirque, hotel-room impersonal at Jean
Georges), and just added a small private dining room to the Sea
Grill at Rockefeller Center that gives the effect of being in a
glass box.
</P>
<P>
   The three private dining rooms at Kings' Carriage House, on the
Upper East Side, a restaurant popular as a party spot, have held
lunches or dinners for Rosie O'Donnell, Leona Helmsley and Frank
McCourt as well as for brides-to-be, secretaries and investment
bankers whose names never appear in boldface.
</P>
<P>
   Like the restaurants themselves, private rooms range widely in
price. The Traulsen-Diamond dinner at Cello cost $250 a person for
food, including tip (but not wine), but other dinners in the same
room have cost $130 a person. In less elaborate restaurants, the
bill can be less than $50 a person.
</P>
<P>
   At Kings' Carriage House, where the rooms feel as if they're in
Virginia horse country, a three-course lunch _ perhaps warm
Camembert in puff pastry with lingonberry sauce, pan-seared salmon
and dark Belgian chocolate truffle cake _ is $27 a person.
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost felt like we were in a country house,'' said Cathy
Klauber Cooper, whose grandmother Lillian Klein gave a luncheon
there. ``But of course, when you stepped outside, the sound of the
taxis kind of ruined it for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Dining rooms can be booked for as few as two (at Picholine, near
Lincoln Center) or as many as 200 (at Vine, which opens next week).
The 50s modern private room at the Brasserie, in Midtown, can seat
40; Eleven Madison Park's can seat 54.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Second Avenue Deli has the Molly Picon Room in the back
that holds 50, with walls covered with pictures from the Yiddish
theater. The Tonic devotes more space to private dining than to the
main restaurant: it has three private rooms with private entrances
and bars that hold 25 to 180 each.
</P>
<P>
   David H. Koch, the oil executive, often entertains in the
private room upstairs at La Grenouille, in Midtown, even though he
and his wife, Julia, live in the apartment once owned by Jacqueline
Kennedy Onassis and have a French chef on their staff. Koch said he
actually prefers going there to going to someone's home. He said
the food was a guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   At home, he said, ``we can entertain about 12 to 20 people
comfortably and maybe 30 people if we move the living room
furniture _ but who has the energy to move the furniture?'' The
private room at La Grenouille can seat 40 and has a working
fireplace and is full of artwork.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants are happy to oblige people like Koch, at least
partly because it is so profitable. With a private dinner, if there
are choices at all, they are limited, usually two choices for the
main course and maybe one vegetarian option.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Menin, one of the owners of Vine, put it this way:
``Before the dinner, you know you're going to order 50 filets
mignons. If they don't eat it, well, they paid for it. In the
restaurant itself you never know if people are going to show up for
their reservations or how much they are going to order.'' The
restaurant also knows exactly how many waiters and bartenders to
have on duty.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If the party is too small to pay its way with the dinner bill
alone, there is often a flat fee for the room, which can easily run
into four figures.
</P>
<P>
   Vine, in an 1898 building on Broad Street, with private rooms in
bank vaults once owned by J.P. Morgan, is another restaurant with
more event space than restaurant space: six private dining rooms
totaling more than 6,000 square feet. The private rooms will have
sofas for smoking after-dinner cigars, martini and single-malt
scotch bars and a private entrance. Prices start at $120 a person,
and 40 parties are already booked, Menin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at the bottom line,'' added Menin, a former
corporate lawyer who spent several years researching the food
industry. ``For every $100 you book in catering, you should bring
$40 to the bottom line. That's so much higher than in the
restaurant business, where it's more likely that you would bring 10
to 15 percent to the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   At one time, diners would have had to book the whole restaurant
for a private party. But restaurateurs are reluctant to do that
anymore, with business booming in their main dining rooms as well.
</P>
<P>
   The owners of La Goulue, on the Upper East Side, said they had
had so many requests for private dining that their new location, in
the former Mortimer's, will include a secluded private room for 40
when the space opens, in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good restaurants have known for quite a while that there's a
good chunk of business in private dining,'' Tihany said, ``but the
question always comes up about can we find the space.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Freiser, 34, who runs an art gallery in Chelsea, booked a
room at Vine for May. He can't fit 30 people in his apartment, but
he is not looking for a homey environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be sexy to eat among safe-deposit boxes,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Booking a private dining room is also a way to get into a hot
new restaurant before it even opens. On a recent Saturday night,
Ann Dexter-Jones, a writer married to Mick Jones, the lead
guitarist of the rock group Foreigner, reserved a room at Commune,
a restaurant that opens Wednesday in the Flatiron district.
</P>
<P>
   At a dinner in honor of her sister, Rosalyn Dexter, guests dined
on tuna tartare with waffle potato chips and lime ginger dressing,
spit-roasted leg of lamb with Parmesan pudding and raspberry lime
cake, for $75 a person, including wine.
</P>
<P>
   The room was spare, with one gigantic piece of modern art
hanging behind the long rectangular table and lighting by
hand-carved Turkish candles. The 20 guests included Jones'
daughters Samantha and Charlotte Ronson, and the musician Duncan
Sheik, all shouting in conversation across the table and taking
pictures with a Leica digital camera. On the sound system, Jones
put on a new song, a compilation by her daughter and Sheik.
</P>
<P>
   For the Joneses, it was like entertaining at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Dexter-Jones said, ``isn't it nice now and again not to
have to wash up?'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Entertaining in a private room in a restaurant has its own rules
of etiquette. Here are a few: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dos for the host: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Get to the restaurant before the guests. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Greet the guests as if you were in your home, so they feel at
ease. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Take place cards. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ask the restaurant to print a menu. Include a vegetarian
option. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Take care of the bill in advance (a 20 percent tip is generally
included). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Send written invitations if you have time; otherwise just call. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don'ts for the guests: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't order a drink till asked. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't order special food. (If you don't eat meat, ask the host
if there is an alternative; if not, don't fuss.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't bark orders at the waiters. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't take your cellular phone. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't cancel _ the host still has to pay. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't move the place cards. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't take hostess gifts to the restaurant, but also don't
forget to send a thank-you note the next day, and maybe some
flowers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (af)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
