<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6911 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-UMBRELLA-SHOP-ART-     04-04 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-UMBRELLA-SHOP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST OF A DRYING BREED FOLDS UP SHOP 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By SHAILA DEWAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Maybe it will never rain again. That is probably the
only thing that could console the regular customers at what is
thought to be the city's last umbrella store, Uncle Sam Umbrellas
and Canes, which is to close next Tuesday after 134 years.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, its owner and employees say, the store has
counted presidents, performers and writers among its clientele.
Sarah Delano Roosevelt haggled over the price of canes for her son,
Franklin. Charlie Chaplin bought whangees, flexible bamboo canes.
John Steinbeck liked to stop in mornings to chat. These days,
Harrison Ford is a regular.
</P>
<P>
   In a city of walkers, Uncle Sam is for those who prefer to
strut, whether holding a $350 Brigg umbrella with a cigarette
lighter concealed in its polished Malacca handle, a bright red
umbrella built for two, or a pointy-topped pagoda. But when the
building that houses the shop, across from Carnegie Hall on West
57th Street, changed hands, the owner, Sandra Schwartz, decided the
business begun by her great-grandfather could not sustain a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't seem to care about umbrellas anymore,'' Schwartz
said. ``It's been a very dry year.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then the gray sky, feinting rain, drove a small horde of
customers into the shop. As they bought, they expressed dismay to
learn that the store would soon close for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been buying umbrellas here for 30 years,'' said John
Wilson, a coated, hatted, wingtipped Upper East Sider. ``I went to
Bloomingdale's. You can't even buy an umbrella there. Except the
folding kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gaumond, who has worked at Uncle Sam for 14 years, showed
Wilson a sturdy, shallow model. ``Sixteen ribs, that's the most
ribs an umbrella can have.'' Wilson investigated the GustBuster,
vented to prevent the wind from turning it inside out. In the end,
Wilson chose a cheaper model that opened with near-lethal force at
the touch of a button. But first he wanted to know if its ribs
could be repaired. ``It's a little too late now,'' Gaumond replied.
``We're closing next week.'' Wilson bought two.
</P>
<P>
   In a back room, another employee, Gilbert Center, makes and
repairs umbrellas. Center, 76, learned his trade in his father's
umbrella shop on the Lower East Side. When umbrellas began to be
mass-produced, the craft began to die out. ``The problem is,''
Center said, ``everything is made in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Sam was started in 1866 by a German immigrant, Adolph
Simon. He named the store for his son and Schwartz's grandfather,
Sam, who passed the store to his son, Norman. When the market for
quality umbrellas faltered, Uncle Sam stayed in business by making
props for magicians and Broadway shows. Center said he had made
umbrellas that were intended to turn inside out and one that shot
out of a gun. He made several parasols for the current run of ``The
Music Man.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed the inventory might not last until the last day. Amy
Hall, an editor for Vanity Fair, bought a silver umbrella for a
photo shoot with the hotelier Ian Schrager. After a quick browse,
she found something for herself too. It was a giraffe print with an
octagonal Lucite handle, one of Schwartz's creations from the '60s,
when she had her own line, Sandi for Uncle Sam, that was sold at
Bloomingdale's.
</P>
<P>
   Thelma Duque came in to replace a folding model she had lost. A
frequent misplacer of umbrellas, she wondered what she would do the
next time. ``I always say to myself, `I hope Uncle Sam's is still
there,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Center speculated that Uncle Sam was the last umbrella store to
survive in New York. The peculiar nature of the business, he said,
is that modern solutions won't save the store. People don't think
to buy umbrellas until they get wet. ``You don't have a walking
city, you don't have an umbrella shop,'' Center said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see it on the Internet, you say, `I'm inside, I don't need
it,''' said Henry Schwartz, Schwartz's husband. ``Malls don't work,
because it's indoors. You're the last blacksmith. There's no
question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
