<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6913 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANGLER-ARTIST-ART-2TA     04-04 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGLER-ARTIST-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PISCATORIAL BIBLIOPHILE TRANSFORMS FLY-FISHING INTO AN ART 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)   (ART ADV: Photos NYT9 and 10 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``What's that?'' Sidney A. Neff Jr. exclaimed, with
the tone of concern that a mother might express when she has just
noticed a blemish on her baby's face. Neff was peering inside
Volume III of his five-volume-and-counting ``Angling in Hibernia,''
an elaborately crafted homage to Irish trout, as the work was being
prepared for display at the American Museum of Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   A mote not quite the size of a fleck of finely ground pepper sat
on the white paper beneath 158 trout flies that seemingly floated
in a kind of shadowbox built into the back of the goatskin-wrapped
book. With a deft touch of a pinky nail, Neff _ a detail man's
detail man _ removed the contaminant.
</P>
<P>
   Neff, 61, who calls himself a piscatorial bibliophile, has taken
his personal library of rare books on fishing and, using the book
binder's art he took up 14 years ago, transformed them into desktop
fishing expeditions. By picking up one of Neff's works, the
``reader'' opens a series of doors to explore an elegantly tooled
world of trout, insects and iris-lined riverbanks, all wrought in
dyed African leathers, Japanese paper and gold.
</P>
<P>
   While he calls himself a piscatorial bibliophile, essentially a
lover of books about fishing, that fancy self-description hardly
hints at the depth of his devotion to the angling tradition and
books, or at the results of those wedded passions.
</P>
<P>
   Five dozen works from his collection, which he has vowed never
to sell or split up, are displayed in an exhibition that opened at
the natural history museum on Saturday (the first day of the
trout-fishing season in New York state) and runs until June 25. The
show then moves to the American Museum of Fly Fishing in
Manchester, Vt., and in the fall to the New York State Museum in
Albany. Some of the books are conventional volumes on fishing that
have been given new exteriors and encased in elaborate handmade
boxes; others are hardly books at all. Instead they are miniature
autobiographical museums that display mementos and photographs
accumulated by Neff in four decades of casting flies in rivers from
Ireland to the Catskills to the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Bookbinding and fly fishing are arts that require fastidiousness
and untold patience, so it is not surprising that someone like Neff
exists. Even so, he tends to astonish even the most accomplished
experts in both fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something about fly fishing that breeds obsessives,
but Sid's done things that no one else has done before,'' said Nick
Lyons, the owner of the Lyons Press, a publishing house in
Manhattan that specializes in books on angling. ``There is nobody
who has ever done individual bindings that remotely approach his.
No one has the patience or the devotion.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, Lyons added, there is the extraordinary fact that
these works _ other than an occasional museum show _ exist only to
please their creator. Years ago Lyons persuaded Neff to create a
limited edition of a dozen of so books so he could sell them to
collectors. ``The discussion went on for awhile but eventually
broke down,'' he said. ``He wouldn't even think of doing such a
thing now.''
</P>
<P>
   David Harvey, the vice president for exhibitions of the museum,
which has large collections of fishing artifacts and books, said he
was displaying Neff's work for various reasons, not all related to
natural history.
</P>
<P>
   Neff, he said, through a peculiar confluence of skills and
singlemindedness, has joined a small but distinctive class of
artists who, in isolation, have created works that resonate with a
broader audience. Among them he cites Joseph Cornell, who spent
years in a basement workshop making shadowboxes containing cutouts
of birds, metal rings and other objects _ works that now grace the
collections of most major museums of contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   Neff began fly-fishing and tying flies at the age of 15 and
bought his first 19th-century fishing book at 20. In middle age,
mainly to preserve some of the more tattered volumes in his
expanding library, he began learning how to restore, and then
altogether reconceive, books.
</P>
<P>
   He turned to bookbinding in the latter stages of a 25-year
career as a graphic designer and, with a hand and eye seasoned by
years of precision work, evolved a binding style all his own.
``He's created his own niche and vocabulary,'' Harvey said.
</P>
<P>
   In many works, he adds raised sections of leather to the outside
of the book or its box to depict objects ranging from fishing reels
to a fish itself, shaped in basswood and covered in a colorful
collage of goatskin to produce the appropriate pattern.
</P>
<P>
   The technique was originally refined by the French, Neff said.
``But,'' he added, ``I've made it into a masochistic experience.''
</P>
<P>
   When he is not on one of the several dozen fishing trips he
takes each year, Neff can be found in the studio of his century-old
house in Sewickley, Pa., where he lives with his wife, Sue, a
retired art teacher and a practitioner of origami.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His time-worn tools include a sliver of cow bone used to turn in
the edges of finely shaved goatskin as well as handmade brass
implements that are heated, touched to wet cotton to test the
temperature _ ``there is a certain sizzle that is just right,'' he
said _ then pressed into the leather to create a groove that can be
left unadorned or filled with gold or a gossamer strip of dyed
leather.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the content of the books as much as the quality of the
construction that catches the eye. Robert H. Boyle, a sports
writer, angler and book collector from the Hudson River Valley,
said that Neff had been able to inform every detail with hidden
meaning. ``There are some binders who never even bother to read the
book they're binding,'' Boyle said.
</P>
<P>
   For the box containing ``Catskill Rivers: Birthplace of American
Fly Fishing,'' by Austin M. Francis, Neff created a swirling
yin-yang image of a brook trout and brown trout.
</P>
<P>
   The design works well enough as a beautiful image of two species
found in the streams of the region, but the meaning goes deeper.
The brook trout, diving downward, is meant to depict the decline of
that species when loggers cleared the Catskills in the 19th
century, raising stream temperatures. The brown trout, leaping
upward, symbolizes how that species, imported from Europe, came to
thrive in the warmer waters.
</P>
<P>
   In many works, Neff has taken a volume with great personal
significance and surrounded it with references to his own related
experience.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most elaborate examples is the ``environment'' he
created in 1992 for a bibliography of works by and about the
English angler Izaak Walton, who wrote ``The Compleat Angler'' in
the 17th century and was one of the progenitors of piscatorial
literature. Neff's book can be reached only by opening a set of two
boxes, he said, so that the experience will be somewhat akin to
time travel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus begins the trip,'' he said, as he gently opened the
boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The outer box is decorated with a raised green leather cypher
melding Walton's initials with those of Charles Cotton, his friend
and fellow chronicler of the angling art. The cypher recalls the
initials above the doorway to the Fishing House on the River Dove,
a retreat built in 1674 in Dovedale by Cotton and used by Walton as
a base for fishing trips.
</P>
<P>
   An inner box covered with a glowing green and powder-blue
landscape shows the house in the background, wrapped by the
legendary river. In the foreground, perched on a waterlily, are
some of the insects prized by the local trout.
</P>
<P>
   Within are the bibliography itself and a folder containing
photographs from a clandestine visit that Neff made in 1968 to the
angling shrine, which is on private land. ``I had to climb a wall
to get there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A panel decorating the bibliography portrays a 17th-century
angler on the riverbank, while another portrays Neff himself in the
same pose in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   He said he wanted the work to celebrate how the river had
retained its beauty over the centuries. The only hints of the 20th
century are his sunglasses and his Land Rover, discreetly tucked
into the background and _ like everything else in the image _
outlined in gold.
</P>
<P>
   Once he finished setting up and celebrating the opening of the
show, Neff said, he was eager for just two things: to go fishing,
and to return to his workshop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got at least 10 years of books to bind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (bl)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6918 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-CUMMINGS-BIRDS05-COX     04-04 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUMMINGS-BIRDS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Try these tips to battle birds, stop mildew or find drapes
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The toughest reader questions for me to answer
are the ones that ask basically, ``Is product A better than
products B, C and D?''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is the experts are usually the manufacturers and
sellers of products A, B, C and D, and the manufacturers naturally
are biased in favor of their own products.
</P>
<P>
   I currently am trying to find reliable, unbiased opinions on
fiberglass doors, catalytic alloy water softeners and some others,
but it's slow going. If you've asked me a question and haven't
gotten a final answer, that doesn't mean I'm not still on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few questions I was able to answer:
</P>
<P>
   HITCHCOCK WAS RIGHT ABOUT `THE BIRDS'
</P>
<P>
   K.B. sent an e-mail asking how he could get rid of the birds
that try to nest under his patio eaves. It's nice to have nature
close by, but having birds trying to protect the area where you'd
like to relax outside your home is a bit too close for comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Suggestions: Holly Coovert, living-museum coordinator at the
Boonshoft Museum of Discovery, said most people don't want to
disturb a nest once the birds have laid eggs. So if you've got
birds trying to move in, you need to react quickly to keep the nest
from being fully established. If the place where the birds are
nesting is easily accessible, reach up and pull out the nesting
materials and throw them away. You'll probably have to do this
several times before the birds get the hint and move on.
</P>
<P>
   On less accessible places _ places you have to set up a ladder
to reach, for instance _ you can make one trip to the site and
place a product call Tanglefoot in the area where the birds perch.
Tanglefoot is available at home and garden stores, and it makes a
place uncomfortable for birds to land. For birds nesting under
eaves or other openings, close the hole. You can tack up netting
over the opening to keep the birds from getting in.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes artificial owls help. These decoys sold at lawn and
garden centers have big eyes, reflective surfaces and parts that
move in the breeze. They scare birds, but sometimes the birds
eventually figure out the decoys are not real, and they come back.
Loud noises also can frighten away birds. But again, sometimes
birds figure out that a loud noise is not really a threat. Also in
a city or suburban setting, loud noises might upset your neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   BLACK SPOTS MAR EXTERIOR PAINT
</P>
<P>
   P.D. said her house has been painted several times in the past
seven years, and each time a pattern of tiny black spots develops
on the white walls, ruining the look of the paint job after a
couple of years. She wants to know how to keep the walls white
without the expense of repainting so often.
</P>
<P>
   Suggestion: The problem appears to be mildew, a fungus that
grows on surfaces, including exterior paint. Mildew and mold are
common problems that can be persistent. According to my experience,
it's possible to get rid of mildew and slow down its recurrence,
but if the conditions are right it eventually returns.
</P>
<P>
   The problem-solving Web site for Benjamin Moore Paints
(www.benjaminmoore.com) says mildew discoloration is prevalent in
warm, moist exposures and can occur in most climates. Keeping the
siding dry may help, as does exposing it to regular sunlight, so
keep the nearby hedges and tree branches trimmed. Mold and mildew
spores are microscopic particles transported by the wind, and, once
the spores land on your wall, they can remain dormant until
conditions are favorable for them to grow. Mildew usually looks
similar to dirt accumulation. However, on some surfaces, as in
P.D.'s case, it might appear as dark spots or be concentrated in
clusters. To tell if it's mildew and not just dirt, drop a small
amount of bleach on the discolored surface. If mildew is present,
bleach will destroy it and lighten the spots. If discoloration is
dirt, bleach will have no effect.
</P>
<P>
   If your wall is mildewed, you must get rid of the mildew before
repainting. If you simply paint over the mildew, it will grow
through paint films rapidly, which may be P.D.'s problem. Benjamin
Moore says the only way to deal with mildew that has grown through
a coat of paint is to strip off the paint to attack the mildew
underneath. Wash all mildew-stained surfaces with a solution of 1
or 2 cups of household bleach per gallon of warm water shortly
before painting, or you can use commercial mildew-removing
chemicals. You might need to clean the wall a few times to
completely remove the discoloration. As soon as the surface is dry,
repaint the wall with mildew-resistant paint. Benjamin Moore says
multiple coats of quality paints resist mildew growth longer than
single coats. You can start with a coat of primer designed to
discourage mildew, then finish with one or more coats of paint.
Latex paints resist mildew better than oil paints in most cases. In
the years after you've painted, inspect the wall regularly and wash
it with a cleaning solution containing bleach.
</P>
<P>
   IN SEARCH OF OLD-STYLE DRAPERIES
</P>
<P>
   G.B. said a Beavercreek company installed draperies in his home
20 years ago, and he's ready to have them replaced. He'd like to
get the exact same type of drapes he bought 20 years ago, but he
couldn't get in touch with the company he worked with originally.
He wants Beauty Pleat or Springcrest draperies, a type of drape
that has pleats formed by a spring running through the fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Suggestion: The company that G.B. used 20 years ago is no longer
active, but the drapes he wanted are still available, and he's
ordering a new set from a Cincinnati company. Donna Jackson of
Donna's Drapery Workroom, a Beavercreek drapery shop, said her
company occasionally installs spring-pleated draperies. She said
the draperies come in wide panels of fabric that are folded into an
accordion pattern but not pressed. A metal spring with a wavy
pattern is inserted into the top of the drape, and the folds in the
fabric help the drape follow the pleat pattern in the spring.
Traditional pleated draperies have gathers at the top that help
pull the fabric into a pleated pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
