<HEADER>
A6924 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-MARCHES-$ADV09-COX     04-04 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARCHES-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A PARADE OF PROTESTERS WILL FILL THE CAPITAL'S SPRING WEEKENDS
 &HT;    780&AMP;add. With MARCHES-LIST. For release Sunday, April 9.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a seasonal rite as predictable as cherry
blossoms and class trips, the nation's capital is preparing for a
spring parade of parades.
</P>
<P>
   Within the coming month, the District will be besieged by labor
unionists demanding global economic justice, gay and lesbian
activists demonstrating for equal rights, environmentalists
rallying against global warming. and moms marching for gun control
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities ranging from Leonardo DiCaprio to Ellen DeGeneres to
Rosie O'Donnell will lead assemblies totaling hundreds of thousands
of supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations will begin on April 16 and 17 with the
``Mobilization for Global Justice,'' whose organizers have
threatened to shut down international meetings of the World Bank
and International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Although organizers say their blockade will be peaceful, police
are bracing for trouble, since the movement includes many of the
groups involved in last year's melee at the World Trade
Organization talks in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not allow another breakdown like that in Seattle,''
vowed D.C. Police Chief Charles Ramsey.
</P>
<P>
   The following weekend, legions of environmentalists are expected
to celebrate the 30th annual Earth Day on the Mall with a giant
science fair and a stage show hosted by DiCaprio and featuring
Carole King, Clint Black, David Crosby, Keb' Mo', James Taylor and
other entertainers.
</P>
<P>
   On April 30, the ``Millennium March on Washington for Equality''
will promote civil rights for gay, lesbian, bisexual and
transgender Americans. Although there has been bickering between
some leaders of the movement, tens of thousands of activists are
expected for the Sunday demonstration and for a Saturday night
concert featuring Melissa Etheridge, George Michael, Garth Brooks,
k.d. lang and other singers.
</P>
<P>
   The month of marches will conclude on May 14 _ Mother's Day _
with the ``Million Mom March'' demanding ``common-sense'' laws for
gun control. TV talk show host O'Donnell said she and other mothers
from across the nation will be coming to Washington ``for the
future safety of all children.''
</P>
<P>
   These crusades are clustered on the calendar, but are hardly
unexpected, said Earl Kittleman, a spokesman for the National Park
Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly used to dealing with large-scale
demonstrations,'' Kittleman said. Marches, demonstrations and
vigils have been commonplace ever since the federal government
moved to the District of Columbia in 1800, he explained. Each year,
the Park Service issues permits for about 3,000 ``public
gatherings'' on federal property in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``The location is a traditional public forum for free speech,''
Kittleman said. And in the television age, familiar public
buildings such as the White House, Capitol, Washington Monument and
Lincoln Memorial provide ``ideal backdrops'' for mass rallies.
</P>
<P>
   Weather has a significant impact on turnout and media coverage
of mass demonstrations, Kittleman noted, so spring is popular with
protesters as well as with tourists and school groups.
</P>
<P>
   Washington rallies are organized to appeal both to a group's
members and to the world at large.
</P>
<P>
   Staging these events ``is a very good means of keeping (members)
involved'' in a cause, said Lee Sigelman, chairman of the political
science department at George Washington University. ``It gives them
a chance to strut their stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, ``there's an arms race aspect to the demonstrations,''
said Sigelman, an expert in political behavior and popular culture.
Competing causes _ anti-abortion vs. abortion rights, for example _
don't want the other side to seem to be more popular, so both hold
rallies.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators come to Washington because they want to
influence Congress, the president and the federal regulatory
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to show those in power that a group or cause has
substantial support outside the Beltway,'' Sigelman explained.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of a Washington campaign is high in terms of effort but
relatively low in dollars, especially when compared to a national
television campaign. The demonstrations are traditionally held on
weekends, a good time for bringing in supporters and for attracting
media coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the demonstrations help shape national policy, such as
the 1960s marches against the Vietnam War and for civil rights laws
protecting racial minorities. Even when no governmental action
results, the demonstrations almost always focus national attention
at least momentarily on a cause, as in the Million Man March and
Promise Keepers rallies in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Size counts in mass rallies, of course, so crowd estimates are
often controversial.
</P>
<P>
   During the last decade, the National Park Service stopped
issuing such calculations after complaints by organizers.
</P>
<P>
   These counts ``were never more than estimates'' and ``were
almost always challenged,'' explained Kittleman. The agency doesn't
have the sophisticated cameras and other equipment needed to
provide accurate crowd counts, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Park Service permits are required for organized gatherings of
more than two dozen people on federal property in the District, but
organizers are not required to post bonds or otherwise financially
insure against damages. Courts have ruled that such requirements
are hindrances to free speech, Kittleman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``About the only reason a permit would be denied is if another
group had applied earlier for same site at same time,'' he said.
Since applications cannot be made more than a year in advance, some
groups apply for next year's demonstration immediately after
holding one year's event.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
