<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6927 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-RIGHTS-580&AMP;ADD     04-04 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-RIGHTS-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. OFFICIAL VISITING CHECHNYA REPORTS EVIDENCE OF ATROCITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Despite an unusually restricted tour of the ruined
Chechen capital of Grozny on Monday, the U.N. high commissioner on
human rights, Mary Robinson, said Tuesday that she had heard and
seen ``shocking'' evidence of extensive human rights atrocities by
Russian military forces in Chechnya. But she also reported a
``constructive'' ending to her trip, saying she had received a
pledge from Russian leaders to consider setting up an independent
national inquiry to investigate the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that ``there must be a day of reckoning regarding the
situation in Chechnya,'' Robinson indicated that Moscow was not
likely to end its isolation in the international community over its
brutal campaign to subdue the Northern Caucuses without purging its
own ranks of those troops and commanders found to be guilty of
atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a news conference here after touring the parts of
Chechnya, Ingushetia and Dagestan affected by the war, Robinson
said, ``I found it devastating to see Grozny, and I was very
affected by the depth of misery and distress'' there.
</P>
<P>
   In Nazran, the refugee center in Ingushetia, Robinson said she
met eye-witnesses who relayed ``truly shocking accounts'' of
summary executions, rape, looting and other attacks on civilians
during the seven-month military campaign by Russian forces. She was
told of the bodies of war victims being ransomed to families and
extortion against civilians passing through checkpoints. ``I
believe Russia and Russians have to take ownership of the
responsibility for addressing the scale of human rights
violations,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But during her tour, Robinson, the former Irish president, was
not able to visit a number of neighborhoods and villages in
Chechnya where alleged atrocities occurred. She was accompanied by
Vladimir Kalamanov, the human rights envoy to Chechnya appointed by
President-elect Vladimir Putin. On Monday, Kalamanov seemed to
clash with Robinson over issues of her itinerary. Robinson said on
Tuesday that she had ``requested to visit a number of different
detention centers'' where hundreds, perhaps thousands, of Chechens
have been held without charge. But she was only allowed to visit
one facility where two Chechen women were being held on looting
charges.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said her visit had ended on a ``very constructive''
note. In a meeting Tuesday morning with Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov, she said she had urged the Russian leadership to consider
``the importance of establishing an independent, national
commission of inquiry as a special measure that recognizes the
scale of human rights violations in Chechnya.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanov, she said, indicated that Moscow was interested in the
proposal, pledged to examine it further and also agreed to accept
further information from the U.N. Commission on Human Rights
regarding ``models'' that could be used for such an investigative
body. Ivanov formally invited Robinson to return to Russia in two
or three months.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Russia also signed an agreement Tuesday accepting the services
of human rights experts from the Council of Europe. The experts
will be assigned to Kalamonov's staff of investigators.
</P>
<P>
   With Russia facing further condemnation both in the Council of
Europe and the U.N. Human Rights Commission, which is meeting this
month in Geneva, incremental steps like those Moscow took Tuesday
may be somewhat diversionary. Since the beginning of its Chechen
campaign, Russia has rejected interventions from human rights
organizations as unwarranted interference in its ``anti-terrorist''
action. In a foreign ministry statement, Ivanov again rejected
outside interference, and he denied there had been ``systematic
human rights violations by federal forces.'' But he also said
Russia was ready to ``resolve the Chechen problem openly, in
cooperation with the international community.''
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that atrocities had been committed on both sides
of the Chechen conflict, Robinson said she hoped that rebel leaders
guilty of atrocities could be brought to justice, but emphasized
that her primary mission was to investigate the Russian
government's compliance with international human rights conventions
and laws.
</P>
<P>
   It was also conspicuous that Robinson did not meet with Putin,
though she denied that any meeting had been set and canceled.
Rather, she said her return to Moscow on Monday was delayed by fog,
leaving no opportunity for a meeting with the Russian president.
Tuesday, Putin, wearing a black arm band, attended a memorial
service in Moscow for three officers of the Federal Security
Service killed in last week's ambush in Chechnya that left 43
policemen and paramilitary servicemen dead.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson she said she hoped to see Putin when she returns.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, speaking in Geneva, backed
Robinson's call for an independent national inquiry in Russia. ``I
think she was right,'' Annan said, ``I think it is even in the
interest of the Russian government to carry out an inquiry into
these kinds of serious allegations.'' (js)
</P>
</TEXT>
