<HEADER>
A6929 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-DESIGN-COUPLE06-COX     04-04 1416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESIGN-COUPLE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Landscape-designing couple agrees, `our gardens are our
children'
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, April 6.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Hugh and Mary Palmer Dargan step into their back yard, they
see things differently.
</P>
<P>
   He pauses to scan it, smiling at how nicely the design flows
from den to pergola to garden, just as they planned it.
</P>
<P>
   She, on the other hand, zooms in for a closer look, ecstatic
that the delicate creeping Mazus she planted between pathway stones
is blooming.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh is big picture; Mary Palmer is details.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the husband-and-wife team of Atlanta landscape
architects are married to the land, consumed by plants and head
over heels in love with design. The Dargans, considered among the
country's leading historic landscape preservationists, have created
or restored hundreds of gardens from Florida to California in their
15-year partnership and Hugh's 12 years before that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our gardens are our children,'' says Hugh, a South Carolina
native. ``It's sad when their homes are sold, and you lose contact
on how they develop. It's like they grow up and move away.''
</P>
<P>
   Their passion for landscape architecture touches every aspect of
their lives. They met at a garden lecture, were married in a
garden, honeymooned while studying gardens _ and saw their
livelihoods nearly wither in the garden.
</P>
<P>
   The Dargans were working in Charleston in 1989 when Hurricane
Hugo destroyed many of the city's historic gardens. ``We had no
work in South Carolina for four months,'' Hugh recalls. ``It was an
emotional disaster for me, not to mention our clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of their ``children'' drowned in the tidal surge, were
burned by the salt water or left inundated by harbor mud. But many
of the gardens rebounded, and the demand for work followed.
</P>
<P>
   The Dargans' designs span the spectrum of garden styles, from
casual English country to formal Italianate. But they are best
known for their preservation efforts, especially during the years
they spent in Charleston before moving to Atlanta in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a candy shop of design,'' Mary Palmer (who prefers that
double Southern name) says of the city with its quaint walled
gardens. ``Every piece of stone was laid more than 200 years ago
for a specific purpose, and each has mellowed with age. The place
left an indelible impression on my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   In Charleston, they became lecturers, because teaching is as
much a part of the Dargans' work as design. They believe part of
their mission is to educate clients about how buildings and
landscapes interact.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just giving them good gardens but also an
appreciation for them,'' says Graham Pittman, a landscape architect
in their firm. ``That's where they excel.''
</P>
<P>
   Their projects and presentations have fueled celebrity images
along the Southeastern gardening circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do Charlotte,'' Hugh says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do Nashville,'' Mary Palmer says of her hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Rarely do the two join forces on one design because, as they put
it, someone has to be in charge. Yet each knows enough about the
other's projects to be able to step in in a pinch.
</P>
<P>
   When they do conspire, they insist there are no egos, no
artistic tempers, no disagreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one exception was Hugh once said we'd never work for
neighbors,'' Mary Palmer recalls. ``But I said, `Hugh, I'm already
doing three.''
</P>
<P>
   One unanimous decision was moving their business, Hugh Dargan
Associates, to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no other place like it for gardening,'' Mary Palmer
says. ``It's so deeply rooted here and at the same time, so global
in terms of so many varied interests in gardening. People from
China are coming here to see gardens. It's fascinating.''
</P>
<P>
   A niche for history
</P>
<P>
   The move was the fourth for Hugh, whose career took him from the
South Carolina town of Darlington to stops in Camden and Columbia,
where Mary Palmer joined the firm in 1985. The couple met at a
meeting of the Southern Garden History Society, an organization
Hugh help found that's dedicated to garden preservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started talking and never stopped,'' he says. ``We realized
we thought so much alike.''
</P>
<P>
   Their expertise in preservation drew them to projects in
Charleston, where they decided to marry, becoming a rare duo in
their field. Appropriately, they held the ceremony and reception in
a romantic parterre garden they had just designed on the Battery.
``From that experience, we learned to never design a garden with a
party deadline,'' Hugh recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Between projects, the Dargans taught design, often for
fund-raisers for preservation efforts. Lectures and tours _ they
estimate they've visited some 600 gardens _ are what keep their
ideas fresh.
</P>
<P>
   The Dargans spent part of their honeymoon studying landscape
restoration at the National Trust in Sussex, England. Their niche
soon earned them projects ranging from a master plan for the Earl
of Wemyss in Gloucestershire to a renovation at Brookgreen Gardens
near Murrells Inlet, S.C. Historic Preservation magazine named them
among the top four preservation landscape architects in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then Hugo hit, and our whole career was blown away. I spent
four months just holding clients' hands,'' Hugh says of the
aftermath and cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   The garden where they were married had been under 5 feet of
water. The tidal surge was so strong it bent a 1790s iron gate.
</P>
<P>
   But Charlestonians rebuilt, not only their homes but also their
prized gardens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The phone began to ring off the hook,'' Hugh says.
</P>
<P>
   Blooming in Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, architect Norman Askins invited the Dargans to work
on some of his projects.
</P>
<P>
   As the number of clients grew, the couple decided to relocate,
settling in Peachtree Heights with their three cavalier spaniels.
There, they've combined all their favorite ingredients to create
their own garden, a popular stop on tours.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, they opened an office in Buckhead, where the
staff includes seven landscape architects.
</P>
<P>
   Developing plans is only part of their day. Mary Palmer
frequently appears as a guest on HGTV shows. They're publishing a
series of design books based on their teachings. And they're
designing a line of cast-aluminum garden furniture they plan to
sell online.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes us enjoy living and working together 24 hours a day
is simple _ our love for our work,'' Hugh says.
</P>
<P>
   They make all business decisions together _ ``usually at 3 in
the morning,'' Mary Palmer says _ but each approaches work
differently.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh is more conceptual, not so concerned with the nuts and
bolts of design.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the one who fixes the lawn mower,'' his wife says. ``I
always have note pad in one hand, a tape recorder in the other, a
tape measure and survey flags falling out of my pocketbook while
schlepping about a site.'' Not to mention a cell phone that's
rarely turned off.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dargans have learned to escape the deadline demands by
hiking in the mountains of North Carolina, where they've bought a
second home in Cashiers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their diverse projects, the two are hard pressed to name
a favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great gardens are ones that photograph best,'' Mary Palmer
says. ``They are constantly changing, and if you can catch on film
their special moment, those are the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Hugh is more sentimental. ``So many memories are attached to our
gardens,'' he says. ``You remember everything that went into
creating one _ the problems, the hurricanes, the weddings.''
</P>
<P>
   And before long, they realize another child is all grown up.
</P>
<P>
   G A R D E N E R S N A P S H O T S
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Dargan
</P>
<P>
   Vitals: 51, native of Darlington, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Training: Bachelor's degree in landscape. architecture,
University of Georgia; studied historic landscape preservation with
the National Trust in England.
</P>
<P>
   Career: Founded Hugh Dargan Associates in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbies: Golf, hiking.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Palmer Dargan
</P>
<P>
   Vitals: 46, native of Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Training: Bachelor's degree in botany, master's in landscape
architecture, Louisiana State University; studied historic
landscape preservation with the National Trust in England.
</P>
<P>
   Career: Botanist and education director at Cheekwood Botanical
Gardens, Nashville; joined Hugh Dargan Associates in 1985
</P>
<P>
   Hobbies: Hiking, photography
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
