<HEADER>
A6930 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MONKS05-COX     04-04 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONKS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Troupe of monks perform for peace, harmony and to raise
awareness of Tibetan homeland
 &HT;    By Nick Tate
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They sing. They dance. They love the Hawks, ESPN, and they play
soccer in their spare time.
</P>
<P>
   But sports, TV and the arts are only a small part of the world
of the Mystic Monks of Tibet _ nine Buddhist lamas in residence at
Emory University. On loan from the famed Drepung Loseling Monastery
in India, the monks are touring the country on an unusual mission:
seeking at once to celebrate Tibet's culture and warn of its
impending disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Their two-hour performance ``The Mystical Arts of Tibet: Sacred
Music Sacred Dance for World Healing'' is at Glenn Memorial Church
tonight as part of Emory's five-day celebration of Tibetan culture.
The Mystical Arts tour has played three dozen cities in the past
six months _ from Carnegie Hall to the Hollywood Bowl _ to rave
reviews.
</P>
<P>
   But Geshe Lobsang Tenzin, director of the Drepung Loseling
Institute at Emory, said he hopes the performances do more than
introduce Americans to ancient Tibetan arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We emphasize two things in our performance,'' he said over
morning tea in the institute's sanctuary near Emory. ``Our primary
objective is to contribute to world peace and harmony, and we hope
people who come to see us will be inspired to find kindness in
their hearts and take it to a deeper level. The second thing is
that we hope people who don't know about Tibetan culture and
civilization, and its current situation, will see that Tibet is at
very edge of its extinction.''
</P>
<P>
   Tenzin, who will lead tonight's performance, said the tour will
continue through the end of the year, when eight of the monks will
return to India. From the 3,000 resident monks, eight replacements
will travel to Emory for the next tour. It's a rotation they
undertake with a mixture of joy, resignation and bittersweet
sadness _ traveling by van from town to town, attempting to rise
above the novelty-act coverage they're often given.
</P>
<P>
   Tibetan monks first brought a show to North America in 1988 to
keep Tibetan culture alive and the heat of public opinion on China,
which occupied the mountain nation in 1959, sending its leader _
the Dalai Lama _ his government and more than 100,000 Tibetans into
exile in India. The Loseling Institute at Emory, which runs the
Mystical Arts tours, was founded as the North American seat of the
monastery soon after Tenzin arrived here in 1991 to study liberal
arts. Other Tibetan monks are based in California and New York.
Today, Tenzin teaches Tibetan culture and organizes weekly programs
to teach Atlantans about Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   When they're not touring, the monks spend their days studying in
the institute's library, meeting with Atlanta visitors or
meditating in the institute's quiet sanctuary, adorned with
pictures of the Dalai Lama and vibrantly colored ``thankas'' _
tapestries depicting Tibetan virtues and values.
</P>
<P>
   The monks are also a not-uncommon sight around town _ in their
flowing burgundy-and-gold robes and close-cropped hair. ``We like
to play soccer together,'' Tenzin acknowledged with a grin. ``We're
not very good, but we have fun.'' They also take in Hawks games,
movies and shows around town. (Tenzin notes ``The Matrix'' is one
of his favorites: ``It had a very Buddhist theme,'' he says, ``the
mind creating reality.'')
</P>
<P>
   Housed in a nondescript office building on Briarcliff, the
Loseling Institute is a living museum of Tibetan culture nestled
among the tree-lined neighborhoods of northeast Atlanta. Only a
small paper sign hung on the doorway heralds its presence. Once
inside, visitors can examine pictures of the Dalai Lama's former
Tibetan home, hung like sacred art pieces on the walls, read about
the historic struggles of the nation's people, finger Buddhist
prayer beads called ``malas'' or meditate in the shrine, where the
monks chant and lead teachings.
</P>
<P>
   Tenzin, one month shy of his 40th birthday, is patient with
Westerners, explaining in a calm, deliberate voice the plight of
his people and Loseling's goals. ``We came here to develop an
understanding of the Western mind and philosophy,'' said Tenzin,
reflecting on his reasons for choosing Emory. And in the past
decade, the city has come to feel like home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it here,'' he said. ``And I have something to do here:
My main purpose is to create a place where people can meditate,
relieve the stresses of everyday life, create love and find some
meaning in life _ all the universal values Tibetans have always
had. The whole spirit of the last 1,300 years has been to cultivate
those values.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Tate writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
