<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6931 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-BLACK-WHITE05-     04-04 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BLACK-WHITE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Courage of hip-hop convictions best of `Black and White'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``What happens when you mix it up?'' That's the tagline for
``Black and White,'' which answers that question pretty quickly:
You get energy, attitude and a big sloppy mess of a movie. For
better and for worse.
</P>
<P>
   It's the latest from writer-director James Toback, a hit-or-miss
auteur. Hit: the screenplay for ``Bugsy.'' Miss: his last movie,
``Two Guys and a Girl,'' which got press mainly for one sex scene.
He plays that same card in the opening minutes of ``Black and
White,'' showing gangsta-turned-rap impresario Rich (Oli ``Power''
Grant) having a stand-up, three-way grope in Central Park with two
teen girls, including poor little rich girl Charlie (Bijou
Phillips). As with ``Two Girls,'' this scene got press because it
had to be trimmed to get an R rating. (Do we see a pattern here?)
</P>
<P>
   It's the look-at-me opening gambit of a movie that's all about
striking a pose, showing off and trying to provoke. The core of the
largely improvised drama is young white teens' fascination with
black hip-hop culture. Charlie and school pal Raven (Gaby Hoffmann)
hang out with Rich and his rap pals and mimic their lingo. Charlie
even wears a clip-on gold tooth, to the horror of her parents.
</P>
<P>
   Other homeboy wannabes include their schoolmate Wren (Elijah
Wood) and two sons of the district attorney (Joe Pantoliano). The
kids capture the attention of a dreadlocked documentary filmmaker
(Brooke Shields) and her sexually ambiguous husband (Robert Downey
Jr.), who follow them around for a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fascinating subject, and you can see what attracted
Toback and his cast to explore it. But ambition and willingness
don't translate into insight. Some of the rambling, impromptu bits
provide some memorable sights, like Mike Tyson, playing himself,
putting the flirtatious Downey in a headlock, or reacting with
delicate pleasure when Shields calls him ``gorgeous.'' Toback
ultimately tries to generate some plot momentum by devising a
police sting and a revenge killing that seem to belong in a
B-movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black and White'' probably won't help Tyson's public image,
since it shows him endorsing this (fictional) gangsta killing. In
his own words, ``A bug needs to be stomped on.'' Unfortunately,
that ``bug'' is one of the movie's few sympathetic characters, a
rising basketball star (Allan Houston) who gets blackmailed by Ben
Stiller, playing a motormouthed creep with a hidden agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the characters verge on caricatures, including Charlie's
stuffy family, complete with investment-banker dad and
quail-serving mom (played by in-joke Marla Maples). Most of the
white characters, including the unimpressive Claudia Schiffer as a
man-eating graduate student, are seen as venal, foolish or impotent
compared with the black characters. The movie seems to buy into the
notion that white women want to have sex with Rich and other black
men because they glean some ``life force'' from them. In pretending
to examine vital racial issues, the movie really just reinforces
some stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, ``Black and White'' is defeated by its structural
shapelessness, and a down-with-it attitude that glosses over the
script's lack of any real analysis of hip-hop's cultural influence.
Instead of trying to reach a real conclusion, the movie comes to an
abrupt end, offering a few tacked-on glimpses of its characters
``six months later.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's the funny part. No, it's not a very good or intelligent
movie. But it's a topical powderkeg likely to launch arguments and
discussions more complex and sophisticated than ``Black and White''
itself. And that's worth something.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black and White''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Bijou Phillips, Oli ``Power'' Grant, Robert Downey Jr.,
Brooke Shields, Allan Houston, Ben Stiller. Rated R for violence,
sexuality and language. One hour, 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An ambitious mess that's all attitude and no
insight.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
