<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6932 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SMALL-GARDEN06-COX     04-04 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-GARDEN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Details bring out true beauty of small, romantic gardens
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, April 6.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Water spews from the pair of fountains, drowning out the distant
grind of mowers and blowers.
</P>
<P>
   English ivy blankets one wall, softening the brick of the
neighboring townhouse, while tightly clipped boxwoods flanking the
French doors lend a mood of formality.
</P>
<P>
   Even the electric meter and other reminders of everyday life are
hidden to enhance the notion that the small courtyard is in
romantic Tuscany, maybe historic Charleston _ not suburban Sandy
Springs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about details,'' said Brooks Garcia, the Atlanta
garden designer who created the haven. ``You can't fudge on them
when you're dealing with a tight, small space.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because courtyards and small gardens are designed up
close and personal so they can be enjoyed from indoors as well as
outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   The little retreats have become popular solutions for both
intown and suburban homeowners wanting to lose the maintenance of a
large back yard while gaining a small outdoor space that's
multifunctional. It's got to be large enough for entertaining
friends but intimate enough for escaping the daily grind. A place
to share a meal, relax with a book or marvel over a few favorite
plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``As children leave home and people travel more and more, they
tend to want tighter spaces with more hardscaping and less
upkeep,'' said Mary Palmer Dargan.
</P>
<P>
   She and husband Hugh, both Atlanta landscape architects, have
designed everything from large country estates to tiny Charleston
courtyards, and all have at least one thing in common _ intimacy.
``Everything we do is small, regardless of the size property,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In dense urban neighborhoods, surrounding structures often lend
the ready-made sense of enclosure necessary for creating the small
garden.
</P>
<P>
   But in sprawling suburban yards, the Dargans solve the dilemma
by divvying up the site into areas with specific functions.
</P>
<P>
   They refer to four major elements: the ``approach'' (the
driveway entry), the ``house'' (the views from rooms), the
``pause'' (small garden spaces tied closely to the house) and the
``destination'' (the view of other areas of the property).
</P>
<P>
   Bob and Gail O'Leary had plenty of reason to pause behind the
Buckhead house they built two years ago: It had only about 8 feet
of yard that dropped some 16 feet into wooded valley.
</P>
<P>
   With about 15 truckloads of earth and a stone retaining wall,
landscape architect Graham Pittman extended the bluff into a
pie-shaped plateau large enough for entertaining large groups. Yet
a breezeway between the house and a rear garage provides a quiet
spot for enjoying conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted a French country feel, a kind of Old World look,
so we used irregular crab orchard stone in the terraces,'' Pittman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny pockets between stones were left unmortared for growing
thyme and other creeping plants that give the terrace an aged look.
Individual stones were set in the brick breezeway to blend it with
the terrace.
</P>
<P>
   These details give small gardens a live-in look.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Stuart and Kathleen Kamille. After two previous designs, the
Sandy Springs courtyard Garcia created fits their low-maintenance
townhouse lifestyle. The dining room's French doors open into the
15-by-45-foot walled garden, allowing guests to spill into another
space or simply admire the view from the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become another room in their house,'' Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
