   DOW-MAIN _ In the aftermath of the Microsfot ruling, it was a
wild day on Wall Street. Technology stocks plunged into a
full-fleged bear market for the first since 1990, as the Nasdaq
composite index traded almost 24 percent below its recent all-time
high. A look at what happened and why. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   COKE _ NEW YORK _Following developments at Coca-Cola Co.
Chairman Doug Daft is on Wall Street today to update analysts on
recent changes at the company and to discuss targets for financial
growth. (Unger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   AIRTRAN-MINNESOTA _ Minnesota Attorney General Mike Hatch and
two managers from Orlando, Fla.-based AirTran Airways met to
discuss the low-fare carrier's troubled efforts to begin serving
the Twin Cities. Last week, AirTran complained to federal
transportation and justice officials that Northwest Airlines had
``dumped'' a large number of seats on flights between
Minneapolis-St. Paul International Airport and AirTran's Atlanta
hub. AirTran officials said the move was unfair competition, and
that it prompted them to shelve plans to begin Twin Cities-Atlanta
service in June. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Personal finance advice. This week: The closer we
get to the tax deadline, the harder it will be to find help,
professional or volunteer. You may have more problems locating
copies of any missing forms and instructions. Even on the Internet,
which has greatly simplified the process, you can't be surprised if
last-minute traffic jams develop. Want to start now? Here are some
steps you can take. (Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
