<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, April 5, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Tuesday, snow flurries fell in Chicago and other portions of
the Middle West as brisk winds imported unseasonably cold air into
the region. On Wednesday, much warmer conditions will reach the
Middle West on strengthening breezes from the southwest. Indeed,
air warming on descent from the Rockies will combine with abundant
sunshine to propel temperatures well into the 80s as far north as
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Colder air will surge into the Northeast behind a departing cold
front. Clouds will be common over the interior while considerable
sun will be found near the coast. After a chilly start with patchy
frost, high pressure will bring ample sunshine to the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Generally dry conditions will cover the western states. Cooler
weather will filter into the interior Northwest while patchy
morning clouds will shroud the California coast.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: SPATE OF EXTREMES
</P>
<P>
   During the past few months, Cold Bay, Alaska, has been a target
for weather extremes. It is situated near the beginning of the
Aleutian archipelago, and strong weather systems are usually
moderated by surrounding waters before reaching the area. However,
last year ended with the coldest December ever measured there. In
January, blizzard conditions occurred on a record 13 days, and the
temperature dropped to a record low of 13 degrees. After a
comparatively tranquil February, the spate of severe weather
resumed when the tiny town had its wettest March on record.
</P>
<P>
   mk
</P>
</TEXT>
