<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6943 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-EUROPE-1900-ART-2TAKE     04-04 0418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-1900-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 SHOWS ON 1900, NOT AS A LANDMARK BUT AS A BRIDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The art world has not escaped the tyranny of round
numbers this year. ``Prague 1900: Poetry and Ecstasy,'' a show at
the Van Gogh Museum in Amsterdam this winter, will soon travel to
Frankfurt. ``1900: Art at the Crossroads,'' recently at the Royal
Academy in London, will be at the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum in
New York from May 19 through Sept. 10. And, having just opened in
Paris, ``1900'' can be seen at the Grand Palais through June 26.
</P>
<P>
   But, one might ask, beyond the obvious, why celebrate 1900 in
art? Certainly 1900 was no avant-garde landmark. At most it was a
bridge, nicely decorated by Art Nouveau, between far more important
art movements. The aim of this year's shows, though, is not to
present great art as such but to convey something of the mood of
the times. And there was indeed much going on, nowhere more than in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate its own glory as well as the turn of the century,
France organized a World's Fair that engendered scores of ornate
national pavilions along the banks of the Seine. Electric lighting
came to the city's public thoroughfares for the first time, while
the Grand Palais, the Petit Palais, the Metro system, the Pont
Alexandre III and the Gare (now Musee) d'Orsay were all inaugurated
for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying the Exposition Universelle, as it was known, was a
vast survey of French art, with one section covering from the
Middle Ages to Watteau and another, the Centennale, from 1800 to
1889. Simultaneously, a contemporary art exhibition called the
Decennale, covering 1890 to 1900, presented 6,543 paintings and
sculptures by 3,223 artists from 29 countries. Clearly, as the
capital of Western art, Paris had no rival.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred years later, however, it was London and New York
rather than Paris that decided to recreate that moment in ``1900:
Art at the Crossroads.'' Wisely, though, its organizers have not
been too literal in evoking the Decennale since much of the
painting chosen by official national committees was frankly
mediocre. Thus, of the 180 artists (with 252 works) in ``Art at the
Crossroads,'' only 67 were part of the Decennale. The rest are
artists of the day who would prove their worth later.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Both the good and the bad have been organized around a series of
themes like portraits, self-portraits, nudes and bathers, men and
women, landscapes, religion and still lifes. The result is an
interesting study in aesthetic anthropology. Above all, hung
alongside long-forgotten works, there are paintings by Degas,
Cezanne, Munch, Klimt and Monet as well as by such newcomers as
Matisse, Kandinsky, Mondrian and Picasso that remind one that these
artists were exceptions to the prevailing rule of Romantic,
academic, allegorical and frequently kitsch art.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in a sense, it is the corny art that  &UR; makes &LR;  the show
since it best illustrates what 1900 was really like. For instance,
Cezanne had already begun work on his revolutionary ``Grandes
Baigneuses'' series, but the chocolate box image of bathing maidens
in Paul Chabas' ``Joyous Frolics'' (1899) was probably closer to
public taste. Similarly, it says much for the era that Leon
Frederic was acclaimed for ``The Stream,'' a triptych portraying
hundreds of naked babies and children pouring down some allegorical
stream of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of the vast melting pot that was art around 1900 came the
many interweaving and sometimes contradictory strands that would
make up the history of 20th-century art,'' explained Norman
Rosenthal, exhibitions secretary at the Royal Academy, who was one
of the show's organizers. He added: ``In the case of `1900: Art at
the Crossroads,' the challenge must be to identify what, before
modernism was born, still looks modern today.''
</P>
<P>
   The new centennial show in Paris has a different focus. Since
1900 was preceded in Paris by Post-Impressionism and Symbolism and
followed by Fauvism, Expressionism and Cubism, the organizers of
the Grand Palais exhibition opted to present more architecture,
photography, furniture, jewelry, illustrated books and ceramics
than painting and sculpture. Interior design in particular was
under the sway of Art Nouveau. (The Victoria and Albert Museum in
London is holding its own show, ``Art Nouveau: 1890-1914,'' which
opens Thursday and runs through July 30.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``1900'' dwells on neither Art Nouveau nor even the Belle
Epoque, which ended abruptly in 1914. Rather, with some 400 art
objects on display, it portrays the last turn-of-the-century as
crowded with a great diversity of visual languages and forms of
expression, variously inspired by old notions like nationalism and
Naturalism and new notions like science and technology and
urbanization. The search for the Gesamtkunstwerk, or total art
form, was frequently the ideal.
</P>
<P>
   The show's opening section, ``The Union of the Arts,''
illustrates how new concepts of design, strongly influenced by the
natural, almost botanical forms of Art Nouveau, were present in
everything: furniture, textiles, crockery, window frames and book
illustrations. And yet, as one sees in a chair and cutlery designed
by Charles Rennie Mackintosh, modernism is also struggling to make
itself felt.
</P>
<P>
   Photography too reflected this ambivalence: Gertrude Kaesebier's
``Heritage of Motherhood,'' is unabashedly romantic, while Alfred
Stieglitz's ``Hand of Man'' celebrates the steam engine.
</P>
<P>
   A section called ``Modernism and Traditions'' elaborates on this
theme, with special attention given to architectural drawings, a
nod to the proliferation of grand palaces _ museums, railroad
stations, town halls _ across Europe and the United States. A
search for national identity through architecture and interior
design was notable in Central Europe. In contrast, ``Fin de Siecle
and New Dawn'' shows how Western Europe was beginning to look
ahead. Already in 1894, for instance, Munch's painting ``Anguish''
spoke to another age.
</P>
<P>
   In Amsterdam the Van Gogh Museum has been taking a longer look
at 1900. In 1992 it organized ``Glasgow 1900: Art and Design,'' and
it followed up in 1997 with ``Vienna 1900: Portrait and Interior.''
Now ``Prague 1900: Poetry and Ecstasy,'' on display at the Museum
of Applied Art in Frankfurt from May 11 to Aug. 27, moves the
spotlight to the capital of Bohemia, part of the Austro-Hungarian
Empire in 1900 but nonetheless marked by a strongly cultural
nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   The show, which has some 100 paintings, drawing and sculptures
and 200 items of decorative art, traces the struggle of Czech
artists to assert their independence from Vienna, starting in 1896
with the so-called Prague Secession, which represented their break
with salon painting. Their work exuded nostalgia for a pre-Hapsburg
era, with Symbolists like Jan Preisler and Maxmilian Svabinsky
frequently using Czech literary classics as the inspiration for
their sensual often mystical oils.
</P>
<P>
   But they also looked west to counter Vienna's influence, with
Paris celebrated in 1902 with exhibitions of works by Rodin and by
French Impressionists. A 1905 Munch show had an even greater
impact, further encouraging artists like Karel Hlavacek toward
darker, more tortured, forms of expression. Similarly, Czech
craftsmen adapted French and Belgian Art Nouveau to their own
furniture, ceramics, metalwork, jewelry and glassware.
</P>
<P>
   Across Europe, then, a great melting pot was swirling. Yet this
moment of synthesis would not last long. The artists of 1900 may
have felt they were stepping into the 20th century, but they still
carried the 19th century with them. Then, within barely a decade,
first Expressionism then Cubism shattered every existing mold.
Modernism had struck and the 19th century finally ended.
</P>
<P>
   (BL)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
