<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6945 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-04 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE BOY SCOUT PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On April 26 the Supreme Court will hear an
especially provocative case on whether the Boy Scouts of America
may continue to prevent gay men from becoming troop leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The legal issue is whether the group is a public organization
that is forbidden in most states to discriminate on the basis of
sexual orientation or a private institution free to choose its own
leaders by its own criteria.
</P>
<P>
   This is a close call with legitimate points on both sides. The
organization is actually a quasi-public, quasi-private group.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways it operates like a private club, taking in
schoolboys of a certain age who promise to behave themselves, wear
uniforms, work for merit badges and profess faith in God. But it
does not admit (horrors!) girls or unknown boys who wander in off
the streets. Meetings are closed, and membership is strictly up to
the discretion of the scoutmasters.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Boy Scouts also use taxpayer-financed facilities in some
places and often get public support in troop sponsorship and
charity donations. National membership is so broad it can hardly be
called exclusive.
</P>
<P>
   The real issue here, however, is one of civil rights. And the
question is whether the Scouts hold such a venerable place in
shaping the character of young boys that they belong in a special
immune category. It is not a close call at all.
</P>
<P>
   The Boy Scouts organization does not approve of homosexuality.
It claims that being gay is incompatible with the Scout obligation
to be ``morally straight'' and ``clean.'' Its officials fear that
gay leaders would be the wrong role models for its good little
boys.
</P>
<P>
   But modern science has come a long way toward proving that being
gay is a matter of biology rather than a wickedly chosen corrupt
lifestyle. California and National Institutes of Health studies
suggest that homosexuals have a different structure in some parts
of the brain than heterosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   No, this case is not about protecting the public against the
spread of inherent immorality. It is not even about preventing
pre-teen boys from associating with gays since they could meet them
in many other places including church.
</P>
<P>
   It is about the intolerance of a major youth organization toward
behavior it does not understand. It is about social disapproval of
men discredited because of the sexual category to which they
belong, without any regard to their individual merit. And that
sends a message the high bench should not endorse.
</P>
<P>
   The Scouts are hiding behind a claim of ``freedom of
association,'' based on the constitutional right to unregulated
expression of beliefs and ideas. A fine principle. We like to pal
around with other people who are just like us. Diversity makes for
awkwardness and sometimes uneasiness.
</P>
<P>
   But this right of choice has long been abused as an excuse to
arbitrarily exclude minorities from activities and organizations
that benefit the majority. Wisely, the courts have steadily
stripped it away in a series of cases.
</P>
<P>
   Businessmen's groups like the Jaycees and Rotary Clubs raised
similar objections in defense of barring women, as did groups that
sought to perpetuate the segregation of blacks. When they lost, the
republic did not fall. Gender and racial integration has not been
perfectly smooth, but it has not had the crippling impact the
affected groups predicted. To the contrary, it has strengthened
both the country and the institutions involved.
</P>
<P>
   The Boy Scouts can similarly survive the acceptance of gay
leaders without mental and moral collapse, although thus far the
Scouts have been a preferred, pampered group. Local courts have
been divided on previous challenges to scouting's exclusionary
policies toward gays. By contrast, atheists who wanted to belong
have decisively lost in court and so have women, although the
Scouts were magnanimous after the latter victory, changing their
policy to allow female scoutmasters.
</P>
<P>
   Boy Scout supporters contend that James Dale, an expelled former
New Jersey Eagle Scout now committed to gay causes who is the focus
of the suit, wants simply to disrupt scouting by promoting his own
agenda. But the real test should be whether he would make a good,
decent scoutmaster, and specific performance should determine that.
</P>
<P>
   He can't prove his worth unless the high bench gives him the
opportunity. The Supreme Court has a tendency to punt rather than
hit a home run on sensitive issues like this that pit cultural
tradition against human rights. It would be good if the justices
faced up to this one.
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
