<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6952 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-BROOKE--SHIELDS-LADN &LR;      04-04 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROOKE--SHIELDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING WITHOUT A NET
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brooke Shields knew what she was getting herself into _ a
non-scripted role in a low-budget, high-concept film. She would
share billing _ and dressing room space _ with plenty of non-actors
and would receive no star frills.
</P>
<P>
   All of which was fine with Shields, who wasn't looking for
safety or comfort. She had had comfort with her NBC sitcom,
``Suddenly Susan,'' which was on its last legs.
</P>
<P>
   So in writer/director James Toback's ``Black and White,'' a
story of interracial relationships that opens today, Shields got
back to basics, which for actors means improvisation. All of her
scenes in the film _ including those with Robert Downey Jr. and
boxer Mike Tyson _ were entirely unscripted. That meant no written
dialogue, just the intention of a scene _ get from point A to point
B. How you do it is up to you.
</P>
<P>
   Actors are accustomed to playing improv games in theater
classes, but the free-form character-building developed for ``Black
and White'' by Toback was no exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really didn't harken back to anything I'd ever
experienced,'' says Shields, speaking from New York. ``There's a
safety if there's scripted dialogue. But with the level of anxiety
and energy that were throughout all of our scenes, nobody could
fall into the safety of the written word.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (Toback) I would be willing to do it providing he would
push me, that he would constantly ask me to give him more of a
commitment to this type of an environment.''
</P>
<P>
   He pushed, she committed, and the results, according to Toback,
were splendid.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was remarkable in her inventiveness, in her energy, her
capacity to surprise,'' said Toback, whose last film was ``Two
Girls and a Guy.'' ``I got from her, in what was potentially a
fascinating role only if the actor contributed in making it so,
every bit that I could have hoped for and more.''
</P>
<P>
   When the words are related back to her, a grateful Shields says
``Wow! Could I have that laminated? That is so generous and so
kind.''
</P>
<P>
   And she returns the compliment, calling Toback a smart and
trustworthy director with a point of view.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jim was going for a documentary feel, a slice-of-life
approach and the shock value that comes from situations rather than
scripted dialogue. I think, to coin the phrase, he really wanted to
keep it real.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Shields' goal as well. She plays a documentary
filmmaker fixated on a group of white kids immersed in New York's
African-American hip-hop culture. To the Manhattan-born Shields,
``Black and White's'' setting and themes were a type of cultural
homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had such an interest and a very unbiased view,'' said
Shields. ``Having been very accepted by black culture since I was
younger, based on my friends, my dance class and my music, I had a
very liberal view. That lack of judgment is what (my character)
needed to have so that Jim could present both black and white
without bias.''
</P>
<P>
   Working as she is, in an ensemble project _ and one with
challenging themes _ Shields says she is pleased to encounter
questions about her views on race and sexual identity more than
about stalkers, past or current romantic interests or her
ex-husband, Andre Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested in reading about me personally,'' she says,
adding that with ``Black and White,'' ``I've been asked some
intelligent questions for the first time in a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm inspired to talk about hip-hop and about how fascinating
these kids are. This is a movie that parents need to see.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's format and Shields' role will invariably inspire
critical barbs that her character, Sam _ even under the dreadlocks,
nose ring and black nail polish _ is another example of Shields
playing herself. It's a statement Shields has heard before, most
recently during her four years as the perky magazine writer in
NBC's ``Suddenly Susan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're really referring to when they say, `Oh, of
course, she's playing herself,' is an image or a preconception that
has been written about for so long that it's become part of the
vernacular and the assumed reality,'' says Shields, who claims she
is selective about which press clippings she reads. ``You see it
enough and that sets the precedent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never ceases to amaze me, the assumption that is made. I
think it could stem from being in the business for as long as I
have. However, I would believe it is impossible to assume that
anybody knows me the way it has been written and claimed.''
</P>
<P>
   Viewers trying to get to know Brooke Shields will now have to do
so through something other than a Monday night sitcom. Despite word
from the the network that ``Susan's'' fate won't officially be
decided until May, Shields says the show is ``done. We're
finished.''
</P>
<P>
   She is pleased that the show will make it into syndication, but
says that an ever-juggling time slot and unsteady promotion caused
a loss of viewers, particularly in its last season.
</P>
<P>
   By the time it reached its fourth and final season, ``Suddenly
Susan'' was practically a new show, says Shields, who was its
co-producer as well its star. By then, it no longer had enough
support or momentum to go further.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sad, for sure, to have it end, but I think it had a
wonderful life.'' she says. ``We were a hit show with talented
actors and we made it into syndication where so many shows don't
even see the light of day.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a cameo in the Chris O'Donnell film ``The Bachelor,''
Shields plays a bitter divorcee who orchestrates a girls-only
weekend in Palm Springs in the upcoming ``The Weekend'' opposite
Gena Rowlands. The drama ``After Sex'' with Jonathan Schaech is
complete but does not have a release date.
</P>
<P>
   No longer in search of specific roles or projects, Shields says
she now goes with the flow, whether that leads her to film or back
to television.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really all about the work, about the actual character and
finding a part that I feel could show a different aspect of
myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
