<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6960 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT05-COX     04-04 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LARGE ISSUES STILL LOOM FOR MICROSOFT AND GOVERNMENT
 &HT;    With MICROSOFT-CONGRESS. Moving in Washington (w) and financial
(f) categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Will feuding antitrust officials be able to speak
with one voice when they return to a federal courtroom to seek a
fit punishment for Microsoft Corp.?
</P>
<P>
   Will Microsoft soften its legendary hard-charging culture to
strike a deal with the government and head off the threat of a
court-imposed breakup?
</P>
<P>
   Both these questions loomed large Tuesday, the day after a
sweeping verdict by U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
that branded Microsoft as a rogue monopoly that had illegally
bullied its rivals, stifled software innovation and harmed
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately following Jackson's sweeping decision, Bill Gates,
Microsoft's chairman and co-founder, continued to take a hard line.
In a series of interviews, he stressed that the ruling could be
reversed on appeal and voiced confidence that the software giant he
co-founded in 1975 as a Harvard dropout would prevail in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Common sense stands on our side,'' Gates told the BBC.
</P>
<P>
   While Gates's wallet is billions of dollars lighter since
settlement talks collapsed last weekend, he may feel buoyed by his
invitation to play a featured role Wednesday at a White House
conference on how technology is changing the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore have both taken a
neutral stance on the antitrust case, even as Attorney General
Janet Reno continues to broadly condemn Microsoft's monopolistic
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly Mr. Gates has much to offer in terms of his point of
view,'' said Gene Sperling, director of the National Economic
Council. ``We aren't endorsing or necessarily disagreeing with all
sorts of things people are going to say'' at the conference.
</P>
<P>
   There were some signs that Microsoft was feeling slightly more
conciliatory after the settlement failure, the hostile verdict and
a big drop in the market value of its stock.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Ballmer, who has succeeded Gates as Microsoft's chief
executive officer, told reporters: ``Our intense focus on moving
forward has at times been threatening and our passion for this has
been misinterpreted. We can do better.''
</P>
<P>
   Such contrition may lead in time to a more forthcoming
settlement offer from Microsoft than the one rejected by the
Justice Department even before it was reviewed by the state
attorneys general who act as equal partners in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Assistant Attorney General Joel Klein, who heads the
Justice Department's antitrust division, sought to put the best
possible face on his team's disagreements with the attorneys
general, which Gates said had stymied the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, by and large, we have seen eye to eye on matters,''
Klein said. ``But at a given time, there may be some disagreements.
Honorable people, people of good faith, on occasion will find
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has told the plaintiffs privately that when the time
comes to suggest remedies he expects them to submit a unitary
brief.
</P>
<P>
   One person who does not expect new flexibility from Microsoft is
James Barksdale, the star government witness at the antitrust
trial, who accused Microsoft of seeking to illegally divide the
Internet market with Netscape Communications Corp., which has since
merged with America Online Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft should apologize for breaking the law,'' Barksdale
said. ``Instead, they've lost the basketball game by 110 points,
and all they can do is boast about the five field goals they
made,'' Barksdale said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't change the spots on this leopard,'' he concluded.
``I don't think they're evil people. I just don't think they
appreciate the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
