<P>
   Here are the business news stories the Los Angeles Daily News
plans to move for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs
of Wednesday, April 5 and thereafter. The stories will carry the
``f'' financial news category code unless otherwise noted. For
questions about stories, please contact Stewart Slavin at the Daily
News at (818) 713-3701.
</P>
<P>
   SOCAL-MARKET-REACT (Los Angeles) _ The mood among local
investors and publicly traded companies was calm, a surprise
considering the chaotic scene on Wall Street. By Chris Sieroty,
Jason Takenouchi and Jason Cohen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 1831EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6971 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      04-04 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE A NICE, DEEP BREATH, THEN LET GO OF YOUR MONEY  
</HEADLINE>
   By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pardon me if I yawn, but I was up late last night cleaning out
my garage. I'm getting ready to launch my own business _ selling
empty boxes on the Internet _ and I want to make sure I have plenty
of room. I expect orders to be quite brisk.
</P>
<P>
   My boxes won't be completely empty, of course. There will be air
inside. Lots and lots of air. That's my product, in fact. Air.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, yeah, I know. You're thinking I'm an idiot. But I happen
to know that some people are willing to pay money _ darned good
money _ for air these days.
</P>
<P>
   I began research and development on this idea three years ago.
That's when newspapers in New York City, Los Angeles and other
major cities began reporting on the emergence of ``oxygen bars,''
trendy little hangouts where patrons routinely pay through the nose
for the privilege of breathing.
</P>
<P>
   It works this way: Customers stick surgical tubes up their noses
and inhale 96-percent to 98-percent pure oxygen. For this, they pay
about $1 per minute, with the typical sitting lasting 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   These bars are now spreading around the country, according to a
recent story in the Tampa Tribune. As one oxygen barkeeper told the
Trib, air is the ``next bottled water.''
</P>
<P>
   People sit around oxygen bars doing pretty much what they do at
regular bars, except there's no liquor, no beer and _ in deference
to the oxygen tanks _ no smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Bottled air comes in a variety of scents, including peppermint
passion, tangerine twist, tropical punch and, for the smoker,
``coughdrop.'' While they're partaking the Big O, customers also
can sip on fruit juice, vitamin-laced beverages called ``smart
drinks,'' or super-oxygenated glasses of water known as ``oxygen
cocktails.''
</P>
<P>
   Some bars have themes. In one establishment, patrons pop tubes
in their noses and relax by watching tropical fish swim around in
an aquarium. (This sounds an awful lot like a badly run nursing
home to me, but I reckon the action picks up, especially around
feeding time.)
</P>
<P>
   A few bars also offer ``oxygen facials,'' which involve blowing
oxygen on customers' skin. The cost? A mere $120. (I haven't had
one myself, but I gather this would be like going into a regular
bar's restroom and turning the automated hand-dryer on my face.)
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen inhalers say their sniffing works wonders. They claim
they have more pep in their step and boast that their hair is
fuller, their skin more supple, their love lives breathier.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors aren't imbibing so deeply, though. They point out that a
healthy person's blood really can't absorb any more oxygen than it
already does. In fact, some docs warn that people who suck down
pure oxygen regularly run the risk of irritating their lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Some of you may think these folks are real airheads, but I'm not
passing judgment. The way I see it, if they have that much spare
change, they must have worked hard for it. They've earned the right
to breathe easy, no matter how much wind it may take out of their
bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that a few entrepreneuring souls have stepped forward
to help them suck air through a straw is, I think, exactly the sort
of thing that makes this country great.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I'm not much of a businessman. I have a head better suited
for inhaling helium than figuring up oxygen profits. I can't
possibly hope to compete with the sharp minds running these bars,
so I'm simply hoping to carve out a little niche for myself in the
mail-order market.
</P>
<P>
   Since I can't afford to buy 98 percent oxygen, I'm offering used
air _ or, if you will, ``pre-breathed air'' or ``vintage air.''
Tonight, I'm heading home to begin packaging special concoctions of
oxygen, carbon dioxide, eau de litterbox and whatever else I manage
to trap in the boxes in my garage.
</P>
<P>
   If this thing really goes airborne, and I have no reason to
believe it won't, I expect to unveil a whole new line of products
in a matter of days. In fact, I'm currently approaching a couple of
nationally known politicians about joining me in creating special
autographed boxes of hot air.
</P>
<P>
   I welcome the opportunity to speak with investors. For
information, call me directly or visit my Web site at
www.airyawithmesucker.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com. The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 1833EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6972 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     04-04 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAZARDS AMONG THE HEADLINES  
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you think working on the copy desk of a daily newspaper isn't
hazardous duty, then you probably aren't the author of one of these
real, honest-to-goodness headlines reprinted in Richard Lederer's
book, ``More Anguished English:''
</P>
<P>
   Drugs And Crime Are Overrated
</P>
<P>
   _ However, sex and violence are not.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia Aims At Illiteracy
</P>
<P>
   _ But presumably misses due to the fact that it couldn't read
the loading and firing instructions.
</P>
<P>
   6 Found Slain In Miami; Missing Toddler Sought
</P>
<P>
   _ This headline was goofy 20 years ago. Nowadays, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   Man Shot, Stabbed; Death By Natural Causes Ruled
</P>
<P>
   _ Must have been a Miami resident.
</P>
<P>
   Another Body Found Missing
</P>
<P>
   _ Maybe they should hire somebody to keep an eye on these found
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Cemetery Allows People To Be Buried By Their Pets
</P>
<P>
   _ Dog-owners will presumably be buried much faster than
snake-owners.
</P>
<P>
   Father Of 9 Fined $100 For Failing To Stop
</P>
<P>
   _ I'd jump off a cliff if I had nine children, but I still don't
think it's right to fine people for having large families. Besides,
what's $100 to a guy who's going to have to put nine kids through
college?
</P>
<P>
   Girl Becomes Methodist After Delicate Operation
</P>
<P>
   _ Sometimes theology by itself just doesn't do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Fencing In Your Swimming Pool Can Save A Child's Life
</P>
<P>
   _ It's hard to see how, unless the kid's afraid to jump into the
pool with all those sharp swords whipping about.
</P>
<P>
   Court Escapee Still On The Lamb
</P>
<P>
   _ Well, he couldn't have gotten too far unless he's riding one
of those genetically engineered lambs.
</P>
<P>
   Man Booked For Wreckless Driving
</P>
<P>
   _ Really? Seems to me like he should be congratulated.
</P>
<P>
   House Declared Haunted By A Manhattan Appeals Court
</P>
<P>
   _ That would be spooky. All those old guys in robes doddering
around in the middle of the night, bumping into furniture and
arguing with each other over the finer points of case law. I'll
take a good, old-fashioned poltergeist any day.
</P>
<P>
   Man Trying To Get Kite Electrocuted
</P>
<P>
   _ That seems like a rather harsh punishment for what is
essentially a child's toy. Besides, these days most states have
switched over to lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   Astronaut Takes Blame For Gas In Spacecraft
</P>
<P>
   _ Well, he really doesn't have much choice, does he? I mean,
it's not like there's a big crowd in those things. Who came up with
the bright idea of freeze-dried bean burritos anyhow?
</P>
<P>
   School Board Agrees To Discuss Education
</P>
<P>
   _ What have they been discussing before now? The Ken Griffey,
Jr. trade? Kathie Lee Gifford's retirement? The creepy guy on Who
Wants To Marry a Multimillionaire? No wonder 47 percent of
8th-graders think Norway is in South America.
</P>
