<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, April 5 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ There was sound. There was fury.
But what stock market investors wanted to know after Tuesday's
bizarre bungee-jump in share prices was, what does it signify?
Midway through one of the weirdest and wildest days in stock market
history, the Nasdaq composite index had plunged 634.31 points,
shearing 13.6 percent off its value. Had it closed there, it would
have been the worst one-day decline in Nasdaq history. But a flood
of buying rescued the composite, bringing it to close with a loss
of only 1.72 percent on the day. By Gretchen Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT17.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-POLITICS (Tokyo) _ Japan's Cabinet resigned en masse on
Tuesday, setting the stage for a rapid political succession, two
days after a life-threatening stroke incapacitated Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi. The resignation, which was formalized in a brief,
final Cabinet meeting Tuesday evening, is expected to lead to the
nomination of a candidate by the governing Liberal Democratic
Party, as early as Wednesday morning, to succeed Obuchi. A
parliamentary vote to ratify the party's choice, which is already
widely reported be the ruling party's second-ranked official,
Yoshiro Mori, would be held almost immediately afterwards. By
Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   ORE-ADOPTION-RECORDS (Albany, Ore.) _ The continuing legal
controversy over a law passed by Oregon voters in 1998 giving any
adult adoptee access to their birth records, which had been sealed,
so that they may try to track down their birth parents and/or
half-siblings. The legal issue, of course, pits their ``right to
know'' versus the confidentiality the state at one time promised to
women who decided to give children up for adoption. The law, the
first such measure approved by voters in any state, has been stayed
ever since by a legal challenge from six anonymous birth mothers.
Now it's coming to a head before the Oregon supreme court. By Sam
Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-DRUGS (Washington) _ Seven months before Election Day,
the struggle over expanding Medicare to cover prescription drugs
for the elderly is escalating, with both parties maneuvering
furiously on an issue with immense significance for a critical
group of voters. As the budget debate began in the Senate Tuesday,
for example, Democrats were pushing for an amendment that would
require the creation of a Medicare drug benefit before any tax cut
could take effect. President Clinton declared that their amendment
was ``good policy, the will of the American people, and addresses a
long-standing unmet need.'' Nu Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HORMONE-REPLACEMENT (Undated) _ Researchers have informed
about 25,000 women taking part in a federal study of hormone
replacement therapy that, far from protecting the heart as many
researchers had assumed, the therapy may put them at slightly
higher risk from heart attacks and strokes. The study, known as the
Women's Health Initiative Hormone Trial, is the first large scale,
controlled clinical trial to test hormone replacement therapy for
post-menopausal women. But in letters sent out Friday, participants
are told that those who had been randomly assigned to take estrogen
were having slightly more heart attacks, strokes, and blood clots
in the lungs than those who had been assigned to take dummy pills
for comparison. While the effect was not sufficiently pronounced to
stop the study, the researchers themselves were taken aback. By
Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SUITS (Undated) _ The ruling against Microsoft in the
federal antitrust case potentially opens the door to a flood of
private litigation against the company by equipping potential
plaintiffs with a legal finding that it is an abusive monopolist.
In addition to a trickle of class-action suits that had already
begun, the decision could embolden major companies _ not only
rivals but in some cases customers of Microsoft _ to take action
against it. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-U.N. (Daru, Sierra Leone) _ This town, attacked 59
times during a nine-year civil war, had been left for dead,
deserted by its residents. Now, a few weeks after U.N. peacekeepers
arrived, life has begun to stir again. The peacekeeping operation
in Sierra Leone will be watched closely, especially as the United
Nations Security Council considers sending troops to Congo, a much
larger country whose conflict has drawn in half a dozen nations. By
Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
