<HEADER>
A6984 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CENSUS05-COX     04-04 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MORE CENSUS ADS PLANNED IN SOUTH AS RESPONSE LAGS
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Census officials, increasingly concerned about the
relatively low response in Southern states, will launch a new ad
campaign Wednesday to convince more people to return their
questionnaires.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, 55 percent of households had responded to the census
by Tuesday, less than what federal officials had hoped for. In the
South, the response rate was generally lower, with Georgia at 53
percent, Florida at 52 percent and Texas and North Carolina each at
51 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Census numbers are used to apportion congressional seats and
distribute billions of dollars in federal spending, and many
Southern governors and mayors have organized campaigns to encourage
residents to return their forms.
</P>
<P>
   The new census radio and television ads aimed at the South open
with the words ``This is an urgent message.'' They begin airing
Wednesday in Georgia, Florida, Texas, North Carolina, South
Carolina, Alabama, Mississippi, Louisiana, Oklahoma, West Virginia,
New Mexico and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, the latest phase of a $167 million national
advertising strategy, comes amid a public debate over privacy
concerns as the census conducts its once-a-decade poll of America.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent Republicans, including presumed GOP presidential
nominee Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott of Mississippi, suggested last week that Americans need
not answer all the questions on the detailed long form if they find
some objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   While census official have no hard evidence to suggest that the
privacy controversy has swayed Americans against answering the
census, ``in the middle of the census, any negative publicity about
the census is harmful,'' director Kenneth Prewitt said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He criticized what he termed ``cheap shots'' against the census
and urged all elected leaders to promote the head count.
</P>
<P>
   With a week remaining before census workers begin their
door-to-door survey to find people who have not responded, Prewitt
remained hopeful that Americans would ``reverse a long tide of
civic disengagement,'' a reference to declining mail-in rates since
1970.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials had hoped that 61 percent of Americans would
have responded by Monday. Prewitt said he hoped a rush of forms
would arrive at the Census Bureau's four national processing
centers in the next few days, boosting the count. Officials suspect
that many Americans did not fill out their forms until April 1, the
date designated as ``Census Day,'' and mailed them on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the Census Bureau has set a mail-in response target of
70 percent for the 2000 census, five percentage points above the
1990 rate.
</P>
<P>
   Among Southern states, Mississippi ranked the lowest Tuesday,
with only 47 percent of households responding, and Virginia was
highest, with 59 percent. Across the nation, Ohio and Nebraska had
the highest percentage of residents returning their forms, each at
62 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In recent decades, the South and Southwest have lagged behind
the rest of the nation in their response rates. Census officials
have dubbed it the ``Southern factor,'' forcing them to spend more
resources in those states to convince people to mail in their
forms.
</P>
<P>
   Among the reasons demographers suspect for the
lower-than-average response in the South and Southwest:
</P>
<P>
   _ A traditional mistrust of federal government.
</P>
<P>
   _ A proportionally higher number of immigrants and minorities
who may be suspicious of the census and who may not fully
understand the form and its intent.
</P>
<P>
   _ A newer, more mobile Sunbelt population that is more difficult
to count compared to regions such as the Northeast and Midwest,
where populations are more firmly settled.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to convince Southerners and other Americans to
respond by mail has an effect on the Census Bureau's bottom line.
Counters must go door to door at households who fail to respond at
an estimated cost of $35 a visit. Raising the mail-in response rate
just one percentage points represents 1.2 million households that
would not need to be visited.
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
