<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6986 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-OREGON-ADOPTION-RECOR     04-04 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OREGON-ADOPTION-RECORDS-ART-2TAKES(1040)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANXIETY RISES AS OREGON PREPARES TO RELEASE BIRTH RECORDS OF
ADOPTEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT23 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, Ore. _ It is just a piece of paper that Berry Price
wants, one locked away by the state all these years, one the
55-year-old machinist thinks may help him finally ``fill in some of
the blanks of my life.'' He wants his birth certificate.
</P>
<P>
   So does Heidi Landtiser, a 32-year-old adoptee from Scappoose.
``It's hard not to know the answer to that basic question about
your background, where you came from,'' she said. ``It's like we
just appeared on earth, and that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   For these two adopted adults, the quest to know more about their
births puts them on one side of the tumultuous legal debate here
over the nation's first voter-approved law granting adoptees access
to long-sealed birth records. But for many birth mothers on the
other side, the law they are fighting to block is bringing
``flashbacks and nightmares,'' as one woman described it. They say
it flatly violates the promises made by counselors and adoption
agencies years ago, that their identities would never be revealed
against their will to the children whom they gave up for adoption.
</P>
<P>
   The law, known as Measure 58, was passed by Oregonians more than
a year ago, but it has been on hold because of a legal challenge
filed by six birth mothers, all of whom have remained anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the Oregon Supreme Court having recently upheld
lower-court rulings that birth mothers have no constitutional right
to keep the records confidential, the state is on the verge of
releasing the records to the more than 2,000 adults who have
requested them. Opponents have until Tuesday to appeal to the U.S.
Supreme Court, and as that date nears, anxiety on both sides has
been heightening.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the debate here seems outdated. Experts agree that
a social sea change in recent years has removed much of the stigma
of pregnancy outside marriage, and many births these days are
``open adoptions,'' under which birth parents maintain contact with
the children and the parents who are raising them. Moreover,
thousands of women and men who gave up children for adoption have
eagerly placed their names with registries, leading to joyful
reunions with children whom they once assumed they would never see
again.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue in Oregon, and in the many other states where
proponents of so-called adoptees' rights are hoping to carry their
cause, is something different, since it centers on those women who
have maintained an adamant desire over the years to have no contact
with the children they gave up. Some say they are petrified that
their husbands or children will discover a long-held secret that
could cause enormous ruptures in their families. Some say they were
raped, and that a call from the person who resulted from that act
would cause them singular trauma.
</P>
<P>
   While everyone agrees these women were generally assured of
privacy when they decided to give children up, it is not clear that
such assurances are legally binding. That is the crux of the issue
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very complicated debate, because you realize there are
rights on both sides,'' said E. Wayne Carp, a history professor at
Pacific Lutheran University in Tacoma, Wash., who is the author of
the book ``Family Matters: Secrecy and Disclosure in the History of
Adoption'' (Harvard University Press, 1998). In Oregon at least,
the promise of confidentiality, he said, was ``an assumed promise
that was never fully articulated in law.''
</P>
<P>
   So whose right trumps? The adoptees argue for the right to
answer such a basic question about their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you know that there's a piece of paper in a courthouse
concerning you,'' Price said, ``concerning an event that took place
between you and another party, your birth mother, and you're not
even allowed to see it, I just think that's wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Price, who has only partially put together the story of
his birth, concedes that he can understand the other side. An aunt
told him that his birth mother was a Portland woman with other
children who had committed an indiscretion during World War II,
apparently when her husband was in the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do see her point of view,'' said Price, who was raised an
only child. ``Maybe she never, ever, wanted her husband or her
children to know about this. But what about me? I've apparently got
a bunch of half-siblings out there, and I'd like to meet them. It
would be nice to be able to see somebody that resembles me
physically. Maybe they'd get a kick out of meeting me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Whalley, 68, a retired postal worker in Albany who has also
sought his records, has had heart and lung problems and wants to
find out more about his birth parents' medical histories. He knows
his mother is probably dead, but believes he has biological
half-siblings.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I really want is the medical background, whether my own
kids could inherit some condition we should know about,'' said
Whalley. ``It would be a bonus if there was a positive desire for
contact, but I don't want to put pressure on my siblings.''
</P>
<P>
   The birth mothers in this debate have not been identified,
though one, called ``Mary,'' recently published an article in The
Oregonian, the state's main newspaper, in which she wrote of the
fear she and other women felt as the law neared taking effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soon, for $15, the state may simply hand over your identity to
the adult you placed for adoption as an infant 21-plus years ago,''
she said. ``In a few days, the very promises we built our lives
upon may be up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``The courts are now saying that no such promises were ever
made,'' she said. ``Yet as young women, we were counseled by
doctors, lawyers and clergymen _ professionals who were
unquestionably convinced that the law guaranteed us the choice of
privacy. We made life decisions based on those assurances. Now we
are being left with our trust shattered, our hearts broken and the
threat of our lives being changed forever without our consent.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for the birth mothers, Franklin Hunsaker, the father
of five adopted children, said many of his clients were dumbfounded
when the measure got off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rejoice when there are reunions,'' said Hunsaker. ``But a
reunion has got to be based on mutual consent.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The law does allow a woman to attach a statement to the original
birth certificate attesting that she does not want to be contacted,
but there are no legal prohibitions against an adoptee who ignores
those wishes. (In 1957, the state Legislature in effect sealed all
original birth certificates for adoptees and directed the state to
create new ones carrying the names of adoptive parents.)
</P>
<P>
   Oregon is unique in having a voter-approved open-records law,
and there is no question that the measure represents the most
determined push yet by adoptees to gain full rights to see their
birth records. Still, it remains unclear whether the law or the
enormous attention on the debate here will propel significantly
higher percentages of adoptees to initiate the search.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, nearly all states have solid prohibitions
that keep adoptees' birth records, or at least the names of their
birth parents, sealed. But in Kansas and Alaska, where there has
never been an explicit privacy protection, officials do not report
discernibly higher levels of adoptees who seek out birth parents.
In Tennessee, courts have established an adoptee's right to
retrieve birth records, but the state can penalize an adoptee who
contacts birth parents against their will.
</P>
<P>
   About two of every three adoptees do not seek out birth parents
and about 80 percent of those who do are women, said Carp, the
professor from Pacific Lutheran University.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Oregon, the voters and three layers of courts have sided
with the right of the adoptees to know. Any appeal to the U.S.
Supreme Court is considered a long shot, though Hunsaker said it
was under strong consideration.
</P>
<P>
   And so, Carp said, ``It appears we're going to have a giant
social laboratory. All of a sudden a lot of people are going to get
their birth certificates and then they will search and they'll have
reunions with their birth mothers, whether the mothers want them or
not. If there's a lot of social turmoil that emerges, I think
that's going to strengthen the case for adoption registries'' _
under which reunions occur only by mutual consent _ and privacy
protections.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if this kind of social turmoil fails to come up,'' he
added, ``then you really have a strong case that there is not a
problem, and records should be open.''
</P>
<P>
   (nk)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
