<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-KOHL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAINTED FILES ON KOHL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Helmut Kohl, who served as Germany's chancellor for 16 dramatic
years, deserves the disgrace brought on by his refusal to obey the
law and reveal the names of donors to slush funds his Christian
Democratic Union acquired while he was in office.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Kohl's countrymen should resist any temptation to
use information about the campaign finance scandal that derives
from the secret police files of the vanished communist state in
East Germany. All material generated by the infamous Stasi, be it
from telephone taps or from agents and moles, ought to be
considered tainted.
</P>
<P>
   There are empirical reasons to regard the Stasi files as
tainted, and there is also a matter of political and ethical
principle.
</P>
<P>
   The files should be off limits not merely because informants to
the East German intelligence services often lied or exaggerated in
their reports. Even if some of the information given to the Stasi
about the donors to Kohl's slush fund might be accurate, the open
society of contemporary Germany risks injecting an old poison into
its bloodstream once it allows material collected by a police state
to be presented as legitimate information.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, German newspapers have already released some
material from the East German secret police archives, and there is
a danger that members of parliament will try to get around a ban on
using such material by drawing on it to pose questions in
parliamentary inquiries into Kohl's fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Hard as it might be for legislators to refrain from exploiting
old Stasi phone taps for the sake of a headline-making question,
they must resist the temptation, for the sake of German democracy.
</P>
<P>
   If it is true, as the daily Berliner Zeitung reported Monday,
that Kohl's government had some Stasi files destroyed before German
unification in 1990 in order to keep his slush fund secret, such an
act would also partake of the communist penchant for defining truth
as that which serves the interest of the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   The Stasi files can poison those who destroy them as much as
those who would release them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 1848EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6996 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-MICROSOFT-B     04-04 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MICROSOFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAMING MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's ringing condemnation that
Microsoft had put ``an oppressive thumb on the scale of competitive
fortune,'' will be remembered as long as there is antitrust law.
Although there now may be years of appeal, Jackson has put a new
industry on notice that there are rules to competition that must be
obeyed.
</P>
<P>
   Now begins the hard work: figuring out how to punish a corporate
giant and seeing if the punishment will stick. Microsoft may
consider that time is on its side, with a new administration coming
in next year and with a war chest to fight on indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Using the language of apple pie entrepreneurism, Microsoft
promises to ``focus on creating the next generation of innovative
software that benefits consumers, the high-technology industry, and
the American economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gates made the seemingly common-sense argument that the
``incredible pace of technological change is the clearest evidence
of the competitive environment in which Microsoft and every other
company must operate . . .''
</P>
<P>
   One extension of this logic: There's no need for legal remedies
because innovations could end Microsoft's dominance. Plus some
opportunities are wide open. There is no software king, for
example, in the world of handheld computers.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be fooled. These possibilities are dwarfed by current
realities. Microsoft's Windows operating system is in a whopping 95
percent of Intel-compatible personal computers. Jackson's ruling
points out a history of predatory practices. Even consumers sitting
at home putting up with Windows' glitches can't help but wonder if
more competition would have led to a more stable operating system.
</P>
<P>
   And Microsoft has been accused of trying to get an iron grip on
the server market by making Windows 2000 slightly incompatible with
the encryption standard. (Servers provide a service, usually
information such as Web pages, to users.) Microsoft says it isn't
at fault, that the standard is evolving.
</P>
<P>
   In 1911, when Standard Oil was fielding lawsuits about its
overbearing hold on the industry, the court's view of monopolies
was blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``No disinterested mind,'' said Supreme Court Chief Justice
Edward White, ``can survey the period in question without being
irresistibly drawn to the conclusion that the very genius for
commercial development and organization . . . soon begat an intent
and purpose to exclude others.'' The massive oil company was given
six months to dissolve itself.
</P>
<P>
   Today, this history along with the breakup of AT&AMP;T has prompted
passionate cries to cut Microsoft into pieces. One approach is to
split off the Windows operating system component and divide this
into three competing companies.
</P>
<P>
   But in this case the next step isn't that simple.
</P>
<P>
   First, Microsoft has reason to gamble on an appeal. Jackson's
ruling is definitive. But in 1998, the appeals court sided with
Microsoft in a dispute over a consent degree. The appeals court
said that a practice many saw as predatory _ adding a Web browser
to Windows _ was OK if the company could show some benefit to
consumers. The appeals court could smile at Microsoft again.
</P>
<P>
   Second, breaking up Microsoft could damage the chemistry that
has made an undeniably powerful contribution to the economy. And it
would require the courts to make the unsettling move of telling a
business how to operate.
</P>
<P>
   So-called conduct remedies, having Microsoft agree to fairer
practices, could help to some extent. But this would force the
courts to play czar, spending time and money to become a virtual
regulatory agency in charger of making sure that Microsoft played
by the rules.
</P>
<P>
   The ideal solution is to pursue a settlement that would end the
anticompetitive behavior. Talks between the company, the US Justice
Department, and 19 states' attorney generals broke down last week,
but they should continue.
</P>
<P>
   A multifaceted settlement could offer substantial relief. Fines
would penalize the company for past predatory practices. Customers
would gain if Microsoft were required to share its source code,
enhancing competition in the software market.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Microsoft wins this appeal, it could face future
lawsuits. The wiser move for the sake of the company and American
legal precedent is for Microsoft to make concessions, to become a
far more conciliatory architect of its future.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the courts decide, the arduous proceedings around
United States of America v Microsoft Corp. will show other
companies that there are high costs to anticompetitive behavior
even in the new economy of the age of globalization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 1849EDT &QL; 
