<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7009 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-CLOONEY-DRAMA-NYT &LR;      04-04 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CLOONEY-DRAMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LIVE TV DRAMA IN BLACK AND WHITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., Fail Safe and Fail-Safe are CQ as they appear) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Television's golden age in the 1950s featured live
dramas like ``Marty,'' ``Requiem for a Heavyweight'' and ``Days of
Wine and Roses.'' But by the end of that decade the networks had
veered away from live drama in favor of weekly series, often about
cowboys and cops, that were filmed. Then the move in the 1960s to
Los Angeles from New York as a base for television shows
accelerated the decline of live drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an excitement and danger about live television drama
that was never recaptured,'' said George Clooney, the actor, seated
in his cluttered office at the Warner Brothers studios in Burbank.
``Why not bring back that excitement and danger? Why not stick your
neck out?''
</P>
<P>
   Clooney is, most certainly, sticking his neck out. He is
producing and starring in a highly unusual live drama, ``Fail
Safe,'' based in the 1962 best-selling novel by Harvey Wheeler and
Eugene Burdick. It is about a U.S. bomber that has been
accidentally ordered to deliver a nuclear strike against Moscow.
The novel was also made into an acclaimed film, in 1964, directed
by Sidney Lumet and starring, among others, Henry Fonda and Walter
Matthau.
</P>
<P>
   In the new version, a top-flight cast of actors will appear live
in the drama on CBS on Sunday from 9 to 11 p.m. The same show,
mistakes and all, will be shown on the West Coast, on a delayed
basis, at 9 p.m. local time. (To coincide with the live version of
``Fail Safe,'' Turner Classic Movies will show the 1964 film on the
West Coast at 11:30 p.m. after the live CBS version on Sunday and
on the East Coast at 2:30 a.m. on Monday.)
</P>
<P>
   The new live drama, directed by Stephen Frears (``High
Fidelity,'' ``The Grifters''), includes Noah Wylie ( Clooney's
former co-star on ``E.R.''), Richard Dreyfuss, Hank Azaria, Brian
Dennehy, Harvey Keitel, Don Cheadle, James Cromwell, Sam Elliott
and John Diehl. The show was written by Walter Bernstein, who also
wrote the original screenplay. ``Actually, the movie lends itself
to television,'' Bernstein said. ``There are no big exterior action
sequences. A lot of the scenes are in a bunker, an office or a
cockpit of a plane. The story is the same. The antagonists are the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   By every account, Clooney has been consumed for years with the
notion of doing ``Fail-Safe'' as a live television drama. As a
successful television and film star he finally had the clout to get
the project rolling. ``OK, my stomach, I'm sure, will be in a knot
when we do this,'' he said. ``But the only real downside for me is
one day being 75 years old and sitting in my bed and going, `You
know, I was once this 800-pound gorilla for about five minutes and
I had the opportunity to try and do new things and I was too afraid
to take risks.' My feeling is, `Why not try?'''
</P>
<P>
   Clooney, 38, said he first saw the 1964 film as a child and has
since watched it more than 100 times on videotape. ``It's my
favorite film, a brilliant film about a sacrifice that's almost
biblical,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, he asked his friend Leslie Moonves, president and
chief executive of CBS Television, to pitch a live version of
``Fail-Safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Clooney said: ``He goes, `OK,' and then there was a pause, and I
said, `It's got to be in black and white.' And then Les sort of
groaned a little and then laughed, and said: `OK, but you've got to
be in it too. You can't just produce it.''' Clooney plays a
somewhat secondary role as a pilot, Col. Jack Grady. (Edward Binns
played the part in the 1964 movie.)
</P>
<P>
   Moonves acknowledged that he was nervous about the show. It cost
about $4.5 million, somewhat more than a conventional television
film. ``You're going in without a net, there could be mistakes
made,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I'm doing this is George's passion for it,'' he
added. ``As a producer, he's delivered everything he's promised. We
have a cast _ and a director _ that we never would have gotten if
we were doing a movie-of-the-week. They're doing it because it's
live.''
</P>
<P>
   Moonves said that CBS was now planning a live version of another
drama, ``On Golden Pond,'' starring Julie Andrews, late this year.
``There's no reason we can't do a live drama every year,'' he said.
He said that live television appeals to well-known actors who would
ordinarily avoid television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fail Safe'' is to be broadcast from two sprawling soundstages
on the Warner Brothers lot. One will house the sets of the war room
of the Strategic Air Command as well as a Pentagon office. The
other soundstage includes the bunker of the president, who is
played by Dreyfuss, and the cockpit of a bomber. During the
broadcast, some technicians and camera crew members will be dressed
in military uniforms just in case they inadvertently step before a
camera.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Ziskin, a film producer, said that the live drama was by
necessity far different from the television shows 50 years ago.
``There's a contemporary audience that expects something visually
and cinematically interesting,'' she said. ``It's a bigger
undertaking. Most of those shows were not anywhere near as
ambitious.''
</P>
<P>
   If an actor forgets a line or trips over a wire? ``You
proceed,'' she said. ``It is what it is. In that way, it's
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Frears, whose latest film, ``High Fidelity,'' opened on Friday,
said he took over the staging of ``Fail Safe'' because ``it was an
adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been done very often,'' he said. ``My concerns are,
of course, that an actor will fluff his lines or face the wrong
camera. But there's nothing I can do about that. And we have very
good actors.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that underlying the project was a powerful sense of
admiration among the cast and crew for the live dramatic shows
shown on television in the 1950s. ``What they did was
extraordinary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wylie, who plays a translator for the president, said that the
rehearsal process was more like working in theater than in films or
television. ``You're able to give an uninterrupted performance,''
he said. ``You're doing it completely in continuity. If you stay in
character without distraction you can give a pretty cohesive
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Wylie was in the highly publicized live broadcast of ``E.R.'' in
1997. That show was criticized for being more gimmicky than
dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't work,'' said Clooney, who had pushed for that live
episode. ``It shouldn't have been in color. We shouldn't have tried
to replicate the show. OK, I'll take the knock, fair enough. But we
gave it a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he had been obsessed with live television since his
childhood, when his father, Nick Clooney, who is now a host on the
American Movie Classics cable network, worked for a television
station in Cincinnati. ``At 12 I was a floor director and my sister
was the cue card girl and my dad was doing a live variety show,''
said Clooney. ``I remember standing next to the cameras while he
was reading off these old teleprompters and there was this horrible
thing in my mind which said, `If I wanted I could go right in front
of the camera right now and yell the most unprintable things.'''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was not worried about the prospect of on-camera
mistakes. ``Actors have a good survival instinct,'' he said.
``We've all done theater. We've all made mistakes onstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, you know, you just can't walk off. You figure it
out and get out of it somehow. More than likely the audience won't
know you made a mistake. At least I hope they won't know.''
</P>
<P>
   dw
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
