<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7016 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-2     04-04 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, April 9,
2000. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE Story &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-PHOTOGRAPHERS (Washington) _ ``Reflections in Black: A
History of Black Photographers, 1840 to the Present,'' an
exhibition through June 30 at the Arts and Industries building of
the Smithsonian Institution here, is a history with a provocative
notion at its core: that at various times, but especially in the
first several decades of the 20th century, American blacks used
photography to resist the image the dominant culture imposed on
them. Without a common program, perhaps even without a fully
conscious intent, people all over the nation devised a way to see
themselves as they were or wished to be, no matter what white
society had in mind. By Vicki Goldberg. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOE-GOULD'S-SECRET-FILM (Undated) _ ``Joe Gould's Secret'' is an
odd book to want to make a movie of. It is a classic of sorts, by
one of the most revered of the old New Yorker writers, Joseph
Mitchell; and until the book-length version was republished
recently by the Modern Library, copies of the original magazine
articles, bleary from over-Xeroxing, were passed around in certain
circles like samizdat. Stanley Tucci, produced, directed and star
in ``Joe Gould's Secret,'' which opened Friday. He and his
screenwriter, Howard A. Rodman, have created a film version that is
earnest and intelligent and, for the most part, painstakingly
faithful to the facts. By Charles McGrath. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DUCHOVNY-FILMS (Los Angeles) _ It's a Tuesday morning on the set
of ``The X-Files'' and David Duchovny is working three jobs. He has
just changed out of his FBI agent suit _ the uniform for the
brooding but sartorially conformist Fox Mulder _ into an orange
T-shirt and jeans, director chic. A Princeton undergraduate, Yale
graduate, Manhattan, Scots-Jewish, Leo, he enjoys contact sports
and yoga. At this point no one knows for sure how much longer
Duchovny will be a part of ``The X-Files,'' Fox's most popular
drama series, or even if this is the show's last season altogether.
They just know he's been spending a lot of time publicizing his new
movie, ``Return to Me,'' a romantic comedy about a heart
transplant. Is film his future? Or can he never escape the
identification with Mulder, a strangely emotionless man obsessed by
government conspiracies, space aliens and his sister? And most
important, is he a truly talented actor or just a really lucky guy
who got cast as the one character he was born to play? By Anita
Gates. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CORPORATE-FILMS (Undated) _ Midway through ``Erin Brockovich,''
I began to peel off from that hugely likable movie and consider its
curious new genre, whose template has already hardened. Once again,
as in ``The Rainmaker'' and ``A Civil Action,'' a David law firm
was suing a Goliath corporation on behalf of the company's victims.
Once again, the corporation was responding with a conspiracy of
silence and intimidation. And once again I had that uneasy feeling
that something was missing: a credible, complex opponent. By
Phillip Lopate. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OM-PURI-FILMS (New York) _ Although Om Puri has appeared, by his
own estimate, in something like 140 films in his 24-year screen
career and has been characterized by one expert on Indian cinema as
``the finest actor of the post-independence generation,'' he does
not expect to be recognized on the streets of New York. But when he
and I step out for a cigarette in front of the SoHo Grand Hotel, a
middle-aged man and woman strolling up West Broadway look startled,
walk a few steps farther up the street, and then, after a fast
conference, return to tell Puri how impressed they had been by his
performance in ``East Is East'' (opening Friday), which they had
seen in Israel. By Terrence Rafferty. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ZE'EVA-COHEN-DANCE (New York) _ The dances of the Israeli-born
choreographer Ze'eva Cohen focus on women, contemporary, ancient
and mythical. Some of the women are feisty, some are noble. All,
ultimately, are tragic: they dance as an act of resistance against
straitened circumstance or passing time, as if they were singing
private songs in a desert. Five of the 40 works Cohen has
choreographed since 1968, collected under the title ``Female
Mythologies,'' will be performed at Danspace Project in St. Mark's
Church in Manhattan from Thursday through Sunday. By Mindy Aloff.
WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HAYLEY-MILLS-THEATER (Undated) _ Given her theatrical pedigree,
Hayley Mills must be aware of more than a few show business maxims.
For example: try to avoid following a tough act, and, there is no
tougher act than a cute kid. But what happens when you're your own
toughest act to follow? In one way, Mills has already found out,
having worked on the London stage for the last 30 years. But in
this country she is still best known as that saucer-eyed little
girl in such popular Disney films as ``Pollyanna'' (for which she
won a special 1960 Academy Award), ``The Parent Trap'' (1961) and
``That Darn Cat'' (1965). If Mills has her way, her New York stage
debut will begin the third act of what has already been a long
career. The London-born actress, who turns 54 next week, opens
Monday at the Lucille Lortel Theater in ``Noel Coward's Suite in
Two Keys,'' an evening of two one-act plays directed by John
Tillinger. By Steven Drukman. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WILD-PARTY-THEATER (New York) _ In the summer of 1926, Joseph
Moncure March, something of a rebel at 26, sat down at a battered
kitchen table in his airless $20-a-month walkup on West 14th Street
in Manhattan to write a narrative in verse about ``a lot of people
getting drunk at a party,'' a subject he had come to know very
well. The result, ``The Wild Party,'' is, as almost everyone knows
by now, the source and title of two musicals this season: one, by
Andrew Lippa, ends its run this Sunday at the Manhattan Theater
Club at City Center; the other, co-produced by the Joseph Papp
Public Theater, is to open on Thursday at the Virginia Theater on
Broadway. With music and lyrics by Michael John LaChiusa and
directed by George C. Wolfe, it stars Mandy Patinkin, Toni Collette
and Eartha Kitt. By Maura Spiegel. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SULLIVAN-MUSIC (Undated) _ A look at Sir Arthur Sullivan's
music, expecially ``The Lost Chord,'' which was inspired by the new
music from France, with its murky chromatic harmony and langid
sensuality. By Anthony Tommasini.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARLAND-WORLD-MUSIC-BOOK (Undated) _ The Garland World Music
Encyclopedia, a projected 10-volume series of telephone-book-size
reference works from Routledge started appearing in 1998. Six
volumes have been published; the two volumes just released, on
Europe and South Asia, are up to the level set by their
predecessors, on Africa, Southeast Asia, Australia and the Pacific
Islands and South America, Mexico, Central America and the
Caribbean. Don't spend too much time fussing here about the loaded
term ``world music.'' In this case it is not a naive stand-in for
``music that North Americans consider foreign''; it literally means
music made all over the world, including here. By Ben Ratliff. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EXIT-ART-CENTER (New York) _ In New York, some seemingly
well-financed art centers flounder or disappear even after
presenting good, memorable shows. And then there are the offbeat,
sometimes more impulsive art outposts that pop up and, despite the
odds, hang on for years and unexpectedly become important, even
treasured institutions. Exit Art/The First World is one such
irascible survivor. Now, with a retrospective exhibition entitled
``The End: An Independent Vision of Contemporary Culture,
1982-2000,'' the nonprofit arts center that has become an essential
stop for many art professionals and art enthusiasts alike is
celebrating _ and dutifully analyzing _ its own history since its
founding 18 years ago. By Edward M. Gomez. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FACT-FICTION-ART (San Francisco) _ At a time when ``based on
real-life events!'' and ``a true story!'' are the most popular
come-ons for everything from memoirs to movies, an entertaining
show at the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art investigates
contemporary artists' fascination with the opposite tactics of
fakery, disguise and deceit. The exhibition, titled ``Fact/Fiction:
Contemporary Art That Walks the Line,'' presents 82 works that
embrace the appearance and techniques of realism, yet delight in
exposing realism as just another deception. ``Fact/Fiction'' runs
through next Sunday. By Tessa DeCarlo. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHINESE-STOOLS-ART (New York) _ William Lipton remembers the
first time he saw Chinese stools. It was the late 1950s, and he was
5. A pair of barrel-shaped stools, in blue and white porcelain,
flanked the sofa in his grandmother's parlor in Dallas. Lipton has
no idea today what became of the stools, family heirlooms that were
trophies of a trip around the world made by a
great-great-grandfather in 1887. Then, on a first visit to China in
1979, when Lipton was a textile designer working for Jim Thompson
Ltd. in Bangkok, stools loomed large again. In Beijing he saw a
towering pile of weathered wood stools, with elegantly carved
aprons and legs, with hoof feet, scrolled feet and flat feet
protruding here and there from a stack that looked like a bizarre
offering to the gods of good taste. The memory of that scene stayed
with him. He became an antiques dealer in 1989, ultimately
specializing in Chinese furniture. Four years ago he began to
assemble as many examples of stools ``with personality'' as he
could find for a show on a form of furniture that is the most
humble and versatile of all in China but is rarely exhibited. He
selected 92 of them for ``The Wondrous and Amenable Chinese
Stool,'' an exhibition at his shop, William Lipton Ltd., in
Manhattan, through April 22. By Rita Reif. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OLSHER-RADIO-SHOW (New York) _ Most radio shows are as
predictable as sunrise. Dean Olsher 36, has decided to surprise
listeners by following his own fancy. Olsher, a former cultural
correspondent for National Public Radio, will be the host of ``The
Next Big Thing,'' a one-hour weekend program that will go on the
air this summer on WNYC. By Valerie Galdstone. WITH PHOTO. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-MEN-COMEDIES (Undated) _ Men in a growing number of comedies
are depicted as rude, crude, sex-crazed, sexist, childish and
blindly egotistical. The curmudgeonly title character of ``Becker''
(Ted Danson), a middle-aged doctor, says things like: ``If you want
to know about women, you don't ask a woman. If you want to know
about meat, do you ask a cow?'' On ``Friends,'' Joey eats steak
with his fingers at Ross's wedding reception. Prime time gives us
grown men who can't stop giggling in church, bawdy male magazine
publishers married to women half their age and men who stick
Montblanc pens up their noses in order to meet women in the
emergency room. Anyone who watches television regularly could get
the impression that one of the two sexes on this planet is not only
dimwitted and uncouth but darned proud of it. By Anita Gates. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
