<P>
   MEXICO-ENVIRON (Iguala, Mexico) _ Humble Mexicans who stand in
the way of profiteering from the country's natural resources have
often faced brutal treatment, but one such man, Rudolfo Montiel,
has discovered in recent days that he has international friends to
help him fight his cause. Montiel organized peasants to block roads
after loggers began felling virgin forests around his village in
the mountains north of Acapulco. Last Friday, Amnesty International
declared Montiel, who is now in prison, a prisoner of conscience,
provoking a flood of protest letters to the Mexican authorities.
And on Wednesday, a San Francisco foundation is to announce that it
has awarded him a $125,000 environmental prize. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
