<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: TBS MARKETING STRATEGY; WB CARTOONS; DIVERSITY AT CBS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   REGULAR GUYS? THEY'RE BACK
</P>
<P>
   Executives at TBS Superstation , which 25 years ago was Ted
Turner's first foray into the television business, are plotting an
image makeover for their cable network in an attempt to draw the
disenfranchised American male.
</P>
<P>
   TBS executives plan to announce Wednesday that the
general-interest station will be repackaged as a haven for average
men who, the executives maintain, have been left out of the recent
marketing frenzy that is targeting societal niches that were
neglected back when everything was directed, in fact, at regular
guys.
</P>
<P>
   The makeover will begin with a advertising campaign intended to
make these men associate the station with their tastes and will
continue with new programming deemed attractive to men.
</P>
<P>
   ``For so long, these regular guys were sort of Americana, if you
will,'' said Constance Barkley-Lewis, senior vice president for
marketing at TBS. ``Everybody has been very niche-focused, and
these guys got lost in the mix. The regular guy wasn't very cool
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   That, she said, is fine by the regular guy because ``he doesn't
aspire to be cool anymore; he just wants to be considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has really simple needs and we want to fulfill them.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the ``regular guy'' label may sound slightly amorphous _
for instance, he is not given an exact age range _ the network's
president, Dennis G. Quinn, said he had a good idea about who this
guy was.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are real, regular guys,'' Quinn said. ``You know, when
you hang around your buddies and you say, `What's Charlie like?,'
and it's, `Ah, he's a regular guy.' A regular guy would be the guy
who would be married to the soccer mom. I would have to say that
they're B students.''
</P>
<P>
   Think Terry Bradshaw meets Tim Allen, he said. A bonus for
advertisers, he said, is that these men watch television with their
families, so the network will be viewed by them and their wives and
children.
</P>
<P>
   TBS, the highest-rated cable network among adults, was already
drawing in these John Does with wrestling, NBA games, auto races
and the ``Movies for Guys Who Like Movies'' franchise. Next year
the executives plan to add reruns of supposedly regular-guy shows
like ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' ``The Drew Carey Show,'' ``Home
Improvement,'' ``Friends'' and ``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   The TBS campaign will promote masculine network programming and
feature the tag line ``It's your world. We're just programming
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Quinn is to outline this strategy for advertisers Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jim Rutenberg
</P>
<P>
   FRATURDAY TOONS
</P>
<P>
   The WB network, which quickly established itself as the leader
in the arena of child viewers of Saturday morning cartoons,
announced a new lineup Tuesday that once again emphasized just how
important one segment of the children's audience is to network
programmers: boys.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new cartoons being added by WB on Saturday are a
series based on the acrobatic action pyrotechnics of the movie star
Jackie Chan, a new show about the popular X-Men taking cartoon
teen-agers into a world of genetic mutations, and, in a first, an
action cartoon with an African-American superhero.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Donna Friedman, the senior vice president of
Kids WB, as the network's children's programming department is
known, announced an expansion of the network's Saturday morning
franchise into a new area: Friday afternoons. ``We're saying that
Saturday morning begins on Friday afternoon,'' Friedman said.
</P>
<P>
   The network introduced a schedule of four new cartoons, anchored
by a spinoff of its breakout hit ``Pokemon,'' to play from 3 to 5
p.m. on Fridays. Friedman said the new programming block was being
called ``Fraturday'' to emphasize the connection to Saturday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   It is not meant to evoke a frat house mentality, she said except
``in the way that it's all about fun.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Friday programming is supposed to be ``gender
neutral,'' as she put it, while the powerhouse Saturday lineup
continues to be ``boys first, with girls right there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saturday shows are heavily skewed toward ``action and
adventure,'' she said, which she said targeted young male
audiences, while Friday shows are ``more about heart and character,
which appeals to girls.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saturday shows already included such action-oriented shows
as ``Batman Beyond,'' ``Max Steel'' and ``Men in Black.'' Added to
that will be ``Jackie Chan Adventures,'' in which the cartoon
version of the star will share ancient Chinese wisdom, and
acrobatic action, with Chan's 11-year-old tomboy niece.
</P>
<P>
   ``Static Shock'' will feature the adventures of Virgil Hawkins,
a black teen-ager with electromagnetic superpowers.
</P>
<P>
   Saturdays and Fridays will include editions of ``Pokemon GS,''
the spinoff of the big children's hit, which will get a sendoff in
a new ``Pokemon'' movie this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The ``gender-neutral'' Friday shows are to include
``Cardcaptors,'' a combination of ``Pokemon'' and ``Harry Potter,''
about a 10-year-old girl named Sukura and wizards and magical
cards. Another new show is ``Generation O,'' about the lead girl
singer of a rock group. The third is ``The Zeta Project,'' about a
renegade robot.
</P>
<P>
   The WB's Saturday morning ratings have grown this year with the
network surpassing Nickelodeon as the leader with child viewers on
Saturday mornings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Carter
</P>
<P>
   DIVERSITY CHIEF
</P>
<P>
   CBS on Tuesday became the second network to name an executive to
be especially in charge of diversity issues when it elevated Josie
Thomas from vice president for business affairs for CBS News to the
new position of senior vice president, diversity.
</P>
<P>
   In March, NBC named Paula Madison, the news director for its
station in New York, WNBC, as vice president for diversity. Madison
will remain in her position at Channel 4, however.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS spokesman said that Thomas would also remain an adviser to
Andrew Heyward, the president of CBS News, for business affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Both positions were created as part of the networks' extensive
agreements with the NAACP to seek solutions to hiring and
programming issues involving minorities.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Carter
</P>
<P>
   bl
</P>
