<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7032 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-HOUSE-ABORTION-HNS &LR;      04-04 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-ABORTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HOUSE REPUBLICANS AGAIN FOCUS ON LATE-TERM ABORTION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans geared up Tuesday for an
election-year fight over abortion as they prepare to vote for the
third time on whether to ban a controversial late-term procedure
called ``partial-birth abortion'' by its critics.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation appears doomed again this year because President
Clinton has pledged to veto any late-term abortion measure, as he
did in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   This expected fate has led some Democrats to accuse Republicans
of raising the issue again so that they will have an attractive
political issue this election year.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nita Lowey, D-N.Y., who opposes the ban, said Republicans
are bringing the measure up before the elections for ``purely
political'' reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they know they're going to lose, why are they doing this?''
Lowey said. ``It's clearly because they want a political issue. By
discussing this and showing the pictures (of the procedure), they
are appealing to the emotions of people.''
</P>
<P>
   A vote is expected Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   House debate over the procedure is always passionate and
graphic, with supporters of a ban arguing that the method is
gruesome and unnecessary and likening it to infanticide. The
late-term abortion targeted by the bill involves a surgical
procedure where the skull of the fetus is crushed while still in
the womb, killing the fetus. The body is then extracted through the
birth canal.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion rights supporters say the procedure is rare and that
the legislation is too vaguely worded and would weaken Roe v. Wade,
the Supreme Court's 1973 decision establishing a constitutional
right to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Richard K. Armey, R-Texas, insisted
Tuesday that the vote is more than symbolic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot in good conscience not have this vote, given the
strong feelings we have,'' Armey said. ``There is a nation full of
people that are appalled by this procedure and Congress is
committed to stopping it.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a January CNN-USA Today Gallup Poll of 1,027
people, 64 percent of respondents said they favored a law banning
``partial-birth'' abortion, while 31 percent said they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton says he objects to the legislation on the basis that it
did not include adequate exceptions to protect the health of the
mother. The House overrode both of Clinton's earlier vetoes but the
Senate fell short of the two-thirds majority needed for an
override.
</P>
<P>
   The surgical procedure, known by doctors as dilation and
extraction, involves partially extracting a fetus through the birth
canal, collapsing the skull and draining its contents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There ought to be a line somewhere _ and this is over the
line, in my opinion,'' said House Judiciary Chairman Henry J. Hyde,
R-Ill. ``This is really indefensible.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Canady, R-Fla., who has crusaded for the ban since
Republicans took over the House in 1995, conceded the chances of
the measure becoming law this year are slim.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand it's an uphill battle in the Senate and it's an
uphill battle with the president,'' Canady said. ``We're going to
give this our best shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would allow the procedure only to save the woman's
life. Earlier versions of the legislation would have followed a
more liberal rule, allowing the procedure when the woman's health
was endangered.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone performing such an abortion in violation of the law could
face up to two years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address Judy(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
