<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-MEXICO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEXAS FARMERS TO LOBBY IN WASHINGTON FOR WATER FROM MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A battle over water rights between Texas and Mexico
has prompted angry farmers from the Lone Star State to come here to
lobby lawmakers and State Department diplomats on Wednesday and
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Texans will urge the officials to prod Mexico into giving
drought-stricken American farmers in the Rio Grande valley water
they say the nation owes them.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992 Mexico has transferred to the United States less than
half the water it should have under a treaty between the two
countries. As a result, Texas farmers have lost an estimated $400
million a year from crop failures, according to JoJo White, a
farmer from Mercedes, Texas, which is about five miles from the
Mexico border. White is also chairman of the Water Treaty Committee
for the Water Districts Managers Association, which apportions
water for the lower Rio Grande valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we are screaming for water, and they're not letting it go
through,'' he complained in a telephone interview Tuesday before
leaving for Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He and four others will discuss the problem with State
Department officials and with Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchinson, R-Texas,
and Democratic Reps. Ruben Hinojosa and Solomon Ortiz and
Republican Rep. Henry Bonilla, all of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A 1944 treaty allotted water from parts of the Colorado and Rio
Grande rivers in the United States to Mexico. It also guaranteed
the United States at least 350,000 acre-feet of water a year from
Mexican tributaries that feed into the Rio Grande.
</P>
<P>
   An acre-foot is 325,889 gallons, enough to cover one acre of
land with one foot of water.
</P>
<P>
   Under the pact, each country transfers certain required amounts
of water by the end of a five-year period except in cases of
extreme hardship.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1992 and 1997 Mexico transferred 41 percent of the water
mandated by the treaty, saying it could not transfer the rest
because of an ``extraordinary drought.'' It said in 1997 that it
should be able to repay its debt over the next five-year period
ending Oct. 2, 2002.
</P>
<P>
   But a study by the R.J. Brandes Co., an Austin-based engineering
consulting firm specializing in water resources, said last December
that Mexico had received 81.4 percent of its average rainfall
between 1992 and 1997 and had extra water in its basins during
those years.
</P>
<P>
   Several calls to the Mexican embassy here and a consular office
in Chicago failed to elicit a response to questions about the
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   In the past Mexico has argued that it is undergoing a worse
drought now than it did in the prior five-year cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, however, it transferred 41,000 acre-feet of water
to Texas. Also, the International Boundary and Water Commission,
which oversees treaty compliance, announced that Mexico had agreed
to transfer another 97,000 acre-feet of water soon.
</P>
<P>
   But White said that since 1997 Mexico's water debt has grown
more than 400,000 acre-feet to a total debt of 1.44 million
acre-feet, Rio Grande farmers fear Mexico may not be able to repay
them fully by the 2002 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The huge volume that is now owed us is rapidly growing, and if
they don't start paying it, they will be in a (definite) treaty
violation,'' White said. ``We need a minimum of 400,000 acre-feet
right now to prevent serious economic losses,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Tuesday that ``Mexico needs to live up to its obligations
under the treaty.'' He said U.S. diplomats have reminded the
Mexican ambassador and Mexico's undersecretary of foreign relations
of this obligation in recent meetings.
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920).
</P>
</TEXT>
