<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7040 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SUPREMES-ART-NYT &LR;      04-04 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPREMES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOP! IN THE NAME OF NOSTALGIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Nev., Calif., Scotland)  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Diana Ross and the Supremes are back, at least in
name. The trio is to tour arenas this summer with two singers who
joined the Supremes after Ross left the group in 1970. The
reconstituted Supremes are to perform '60s hits like ``Where Did
Our Love Go,'' ``I Hear a Symphony,'' ``Baby Love'' and ``You Keep
Me Hangin' On.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at Grand Central Terminal Tuesday, Ross
announced an arena tour to start on June 14 in Philadelphia and end
on Aug. 15 in Las Vegas; it plays Madison Square Garden on July 6.
Ross, who has sung medleys of Supremes songs on her solo tours,
said she would be performing the songs complete for the first time
in 30 years. ``It was hard for me to step back into being part of a
group,'' she said. ``But people said it looked easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross took pains to say that the tour was not a reunion. The
backup Supremes, Lynda Laurence and Scherrie Payne, joined the
group in 1971 and 1973 respectively. Mary Wilson, who founded the
group as the Primettes with Ross in 1959 and had stayed in
successive lineups of the Supremes, is not part of the tour; nor is
Cindy Birdsong, who replaced the Supremes' other founding member,
Florence Ballard, in 1967. ( Ballard died in 1976.) Birdsong is now
a minister in Los Angeles. She and Wilson last sang with Ross for
the ``Motown 25'' television special in 1983. Ross had not
performed with her new Supremes until they taped an appearance on
Oprah, to be broadcast Wednesday. They will also perform together
on VH1's ``Divas 2000'' tribute to Ross, to be broadcast on
Tuesday. Further tour information is available on the tour's Web
site: www.dianarossandthesupremes.net.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Glasgow, where she was performing,
Wilson said she had not been contacted until months after she began
hearing about plans for a Supremes tour last year. After she
complained to her manager and the tour's promoters, TNA
International Ltd., Ross called her. ``I was very offended that she
had not called me in an entire year to say, `Hey, don't you want to
do this tour?''' Wilson said. ``She said we should get together,
but I said we should work out the business first.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said she had been offered $2 million to join the tour,
and then $3 million, ``take it or leave it.'' ``I don't think
that's the way you approach someone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said she thought she deserved a larger proportion of the
performance fees, which she believed were $15 million to $20
million. Arthur Fogel, the president of TNA, said that those
figures were incorrect but declined to specify them, saying his
company never publicly discussed deal terms. ``Over several weeks
we conducted a sincere attempt to come to terms with Mary,'' Fogel
said. ``We all tried our best, and sometimes it just doesn't
happen. We feel we were fair and reasonable and respectful.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said: ``I've been the keeper of the Supremes for 30
years, maintaining it on such a high level that she could come back
and have a reunion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hired these two women in the 1970s,'' she said, referring to
Long and Payne. ``I taught them, I invested in the gowns, I did
everything.'' She later sued to prevent them from touring as the
Supremes without her.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my friends said, `Girl, you should just take the
money and run,''' Wilson said. ``But my heart has been broken. I've
turned the cheek many many times. I don't need to get back in that
same situation and make myself unhappy. That would have killed me
like it killed Florence.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross said: ``The tour is not about me, it's not about
individuals. It really is a celebration of the music.''
</P>
<P>
   dw
</P>
</TEXT>
