<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7042 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SEX-TRADE-0405-COX     04-04 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-TRADE-0405-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WOMEN TELL OF BEING FORCED INTO SEXUAL SERVITUDE
 &HT;    (550&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Her face obscured by a large scarf and her eyes
hidden behind dark glasses, a soft-spoken Mexican woman told a
Senate panel Tuesday of her nightmare that began when, at age 18,
she had been lured into Florida with the promise of a job. Once
there, she was brutally beaten and forced to become a prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   Hers seemed only a rare and horrible story in 1998 when law
enforcement officials discovered the trailer-brothels, where Maria,
as she calls herself, and 16 other women were heavily guarded and
constantly moved around Florida and South Carolina to service
migrant workers.
</P>
<P>
   But such sexual servitude is no longer seen as a rarity,
witnesses told the Senate Foreign Relations subcommittee on Near
Eastern and South Asian Affairs. It is now a growing worldwide
trend which is highly profitable and rarely prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is profoundly troubling,'' William R. Yeomans, chief of
staff for the Civil Rights Division of the U.S. Justice Department.
``We are talking about slavery _ slavery in its modern
manifestation.''
</P>
<P>
   Although exact numbers are not known, officials believe that at
least 700,000 women and children are transported for involuntary
prostitution worldwide each year. In the United States, the number
is thought to be 50,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a phenomenon that doesn't really look like anything
we've seen before,'' said Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kan., a
conservative who called the hearing along with a liberal ally, Sen.
Paul Wellstone, D-Wis.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the darkest aspects of the globalization of the
world economy,'' Wellstone said in pledging to join efforts behind
legislation to crack down on traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Current laws don't have enough teeth to bring perpetrators to
justice, Yeomans and others told the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   In her testimony, delivered through translation, Maria said she
disguised her identity out of fear of her former captives, most of
whom remain free. Six, including ringleader Rogerio Cadena, were
convicted in federal district court in West Palm Beach, Fla., last
year. But at least 10 more are thought to live near her family in
Veracruz, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia P. Coto, who is the lawyer for Maria and 13 other
victims of the Cadena trafficking ring, said current laws didn't
provide stiff enough sentences. ``Two defendants got two years for
enslaving these girls,'' said Coto, who works with the Florida
Immigrant Advocacy Center in Miami. ``That's really disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   Coto read testimony from another of Cadena's victim, who told of
being 14 years old in Veracruz when a man came to her home and
convinced her that she could find a good job in the United States.
She was smuggled to Orlando, where she told of being raped
repeatedly by her smugglers and forced into prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel shame,'' she read from the statement. ``I was a
decent girl in Mexico. I used to go to church with my family.''
</P>
<P>
   For all of its tragedy, the Cadena case is considered relatively
successful because at least some of the criminals were prosecuted.
In another exceptional case, the leader of an Asian prostitution
ring pleaded guilty in Atlanta last January to forcing Asian women
and girls into prostitution.
</P>
<P>
   But such examples are still the exception, both in the United
States and in other countries that are the ``destinations'' for
sexual trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   At the Senate hearing, two Russian victims, who also kept their
identities secret, said that they had also been tricked into going
abroad in search of better jobs. One was lured to Israel, the other
to Germany, and both were forced to become prostitutes before they
escaped.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really pains me is those responsible remained completely
unpunished,'' said Marsha, from southern Russia, who was in a
brothel when German police raided it. She was never given a chance
to explain that she was there under duress. ``Instead, I was
charged with prostitution and held in a jail cell.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor do Russian authorities act to stop human trafficking, the
senators were told by Khodyreva Natalia, the director of a Crisis
Center for Women in St. Petersburg, Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what they would like to see happen now, Maria told the
hearing her wish was ``to help protect young women like ourselves''
by halting the trafficking and publicizing the dangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let mothers know so they will protect their young children,''
she said.
</P>
