<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROKERS-SELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST PROFESSIONAL ADVICE: STAY CALM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES STEIN AND STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Karen Oslo, a legal secretary at Ropes and Gray &UR;  &LR; in Boston, has
been checking the markets every hour on the Internet since the
Nasdaq Composite index began its wild ride two weeks ago. Despite
losses on some high-tech stocks in her portfolio and concerns about
a technology-heavy mutual fund in her 401(k) plan, she is holding
fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all been talking about what to do,'' she said of her
colleagues in a similar position. ``But nobody here is going to
pull their money out right now. This might change the way we do
some things in the future, but it doesn't seem smart to panic right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Oslo is a financial planner's dream. Her response to
Tuesday's stomach-turning day in the stock market _ doing nothing _
is exactly what most specialists recommend. That was hard to do as
the Nasdaq index dropped more than 13 percent at one point, only to
rally and close down less than 2 percent for the day. The Nasdaq,
home to most technology stocks, fell 7.6 percent Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The professionals say investors should stay calm, take a deep
breath, and avoid sudden moves they may later regret. ``My main
advice would be not to panic,'' said Ned Riley, a longtime tracker
of the stock market and chief investment strategist at State Street
Global Advisors in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Like the games in the recent NCAA basketball tournament, the
stock market is virtually impossible to predict, even for the most
sophisticated among us. As a result, say the planners, investors
should avoid extreme bets and be prepared to cope with whatever the
market offers up.
</P>
<P>
   What else should investors do? A group of stock market veterans
interviewed made the following suggestions. They said you should:
</P>
<P>
   --Use the current period of volatility to reassess your
holdings. ``If the events of last two days will make it hard for
you to pay your mortgage, you don't have the right portfolio,''
said Maureen Allyn, chief economist at Scudder Kemper Investments,
a mutual fund company.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks are inherently risky, especially in the short-term, and
investors who can't handle that risk _ either financially or
emotionally _ need to make adjustments. John Burk knows that
feeling. A local record company executive, he got out of high-tech
stocks after he was burned on one bad investment. ``I found out I
don't have the time or stomach for high-tech,'' he said. ``I leave
that for people who are willing to stay on top of it.''
</P>
<P>
   --Make sure you are diversified. Diversification is the golden
rule in investing. Don't have all your eggs in one basket. It is
boring advice, but sound advice, say planners. Since no one can
accurately forecast which sectors of the market will do best, it
pays to have some money in different areas.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Glovsky, president of Mintz Levin Financial Advisors, notes
that many old-economy stocks have rallied over the past two weeks,
even as high-tech stocks have been heading in the opposite
direction. ``This has been a perfect illustration of why you need a
balanced portfolio,'' said Glovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Planners say this is no time to bail out of technology,
altogether. Over time many technology stocks will perform
splendidly and investors want to benefit from that performance. The
trick is not to be so overweighted in technology that you subject
yourself to excessive risk.
</P>
<P>
   Planners recommend a blend of not just old- and new-economy
stocks, but small-company and large-company stocks, and domestic
and international stocks. Most mutual fund companies have
recommendations on their Web sites for how to apportion assets.
</P>
<P>
   --Think long term. Glovsky tells clients they should not be in
the stock market unless they are willing to stay invested for at
least five years. ``Anything less and you should not be in the
market in the first place,'' he said. Over most, though not all,
long stretches of time, stocks have outperformed other types of
investments. It is worth pointing out that even after the decline
of the past week, the Nasdaq index is up 62 percent over the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   Riley says the extreme ups and downs of the past few weeks may
have taught investors a lesson that has been forgotten in the
euphoria of the past few years: That stocks can go down and up, and
that there is risk and reward in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   That was a lesson that Jon Burk, a Boston record company
executive, learned even before he watched Tuesday's market plunge.
Like many investors trying to ride the Nasdaq's coat tails, he
acted on a tip from a friend and put $5,000 into a local computer
company startup, only to say the stock go into the tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got burned, and I found out I don't have the time or the
stomach for high-tech,'' he said. ``I don't want to be in having to
check on how it's doing day by day and hour by hour. It's too much
like gambling. I leave that for people who are willing to stay on
top of it all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   While he kept some money in higher-risk stocks, he switched most
of it to blue chips before the markets' wild see-sawing began early
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer the pragmatic, cautious approach,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's plunge may have a similar effect on legions of other
investors who have trolled the technology stocks for fast, easy
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we wring out some of the casino mentality, that will be a
good thing,'' Riley said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
