<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7047 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-CATALAN-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      04-04 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATALAN-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOTTSDALE BUSINESSMAN SHARES ELIAN'S DILEMMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSE CATALAN  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - Like Elian Gonzalez, I was six when I left
Cuba alone for Miami. I arrived, not clinging to a broken raft,
thank God, but aboard a Pan Am prop aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   I was alone. My parents could not afford to take care of both my
2-year-old brother and me on Papa's $20 a week and Mama's
occasional sewing jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1950, nine years before Fidel Castro came to power, my
family's life in Havana was not too different than it is today for
most people in Cuba. If you're born poor, you die poor.
</P>
<P>
   My parents hoped that by sending me to Miami to live with my
``rich'' aunt and uncle, I would find a better life. I remember
Mama and Papa crying at the airport, repeating, ``Pepito, you'll
have a better life there.'' At six, I did not know what a better
life meant, particularly without my parents.
</P>
<P>
   All I remember about those days in Miami was going to the beach
practically every day, which I loved for about one week. ``We've
much better beaches in Cuba,'' I told everyone who would listen.
Most of all, I hated the food. Hamburgers and french fries was
about all I ate.
</P>
<P>
   I remember crying day and night while my aunt and uncle tried to
understand this Cuban kid who spoke only Spanish and refused to say
even ``yes,'' much less ``thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   They would take me to the movies to watch a comedy and I would
cry. At the restaurants I would scream. In the supermarket, I would
throw temper tantrums. I was far from adorable yet I knew exactly
what I was doing. I wanted to go home to my parents.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, my frustrated aunt and uncle sent me back to
Havana, suntan and all. Likely as it will be with Elian, I was
happy to return to Cuba. I was back to our one-room home in a
run-down building in Old Havana, near prostitutes and pimps. The
toilet and shower, which we shared with five other families, were
down the hall, just where I fondly remembered. I could go back to
eating ``arroz con frijoles,'' and from time to time a piece of
chicken. I was back in heaven, my heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later I was longing for hamburgers and fries, for
carefree days on the beaches of Miami. For a toilet I did not have
to share with 20 people, especially when I had to go really bad. It
took me this long to admit that this Havana I returned to was not
as great as I remembered. I had had a taste of life in America and
I wanted it back!
</P>
<P>
   I started a plan. In school, I would be the best student of the
English language, which was a challenge. I began to write nice
letters to my aunt and uncle, using the English I was slowly
acquiring.
</P>
<P>
   At 13, I started working days to save money and going to school
at night. I kept up with life in America watching ``I Love Lucy''
on TV. It was not exactly as I remembered life in America but
that's what I wanted.
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half later, Castro came to power on New Year's Day.
Everyone thought our worries were over. He promised us poor Cubans
a life of dignity and freedom. No more poverty, too, my parents
believed. I still wanted to leave Cuba. To that Bali Hai I called
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The process of leaving Castro's Cuba became a horrendous ordeal.
My parents decided I needed to leave first because, at 15, I was
approaching military age. Mama arranged for a religious group to
assist with the expenses, which for us was insurmountable. They
coordinated all of the contacts with the Cuban and U.S.
governments.
</P>
<P>
   Every step of the way the Communist bureaucracy made sure we
felt like outcasts. ``Gusanos _'' worms _ they called us. Standing
in long lines at the passport office, my mother and I endured angry
protesters who dared us to return their insults, knowing full well
that, if we did, we would be automatically jailed for disrupting
the peace and banned from leaving the island. The lines and insults
were repeated every step of the way, including the KLM airline
ticket office.
</P>
<P>
   In 1961, at age 16, I finally left Cuba to re-join my aunt and
uncle, who were now living in Puerto Rico, a U.S. possession. I was
still without my parents, but by now I appreciated the opportunity
they and the American government were offering me.
</P>
<P>
   Reading about Elian's ordeal, his mother's brave attempt to get
him out of Cuba, and the dispute between both sides of the same
family, it is difficult for me to know what is right.
</P>
<P>
   One thing I do know. At age 6, all I wanted was to go back to my
parents. Probably I would do the same if I were age 6 again. In
retrospect, however, I can understand why so many Cuban-Americans
feel so strongly against returning Elian to Cuba, even to his
father.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, when I was 6 all I wanted was to return to the love of my
parents and young brother. I wish I could have understood what a
mistake I was making, but I was only a small child.
</P>
<P>
   Like me, I am certain Elian, will yearn to come back to
hamburgers and fries soon enough. Like me, he will someday
appreciate the magnitude of his American aunt and uncle's efforts
to keep him here. He will someday thank the American people for
trying to do ``the right thing.'' Let's pray that if Elian is
returned to Cuba he will not be so desperate to take the same route
his mother and countless others have attempted.
</P>
<P>
   I am forever in debt to this country for giving me so many
opportunities. Most of all, I am grateful to my parents for their
selflessness that allowed them to give me up twice so that I could
have a chance for a better life. &QL; 
__
</P>
<P>
   Jose Catalan moved to Arizona in 1970 to attend Arizona State
University, where he graduated with a degree in journalism.
Catalan, 55, is a Scottsdale businessman who is active in various
civic and city organizations as a ``small way to repay my debt to
America.'' He has not returned to Cuba since leaving in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Catalan's brother left Cuba in 1962, and his parents joined
them in Puerto Rico the following year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
