<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7052 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-COURTS-BOS &LR;      04-04 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-COURTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT CASE STRENGTHENS ROLE OF REGULATORS, COURTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Software is no longer untouchable here.
</P>
<P>
   The government's stunning win in Round 2 of the Microsoft Corp.
trial shows that antitrust regulators can now reach into the heart
of the software world _ a capability that was in doubt when the
trial began 18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   And it topples the notion that software is too complex for
judges to scrutinize. In 1998, a panel of the Court of Appeals for
the District of Columbia famously wrote in a previous Microsoft
case that ``the limited competence of courts to evaluate high-tech
product designs'' should make judges ``wary'' of second-guessing
software engineers.
</P>
<P>
   But Federal District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson brushed aside
that concern, issuing a broad ruling Monday that analyzed the
software industry at length and concluding that Microsoft's
software design had a harmful effect on consumers.
</P>
<P>
   It's likely the ruling will embolden antitrust regulators at the
Justice Department and the Federal Trade Commission to become more
aggressive and to challenge other high-tech companies, several
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   That stance contrasts with the Justice Department's preferred
mode of action only five years ago, when it was less likely to take
on the risks of litigation in order to enforce the antitrust laws.
More often, the department sought to alter a company's behavior by
settling cases out of court.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you'll see in the near term is an increased willingness
to litigate and a harder line in negotiating,'' said Thane Scott,
an antitrust lawyer with Palmer &AMP; Dodge in Boston. ``Those of us
who go and meet with these agencies following one of these
victories see that you face a different group across the table,
different in that they can point to a ready example of success and
take more leverage in negotiating.''
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust regulators not only police anticompetitive behavior by
companies, but try to block or alter the terms of mergers that
would harm consumers.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 victory energized the Federal Trade Commission and made
it more aggressive, said Scott. In a case with local impact, the
FTC that year successfully went to trial to block the proposed $4
billion merger of Office Depot Inc. by Westborough-based Staples
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   With the latest Microsoft victory, ``it looks like the high-tech
industry, like every industry, can be subjected effectively to the
antitrust laws, but we'll see,'' said Ed Black, president of the
Computer and Communications Industry Association. The group favors
the toughest sanction against Microsoft: breaking the company up.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft case is only one area where government has stepped
with new engery into business regulation and antitrust enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Congress was derided as behind the times when a large
bank and a giant insurer, Citicorp and Travelers Group Inc.,
announced a merger that was partly illegal under federal law at the
time. Congress had tried unsuccessfully for two decades to update
the law, which generally barred mergers among banking, insurance
and brokerage firms, even though those combinations are common in
other countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Citicorp merger was seen as an example of markets racing
ahead of the government's ability to regulate. But last year,
lawmakers finally updated the banking laws.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Congress could approve sweeping new regulations for
the managed health care industry. And it has begun grappling with
rules of the road for the Internet, taking on such questions as
whether to tax online sales and whether digital signatures have the
same legal force as traditional signatures.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that judges should stay out of the software business
has been prevalent enough that Lawrence Lessig, a Harvard law
professor whom Jackson asked to provide guidance in the Microsoft
case, went out of his way to urge Jackson not to be afraid to
scrutinize software.
</P>
<P>
   ``The apparent feeling among a number of courts and commentators
is that (software) code is different: that the task of evaluating
design decisions involved in technological products is uniquely
beyond the ken of federal courts,'' Lessig wrote in a February
brief for Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it is a mistake to fetishize code this way,'' Lessig
said, adding that software is too crucial to society for courts to
turn away.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson appears to have listened to Lessig's advice, as his
ruling Monday discussed how Microsoft linked one of its products,
its Windows operating system, to another, its Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson issued broad rulings and analyses of software markets,
said Scott, ``to convince the appellate court that, `I (Jackson)
understand the markets, I understand the products, I understand the
law, and I am capable of developing a solution.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers have moved quickly to create a role for themselves
after Jackson's ruling. Leaders of the Senate's judiciary and
commerce committees said separately in the past two days that they
would hold hearings on the public policy implications of various
penalties that Jackson might apply to Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's the role of Congress to second-guess or to
critique a judge's decision,'' Senator John McCain, Republican of
Arizona, who leads the Senate Commerce Committee, said on the NBC
program ``Today.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``I think it is the role of Congress to assess two
things: One, the impact on the consumer of such actions that might
have to be taken on the part of Microsoft; and two, what is the
impact on this incredible engine that's driving America's
economy?''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates said it was premature to talk
about the most serious penalty: breaking the company into pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that any remedy of that kind makes sense for
people to be talking about,'' Gates said on the ``Early Show'' on
CBS. ``Even taking what the district judge said, that kind of
remedy is not resposive to what he talks about there. So, I think
it's definitely reckless for there to be talk of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
