<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7057 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-DISGRACE-BO     04-04 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-DISGRACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME CUBANS SEE DISGRACE IN ELIAN PROTECTION EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ In Spanish, in English, and in a smattering of both, the
voice of reason came through over cups of thick Cuban coffee
Tuesday: Sad is sad, but the law in a democratic society is the
law.
</P>
<P>
   It is, after all, why many of the exiles who have remade Miami
in their own image risked everything to come to America, and why
they continue coming.
</P>
<P>
   As Jose de Junco, 78, explained, throwing up his arms in
exclamation as well as exasperation, ``Of course we'll accept what
the court says. We are in a country governed by laws we can
understand. But it is a shame, and I am ashamed of the whole free
world for playing into Castro's hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the retired de Junco, none of the men and women nursing
cafe con leches or snacking on sugar-glazed pastries liked the idea
of sending any boy back to Cuba, especially into Fidel Castro's
eager arms. But the late-morning patrons at a popular Little Havana
cafe liked the idea of being viewed by the rest of the country as
immigrant ingrates, as more loyal to anti-Castro ideology than to
their adopted homeland, even less.
</P>
<P>
   Just minutes before an angry crowd Tuesday pushed through a
metal barricade and surrounded the house where the 6-year-old at
the center of the custody storm has been staying with relatives
since he was pulled from the sea in November, they cafe patrons
said they would watch little Elian Gonzalez return to his father in
Cuba with great sorrow, but without the violence that some in their
community have threatened.
</P>
<P>
   The hardliners, the ones who turn out to protest Cuban bands
performing in Miami and shout down politicians who dare speak
against their no-trade-with-Cuba cause, are in fact a minority of
Cuban-Americans, community observers said. They number no more than
7,000, a tiny and mostly older segment of the 800,000 or so Cubans
in Miami-Dade County.
</P>
<P>
   The moderates, like those at the cafe Tuesday, tend to skew
younger, although they cut across demographic and economic lines in
a place where the Hispanic community alone is more diverse than
some other entire cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community is so large that you can have a small percentage
turn out and still get attention,'' said Lisandro Perez, director
of the Cuban Research Institute at Florida International
University. ``It doesn't take much to surround a house in Little
Havana.''
</P>
<P>
   With the arrival of Juan Miguel Gonzalez's small entourage in
Miami seemingly imminent, negotiations over the logistics of
delivering Elian to his father broke down Tuesday. Led by his
great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez, Elian's Miami relatives are appealing
a federal court ruling. That decision upheld an Immigration and
Naturalization Service order that Elian be sent home to Cuba. In
the interim, the relatives have agreed to give Juan Gonzalez
``temporary care'' of his son if he promises to remain in the
country until the court rules.
</P>
<P>
   At Lazaro Gonzalez's house, where demonstrators briefly and
erroneously feared federal authorities were about to take Elian
away, real estate broker Rene Iturrey tried to sum up his side of
the debate, an argument that emphasizes non-violence until the
possibility of defeat is considered. ``We're not criminals,'' he
said, surveying the hundreds praying aloud for Elian. ``We want the
court to decide. . .If federal marshals show up here, there will be
dead old ladies and children standing in front of them, but they'll
have to get past me first.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a short drive but an ideological chasm away, at the
Versailles cafe on Calle Ocho, Little Havana's main street, a
businesswoman who identified herself only as Maria shook her head
at such inflamed rhetoric. She said she loathed the image of the
Cuban-American community as ultra-conservative extremists, and that
she was as shocked as anyone by the sometimes ugly statements
coming from Elian's most ardent supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can be very emotional, but also very American,'' said Maria,
54. ``The thought of that child going back _ and to what, except to
be used as a puppet _ breaks my heart. But absolutely he should go
back if that's what is decided.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Maria, whose parents sent her to Miami alone as a teenager
and joined her later when they could, many Cuban-American exiles
understand almost innately that any chance at freedom must be
taken. Of course a boy should be with his father, they said, but a
boy should also be free.
</P>
<P>
   Their words, political sounding, were also personal. At one time
or another, most of them have left loved ones behind or been left
behind. They gave up good jobs and grandparents, they said, home
ownership and happy homes, to start anew with nothing but the
certainty that they would fare better under democratic rule than
under a communist regime.
</P>
<P>
   Another Gonzalez household, no relation to the family fighting
over custody of Elian, was divided over whether the boy found
clinging to an inner tube on Thanksgiving Day should be repatriated
to Cuba if the court orders it. Nelson Gonzalez, 48, said yes.
Maria Gonzalez, 45, said no. But both agreed a good father would
let his son stay in this country. They themselves said they came to
Miami 15 years ago for the sake of their own children, two
daughters now 19 and 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``A father who wants a better life for his son does the right
thing for his son,'' said Maria Gonzalez, a secretary who, like her
husband, was a professor of medicine in Cuba. ``In Cuba we are
something. Here we are nothing. But we are better off here.'' Added
Nelson Gonzalez, now a video game repairman, ``It's the point of
coming here. It's liberty of expression and action. . .The father
deserves his day in court, but I feel sorry for the boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Cubans and Cuban-Americans in Miami are particularly
interested in hearing what Juan Miguel Gonzalez has to say for
himself and Elian once he is on US soil. For now, they believe, he
is speaking mostly for Castro, a mouthpiece for a country that gags
dissenters.
</P>
<P>
   And their hearts are not with him. Almost everyone interviewed
in turn asked the same questions: Where was the father when Elian
was recovering in the hospital? Why was he not at his son's side
all these months? They insisted it could not have been Castro, who
would have seen a public relations coup in a father's racing to
Miami, then voluntarily returning to Cuba with the son his former
wife had taken without telling him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The father didn't care in the beginning, how do we know he
cares now?'' said Norma de Junco, retired like her husband, and
living in the United States for 30 years, 10 of them in Miami.
``What he is saying is what Castro says to say. In Cuba, the chief
of the family is Castro. I brought my two children here for
freedom, Elian's mother brought him here for freedom. The father
should know that, even if the court doesn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
