<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7061 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CLONING-NERVES-BOS &LR;      04-04 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLONING-NERVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIANS CLONE NERVE CELLS IN LAB EXPERIMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a step toward harnessing human embryo cells to repair damaged
brains and other organs, Australian scientists say they have coaxed
uncommitted embryonic ``stem cells'' to turn into nerve cells in a
laboratory dish.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic demonstration shows how quickly scientists are
learning how to direct development of these stem cells, taken from
days-old human embryos, into different types of cells that could
become new body parts or used to treat neurodegenerative diseases
like Alzheimer's and Parkinson's.
</P>
<P>
   One US stem cell expert said the report from the Monash
Institute of Reproduction and Development ``is exciting because
there has been a question about whether stem cells can
differentiate into useful cells in a culture dish.'' The American
researcher, James A. Thomson of the University of Wisconsin, said
that he and others had done similar work but hadn't yet published
it.
</P>
<P>
   Stem cells in the developing embryo and fetus become bone or
liver or skin or other kinds of cells in response to signals from
their surroundings. Scientists are learning how to direct their
development in the laboratory by altering the fluids they're
cultured in.
</P>
<P>
   Although they're believed to have enormous potential for medical
benefits, stem cells are controversial because they must be
obtained from human embryos only a few days old, and removing them
destroys the embryos. The federal government has proposed
guidelines allowing government funding for research applying stem
cell technology to medicine, but would not allow federal funding
for obtaining the cells: that would have to be done with private
money.
</P>
<P>
   Stem cells could also be harvested from embryos created for the
purpose by nuclear transplantation, the method that generated Dolly
the lamb from cells of an adult sheep. The resulting embryo and its
cells would be compatible with the donor, so that cells taken from
the embryo could be grown into desired tissues and used to repair
disease or injury in the donor, without fear of immune rejection.
</P>
<P>
   Called ``therapeutic cloning,'' the technique is currently
outlawed in Great Britain but news reports this week said that a
government panel of experts will soon recommend legalizing it.
``That report was sheer speculation,'' said Ruth Deech, who heads
Britain's Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority in a
telephone interview. A spokesman for the authority said that the
advisory panel is expected to issue a recommendation within a few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Michael West, CEO of Advanced Cell Technology in Shrewsbury,
Mass., said that if the report from Britain is true, ``they are
brave souls and are to be commended for leading on this'' issue.
``They have done a lot of research into the potential uses of
therapeutic cloning and have been weighing the ethical
implications.''
</P>
<P>
   ACT is pursuing therapeutic cloning using private funds, and
says it hopes to develop the technology to repair many different
kinds of body parts.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian research did not use therapeutic cloning but
instead apparently used embryos that had been created during in
vitro fertilization treatment, but were not implanted into the
woman.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the work was done at the Medical University of
Singapore. A US scientist, Dr. John Gearhart of Johns Hopkins
University in Baltimore, speculated that the embryos that provided
the stem cells were obtained in Singapore, as that type of embryo
research is outlawed in Australia. Then the cells were flown to
Australia to be studied in the lab, Gearhart speculated.
</P>
<P>
   Gearhart downplayed the significance of the Monash research,
saying that US scientists ``have gone far beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   What is cutting-edge in the field now, Gearhart said in an
interview, ``is putting these cells into animal models and getting
them to function. We have been talking about this stuff for the
past nine months at different meetings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Experiments have already shown, said Gearhart, that nerve cells
derived from embryonic stem cells can be implanted into the brain
or spinal cords of animals ``and they will differentiate into the
appropriate kind of nerve cell for that region.'' These findings
suggest that the cues from the implanted cells' surroundings are of
crucial importance in determining the stem cells' fate, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
