<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-LAUNDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWITZERLAND PROBES ILLICIT ACCOUNTS LINKED TO LATE NIGERIAN RULER 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Swiss authorities have brought the first charges in a
case involving at least $654 million in bank accounts here that
were connected to the late Nigerian dictator Sani Abacha, his
family and associates.
</P>
<P>
   A businessman was charged last week with faking documents to set
up an account in a Geneva bank for the Abacha family, the city
prosecutor, Bernard Bertossa, confirmed Tuesday. Under Swiss legal
rules, names of the accused are kept confidential but people
following the case identified the businessman as Dharam Vir, of New
Delhi.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria's new democratically elected government is seeking
return of the money, scattered in 140 accounts in 11 banks in
Geneva and Zurich, contending that Abacha looted the money from his
country. Swiss officials have frozen the accounts and are carrying
out a criminal inquiry to pinpoint how the money was transferred
out of Nigeria and into Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Vir supposedly used false documentation saying the money was to
pay Russia for building a steel plant in Nigeria to divert an
undisclosed sum of money from Nigerian government accounts to the
Swiss accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The total amount in the accounts uncovered so far is even more
than the most notorious previous similar case _ the $550 million
that the longtime Philippine dictator Ferdinand Marcos hid through
a series of foundations.
</P>
<P>
   The impoverished Philippines began a 12-year effort in 1986 to
regain the money said to have been stripped from the country's
coffers and concealed in Swiss accounts. Beginning in the
mid-1990s, an embarrassed Switzerland changed its banking rules.
Swiss banks now are not allowed to accept money from foreign
dictators, and they are required to ascertain the source of large
amounts deposited.
</P>
<P>
   Abacha is reported to have stowed the money during the five
years he was Nigeria's dictator, before dying at age 54 in June
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss authorities say they are planning further indictments and
have asked Nigeria and other European countries for legal help in
tracking down suspects who live outside of Switzerland, Bertossa
said. Although he declined to name the European countries,
plundered funds have also turned up in Luxembourg, where they are
frozen, and in Belgium. Lawyers are also trying to block funds in
Germany and suspect there is additional money in France.
</P>
<P>
   ``One person is charged for the moment, but we expect to bring
money laundering charges against more people,'' Bertossa said.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery of the Abacha hoard has provoked an outcry in official
Switzerland, with its finance minister telling Parliament in March
that he was furious to find out that such accounts existed and that
the scandal could damage the country's image as a financial center.
</P>
<P>
   A substantial portion of the funds were deposited in
Switzerland's two biggest commercial banks, Credit Suisse and UBS.
In 1995, two years after Abacha took power, Credit Suisse is said
to have accepted $200 million in the name of Abacha's son,
Muhammad.
</P>
<P>
   The Nigerian government contends that Abacha systematically
embezzled money from the country's central bank through a system of
false invoices. Enrico Monfrini, Nigeria's lawyer in Geneva,
contends that the money was withdrawn from the central bank and
deposited in local banks or offshore companies controlled by the
Abacha family in a scheme orchestrated by the country's former
national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Documents handed over to Swiss authorities indicate that Abacha
personally authorized the transfer of sums of money to overseas
accounts in his name and the names of 14 others, Monfrini said. In
addition, there was a network of fictitious accounts, commissions
and kickbacks that helped to funnel as much as $2.2 billion out of
Abacha's oil-rich but cash-poor country, Monfrini contends.
</P>
<P>
   While many documents have been destroyed, Nigerian officials
produced enough material to persuade Swiss authorities to help
track down the missing money. Last October, the Swiss froze an
initial $550 million and turned up the additional $104 million
after inquiries. Making their announcement in January that the
accounts were blocked, the Swiss authorities noted that they
expected that more money could be found.
</P>
<P>
   (bl)
</P>
</TEXT>
