<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE TO SEND MCCAIN, BUSH DELEGATES TO GOP CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HILLARY CHABOT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Governor A. Paul Cellucci and the McCain 2000 campaign
Tuesday reached an agreement concerning the Massachusetts
delegation to the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John McCain won the Massachusetts presidential primary
March 7 and is therefore entitled to all 37 of the state's
delegates. Yet the McCain campaign agreed to send seven Bush
supporters as part of the number.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci and Lt. Governor Jane Swift will be two of the Bush
advocates attending the convention. They are expected to be picked
by the Republican State Committee in early June.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining five Bush delegates will be elected, along with 25
McCain delegates, at local caucuses April 29.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Inman, head of McCain's Massachusetts branch, will chair
the Massachusetts delegation. The Republican National Convention
takes place in Philidelphia July 30.
</P>
<P>
   Both Cellucci and Inman said the compromise creates a stronger
Republican party within the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal allows us to move on and focus on the important
business of electing a Republican president next fall,'' Cellucci
said in a written statement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   While Cellucci was in China last week on a trade mission, he
called McCain to work out a deal with the delegates, Cellucci's top
political advisor Rob Gray said. Gray spent the rest of the week
working with McCain national political director John Weaver in
order to craft the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's convention delegates can influence platform issues
where McCain differs from Bush, such as campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican party will announce similar deals Wednesday that
have been worked out in Vermont, Conneticut and Rhode Island, all
states where McCain carried the primary.
</P>
</TEXT>
