A7069 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-AIRTRAN-MINNESOTA05-C     04-04 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN-MINNESOTA05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AirTran, Northwest in feud over service to Minneapolis
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The prospect of lower airfares between Atlanta and
Minneapolis is in limbo amid a feud between AirTran Airways and
Northwest Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Discount carrier AirTran announced plans last month to start
service on the route in June at fares below those currently charged
by Northwest Airlines and Delta Air Lines.
</P>
<P>
   But those plans are on hold because of what AirTran calls
``anti-competitive'' tactics by Minneapolis-based Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran says Northwest is switching to bigger planes on the
Atlanta-Minneapolis route, boosting its average daily seat count by
about 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of increase goes well beyond reasonable
competition,'' AirTran marketing director Tad Hutcheson said.
``It's almost as many seats as we were going to put in the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   He said AirTran has been forced to ``reconsider the economic
conditions'' on the route but may still go ahead with the flights
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest denies the move to use bigger Airbus A320s and Boeing
757s for some Atlanta flights was aimed at AirTran.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is, quit whining and start flying,'' spokeswoman
Kathy Peach said.
</P>
<P>
   She said Northwest decided to change planes on the route before
AirTran announced its plans.
</P>
<P>
   Hutcheson said AirTran was openly wooed for months by local
officials in Minneapolis, adding that Northwest knew the smaller
carrier was likely to launch service this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The case reflects the broader issue of fair competition between
giant carriers and small discounters.
</P>
<P>
   Small carriers, including AirTran, have long complained that
mega-carriers add capacity to soak up demand, taking short-term
losses if necessary to protect their positions.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Transportation Department developed guidelines and
penalties governing fair competitive practices, but they have yet
to be enacted. AirTran has lodged fresh complaints to the DOT over
the Minneapolis situation, and this week executives of the carrier
met with the Minnesota attorney general at his request.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest claims it's switching to bigger planes to better
compete with Atlanta-based Delta, the only other nonstop carrier on
the route.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust me,'' said Peach. ``Delta is a far greater competitor in
that market than AirTran ever would be.''
</P>
<P>
   She suggested AirTran's complaints might be a case of sour
grapes. Peach said AirTran executives recently approached Northwest
about joining its multicarrier marketing alliance but went home
empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
