<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7071 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0405-COX     04-04 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0405-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ELIAN TALKS BOG DOWN - AGAIN; PROTESTERS VOW TO KEEP HIM IN U.S.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The city swirled with rumors and uncertainty Tuesday as
negotiators failed to reach agreement over the fate of 6-year-old
Cuban rafter Elian Gonzalez and once again postponed their talks.
</P>
<P>
   Protestors briefly toppled police barriers outside the home
where the boy has been living with his Miami relatives, and one of
Elian's chief caregivers, his cousin Marisleysis Gonzalez,
collapsed in emotional exhaustion and was hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the boy's father was issued a travel visa in Cuba but
continued to say he would not come to the United States without a
guarantee he would be given custody of his son.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the day, Juan Miguel Gonzalez's Washington D.C.
attorney, Gregory Craig, reportedly flew to Havana to try to smooth
out arrangements for the visit.
</P>
<P>
   But a conclusion to the long-running saga remained elusive, as
both sides refused to budge on demands that complicated the
transfer of the boy to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the Miami relatives who want to keep Elian in this
country said they do not want to turn the boy over to his father
until he is examined by a panel of psychologists who would
determine what is best for Elian. They also want a promise that the
boy won't be returned to Cuba until their appeal of a court ruling
can be heard.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials refused to grant those conditions, however,
insisting they have the authority to turn the boy over to his
father once he arrives in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus of the government continues to be on how best to
accomplish the reunion of Elian with his father,'' said Robert
Wallis, head of the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service's
Miami office.
</P>
<P>
   Wallis and attorneys for the Miami relatives agreed to take a
one-day break Wednesday and resume their talks Thursday morning.
They have failed to reach agreement despite four full days of
negotiations stretching over the past week.
</P>
<P>
   The possible visit by Elian's father seemed to be the spur that
might break the deadlock, although the visit was still up in the
air late Tuesday. The Cuban government has said that Gonzalez would
live in the home of a Cuban diplomat in the Washington area during
the visit.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to wanting a guarantee that Gonzalez will be given
custody of his son, Cuban officials want travel visas for 22 other
people, including Elian's classmates and a team of psychologists,
as well as Ricardo Alarcon, president of the Cuban National
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   While U.S. officials in Havana issued visas Tuesday for
Gonzalez, his second wife, their infant son, Elian's teacher and a
pediatrician, they said applications for the other visas would be
handled on a case-by-case basis.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether Cuban officials would allow Gonzalez to
come without assurances that the other visas would be issued.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's ordeal began Thanksgiving Day, when he was found
floating in an inner tube off the Fort Lauderdale coast. His mother
and 10 other people drowned when the boat they were using to flee
Cuba sank.
</P>
<P>
   In January, federal officials ruled the boy must go back to his
father in Cuba, but Elian's Miami relatives challenged the decision
in a federal lawsuit. A Miami federal judge ruled against them in
late March, but they immediately appealed to the 11th Circuit Court
of Appeals in Atlanta, which has set oral arguments in the case for
May 11.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the stalemate over the boy's fate are the intense
emotions surrounding the case among Miami's Cuban exiles. Hundreds
of protesters snarled traffic and briefly blocked the entrance to
Miami's bustling seaport in January after the initial federal
decision to return Elian to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, a small but determined group of protesters has kept
a nearly constant vigil outside Elian's Little Havana home, the
crowd swelling at times to hundreds. They have vowed to lay down
their lives to keep Elian in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a group of about 60 demonstrators knocked aside
police barricades after they heard a rumor that federal officials
might be coming for the boy. They locked arms in front of a fence
surrounding the modest home, chanting, singing and praying.
</P>
<P>
   Police stood aside, saying they would allow the protestors to
vent their emotions. Calm returned after about an hour as the
barricades were re-erected and the protestors slowly moved away
from the house.
</P>
<P>
   The flare-up marked a day that began with Marisleysis Gonzalez
giving several interviews with the network morning shows, begging
the American public to understand the family's heartbreak over the
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``All they care about is pieces of paper and a signature,'' she
told NBC's ``Today'' show, referring to federal immigration
officials. ``I don't see anybody caring about this little boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez also said she was convinced Elian would be taken away
from his father and brainwashed if he is returned to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   After several more interviews, she collapsed in a dizzy spell,
then was taken to Coral Gables Hospital by paramedics. She was
expected to remain hospitalized overnight. She has been
hospitalized one time previously during the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Lazaro Gonzalez, visited her and then made a brief
statement to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the government expects,'' he said. ``All
we're doing is protecting the child. The government is destroying
this family.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
