   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ There was sound. There was fury.
But what stock market investors wanted to know after Tuesday's
bizarre bungee jump in share prices was, what does it signify?
Midway through one of the weirdest and wildest days in stock market
history, the Nasdaq composite index had plunged 634.31 points,
shearing 13.6 percent off its value. Had it closed there, it would
have been the worst one-day decline in Nasdaq history. But a flood
of buying rescued the index, propelling it up almost 500 points.
Even though the markets recovered by the end of the day, traders
and investors were shellshocked by the extraordinary moves. By
Gretchen Morgenson. (We plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in
``f'' news file.) 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   With 2-column graphic; photo, NYT17, inside.
</P>
<P>
   See also MARKET, inside.
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HORMONE-REPLACEMENT (Undated) _ Researchers have informed
about 25,000 women taking part in a federal study of hormone
replacement therapy that, far from protecting the heart as many
researchers had assumed, the therapy may have put the women at
slightly higher risk of heart attacks and strokes. The study, known
as the Hormone Replacement Therapy trial of the Women's Health
Initiative, is the first large-scale, controlled clinical trial
asking whether hormone replacement therapy prevents heart disease
in healthy post-menopausal women. By Gina Kolata. (Scheduled to
move by 8:15 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-POLITICS (Tokyo) _ Japan's cabinet resigns, setting the
stage for a rapid succession to the prime minister, Keizo Obuchi,
who has been in a coma since Sunday. The cabinet's resignation is
expected to be followed by the nomination of the Liberal Democratic
Party's candidate to take over from Obuchi, perhaps on Wednesday
morning. The party's choice is already widely reported be its
second-ranking official, Yoshiro Mori. Once nominated, the
parliament would vote almost immediately to ratify him. By Howard
W. French. (Eds.: an early version of this story has moved; the
1stLd-Writethru is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``i'' news
file.) 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-DRUGS (Washington) _ Seven months before Election Day,
the struggle over expanding Medicare to cover prescription drugs
for the elderly is escalating, with both parties maneuvering
furiously on an issue that matters, deeply, to a critical group of
voters. As the debate over the Republican budget resolution began
in the Senate, for example, Democrats were pushing for an amendment
that would require the creation of a Medicare drug benefit before
any tax cut could take effect. Nu Robin Toner. (The story has moved
in ``w'' news file.) 1,800 words.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   ORE-ADOPTION-RECORDS (Albany, Ore.) _ The continuing legal
controversy over a law passed by Oregon voters in 1998 giving any
adult adoptee access to their birth records, which had been sealed,
so that they may try to track down their birth parents and/or
half-siblings. The legal issue pits their ``right to know'' versus
the confidentiality the state at one time promised to women who
decided to give children up for adoption. The law, the first such
measure approved by voters in any state, has been stayed ever since
by a legal challenge from six anonymous birth mothers. Now it's
coming to a head before the Oregon supreme court. By Sam Howe
Verhovek. (The story has moved in ``a'' news file.) 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT23.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE-U.N. (Daru, Sierra Leone) _ This town, attacked 59
times during a nine-year civil war, had been left for dead,
deserted by its residents. Now, a few weeks after U.N. peacekeepers
arrived, life has begun to stir again. The peacekeeping operation
in Sierra Leone will be watched closely, especially as the U.N.
Security Council considers sending troops to Congo, a much larger
country whose conflict has drawn in half a dozen nations. By
Norimitsu Onishi. (The story has moved ``i'' news file.) 1,400
words.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SUITS (Undated) _ In the wake of a federal judge's
harsh antitrust ruling, Microsoft Corp. now faces the threat of a
rising wave of consumer class-action and other private lawsuits.
But while the ruling in the government case makes things easier for
private antitrust plaintiffs, it by no means insures that they will
win in court. By Steve Lohr. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS (Washington) _ The House approves legislation
that would block the Clinton administration's plans to revamp the
system for allocating donated organs based on medical need,
regardless of where the recipients live. Today's action fuels a
painful, long-running fight between Congress and the administration
over which patients should have priority in receiving human organs.
By Eric Schmitt. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``w'' news
file.) 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-STATUS (Washington) _ Americans are mailing in their
census forms at a rate well below what federal officials had hoped
for, raising concerns that getting an accurate count of the
population will take longer and cost more than it should, the
director of the Census Bureau says. By David Stout. (The story has
moved in ``w'' news file.) 800 words.
</P>
