u f BC-DAVE-THOMAS-ART-NYT &LR;      04-04 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVE-THOMAS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY COMPANIES SHOULD PAY ADOPTION BENEFITS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Tenn.)  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Dave Thomas is founder and senior chairman of the board, Wendy's
International Inc., the fast-food restaurant chain.) 
 By DAVE THOMAS with CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was adopted when I was 6 weeks old, and my adoptive mother
died when I was 5. I went to live with my dad, who married three
more times. I never really wanted to talk about adoption. I didn't
find out about it until I was 13. My foster grandmother told me. I
was really mad about it.
</P>
<P>
   I got my first job when I was 12, and I've been on my own since
I was 15. We lived in a trailer, and it was overcrowded, and I just
didn't like the living conditions. There was a YMCA right where I
was working, and so I moved there.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurants have been my families. At my first job, in
Knoxville with the Regas Restaurant, the people there were another
family. At my restaurants, we are one big family. That's your
success: when you have happy people having fun. It's pretty
exciting.
</P>
<P>
   In the late '80s, we were having a meeting, a kind of
motivational meeting for our managers, and I went public. I said,
if I can do it, you can do it. How many people in this room know
your mother and father? Raise your hand if you've never seen your
biological mother and father. And I raised my hand.
</P>
<P>
   Then one of my managers came up to me and said, ``I'm adopted.
Why don't you talk about adoption?'' In 1990, President Bush asked
me to come to the White House and talk about the adoption
initiative, which was asking corporate America to give adoption
benefits. Anyone who gives maternity benefits should also have
adoption benefits _ it's kind of a no-brainer. Today, about 62
percent of the Fortune 1000 companies have adoption benefits, like
paid time off and reimbursement for expenses like travel.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1995, we got the tax credit for people who adopt, and in
1997, the Adoption and Safe Families Act. The federal government
says we don't want these kids in foster care more than 18 months,
and we'll give the states an incentive. About $30 million has been
given back to the states. The adoption stamp is coming out in May.
Adoption is one thing I'm really proud of. I'm proud that we have a
large number of franchisees that have supported us, and it's
growing. The more we talk about adoption, the more things are
happening.
</P>
<P>
   We set up a book tour, and we went to 20 cities to talk to high
school editors about honesty and integrity and about not doing
drugs. We were hoping the high school students would take this
pretty seriously and do something about their lives, like if you
have bad friends, dump them.
</P>
<P>
   But I kept hearing one thing: why did you drop out of high
school? So we were in Seattle, the 20th city, and one young lady
said to me, why don't you go back and get your general equivalency
diploma? I said, maybe I will. I was afraid I was setting a bad
example. I hated the word dropout. I hated the word adoption. I
hated being born out of wedlock.
</P>
<P>
   So I went and got a tutor, and it took me half a year, but I
passed. I wouldn't say I was brilliant. At least I got my GED.
</P>
<P>
   dw
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
