<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
 RENAISSANCE BOY MEETS NATURE MAN 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; L &LR; 
 &UR; eonardo DiCaprio &LR; : actor, teenage heartthrob, environmental
villain, environmental poster boy and, now, journalist? DiCaprio,
who in the wake of his beach-destroying movie, ``The Beach,''
became the official Earth Day spokes-celebrity, stopped by the
White House on Friday, March 31, to tape a walk-around with
 &UR; President Clinton &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The president was supposed to show the movie star the
environmental improvements he'd made in the presidential habitat in
a segment for an ABC environmental special to be broadcast April
22. But Clinton offered DiCaprio a sit-down interview in which he
discussed global warming and policy on related matters. At least
that was how ABC brass described the encounter in response to
complaints from news-gathering staff members about a movie star
doing their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The network's news chief,  &UR; David Westin &LR; , e-mailed them all his
assurance that ``all roles of journalist must be played by
journalists.'' (NBC, are you listening? Doesn't this apply to
Fergie, too?) Westin said no one in power would be ``that stupid''
to send the actor to conduct an interview and that ``it's quite
possible we'll use none'' of the taped segment.
</P>
<P>
   The White House denied Westin's version, saying that ABC had
sent a formal request for a sit-down interview months ago, and had
the day before the interview forwarded a list of questions DiCaprio
would ask (a fine journalistic practice from the network of heavy
hitters like  &UR; Barbara Walters &LR;  and  &UR; Diane Sawyer &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   P.S. More on Bill Clinton, environmental president:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Alice Waters &LR; , who cooked a fund-raising dinner for Clinton in
early March chez  &UR; Susie Buell &LR;  in San Francisco, is determined to
get more from him than a clean plate and a thank you. Waters
believes that planting seeds, tending to gardens and eating the
produce creates a profound connection with the land. She has been
trying to get the president to plant a vegetable garden at the
White House since the beginning of his administration, and she
wrote him again following the Buell dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is an avid fan of Waters' cooking but so far hadn't
taken action on several letters she wrote to him previously.
Although first lady  &UR; Hillary Clinton &LR;  assured a luncheon group in
San Francisco last year that she grows tomatoes on the White House
roof, Waters has more in mind, especially, she notes in the opening
passage of her letter, since he is now in ``the final days of your
presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. President, plant that garden on the White House grounds!
Let the nation know that its highest leader understands the
necessity of a life lived in harmony with the earth. You can do
this quietly, swiftly and without any rhetoric. I can think of no
more powerful way to ground your legacy than to leave behind a
kitchen garden and the compost pile to nourish it . ... Launch this
project and I will happily come and cook you dinner from the
garden.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ADS ARE A DRAG &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Seen those WebEx billboards picturing a reclining  &UR; RuPaul &LR;  with
the words, ``Meetings used to be a real drag''? New York magazine
ad critic  &UR; Simon Dumenco  &LR; disses ``the cultural tone-deafness on
display here.''
</P>
<P>
   WebEx is an Internet site that enables businesses to conduct
meetings via the Web. Dumenco can't understand ``a wannabe-hip
dot-com spending millions to embrace a cross-dressing icon five
years after his popularity peaked. Somebody at the pitch meeting
probably said, `Drag is hot!' The worst thing about this campaign
is its condescending simplemindedness.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _The publishers of Mother Jones magazine made an April 1
announcement that they would spin off the progressive publication's
MoJo wire, go public and add an ``e-commerce adjunct'' to sell such
products as ``gas masks for WTO-style protests, gallon jugs of
organic wheat paste'' and ``reusable `Free _''' buttons with
stickers reading ` &UR; Mumia &LR; ,' ` &UR; Peltier &LR; ' and `Trade Sucks.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``They're steaming vegetables, following their own recipes. &LR; 
 &UR; Julia (Child) says, `My beans are greener than yours,' to which &LR; 
 &UR; Jacques (Pepin) replies, `Mine are just a different green.' It &LR; 
 &UR; soon becomes apparent that these two are not cooking per se, but &LR; 
 &UR; channeling, and what they're conjuring up is the spirit of &LR; 
 &UR; `Waiting for Godot' as they play the gastronomic equivalents of &LR; 
 &UR; Vladimir and Estragon. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Akiko Busch &LR;  makes dramatic sense of the PBS series ``Julia
and Jacques Cooking at Home,'' in Metropolis magazine. Meanwhile,
 &UR; Robert Mondavi &LR; 's new wine and food center in Napa has announced
that ``Julia's Kitchen,'' a demonstration facility and dining room,
will be its cornerstone.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
