<HEADER>
A7079 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f BC-STATES-CHINA-NAT     04-04 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-CHINA-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  TEXAS LAWMAKERS SPLIT OVER CHINA TRADE
</P>
<P>
   By Jeff Russell
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, April 4 -- With the targeted deadline for Congress'
vote on trade with China closing in, factions on both sides of the
issue are turning up the heat in Washington as Texas lawmakers
scramble to stake out positions.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of efforts to normalize trade relations with China
contend that the country's enormous market would be an economic
boon to U.S. exports.
</P>
<P>
   But some Texas lawmakers voice fear that a bill to grant China
permanent normal trade relations may lose crucial swing votes if it
fails to come up before the end of May.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can afford to isolate ourselves,'' said Rep.
Solomon Ortiz, D-Corpus Christi, who supports the bill. He cited
examples of foreign nations who, according to Ortiz, are taking
advantage of China's opening markets at the expense of American
companies. ``They're eating our lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   But the bill's challengers counter that granting permanent
normal trade relations, or PNTR, to China will backfire on American
industries in the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned that American businesses will be subject to a
flood of price-busting Chinese imports,'' said Rep. Ciro Rodriguez,
D-San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez has supported extending normal trade relations to
China every year it has come up for a vote under Congress' annual
review. But last week he signed on with a group of 19 other
Democratic ``switchers'' who now oppose PNTR.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Republican support for PNTR remains solid, with
backers such as Texas Sens. Phil Gramm and Kay Bailey Hutchison
pledging their unwavering support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is going to be perfect,'' said GOP Rep. Henry Bonilla
of San Antonio, ``but I'm confident that the U.S. will come out on
top.''
</P>
<P>
   China is among a small number of nations that must win
congressional approval on a yearly basis to continue enjoying most
favored nation status. Approval of PNTR would eliminate the need
for the annual vote, which Congress has threatened to use in the
past to influence China's human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   The fracture among the Texas delegation mirrors the growing
dispute at the national level. Labor unions, threatened by the
prospect of a job drain, have thrown all their weight towards
defeat of PNTR. ``The vast majority of people in China are not able
to afford the goods we want to sell,'' said Ed Sills, a spokesman
for the Texas AFL-CIO. He indicated that the union plans to
mobilize its membership in the coming weeks by staging protests at
congressional offices and igniting a massive letter-writing
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And by all indications the unions' efforts are helping to drum
up opposition from lawmakers like Rodriguez, whose district is
weighted heavily in agriculture and industry.
</P>
<P>
   But agri-business groups have waged a war of their own to garner
support for open trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need new markets, and China's the biggest market in the
world,'' said Mike Barnett, a spokesman for the Texas Farm Bureau.
He called PNTR a ``win-win'' situation, asserting that China's
immense demand for commodities like rice and citrus fruits could
invigorate the sagging U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech on Monday in San Jose, Calif., President Clinton --
who has made the bill a top priority of his final year in office --
reaffirmed his arguments in support of PNTR.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe there's ever been one (trade agreement) this
weighted in our favor,'' he told a group of party supporters. ``The
main consequences of (voting against) this will be to hurt America
economically and to dramatically strain our relations with China.''
</P>
<P>
   But a number of mostly Democratic lawmakers are still undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ruben Hinojosa, D-McAllen, is involved in talks with the
White House and other interest groups, his press secretary David
McFarland said. He refused to discuss the issue publicly until he
comes to a decision.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
