A7080 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      04-04 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA: INVESTIGATING CULT DEATHS
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred members of a doomsday cult who died in a fire in
a church last month were still alive when the flames broke out,
forensic tests show. The doors and windows of the chapel were
bolted from the outside, the preliminary investigation findings
confirm. ``It was an attack from the inside,'' A.B.M. Lugudo,
deputy commissioner of Uganda's forensics agency, told The
Associated Press. ``We are still looking to see if these people
started the fire and tried to run away, but got caught up in the
fire.''
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: RIGHTS CAMPAIGNER RELEASED
</P>
<P>
   Su Bingxian, the mother of a student killed in Tiananmen Square
on June 4, 1989, was released Tuesday after 24 hours in detention.
She was arrested on Monday when she tried to deliver gifts from the
widow of the journalist Edgar Snow to Ding Zilin, another mother of
a slain student. Su told reporters she was stripped and searched
and then interrogated constantly from Monday afternoon until
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: LEADER'S ASSETS CHALLENGED
</P>
<P>
   The Central Bureau of Investigation charged Rabri Devi, the
chief minister of Bihar, India's poorest and second most populous
state, and her husband, Laloo Prasad Yadav, with having $99,000
more in assets than can be explained by their legitimate sources of
income. Devi was sworn in three weeks ago after the party her
husband leads won the largest number of seats in the state
assembly.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: KASHMIR LEADERS RELEASED
</P>
<P>
   India freed three leaders of the Kashmir Freedom Conference, a
group of about two dozen organizations opposed to Indian rule of
the predominantly Muslim state of Kashmir. The men had been
detained for six months without trial for organizing an election
boycott. Human rights groups had sought their release.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   ROMANIA: KING TO GET CASTLE BACK
</P>
<P>
   King Michael of Romania, who was deposed by the Communists in
1948 and has since lived in Switzerland, will get back a
confiscated castle, according to a private news agency quoted by
Reuters. The castle in Arad had become one of many homes of the
communist dictator Nicolae Ceausescu. Many other Romanians are
seeking land seized under communism, and the issue has tied up
courts and Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: ENGLISH IN THE AIR
</P>
<P>
   Air France's decision last month to have its pilots speak
English for safety reasons when they approach Charles de Gaulle
airport near Paris isn't getting much help from the French
government, which said that it would continue to support
French-speaking pilots and air controllers. The decision follows a
nudge from the prime minister of the Canadian province of Quebec,
Lucien Bouchard, who last week called Air France's decision
scandalous.
</P>
<P>
   UKRAINE: DISPUTE OVER REFERENDUM
</P>
<P>
   President Leonid Kuchma is going forward with a planned April 16
referendum that, if passed, would give him power to break an
impasse with Parliament over stalled economic reforms. The assembly
of the Council of Europe, meeting in Strasbourg, urged Kuchma to
delay the vote until a law on referendum procedures could be
considered by Ukraine's lawmakers. If Kuchma goes ahead with the
referendum, the council said it would consider suspending Ukraine
for changing the balance of power in violation of the constitution.
</P>
<P>
   (hlw)
</P>
