<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7082 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TECH-CARRIERPOINT05-C     04-04 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-CARRIERPOINT05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Net site linking shippers, carriers
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You're a shipping manager with 1,000 pounds of dog
food sitting on your Atlanta loading dock. It needs to be in a
grocery store in Mobile, Ala., by noon tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   To find a truck, you have a few choices: use software that
hopefully is new enough to contain accurate shipping rates, break
out the Rolodex or call a broker.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's another way. The Internet is squeezing middlemen by
linking businesses and people in such wide-ranging consumer
industries as stock trading and air travel. But it promises to make
shipping transactions smoother and cheaper as well.
</P>
<P>
   An Atlanta-based firm, CarrierPoint, is developing a Web site
where truckers can bid on shipments. It cuts out transportation
brokers by linking shippers with carriers needed to haul the
freight.
</P>
<P>
   CarrierPoint, started in 1997, expects to close on a $21.8
million second round of funding this month. The Atlanta-based
company was started by John Thomson and Cliff Isaacson. They
launched the first version of the market early last month.
</P>
<P>
   They are not alone. More than half a billion dollars has flowed
into the market in the last year, said John Fontanella, an analyst
with AMR Research in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``They better hurry,'' Fontanella said. ``There are a lot of
people moving into this space.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies such as National Transportation Exchange,
Cargosphere.com, OpenShip.com and Shipping-Auction.com also hope to
create Internet-based auctions where shippers can bid on freight.
Other firms _ Logistics.com, Arzoon.com and Celarix.com _ have
similar efforts under way.
</P>
<P>
   Carriers and shippers can register at CarrierPoint's site, www
</P>
<P>
   .carrierpoint.com. Registered users are required to mail a copy
of their signature. CarrierPoint verifies that the carriers have a
satisfactory rating with the U.S. Department of Transportation,
that they are solvent and that the insurance is current.
</P>
<P>
   Registered shippers request bids on loads. Carriers can bid by
the price of their service or by pickup and delivery time. They can
be notified if they win by almost any means: phone, cell phone,
e-mail, hand-held devices.
</P>
<P>
   Shipments can range in size from 500 pounds to a truckload _
anything less probably is better suited for a parcel service,
Thomson said.
</P>
<P>
   Once a contract is generated, shippers and carriers each pay a 2
percent fee based on the cost of the shipment. Broker fees can be
12 percent to 15 percent, said Brian Kinsey, CarrierPoint's chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Thomson, 34, said he saw the opportunity for the Web solution
while working as a consultant, installing distribution management
software programs. He said the traffic managers using the software
would ask him to disconnect the features that chose the least
expensive carrier for the shipment. Thomson said the software was
not updated enough to make the shipping rates relevant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shipping managers would end up picking up the phone and
calling carriers,'' Thomson said. ``I'd see this and think, 'Why
pick up the phone? The Internet is the perfect solution.'''
</P>
<P>
   So far, nine carriers have signed up as have a handful of small
shippers. CarrierPoint also has signed deals with several
business-to-business Internet exchanges to provide shipping for the
goods purchased.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-employee firm is developing version two of the software,
expected to be ready by the end of the year. The new version is
expected to broaden the site's features, offering news, weather and
trip insurance as well as the ability to track shipments.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
