<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7084 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CHINESE-STOOLS-ART-$A     04-04 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINESE-STOOLS-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHINESE STOOL, HUMBLE YET WONDEROUS  
 FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RITA REIF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   William Lipton remembers the first time he saw Chinese stools.
It was the late 1950s, and he was 5. A pair of barrel-shaped
stools, in blue and white porcelain, flanked the sofa in his
grandmother's parlor in Dallas. ``Even on a hot summer day, they
felt icy,'' he said. ``They were plump and smooth and had wonderful
pictures of tall sailing ships in a harbor all around the sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipton has no idea today what became of the stools, family
heirlooms that were trophies of a trip around the world made by a
great-great-grandfather in 1887.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on a first visit to China in 1979, when Lipton was a
textile designer working for Jim Thompson Ltd. in Bangkok, stools
loomed large again. In Beijing he saw a towering pile of weathered
wood stools, with elegantly carved aprons and legs, with hoof feet,
scrolled feet and flat feet protruding here and there from a stack
that looked like a bizarre offering to the gods of good taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this was not in a temple,'' he said. ``It was in the yard
of a government warehouse compound, standing next to a huge kiln
where the pieces of wood were being recycled into charcoal.
Hardwoods make charcoal that really lasts.''
</P>
<P>
   The memory of that scene stayed with him. He became an antiques
dealer in 1989, ultimately specializing in Chinese furniture. Four
years ago he began to assemble as many examples of stools ``with
personality'' as he could find for a show on a form of furniture
that is the most humble and versatile of all in China but is rarely
exhibited.
</P>
<P>
   He selected 92 of them for ``The Wondrous and Amenable Chinese
Stool,'' an exhibition at his shop, William Lipton Ltd., in
Manhattan, through April 22. He invited Sarah Handler, an art
historian, to review the stools he had acquired and to write an
essay on their history in a book that accompanies the show ($60).
</P>
<P>
   Lipton purposely omitted the best-known types of stools: the
most formal ones, like those made for Ming and Ching palaces and
the homes of scholars and merchants, along with the porcelain
garden stools that have been a mainstay of trade with the West for
three centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The stools on view are less perfect. They range from a
15th-century barrel-shaped elm stool to a mid-20th- century
four-legged one, emblazoned with political messages in red
calligraphy on two sides: ``Listen to Chairman Mao'' and ``Walk
with the Communists.'' The prices run from $650 for a tiny vendor's
stool to $42,000 for a set of four stools and a table, all in the
shape of barrels.
</P>
<P>
   There are stools in all possible shapes: an X-framed
17th-century folding stool, made of rosewood-like huanghuali, is
the earliest type of stool known to have been used in China,
probably brought there by nomads in the second century. Its minimal
form contrasts sharply with a pair of rootwood stools inset with
circular seats; they are 18th-century rococo extravaganzas of
joinery, dripping with tubular growths and squiggly things.
</P>
<P>
   There are barrel-shaped stools with four or five legs, and there
are low and tall stools fitted with straight or raked legs. There
is only one log stool, a massive seat carved out of a tree trunk
that was probably used near the gate of a residential compound.
</P>
<P>
   But there are many tradesmen's stools, and those for itinerant
barbers outnumber all others. Barbers brought their own stools to
the streets where they found customers. Some were fitted with a
drawer for razors and a comb; others had a slot to deposit coins.
</P>
<P>
   Masseurs worked the streets too, using two stools with splayed
legs and narrow seats: the client sat on the low one and the
masseur perched on the other, which was twice as tall and also
served as a back rest for the client.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tall stools were probably always used by tradesmen because
they were too tall to be used at a table in the house,'' Lipton
said. The most distinctive tall stool in the show is occupied these
days by an articulated lacquered wood figure, a five-foot image of
a deity that was used in festivals.
</P>
<P>
   Informality reigns in the converted town house that serves as
Lipton's shop, which is two steps down from the street. The space,
a bit wider and longer than a railroad car, is always chockablock
with furniture in what might appear to be casual arrangements but
are, in fact, well-ordered groupings of similar pieces placed, side
by side, on the floor, on table tops, on platforms, on counters and
in the window, all to spur comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   There are no wall labels, but explanatory notes are filed in a
loose-leaf binder for visitors to peruse. The show continues out
back in the garden where stone seats are displayed among the pine
trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted people to feel free to sit on all these stools and
experience them,'' Lipton said. ``You wouldn't be able to do that
in a formal arrangement.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked what he had learned from organizing the exhibition,
Lipton said that he was reminded of the young Ming incense merchant
who wanted to read a few poems to acquire a little refinement. ``In
my case,'' Lipton said, ``these stools are deceptively simple, like
poems: After studying them I too feel a little more refined.'' (af)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
