<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7085 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-GLF-TIGER-MASTERS-TEX     04-04 2326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TIGER-MASTERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`REVAMPED' TIGER EVEN BETTER THAN ORIGINAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Davis Love III received the ominous warning five
years ago, long before Tiger Woods invoked squatter's rights on PGA
Tour leader boards.
</P>
<P>
   It came from Butch Harmon, Woods' swing instructor, who had yet
to watch his star pupil earn the first dollar in a journey that
would lead him to the top of the tour's career money list by age
24.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept telling me, `Davis, when he learns to control his
irons and control his distances, nobody is going to be able to beat
him. Not because I'm teaching him. Because he's that good,' '' Love
said. ``I repeated that a few times when he first came out. I told
some other players, `You know, this guy is not anywhere near as
good as he can be.' People didn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now they believe. Heading into Thursday's opening round of the
Masters Tournament, Woods has won seven of his past 11 starts at
tour events. He has finished below second only once in that
stretch. With 18 victories in 91 tour events, Woods' career winning
percentage (19.8) dwarfs Jack Nicklaus (12.3) and Arnold Palmer
(8.3), the two competitors in the Masters field with the most green
jackets and career victories. Woods also bypassed Love in February
to become the tour's all-time earnings leader ($14,546,859).
</P>
<P>
   Hailed as everything from the Next Nicklaus to the Pied Piper
for minority golfers since his arrival on the tour in 1996, the
multiethnic Woods has matured in the past four years into
``everything we'd hoped he would be'' as a player and role model,
PGA Tour commissioner Tim Finchem said. Tour officials also credit
Woods as a primary reason for shifting demographics, higher
television ratings and rising purses.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' presence has become so consuming that Colin Montgomerie,
the No. 3 player in the world rankings, said peers believed ``the
tournament was finished'' when Woods carded an opening 69 in
difficult conditions to emerge a stroke off the lead at the Bay
Hill Invitational March 16-19. Woods went on to win by four shots.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie's stance drew some hot rejoinders from fellow
tourists, most notably Hal Sutton, who defeated Woods by one stroke
at The Players Championship on March 27. Sutton criticized
Montgomerie for adopting a ``defeatist attitude'' toward the game's
top-ranked player, a charge Montgomerie dismissed. Instead,
Montgomerie said he merely uttered the truth, as it pertains to the
majority of PGA Tour participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm third in the world and feel that way, can you imagine
how the others are feeling?'' Montgomerie, 36, said. ``He seems to
have everything. We have never had someone as dominant as Tiger,
not in my career, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who quibble with his take on Woods, Montgomerie said,
``are kidding you ... and kidding themselves.'' He likened Woods,
the golfer, to Michael Jordan, the basketball player, in terms of
separating himself from peers mentally and physically.
</P>
<P>
   ``With his ambition and his will, we have a battle on our hands
every week,'' Montgomerie said. ``This is all very new, this
complete dominance by one player. He has no weakness in his game.''
CHANGES FROM '97
</P>
<P>
   That was not the case in 1997, when Woods stormed into the
public consciousness with a record-setting, 12-stroke victory at
the Masters. As a 21-year-old, Woods set the tournament scoring
record (18-under-par 270) and posted the largest margin of victory
in Masters history.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the time, Woods said he realized he had caught lightning
in a bottle. He played the final 63 holes at 22 under and did not
three-putt any of Augusta National Golf Club's sloping greens. He
won his next tournament, the 1997 GTE Byron Nelson Classic, but
failed to crack the top 19 in any of the season's remaining major
championships. In each, Woods posted a round of 74 or higher. The
occasional soaring score became a recurring theme at weekly tour
stops, prompting him to take action.
</P>
<P>
   During the off-season, Woods retooled his golf swing, with help
from Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to,'' Woods said. ``I didn't like the way I played in
'97, even though I won some tournaments. I wasn't consistent.
Anybody can win when they're hot. That's not hard. But it's hard to
win when you're off. I got tired of shooting 62 one day and 78 the
next.''
</P>
<P>
   With an eye toward distance control on short-iron shots, Harmon
had Woods cut down on his backswing and follow-through. He weakened
Woods' grip and urged him to keep his right heel planted,
minimizing the tendency to swing too quickly and airmail greens.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the two have worked to keep Woods' club face square
at the top of his swing. They've shallowed the angle of his
downswing to limit spin on approach shots. They've sought to
prevent his arms from lagging behind his right elbow, which causes
a player to push the ball to the right.
</P>
<P>
   Even the putting stroke is different from the one Woods used to
win the 1997 Masters. Rather than a straight-back, straight-through
stroke on the greens, Woods now putts with more of an arcing motion
that is similar to a normal golf swing. It is the type of putting
stroke used by Ben Crenshaw, Phil Mickelson and Justin Leonard,
among others.
</P>
<P>
   The mind-set also is different. Woods hits more 3-woods and
2-irons off tee boxes, rather than drivers, to keep the ball in
play. His average driving distance is down by 11 yards from 1997,
but his driving accuracy is up, from 96th among tour participants
(68.6 percent) to 18th (74.3 percent). The tradeoff, Woods said,
has been worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Since making the swing changes, he's hitting more greens in
regulation (73.8 percent), he has improved his putting average
(1.752) and he's winning more tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   By doing so, he has beaten the odds, said John Rhodes, a Fort
Worth-based golf instructor who has tutored several PGA Tour
participants, including Sutton, Peter Jacobsen and Tom Kite. Rhodes
has seen countless tour players revamp their swings over the past
three decades. Few emerge with the type of turnaround seen in
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very rare,'' Rhodes said. ``For every one who makes it,
there are five or six you never hear from again.'' SHORT-TERM
STRUGGLES
</P>
<P>
   Provided financial security from a $60 million endorsement deal
signed before hitting his first shot as a professional, Woods said
he never hesitated when Harmon told him he would experience
short-term struggles while tailoring his swing to achieve long-term
success. Woods described the changes as ``not nearly as severe'' as
those undertaken by Nick Faldo in the late 1980s, before Faldo
emerged as a winner of six major championships.
</P>
<P>
   In the process of becoming a more consistent ball-striker, Woods
became an infrequent visitor to the winner's circle. During an
19-month stretch _ from July 1997 to February 1999 _ he recorded
only one victory but several top-10 finishes. David Duval replaced
him as the No. 1 player in the world golf rankings. When questioned
during his winless stretch about a slump, Woods responded by saying
he felt no frustration and that the changes would help in the long
run.
</P>
<P>
   The first glimmer of hope emerged at the 1999 Buick
Invitational, where Woods shot 17 under during the weekend rounds
(62-65) to break a 19-month victory drought at tour events.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I knew the swing changes were coming together,''
Woods said. ``On Saturday of that tournament, I was able to swing
naturally, instead of having to worry about each position on my
backswing and my downswing. I could visualize the shot, hit it and
there it was. I could feel it. Things were jelling.''
</P>
<P>
   By late in the season, they had solidified. Woods won five of
his last six starts at tour events, including the 1999 PGA
Championship, his second major title. He set a season earnings
record ($6,616,585), received his second Player of the Year award
from peers and touched off a fresh wave of ``Tigermania'' among
golf fans.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in today's Tiger and the 1997 Masters champion is
striking, Rhodes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, he had one speed, one shot,'' Rhodes said.
``Everything was full-bore, all the time. If he'd never (changed
his swing), he'd still have been remembered as a great player ...
and probably would have won a tournament every year or 18 months.
But he's driven to be the best who ever played. I think he'd have
been very, very frustrated if he hadn't changed anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The result, Rhodes said, is a power player who now has
creativity and shot-making skills comparable to golf legends Ben
Hogan or Byron Nelson. Woods has developed something else over the
past three years: a more mature approach to stardom.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Woods said, he feels ``far more comfortable''
dealing with the demands of the limelight than in 1997. He's three
years older and, by his estimation, quantum leaps wiser. He fidgets
less during news conferences, smiles more on the course and
interacts with a wider group of players.
</P>
<P>
   He has expressed regret for incidents where he has thrown clubs
or cursed on the course, especially in front of children. He has
taken to heart suggestions from Arnold Palmer about the need for
better displays of golf etiquette and a more deferential posture in
matters of golf history.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Woods is not big on signing autographs (too time
consuming) and he jealously guards his private time. To maintain
sanity in his life, Woods said, ``I have to be ruthless
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, the ruthless displays take place away from
television cameras and fans. Instead, fans see a rare talent who is
becoming more his own man away from the course. Since joining the
tour, Woods has fired three members of his support system put in
place by his father _ lawyer John Merchant, agent Hughes Norton and
caddie Mike ``Fluff'' Cowan _ and replaced them with confidants of
his own choosing. His father, Earl, also maintains a much lower
profile, partly by design and partly because of Earl Woods' ongoing
battle with heart disease. THE TIGER EFFECT
</P>
<P>
   The changes within his inner circle, Woods said, have made him
more relaxed in his dealings with fans, media and peers. And there
are plenty of dealings on all fronts.
</P>
<P>
   What impact has Woods had on the PGA Tour and the golf world
since his arrival? Consider:
</P>
<P>
   The season's highest-paying event, The Players Championship,
offered a $3.5 million purse in 1996, the last year Woods played
college golf. Last month, the event paid $6 million. Other tour
purses have exploded in similar proportions under a new television
agreement finalized in 1997, Woods' first full season as a tour
participant.
</P>
<P>
   Television ratings for the final round of this season's Buick
Invitational, where Woods' six-event winning streak ended, pulled
an 8.0 rating on CBS. That easily topped the 6.9 mark earned by the
NBA All-Star Game on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys taken at tour events show sharp increases in minority
and younger attendees since Woods joined the circuit. A demographic
survey from 1998 showed African-American fans accounted for 9.8
percent of tour galleries, up from 3.0 percent in 1995. There were
similar increases among other minority fans (3.8 to 3.0) and fans
in the 18-24 age group (10.0 to 7.3).
</P>
<P>
   A National Golf Foundation survey, conducted in 1998, showed the
African-American golfer population has increased by 30 percent
since 1996. In addition, the number of golf newcomers topped 2.9
million in both 1997 and 1998, well above the 2 million per year
average for the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   The First Tee, a World Golf Foundation initiative to introduce
the game to those of limited financial means, is on target to have
100 facilities completed or on the drawing board by the end of this
year. Launched in 1998, the First Tee has 13 facilities in
operation and 40 to 45 more under construction, said Len Stachitas,
acting executive director. A Fort Worth facility has been on the
drawing board since 1999, with plans to break ground when the
funding is complete.
</P>
<P>
   Those involved said Woods' nonprofit organization, the Tiger
Woods Foundation, has been a driving force in expanding the growth
of The First Tee initiative.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Finchem, the tour commissioner, said he looks at
Woods and sees a star player and role model who has become
``everything we'd hoped he would be,'' from the day he joined the
circuit in August 1996. It's why Love said Woods has learned from
past mistakes and ``is doing everything just right'' today as a
touring professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may throw a bad word out every once in a while because he's
trying so hard, but that's the worst thing you can say about the
guy,'' Davis Love said. ``His attitude is very, very good. His
physical conditioning is great.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say he's doing everything a little bit better than
everybody else on tour, all the way across the board: putting,
driving distance, control, mental game. Everything is just a little
bit sharper than everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, arguably the world's most visible athlete among active
participants, said he is comfortable with his status in the game
and in the sports world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel comfortable being a role model,'' Woods said. ``It's
cool to see more minority faces in the crowds at tournaments, and
see those people taking a serious interest in golf. My goal, all
long, was to make golf look more like America.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can live my life the way I'm going right now, and stay
true to myself, then hopefully kids will say a lot of positive
things about me ... and want to strive to be like me or better than
me. That's great, because then I know I have impacted their lives
in a positive way. Hopefully, when I'm done with golf or six feet
under, I can look back and say I left the game in better shape than
I found it.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years into a well-hyped career, golf's Next Nicklaus
appears headed in that direction. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
