<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7089 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TECH-BATTERIES05-COX     04-04 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-BATTERIES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Metro firm energy source for new electronic products
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ New electronic products are popping into the
marketplace like clockwork these days, but new radios, laptops and
wireless phones demand new battery products _ and that's what
Motorola Energy Systems Group provides.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to their new facilities unveils a dazzling display of
storage batteries, tiny and large, that range from self-charging
units you can use marooned in the jungle or powerful units that can
run a notebook computer for 11 hours straight.
</P>
<P>
   The Lawrenceville research labs and battery production lines,
part of a quiet Motorola campus near Interstate 85, are flagship
operations in Motorola's worldwide battery production subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the unique things about our operation is that we are in
at the beginning,'' said Ed Myszka, director of strategy and
business development for ESG. ``We and other companies are brought
in when any manufacturer has a new proposed product, to help them
arrive at the right energy source.''
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence Myszka and his staff always know months ahead
of the public what new things are coming down the electronics
pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 900 employees in Lawrenceville, a squadron of
engineers specializing in electronics, chemistry and polymers work
on the latest battery units, striving for products that are
powerful but also lightweight and responsive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The holy grail for people in our business is to create
batteries that are `out of sight and out of mind,' like the
batteries in your remote control,'' Myszka said.
</P>
<P>
   That's easier said than done, given the huge and growing variety
of devices now on the market that range from simple cell phones and
pagers to interactive pagers and the latest devices that act as
all-around communicators like the Motorola IDEN phone with Web
browser.
</P>
<P>
   These phones are being attached to a variety of networks by
Nextel, Microsoft and others. But because of their many uses, there
is a need for ever stronger, higher-capacity batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Because most of the units produced by Motorola carry the brand
names of the manufacturers, many consumers may be unaware of the
source of the batteries.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, nearly all lithium-ion batteries for Compaq
notebook computers are products from ESG. Micron has ordered for
some of its laptop computers a special battery system that can
function for 11 hours of steady operation.
</P>
<P>
   The lithium-ion batteries and the newer polymer batteries, the
latest ideas from the battery makers, are highly prized both for
their efficiency and for being ``smart.'' Unlike older battery
technology, they can be charged at anytime and, when used with the
proper charging units, they will not overcharge.
</P>
<P>
   Product safety is another assignment carried out in the
Lawrenceville facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there is plenty of talk and concern about product
quality, safety is one of our leading priorities,'' said Doug
Morris, technology director and who runs a laboratory that tests
products to the point of destruction.
</P>
<P>
   They test the products for various forms of stress, including
temperature, he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the latest batteries is the zinc air self-charging
battery, a light unit the size of a business card that does not
charge until opened and exposed to the air _ the kind of product
that would be useful for a person stranded for a long time in an
isolated area.
</P>
<P>
   Other cutting-edge technologies are poised to produce
lighter-weight batteries for wearable computers, and others for
Blue Tooth technologies that will provide for wireless
communication among devices within a home or office.
</P>
<P>
   What are some of the biggest challenges for battery makers?
</P>
<P>
   To come up with longer-lasting units, perhaps powered by fuel
cells, said Myszka, and also for tinier devices.
</P>
<P>
   Among those around the corner are, yes, the Dick Tracy
wristwatch communicators. And wireless phones that consist mostly
of an earpiece and a mouthpiece attached to the lapel, perhaps the
ultimate hands-free communication.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
