A7092 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GLENN-BO     04-04 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GLENN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN SEEKS NEW DEAL FROM PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Is a Keyshawn Johnson-like storm brewing in
New England?
</P>
<P>
   Terry Glenn and his agent, James Gould, will know in the next 10
days.
</P>
<P>
   Gould confirmed Tuesday that he has asked the Patriots for a new
multiyear deal for Glenn, who, like the Jets' Johnson, has two
years remaining on his current pact. Gould expects to talk with the
Patriots this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' plans for the April 15 draft could be altered
depending on how Glenn and Gould react if they receive ``no'' for
an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll definitely know more by the end of the week,'' said
Gould. ``To this point there's been a spirit of cooperation between
Terry and the team. My sense was the Patriots were genuinely taking
the request seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, who caught 69 passes for 1,147 yards, last season, is
part of the great 1996 wide receiver class that produced Johnson
(No. 1 to the Jets), Glenn (No. 7 to the Patriots), Marvin Harrison
(No. 19 to the Colts), and Eric Moulds (No. 24 to the Bills).
</P>
<P>
   Harrison reportedly is close to a four-year deal that would
include an $11 million signing bonus and average $6 million a year.
That certainly would be a measuring stick for Johnson and Glenn,
though Harrison had biggers numbers last year: 115 passes for 1,663
yards and 12 touchdowns. He was scheduled to earn $1.02 million
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who caught 89 passes for 1,170 yards, requested that
his contract be redone, but new Jets owner Woody Johnson has
emphatically stated that he should honor the deal he has. Johnson
is scheduled to earn $2.24 million this year and $2.46 million in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens, Buccaneers, and Redskins had some interest in
talking trade with the Jets for Johnson, but now that appears
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Moulds, who caught 65 passes for 994 yards, is entering the
final year of his contract and will earn just under $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn has been a willing participant in the Patriots' strength
and conditioning program after coach Bill Belichick strongly urged
that he be on hand. With Ben Coates and Shawn Jefferson out of the
receiving picture, Glenn will be relied on even more in the
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn is scheduled to earn $2.3 million this season, which
includes a $200,000 reporting bonus and a $56,000 workout bonus.
His pay next season is around $2.4 million, with a base of $1.2
million and a reporting bonus of $1.13 million, as well as a
workout bonus.
</P>
<P>
   But he is not the Patriots' highest-paid receiver. The team
signed Troy Brown to a five-year, $12.5 million deal this year.
</P>
<P>
   There seems to have been a sense of goodwill between Glenn and
the Patriots since Belichick came aboard, with Belichick even
dropping the suspension Glenn was handed by Pete Carroll at the end
of last season for allegedly violating team procedures in how he
handled an illness.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn has said he wants to bear the burden of being the big-play
receiver, the ``go-to'' guy. For that, he would like to be
compensated the way the best receivers in the game are.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
