<HEADER>
A7093 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS-NYT     04-04 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORGAN-TRANSPLANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE VOTES TO KEEP CURRENT SYSTEM OF ALLOCATING DONATED ORGANS
</HEADLINE>
 By ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House approved legislation Tuesday that would
block the Clinton administration's plans to revamp the nation's
system for allocating donated organs based on medical need,
regardless of where the recipients live.
</P>
<P>
   The action fuels a long-running fight between Congress and the
administration over which patients should have priority in
receiving human organs, the nation's scarcest medical resource, and
what role the federal government should have in that process.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers, by a vote of 275-147, reaffirmed that the authority
for organ distribution lies not with the federal government, but
with the private sector and specifically with the United Network
for Organ Sharing, a nonprofit agency that is under contract with
the government to coordinate distribution of donated human organs.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, if enacted, would overturn a long-delayed federal
regulation that took effect on March 16. The rule gives the
secretary of health and human services, Donna Shalala, authority to
direct the agency to change its policies so organs are shared
broadly across regional lines, with sickest patients generally
given first priority.
</P>
<P>
   The debate, which has been waged along parochial lines rather
than party lines, affects thousands of patients nationwide, many of
whom are critically ill and have been waiting for months or years
for new organs.
</P>
<P>
   A similar bill, sponsored by Sen. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., who is a
physician, is to be introduced in the Senate on Wednesday. But the
Senate bill differs from the House version in at least one
important way: The ultimate policy would be made by a commission
made up of federal authorities, the transplant agency and an
independent medical institute.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's advisers say they would recommend he veto
the House bill, arguing in a policy statement put out by the White
House that the measure ``would preserve existing inequities in the
organ transplantation system, and could result in potential harm to
patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Shalala, in a statement after the vote, observed that supporters
failed to muster a veto-proof majority, and said the House measure
would be remembered as ``an unfortunate footnote to the larger
good-faith efforts that are underway to achieve the best organ
transplant system possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the existing system, the country is divided into 11
regions, which are in turn split into 62 local areas; these areas
range in size from a few counties to several states, and in
population from 1 million to 12 million.
</P>
<P>
   When an organ becomes available, it is offered locally first. If
a matching patient is not found, the organ is then offered
regionally, and, in rare cases, nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala has criticized the system as unfair to patients because
waiting times vary greatly from region to region. Under the new
federal regulation, the organ-sharing network must propose a plan
that meets new federal requirements for broader, regional sharing.
If not, Shalala could propose one herself.
</P>
<P>
   But in a key amendment, the House rejected a proposal to codify
that approach. The vote was 260-160. Later, by voice vote,
lawmakers agreed to nullify the regulation altogether.
</P>
<P>
   In spirited debate on the House floor, critics of Shalala's
approach defended the current system. ``It keeps organ allocation
out of the hands of federal bureaucrats and in the hands of local
communities,'' said Rep. Joe Scarborough, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Martha M. Kendrick, a lobbyist for the Patient Access to
Transplant Coalition, a group of 29 transplant centers of varying
sizes, said, ``The system today tries to do the greatest good for
the greatest number of patients.''
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of the existing system say it places too much
authority in a private company, and denies organs to the neediest
patients. The Health and Human Services Department ``worked hard to
come up with a final rule that reflects the views of patients,
donors and the medical community,'' said Rep. Sherrod Brown,
D-Ohio. ``The right way to serve the public interest is not to
protect a private government contractor.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 66,000 Americans are now waiting for a heart, lung,
liver, kidney or pancreas and, according to the health and human
services agency, nearly 5,000 patients die every year while
awaiting a transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Organ donation has grown much more slowly than demand. The
federal health agency said that the number of transplants performed
increased to 20,961 in 1998 from 12,618 in 1988. But the number of
donations only increased to 9,913 in 1998 from 5,906 in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   To help resolve that shortfall, the House on Tuesday adopted an
amendment authorizing $15 million in grants to states that promote
organ donation.
</P>
<P>
   (nk)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
