<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7094 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-STOCKS-BOS &LR;      04-04 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-STOCKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOT-COM COMPANIES AWAITING IPOS SUFFER THROUGH NASDAQ DIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You could smell the fear.
</P>
<P>
   At their worst point in the day, Nasdaq stocks had nearly
doubled their Monday losses, for a 20 percent dive in less than 48
hours. For entrepreneurs and venture capitalists, it was a stark
sign that the easy money may be over for initial public stock
offerings of dot-com companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's simply a reminder of how quickly these markets come and
go for companies that don't have earnings,'' said Andy McLane,
managing director at TA Associates, a Boston private-equity firm.
</P>
<P>
   Most start-up companies with venture backing don't have profits.
But that hasn't bothered the investors who have been snapping up
young technology companies as soon as they hit the IPO market.
</P>
<P>
   ``A company could achieve a billion-dollar market capitalization
overnight _ until today,'' McLane said.
</P>
<P>
   The hot IPO market lately has enabled venture capitalists to
take fledgling high-tech companies to the public markets after only
a year or two, about the half the time it typically takes.
</P>
<P>
   That means stock investors, eager to fetch big returns on
high-flying technology companies, are taking on more risk than they
would with more established companies.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the late 1970s, and briefly during the biotech craze
of the 1980s, have ordinary investors taken on so much risk in
unproven companies, McLane said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shareholders are being venture capitalists,'' he observed.
``The public markets have been providing the second and third
rounds of venture financing.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, venture capital firms have been getting cool receptions
from mutual fund managers and other big investors for their
consumer Web site companies. Most firms are avoiding investing in
business-to-consumer companies, as a result, and are also being
more cautious about their business-to-business financings.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Cowan, a general partner with Bowman Capital in San
Mateo, Calif., said the volatile Nasdaq market will have a chilling
effect _ and perhaps tilt things back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are b-to-c companies in registration right now that will
never get out,'' or go public, Cowan said. ``The world does not
need the tenth entrant into an already competitive sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Many venture capital firms from Boston to Silicon Valley have
portfolios with as many as six companies waiting to go public in
the next few months. A weaker stock market makes it harder to
launch IPOs, as investors sign up for fewer shares of firms deemed
to be risky.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture.com Inc., the Framingham-based online furniture site
that's backed by CMGI Inc., is slated to go public this month. So
is Zefer Corp., a Boston Web-strategy consulting company. I3 Mobile
Inc., a Stamford, Conn.-based provider of wireless Web equipment,
is supposed to be priced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   None of the companies was willing to say whether it would delay
its IPO as a result of the bloodletting on the Nasdaq. Some
companies delayed their IPOs. MetLife, the big New York insurer,
went ahead and priced its IPO on the New York Stock Exchange, at
$14.25, having previously scaled back its hopes for raising money
by half, to $2.88 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, entrepreneurs poised to file for public offerings
this year had to brace for disappointment Tuesday. Some observers
said the reality check would be good for the market and for
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the market saying, `We've had enough of this
particular type of company, so stop the flow,' '' said Jonathan
Guerster, a principal with Charles River Ventures in Waltham. ``It
shakes out the companies that are less strong (whether they are)
public or poised to go public.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Guerster suggested, the stock prices of the better
companies will rise. In the meantime, he admitted, for companies
that are getting mid- to late-stage venture capital, ``this is
putting hiccups in their plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists are shrugging off the market jitters, saying
they'll go back to their old practices if the IPO market shuts down
for a while. When they can't take companies public, venture firms
tend to hold on to companies for longer and pour more money into
them. They eventually try to sell them to larger companies, or wait
for a new IPO window.
</P>
<P>
   Said Bowman's Cowan: ``We may be back to some sense of normalcy,
where companies have to show a clear path to profitability before
going public.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
