<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7095 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-NASDAQ-FREEFALL-BOS &LR;      04-04 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASDAQ-FREEFALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ FREEFALL EASED BY LATE TURNAROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stock market went for a wild ride Tuesday as panicked
investors drove the Nasdaq down 575 points and the Dow more than
500 points before both indexes snapped back in a dramatic afternoon
turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   At day's end, losses in the technology-dominated Nasdaq were
contained at a modest 74.79 points, down 1.77 percent to 4148.89.
It was a remarkable comeback for the index which had, at its low
point, shed almost 14 percent in a temporary rout that evoked
memories of the 1987 market crash.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow, which also recovered, lost 57.09 points _ just one-half
a percent. The Dow closed at 11,164.84.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rebound, the rollercoaster market unnerved
investors. One expert called it ``one of the whackiest days'' ever
on Wall Street, and it came on the heels of Nasdaq's enormous
decline Monday in reaction to the collapse of settlement talks in
the Microsoft antitrust case. Over the past week, Nasdaq's
double-digit gains in year 2000 have been trimmed to a modest 1.96
percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet technology shares remain highly valued and, many believe,
vulnerable to further declines: Nasdaq is more than twice its level
of a year ago when it was just over 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   If Nasdaq stocks slip again, economists said the US economy _
and particularly high-tech cities such as Boston and San Francisco
_ will suffer. Initial offerings by small companies are already
being canceled due to uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Boston area is doubly vulnerable because it has such a
high concentration in the financial services industry, as well as
the technology sector,'' said Rachael Chioino, economist for
Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI, a consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Investors early on engaged in panic selling amid doubt about
their tech shares' prospects in the aftermath of a federal court
ruling charging Microsoft with illegally hurting competition in the
software industry. As the market sank, some investors who had
bought shares with borrowed money were forced to sell to meet
brokers' demands for more cash.
</P>
<P>
   Then, steely investors, taking advantage of the technology
industry's plunge, rushed back in and bought shares, said Bruce
Addison, Boston branch manger for First Union Securities, a
brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   The ``meltdown,'' he said, started with Microsoft and spread to
other companies. At first, ``nobody was buying.'' As the day
progressed, investors started calling up and placing orders to buy.
``At mid-afternoon, the volume picked up, buyers stepped in, and we
showed strength in buying right into the close,'' Addison said.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq's performance this year is still better than the Dow's,
which is down 2.89 percent since Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   But such volatility in technology stocks bodes huge
uncertainties for investors. After Nasdaq retreated last week, a
growing number of investment analysts speculated the bubble was
bursting. The performance added to the confusion but did nothing to
deter pessimists.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors seeking a safe place for their money purchased US
Treasury bonds, which experienced their biggest rally in almost two
months. The yield on 30-year Treasury bonds dropped 3 basis points
to 5.78 percent, its lowest level since May 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a month now where the Dow has outperformed the
Nasdaq,'' said Boston money manager Kenneth Heebner. ``If money
starts coming out of Nasdaq, that could pop the tech bubble.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Cliggott, managing director for J.P. Morgan in New York,
said stock traders had a glimpse of a dark day. Traders, he said,
were ``starting to come to grips with what things might look like
when liquidity dries up. That's where their sharpest declines were
_ in a lot of the Nasdaq names.''
</P>
<P>
   At the market's depths, institutional investors were seeking
buyers for 10,000-share blocks of giant technology companies, such
as Microsoft, Oracle Corp. and EMC Corp., one broker said. A
shortage of buyers for technology shares pushed Nasdaq down
sharply. Microsoft lost another $2.3125 a share, closing at
$88.5625. Oracle Corp.'s stock price was shaved 94 cents, closing
at $75.94, but EMC rose $1 a share, to $128.
</P>
<P>
   But, drugmakers' shares, led by Bristol-Myers Squibb Co. and
Pharmacia Corp., rose as investors left biotechnology and bought
stakes in pharmaceutical stalwarts.
</P>
<P>
   For now, doomsday predictions were put on hold due to one of the
most dramatic rebounds in the stock market's history.
</P>
<P>
   There was sharp disagreement among experts about where the
technology sector and financial markets are going. Wayne Ayers,
chief economist for FleetBoston Financial, argued that a strong
economy provides a floor under stocks _ even Nasdaq stocks. The
federal government reported recently that the US grew 7 percent in
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a Nasdaq correction but whether we plummet further
from here _ I don't think that's likely,'' said Ayers. ``This
economy, while it's going to slow, isn't in any danger of falling
off a cliff.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Yardeni, an economist at Deutsche Bank Securities, said
his belief that a new technology-based economy is emerging does not
mean Nasdaq's near future is assured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a believer in the new economy doesn't mean I haven't
perceived the bubble characteristics in the Nasdaq,'' Yardeni said.
``There's the economy, and there's the stock market, and they don't
always tell the same story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
