<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7097 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-BARLOW-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-04 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARLOW-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
WHY GIVING STAFF FREE PCs IS SMART 
 
By JIM BARLOW 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Intel Corp., the huge California maker of computer chips, is
giving its 70,000 full- and part-time employees a Pentium III
computer, Internet access and frequent computer updates _ for free.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. says it will buy high-speed computers for all its
350,000 employees and throw in unlimited Internet access _ for $5 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Airlines will give free computers to its 72,000 employees.
General Motors and United Airlines are exploring doing the same.
</P>
<P>
   Just another example of perks gone mad? Not so, says Adam
Corson-Finnerty, director of external affairs for the University of
Pennsylvania library, in a piece he wrote for the Wharton School of
Business.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are actually saving money by giving _ or nearly
giving _ computers to their employees to use at home.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BETTER COMPUTER SKILLS NEEDED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's why that's true.
</P>
<P>
   We are in the computer age. They are used in business for
everything from controlling tools on the factory floor to getting
out an order to a customer.
</P>
<P>
   Companies need employees with computer literacy. Which is a
fancy way of saying that employees need to be able to use a
computer, not be afraid of it. For the computer is a tool, no more
or less than a screwdriver. You don't need to know how to build a
screwdriver to use it. You don't need to know how to program a
computer to do likewise.
</P>
<P>
   Employees who are wired can also push ideas up the chain of
command with little or no effort. And companies can push down
memos, the company newsletter, benefits manuals and a wide range of
communications to employees at little or no cost.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual teams can be formed and meet over the Internet, saving
millions in travel costs.
</P>
<P>
   People with computer skills are a hot ticket item these days.
Instead of going out and paying top bucks for those folks, the
companies giving their employees take-home computers are, in
effect, growing their own.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LEARN AT HOME, CUT TRAINING COSTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now they could develop those same computer literacy skills by
setting up massive training programs. But consider the costs. A
company would have to hire consultants, buy computers, build
classrooms and pull people off their jobs during regulator working
hours or pay overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Giving employees computers seems downright cheap. Let them play
at home on their own time. The results will be about the same. And
when it comes time for formal training on software they might not
encounter at home, the employees don't have to start at ground
zero.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows, the companies might even make money on the deal. Ford
will have 350,000 people hooked to its network. That's a lot of
buying power. Perhaps the company can make deals with Internet
companies so their employees can get lower prices, and the company
can get a tiny piece of the price in return for access to the
network and deducting purchases from the paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   Employees who didn't want to buy from the company Internet store
could easily bypass it. Which means that the company would have to
offer real values in price and services. If it did, everybody would
win. Employees would get better goods at lower prices, the company
would get a few cents profit and the Internet suppliers of products
and services would get a huge customer base to appeal to.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the downside to a company wiring its employees?
Simple. While the company can more easily communicate with them, so
can anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   You might have read recently how unions are using computers to
help them organize new members and keep in touch with old ones.
</P>
<P>
   All the major unions, and many locals, now have Web sites. That
makes it easy for a disgruntled employee to contact them.
</P>
<P>
   Which means that Ford, which prides itself on its good employee
relations, might find it harder to relate. Delta, its
once-excellent employee relations hurt by a cost-cutting initiative
a few years ago, will have to redouble its communications efforts
with employees.
</P>
<P>
   Will non-union companies, which supply employees with computers,
put themselves in union jeopardy? If so, their employee relations
are so poor they deserve it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
