<HEADER>
A7103 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FACT-FICTION-ART-2TAK     04-04 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FACT-FICTION-ART-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAYING BARE THE UNCERTAIN UNDERSIDE OF THE TRUTH  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos was sent as NYT32-33 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.) 
 Tessa DeCarlo's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about
the artist Thomas Kinkade.  
 By TESSA DeCARLO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At a time when ``based on real-life events!''
and ``a true story!'' are the most popular come-ons for everything
from memoirs to movies, an entertaining show at the San Francisco
Museum of Modern Art investigates contemporary artists' fascination
with the opposite tactics of fakery, disguise and deceit.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, titled ``Fact/Fiction: Contemporary Art That
Walks the Line,'' presents 82 works that embrace the appearance and
techniques of realism, yet delight in exposing realism as just
another deception. True, there's nothing new about artists using
deception _ the illusion of perspective, for example, or tricks of
light _ to reveal a higher truth. But in this show, as in a great
deal of art nowadays, the higher truth seems to be that truth
itself is a perilously slippery concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fact/Fiction'' runs through next Sunday and draws on the
museum's permanent holdings and the vast collection of Vicki and
Kent Logan, a local couple who have given or promised more than 300
works to the museum. Thanks to them and other donors, the museum
has been aggressively expanding its contemporary holdings in recent
years, adding works by Jasper Johns, Robert Rauschenberg and other
big names as well as a host of younger artists.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the wave of new acquisitions helped inspire the show's
theme, says Janet Bishop, the museum's associate curator of
painting and sculpture. ``I noticed that in the justifications we
were writing for acquiring new works, the play between fact and
fiction kept coming up again and again,'' she says. ``It seemed
like a great way to look at our contemporary collection.''
</P>
<P>
   The show starts in the 1960s, with a pile of 11 of Andy Warhol's
Brillo, Campbell's tomato juice and Kellogg's cornflakes boxes _
blocks of wood painted and stenciled to look exactly like the large
cardboard cartons in which these popular consumables travel to
market. On two adjacent walls are a set of Cindy Sherman's
``Untitled Film Stills'' from the late 1970s, with the artist
posing as battered woman, film noir femme and sex kitten. The
juxtaposition reveals that Sherman's photographs are as teasingly
deceptive as Warhol's boxes, and that the cinematic conventions she
exploits are every bit as prefabricated as cereal packages.
</P>
<P>
   On a third wall is a set of more recent fake film stills, a
series of 1996 ``self-portraits'' by Yasumasa Morimura, who
photographs himself elaborately cross-dressed as Liza Minnelli,
Greta Garbo, Marilyn Monroe and other screen divas. Around the
corner are Morimura's three gigantic, digitally created renditions
of himself as da Vinci's Mona Lisa, first clothed, then nude and
pregnant, then in cross-section, revealing the heart, lungs and
fetus within.
</P>
<P>
   The Warhol boxes and Sherman's pictures look austerely classical
by comparison, yet Morimura's exhibitionism also seems like an
inevitable outgrowth of the earlier works' more discreet campiness,
fired by the same desire to reinvent the world rather than merely
comment on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether they're referring to art history or movies or objects
from the everyday world, artists are taking as their starting point
things that people know,'' Bishop says. ``And they're showing that
artists as well as writers are in the wonderful position of being
able to present a new reality.''
</P>
<P>
   If works of art can be said to converse with each other, the
dialogue among the reimagined realities in ``Fact/Fiction'' is the
visual equivalent of a high-energy cocktail party, with allusions,
influences, jokes and arguments caroming off the gallery walls.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in one room a small card concocted by the local
artist Tom Marioni announces that he has just been named the San
Francisco museum's new director _ a hoax that fooled many
colleagues when the artist mailed it in 1971. Across the room, a
small painting by Sandow Birk imagines what the museum and its
environs might look like after several days of aerial bombing. It's
hard to think of a better summing up of artists' love-hate
relationship with the museum as institution.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Stephanie Syjuco's carefully drawn ``False Botanical
Studies'' of a plastic daisy debate the nature of reality, and the
reality of nature, with Nic Nicosia's obviously staged ``Real
Picture'' of three children burning down a tree.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gober seems to be replying to Warhol's boxes with a
hand-crafted sack of Kitty Litter that slouches in a corner, while
Cindy Sherman's photos turn a cool eye on Jeff Koons' series of
advertisements for himself in which the tanned, blow-dried and
meticulously made-up artist is shown variously embracing pigs and
teaching enthusiastic schoolchildren a lesson on ``Banality as
Savior.''
</P>
<P>
   The show as a whole can even be seen as a high-spirited
rejoinder to the Sol LeWitt retrospective also on view at the
museum. After two floors of LeWitt's insistence that a line is a
line and nothing more, ``Fact/Fiction's'' revelations of the
personal and embrace of the everyday are a welcome change _ even if
they're far from sincere.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the show's most extreme challenge to notions about
what's really real comes from Sherrie Levine's 1981 copies of two
photographs by Walker Evans. Virtually indistinguishable from the
revered photographer's original prints, the two photographs elevate
theft to an art form, and call it ``appropriation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stealing is something everyone understands,'' says Levine, who
confesses she was a shoplifter in her youth. ``They might not like
it, but they get it. And the art history side of it is the fact
that stealing is what all artists do.''
</P>
<P>
   While many works in the show comment on the realities and
unrealities of the art world, others examine the world everybody
else inhabits. Thomas Demand's six-and-a-half-foot-wide photograph
titled ``Corner'' appears at first to depict the most mundane
scene: an office cubicle messily strewn with papers and manuals.
</P>
<P>
   But then the eerie blankness of the desktop, the lack of
identifying names or logos on the manuals and the computer, reveals
that this is in fact a picture _ a strangely beautiful picture _ of
a paper model, which duplicates with fanatical fidelity something
that would probably never engage our attention if it were real.
</P>
<P>
   One of the show's most dazzling feats of trompe l'oeil is Steve
Wolfe's three-dimensional rendering of a stack of cardboard cartons
filled with books. The bright colors of the cartons and the
interplay of the book covers _ ``Conversations With Duchamp''
alongside Raymond Carver's ``What We Talk About When We Talk About
Love'' alongside a book about that modernist icon of lovesickness,
Krazy Kat _ offer a feast of visual, historical and philosophical
ideas. But the viewer must see past Wolfe's virtuosity to glimpse
the art beneath the artfulness.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, a Tina Barney photograph demonstrates in a different way
how issues of fact and fabrication can become so intertwined they
can hardly be unraveled. The 1989 photo shows Barney, looking tense
and rather aggrieved, talking to her two 20-something sons around a
barbecue grill on a summer evening. It could almost be a snapshot,
yet its size, its technical perfection and the beauty of the colors
and the composition tell us it is anything but.
</P>
<P>
   The picture was in fact carefully posed, as Barney hints by
showing the camera's shutter release in her hand. Yet the feelings
revealed in her face were not entirely an act, she says, because
she was genuinely anxious about capturing the shot before the light
faded, and sad that divorce and her sons' growing up seemed to be
dissolving her family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing people always want to know more than anything is _
is it real?'' Barney says. Like most of the works in
``Fact/Fiction,'' her photograph answers ``yes'' and ``no'' with
equal truth. (af)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 2029EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
