<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7106 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-RIDGE-NYT &LR;      04-04 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-RIDGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S BEHIND THE SMILE? MAYBE AN OFFER TO RUN FOR VICE PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Like impatient relatives expecting a wedding
announcement, reporters analyzed every nuance of the political
flirtation between Govs. George W. Bush of Texas and Tom Ridge of
Pennsylvania, looking for signs of a ring.
</P>
<P>
   There was the frequency of their exchanged smiles and the
gallantry in the way they introduced each other to audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was where Bush chose to stay between campaign
appearances in Pennsylvania on Monday and Tuesday: at Ridge's pad.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels had been good enough last week when Bush dropped in on
Gov. Christie Whitman of New Jersey and Gov. Tommy Thompson of
Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Why the change?
</P>
<P>
   ``Fiscally conservative; huge TV screen for the Final Four; like
him,'' said Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee,
aboard his campaign plane on Monday afternoon, suggesting that
thrift and college basketball were secondary in the equation.
</P>
<P>
   His coy, teasing manner indicated an understanding of what
reporters, Washington pundits and aficionados of politics
everywhere really wanted to know. Was Ridge a serious vice
presidential possibility? And if not him, who?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no lists, and I won't for awhile,'' Bush insisted at a
news conference on Tuesday in Abington, Pa., near Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Less than a month after he and Vice President Al Gore
effectively secured their parties' presidential nominations, the
guessing game is in full swing, with a dizzying array of names
being tossed around, and the two candidates' actions being
scrutinized for even the murkiest signals.
</P>
<P>
   The Hotline, an Internet journal that political junkies read
with an almost fanatical devotion, recently published the names of
22 Republicans and 20 Democrats who might make the vice
presidential cut. The lengths of those lists have raised hedging to
a new level and have guaranteed contented hours of cocktail
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant Gumbel last week apportioned a lengthy segment of his CBS
morning program, ``The Early Show,'' to the soothsayings of Jack
Kemp, the Republican vice presidential nominee in 1996, and former
Gov. Mario Cuomo of New York, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Both men readily conceded that it was too soon to credibly
handicap the vice presidential sweepstakes, then went ahead and did
precisely that, proving that when it comes to the political world's
closest approximation of the Oscars, nobody can resist.
</P>
<P>
   Political operatives in and around Washington say that the
casual conversation about the subject has become nonstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable,'' said Greg Mueller, a Republican
strategist who worked on the presidential campaign of Steve Forbes.
``A lot of us consultants work for corporations not necessarily
involved in politics, but the first topic when you sit down at a
table is always, `Who is Bush going to pick?' or `Who is Gore going
to pick?' The list grows with every meeting inside the Beltway.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, the roll call often begins with Ridge,
in part because Gen. Colin Powell has repeatedly disavowed any
interest. Other names include Thompson, Gov. Frank Keating of
Oklahoma, Elizabeth Dole, Sen. Fred Thompson of Tennessee, Rep.
John R. Kasich of Ohio, former Defense Secretary Richard Cheney,
Sen. Connie Mack of Florida and Sen. John McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, the chatter encompasses Sen. Bob Graham
of Florida, Sen. Evan Bayh of Indiana, Sen. Richard Durbin of
Illinois, Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, Sen. Dianne Feinstein
of California and Gov. James B. Hunt Jr. of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The mention of almost any of these names is accompanied by an
elaborate rationale. The argument for Ridge reflects several
factors that are typically cited and often guide the selection of a
vice presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Geography, for starters. Ridge, in his second term as governor,
leads a state that has the fifth highest number of electoral votes,
23, and does not lean too strongly in either party's direction. His
presence on the ticket could tip Pennsylvania toward Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Biography. Presidential candidates often choose running mates
who offset their potential weaknesses. Bush, 53, was a child of
privilege who did not fight in Vietnam, while Ridge, 54, grew up in
humbler circumstances and earned a bronze star for his tour of duty
there.
</P>
<P>
   Religion. Ridge, who is Roman Catholic, could strengthen Bush's
appeal to voters of that faith and help undo any lingering damage
from Bush's visit to Bob Jones University, a South Carolina school
with a history of anti-Catholic bias.
</P>
<P>
   Political record. This is where Ridge represents either a bold
opportunity or a potential disaster, and it all boils down to his
support for abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   By choosing Ridge, Bush might be able to diminish fears among
some swing voters that he is too far to the right on social issues.
But he might also inflame social and religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   As Bush and Ridge traveled around Pennsylvania this week,
reporters repeatedly asked the Texas governor whether Ridge's
position on abortion would remove him from consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Bush answered somewhat evasively, saying the principal criteria
he would use to pick a vice president were whether the person was
ready to become president and whether the person liked him.
</P>
<P>
   Although the question was serious, it did not seem to prevent
the two governors from toying with all the speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure, over the next couple of months, people are going to
say, `Did the governor call you?,''' Ridge said on Monday afternoon
in Aliquippa, Pa., just outside Pittsburgh. ``And I'm just not
going to tell you if he calls or when he calls. And I think it's
very important.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the governor's call, pure and simple,'' Ridge continued,
dwelling on the topic for an awfully long time. ``And the last
thing in that very important process he needs is a bunch of other
elected officials running around saying, `Hey, I got a call! I got
a call! I'm on the list! I'm on the list!'''
</P>
<P>
   As he chanted those last lines, he pumped his hands up and down,
mimicking an excited little boy. Bush raised his eyebrows at the
spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to try that again?'' Bush said, and the two men's
reactions demonstrated yet another reason they might want to join
forces. They laugh at the same jokes.
</P>
<P>
   (sw)
</P>
</TEXT>
