<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7107 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-OLSHER-RADIO-SHOW-ART     04-04 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLSHER-RADIO-SHOW-ART-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RADIO HOST EMPOWERED TO FOLLOW HIS WHIMS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo was sent as NYT13 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.) 
 Valerie Gladstone's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was
about the choreographer Bob Fosse.  
 By VALERIE GLADSTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Most radio shows are as predictable as sunrise. Dean
Olsher has decided to surprise listeners by following his own
fancy. Olsher, a former cultural correspondent for National Public
Radio, will be the host of ``The Next Big Thing,'' a one-hour
weekend program that will go on the air this summer on WNYC.
</P>
<P>
   Over dinner in Manhattan, months before its debut, he said
excitedly, ``It will be about anything.'' Not about the next big
thing? ``No,'' he said, laughing, ``the title is ironic.''
</P>
<P>
   To give listeners an idea of what he is up to, Olsher, who at 36
looks like a young college professor, has been presenting a series
of specials to commemorate WNYC's 75th anniversary. The first,
``This Is What I Live For,'' broadcast earlier in the year, will be
rebroadcast this Sunday at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   As the show begins, Charles Mingus's mellow ``II B.S'' fades in
the background. ``Pop psychologists have started to tell us that
it's a bad idea to equate who we are with what we do for a
living,'' Olsher says. ```Don't define yourself by your job,' they
say.'' The Mingus returns before he continues. ``It's such a downer
when somebody says, `That's why they call it work; otherwise they'd
call it play.' Wouldn't it be great if that idea would be replaced
with what Buddhists call `right livelihood' _ the idea that what
you do for a living should be a natural extension of your
personality?''
</P>
<P>
   The talk then turns to dream jobs, with Olsher confessing his
own secret wish to play cello with the Guarneri Quartet. But is
David Soyer, the cellist with the Guarneri Quartet, content? No, it
turns out. When Soyer comes on the air, he fantasizes about being a
tugboat captain, although not in choppy seas. What about the
tugboat captain Buddy Cantrelle? The job is lonely, he reports.
Running a Cajun restaurant might be cozier. And so it goes, until
Olsher discovers, in his idiosyncratic survey, that nothing beats
being paid for animal care.
</P>
<P>
   How quirky can jobs get? Olsher visits the actress Sally Parrish
backstage at the acclaimed play ``Wit''; though pivotal to the
drama, she has few moments onstage. Dolly Gallo. 85, explains why
she does not want to be paid for selling gifts at a South Street
Seaport shop, interspersing gossip about her customers with salty
memories of her childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Other unusual New Yorkers appear before the program closes with
a dramatic reading by the actor Barnard Hughes of Herman Melville's
melancholy short story, ``Bartleby the Scrivener,'' whose
protagonist stubbornly refuses to work. Artfully, Olsher comes full
circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wake up in the middle of the night thinking about ideas for
upcoming programs,'' Olsher said. One brainstorm led to a segment
in February called ``Every Day Is a New Thing to See'' in which he
accompanied the architectural historian Tony Hiss on a tour of
Grand Central Terminal, chancing upon little-known glories.
</P>
<P>
   On the same program, the writer Paul Auster read from his
stories about the physical space of New York. A March special on
consumption, ``How Can Anybody Explain the Success of a Product
Like Jell-O,'' sparkled with segments by David Rakoff and Janeane
Garofalo doing improv comedy in the style of Nichols and May.
</P>
<P>
   It seems Olsher was destined to create a radio program. How many
kids spend their youth, as he did in rural Hunterdon County, N.J.,
ignoring television and hooked on ``The Bob and Ray Show'' on WOR
and Jonathan Schwartz on WNEW? ``I always got attached to the
people on the radio,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After college at Simon's Rock in Great Barrington, Mass., and
graduate studies in musicology at the University of North Carolina,
he signed on as the afternoon announcer at WUNC in Chapel Hill in
1985 and freelanced cultural reports for NPR before being hired as
a correspondent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Cappello, director of programming at WNYC, was crucial in
getting ``The Next Big Thing'' on the air. ``Dean had been a
standout on NPR,'' Cappello said. ``I wanted to set him free.''
They had both been thinking about a New York-focused show with a
magazine format that would do things differently.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Laura Walker, president of WNYC, was already
planning to expand the station's cultural programming. ``I'd like
to see the arts talked about with the same passion as sports and
politics,'' she said. Later this year, the station will broadcast
another cultural program, ``Studio 360,'' with the journalist Kurt
Andersen as host.
</P>
<P>
   But even with WNYC's enthusiastic support, Olsher has a tough
road ahead. While special series and shows devoted to music are
mainstays of public radio, daily and weekly cultural programs have
not had much luck. The few noteworthy exceptions include Garrison
Keillor's ``A Prairie Home Companion,'' from Minnesota Public
Radio; Terry Gross's ``Fresh Air,'' from WHYY in Philadelphia;
Leonard Lopate's ``New York &AMP; Company,'' from WNYC; and a relative
newcomer, Ira Glass's ``This American Life,'' from WBEZ in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One reason for their scarcity is that ever since NPR became a
major news source during the Persian Gulf war in 1990, news has
increasingly dominated air time on public radio. ``We spend five
times more money on news than culture,'' said Kevin Klose, NPR's
president, vowing a change. In fact, the network just hired Bill
Davis, former general manager of WUNC in Chapel Hill, specifically
to oversee that change.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the field think it will take a minor revolution for
public radio to regain its creativity. Partly out of frustration,
Jay Kernis, who had produced popular news-oriented programs for
NPR, left the network in 1987 to become a producer of ``60
Minutes'' on CBS-TV. For Kernis, the question is whether NPR and
Public Radio International (PRI) are supplying the 600 public radio
stations with the programming they should have.
</P>
<P>
   Radio, he said, echoing the CBS producer Don Hewitt, has a
journalism part and a show business part, an Edward R. Murrow side
and an Ed Sullivan side. ``Right now,'' he said, ``the Murrow side
is more appreciated. We need storytellers. People are hungry for
shows like `A Prairie Home Companion,' `Fresh Air' and `This
American Life.'''
</P>
<P>
   These programs were not overnight hits. ``A Prairie Home
Companion'' went on the air in 1974 and was only picked up by NPR
in 1979. Gross, considered by her peers to be one of the best
interviewers in the business, became the host of ``Fresh Air'' in
1975 and slowly built enough of a following to be distributed
nationally by NPR in 1989. Glass's ``This American Life,'' with its
first-person stories, fiction and poetry, has been on the air since
1995 and is now one of the fastest growing programs in public
radio, nationally distributed by PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew how to market myself,'' Glass said. ``I hired a
part-time publicist, sent out funny postcards, and offered every
station entertaining spots for their pledge drives.'' Just as
important, Glass connected with his listeners.
</P>
<P>
   But charismatic hosts and lively subjects do not necessarily
keep shows on the air. In 1989, NPR launched ``Heat,'' with John
Hockenberry as the host. An innovative mix of public affairs
segments and performances, it lasted barely a year. ``The recession
came along, and the network wasn't finding the underwriting dollars
they had committed to,'' said Steve Rathe, president of Murray
Street Enterprise, which created the program with WGBH in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't NPR's own baby. I understand.'' Sometimes, he said,
even the brightest executives cannot identify the next good thing.
``The greatest successes have been built by passionate _ maybe a
little crazy _ individuals scattered around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Another adventurous program, ``Anthem,'' produced by NPR in
1998, did not last quite two years. One of its hosts, Rick Karr,
now an NPR cultural correspondent, thinks its concept was too
complex to sell to stations. ``It was more than offbeat music,'' he
said. ``We couldn't sum it up in 10 words. It was also expensive.
The best way to launch one of these programs is fast and cheap.''
</P>
<P>
   But someone also has to be willing to stay with them while they
build an audience, as Melinda Ward, a senior vice president at PRI,
has done with ``Sound and Spirit.'' That show, introduced at WGBH
in Boston in 1996, draws on a wide variety of spiritual music and
ideas. ``It took quite a while for people to know what to expect
from it,'' Ward said.
</P>
<P>
   Olsher fully appreciates the risks of his venture; still, he is
intrepid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel,'' he said, ``as if I've found the keys to the
sandbox.'' That must be something like discovering your ``right
livelihood.'' (af)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 2039EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7110 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      04-04 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS AND EXECUTIVES TAKING TECH STOCK TURMOIL IN STRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: See also STOCKS-MARKETPLACE)  
 By MATT RICHTEL and KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On their roller-coaster ride Tuesday, investors and
executives in technology companies traded on the Nasdaq market
could be expected to feel a little queasy.
</P>
<P>
   A co-worker approached Dr. Pehong Chen, chief executive of a
software company called Broadvision, based in Redwood City, Calif.,
and asked him how he was early in the morning. ``He saw me standing
at the trash can and thought I was throwing up,'' Chen said. In
fact, ``I was peeling an orange.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he said he had lost about $2.5 billion on paper in the
last two weeks, Chen seemed calm Tuesday Then again, his stake is
still worth at least a couple of billion dollars, since the stock
was one of the best performers on Nasdaq last year.
</P>
<P>
   Other executives punished by the stock market also sounded
philosophical, suggesting that they had hit a speed bump _ and
nothing more. Their comments were echoed by many smaller investors,
who continue to sit on profits after a year of tremendous gains.
Some even find the rapid decline an encouraging sign because
excesses are being quickly wrung out of the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The valuations were such that this was a balloon looking for a
pin,'' said Kent Simons, manager of the $2 billion Neuberger Berman
Focus fund. ``Things that used to take six or seven weeks are now
over in six or seven days.''
</P>
<P>
   And what a few days it has been. A rout that began in the Nasdaq
market early last week picked up steam Monday as investors braced
for the ruling that Microsoft had violated antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices plunged Tuesday morning and early afternoon in what
some traders described as panic selling by individuals and hedge
funds forced to unload shares to meet margin calls. At one point,
the Nasdaq composite index was down nearly 575 points, or 13.6
percent. That spilled over to the Dow Jones industrial average,
which fell as much as 504 points, or 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The panic lifted soon afterward as one market participant said
mutual funds began buying. The major averages then retraced much of
the lost ground.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, the Nasdaq composite and the Dow Jones
industrial average had recorded their largest point swings ever.
Though the major averages closed only moderately lower than they
had on Monday, the final numbers do not convey the volatility, nor
the pain and psychological damage inflicted on investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only positive thing you can take away from this is that
you did see almost capitulation selling,'' said Rob Cohen co-head
of block trading at Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   By the close, the Nasdaq composite was down 74.79, or 1.8
percent, to 4,148.89. The 634-point swing in Nasdaq from its peak
to its trough Tuesday was its biggest ever in a single day and was,
in fact, twice the previous record of 328 points on March 30.
</P>
<P>
   At its low point, the Nasdaq was down nearly 28 percent from its
peak March 10. By the end of the day, it was about 18 percent off
its peak. For the year, it remains ahead 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the day, the Dow slipped 57.09, or 0.5 percent, to
11,164.84. And the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index shed 11.24, or 0.8
percent, to 1,494.73.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is just wishful thinking, but stock analysts said
some of the speculative excess that has been building in technology
stocks has now been purged.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people who thought the market owed them a living now
realize that the market won't go up forever,'' said Laszlo Birinyi,
who runs his own stock market research firm in Westport, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   William Meehan, chief market analyst at Cantor Fitzgerald, said
``a lot of speculators have either seen the light or run out of
cash.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of highly speculative companies in the technology and
Internet world suffered the most, and by some counts, they have
further to fall.
</P>
<P>
   Alan F. Skrainka, chief market strategist at Edward Jones, a St.
Louis-based brokerage firm, said stock values have been totally out
of whack. ``We have a new economy, but the same old rules of
investing still apply,'' he said. If you buy companies with no
earnings, ``you're going to get burned.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is the beginning of the end of the wild wild
west style of investing.''
</P>
<P>
   Skrainka pointed to a joint study by Edward Jones and Ned Davis
Research, a securities research firm in Venice, Fla., on the stock
performance of companies whose shares reached levels equivalent to
100 times their annual earnings. Among the resulting 1,780 Nasdaq
stocks since 1972 (ending in 1995), the 5-year median return was
just over 10 percent, or 2 percent a year. And the risk was 17
times more for these stocks than for the S&AMP;P 500 and 100 times more
than for Treasury bills.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Kerschner, chief market strategist at Paine Webber,
issued a warning last week about the values of what he called the
``New, New Industrial'' stocks trading at high multiples of
earnings, if they have earnings that is. As of Tuesday morning, the
stocks on his list, including Ciena, Akamai and Juniper Networks,
were still about 40 percent overvalued, Kerschner said. By midday,
those stocks ``were down another 15 percent to 20 percent,'' he
said. ``That means they need to fall another 20 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even as he called for a sharp correction in these stocks last
week, Kerschner reiterated his generally positive outlook for
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you will see a widespread correction, but a
cleansing action in the frothier parts of the Nasdaq,'' he said.
``Overall, the market is still trading at attractive levels.''
</P>
<P>
   The economy is still strong, said Simons of Neuberger. ``The
fundamental outlook is actually a lot better than the price action
in Nasdaq would have you believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors who have ridden the technology wave in recent years
cannot be easily shaken from their seats. Howard Appel, 43, of
Merrick, N.Y., said Tuesday that he had a big loss in his 401(k)
retirement account because it was invested in technology stocks.
``If I was retiring in the next few years, I'd be in a panic,'' he
said. ``It's not fun losing $50,000 in a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I`m going to be able to buy a lot more shares at a lower
price,'' he added. ``I expect in the near future, technology and
the Nasdaq are going to come roaring back.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Hopkins, a 68-year-old retired publisher of trade
magazines who lives in Keswick, Va., said he remained on the
sidelines Tuesday. ``I was tracking it all day long,'' he said. ``I
don't think anybody could watch it and not be concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said he did not sell anything in his portfolio, which has
fat profits from recent years. ``I'm still playing on house
money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Silicon Valley, where so much wealth has been
minted in the last few years, there is plenty of ticker checking
going on in the hallways at work. And the tension is heightened at
companies whose insiders will soon get their first chance to sell
after the lock-up period _ imposed after a public offering. More
than half the initial public offerings of stock this year are now
trading under their offering price, challenging the market wisdom
that getting into a hot IPO is easy money in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Beindorff, president and chief operating officer of
PlanetrX.com, an online pharmacy based in South San Francisco, said
that the volatility is `not terribly surprising.'' Still, ``It's
scary for everybody,'' said the executive, whose stock went public
in October, peaked around $36, hung around $20, but then slid
steadily. It finished yesterday at a new low of $5.6875, down from
its $16 offering price.
</P>
<P>
   The stock has been under pressure because its lock-up period
ended on Monday, Beindorff said. In recent days retail investors
sold the stock in anticipation that company insiders would do so
when they could, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the demoralizing dips, executives at some of these
technology companies said it was premature to consider buying back
company stock or repricing options granted to employees. The
message they are trying to send to employees is that if they keep
the company on track, valuations will follow.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Slatt, 41, chairman and chief executive of WatchGuard
Technologies, an Internet security firm in Seattle whose stock has
fallen 30 points in the last several weeks to $75.50, but which
remains far above its opening price of $13 last July, sent an
e-mail designed to bolster employee morale 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these fluctuations, you'll literally drive yourself mad
looking everyday'' at your personal worth, said Slatt, whose said
his own net worth has fallen some $500 million in the last two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he and other executives of public companies say they are
keenly aware of one benchmark: how their own company's stock is
doing relative to that of direct competitors. In short, executives
say they have learned to live with wild drops they say are largely
beyond their control, but are far less comfortable when their
stocks fall in percentage terms more than that of business rivals.
</P>
<P>
   (BL)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
