u w BC-CUBAN-BOY-HNS &LR;      04-04 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSIONS GROW AS INS URGES U.S. RELATIVES TO RELINQUISH CUSTODY OF
CUBAN BOY  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Immigration officials pressed the Miami relatives
of Elian Gonzalez to relinquish custody of the boy as tensions grew
Tuesday in the Cuban exile community in anticipation of the arrival
of Juan Miguel Gonzalez to reclaim his son.
</P>
<P>
   Visas were issued Tuesday morning in Havana by the U.S. State
Department interest section to Gonzalez, Elian's stepmother and
stepbrother, his former kindergarten teacher, a pediatrician and a
cousin. The move cleared the way for Gonzalez to travel to the
United States at any time. But he has said he will not make the
trip until he receives assurances that his son will be returned.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's Miami relatives were still balking Tuesday night at
the idea of handing over the 6-year-old to his father, who has not
seen his son since November when he was taken from Cuba by his
mother in an attempt to reach the United States by boat.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration and Justice Department officials said negotiations
would resume Thursday, but they insisted they are prepared to
revoke the temporary custody status the Miami relatives now have in
order to comply with U.S. immigration laws and a federal court
decision mandating that the boy be reunited with his father.
</P>
<P>
   Elian Gonzalez has been living with relatives in Miami since he
was rescued at sea more than four months ago after the boat he was
on sank trying to cross from Cuba to Miami. His mother and 10 other
Cubans drowned, but Elian and two others managed to survive by
clinging to an inner tube.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Tuesday when Juan Miguel Gonzalez might make
the trip to reclaim his son, or whether he would fly to Washington
or Miami to await the custody transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials have said they hope the reunion will take
place in Miami. But the situation there, especially in the Little
Havana neighborhood where the boy has been living since his
relatives were given temporary custody, is volatile. Local
officials fear there could be violent protests from the Cuban exile
community if the INS attempts to take the boy.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday afternoon, Miami police stood by and watched as
dozens of protesters broke through barriers keeping them away from
the home of Lazaro Gonzalez, the great-uncle whom Elian has been
staying with. The protesters linked arms to form a chain around the
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elian is not leaving,'' they shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez said the boy's father would be welcomed in his
home if he comes to Miami. ``Don't ever doubt the Gonzalez family
has their door open for their family,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wallis, director of immigration services for the Miami
area, reiterated that the transfer of custody will take place, but
suggested that it might not happen immediately, as Juan Miguel
Gonzalez wants.
</P>
<P>
   Washington attorney Gregory Craig, who represented President
Clinton during his impeachment trial last year, was in discussions
with the INS Tuesday on how the transfer of custody will take
place. Craig is representing Juan Miguel Gonzalez as he seeks to
reunite with his son.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department rejected a plea by the boy's Miami
relatives that a panel of psychologists be appointed to examine
Elian and help determine whether he should remain in the United
States or be returned to Cuba with his father. One Justice
Department official said the boy might be examined by a doctor but
only in the context of helping to ease the transition from his
Miami relatives back to his Cuban family.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, in consultation with the
Justice Department, is still considering whether to grant visas to
Ricardo Alarcon, president of the Cuban National Assembly, and 21
other Cubans, including 12 kindergarten classmates of Elian, to
help ease his transition back into Cuban life.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the 6-year-old has apparently not been told that his
father and other family members may be coming to the United States.
Marisleysis Gonzalez, Lazaro's daughter who has been caring for the
boy, said Elian has not been told because the last time she
mentioned it to him he became upset. She continued to insist that
he does not want to go back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's case, meanwhile, continued to play center stage in the
presidential campaign with Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov.
George W. Bush issuing statements about it.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, appearing on NBC-TV's ``Today'' program, said the boy
should be allowed to return with his father to Cuba ``if the father
says on free soil that he believes that the son should go back to
Cuba with him.''
</P>
<P>
   But he called on government authorities to allow a family court
to decide custody, a position that the boy's Miami relatives have
taken in their appeal of the recent federal court ruling upholding
INS efforts to reunite the boy and his father.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the presumed Republican presidential nominee, echoed that
view. He called on Attorney General Janet Reno to make sure that
the final outcome in the case is decided by a Florida family court.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and Gore ``agree that the family court in Florida
ought to determine the fate of this young man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that's where the decision will be made,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   That view is also held by many lawmakers in Congress, where
legislation is pending that would grant permanent residency to
Elian, his father and immediate family in order to prevent the boy
from being taken back to Cuba. Gore said last week that he supports
the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   However, short of votes, sponsors of the legislation indicated
Tuesday that they may push instead for a nonbinding resolution
urging that the boy's custody be decided by an impartial panel, The
Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., said he may introduce such a measure
this week as an amendment to the fiscal 2001 budget.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls show that nearly two-thirds of Americans disagree
with the political leaders on the issue and believe that U.S.
authorities are right in pushing to reunite the father with his son
and facilitate his return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
