<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7117 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-BUSH-MICROSOFT05-COX     04-04 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MICROSOFT05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush win may be good for GatesBy Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Probable GOP presidential nominee George W. Bush
_ who has high-level backing from within Microsoft _ is trying to
steer clear of the software giant's legal woes.
</P>
<P>
   In a bland statement issued when a federal judge declared
Microsoft an illegal monopoly, Bush said little more than that he
would ``fully enforce antitrust laws.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush had a lot more to say in late February during a
campaign swing through Washington state when the Microsoft homeland
loomed as a crucial primary battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the great fear is that Microsoft will be broken up,''
he said on the eve of the Feb. 29 Washington primary that put him
on the road to securing the GOP presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, a longtime fan of free-market forces, also said he
``worried'' about the consequences, ``if this company were to be
broken apart, this engine of change, engine of growth.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Microsoft case moves toward the remedy phase,
Washington think-tank experts with opposing views on what's best
for the country agreed that a Bush win in November is what's best
for Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   At the Cato Institute, Senior Fellow Robert Levy, whose
expertise is in constitutional studies, believes Bill Gates ``may
be praying'' for another Bush White House.
</P>
<P>
   Levy, who opposes a Microsoft breakup, said Tuesday that his
comment is based more on what he is sure Al Gore would do than what
Bush might do.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is every indication (Gore) will be as activist in
antitrust as President Clinton, who is the most activist in
memory,'' Levy said. ``Bush has made some noises about being a
little more conciliatory toward market power, but he has backed off
when pressed. I'm not suggesting he necessarily will do what
Microsoft wants him to do. But it's quite clear Gore would do
nothing Microsoft would like him to do.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Brookings Institution, Vice President Robert Litan, who
believes a Microsoft breakup would be good for the country, said a
Bush win would be a victory for Microsoft though not the end of the
company's legal woes. ``I expect that Microsoft wants Bush to be
elected, but Bush by himself is not going to solve all their
problems,'' said Litan, who believes Microsoft is counting more
heavily on evolving technology that will create a far different
competitive landscape by the time the case is finally decided on
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made his feelings on the lawsuit clear in November during a
visit to Microsoft headquarters. He talked about ``unfair use of
market dominance in one sector to stifle innovation in another
sector,'' and said, ``If competition is valuable, which I think it
is, then antitrust laws have a place in embodying the values of our
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's White House campaign has gotten a solid boost from Robert
Herbold, Microsoft's chief operating official and a Bush campaign
``pioneer'' who has raised more than $100,000 for the presidential
race. Herbold was a co-host at a July 1999 Bush fund-raising event
targeted at Silicon Valley executives.
</P>
<P>
   At the Palo Alto luncheon, Herbold labeled himself ``a champion
in the Northwest part of the country as regards to fund raising''
for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, while Bush was doing his best to stay out of it,
former foe John McCain pushed his way into the case. McCain,
chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee, called for congressional
hearings on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is the role of Congress to assess two things: one,
the impact on the consumer of such action that might have to be
taken on the part of Microsoft; and two, what is the impact on this
incredible engine that's driving America's economy,'' said McCain,
who Bush defeated in the GOP presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Back when he was willing to comment more freely about the case,
Bush said he lines up ``on the side of innovation, not
litigation.'' During the Washington state campaign swing, he told
reporters: ``I am not sympathetic to lawsuits. Write that down. I
worry about the effect of lawsuits on job creation. If you are
looking for the kind of president I will be, I will be slow to
litigate.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gordon (R-Wash.), who also is Bush's state chairman,
predicted Bush would ``seek to resolve (the case) in a way that
does not break up the company.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a Bush administration would have brought the
case to begin with,'' Gordon said _ a comment later disavowed by
the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, like much of the high-tech sector, has pumped up its
political giving in recent years. Since 1997, the company and its
officers have poured almost $1.5 million in soft money into
political coffers. About 68 percent has gone to Republicans, though
the amount for the current election cycle is more evenly split.
</P>
<P>
   Through March 1 of this year, Microsoft has been the nation's
sixth largest provider of political soft money.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
