u a BC-MLK-ANNIVERSARY05-COX     04-04 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MLK-ANNIVERSARY05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Boycott by SCLC threatened if Georgia flag not changed
 &HT;    By David Pendered
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Southern Christian Leadership Conference will call
for a tourism boycott of Georgia unless the state flag is changed
next year, SCLC President Martin Luther King III said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are poised (to call a boycott) if righteousness and justice
does not happen and the flag is not changed,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge capped more than two hours of speeches
commemorating the 32nd anniversary of the assassination in Memphis
of King's father, the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Other activities followed a familiar path. The King family laid
a wreath at King's crypt. King's widow, Coretta Scott King, urged
support for a King memorial in Washington and said a conspiracy was
behind her husband's assassination.
</P>
<P>
   King III did not detail how a boycott would unfold. It could
involve a statewide boycott, like the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People program against South Carolina. Or it
could be targeted to specific events where impact would be easier
to measure.
</P>
<P>
   Results of the South Carolina boycott, started last summer, are
hard to determine. King said the state lost $50 million in tourism.
Published reports put the figure closer to $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, industry invested $6.3 billion last year and created
30,000 jobs, according to the South Carolina Department of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, supporters said King's comments will resonate
across Georgia and strengthen support for changing the flag by
removing the Confederate emblem within it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It carries a great deal of moral authority amongst the
mainstream of Georgia for Martin Luther King III to say, on the
32nd anniversary of his father's death, that the flag should be
changed,'' said Sen. Vincent Fort (D-Atlanta), a history professor
at Morris Brown College in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   King also may find support from unexpected corporate allies,
said Daniel Levitas, executive director of the Georgia Rural Urban
Summit, which promotes social justice. He noted that both Coca-Cola
and Lockheed Martin have been accused of racial discrimination
against black employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to improve their image in the African-American
community, and that means the possibility of some corporate allies
on the flag issue,'' Levitas said.
</P>
<P>
   There is a significant difference between King III's call to
remove the Confederate emblem from the Georgia flag and past
efforts to change the flag. This campaign will be waged by students
in high schools and colleges, a group that has little political
clout to lose in the battle. The last effort was led by then-Gov.
Zell Miller, who was defeated by the 1993 state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP's regional coordinator of college students, Mark Bell,
said students will arrange educational sessions across Georgia this
summer to drum up interest among youth to change the flag. Other
organizers said students will call for the flag to come down.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Centennial High School, in Roswell, the young people
declared that this flag will be removed,'' said Brenda Davenport,
head of student affairs for the SCLC. ``The governor will have it
on his agenda because students will say it will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes told a national television audience in
February that changing the flag was not a priority for him or
African-American lawmakers in the legislative session that ended
last month. Barnes' administration officials could not be reached
for comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
