<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7131 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-UGA-FRATS05-COX     04-04 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGA-FRATS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Soul-searching on University of Georgia's fraternity row
 &HT;    By James Salzer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ The death of a University of Georgia fraternity
member last week comes at a time in which members of the Greek
system at UGA say they already feel they are under a microscope.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely doesn't help,'' said Matt Sawhill, 21, a senior
from Rome, Ga., and president of the Kappa Sigma fraternity. ``We
all understand that we have to hold ourselves up to a higher
standard.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, Sawhill's Kappa Sigma brothers were on the roof of
their house, draping black cloth over the fraternity's letters to
pay respect to Ben Folsom Grantham III, a member of the Alpha Tau
Omega fraternity a few doors down.
</P>
<P>
   Grantham may have been handcuffed and blindfolded when he died
last week in a car crash. Wynn Smiley, executive director of the
Indianapolis-based national ATO organization described the incident
as a ``road trip that got out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past five years, UGA officials said 10 fraternities and
sororities have been disciplined for hazing, alcohol or curfew
abuses. Officials say there are about 40 fraternities and
sororities on campus, and 17 percent of UGA's students are members.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia law punishes hazing _ defined as putting a person
through physical punishments and humiliation _ by as much as a year
in jail and a $5,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have taken a zero tolerance on hazing,'' said Brad
Bohannon, 20, a junior from Augusta and member of the Lambda Chi
Alpha fraternity. ``It doesn't occur here.''
</P>
<P>
   Derick Corbett, 23, a senior from Canton and member of the
fraternity, added, ``In this house, the attitude has changed
dramatically. We realize hazing is less educational and more about
paying your dues. You're never going to end it completely. You have
the old boys with the old rules.''
</P>
<P>
   While he still hears about hazing on campus, Corbett said those
stories rarely involve ``physical brutality.''
</P>
<P>
   The most highly publicized hazing case in recent years at UGA
likely was in 1996, when three Phi Beta Sigma fraternity members
pled guilty to battery and hazing charges after the paddling of
then-20-year-old Rod Perrymond, a University of Georgia Bulldogs
football player in an off-campus apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bracewell, former director of student judicial programs at
UGA, said, ``There has been a definite trend, and it's been away
from life-threatening, dangerous activity'' at fraternities and
sororities.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said pledges remain a sort of second-class citizen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem remains, as long as you're thinking that way, and
it's OK to make them drive you to class, then it becomes OK to make
them clean your apartment, then it becomes OK to ... you're on a
slippery slope,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Bracewell said for years, what was going on in local
fraternities wasn't of great concern to national organizations and
universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a part of American society for a long time. What
happened is people started getting maimed and killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Campuses started cracking down, broadening the definition of
hazing to the point, he said, that they ``outlawed silliness.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Williamson, assistant chief of UGA's police, said he
doesn't see as many big parties at fraternities these days. ``It's
easier downtown to rent out a facility and have it all provided,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason may be policies that force fraternities to
have security, police underage drinking and keep their events
contained on their premises.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Mullendore, UGA's vice president for student affairs,
said the school has year-round education programs for fraternity
members and pledges on hazing and other issues. The school also has
a hazing hotline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe my staff is doing everything that is humanly
possible (to educate students),'' he said. ``Sometimes, out of
tragedy, education occurs. There is not a student who pledges at a
fraternity or sorority that does not know what the policy on hazing
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Other schools in Georgia and across the country are tackling
similar issues.
</P>
<P>
   Emory University decided a few years ago to mandate fraternity
houses have full-time house directors to keep a closer eye on
what's going on. Members of fraternities and sororities also must
undergo anti-hazing orientations and sign a pledge not to haze. The
house directors are employees of the school, not the fraternities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worked out wonderfully,'' said Bridget Guernsey Riordan
of Emory's Campus Life office, who added that few schools mandate
house directors. She said there hasn't been a reported hazing
incident on the campus in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech, meanwhile, has been aggressive in attacking
underage and binge drinking on campus. The school is considering
changing its policies on when to notify parents that their underage
children have been caught drinking or using illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Bracewell said Greek chapters may have more to worry about than
college clamp-downs when accidents occur, like the one involving
Grantham. ``The resulting lawsuit is probably more important to
whether the organization continues to exist,'' he said. ``Somebody
might get sued over this. ``
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Gita M. Smith
contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
