<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7135 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-GARLAND-WORLD-MUSIC-B     04-04 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARLAND-WORLD-MUSIC-BOOK-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AROUND THE WORLD OF MUSIC  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ethnomusicologists are rarely accused of getting popular music
right. More often, they're engaged in pursuits that seem
excessively narrow and clinical _ pitch variance among Central
African xylophones or Connecticut River Valley fife-and-drum
history.
</P>
<P>
   Individual projects of ethnomusicology are often hard to read
and feel abstracted from what most of us consider the important
stuff: the music that we have emotional attachments to, the music
that our commercial society points us toward.
</P>
<P>
   But collect the best work of a few hundred musicologists, make
their language palatable to a general readership and, lo, the
notion that Wagner and Charlie Parker and the Beatles really
changed life as we know it holds less water. You may move beyond a
record-based understanding of music; you will see how music-making
has its basis in society and religion and commerce and the
traveling of different peoples from place to place.
</P>
<P>
   The Garland World Music Encyclopedia, a projected 10-volume
series of telephone-book-size reference works from Routledge that
started appearing in 1998, brings together this confluence of
research. Six volumes have been published; the two volumes just
released, on Europe and South Asia, are up to the level set by
their predecessors, on Africa, Southeast Asia, Australia and the
Pacific Islands and South America, Mexico, Central America and the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Don't spend too much time fussing here about the loaded term
``world music.'' In this case it is not a naive stand-in for
``music that North Americans consider foreign''; it literally means
music made all over the world, including here.
</P>
<P>
   Approaching such a large canvas _ as well as music's importance
in dance, literature and religion _ messes profoundly with our
built-in cultural orientation. European art music, in the Garland
books, is represented by two intelligently written chapters in the
Europe volume: one a brief history running from Gregorian chant to
Alfred Schnittke, the other a historiographical chapter on how
classical music is understood in the West and an analysis of
Western concert music as ritual.
</P>
<P>
   The Garland books are not consumer guides, and they militate
against the notion that the music of a nation can be easily reduced
to a few great men making a single national music.
</P>
<P>
   For example, American music. In the forthcoming volume on the
United States and Canada, of which I have seen only a table of
contents (the book will be published in November), American music
seems to mean simply whatever has been played by people who live
here, and the circumstances of business and culture under which it
has been made.
</P>
<P>
   If you think this volume might settle heavily on blues, jazz,
country, gospel and Cajun _ our best-known heritage music _ think
again. Among the 120 chapters are ``Railways as Music Patrons,''
``Japanese Music'' (including karaoke in the United States),
``Campaign Music in the United States,'' ``Heavy Metal and Male
Desire,''and ``Prairies: A Musical Overview,'' as well as, of
course, ``Blues'' (by Neil Rosenberg, who has written a good book
on bluegrass), ``Jazz'' (by the scholar Ingrid Monson) and
``Country and Western'' (by Charles K. Wolfe, a pre-eminent
historian of early country music).
</P>
<P>
   The Garland series was first planned in 1988, when there was
almost nothing available that tried to be comprehensive. Its
editors decided to put the emphasis on place above all, so that
these encyclopedias aren't alphabetical; they're done region by
region. You can't just look up King Sunny Ade under A and be done
with it; you have to find him in the greater weave of West African
culture. Music is a consequence of all history, not just of music
critics' 10-best lists.
</P>
<P>
   Really, you may not know how important music is until you see
how these books can be used almost as general sources of knowledge
about a country. You can consult them when you're about to travel
to any place that has its own regional culture; when you see the
``Buena Vista Social Club'' and want to know the history of son;
when you want to know what the polka came from or why Yoruban
culture is so important or how Western scholars struggled to reckon
with African music's idiosyncrasies of time, harmony and timbre.
</P>
<P>
   All the essays were commissioned especially for these books; in
some cases, as in Peter Manuel's ``Pop Music and Audio-Cassette
Technology in South Asia,'' the information seems a useful
compression of books already written and published. Each volume
comes with a CD of music drawn mostly from the writers' own field
recordings.
</P>
<P>
   My one frustration with these books is that they have an uneven
standard for treating music of the last 50 years; even where you
wish they would reflect Western critical thought a little more,
they tend not to. If you look for information on Jamaican dub music
or the new Cuban timba style, you get dissertations on instrumental
ensembles instead, with a generalized history that weakly trails
off in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the Afro-Brazilian chapter is better than you
would expect, taking seriously the newer pop styles that music
critics tend to wave off: samba-reggae, axe and rap.
</P>
<P>
   At $195 each, these books aren't objects one buys lightly.
(Abridged paperback versions are already under way.) But as
regional culture seems to become both more precious and more
visible _ because of the homogenizing global effect of MTV and an
increasingly sophisticated market for ``world music'' _ these books
could become as important to serious music enthusiasts as the
Oxford English Dictionary is to serious readers. (af)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
