<HEADER>
A7140 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-COKE-INVEST-(TRIMS)-N     04-04 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-INVEST-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COKE KEEPS GROWTH TARGET THE SAME AS IN PAST YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a bold display of the optimism that has
characterized its growth predictions in the past, Coca-Cola Co.
told investors Tuesday that it expected its sales volume to
increase 7 percent to 8 percent a year over the long term and that
it planned to increase earnings by 15 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the company disclosed preliminary results for
the first quarter, which show lower-than-expected growth of 1.5
percent worldwide, with many regions flat or down, and said it
would take a $400 million charge against earnings for poorly
performing plants and other assets in India.
</P>
<P>
   Coke made the announcements at a long-awaited meeting in New
York with analysts and money managers. It was the first such
gathering since late January, when Coke's management called
analysts together to discuss the sweeping changes set for the
company that included layoffs of 6,000 employees, decentralizing of
the business from Atlanta to the local offices around the world,
and write-downs of $1.6 billion for bad investments and the costs
of the reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts listened politely Tuesday while Coke's chairman and
chief executive, Douglas N. Daft, and other senior executives
described the marketing, new-product development and other plans
the company has to generate volume growth, which is expected to be
5 percent to 6 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   In questions to Coke management and in interviews afterward,
however, most analysts seemed less than convinced that the company
would be able to hit its targets. Missing the target has plagued
Coke for the last eight quarters and has been a principal reason
for the 41 percent drop in the company's share price over the last
20 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``That 7 to 8 percent volume growth, compounded annually for 5
to 10 years, is a little aggressive,'' said Andrew Conway, a
beverage stocks analyst for Morgan Stanley, who downgraded Coke in
December, when its former chairman and chief executive, M. Douglas
Ivester, said he would step down. ``That rate is doable in any one
year, but can they do it for 10 years straight?''
</P>
<P>
   Daft said several times that the rate was realistic. ``We
believe in it, it's achievable, and we've got the programs to do
it,'' he said in response to a question from Jennifer Solomon, an
analyst for Salomon Smith Barney, who asked why he was sticking
with the same growth target that Coke has had for years. ``We had
to be honest with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the audience described the meeting as unexpectedly flat,
apart from the growth predictions. With Coke's share price closing
at $52.375 Tuesday, up $3.0625, after falling into the low $40s in
recent weeks, the meeting had been seen by some analysts as Coke's
big chance to persuade Wall Street that the worst was behind it.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some presentations dwelled for close to an hour on topics
already well known to analysts and investors, like pricing patterns
in supermarkets and marketing efforts overseas. One long video
discussed Coke's investment over several years in building schools
in rural China and was followed by a satellite feed from Hong Kong,
where it was 4 a.m. Another showed clips from Coke-sponsored beach
parties in Chile.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The charge to earnings related to investments in India, where
Coke has spent heavily to reorganize the bottling business, will
result in a decrease of about 11 cents a share in first-quarter
earnings, said Emanuel Goldman, an analyst for Merrill Lynch.
Coke's chief financial officer, Gary P. Fayard, said the layoffs
would total about 5,200 people, rather than the 6,000 originally
predicted, at a cost of $725 million, less than the $800 million
forecast in January.
</P>
<P>
   Annual savings from the job reductions would be about $200
million this year, Fayard added. About 10 cents will be shaved from
first-quarter earnings to cover most of the costs of the job cuts,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BL)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
