u a BC-UGA-WRECK05-COX     04-04 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGA-WRECK05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    University of Georgia revokes fraternity's rights as probe into
fatal wreck continues
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ University of Georgia officials suspended a
fraternity Tuesday as authorities continue to investigate the death
of one of its members in a one-car crash on a quiet country road.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Folsom Grantham III, 20, of St. Simons Island died
Thursday after the crash in nearby Watkinsville. Oconee County
Sheriff Scott Berry said that at the time of the accident, Grantham
was handcuffed and blindfolded as he rode in the cargo hold of the
Infiniti sports utility vehicle driven by a fraternity pledge.
</P>
<P>
   The Sheriff's Department and UGA officials are investigating
whether his death was the result of hazing by Alpha Tau Omega.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel at this point that we need to send a very serious
message to the organization,'' said Richard Mullendore, UGA's vice
president for student affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Under UGA's policy governing organizations, the interim
suspension is imposed ``when the alleged action of the organization
is of such an egregious nature as to require an immediate
response.'' The fraternity may not hold any social or recruitment
activities.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn Smiley, the fraternity's executive director, agreed with
the suspension and said the national organization has issued its
own suspension of UGA's chapter as the investigation continues.
</P>
<P>
   But Smiley and Berry disagree on several facts surrounding the
accident:
</P>
<P>
   _ Whether Grantham was handcuffed and blindfolded.
</P>
<P>
   _ Whether there were two or three cars carrying fraternity
brothers in a caravan.
</P>
<P>
   _ Whether fraternity members left the scene of the accident
before help arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also want to know whether Grantham was forced into
the vehicle _ or a willing participant.
</P>
<P>
   Smiley said a group of ATO pledges took Grantham from his
apartment near the UGA campus Thursday night and loaded him into
the back of an Infiniti SUV driven by fraternity pledge Walter
David Penn Jr., 20, of Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   Smiley said it started as a harmless fraternity prank _ a ``road
trip.'' The fraternity tradition involves takingsomeone off-campus,
leaving him and letting him find his way back.
</P>
<P>
   ``My understanding at this point is that Ben knew about it, he
was prepared for it and he was a willing participant,'' Smiley
said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he has not seen any evidence that Grantham was
handcuffed.
</P>
<P>
   The prank took a tragic turn south of Watkinsville. The SUV
flipped and hit a tree. Three people, including Grantham, were
thrown from the vehicle. Investigators say none of the five
passengers wore seat belts.
</P>
<P>
   Penn, who underwent surgery Monday for two broken legs, remains
in fair condition at an Athens hospital. Rob Bailey, 18, of Dalton
was in good condition Tuesday. Authorities have not identified the
two other occupants of the car. Officials said they were not
injured.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say Grantham probably died moments after the 11:37
p.m. crash. ``The wounds that he received from the crash were
mortal wounds,'' Oconee County coroner John Simpson said. Abrasions
around Grantham's wrists indicated he had been wearing handcuffs or
some kind of restraints when he died, Simpson added.
</P>
<P>
   Berry said officers found handcuffs at the scene of the accident
and that they may have been taken off Grantham after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson said the handcuffs didn't make any difference in
Grantham's chances for survival, ``but not wearing a seat belt and
being in the back of the vehicle didn't help his situation any.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry said information indicates that there was a three-vehicle
caravan of ATO members. Berry also said that when authorities
arrived at the wreck, the other two vehicles were gone.
</P>
<P>
   Smiley said only one other vehicle with ATO members was in the
caravan. The other vehicle took Penn to the hospital because the
members knew Grantham and Bailey needed medical assistance, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the (third) car just happened on the scene,'' Smiley
said. ``Maybe it was high school kids or something,''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution correspondent Andrew DeMillo
contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
