<HEADER>
A7144 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-1STLD-     04-04 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIGNATION OF JAPAN'S CABINET PAVES WAY FOR NEW PRIME MINISTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Subs to reorganize, recast top grafs, raise Watanabe's quote
to 4th graf.) 
(See also JAPAN-OBUCHI-REACT) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japan's Cabinet resigned Tuesday, setting the stage for
a rapid succession after Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi fell into a
coma on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Formalized at a brief meeting Tuesday evening, the cabinet's
resignation is expected to be followed by the nomination of the
Liberal Democratic Party's candidate to take over the government.
That nomination may come as early as Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The choice is already widely reported be the party's
second-ranking official, Yoshiro Mori. Once he was nominated,
Parliament would vote almost immediately to ratify him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question about the choice,'' said Kozo Watanabe,
vice speaker of Parliament's lower house. ``The central commission
of the LDP will announce Mr. Mori's selection, and their junior
coalition partners will support it. In that event, we will have a
new prime minister before Parliament tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   With tears streaking down his cheeks, the caretaker prime
minister, Mikio Aoki, said Tuesday afternoon that the dissolution
of the government was made ``based on the judgment of the doctors
and from the viewpoint that we should not allow even one moment's
political vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   The news came after persistent reports throughout the day that
Obuchi's condition was steadily worsening and that the prime
minister was brain dead. Aoki denied that, calling himself ``very
upset'' at news organizations for passing on rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians close to the transition process and several Japanese
political analysts said Tuesday that the governing party had used
the extraordinary 22-hour news blackout surrounding Obuchi's
hospitalization early Sunday, and the carefully stage-managed
process since, to engineer the selection of Mori as its unopposed
candidate for the succession.
</P>
<P>
   The party has a long history of running things; it has governed
the country alone or in coalitions for all but two and a half years
since 1955.
</P>
<P>
   The secretive handling of the news of Obuchi's hospitalization
and the back-room machinations drew renewed criticisms Tuesday from
several quarters, with the view that the episode revealed a side of
Japan that was neither altogether modern nor democratic.
</P>
<P>
   Mori, who is 62 and has been the party's secretary-general, won
support by demonstrating a strong loyalty to Obuchi. Even more
useful to him were his close ties to the party's major coalition
partner, the Buddhist-backed New Komeito.
</P>
<P>
   Mori's ratification by the parliament, or Diet, is already
considered a foregone conclusion, since the coalition, led by the
Liberal Democratic Party, has a large majority.
</P>
<P>
   Many commentators said Tuesday, however, that by choosing Mori _
a burly, raspy voiced politician not especially known for his
personal popularity or campaigning skills _ the party was taking a
huge risk in national elections that are expected to be held before
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The choice spoke volumes, they said, about some unusual
imperatives in Japanese politics _ loyalty to partners and allies
in a crunch _ rather than to the party's immediate political needs
and even potentially to its survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not that the LDP lacks people who could enjoy
popularity,'' said Masumi Ishikawa, a professor of politics at
Niigata University of International and Information Studies.
``There is Mr. Kono and Mr. Kato, both of whom would probably be
more popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Yohei Kono, the foreign minister, and Koichi Kato, a former
chief Cabinet secretary, were both believed to aspire to the prime
minister's job.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the LDP is basing its decision on who has a good
relationship with Komeito,'' Ishikawa, a former senior political
correspondent of the daily Asahi Shimbun, said. ``They are not
thinking of the reaction of the people of Japan, and this behavior
is very strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, many analysts were already describing the Liberal
Democratic Party's choice of Mori on the basis of the New Komeito
Party's comfort as a recipe for electoral difficulties, because the
coalition between the two parties has been deeply unpopular since
it was formed last October. Opinion polls have consistently shown
that Japanese voters disapprove of having a party with religious
affiliations in the government.
</P>
<P>
   The new government will have to dissipate growing criticism of
the secretive, seemingly antiquated mechanics of a succession in
which Aoki was allowed to become caretaker merely on the basis of
what he described as a private conversation with Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
   Further contributing to the image of a process of party barons
meeting in smoke-filled rooms to keep the public in the dark was
the way in which Mori was selected.
</P>
<P>
   Some political insiders spoke Tuesday with almost reverential
approval of the off-stage consultations that produced Mori as
Obuchi's successor, describing it as a confirmation of the
efficiency of Japan's political system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Aoki's reaction to Obuchi's collapse was very tactful,''
said Watanabe, the deputy speaker. ``If he had waited a week or 10
days after Mr. Obuchi collapsed, somebody else could have raised
their hand as a candidate, and there could be some chaos. But by
the time Mr. Aoki announced the condition of Mr. Obuchi, it was
already virtually decided who would take over.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, for independent politicians and commentators,
and indeed much of the public, the process provided a field day of
introspection about how, 55 years after World War II, Japan has
remained a democracy largely in name rather than in spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although Japanese politicians keep saying `minshushugi' there
is no spirit of democracy in this country,'' said Kaoru Okano, a
political commentator who is a former president of Meiji University
in Tokyo, using the Japanese word for democracy. ``There are
statesman and politicians in the west. In Japan there is a third
category, wheeler-dealer.''
</P>
<P>
   Okano said that the current crisis had revealed Japan to be
dominated by this latter category.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Other commentators said the failure of the country's leaders to
operate in a more open manner and include the people in their
decision making had contributed to widespread public distrust of
politicians and disillusionment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process of choosing a successor has revealed itself as not
very democratic, and is indeed very closed,'' said Shusei Tanaka, a
political scientist at Fukuyama University in Hiroshima. ``I have
the feeling that whoever comes out of this coalition will probably
be the same, and the people of Japan feel much the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling is that even if the prime minister changes, the
policies won't. We are in need of dramatic reforms of Japanese
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   (js-nk)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
