u w BC-HEALTHCARE-SPENDING-4     04-04 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHCARE-SPENDING-465&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSULTANTS AND STATES SIPHON MILLIONS IN MEDICAID FOR YOUNG, SAYS
GAO 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hundreds of millions of dollars in Medicaid money
designated for disabled poor children has been siphoned off by
consulting firms and state governments, federal investigators said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In a new report on Medicaid in schools, the General Accounting
Office, an investigative arm of Congress, described many ``improper
payments,'' accused schools of overstating their Medicaid costs and
said the problems had been allowed to fester because of weak
supervision by federal Medicaid officials.
</P>
<P>
   School districts often pay contingency fees to private firms to
help them prepare and submit Medicaid claims, then bill Medicaid
for these fees, in violation of federal rules, the investigators
said. The consultants typically charge fees equal to 10 percent or
15 percent of any federal Medicaid money they get for schools, but
some firms charge 20 percent or 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The contingency fees tend to ``encourage questionable claims,''
the accounting office said. Schools and consulting firms operate in
``an environment of opportunism,'' filing ``improper Medicaid
claims for administrative activities'' without providing
appropriate services to needy children, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy M. Westmoreland, the top federal Medicaid official, said
he generally agreed with the findings. ``The GAO found problems and
made recommendations,'' he said. ``We concur. We'll take steps to
make sure Medicaid money is used only for children and services
covered by Medicaid.''
</P>
<P>
   But state health officials took issue with the criticism. They
said the Clinton administration had never given them clear guidance
about how federal Medicaid money could be used in schools.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said Tuesday that they were trying to
establish the exact amount of the improper payments and might try
to recover some of the money.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation was requested more than a year ago by Sens.
William Roth, R-Del., who is chairman of the Finance Committee, and
Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York, the senior Democrat on the
panel. The committee plans to hold a hearing on the issue
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid provides health insurance coverage to 41 million
people, including 13 million school-age children. States have
increasingly used the schools as a way to deliver health care to
children, especially those with physical and mental disabilities,
mental retardation, autism and similar problems. Many schools also
identify children eligible for Medicaid and help them enroll.
</P>
<P>
   Schools in 47 states received $2.3 billion in Medicaid payments
for school-based health services last year. The average claim for
each child on Medicaid ranged from a high of $818 in Maryland to
less than $1 in Mississippi. Claims averaged $703 for a child in
New York, $248 in New Jersey and $174 in Connecticut.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In its report, the GAO's office of special investigations made
these points:
</P>
<P>
   _ Schools, states and consulting firms use ``creative billing
practices'' to maximize the money they get from the federal
government for school health services, but states often keep much
of the money. Schools in some states, like New Jersey, receive as
little as $7.50 in federal Medicaid reimbursements for every $100
they spend on health care for needy children.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some schools improperly claimed Medicaid money for health care
and medical evaluations provided to children who were not eligible.
</P>
<P>
   _ In some states, schools got more than $600 a month from
Medicaid simply because an eligible child attended school for one
day a month, regardless of whether the child received any health
care services.
</P>
<P>
   _ Schools charged Medicaid for school bus transportation never
provided to children, ``resulting in improper Medicaid
reimbursements.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Group therapy sessions were billed as individual therapy
sessions,'' and as a result schools received higher Medicaid
payments than they should have.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said the consulting companies included Maximus
and Deloitte &AMP; Touche.
</P>
<P>
   Rachael A. Rowland, a spokeswoman for Maximus, based in McLean,
Va., said such companies played a legitimate role. ``Small and poor
school districts would not be able to obtain Medicaid funds and
provide services to the disabled if they did not have consulting
firms to help them'' file claims, she said. But, she added, ``some
firms other than Maximus do charge excessive fees.''
</P>
<P>
   Deloitte &AMP; Touche did not return calls requesting comment.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO said that schools in Michigan had received tens of
millions of dollars from the federal government for staff training
and other activities supposedly related to Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   But, it said, the activities had no connection to Medicaid, the
program was not mentioned in training sessions and ``the staff did
not know what Medicaid covers, where or how to apply for Medicaid
or who might qualify for coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Geralyn A. Lasher, a spokeswoman for the Michigan Department of
Community Health, defended the state's practices. ``We are
providing health care to children who need it,'' Lasher said. ``For
four or five years, we have been asking the federal Health Care
Financing Administration for guidance on school-based health
services. We got no answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth said, ``I find it appalling that anyone would take
advantage of a system designed to serve children who are
predominantly poor and disabled.'' Senator Moynihan said: ``The GAO
is obviously right. Medicaid needs to be policed and administered
to make sure the money is used for medical care for children, not
to offset other costs.''
</P>
<P>
   The report said schools often ended up with a small part of what
Medicaid paid for the services they provided. For example, it said,
when a New Jersey school files a claim for $100, the federal
government pays half of that amount, or $50. But, it said, the
state keeps $42.50 of the federal payment, leaving $7.50 for the
school district.
</P>
<P>
   (BL)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
