u f BC-COKE05-COX     04-04 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Analysts call Coca-Cola's 15% profit growth estimate too high
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Innovation. Innovation. Innovation.
</P>
<P>
   For five hours Tuesday, Coca-Cola Co. executives hammered on
that theme as they outlined the company's strategic plans to about
250 beverage analysts and institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the first or last time Coca-Cola has reinvented
itself,'' Chairman Doug Daft said at a Wall Street hotel only a
stone's throw from the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Daft told analysts that the ``new'' Coca-Cola will be creative
and flexible enough to produce long-term profit growth of about 15
percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   While that number is lower than the previous company target of
15 percent to 20 percent earnings-per-share growth, several
analysts think it's too high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Year in and year out, it's an ambitious strategy,'' said
Andrew Conway of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. A more realistic goal,
Conway said, is 12 percent to 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs analyst Marc Cohen thinks the number should be 13
percent, while Bill Pecoriello of Sanford Bernstein estimates it at
13 percent to 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Every percentage point is important because the company's stock
price is largely dependent on whether it hits its targets.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's stock posted a strong gain Tuesday despite a rocky
trading session. The stock closed at $51.75, up $2.43 3/4. It was
higher in after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   Daft announced that the company was comfortable keeping its
target for growth in case sales _ a key indicator _ at 7 percent to
8 percent a year. Several analysts also thought that was too high,
by a percentage point or two.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the company announced that case sales for the first
quarter rose by only 3 percent. For the year, officials said, case
sales should rise by 5 percent to 6 percent, before returning to
target levels as economies continue to rebound around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Missing targets in recent years is one of the reasons the
company's stock has fallen so much. It's also one of the reasons
why Daft and the company's other top executives spent so much time
and energy talking about the innovation that will pump sales in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   From top to bottom, they said, the company's major
reorganization will make it far less bureaucratic and much more
able to meet local beverage needs in the 200 markets it serves. The
company also promised to react much more quickly to changes in
those markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the concentration on innovation is to say that we can
come up with the products, packages and distribution ideas to meet
our long-term targets,'' said Manny Goldman, an analyst with
Merrill Lynch. ``I think meeting those targets are a challenge. But
I think they have a good chance. It will get back to how innovative
they can be.''
</P>
<P>
   A variety of Coca-Cola execs from throughout the world paraded
in front of the podium to explain their strategies. Those included
creating new local drinks for different markets, relying more on
noncarbonated drinks to meet more consumer needs, employing
e-commerce marketing strategies to take advantage of the Internet
and teaming with retailers to drive sales with joint marketing
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we have increased your conviction that we can do
it,'' President Jack Stahl told the analysts.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, of course, time will tell.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments:
</P>
<P>
   _ Coca-Cola said it will be taking a charge of $400 million to
write down its bottling assets in India because of excess capacity
and a substantial tax increase there.
</P>
<P>
   _ Daft told reporters he could not comment on the settlement
negotiations regarding a racial discrimination lawsuit filed by
former and current African-American employees. He said he did not
agree with the plaintiffs' claims that the company has
systematically discriminated against African-Amercians in pay,
promotions and performance evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that diversity is one of his top priorities and
that the company is committed to making changes that improve the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
