<SLUG> BC-CORPORATE-FILMS-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CORPORATION AS FANTASY VILLAIN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 9) 
</HEADLINE>
   Phillip Lopate's most recent book is ``Totally Tenderly
Tragically,'' a collection of film essays.  
 By PHILLIP LOPATE c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Midway through ``Erin Brockovich,'' I began to peel off from
that hugely likable movie and consider its curious new genre, whose
template has already hardened. Once again, as in ``The Rainmaker''
and ``A Civil Action,'' a David law firm was suing a Goliath
corporation on behalf of the company's victims.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the corporation was responding with a conspiracy of
silence and intimidation. And once again I had that uneasy feeling
that something was missing: a credible, complex opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Erin, the white-trash paralegal, was silencing with her earthy
eloquence the top legal brains of Pacific Gas and Electric, as well
as her snooty Ivy League superiors. Like a Capra hero facing down
Washington bigwigs, she was shaming them all with populist lectures
on decency.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it mattered somewhat that Erin was played by Julia
Roberts, and most audiences were willing to suspend disbelief to
see their adorable, cleavage-baring audience-surrogate making
mincemeat of the boys and girls in suits. It was wish-fulfillment
time. Never mind that Erin Brockovich was based on a true story of
a lawsuit that PG&AMP;E settled for a record $333 million; it could not
have been this easy in real life.
</P>
<P>
   But even when the results are less triumphant, as in ``The
Rainmaker,'' Francis Ford Coppola's elegant 1997 rendition of the
John Grisham novel, or ``A Civil Action'' (1998), the lugubrious
screen version of Jonathan Harr's fine book, this is a strangely
compromised genre. Suing the big bad corporation for its misdeeds,
you might say, is the old Kurosawa revenge plot with a non-violent
twist: instead of laying waste to the castle for ruining the
villagers, the hero invades it in order to bring them back an
indemnification check.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the dramatic problem is that it is so hard to put human
features on the narrative's villain, the corporation. Since
corporate power has become so diffuse, it's not easy to locate a
center of authority. Though millions of Americans work for
corporations, it's curious how reluctant movies are to show the
corporate world from inside. The last time Hollywood seriously
tackled corporate life was in the 1950s and '60s, when movies such
as ``The Man in the Gray Flannel Suit,'' ``Executive Suite,''
``Patterns,'' ``The Apartment'' and ``How to Succeed in Business
Without Really Trying'' dealt with the conforming stresses the
individual employee faced in making his way up the corporate
ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, except for the occasional Michael J. Fox or Michael
Douglas vehicle, the emphasis has shifted to the investigative
outsider trying to bring down the blood-stained corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Why are corporations made the villains now? They began to be
demonized in the '60s as part of the attack on the
military-industrial complex. And now, with the Cold War over and
big government under siege, big business would seem to be the only
power in town. Yet there is also no socialist alternative being put
forth in the political discussion; a booming stock market beckons
even the smallest investor.
</P>
<P>
   And movies are made by entertainment conglomerates, so a
Hollywood attack on corporatism must pull its punches. (On the
other hand, one often has the sense that filmmakers, seeing
themselves as mavericks, smuggle into these projects their
resentment against the studio bean counters who oversee them.) How
much can we Americans bear to see corporations treated as villains?
</P>
<P>
   The movies in question show a deep ambivalence on this score.
Backing off from a nuanced presentation of corporate life, the
filmmakers opt for melodramatic caricature. Thus, even in ``The
Insider,'' probably the most subtle of the recent anticorporate
films, the Big Tobacco executive played by Michael Gambon is shown
stroking a tabby cat, a sure sign of his diabolical nature.
</P>
<P>
   The closest we come to a corporate face in ``A Civil Action'' is
the Grace executive played by Sydney Pollack, who (perhaps
preparing for his debauchee role in ``Eyes Wide Shut'') demands
that the hero put his feet up on a glass coffee table _ that's the
extent of his characterization.
</P>
<P>
   The mistake of ``A Civil Action,'' besides miscasting John
Travolta as a worldly lawyer, was building the film around a
successful middle-class character who gets idealism and suffers
financially as a result. A rule of the genre is that the hero who
takes on the corporation must do so from the outside: from a tiny,
marginal law firm, preferably as a working-class paralegal such as
Erin Brockovich (the Danny DeVito character in ``The Rainmaker''
never got his law degree, either).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The first, often most satisfying, act of these pictures follows
the straitened protagonists, chasing jobs and cockroaches,
scrambling around a hardscrabble trailer- camp milieu, until they
discover the Big Wrong, a trail of ordinary folk victimized by
corporate misconduct. The investigators confront the corporation
with their suspicions: a camera panning up the glass-curtained
tower leads to the scene with the Suits, a phalanx of well-dressed
lawyers facing off against the good guys in a conference room.
</P>
<P>
   Though we are meant to get a chill from the steel and glass,
there is invariably something enticing about this corporate decor,
especially after all the broken-down bungalows and motel rooms we
have been treated to. Here is the first ambivalence: the audience
has been ushered into the dragon's den, only to find nothing very
sinister and much that is glossy-magazine appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but the inability to differentiate the wall of
Suits, who speak as one, means that they come off as comically
weak, afraid to make decisions or negotiate. Ultimately, the
consensus nature of corporate power is distorted as bureaucratic
cowardice; the CEO, if he appears at all, is only another empty
suit. The fact that corporations may have their own intelligent,
articulate rationales for what they do, however self-serving, is
rarely made clear.
</P>
<P>
   The genre alternates between the working-class and corporate
worlds: the protagonists try to keep the victims united under one
legal strategy (scenes of worsening illness and death stiffen the
team's resolve), then return to the corporate fortress for more
jousting with the Suits.
</P>
<P>
   There is a bloated, protracted quality to these films; they tend
to sag in the middle, and go on for half an hour too long. The
lassitude that invades their second acts comes partly from the loss
of confrontational edge. As the Enemy recedes from definition,
turns increasingly vaporous, the vacuum on one side of the conflict
can only be balanced by more dogged ``procedure'' on the other.
</P>
<P>
   Procedure is also a way of demonstrating the heroes' work ethic.
It pays off in the ``leak'' or the location of the missing document
at the end of Act Two, which cracks the case.
</P>
<P>
   Anticorporate films are only seemingly subversive. In fact, they
enshrine the capitalist principles of individualism and hard work.
The old American ethos declared that if you worked hard you might
become a millionaire; the new one says, if you pound the pavements
and scan the computer records long enough, you might nail a
millionaire. And maybe become one in the process, as shown by the
having-your-cake-and-eating-it ending of ``Erin Brockovich.''
</P>
<P>
   She gets a $2 million dollar bonus and continues to ring
doorbells to help the little people. Meanwhile her boss (played by
Albert Finney) moves his law firm from its modest digs to a sleek
tower. If you can beat them, join them. There is no perceptible
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   While Hollywood seems unable to portray corporations
realistically, it uses the more manageably compact law firm as a
surrogate. Hence our obsession with lawyers, those middlemen
between the powerless public and the glacial corporation. The law
firm, the hospital and the Mafia are all being pressed into
metaphorical service for corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   But until our movies give us an intelligent working model of
corporate life, there will be a fairy-tale thinness to the screen's
representation of the way our society functions at this moment.
(af) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
