<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7154 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-MASTERS-TIGER05-C     04-04 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-TIGER05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Simply put, Tiger's The Man
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Tiger Woods admitted it. Right there in front of
100 reporters and CNN and the world. Didn't bat an eye, didn't
pause, just flat-out blurted that, indeed, it was true.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Tiger Woods has been intimidated on a golf course.
</P>
<P>
   Not lately, mind you.
</P>
<P>
   Before Thomas Bjorn and Rocco Mediate start hyperventilating
about their chances in the 64th Masters, which begins Thursday,
they should be forewarned. This once-in-a-storybook-lifetime
revelation came more than a decade ago when the best golfer on this
planet was playing in the Junior World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger was 11.
</P>
<P>
   He was standing on the tee staring at a par-4 hole 290 yards
away when Woods' 12-year-old opponent, whose name he can't even
remember, drove the green. Drove it. At age 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little taken aback,'' he conceded. ``It was the first
and only time in my life I was intimidated on a golf course. I felt
like there was no way I could compete.''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, Tiger's gotten over it. Now it's Tiger who
intimidates, who dominates, who sends golfers fleeing in his path
at first sight of his name on the leader board. Davis Love III has
all but said as much when he said, ``He's driving this tour right
now. If anybody starts beating you like he does, you start
thinking, `Can I beat him?' And he thrives on that.''
</P>
<P>
   And Love's the fourth-ranked player in the world. After losing
four times head-to-head to Tiger, Love said what probably 98
percent of the PGA Tour had to be thinking. The tour's become Tiger
and everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   First- or second-place finishes in 10 of his last 11
tournaments, including six straight victories for the longest such
streak since Ben Hogan in 1948, have a way of convincing people
Tiger is unbeatable. Only Hal Sutton, after his one-stroke win over
Tiger at The Players Championship two weeks ago, spoke as the voice
of hope when he suggested that Woods is not God.
</P>
<P>
   Some who have seen Tiger's drives might argue that point. In
fact, there is a new Web site up whose self-deprecating address is
TigerWoodsIsGod.com, complete with a photo of a Zeus-like figure
superimposed atop the leader board at the 18th as Woods won here in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The site welcomes you to the First Church of Tiger Woods and
even posts a Ten Commandments that begins with ``Thou shalt not
wear red on any day but Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger's reaction?
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow,'' he said Tuesday in typical understated fashion.
``That's interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   To date, Tiger has yet to be seen walking on water and, in fact,
spends very little in the stuff. He doesn't necessarily refute the
idea of his own divinity, but it's safe to say that very few of his
rivals have a prayer of standing up to the 24-year-old phenom who
won here by a 12-stroke margin in his first Masters as a pro and
has since improved.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Augusta National has new teeth in the form of
tighter fairways, more pitched greens and the identical 1 3/8-inch
rough that was introduced last year only plays to Tiger's strength.
Tiger said he didn't understand the need for the Masters to
constantly tweak the course by adding rough here and a bunker
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's just something they like to do around here,'' he
said. ``Maybe they get bored.''
</P>
<P>
   One would think Tiger might have a similar problem, given his
dominance over the last year and his 18 tour victories in only 3
1/2 years.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, since he left here a year ago, he comes better equipped
to win his third major and gain more ground on the 18 major
championships of Jack Nicklaus, a specific goal of Tiger's and a
list he kept taped on his bedroom wall growing up.
</P>
<P>
   The Masters? Heck, he's already got his sights set on a
modern-era Grand Slam. I wrote three years ago that that goal was
well within his reach and little has changed to dissuade that
opinion. His answer on the subject was flippant.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you win the right four tournaments,'' he said, ``you're
doing all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods is obviously doing better than that. He's likely to erase
all golf records before he's 35 and, with $14 million in earnings,
has already made more money than Nicklaus has in his entire career.
If you have first pick in your Masters office pool, the choice is
obvious. Gonzaga might be a trendy selection in the basketball
pool, but other than David Duval, Darren Clarke, Phil Mickelson or
maybe even Love, Tiger's the man. In his last 12 rounds here, he's
20 under par.
</P>
<P>
   And with his tunnel vision, coupled with better 20/15 eyesight
after laser surgery to correct his nearsightedness, that can only
be scary for the rest of the field.
</P>
<P>
   As he put it, ``I've been targeting this.''
</P>
<P>
   So were his victories in the Mercedes and AT&AMP;T and Bay Hill
afterthoughts? Rather, his life is coming around in a way that
perfectly complements his golf game. He is more at ease with the
press, gets along better with his fellow golfers and has a better
understanding of himself.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger comes to the Masters with a new, tighter, more compact
golf swing, a new, more positive and upbeat caddie, a new
less-serious manager, a new, 25-pounds-heavier physique, even a new
girlfriend. A girlfriend who the sacrilegious Web site reminded is
named Joanna Jagoda, or JaGODa.
</P>
<P>
   However, he still has that same old mind-set. That's got to
worry his opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he no longer has any feelings of inadequacy, of
intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he said, ``if I stepped into a ring with Tyson, I
wouldn't feel too good about my chances.''
</P>
<P>
   The Masters, however, is Tiger's own personal ring. Oh, and that
junior tournament in which he was outdriven? Tiger came back to win
that one, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
