<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JOSEPH-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOSEPH IS BLAND, BUT CHECK OUT THOSE TEETH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are there sunspots? Meteor showers? Something else akimbo with
the cosmos? Surely so, because PBS is packaging Andrew Lloyd
Webber, Donny Osmond and Joan Collins into one gaudy package
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   As the public network's slogan says: If PBS won't, who will?
Excellent question. Well, who? I'm waiting.
</P>
<P>
   The show is a newly filmed version of Webber's ``Joseph and the
Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat,'' a freaky, creaky, campy bit of
stagecraft based on the Genesis story of Joseph, the son of Jacob,
triumphing after his 11 envious brothers sell him into slavery.
</P>
<P>
   A dewy-eyed and dentally endowed Osmond is Joseph in the
80-minute production, as well as PBS' host for a whole three hours
of Webbermania.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first ``PBS Showcase'' from the ``Great
Performances'' folks _ an entire night of programming wrapped
around a single theme.
</P>
<P>
   First it's ``Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat.''
Then Osmond will guide viewers into a documentary about Webber.
Next come peeks at Webber's ``Jesus Christ Superstar'' _ a new
production is brewing _ and ``Whistle Down the Wind.'' Finally,
there's a repeat of a 1985 television production of Webber's
``Requiem,'' with Placido Domingo and Sarah Brightman.
</P>
<P>
   After that it's bedtime, and a strong likelihood of disturbing
dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat'' was filmed at
Pinewood Studio in London. Besides Osmond, it stars a mainly
decorous Richard Attenborough as Jacob, Maria Friedman as the
Narrator, Robert Torti as the Pharaoh, Ian McNeice as Potiphar,
Collins as Potiphar's horny wife, and seven or eight showgirls
barely attired in fishnet.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has seen the stage version knows that ``Joseph'' is
colorful, energetic, eclectic enough to encompass calypso, rock 'n'
roll and country music, and plain dumb.
</P>
<P>
   The musical evolved from a minutes-long presentation at a London
school in 1968 and was the first collaboration between Webber and
lyricist Tim Rice. ``Evita'' and ``Jesus Christ Superstar'' came
later.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Joseph'' lyrics range from maple to oak. I'd like to think
that even Rice would cringe today at ``I look handsome, I look
smart, I am a walking work of art.'' Or, as a chorus of fellow
prisoners in Egypt tell our despairing hero, ``Don't give up,
Joseph, wait and you'll see. We've been outside and you're on the
marquee!'' Brother.
</P>
<P>
   McNeice squeezes chuckles from his short stint as Potiphar, the
Egyptian mogul who buys Joseph. And Torti, coiffed in a slick
pompadour, turns the pharaoh into Elvis with a sort of ``Beach
Blanket Babylon'' pizzazz. Collins is onscreen only briefly, in
high-glam mode. She's adorned in a Nefertiti getup, and the pasties
over her bodysuit suggest that the emphasis is on the proper
syllable.
</P>
<P>
   Osmond has toured extensively in the title role, and PBS says he
was Webber's choice. It isn't much of a challenge, really, singing
or acting. But let's face it. No matter what the poor guy does _
even when he's dressed in a loincloth and being pawed by Collins _
he is destined, always, to project this: I'm a bland, pretty pop
singer from Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat'' does, however,
finally enable Osmond to attach the word ``weird'' to his resume.
If not much else, this hard-driving, aging musical is certainly
strange.
</P>
<P>
   PBS and ``Great Performances'' at New York's WNET-TV anticipate
three or four ``PBS Showcase'' nights a year.
</P>
<P>
   The next one, still unscheduled, probably will be built around
``Buena Vista Social Club,'' the Oscar-nominated film about Cuban
musicians.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
