<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GREENSPAN, THE MARKET GIVETH, THE MARKET TAKETH AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MARKET, STOCKS-MARKETPLACE) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alan Greenspan got just what he wanted Tuesday
morning: a sharp break in the stock market's ever-upward psychology
and a broad downturn in prices that took a big chunk of wealth out
of investors' bulging pockets.
</P>
<P>
   But then the markets snatched it back. After a stomach-churning
plunge, stock prices rebounded smartly in the afternoon, closing
with losses that, while not trivial, were hardly paradigm-changing.
The prevailing assumption _ that every dip is a buying opportunity
_ remained more or less intact, though day traders no doubt ended
the session wondering whether investing is as easy as it was last
year.
</P>
<P>
   And Greenspan and his colleagues at the Federal Reserve were
left to wonder anew what it would take to rein in Wall Street,
which they have come to view as the channel through which inflation
is most likely to infect the economy.
</P>
<P>
   True, technology stocks have taken a battering over the past
week. But most of the wealth created in the market over the last
few years is still intact, fueling consumer spending and a general
sense of economic invulnerability. And by some measures, stocks are
still grinding their way upward.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's preferred measure of market performance, the
Wilshire 5000, which captures the movement of nearly all stocks, is
still up about 1 percent for the year, and up 10.9 percent since
last June 30, when the Fed began its current round of rate hikes.
For all its troubles in the past few weeks, the Nasdaq index is
still 54 percent higher than it was on June 30.
</P>
<P>
   All of which suggests that nothing that happened Tuesday will
deter the Fed from continuing to raise rates. The very resiliency
of the markets might even lead the central bank to conclude that it
needs to raise rates further, and in bigger increments than it has
so far, to grab the attention of investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we have neither a sustained correction in the stock
market nor a significant slowdown in the economy,'' said Sung Won
Sohn, an economist at Norwest Bank in Minneapolis. ``To keep the
market contained will require at least a couple more interest rate
hikes and a continued open-mouth policy on the part of chairman
Greenspan.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors will no doubt be listening intently when Greenpsan
speaks on Wednesday afternoon at a White House conference on the
economy. Greenspan is expected to discuss technology's effect on
the economy, a subject that would give him ample opportunity, if he
chooses, to assess the markets and signal his intentions for the
next Fed policy meeting on May 16.
</P>
<P>
   There are many reasons why the economy continues to stampede,
not least that low unemployment and rising wages are making most
people feel confident and willing to spend. But Greenspan has
repeatedly emphasized the potential for the wealth generated by the
market to be the force that leads the economy to overheat and start
throwing off inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed chairman has said repeatedly that he is not targeting
the stock market per se. But he has also made clear that, absent a
pronounced slowdown in some other sector of the economy, the
market's sustained rise would have to slow considerably to allow
the economy to remain on an even keel.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan has even set out a speed limit for the market: Asset
values should not rise faster than household income. His equation
roughly implies that stock prices should not rise at more than
around a 6 percent annual rate.
</P>
<P>
   Measured from the start of this year, the markets are generally
within the speed limit, at least as measured by the Wilshire 5000.
</P>
<P>
   But over longer periods the upward surge in equity prices
remains too rapid for Greenspan's taste. And with markets so
volatile, it is hard to say whether there is a sustainable trend of
deceleration.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at where we are today relative to the beginning of
the year, you'd say we're not too far from the beginning of the
neutralization of the wealth effect,'' said Richard D. Rippe, an
economist at Prudential Securities. ``But since the market is so
volatile, your perception can change substantially in a couple of
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Ian Shepherdson, an economist at High Frequency Economics, a
consulting firm, said the decline in the Nasdaq has only taken the
index back to where it was two months ago, ``and we don't recall
seeing much evidence back in February that the economy was slowing
down.''
</P>
<P>
   If stock prices stabilize where they are now, ``we think there
will probably be some measurable impact on consumer confidence over
the next month or two,'' Shepherdson said. ``But it will not be
enough to slow the economy as much as the Fed wants.''
</P>
<P>
   The next big indicator of the economy's performance will come on
Friday, when the Labor Department reports on job creation and the
unemployment rate for March. If the economy continues to create
jobs at a robust pace, and if the unemployment rate falls back to 4
percent or below, it would be another sign that economic growth
remains at a level far beyond what the Fed considers prudent.
</P>
<P>
   (mk)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
