<HEADER>
A7165 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-FINALFOUR-FOLO05-     04-04 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-FINALFOUR-FOLO05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Donovan, Gators turn their focus to future
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The pain of Monday night's 89-76 loss to Michigan
State in the NCAA basketball championship was only a few minutes
old when Florida coach Billy Donovan began looking ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know these guys don't want to hear this right now, but I
wish it was Oct. 15 and we could start all over again,'' Donovan
said. ``We are excited about how far we have come. We're even more
excited about where we can go.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida (29-8) made a memorable run through the NCAA Tournament
in Donovan's fourth year as coach. It began with a near-loss to
Butler (69-68 OT) in the first round and included wins over
Illinois, Duke, Oklahoma State and North Carolina. Not bad for a
``football school.''
</P>
<P>
   But Monday night before 43,116 at the RCA Dome, the youthful
Gators were no match for the tenacity of Mateen Cleaves and
Michigan State. Florida was a young team trying to do something
bold. Michigan State's seniors _ Cleaves, Morris Peterson and A.J.
Granger _ were delivering their school a national championship in
their final game.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators did not dwell in their disappointment. With only one
senior, Kenyan Weaks, on the squad, talk of the future came
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   And what will that future be? Can the 34-year-old Donovan, after
punching most of the right buttons at so young an age, sustain this
success?
</P>
<P>
   After last season's Sweet 16 appearance, athletics director
Jeremy Foley renegotiated Donovan's contract into a five-year $3.5
million deal. After this, Donovan is bound to become an even hotter
hot property.
</P>
<P>
   When the NFL came calling on Steve Spurrier several years ago,
Foley made him college football's highest-paid coach at $2 million
per season. It's a sure bet that the NBA will be knocking soon on
Billy D's door.
</P>
<P>
   Foley said he is prepared to rework Donovan's contract again,
``if that becomes necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida has made the commitment in every other phase of the
basketball program. It spent more than $10 million in improvements
to the O'Connell Center, which has been voted as the toughest home
court in basketball. The school is about to break ground on a new
$10 million practice facility, scheduled to open in August 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The team loses only Weaks, but the concern is about sophomore
forward Mike Miller.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-8 Miller did not have a memorable Final Four, with just 20
points in two games, and said he will take some time to evaluate
his situation. Underclassmen have until May 14 to declare their
intention to turn pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it tempting? Yes, but I haven't allowed myself to think
about it during the tournament,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Donnell Harvey, the former Mr. Georgia Basketball, has
said he will return to Gainesville next season. But there are
rumblings that Harvey still might decide that college is just not
the place for him.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan, meanwhile, has continued to recruit. Next season, he
adds 6-5 swingman Orien Green, Florida's Mr. Basketball. Of the 10
players on the floor Monday night for Florida, four were freshman,
three were sophomores and two were juniors.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Florida's third year under Donovan, the Gators reached
the Sweet 16 and were within a basket of advancing to the Elite
Eight. In 2000, they reached the national championship game. Now,
Gator fans want to know if the program will keep moving forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to be successful once,'' Donovan said. ``Now
what we have to do with our program is take the next step.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
