<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Antitrust Ruling Could Generate Lawsuits
</P>
<P>
   The federal antitrust ruling against Microsoft could lead to a
wave of class-action and other consumer lawsuits against the
company. With Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson having ruled on Monday
that Microsoft is a ``predatory'' monopolist that repeatedly
violated antitrust laws, private plaintiffs have a far less
daunting challenge in suits already filed _ and in actions being
considered by companies that believe they have suffered from abuse
of Microsoft's market power.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn Bids for Nabisco Group
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco Group Holdings is reviewing the latest bid by Carl Icahn
to buy the company. Icahn, who already owns about 9 percent of the
company, bid $5.2 billion, or $16 a share, to buy the rest. Nabisco
had rejected Icahn's earlier offer to buy 30 percent of the company
for $13 a share, but in response to the new offer Nabisco has hired
investment bankers to consider its options.
</P>
<P>
   Coke Sees Profit and Sales Growth
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola told investors that it expects long-term sales growth
of 7 percent to 8 percent and profit growth of 15 percent a year,
but its optimistic presentation was tempered by news that
first-quarter growth will be only about 1.5 percent and that the
company will take a $400 million charge in the period to close
poorly performing plants.
</P>
<P>
   How Does the Fed Read Wall Street?
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's gyrations must have left Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan wondering just what it will take to keep the stock
market under control. Investors will be listening intently today
when he speaks at a White House conference on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Bond Yield Reaches 10-Month Low
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond slipped to 5.77 percent,
its lowest since last May, as the sharp midday decline in the
Nasdaq stock index sent investors scurrying to the safety of
government securities.
</P>
<P>
   Leading Economic Indicators Fall
</P>
<P>
   The Conference Board's index of leading economic indicators fell
0.3 percent in February, its first decline in five months, as
factory orders for capital goods, building permits and stocks
declined. But analysts expect the index, a gauge of future growth,
to rebound in the next report.
</P>
<P>
   Reno to Speak in Silicon Valley
</P>
<P>
   In a speech at Stanford University and in talks with executives
of technology companies, Attorney General Janet Reno will extend an
olive branch today to Silicon Valley companies over issues like
digital surveillance and will offer the government's support in
fighting computer crime.
</P>
<P>
   A Champion for Adoption Benefits
</P>
<P>
   Dave Thomas, founder and senior chairman of the board of Wendy's
International, the fast-food restaurant chain, talks about his
experience as an adopted child, how he tried to cope growing up but
failed to finish high school and about his work in Washington to
encourage companies to provide benefits for families that adopt
children.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Threatens Mexico Trade Action
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. trade representative, Charlene Barshefsky, said that
Mexico was failing to support competition in telecommunications and
that she might take action before the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Investors Favoring Japanese Shares
</P>
<P>
   Japan's stock market and its currency are showing strength as
buying by mutual funds and a penchant for high-technology companies
is overcoming a host of negative factors.
</P>
<P>
   An Inflight Cineplex in First Class
</P>
<P>
   Singapore Airlines is setting the pace in providing inflight
entertainment in first and business class, with a wide array of
movies, short films and audio cds and viewing screens at each
individual seat with controls that have all the features of a VCR.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
