<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: AIRLINES IMPROVE FILM-VIEWING OPPORTUNITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (duplication notice: also sent with `t' code)  
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Given the way the movie business tends to fill up the available
screens mostly with lowest-common-denominator blockbusters and not
much else, the best place to find a wide selection of films may
eventually be in the premium seats on an intercontinental flight.
</P>
<P>
   Singapore Airlines, for example, is spending about $18,500 a
seat to install a fiber optic in-flight entertainment system that
provides a menu of 25 movies, 50 short films and documentaries, and
50 full-length audio CD's for passengers in first and business
class, with the videos shown on individual screens at each seat.
Singapore says the real innovation is that the system, based on
digital technology developed by Matsushita Avionics Systems, allows
passengers to freeze, forward, pause or rewind movies and CDs just
as they could on a home entertainment system.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get halfway through the movie and want to take a nap,
you can hit pause and resume watching when you wake up,'' said
James Boyd, a spokesman for the airline, which introduced the
system last week in the front of the planes on flights from New
York and Newark to Asia via Europe. The airline expects the system
_ which is being marketed as a way for premium-class passengers to
feel more in control of their environment on long hauls _ to be
installed in flights to Asia from the West Coast by the end of
April.
</P>
<P>
   Singapore's international flights already have individual video
monitors at each seat, including those in coach. But the coach
sections will continue to have the old entertainment system, which
provides a choice of 13 movies as well as video games and music
channels.
</P>
<P>
   The Matsushita engineers who developed the system say they are
leading the way in revolutionizing in-flight entertainment and
information systems.
</P>
<P>
   The Matsushita system now has a capacity of 100 hours of movie
content and about 50 CDs, said Kevin Munday, the company's manager
of technical marketing. ``But within a year and half to two years,
you're going to see easily a quadrupling of that capacity, and the
direction downstream is not just to provide movies and audio but
full-on Web and multimedia content,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The JetBlue Experience
</P>
<P>
   The good news about the new regional start-up airline JetBlue
Airways, based on a recent business trip I made from New York to
Tampa, Fla., is that the planes are comfortable and so new that
they smell like just-bought cars. The chipper flight attendants and
ticket clerks seem actually delighted to see you; the flights
depart and arrive on time, and advance purchase fares are low.
</P>
<P>
   The other news, not bad, but certainly worth noting for business
travelers, is that those low fares can get higher if, as is common
among business travelers, a change or two of schedule is required
after the initial reservation. And for travelers who live in the
sprawling New York metropolitan area, the inconvenience and expense
of getting to Kennedy International Airport are also factors to
consider.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what I found: Booked over two weeks before departure, my
original fare was $119 from New York to Tampa, and $79 for the
return trip. A few days before departure, I needed to change my
schedule to leave and return a day later. The $119 fare to Tampa
became $159, with a $25 change fee. The $79 return fare went up to
$159, with another $25 penalty.
</P>
<P>
   So the original $198 round-trip fare now was $368 _ still a
pretty good price. However, Kennedy is notoriously difficult to get
to from outside New York City. From my home in New Jersey, 15 miles
from Manhattan, the airport car-service fare to and from the
airport is $90 (plus tip). So that added another $216 to my costs,
for a grand total of $584.
</P>
<P>
   Still not bad, considering it can cost twice that much to book a
last-minute flight on a major carrier. But wait: a few hours after
I changed my JetBlue itinerary, I went to the two major online
booking services to comparison shop for fares to Tampa from Newark
International Airport. Even at the last minute, Expedia.com offered
a choice of Delta flights for the same days at a round-trip fare of
$530. Travelocity.com had flights on AirTran, same itinerary, for
$535. Add the airport car-service fare of $30 (plus tip) to the far
more convenient Newark airport, and for me the JetBlue competitive
edge began to fade for that itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson: For the sort of last-minute itinerary changes that
characterize business travel, it can pay to do some quick
comparison shopping on the online travel sites.
</P>
<P>
   JetBlue, which now flies between Kennedy and Tampa, Fort
Lauderdale and Buffalo, plans to add about 10 more destinations
this year. ``Our focus has been for travelers across the board, not
strictly corporate or leisure,'' said Gareth Edmondson-Jones, a
spokesman for the airline. In general, he pointed out, ``business
travelers can fly us for 65 percent less, and still experience new
planes and leather seats.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (BL)
</P>
</TEXT>
