<SLUG> BC-REORG-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: NEW ECONOMY CHANGES HOW 2 AGENCIES OPERATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two well-known agencies based here are reorganizing
in ways that are indicative of the substantive shifts taking place
along Madison Avenue to try matching the pace of change in
cyberspace and at client companies.
</P>
<P>
   One agency, Messner Vetere Berger McNamee Schmetterer/Euro RSCG,
is combining under one roof a variety of services outside the realm
of traditional advertising that include interactive marketing,
sales promotion, retail advertising, data base management, direct
marketing and design.
</P>
<P>
   Those communications services are being offered by Messner
Vetere, part of the Euro RSCG Worldwide unit of Havas Advertising,
under the name Fuel North America. That had been the name of a unit
devoted to handling the retail account of a large client, Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   And Mezzina/Brown, an agency that has added a skein of dot-com
accounts to a client roster that includes DuPont; Goldman, Sachs;
and R.J. Reynolds, is being reorganized under the name Mezzina
Brown &AMP; Partners. The goal of the principals of Mezzina Brown, who
are teaming up with outside companies that include Netcentric
Partners, a venture capital firm, is to place additional emphasis
on business development for so-called new-economy marketers.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Berger, chief executive and chief creative officer at
Messner Vetere, offered an explanation of the shifts at his agency
that described the motivations of both shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to design and evolve the agency's offerings to reflect
where the world is today,'' Berger said, ``building on our
experience with brands and our clients' needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuel North America has about 140 employees handling assignments
with billings estimated at $100 million, which include the Volvo
retail account, creating campaigns for the automaker's dealer
associations, as well as for other Messner Vetere clients like
Intel, MCI WorldCom, J.P. Morgan, New Balance, Philips and
Schering-Plough.
</P>
<P>
   Among the operations being combined under the Fuel North America
banner, in addition to the Volvo unit, are the New York office of
Cohn &AMP; Wells Partners, which specialized in direct marketing;
Compelling Content, an interactive agency acquired in September by
Cohn &AMP; Wells; and the Messner Vetere divisions focused on design,
sales promotion and Internet ad work.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel North America, which reports to Berger, has four partners,
headed by Beth Waxman, 37, managing director, who continues as a
partner at Messner Vetere, where she had been overseeing the Intel
account. The other partners at Fuel North America, all creative
directors, are: Bertrand Garbassi, 40; Marshall Karp, who declined
to give his age; and Paul Trantanella, 37.
</P>
<P>
   At Mezzina Brown, which has about 120 employees and billings
estimated at $145 million, a highlight of the restructuring is the
formation of a specialty division, MB Capital and Consultancy,
``devoted to helping pre-IPO dot-coms identify business models,
determine efficient revenue streams and even if necessary write
their business plans,'' said William G. Brown Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 52, becomes senior partner and chief executive of the
agency after serving as president before the reorganization. John
Mezzina, 51, shifts from chairman and executive creative director
to senior partner and chief strategy officer. Mark A. Morrissey,
41, executive vice president and client services director, becomes
partner and chief operating officer. And David Frutko, 49,
continues as chief financial officer while moving from executive
vice president to partner.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said that Mezzina would take ``a temporary leave of
absence'' from the agency to focus on Freeride.com LLC, an Internet
company spun off from Mezzina/Brown in 1996 that offers computer
users rewards meant to strengthen their ties to companies with
which they do business.
</P>
<P>
   ``John's leave is to shepherd that business to the next level,''
Brown said, smiling. He declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Can you say initial public offering?
</P>
<P>
   Among the dot-com clients of Mezzina Brown, which started an
interactive division in 1993, are Freeride.com, NexGenix, Newsweek
magazine, Real Media, VarsityPlanet.com and Wit Capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``In response to the new economy, we've created our consultancy
group,'' Brown said, ``which can also help source capital through
Netcentric Partners,'' with a war chest planned to reach $200
million.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl L. Benton is joining Mezzina Brown as managing director
for interactive services, overseeing the MB Interactive division.
Benton, 49, had been executive vice president at JMCP Touch
Interactive, a division of Jordan McGrath Case &AMP; Partners/Euro
RSCG, part of the Euro RSCG Worldwide unit of Havas.
</P>
<P>
   In another change, seven top executives at Mezzina Brown are
being promoted because, Brown said, ``with the dramatic shift in
the marketplace for key talent, it's important to offer
partnerships to our key players.''
</P>
<P>
   The new partners are: Jean Andrews, 38, manager for strategic
support services; Robert Earl, 58, managing director for direct
marketing creative services; Robert Moore, 47, managing director
for account services; Clark Moss, 38, managing director for
creative services; Donna L. Walters, 36, managing director for
graphic services; Gary Watson, 40, managing director for client
services; and Margaret A. Williams, who declined to give her age,
managing director for administrative services. The majority
shareholders are Brown, Frutko, Mezzina and Morrissey.
</P>
<P>
   (BL)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
