<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7170 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-MASTERS-FEATURE05     04-04 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-FEATURE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Giddy ride before fall: Day 1 lead
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Before Tiger Woods turned the 1997 Masters into
his personal showcase, most of the attention was on one John
Huston. The first-round leader capped a solid day with an eagle on
the 18th hole from near the 10th fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Huston felt good that night. His dinner tasted better. His bed
was more comfortable. Family and friends were thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   It is a routine that Day 1 leaders of the Masters often
experience. But it can be short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   Many first-day leaders of the tournament descend the leaderboard
rapidly and drop right out of contention. Being atop the year's
first major _ which begins Thursday morning at Augusta National _
is a satisfying position. Even for a day.
</P>
<P>
   Huston isn't an outwardly expressive person, but he still had to
suppress his emotions; there were still three days of golf ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``As good as you feel about being in the lead,'' he said, ``you
haven't done anything. Being at the top of the first-round
leaderboard doesn't mean anything. It's nice to be there, but
there's a long way to go. So, while I was glad to be in front, I
wasn't overly excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Huston was right not to get too giddy. He shot a 77 on Friday.
Meanwhile, Woods ate up the field, and Huston was forgotten; he
finished 21st. ``There's potential after a good first day to do
good things,'' Huston said. ``I felt good about my game, of course,
after that day. But in golf, that means nothing. Tiger came along
and that was that.''
</P>
<P>
   The greatest fall in the last 10 years was by Mike Donald. In
1990, Donald shot 64 for the first-day lead.
</P>
<P>
   His euphoric feeling lasted less than a day. He came back to
shoot an 82 and wound up 47th by the end of the tournament. ``It's
not easy to stay up there,'' said Brandel Chamblee, who shared the
lead after the opening round last year.
</P>
<P>
   Chamblee made his debut at the Masters after ``learning the
course from watching it on television,'' he said. ``So, it was just
a big thrill for me to be there. It's a tournament unlike any
other. I thought before I went to Augusta how great it was, but I
was even more in awe of the place afterward. There was no letdown,
even after the way the rest of the tournament went for me.''
</P>
<P>
   After his opening round of 67 and a four-way tie for first, ``it
was almost unreal,'' he said. ``You can imagine yourself there, on
top of the leaderboard, but it's nothing like actually being there.
My family and friends were ecstatic.... There was a lot of smiles
and celebration.''
</P>
<P>
   Not too much by Chamblee, however, ``Still three days left,'' he
said. And sure enough, the game that was wonderful the first day
was not the second. Or the third. Chamblee tied for 17th. Worse, he
missed being eligible to return to this year's Masters, by one
stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I would have shot one lower, but I can't complain too
much about my experience there,'' Chamblee said. ``I was in first
after one day. It was great. It wasn't an intimidating position,
but it's one you'll never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   People might have forgotten that even Jack Nicklaus, a six-time
Masters winner, had his own fade after a first day of glory. It was
1993, and Nicklaus shot an opening 67 to assume the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus, the Day 1 leader four times, led the whole tournament
only once, in 1972. In 1966, he led after the first round, fell to
third, retook the lead after three rounds and won it in an 18-hole
playoff.
</P>
<P>
   Only eight Masters champions have led the tournament from
Thursday to Sunday. Arnold Palmer did it twice.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Nicklaus shot a 75 on the second day, 76 on Saturday
and a 71 on Sunday. Bernhard Langer won for the second time;
Nicklaus finished 27th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not bad company to be in,'' Chamblee said. ``If Jack Nicklaus
can lead after one round and then disappear, it can happen to
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
