<HEADLINE>
JURY INDICTS 11 PARENTS BECAUSE CHILDREN ARE TRUANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In a new attack on truancy, a Jackson County
grand jury has indicted 11 parents in two school districts on
charges that their children constantly skip school.
</P>
<P>
   County Prosecutor Bob Beaird said Tuesday that this was the
county's first use of a 1963 law that made it a misdemeanor for
parents not to have their children in school.
</P>
<P>
   The names of the parents in the Kansas City and the Fort Osage
School districts who were indicted Friday would remain sealed until
they received subpoenas, Beaird said.
</P>
<P>
   They will be ordered to report to Circuit Court, where
conviction is punishable by up to 15 days in jail and up to a $500
fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's the last thing we want to do,'' Beaird said of the
jail time. ``We want to work with them to get these children back
in school.''
</P>
<P>
   The parents may be ordered into parenting or family programs or
drug treatment, Beaird said. Those who cooperate and get their
children to attend school will be rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they live up to their moral responsibility,'' Beaird said,
``we'll dismiss the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Beaird said prosecutors should be active in fighting truancy
because children who dropped out of school were at a higher risk
for committing crimes and suffering other social ills.
</P>
<P>
   The new approach has been used in at least one other area
jurisdiction. The Buchanan County prosecutor first used it about
three years ago against a few parents of chronic truants.
</P>
<P>
   The indicted Jackson County parents were repeatedly warned by
the school districts and by letters from the prosecutor's office,
Beaird said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've gotten every chance times 10,'' Beaird said. The new
approach, he added, ``puts some teeth behind our bark.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Hammock, a spokeswoman for the Kansas City School District,
said Tuesday that the district had worked with prosecutors for
months in planning the stronger attack on the truancy problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a last resort,'' Hammock said. ``It should get
parents' attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Last June the district discontinued a program designed to round
up truants. Budget cuts forced the district to lay off 12
parent-school liaisons.
</P>
<P>
   Although the district does not keep statistics that break out
truants separately from students who are legitimately absent,
police have delivered 171 students to the district's drop-out
center this academic year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
