<HEADER>
A7174 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-TEN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     04-04 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
 
McENROE IS REBEL WITH A CAUSE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ John McEnroe's voice rises like a lob whenever he
talks about the Davis Cup. His passion for the competition goes
right over the heads of all the mercenary millionaires in his sport
who would sooner lose their entourages than pay tribute or taxes to
their countries.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two decades, McEnroe has engaged in verbal volleys
with some of this country's best tennis players. Everybody from
Jimmy Connors to Pete Sampras has felt the sting of McEnroe's
shots, has heard him rail that their refusal to play in the Davis
Cup is ``a dagger in the heart of tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   He's about as subtle as an overhead smash. Get McEnroe talking
about those tennis players who can't be bothered by the Davis Cup
and his voice takes on that ``absolute pits of the world'' pitch
that's like an air raid siren to chair umpires the world over.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, too, has felt the heat from a McEnroe fallout. The L.A.
resident turned back every challenger to his world No.1 ranking for
six straight years but in the end was no match for McEnroe. Sampras
re-enlisted for Davis Cup duty at the end of last year after going
AWOL for a spell. He came to his senses with the help of all those
smelling salts McEnroe kept shoving under his nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get so consumed with your personal goals and being
No.1, you can lose sight of what the sport needs,'' Sampras
admitted, saying in a more sanitized way what McEnroe has been
screaming for years.
</P>
<P>
   A tear in his right hip muscle kept Sampras out of the U.S.'
first-round victory against host Zimbabwe in February. A rift in
communication between the world's No.3-ranked player and McEnroe in
the wake of the injury threatened to sideline Sampras from the U.S.
squad's quarterfinal tie against the Czech Republic Friday through
Sunday at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for Americans is Sampras' hip is better and so is
his relationship with McEnroe, 40, who was named the U.S. Davis Cup
captain last September. McEnroe roiled the waters in Zimbabwe when
he questioned the severity of Sampras' injury, which he had
suffered the previous week during a tough semifinal loss to Andre
Agassi at the Australian Open.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the first time McEnroe had challenged Sampras'
sincerity. At the 1996 U.S. Open, Sampras vomited on the court
during a fifth-set tiebreaker in his quarterfinal match against
Alex Corretja, which Sampras somehow went on to win. Afterward,
McEnroe was quoted as saying, ``That's pretty tremendous acting. If
you're that out of it, you don't serve 120 miles per hour. No one
does that.''
</P>
<P>
   Launched by a former No.1 player, McEnroe's words hit like a
stink bomb, causing mostly just a foul odor. Speaking as the Davis
Cup captain, McEnroe's words did more damage. They were like a hand
grenade that singed bridges and wounded an ego.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe responded to the unfolding crisis as a captain should.
He phoned Sampras and patched things up.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to learn to sort of do what it takes,'' McEnroe said.
``This is what the (captain's) job is about. It's about a bigger
picture. I have to keep telling myself that it's about something
bigger than me or Pete Sampras.''
</P>
<P>
   And there it is: one small step for diplomacy never McEnroe's
strong suit and one giant step for the Davis Cup, which has
suffered lately for not having the game's top players involved.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, Don Budge deemed the event important enough
that he turned down $50,000 to turn pro so he could represent the
U.S. in the 1938 Davis Cup. The event meant enough to McEnroe that
he cleared room for it in his schedule for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Like the expletives he is quick to hurl at others when his own
play has him furious, McEnroe's passion for the Davis Cup would
seem to be misplaced.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the player whom the British press once dubbed
``Superbrat'' comes across as an unlikely ``Superpatriot.'' This
is, after all, the same man who used to speak of USTA officials as
though they were kept administrators, the same man whose whining
during the 1984 Davis Cup final in Sweden nearly cost the United
States Tennis Association its corporate backing for future Davis
Cup events (and did lead to a written code-of-conduct that the U.S.
players were required to sign).
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the high jinks of the high-maintenance McEnroe and
the higher-maintenance Connors would effectively cost Arthur Ashe,
whom McEnroe once deemed ``too passive,'' his Davis Cup captaincy.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, like sandpaper, McEnroe has a softer side. He once
said he played Davis Cup to keep a promise to his mother, Kay.
</P>
<P>
   That might have been true. But what started out as something
McEnroe did to make somebody else happy quickly evolved into
something he did because of how it made him feel.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out, McEnroe enjoyed wringing out his ego, that sponge
of self-absorption. He still does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, I'm selfish like all those other tennis guys,''
McEnroe said. ``We all have our selfish tendencies. In the Davis
Cup, you get to see people who generally are thought of as selfish
trying to play together as a team and do something not just for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something to me that is magical about the camaraderie
that develops, hopefully, when you get a team together to play
another country.''
</P>
<P>
   There you have it; the biggest difference _ the only difference,
really _ between McEnroe the player and McEnroe the captain:
Instead of a racket, he wields a wand. It's now his spell to cast. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Karen Crouse's column appears in the Daily News four days a week.
She can be reached at (818) 713-3619. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
