<SLUG> BC-KC-KEN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR HAS A FEW KIND WORDS FOR CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Former independent counsel Kenneth Starr
isn't the most likely person to publicly praise President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But there was Starr, in Kansas City on Tuesday, complimenting
Clinton for his ``enormous gifts,'' his intelligence and his
ability to communicate and empathize with people.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a political level, he is indeed `first in his class,' &UR; ''
Starr said, referring to a best-selling biography written about the
president. ``I don't see anyone who's been a close second to him in
the boomer generation in terms of political skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr's kind words ended there. The president's chief antagonist
in his tortuous impeachment battle then began a discussion about
character, honor and the importance of truth.
</P>
<P>
   He talked about the Declaration of Independence, which Starr
said placed a premium on the concept of truth. He referred to
President Lincoln, who once issued a statement that his oath of
office was ``registered in heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, after mentioning school honor codes that demand students
not lie, cheat or steal, Starr said: ``I think that has been
unfortunately the aspect of presidential character that has been
wanting these past seven years. And we as a nation have suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr, who spoke Tuesday night at the University of Kansas in
Lawrence, Kan., resigned as independent counsel in October. He is
writing a book on the U.S. Supreme Court and serves as an adjunct
professor at the New York University School of Law.
</P>
<P>
   He defended his months-long probe of the president, which cost
taxpayers more than $52 million, as critical to preserving the rule
of law and preserving high standards for public officials. He
insisted that he faithfully discharged his duties, which resulted
in 14 convictions _ including one of former Arkansas Gov. Jim Guy
Tucker, who was forced to resign from office.
</P>
<P>
   Starr acknowledged that his work took a long time and that the
public grew weary of what seemed to be an endless probe. On that
score, Starr acknowledged that he should have refused the added
duties of investigating the White House travel office
(``Travelgate'') or the case of the misplaced FBI files
(``Filegate'').
</P>
<P>
   Those matters might have been handled faster by other
independent counsels, although that would have added to the overall
cost of investigating the Clinton White House, Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most efficient, cost-effective way of conducting
the investigation,'' Starr said. ``But sometimes cost savings can
come...at the cost of public confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Killing the independent counsel law was a wise move, Starr said.
The statute, which was enacted in the wake of Watergate,
effectively worked to ``shoehorn a fourth branch of government''
into the nation's three-branch system.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to handle investigations of top government
officials is for the attorney general to appoint an investigator,
the former federal judge said. That way, accountability for the
investigation remains with the executive branch.
</P>
<P>
   The nation has relied on such a system, now back in place, with
great effectiveness dating to the Civil War, Starr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress departed from that historical lesson'' when it
enacted the independent-counsel law in 1978, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 2152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
