<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7178 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DOW-MAIN05-COX     04-04 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-MAIN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wall Street says 'whew' after wild day
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Technology stocks took investors Tuesday on a
gut-wrenching ride that had the Nasdaq composite plunging as much
as 13.6 percent in the worst fall since the 1987 crash, then being
rescued from disaster by a rally that recaptured almost all the
losses.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's plummet pulled the recently surging Dow Jones
industrial average down by more than 500 points before the saving
rally took hold there, too.
</P>
<P>
   The rebound gave some analysts reason to think the worst of the
recent sharp slide in mostly ``new economy'' stocks may be near an
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows we are still in a bull market,'' Standard &AMP; Poor's
senior analyst Joe Tigue said of Tuesday's heart-pounding
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Tigue and other analysts attribute the rally to the combination
of a still-strong economy, an upbeat outlook for first-quarter
profits and falling Treasury bond yields.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, he said the sell-off created ``terrific
buying opportunities'' that attracted investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nasdaq has had a tremendous run here recently, and it's
natural to have some type of pullback _ which we felt was coming,''
said Paul J. Marshall, senior vice president-investments for Robert
W. Baird &AMP; Co. in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   After rising 86 percent in 1999, the Nasdaq peaked March 10 with
a close of 5,048.62.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going through a correction that may be over in another
week or month, but eventually the Nasdaq will turn back up because
of the new realities of the new economy,'' said Fred C. Allvine,
director of the Georgia Tech Stock Market Project.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize the extent to which the Internet will
change our economy. The Nasdaq is down but don't count it out,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are never sure why a sell-off occurs. But after the
Nasdaq, Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 and Russell 2000 small stock indexes
set highs in March, the market was shaken by a series of events,
including a stock panic in Japan, sudden weakness in the
biotechnology sector, several warnings of disappointing earnings
and a recommended 5 percent reduction in stock holdings by
superbull Abby Joseph Cohen of Goldman, Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   There was a rally Friday, but the optimism turned to pessimism
over the weekend when bellwether Microsoft failed to settle its
antitrust lawsuit with the government. The Nasdaq fell 7.6 percent
in heavy volume Monday, even before the federal court ruled against
the company.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the Microsoft deal should not have had that big an
impact by itself. They blame the selling pressure in part on
investors forced to sell securities to meet margin calls _ demands
for more collateral for loans used to buy stocks _ and on day
traders selling to meet April 15 income tax obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the trigger, investors found reasons to go back into
the market Tuesday afternoon, making for the busiest day in Nasdaq
history, with almost 2.9 billion shares trading hands.
</P>
<P>
   At its lowest point, the Nasdaq composite was down by 574.57
points, far exceeding Monday's record one-day point decline of
349.15.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq's temporary fall of 13.6 percent surpassed the 11.4
percent loss of Oct. 19, 1987 _ the steepest ever for Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow closed at 11,164.84, down 57.09 points, or 0.5 percent.
At its lowest, the Dow traded at 10,717.80, or almost 5 percent
below its Monday close.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 small-stock index was down as much as 51.96
points, or 10.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The latest round of Nasdaq and small-cap losses comes after a
week of almost uninterrupted declines knocked the Nasdaq composite
and Russell 2000 indexes down by more than 10 percent from their
recent highs, putting the two groups into a correction by most
definitions.
</P>
<P>
   The weakness has pushed the Russell 2000 index below where it
ended 1999, having been up 20 percent at its March 9 record close.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite stands 17.8 percent below its record close,
but at one point Tuesday was almost 28 percent below its recent
all-time high, well below the 20 percent level that generally marks
a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   Baird's Marshall said the next month and a half of first-quarter
earnings reports is a reason for optimism that the rally that
halted the plunge will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first week or so of earnings reports is typically weak,
but then in the latter weeks you will see stronger reports,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
