<HEADER>
A7179 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-DUCHOVNY-FILMS-ART-2N     04-04 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUCHOVNY-FILMS-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: the series.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I should have just bailed out, but I didn't know,'' he says.
``Now I know. That's really too bad because I really think that's a
good idea for a movie and now it'll never get made because we
screwed it up.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds, ``I had a lot of pain involved because I was attacked
personally,'' adding that his wife liked the film. He has never
actually seen it, but he imagines an old age in which he will.
``One day I'll be like Howard Hughes, in a room, touching things
with Kleenex,'' he says, ``and watching `Playing God' over and
over.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times review of ``Playing God,'' by Janet Maslin,
declared him ``utterly lifeless and without charm.'' And there are
those who still contend that he's not a particularly brilliant
actor, that he'd be nowhere without Mulder. (Others say it's vice
versa. He is suing 20th Century Fox over his share of the show's
syndication-rights sale.)
</P>
<P>
   His supporters, however, are enthusiastic about his potential
and suggest that playing Agent Mulder, with his general lack of
affect, is harder than Duchovny makes it look.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that David is a much smarter actor than people give
him credit for,'' says Kim Manners, an ``X-Files'' supervising
producer who has just directed his 37th episode. ``David is a very
clever actor. He doesn't see Mulder as a hero, just a guy, but it's
interesting the way Mulder comes off on camera. When you look at
him, you see a guy who doesn't have any airs about him, who wears
his heart on his sleeve.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mulder also comes across, his fans say, as the screen's first
sexy nerd, a description that his portrayer understands. ``He's
completely committed to what he does,'' Duchovny says of his
character. ``And even though it doesn't involve girls at all,
commitment is attractive to people.'')
</P>
<P>
   And, Manners adds, Duchovny often does things his own way. In
the recent episode in which Mulder was reunited all too briefly
with his sister, the script called for him to embrace her and break
down in tears. Instead, ``he just took her in his arms,'' Manners
recalls. ``There was a peace, a great calm about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunt thinks ``Return to Me'' could indeed be the beginning of a
new phase of Duchovny's career.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is, for David, the first time he was in his element,''
she says, ``where he could really expand his wings.'' She says she
had no problem breaking him of his longtime television character's
habits. He, however, remembers her walking over after a scene,
shaking her head and telling him, ``That was so Mulder.''
</P>
<P>
   Why do so many television stars have trouble making the switch
to feature films? Is it true that some actors who are great on the
home screen are just not ``big'' enough? ``I think probably 90
percent of it is luck,'' Hunt says. ``I wouldn't even attempt to
philosophize about it. But sincerity of character helps, maybe more
so in film because the screens are so much bigger and you have the
audience's undivided attention.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain on screens of any size: the man has a sense
of humor, although he says people are always surprised to learn
that. Clearly those people never saw Duchovny on ``The Larry
Sanders Show.'' The two episodes in which he played himself as a
guest on the HBO series' fictional talk show _ and declared himself
in love with Larry (his pal Garry Shandling) _ are regarded as
classics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally think David has a great career in comedy,''
Manners says. ``He's a very, very funny man and he has impeccable
timing. He could do a Cary Grant thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless he starts enjoying the behind-the-scenes work too much.
After all, when he first started taking acting classes in New York,
he envisioned a screenwriter's or playwright's career. He
reconsidered and went into acting because, he says, ``it was more
fun for a man of the age I was,'' and ``I was probably rebelling in
some way against using my mind too much.''
</P>
<P>
   He's over that now. And it could make a huge difference in his
future. He denies (with a laugh) reports that he was offered $1
million an episode to stay with ``The X-Files'' for another season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, to be honest with you,'' he volunteers, ``the fact that I
can write and direct is really the thing that might keep me coming
back.'' (af)
</P>
</TEXT>
