<SLUG> BC-TENN-EXECUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. COURT STAYS EXECUTIONS OF 2 TENNESSEE PRISONERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two Tennessee inmates who were scheduled to die this
week in back-to-back executions received last-minute reprieves
Tuesday when a federal appellate court ruled that more time was
needed to review their cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a relief,'' said Jim H. Walker, a lawyer for Robert Glen
Coe, who had been scheduled to die at 1 a.m. Wednesday, 15 hours
after the stay was issued. ``We got pretty close.''
</P>
<P>
   Coe would have become the first murderer executed in Tennessee
in 40 years. Tennessee is one of 8 states among the 38 with death
penalty laws that have not executed an inmate since capital
punishment was reinstated in the 1970s. The U.S. Supreme Court
struck down the death penalty as unconstitutionally arbitrary in
1972, thereby commuting the death sentences of 629 inmates. States
then began revising their death penalty laws to satisfy the court's
objections, and Tennessee did so in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the men who were scheduled to die this week were spared,
at least temporarily, by the 6th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals,
which sits in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Coe, who was convicted of raping and murdering an
8-year-old girl in 1979, a three-judge panel of the court ruled
Tuesday morning that the execution should be stayed while it
reviewed whether Coe was mentally competent to be executed. State
law says that an inmate cannot be executed ``if he lacks the mental
capacity to understand the fact of the impending execution and the
reason for it.'' Coe, 43, has a long history of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court also stayed the execution of Philip Ray
Workman, 46, who was convicted of killing a Memphis police officer
in 1981 while fleeing a fast-food restaurant he had robbed. He had
been scheduled to die 24 hours after Coe, at 1 a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Workman's lawyers were also breathing easier Tuesday. ``Talk
about being at death's door,'' said one, Jefferson T. Dorsey,
adding that Workman shared his relief. ``It's the first time I've
seen color in his face in about two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorsey and other lawyers maintain that ballistics evidence that
was not explored at the trial demonstrates that the fatal shot was
most likely fired by another officer, not by Workman. They contend
that Workman was hit over the head while scuffling with police and
involuntarily fired two shots but that neither killed Lt. Ronald
Oliver.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a three-judge panel of the appellate court denied
Workman's request for a hearing to examine new evidence. But the
full court said Tuesday that a majority of its members had voted to
review the case, superseding the decision of the three-judge panel.
Workman's lawyers have until April 17 to file a brief about a
recently discovered X-ray that they believe is exculpatory and
about the recanted testimony of a man who swore at the trial that
he saw Workman fire the fatal shot.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's attorney general, Paul G. Summers, said Tuesday that
his heart went out to the families and friends of the victims. ``We
are disappointed for those people,'' he said in a statement, ``who
expect their justice system to work efficiently in a timely
manner.''
</P>
<P>
   bl
</P>
</TEXT>
