<HEADER>
A7184 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-FALLOUT-FALLOUT_SFCHR     04-04 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALLOUT-FALLOUT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Microsoft Rivals See Opportunity  &HT;     By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Microsoft's rivals in the operating systems market took heart from
the software giant's resounding legal defeat on Monday, and
investors rewarded them with a slight uptick in share price
yesterday.
<P>
   But analysts warned that Microsoft's legal entanglements and
depressed stock price may not lead its competitors to Easy Street.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems, Corel and VA Linux all saw their shares edge
up yesterday, while Microsoft's again declined, in the first full
day of trading after U.S. Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's historic
decision. The judge ruled that Microsoft broke state and federal
antitrust laws to protect its monopoly in operating systems _ the
platform on which other software like Internet browsers and
spreadsheets run.
</P>
<P>
   Investors seemed to agree with the firms who say the ruling
could boost alternatives to Windows such as the Linux operating
system, which is gaining momentum in the Web server market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marketplace was already looking for a choice,'' said Tim
Buckley, chief operating officer at Red Hat of Durham, N.C., which
markets a commercial version of Linux. ``This elevates the issue
(and) helps the alternatives to Microsoft that the consumer may be
looking at.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Red Hat, and Sunnyvale's VA Linux, a maker of
servers and workstations for Linux, have seen a groundswell of
support for the ``open source'' operating system, which, like its
cousin Unix, is generally thought to be speedier and more stable
than Windows.
</P>
<P>
   But software industry analysts warn that Microsoft won't become
an also-ran anytime soon, if ever.
</P>
<P>
   That's because corporate networks are one thing, while consumer
and business desktop machines, where Microsoft owns an a huge chunk
of the market, are quite another.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, there are very few workaday Linux-based
applications like spreadsheets and word processing.
</P>
<P>
   And so far, products like Sun Microsystem's StarOffice, a free
suite of office applications that has been downloaded roughly 2
million times, have yet to eat into Microsoft's 95 percent market
share.
</P>
<P>
   ``I question people who are saying new competition and choice
will happen'' as a result of the ruling,'' said Clay Ryder, an
analyst at Zona Research. ``The thought that Linux will become the
operating system of choice for home users ... that's a bit
far-fetched.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that Linux won't catch on with corporate
users. Red Hat, whose sales tripled last year to $42 million, says
about 30 percent of the servers on the Internet run Linux.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's decision ``allowed the market to question how powerful
Microsoft is,'' said Brian Biles, vice president of marketing at VA
Linux Systems. ``It allowed customers to think (Microsoft) they
 &LR; might be vulnerable after all. That can't do anything but help
us.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Microsoft won't likely sit idly by if Linux creeps into
more high-end corporate networks. The company has made an
aggressive push into the market with its Windows 2000 product, the
newly released successor to NT 4.0.
</P>
<P>
   As the case winds toward the penalty phase and then the appeals
process, the software landscape will remain largely unchanged,
according to Jeff Tarter, editor of SoftLetter, an industry
newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is divided into Microsoft customers and everybody
else, and there happens to be a lot of Microsoft customers and not
a lot of everybody else,'' he said. ``I don't think there are going
to be more than a tiny portion of customers that change their
buying based on this legal decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts admit that could change if the Justice Department
decides to break the company up into smaller pieces made to
function on their own. But even if the judge orders that, the
process will likely be tied up for years in appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Microsoft rivals may just have to hope that the rise
of Internet appliances, gaming consoles and cell phones creates new
opportunities for their wares.
</P>
<P>
   Even then, as it has so many times in the past, Microsoft will
probably make inroads. Recently, the company unveiled a prototype
for the X-Box, a gaming machine due out in late 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past 15 years, everybody has envisioned scenarios
where Microsoft gets killed, and it never happens,'' Tarter said.
``Certainly they have their vulnerabilities. Every company does.
But this is a competitive company. This is not a company that
ignores their vulnerabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Staff writers Carolyn Said and Henry Norr contributed
to this report.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Kelly Zito at kzito(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
