<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7186 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-INVESTORS-INVESTORS_S     04-04 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVESTORS-INVESTORS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Traders Survive Stock Thrill Ride  &HT;     By David Lazarus and Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
``Oh man,'' muttered Paul Berger, a trader at the Pacific
Exchange's options market, as the Nasdaq suddenly reversed course
and rebounded from its worst sell-off ever.
<P>
   Berger had been hammered when the price of Sun Microsystems
plunged an hour or so earlier. Now, after adjusting his positions,
he was equally vulnerable as the Nasdaq clawed its way back to
higher ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``This hasn't been fun,'' he said as the numbers flashed past on
the bank of screens overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone, however, was left reeling as the Nasdaq at one
point yesterday plummeted 574 points, or 13.5 percent, only to
ultimately end trading down just 75 at 4,148.89.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the hundreds of traders on the noisy, crowded options
floor rode out the market tsunami as they embraced the late
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great day,'' said William White as he took a breather
from shouting out orders for America Online options. ``We're
talking about hundreds of thousands of dollars I'm making.''
</P>
<P>
   In his case, White said he just trusted his gut when it came to
timing the bottom of yesterday's midday mid-day  &LR; meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``You sense when the climax is coming,'' he explained. ``Then
you buy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Exchange's options pits in downtown San Francisco
were whirling with frenetic activity throughout the day as traders
rushed to execute orders for clients.
</P>
<P>
   Volume on the options floor was a record 716,000 contracts. On a
typical day last month, exchange officials said, about 489,000
contracts would be logged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twelve thousand COMS at five-eighths!'' one shouted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sell five-eighths Sun!'' yelled another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are those 850s?''
</P>
<P>
   Trader Gregory MacCleave could only shake his head as tried to
keep pace with rapid changes in the price of Micron Technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're on the wrong side of something like this, it's
awful,'' he said. ``This is the biggest move I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as the market was redefining the term ``thrill ride,''
traders still found plenty of opportunities to joke around and blow
off steam. They had a good laugh after one stealthily taped paper
spurs to the heels of a Chronicle reporter.
</P>
<P>
   And they nudged one another when a TV camera approached.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buy!'' they suddenly screamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sell!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all going to hell!''
</P>
<P>
   The camera moved on and the traders shared a good chuckle. Then
it was back to business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sun five-eighths!''
</P>
<P>
   Options trading is definitely a guy thing. Few women were among
those fighting for elbow space in the pits, and most of the men
carried themselves with a hitch-up-your-pants cowboy swagger.
</P>
<P>
   Around the corner on the main floor of the Pacific Exchange,
where stocks rather than options are traded, the mood was
infinitely calmer.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street might have been twisting around like a pretzel, but
the stock traders were doing their best to maintain an even keel.
About 27 million shares changed hands, compared with an average 23
million a day last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no panic on the floor,'' said trader Jonathan Werts.
``There's some anxiety, but no panic.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Nasdaq started tanking, Werts said he quickly sold off
tech stocks. Then he sat back and tried to get a fix on what was
going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the largest sell-off we've ever had on the Nasdaq,''
Werts noted as the index hit bottom. ``It's a hectic job by nature.
On a day like this, it's even more hectic.''
</P>
<P>
   For some traders, the day only worsened as it went along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disaster has struck,'' groaned Brian Fuller as the numbers
changed on his screen. ``This has been pretty ghastly.''
</P>
<P>
   As his losses piled up, he said he could only keep his fingers
crossed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hope it's going to turn around,'' Fuller said. ``Sometimes
it does.'' He gazed at his screen with a stricken expression.
``Today it didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hal Requa, yesterday's action constituted a huge buying
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a typical, massive three- or four-day correction,'' he
said. ``Luckily, we caught the downdraft fairly early.''
</P>
<P>
   Among investors, a similar roll-with-the-punches attitude
prevailed at Charles Schwab's main branch on Montgomery Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bear market _ we're not quite there yet,'' said Al
Karahdian,  &LR; Karahadian, 83, who said he routinely hangs out at
Schwab and watches the ticker scroll past. ``But we're getting very
close.''
</P>
<P>
   He said most of the old-timers like himself were able to take
yesterday's gyrations in stride. But he noted scornfully that
things are different among the younger investors, who ``have been
cockier than hell'' riding tech stocks to stratospheric highs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've never seen a sell-off,'' Karahadian sniffed.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he will probably wade back into the market in
another day or two and pick up some bargains. Others weren't
bothering to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband is upstairs buying right now,'' said Pauline
Maloof, a Florida resident whose visit in San Francisco was put on
hold because of the market's brief collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ben Briggs, a 30-year-old San Francisco jewelry store
owner, seized the opportunity to purchase 200 more shares of 3Com.
``Every time it goes down, I buy more,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Briggs' experience as a market player is brief. He has
invested his life savings in stocks over the past four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the bank, I was making zip,'' he observed. ``In the first
two weeks after I started trading, I made $4,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's barely breaking even.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the options exchange, traders grew increasingly frantic
as the session drew to a close.
</P>
<P>
   Paper littered the floor and shouting erupted intermittently.
Tempers were barely held in check at the Microsoft pit, where a
pair of traders bickered over the price of a sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's typically not this exciting here,'' said trader David
O'Neal. ``When things go down this far, you start getting scared.
But if you start selling, that's panic. That's how you get yourself
into a bad situation.''
</P>
<P>
   He looked around at the crush of last-minute activity as the
closing bell was about to ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drink a lot of coffee around here,'' O'Neal said. ``On a
day like this, you don't need much at all.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail David Lazarus at davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com &QL; 
E-mail Sam Zuckerman at szuckerman(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
