<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NORMAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYONE IS ROOTING FOR NORMAN AT AUGUSTA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ The fans filing through Augusta National Golf
Club's gates Tuesday seemed to have two predominant spring
thoughts: Please don't let it rain and let Greg Norman reign.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn broke drizzly after this city spent Monday night under a
tornado watch, which, contrary to public belief on the PGA Tour
these days is not the same thing as awaiting the arrival of Tiger
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Woods has been a force of nature on the golf course
this year. The 24-year-old has finished first or second in six of
his seven starts (the lone exception being L.A.'s Nissan Open),
making him the prohibitive favorite to win his second green jacket
when the 64th Masters tournament commences Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the patrons' favorite and the sentimental choice of
even a few of the players would appear to be the 45-year-old
Norman, whose window for winning a Masters tournament is closing
fast.
</P>
<P>
   The affable Australian, who has won 74 tournaments worldwide,
including two British Opens, readily admits Augusta National Golf
Club has this week and next year to settle its considerable debt
with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Realistically,'' he said, ``in the next two years if I stay
focused, then I can perform.''
</P>
<P>
   He has performed well here before, only to have victory elude
him every which way. He was stomped by a charging 46-year-old Jack
Nicklaus in 1986, stunned by Larry Mize's 140-foot chip-in on the
second extra hole in 1987 and strangled by his own hand in 1996.
That was the year Norman frittered away a six-stroke lead with a
closing six-over-par 78 to hand the tournament to Nick Faldo.
</P>
<P>
   Norman has come close here so many times, it's a wonder he
hasn't changed his company's logo from a shark to a horseshoe.
</P>
<P>
   The gracious way he handled his collapse in 1996 elevated him in
the eyes of the badge-holding patrons. As he walked the packed
grounds Tuesday, voices in the crowd cried out, ``This is your
year, Greg,'' and ``We love you, Greg.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Woods oozed empathy for his rival, saying, ``You know, it's
a shame that he hasn't won (here) because he's such a great player.
It's tough for me to imagine somebody going through all the
(heartbreaks) he has had here and coming back again and again and
putting himself in that position.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman insists he doesn't step on Augusta National's grounds and
die a little, remembering all her slights. ``I can walk to every
hole and remember the good shots I hit on that hole,'' he said. ``I
don't let ... the negative energy of this place pollute my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Jose-Maria Olazabal, who answered Norman's
finishing kick last year with a better one of his own, is hoping
good karma follows Norman around the course like his biggest fan.
``I want to see Greg win the Masters,'' Olazabal said. ``Then I
think he can retire in peace.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
