u i BC-JAPAN-OBUCHI-REACT-1S     04-04 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-OBUCHI-REACT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-395&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MANY JAPANESE, SECRECY AND POLITICS ARE INSEPARABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EXPANDS 5th graf to sum up Japanese reaction) 
(See also JAPAN-POLITICS) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Their prime minister was lying in the intensive care
unit of a local hospital, kept alive by a respirator.
</P>
<P>
   The media was full of stories about how their elected
representatives had lied about the gravity of his condition in
order to put in place a succession plan before critics could raise
their voices. The very legitimacy and credibility of their
political system had been thrown into question.
</P>
<P>
   But the Japanese people barely shrugged. ``I am from Kagoshima
prefecture, where a former governor collapsed and the prefectural
officials hid it for some time,'' said Yoshiko Sano, a 48-year-old
housewife hurrying through Ginza, Tokyo's premier shopping
district, who described herself as a ``typical'' Japanese.
``Everything here is always hidden behind a veil, which means that
even if they make timely announcements, I am doubtful about the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The sudden stroke that put a sudden end to Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi's tenure and focused world attention yet again on the
back-room horse-trading that determines how this country _ the
world's second-largest in terms of economic muscle _ functions
politically has elicited little more than a shrug from most
Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   The sense of outrage that in the West might have greeted the
deliberate obfuscation that surrounded Obuchi's illness and the
peremptory manner in which elders of the ruling Liberal Democratic
Party determined his successor was treated as business as usual by
Japanese interviewed on the streets. Judging by their reactions,
some Japanese were clearly pleased that stability and process were
being protected, even if it was at the expense of full disclosure.
Other simply dismissed the fog that surrounds Obuchi's health as
the sort of thing that they have come to expect. ``Hiding important
things is done everyday,'' said Reiko Inoue, a 49-year-old
housewife. ``And it doesn't matter who becomes prime minister.
Nothing will change.''
</P>
<P>
   Some even expressed a bit of understanding about the way news of
Obuchi's tragedy has been handled by the political leadership. ``I
suspect that they may be concealing a lot more, but there are a lot
of things probably only the insiders can understand,'' said Kiyoshi
Kojima, a 54-year-old salary man. ``You know we salarymen, even
among ourselves, there are a lot of things that are hard to explain
to outsiders.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many had assumed from the beginning that they were being lied
to. Obuchi fell ill after a meeting with Ichiro Ozawa, the leader
of one of the ruling party's coalition partners who has a
well-known history of ``kumogakurei,'' literally ``hiding behind
the clouds,'' when faced with adversity. Ozawa had told Obuchi that
he and several members of his party intended to abandon the
coalition, and many people assumed that the prime minister had
simply reached into Ozawa's bag of tricks and done a disappearing
act in response to the bad news.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first heard the news that he was in the hospital, I
doubted that it was really true,'' said Masashi Higuchi, 30, who
works at a trading company. ``I suspected he had simply fled to the
hospital to hide after his meeting with Ozawa.''
</P>
<P>
   Makiko Ezoe, 24, said she initially assumed the same thing.
``When I heard his secretary had said he didn't know where he was,
I thought of Ozawa and his habit of kumogakurei,'' she said. ``But
then I had second thoughts. Mr. Obuchi is not the kind of person
who would do that. He seems too kind-hearted.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, several of those interviewed expressed a tender fondness
for their soon-to-be former prime minister that was often lost in
characterizations of him that compared him to ``cold pizza'' and an
``oji-san,'' or old, bumbling man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that Mr. Obuchi was really kind and gentle to the
people around him,'' said Goro Takano, 33, a literature major at a
local university. ``Probably his life was shortened because he
worried too much about taking care of others. In that sense, I feel
sorry for him.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, many yearned for a different kind of
leader, someone less concerned with the traditional effort to
promote consensus and harmony and more of an activist, someone more
like Tokyo Governor Shintaro Ishihara. ``Personally, I want someone
like Ishihara, who has strong leadership and solid beliefs,''
Higuchi said.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshiro Mori, the secretary-general of the ruling party and the
man widely reported to be Obuchi's successor, is a polar opposite
of Ishihara, whose recent success in passing a bill that will levy
a special tax on big banks has made him something of a folk hero
among city residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want somebody who is young and fresh and can exercise
leadership to replace Mr. Obuchi,'' said Shinji Yamada, a
55-year-old salaryman. ``But I can't have such great expectations
about Mr. Mori. There's nothing new and fresh about him.''
</P>
<P>
   (JS/BL)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
