<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7198 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-MASTERS-ELDER05-C     04-04 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-ELDER05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Path Elder opened hardly used
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga., _ Twenty-five years ago, Lee Elder became the
first black man to play the old South's favorite golf tournament,
the Masters. At that same tournament, Rod Curl joined the field as
the breakthrough American Indian. The place that celebrates all the
colors of spring had begun indulging the human spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   In the year 2000, Tiger Woods is the one player of
African-American lineage in the field. Notah Begay the solitary
Native American. Vijay Singh is another player of color; and there,
quickly as that, we have finished the diversity roll call.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a tribute to the immutable nature of Augusta
National and the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   The trailblazer returns _ greatly honored _ only to find that
the trail he blazed is going virtually unused. If the
groundskeeping wasn't so good around here, there'd be weeds and
vines choking the path that Elder cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to see more (minority players) here today,'' said
Elder, ``but it just so happens that we don't have any that's in a
position to qualify here.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor are there many applicants on the horizon. ``I don't see any
who really has the game to come out, be productive and be able to
qualify. I think it's going to take some time,'' he said. Elder's
65 now, with time no longer such a friend.
</P>
<P>
   For those keeping score at home, there is one black player on
the developmental Buy.com Tour. And one African-American woman on
the LPGA Tour. Elder's legacy and Woods' popularity have yet to
translate into a tidal wave of participation. The economic and
cultural barriers to golf clearly have not been overcome at the
highest levels.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the future Elder had hoped for when he made the
first nervous drive down Magnolia Lane in 1975. Over his lifetime
he had known a ``Caucasian-only'' clause in the bylaws of the PGA
of America (repealed in 1961). He had seen the Masters pressured by
Congress to invite him to the tournament, but much more
meaningfully, Elder would earn his way there. At a tournament site
where six years before he had been refused entrance to the
clubhouse _ the Pensacola Country Club _ Elder won the 1974
Monsanto Open and his Masters invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Elder tells of sweaty palms on his first drive up Magnolia Lane.
Death threats had followed his victory in Pensacola, and a natural
suspicion accompanied him through the gates. ``I really felt it was
a racist place in the fact that they had not invited a black. Very
few blacks had even been around the Masters, besides the waiters
and caddies,'' Elder has said.
</P>
<P>
   He tells of trembling on the first tee. How could he not? Elder
was not allowed the luxury of being a mere 40-year-old Masters
rookie. He was a symbol.
</P>
<P>
   Strangely, missing the cut in the first of his six Masters
appearances, was what helped assure Elder he belonged here. ``I had
more people come up to me and say, `Lee, that was a magnificent job
you did. Just because you didn't play good golf doesn't mean you're
not a good person or have a good character.'''
</P>
<P>
   Inside these gates, Elder found the Masters experience
everything it should be. He said he was treated with all due
respect, even warmly greeted by the late Clifford Roberts, the
tournament's hard-edged chairman. Now, he is regarded as an
important historical figure, who just had to be on the grounds
during Woods' 1997 victory march.
</P>
<P>
   On this anniversary of his first Masters appearance, he'll be
honored by the Golf Writers Association of America tonight, then
spend the rest of the weekend at the tournament with his family.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Woods will command his attention. But Elder also is
keen for perhaps the whitest man in the field. ``I think it's high
time for Davis (Love III) to come to the top here,'' he said. There
is a beautiful balance in this little corner of golf.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
