<HEADLINE>
DUCKS LOOK AHEAD, NOT BEHIND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Mighty Ducks play game No.80 of the season tonight
in Chicago with their playoff hopes hanging by a thread.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim would be in much better position had it not lost to the
likes of Tampa Bay and the New York Islanders this season and
squandered some third-period advantages, especially during one
stretch in February.
</P>
<P>
   However, coach Craig Hartsburg says now is certainly not the
time to be looking back.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are in the middle of something, you can't look at the
things you have done wrong or should have done,'' he said. ``That's
for when the season is over _ that's when you look at the areas
that hurt you and you need to fix _ and hopefully that is not for a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   PUTTING ON PRESSURE: The Ducks will begin their final three
games several hours ahead of the teams they are battling with, and
they hope to put some pressure on their rivals by posting early
wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to do what we have to do and make them feel the
pressure,'' said defenseman Oleg Tverdovsky, who knows one loss
will likely end the Ducks' postseason hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim captain Paul Kariya, as usual, had the most logical
response when asked if playing early is an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have got to win whether you play before or after them,''
he said. ``It's the same with them, they have to take care of their
own business too.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
