<HEADER>
A7205 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-COMMUNICATIONS-DEAL-N     04-04 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMMUNICATIONS-DEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 PHONE GIANTS SAID TO BE NEAR DEAL TO MERGE WIRELESS UNITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Exclusive) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hoping to create a national giant in wireless communications,
BellSouth and SBC Communications are near a deal to merge their
North American wireless operations, executives close to the
negotiations said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The companies' boards were scheduled to meet Tuesday night to
approve the deal, the executives said, and the companies hope to
announce the agreement as soon as Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth and SBC, which does business as Ameritech, Pacific
Bell and Southwestern Bell, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   After years of fragmentation, the wireless communications
business is now in a period of furious consolidation. As wireless
companies merge and form wide-ranging joint ventures, they are
searching mostly to expand their geographic reach.
</P>
<P>
   Controlling a national network allows a wireless carrier to
attract customers looking to use their cellular phone across the
nation. But at least as important, a nationwide system also allows
carriers to achieve economies of scale in advertising and marketing
and allows them to reduce the ``roaming'' fees they pay when their
customers use other carriers' systems.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth and SBC, both created in the breakup of the American
Telephone and Telegraph Co. in 1984, are each titans in the local
telephone business. SBC, the No. 1 local phone company, is the main
local carrier from Illinois to Texas and also in California.
BellSouth is the dominant local phone company from the Carolinas to
Florida to Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   But neither company's wireless operation yet enjoys national
scope. By merging, the combined BellSouth-SBC wireless unit,
concentrated in the fast-growing Sun Belt, would be able to serve
more than half the nation's population.
</P>
<P>
   The combined wireless unit would serve more than 16 million
total subscribers and would have annual revenue of more than $8
billion. Based on the valuations that investors have given other
wireless companies, the combined unit would probably have a market
value of at least $60 billion were it publicly traded.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the deal said that BellSouth and SBC do intend
to offer stock in the new unit to the public, though perhaps not
until early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Bell Atlantic and Vodafone AirTouch PLC reached a
similar deal to merge their U.S. wireless operations and on Monday,
Bell Atlantic announced that it would call the new venture Verizon
Wireless. Tuesday, the new Bell Atlantic-Vodafone operation said it
would sell stock to the public but did not say when the initial
offering would take place or how much stock would be put up for
sale.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the numbers are likely to be big for both Verizon
and the combined BellSouth-SBC unit. Last week, AT&AMP;T said that it
intended to raise up to $13.2 billion when it sold new shares meant
to track its national wireless operation. AT&AMP;T's offering will
probably take place late this month.
</P>
<P>
   Because federal rules do not allow one company to own multiple
major wireless licenses in any given market, Bell Atlantic,
Vodafone and GTE, which has agreed to be acquired by Bell Atlantic,
have faced the prospect of shedding broad swaths of their
overlapping wireless properties. SBC dealt with the same issue
after it agreed to acquire Ameritech; SBC and Ameritech were
wireless competitors in markets including Chicago and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   It would take months for SBC and BellSouth to win regulatory
approval for their joint venture, but they would not face nearly as
much of a divestiture problem because the two companies' wireless
units do not overlap much, analysts said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   What will overlap, however, are the two companies' management
roles. According to executives close to the talks, SBC and
BellSouth will have equal power over management decisions in their
new venture, overseeing a single chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   That is something of a departure for SBC, which has
traditionally preferred to control its ventures outright. But
BellSouth insisted that it not be a junior partner to SBC,
executives close to the talks said, and in the end SBC agreed to
share control.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the first time the two companies had had that
discussion. Before SBC agreed to acquire Ameritech in 1998, SBC had
in fact preferred the idea of acquiring BellSouth, according to
people close to those discussions. But BellSouth would not sell and
Ameritech would.
</P>
<P>
   In the new wireless venture, SBC will control 60 percent of the
economic interest while BellSouth will control 40 percent,
reflecting the fact that SBC's existing wireless business is bigger
than BellSouth's, according to an executive close to the talks.
</P>
<P>
   One person close to the deal said that SBC and BellSouth had not
yet decided on a chief executive for the new operation. The person
added that SBC and BellSouth intended to form a new brand for the
new unit, but said the companies had not yet created it.
</P>
<P>
   The new wireless venture, which is to involve the companies'
wireless holdings both in the United States and the Caribbean, is
set to include not only wireless telephone systems but also
wireless data networks. BellSouth controls the national network
used by the new Palm VII handheld computer.
</P>
<P>
   mk
</P>
</TEXT>
