   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Tuesday, 04/04/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT44) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- GUN-DEALER -- Anthony
Imperato's family owns the oldest gun shop in New York City.
Growing up in Bensonhurt, Imperato said, he and his father, Louis,
never once went hunting. ``We didn't shoot at targets. None of our
hobbies ever involved guns. Guns were a job. Maybe the guys who run
Lobel's meat market are, you know, vegetarians. You never know.''
(Frances Roberts/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT43) NEWARK, N.J. -- April 4, 2000 -- NJ-NEWARK-RESTORE --
The 70-year-old 34-story building at 744 Broad Street - the tallest
building in Newark - is a sentinel on the far reaches of the city's
revival. Its ability to attract tenants is seen as a test of the
city's recovery from its 30-year economic doldrums. (Fred R.
Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT42) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9 --
HAYLEY-MILLS-THEATER -- Hayley Mills has been working the London
stage for the last 30 years. But in this country she is still best
known as the saucer-eyed little girl in such popular Disney films
as ``Pollyanna'' (for which she won a special 1960 Academy Award)
and ``The Parent Trap.'' The London-born actress, who turns 54 next
week, opens Monday at Manhattan's Lucille Lortel Theater in ``Noel
Coward's Suite in Two Keys,'' an evening of two one-act plays
directed by John Tillinger. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT41) UNDATED -- April 4, 2000 -- OBIT-BECK -- Bertram M.
Beck, a longtime leader in social work and for 10 years the head of
the Henry Street Settlement in New York City, died Monday at
Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in Manhattan. He was 82,
lived on Roosevelt Island and had a vacation home on Fire Island.
(The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) PIEDMONT, Ala. -- April 4, 2000 -- ALA-TORNADO-2 -- On
Monday, Waylon Motes went through what's left of the trailer home
his grandmother, Annie Surrett, had lived in near Piedmont. Surrett
was killed Sunday night when a tornado lifted her home from its
moorings and deposited it across the road. The tornado was rated an
F2 by the National Weather Service. (Grant Blankenship/The Gadsden
Times)
</P>
