<P>
   (NYT35) HOLLYWOOD -- April 4, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9 --
DUCHOVNY-FILMS -- Is film David Duchovny's future? Or can he never
escape the identification with Mulder from ``The X-Files,'' a
strangely emotionless man obsessed by government conspiracies,
space aliens and his sister? Is he a truly talented actor or just a
really lucky guy who got cast as the one character he was born to
play? ``I feel good about doing movies,'' he says. ``I feel like
I'm just beginning that part of my career, which seems weird at
what I feel to be an advanced age.'' He is 39, facing his 40th
birthday in August. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) UNDATED -- April 4, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9 --
BLACK-PHOTOGRAPHERS-B&AMP;W -- ``Easter Sunday in Harlem,'' a 1939
image by Morgan and Marvin Smith, is part of ``Reflections in
Black: A History of Black Photographers, 1840 to the Present,'' an
exhibition through June 30 at the Arts and Industries building of
the Smithsonian Institution. At various times, but especially in
the first several decades of the 20th century, American blacks used
photography to resist the image the dominant culture imposed on
them. (Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
