<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- STOREBOUGHT -- A chocolate
cup filled with mousse at Black Hound and a meringue disk with
sorbet from Payard Patisserie. Why cook every course? There's no
stigma in storebought appetizers or desserts. (Frances Roberts,
top, Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WINDSOR, Vt. -- April 4, 2000 -- PARRISH-LANDSCAPE-BOS --
Maxfield Parrish's landscape painting hangs near where bank tellers
conduct business at the Chittenden National Bank. Try to take the
Maxfield Parrish painting from this little branch office and , as
one art gallery discovered last winter, you'll face the wrath of a
town. Such is the affection Windsor's 4,000 residents hold for the
early 20th-century illustrator. And such is their determination to
keep the painting, even if they have to fight the waves of
commerce. (Barry Chin/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- SAND-BOILED-COFFEE -- Making
coffee may not be rocket science, but the way it is done at Avra, a
new Greek restaurant in Midtown, it looks like an archaeological
dig in the desert. Nikos Mavreas prepares the coffee which involves
heating sand. (William Lopez/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- April 4, 2000 -- GEFILTE-BOOK-REVIEW -- ``The
Gefilte Variations'' by Jayne Cohen. The book reveals the author's
frequently playful approach to Jewish food. Though there are riffs
on gefilte fish, including versions made with salmon and even one
using chicken, they are just one element in a book that reworks
typical Jewish cooking with improvisational flair. (Tony
Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- April 4, 2000 -- ASPARAGUS-EATING-WELL -- The
fresh bright spring flavor of asparagus is at its peak from March
to May. This is the time of year for people who don't want to load
up on cream and butter to make things taste good. Naked asparagus
spears rival peanuts for their can't-eat-just-one quality, but they
have even more advantages for good eating. (Tony Cenicola/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- SERVING-SOUP -- The spring
pea soup served at Quince. Unlike many pleasures of restaurant
dining, the technique of serving a hansome soup is perfect for
entertaining at home. The garnishes can be arranged on the plates
hours ahead and the soup should be served hot at the table from a
tureen or a pitcher, without the risk of sloshing over a shallow
rim on the way to the dining room. (Tony Cenicola/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- April 4, 2000 -- CHARD -- Both the leaves and
stems of red chard and its white-stemmed cousin are edible. Chard
leaves can be used in most recipes calling for spinach (salads are
the exception, since chard leaves are too tough to eat raw), but
the ``chard equals spinach'' formula ignores the fact that the
stems of the two vegetables are very different. Spinach stems are
stringy and fibrous and don't make very good eating. Chard stems
have a delicious, earthy flavor and a distinctive texture that is
silky and meaty when cooked. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
