<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Tuesday, 04/04/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT44) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- GUN-DEALER -- Anthony
Imperato's family owns the oldest gun shop in New York City.
Growing up in Bensonhurt, Imperato said, he and his father, Louis,
never once went hunting. ``We didn't shoot at targets. None of our
hobbies ever involved guns. Guns were a job. Maybe the guys who run
Lobel's meat market are, you know, vegetarians. You never know.''
(Frances Roberts/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT43) NEWARK, N.J. -- April 4, 2000 -- NJ-NEWARK-RESTORE --
The 70-year-old 34-story building at 744 Broad Street - the tallest
building in Newark - is a sentinel on the far reaches of the city's
revival. Its ability to attract tenants is seen as a test of the
city's recovery from its 30-year economic doldrums. (Fred R.
Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT42) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9 --
HAYLEY-MILLS-THEATER -- Hayley Mills has been working the London
stage for the last 30 years. But in this country she is still best
known as the saucer-eyed little girl in such popular Disney films
as ``Pollyanna'' (for which she won a special 1960 Academy Award)
and ``The Parent Trap.'' The London-born actress, who turns 54 next
week, opens Monday at Manhattan's Lucille Lortel Theater in ``Noel
Coward's Suite in Two Keys,'' an evening of two one-act plays
directed by John Tillinger. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT41) UNDATED -- April 4, 2000 -- OBIT-BECK -- Bertram M.
Beck, a longtime leader in social work and for 10 years the head of
the Henry Street Settlement in New York City, died Monday at
Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in Manhattan. He was 82,
lived on Roosevelt Island and had a vacation home on Fire Island.
(The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) PIEDMONT, Ala. -- April 4, 2000 -- ALA-TORNADO-2 -- On
Monday, Waylon Motes went through what's left of the trailer home
his grandmother, Annie Surrett, had lived in near Piedmont. Surrett
was killed Sunday night when a tornado lifted her home from its
moorings and deposited it across the road. The tornado was rated an
F2 by the National Weather Service. (Grant Blankenship/The Gadsden
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) PIEDMONT, Ala. -- April 4, 2000 -- ALA-TORNADO -- Metal
from a trailer home sits twisted around a tree in a neighboring
yard at the site of a tornado touchdown in the Vigo community near
Piedmont on Monday. The tornado, which struck Sunday night, was
rated an F2 by the National Weather Service. (Grant Blankenship/The
Gadsden Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9 --
WILD-PARTY-THEATER -- Toni Collette as Queenie and Mandy Patinkin
as Burrs in ``The Wild Party'' which explores one not so-atypical
night in the '20s. No era is so fully identified with its parties
(and no parties seem to have been wilder). (Sara Krulwich/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) IGUALA, Mexico -- April 4, 2000 -- MEXICO-ENVIRON --
Rodolfo Montiel, 44, who organized a protest by peasants against
logging in the mountains north of Acapulco, at the federal
penitentiary at Iguala where he is being held pending trial on
drugs and weapons charges. But last Friday, Amnesty International
declared Montiel to be a prisoner of conscience. And on Wednesday,
a San Francisco foundation will award him with a $125,000
environmental prize. ``The only award I've gotten from the
government is prison, so I don't know quite what to think about
this prize from foreigners,'' he said. (Sam Dillon/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9 --
OM-PURI-FILMS -- Om Puri, in SoHo last month, plays a Pakistani
Muslim married to an Englishwoman in 1970s Manchester in ``East Is
East.'' Although Om Puri has appeared, by his own estimate, in
something like 140 films in his 24-year screen career and has been
characterized by one expert on Indian cinema as ``the finest actor
of the post-independence generation,'' he is still far from a
household name in the United States. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) HOLLYWOOD -- April 4, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9 --
DUCHOVNY-FILMS -- Is film David Duchovny's future? Or can he never
escape the identification with Mulder from ``The X-Files,'' a
strangely emotionless man obsessed by government conspiracies,
space aliens and his sister? Is he a truly talented actor or just a
really lucky guy who got cast as the one character he was born to
play? ``I feel good about doing movies,'' he says. ``I feel like
I'm just beginning that part of my career, which seems weird at
what I feel to be an advanced age.'' He is 39, facing his 40th
birthday in August. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) UNDATED -- April 4, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9 --
BLACK-PHOTOGRAPHERS-B&AMP;W -- ``Easter Sunday in Harlem,'' a 1939
image by Morgan and Marvin Smith, is part of ``Reflections in
Black: A History of Black Photographers, 1840 to the Present,'' an
exhibition through June 30 at the Arts and Industries building of
the Smithsonian Institution. At various times, but especially in
the first several decades of the 20th century, American blacks used
photography to resist the image the dominant culture imposed on
them. (Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) UNDATED -- April 4, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9 --
FACT-FICTION-ART-2 -- An Andy Warhol ``Brillo Box'' from 1968, part
of an exhibition, titled ``Fact/Fiction: Contemporary Art That
Walks the Line,'' at the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art through
next Sunday. The exhibit draws on the museum's permanent holdings
and the vast collection of Vicki and Kent Logan, a local couple who
have given or promised more than 300 works to the museum. (San
Francisco Museum of Modern Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) UNDATED -- April 4, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9 --
FACT-FICTION-ART-1 -- Yasumasa Morimura in his ``Mona Lisa in the
Third Place'' (1998), part of an exhibition, titled ``Fact/Fiction:
Contemporary Art That Walks the Line,'' at the San Francisco Museum
of Modern Art through next Sunday. Morimura's exhibitionism seems
like an inevitable outgrowth of his earlier works' more discreet
campiness, fired by the same desire to reinvent the world rather
than merely comment on it. (San Francisco Museum of Modern Art/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) UNDATED -- April 4, 2000 -- WINE-TALK -- Argentina is
one of the great wine-producing nations, right up there after
France, Spain, Italy and Spain. But hardly anyone knows this. Well,
maybe a few people do, but they are mostly in Argentina. Why?
Because it was a closed-in country, an economic and political
basket case for 40 years. Until now. Bodegas Etchart's Rio de Plata
wines are a good value at around $7 a bottle. (Tony Cenicola/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- SUPREMES -- Diana Ross,
center, with two other former members of the Supremes, Lynda
Laurence, left, and Scherrie Payne, right, at a news conference at
Grand Central Terminal on Tuesday. The trio is to tour arenas this
summer with two singers who joined the Supremes after Ross left the
group in 1970. The reconstituted Supremes will perform the original
group's '60s hits during an arena tour, starting June 14 in
Philadelphia. (Ruby Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- DINNER-PARTY -- The
dinner-party instinct is irrational. More often than not,
entertaining involves blood, sweat and tears, and can be a one-way
ticket to recrimination and regret. For the guests, of course, it's
a sweet deal. They bring a bottle of wine or a bouquet and they're
inside the velvet rope, ready for a stress-free evening of food and
wine. A tarte flambee was the inspiration for the author's dinner
party. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) PORTLAND, Ore. -- April 4, 2000 -- DOTCOM-FAMILIES -- In
the dot-com world, peopled largely by 20-somethings and
30-whatevers, an increasing number of chief executives are turning
to their parents to tap into their elders' experience. Gregory P.
Sullivan, center, with his father, Kevin, left, and stepfather,
Robert Gilbert. Fifteen months ago, the younger Sullivan, 34, hired
his father, 58, to help him launch an Internet company called
Flagship Communications, specializing in e-support and
telemarketing services. (Herb Swanson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- DISABILITY-WORKPLACE --
Susan Barters is a customer service representative at Unum
Provident, a disability and life insurance company. ``I live with
multiple sclerosis, so when I roll into work, my fellow employees
sometimes have to tell me to slow down and yell for people nearby
to watch their toes,'' she wrote. ``I don't show fear or that I'm
different in any way. I just happen to be sitting. It comes across
to my boss, my co-workers and clients that I don't take guff from
anyone.'' (Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) ALBANY, Ore. -- April 4, 2000 -- ORE-ADOPTION-RECORDS-2
-- A law giving any adult adoptees access to their birth records
has been stayed since its approval in 1998 by Oregon voters as a
result of legal challenges from six anonymous birth mothers. The
case will soon be heard by the Oregon supreme court. Bob Whalley,
an adoptee, wants information on his biological parents. (Shane
Young/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- STOCKS-MARKETPLACE-2 --
Frenzied activity on the floor of the Nasdaq 100 futures pit at The
Chicago Mercantile Exchange, Tuesday. Midway through one of the
weirdest and wildest days in stock market history, the Nasdaq
composite index had plunged 634.31 points, shearing 13.6 percent
off its value. Had it closed there, it would have been the worst
one-day decline in Nasdaq history. But a flood of buying rescued
the composite, bringing it to close with a loss of only 1.72
percent on the day. (Steve Kagan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- April 4, 2000 -- DAVE-THOMAS -- Dave Thomas
is founder and senior chairman of the board of Wendy's
International Inc., the fast-food restaurant chain. ``At my
restaurants, we are one big family,'' he wrote. ``That's your
success: when you have happy people having fun. It's pretty
exciting.'' (Wendy's/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) ALBANY, Ore. -- April 4, 2000 -- ORE-ADOPTION-RECORDS --
A law giving any adult adoptees access to their birth records has
been stayed since its approval in 1998 by Oregon voters as a result
of legal challenges from six anonymous birth mothers. The case will
soon be heard by the Oregon supreme court. Berry Price, an adoptee,
wants information on his biological parents. (Shane Young/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) HUANUCO, Peru -- April 4, 2000 -- PERU-POLITICS --
Alejandro Toledo, running for president of Peru, during a campaign
rally on Saturday. Toledo, who is giving President Alberto Fujimori
the toughest political battle of his life, is attracting votes from
disaffected urban lower class voters who are rejecting the
traditional ruling elites. (Ana Cecilia Gonzales-Vigil/The New York
Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- April 4, 2000 -- CLINTON-INTERNET --
President Clinton stops to thank David Mercer, of Mercer and
Associates, for his work in calling for an increase in
collaboration between the public and private sectors in making the
Internet more accessible to less affluent Americans, Tuesday at the
White House. Clinton called on the private sector to help close
what he characterizes is the ``digital divide'' between Americans
accessing the Internet through their home computers, and those left
out because they cannot afford the technology. (Paul Hosefros/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) UNDATED -- April 4, 2000 -- HUMAN-FILM-REVIEW -- Jalil
Lespert, left, and Jean-Claude Vallod in ``Human Resources.'' The
film slowly and deliberately spirals its ingenuous hero down a
treacherous rabbit hole of duplicity and corporate politics at a
French factory, and eventually threatens to put him and his father
on opposite sides of a war between management and labor. As
directed by Laurent Cantet, the film explores class differences,
corporate behavior, labor relations and father-son strife with an
unusual depth and subtlety. (Film Society of Lincoln Center/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- NY-UMBRELLA-SHOP-2 --
Robert Gaumond, an employee at Uncle Sam Unmbrellas and Canes,
showing John Wilson, a 30-year customer, a sturdy model. The store,
thought to be the last of its kind in New York, is closing after
134 years. Over the years, its owner and employees say, the store
has counted presidents, performers and writers among its clientele.
(Richard Perry/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- NY-UMBRELLA-SHOP-1 -- Maybe
it will never rain again. That is probably the only thing that
could console the regular customers at what is thought to be the
city's last umbrella store, Uncle Sam Umbrellas and Canes, which is
to close next Tuesday after 144 years. Over the years, its owner
and employees say, the store has counted presidents, performers and
writers among its clientele. (Richard Perry/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- MARKETPLACE -- People look
through the window at the Nasdaq Marketsite on Times Square,
Tuesday. Midway through one of the weirdest and wildest days in
stock market history, the Nasdaq composite index had plunged over
633 points, shearing 13.6 percent off its value. Had it closed
there, it would have been the worst one-day decline in Nasdaq
history. What stock market investors wanted to know after Tuesday's
bizarre bungee-jump in share prices was, what did it signify? (Fred
R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- April 4, 2000 -- SONG-FILM-REVIEW-B&AMP;W -- Anna
Simpson in ``Our Song,'' Jim McKay's drama about three young women
growing up in Brooklyn. In the course of the film, which moves with
the ease and warmth of its season and place, Lanisha, Jocelyn and
Maria face the usual dilemmas and frustrations of teenage life in
America - and in the movies - today. But ``Our Song'' is so unlike
most Hollywood coming-of-age stories as to seem downright
revolutionary. (Film Society of Lincoln Center/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- April 4, 2000 -- EUROPE-1900-B&AMP;W --
Exhibitions in Amsterdam, London and Paris are currently
celebrating the art of 1900. The aim of this year's shows is to
convey something of the mood of the times. And there was indeed
much going on in 1900, nowhere more than in Paris. A bronze
decorative sculpture by Rene Lalique, made for the Exposition
Universelle in Paris in 1900, is on display in ``1900,'' the
current show at the Grand Palais in Paris. (Kunstgewerbemuseum,
Berlin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) HUNTINGTON, N.Y. -- April 4, 2000 -- NY-GIULIANI-MCCAIN
-- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York, right, and Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., who has suspended his run for the Republican presidential
nomination, during a town hall meeting at the American Legion Post,
Tuesday. Calling him his ``soul mate,'' McCain urged New Yorkers to
elect Giuliani in order to help reform big-money politics. (Ozier
Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9 --
OLSHER-RADIO-SHOW -- Dean Olsher, who will have a new hour-long
show, ``The Next Big Thing,'' on WNYC this summer, has been hooked
on radio since he was a boy. ``It will be about anything,'' said
Olsher, a former cultural correspondent for National Public Radio.
Not about the next big thing? ``No,'' he said, laughing, ``the
title is ironic.'' (Angel Franco/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- April 4, 2000 -- CENSUS-STATUS -- Census
Bureau Director Kenneth Prewitt holds a news briefing on the status
of Census 2000 operations before a map showing the percentage of
returned forms from each city, Tuesday. According to a report
released Monday by the Census Monitoring Board, the once-a-decade
count was going well in spite of criticism from citizens and some
congressional Republicans that the Census Bureau was asking too
intrusive questions. (Justin Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- April 4, 2000 -- SPRING-FLOATER -- Tulips
on Capitol Hill are in bloom near the statue of President James
Garfield, Tuesday. (Justin Lane/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- ANGLER-ARTIST-2 -- The
contents of a box designed by Sidney Neff which contains fishing
treasures at the Museum of Natural History. Neff, who calls himself
a piscatorial bibliophile, has taken his personal library of rare
books on fishing and, using the book binder's art he took up 20
years ago, transformed them into desktop fishing expeditions. By
picking up one of Neff's works, the ``reader'' literally opens a
series of doors to explore an elegantly tooled world of trout,
insects, and iris-lined river banks, all wrought in dyed African
leathers, Japanese paper, and gold. (Librado Romero/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- ANGLER-ARTIST-1 -- Sidney
Neff with the cover of one of his boxes which contains fishing
equipment, during a recent interview at the Museum of Natural
History. Neff, who calls himself a piscatorial bibliophile, has
taken his personal library of rare books on fishing and, using the
book binder's art he took up 20 years ago, transformed them into
desktop fishing expeditions. By picking up one of Neff's works, the
``reader'' literally opens a series of doors to explore an
elegantly tooled world of trout, insects, and iris-lined river
banks, all wrought in dyed African leathers, Japanese paper, and
gold. (Librado Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- RESTAURANTS-PRIVATE-ROOMS --
Vine, a restaurant in the financial district, has private rooms in
bank vaults once owned by J.P. Morgan. It used to be that private
rooms were the exclusive domain of the rich and well connected. But
today, as the economic boom continues, restaurants at all levels
are building private rooms of all descriptions. (Barbara Alper/The
New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- STOREBOUGHT -- A chocolate
cup filled with mousse at Black Hound and a meringue disk with
sorbet from Payard Patisserie. Why cook every course? There's no
stigma in storebought appetizers or desserts. (Frances Roberts,
top, Rebecca Cooney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WINDSOR, Vt. -- April 4, 2000 -- PARRISH-LANDSCAPE-BOS --
Maxfield Parrish's landscape painting hangs near where bank tellers
conduct business at the Chittenden National Bank. Try to take the
Maxfield Parrish painting from this little branch office and , as
one art gallery discovered last winter, you'll face the wrath of a
town. Such is the affection Windsor's 4,000 residents hold for the
early 20th-century illustrator. And such is their determination to
keep the painting, even if they have to fight the waves of
commerce. (Barry Chin/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- SAND-BOILED-COFFEE -- Making
coffee may not be rocket science, but the way it is done at Avra, a
new Greek restaurant in Midtown, it looks like an archaeological
dig in the desert. Nikos Mavreas prepares the coffee which involves
heating sand. (William Lopez/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- April 4, 2000 -- GEFILTE-BOOK-REVIEW -- ``The
Gefilte Variations'' by Jayne Cohen. The book reveals the author's
frequently playful approach to Jewish food. Though there are riffs
on gefilte fish, including versions made with salmon and even one
using chicken, they are just one element in a book that reworks
typical Jewish cooking with improvisational flair. (Tony
Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- April 4, 2000 -- ASPARAGUS-EATING-WELL -- The
fresh bright spring flavor of asparagus is at its peak from March
to May. This is the time of year for people who don't want to load
up on cream and butter to make things taste good. Naked asparagus
spears rival peanuts for their can't-eat-just-one quality, but they
have even more advantages for good eating. (Tony Cenicola/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- April 4, 2000 -- SERVING-SOUP -- The spring
pea soup served at Quince. Unlike many pleasures of restaurant
dining, the technique of serving a hansome soup is perfect for
entertaining at home. The garnishes can be arranged on the plates
hours ahead and the soup should be served hot at the table from a
tureen or a pitcher, without the risk of sloshing over a shallow
rim on the way to the dining room. (Tony Cenicola/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- April 4, 2000 -- CHARD -- Both the leaves and
stems of red chard and its white-stemmed cousin are edible. Chard
leaves can be used in most recipes calling for spinach (salads are
the exception, since chard leaves are too tough to eat raw), but
the ``chard equals spinach'' formula ignores the fact that the
stems of the two vegetables are very different. Spinach stems are
stringy and fibrous and don't make very good eating. Chard stems
have a delicious, earthy flavor and a distinctive texture that is
silky and meaty when cooked. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
