<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
11 U.S. SOLIDERS HURT IN KOSOVO AS SERBS PROTEST AN ARMS ARREST 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Eleven U.S. soldiers were injured Tuesday in
southern Kosovo by an angry crowd of Serbian villagers who were
protesting a Serb's arrest in a case that involved illegal arms
possession, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
   A Polish peacekeeper and an interpreter were also injured in
what was supposed to have been a routine arrest by NATO forces in
Sevce. The melee began after 150 Serbs had surrounded the suspect's
house and blocked the troops' exit.
</P>
<P>
   Reinforcements were flown in by helicopter from the U.S. base at
Camp Bondsteel to rescue the squad of U.S. military police
officers, the Pentagon said. They were joined by Polish troops, who
set up a roadblock to stop an additional 300 Serbs from Jacinze,
two miles away, who were trying to join the protest.
</P>
<P>
   The security forces suffered what the U.S. Army described as
``non-life-threatening injuries'' while arresting the Serb because
he had reportedly hid two hand grenades in his house. A Pentagon
official said the crowd was throwing rocks and sticks at the
security forces, who fired rubber bullets, holding off the crowd
until reinforcements arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The Army offered no estimate of the number of civilians injured
near the house or at the roadblock. Beta, the independent Yugoslav
news agency, reported that 4 Serbs were hurt at Sevce and 12 were
wounded by rubber bullets at Jacinze.
</P>
<P>
   A Pentagon official said arrests of Serbs and Kosovar Albanians
over illegal possession of weapons were almost daily events.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is most upsetting about this incident is the number of
people who came out to confront the peacekeepers and came out
quickly,'' the official said. ``Maybe it was an organized
resistance.''
</P>
<P>
   Two U.S. soldiers were slightly injured in February in a weapons
search in Kosovska Mitrovica.
</P>
<P>
   The incident Tuesday prompted new Pentagon complaints about
using soldiers for police duties. ``When peacekeepers are forced
into police duties all the time,'' the official said, ``they are
perceived as taking sides.''
</P>
<P>
   (BL)
</P>
</TEXT>
