weirdest and wildest days in stock market history, the Nasdaq
composite index had plunged 634.31 points, shearing 13.6 percent
off its value. Had it closed there, it would have been the worst
one-day decline in Nasdaq history. But a flood of buying rescued
the composite, bringing it to close with a loss of only 1.72
percent on the day. (Steve Kagan/The New York Times)
