<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS AND NOTES FROM AROUND THE U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS: ADVOCATE PULLS OUT
</P>
<P>
   Sam Wyly, the Texas financier and supporter of Gov. George W.
Bush, says he has learned his lesson and is retreating from
presidential politics. During the primary season, Wyly sponsored a
hard-hitting _ and widely criticized _ advertising attack on Sen.
John McCain's environmental record. More recently, Wyly called Vice
President Al Gore a regulation-happy environmentalist and mused
about cranking up an anti-Gore advertising campaign. But Tuesday,
speaking to an environmental group in Seattle, Wyly said that he
actually admired Gore, especially since reading his book on the
environment. Then he added: ``I learned from it. Many of you are
aware of my recent foray into presidential politics. It is to be my
last.''
</P>
<P>
   THE POLLS: GORE AND BUSH TIED
</P>
<P>
   Two new polls indicate that the 2000 presidential race is still
a tossup. An ABC News/Washington Post survey of 1,083 voters, has
Gov. George W. Bush leading Vice President Al Gore by 47 percent to
45 percent, while a CNN/USA Today/Gallup survey of 998 voters has
Gore leading Bush 45 percent to 44 percent. Both polls were
conducted March 30-April 2 and have a margin of error of plus or
minus three percentage points. The ABC News/Washington Post poll
confirmed the judgment of both candidates that improving education
is among the foremost concerns of voters _ 76 percent called it
``very important.'' Asked which candidate would best carry out that
task, 48 percent of the respondents said Gore, compared with 39
percent for Bush. Some earlier polls indicated that voters believed
that the candidates could handle the job about equally well.
</P>
<P>
   THE SENATE: RHODE ISLAND DEMOCRATS PICK
</P>
<P>
   Party endorsements matter less than they once did in Rhode
Island, given that parties now have less cash and patronage to
spread around. Still, it was a slap to Representative Robert A.
Weygand when the state Democratic Party voted Monday to give its
endorsement for senator to Weygand's opponent, Richard Licht, a
former lieutenant governor. Licht has been trailing Weygand in
polls in the race for the party's nomination and the chance to take
on the Republican incumbent, Sen. Lincoln Chafee, who took over the
seat last year when his father, John H. Chafee, died. Licht last
held a state office 12 years ago. But party stalwarts, urged Monday
by the powerful speaker of the Rhode Island House, John B. Harwood,
voted 111-65 to support Licht over Weygand, now in his second term
in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS: GORE RAISES MORE
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore went to affluent Glen Cove, N.Y., on
Tuesday for a pair of fund-raisers aimed at pulling in $300,000. At
a sprawling mansion overlooking Long Island Sound, 10 couples paid
$25,000 each to dine with Gore. Later, 50 people paid $1,000 each
to visit with Gore at a desert reception.
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY'S SCHEDULES  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH _ Sacramento and Martinez, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE _ Annapolis, Md., and Charlotte, N.C. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (BL)
</P>
