</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-LESSONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW WORDS IN PRAISE OF THE UNEXCEPTIONAL SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Please note subslug for EDUCATION-PARTY)  
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps the best science teacher I ever had was one who didn't
believe in evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Newby, who taught seventh- and eighth-grade math and
science, scorned the idea that humans are related to apes. He
recommended not Darwin but Genesis.
</P>
<P>
   Since he did not know much about either math or science, he was
a pretty awful teacher by any conventional measure. Yet I remember
his classes vividly.
</P>
<P>
   In our desperation to figure out what we believed in, we
students reflected on the simian eyebrows of some grown-ups we
knew. We pondered why humans lacked useful things like tails.
</P>
<P>
   So in the end Mr. Newby taught science pretty well. Since moving
to New York a few months ago, and seeing firsthand the incredible
drive of parents to get their children into ``good'' schools, I've
been thinking of Mr. Newby again.
</P>
<P>
   Having gone through schools that most New Yorkers would regard
as terrible, I have a soft place in my heart for ``bad'' schools.
It's not exactly that I believe in bad schools, of course, and I'm
hypocritical enough to send my own children to a school with a
strong academic reputation. But I do think professional parents
often exaggerate the impact if their children do not get into the
most competitive preschool and then rigorous schools all the way.
</P>
<P>
   I went to grade school and high school in Yamhill, Ore., in a
rural area where far more children studied welding than French. And
the reason was not just that my high school French teacher did not
speak French.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the French class underscored the school's flexibility.
The teacher spoke beautiful Spanish, having been a Mormon
missionary in Mexico, and when a few of us expressed interest in
French, he agreed to teach himself and stay one lesson ahead of us.
</P>
<P>
   The main lesson that I derive today from that French class is
that the most important credential for a teacher is often not a
degree or even knowledge, but enthusiasm. As Yeats said,
``Education is not filling a bucket but lighting a fire.'' (Alas,
this injunction is taken literally by some youthful pyromaniacs.)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, enthusiastic teachers may be harder to find anywhere
these days, and the bad schools that I'm praising are not the huge,
overcrowded ones with metal detectors, chaotic classes and teachers
who burn out within a few years. I'm fonder of bad small schools
than bad big ones. But I do think that an enjoyable school is just
about the best one, and that many parents worry more than they need
about their own children's school (partly because any parent who
frets so much is going to be a good influence from home).
</P>
<P>
   Small bad schools offer several advantages. One is the chance to
take part in extracurricular activities that a kid is awful at; in
high school I was pressed into service as a distance runner,
despite a lack of any ability, and running ultimately became an
important part of my life.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there is diversity. Of course, good schools try to
achieve some kind of racial or ethnic diversity, but invariably one
kind of student is hugely underrepresented: the dumb one. And it is
useful to be exposed to nonacademic types who do not believe in
fractions and are disgusted by the Diet of Worms.
</P>
<P>
   In my sophomore year of high school, we boys judged ourselves
largely on our ability to make straight welds in vocational
agriculture class. School had generally been easy for me, so it was
mortifying _ but also painfully edifying _ to discover that I was a
terrible welder.
</P>
<P>
   Parents are obsessive about good schools partly because it is
getting harder to enter good colleges. But one reason is that
Harvard now admits more graduates of ``bad schools'' and fewer from
Andover and Exeter than it did a generation ago. And the Internet
reduces the academic price that students pay for going to less
rigorous schools.
</P>
<P>
   The virtues of (particularly) public schools have been on my
mind because Betty Krier, my high school social studies teacher,
died last month, and the whole community turned out to mourn her.
In three decades as a teacher in Yamhill, she had shaped the
community in important ways, and everybody recognized that she was
a great teacher _ even if she never had the degrees or expertise
that would have enabled her to get hired by a good New York school.
What she offered was warmth and enthusiasm, and that made all the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   A small, nonacademic school is unlikely to offer calculus, an
excellent library or advanced placement classes. But what most
people regard as a second-rate school may compensate in other ways.
It may open minds by introducing a parallel universe in which
welding skills are paramount. It may force debate about evolution
or a search for the monkey in all of us. And it may jump-start
students along life's roads with the passion of a teacher like
Krier. (af)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
