<HEADER>
A7216 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-DOGGETT-FUNDRAISING-B     04-04 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOGGETT-FUNDRAISING-BILL05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Proposal would disclose political groups' backers
 &HT;    By Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. Rep. Lloyd Doggett is taking aim at an
exploding number of mystery groups using a provision in the federal
tax code that can help them propel political candidates into office
with no disclosure about the groups' makeup.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrat from Austin, Texas, wants to force groups such as
Republicans for Clean Air, which ran ads attacking Sen. John McCain
days before the March 7 Super Tuesday primaries, to disclose the
names of the people who control the group, people who receive
payments of more than $200, and donors who contribute at least $200
in a reporting period. Failure to disclose the information to the
Federal Election Commission could cost the groups $100 a day and as
much as $50,000, under the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas businessman Sam Wyly, a friend of Gov. George W. Bush,
formed such a group, which then launched a $2.5 million ad campaign
slamming McCain's environmental record in three critical states
days before the heated May 7 primaries. Wyly's role was revealed by
the media.
</P>
<P>
   Wyly formed his group under Section 527 of the Internal Revenue
Code written more than a quarter century ago. Such groups do not
have to tell the IRS or the FEC that they exist, and there are no
limits on how much they can take in or spend. They can run ads
touting positions on issues but are prohibited from expressly
calling for the election or defeat of a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 527 is not a bird or a plane, but it is rapidly becoming
Superman, the political superweapon of choice in this year's
elections,'' Doggett said. ``Operating as a clandestine political
committee, a 527 can secretly accept unlimited amounts of money
from unidentified contributors to fill the airwaves with hate and
the mailboxes with disinformation.''
</P>
<P>
   Doggett called on Republicans and Bush to support his effort.
``To those Republicans who have so steadfastly fought campaign
finance reform by urging the alternative of full and immediate
disclosure, now is the time to put up or shut up,'' he said. ``I
have written every one of my Republican colleagues to invite them,
in the reform spirit of John McCain, to join in cleaning up this
mess and stopping these covert operations now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign posts contributors on the Internet, and Bush
has called for near-instant disclosure as one way to help reform
the campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush believes groups should let the sun shine in and
fully disclose who is funding their ads,'' campaign spokesman Scott
McClellan said. ``But he recognizes that the Supreme Court has
repeatedly held that organizations such as the NAACP or Sierra Club
cannot be forced to disclose their donors or members.''
</P>
<P>
   Section 527 groups cover the spectrum of tactics and ideology.
The Sierra Club set one up in 1996, and Scott Reed, former Sen. Bob
Dole's 1996 presidential campaign manager, established one to help
win Hispanic voters to the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   The 527s often ``aren't really organizations in the conventional
sense,'' said Frances R. Hill, a University of Miami law professor.
``It can just really be a checking account.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Doggett's bill places no limits on how much the
nonprofits can spend, Hill said, it shines light on the groups
without gagging citizens who want to express their views on issues.
</P>
<P>
   The bill has 153 co-sponsors, all Democrats. Hill discussed the
issue with Doggett as he prepared the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's mounting evidence that the new 527s are in place
primarily to preserve the anonymity of the sources of funds, the
very thing that voters seem to have some interest in knowing,''
Hill said. ``Some may not care what the source of funds might be.
Others will.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
