<HEADER>
A7217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CELEBRITY-JOURNALISM-     04-04 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELEBRITY-JOURNALISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC NEWS RETHINKING INTERVIEW DICAPRIO HAD WITH CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM RUTENBERG and BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC News executives are rethinking a decision to show an
interview of President Clinton conducted by the screen star
Leonardo DiCaprio amid internal debate over whether it is
appropriate for the news division to use an interview conducted by
a celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, a representative for DiCaprio and executives at
ABC News each offered differing versions of events that led up to
DiCaprio's interview of the president on Friday on the patio
abutting the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Segments from the 20-minute interview were to be shown during an
ABC News special, ``Planet Earth 2000,'' on global warming, which
is scheduled for broadcast later this month in connection with the
30th anniversary of Earth Day on April 22. DiCaprio is chairman of
the Earth Day 2000 celebration committee.
</P>
<P>
   No one involved with the interview disputed that plans had been
discussed for weeks concerning some sort of videotaped talk about
the environment between DiCaprio and Clinton at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC News president, David Westin, said in an e-mail to his
staff members, many of whom were irate over the interview, that on
Friday he had been told that ``Mr. DiCaprio was visiting the White
House (at the request of the White House).''
</P>
<P>
   He said that it was his understanding that DiCaprio would ``be
doing a walk-through taking a look at some of the things the White
House has done internally with an environmental slant (things like
recycling its trash and insulating)'' and that the president might
appear during that walk-through.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, when the crew and DiCaprio arrived at the White
House on Friday, they were told that the president wanted to be
interviewed by DiCaprio. ``We did not send him to interview the
president,'' Westin wrote. ``No one is that stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering that a formal interview did take place, he wrote,
the interview might not be broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   After reviewing a copy of that e-mail Tuesday, a White House
spokesman, Jake Siewert, said it was ``rife with inaccuracies'' and
maintained it was ABC that requested the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the time and the schedule, we made it clear that we
would actually do a sit-down interview instead, and that was
perfectly clear, and they came prepared to ask questions,'' Siewert
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Sunshine, a spokesman for DiCaprio, said the actor was fully
prepared for an interview, regardless of whether it happened during
the walk-through or as a sit-down.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was well prepared to engage in a serious discussion with
the president about the issue of global warming,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine said that DiCaprio approached ABC News executives about
a special on the environment earlier in the winter and that the
host of the special, Chris Cuomo, a ``20/20'' correspondent and son
of the former New York governor, acted as a contact between
DiCaprio and the news division.
</P>
<P>
   DiCaprio's representatives originally pitched the idea for an
Earth Day special to NBC Entertainment a year and a half ago,
executives at NBC said.
</P>
<P>
   ABC News executives said that they agreed to work with DiCaprio
because he is a popular face for the younger generation of viewers
that every network news division has had a difficult time reaching.
They also said they were already discussing some sort of Earth Day
special.
</P>
<P>
   Concerning the differing versions of how the interview took
place, an ABC News spokeswoman, Eileen Murphy said, ``I think we're
just going to have to disagree on it.''
</P>
<P>
   She said everybody in the Washington bureau initially ``was
outraged'' about the interview, but that they have since calmed
down.
</P>
<P>
   One offended ABC News producer summed up his feelings this way:
``There is a line that has been crossed often in the past couple of
years between entertainment and news. The line has been pushed and
pushed, and I think this pushes it way too far, beyond where it's
been before.''
</P>
<P>
   nk
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
