<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE POLICE ADMIT FAILURE ON '99 PROTESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Referring to protesters as a ``well-trained and
equipped adversary,'' Seattle police officials issued a report
Tuesday blaming inadequate financing and lack of preparation for
the violence that marked the World Trade Organization's meeting
here last year.
</P>
<P>
   Even as it admitted its own organizational failures in preparing
for the protests, which led to the resignation of the police chief,
the report angered many protesters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frightening to think that members of the general public,
nonviolent protesters and people of conscience are being viewed as
adversaries by the Seattle police,'' said Juliette Beck, an
organizer with Global Exchange, a human rights organization in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The police used tear gas and rubber pellets to contain
protesters estimated at up to 45,000 in a march on Nov. 30 that
ended in Seattle's downtown, blocks from where trade delegates were
scheduled to meet.
</P>
<P>
   Many Seattle residents were angered that the police had used
such tactics on peaceful protesters while a much smaller group of
vandals, a few blocks away, went virtually unchecked as they
smashed windows, ransacked stores and caused more than $17 million
in damage.
</P>
<P>
   In all, more than 500 people were arrested during four days of
protests, but city prosecutors have since dropped most of the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   The police report issued Tuesday said the city did not spend
enough money to prepare, in part because city officials had
underestimated the determination of many protesters to stop
delegates from attending the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``SPD commanders put their faith in historical precedent, the
Seattle tradition of peaceful protest, in assessing the needs for
policing the WTO event,'' the report said. It added that the
department was ``taught a hard lesson'' by protesters who used the
Internet, cell phones and walkie-talkies to marshal demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   mk
</P>
