<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS LOSE SMOLINSKI FOR SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, B.C. _ Doctors confirmed Tuesday what the Kings
feared when Bryan Smolinski's right knee buckled in the final
moments of Monday's loss at Phoenix. His season is over.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is how does a team already lacking in offensive
depth compensate for the loss of its second-line center with the
playoffs set to open in just over a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am there if they need me,'' said Ian Laperriere, the
third-line center who will be moved to the second unit. ``At this
point in the season you do whatever it takes. We are not going to
fold up and go home.''
</P>
<P>
   But for a team missing Ziggy Palffy (sprained right shoulder)
and Nelson Emerson (broken left index finger) from the top two
lines, news that an MRI revealed a torn medial collateral ligament
in Smolinski's right knee doesn't help.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Jason Blake, who washed out in a brief appearance on the
first line earlier this season, will remain a winger on the fourth
line. Blake is quicker than Smolinski and has shown some good
chemistry with Luc Robitaille.
</P>
<P>
   But Blake has five goals and 23 points. Even though Smolinski's
scoring was down in the second half, he had 20 goals and 56 points,
tied with captain Rob Blake for fourth on the team.
</P>
<P>
   The injury comes at a time the Kings playoff seeding still is in
doubt. Right now they are fifth with 89 points and face the
unenviable task of playing Detroit in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   But they are just two points ahead of No6 Phoenix, which has one
more victory and four wins in six meetings head to head. If the
Kings can pass the Coyotes, they probably will play Colorado in
their playoff opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we play as well as we sound,'' said coach Andy Murray,
who held individual meetings Tuesday with each of his players.
``They talked about all we've been through with injuries earlier in
the season and how we came through. They expect to come through
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski, who will not require surgery, was injured with 16
seconds remaining in the Kings' 2-1 loss that clinched a playoff
spot for Phoenix. Coyotes forward Travis Green fell and landed on
the outside of Smolinski's right leg.
</P>
<P>
   The team flew here after the game, but did not work out Tuesday
in preparation for tonight's game against the Vancouver Canucks.
Smolinski returned to Los Angeles on Tuesday morning and underwent
the MRI. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
