<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-6ap0405a </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Favoritism seen in Fulton's waste water bids
 &HT;    By Alfred Charles
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Fulton County Commission is expected today to award a nearly
$40 million long-term contract to a firm that will operate and
maintain its three Northside waste water facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the industry's biggest players are in the running for
the high-profile job, which has generated fierce competition and
behind-the-scenes grumbling by the firms.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton administrators have recommended the 10-year contract be
awarded to Operations Management International Inc., a subsidiary
of the Denver-based consulting and engineering corporation CH2M
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   But some officials with the other companies _ U.S. Filter
Operating Services Inc., United Water Services and Azurix _ are
complaining privately about the selection process. They want it
thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   The four vendors are bidding to run the north Fulton portion of
the system, which includes operation and maintenance of the Big
Creek, Little River and Johns Creek plants and 29 pumping stations.
</P>
<P>
   The county evaluated the firms based on their technical
expertise and cost. United Water had the lowest cost during the
10-year period. U.S. Filter had the highest technical score.
</P>
<P>
   The Fulton contract has been held through a series of short-term
contracts since 1992 by United Water, the same company that
operates Atlanta's drinking water system.
</P>
<P>
   The company wants to keep the contract, but it has been under
fire for a series of spills. The most recent occurred last month,
when about 600,000 gallons of partially treated sewage spewed into
the Chattahoochee River from the Big Creek plant. State
environmental officials have fined the county $433,500 for the
spills.
</P>
<P>
   United Water officials argue that their overall record of
service, despite the most recent incident, has been exemplary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a 99.5 compliance rate in running the facilities,''
said United Water Vice President Mark Halleman.
</P>
<P>
   Though United Water submitted the lowest cost, OMI was ranked
the highest based on cost. In their analysis, Fulton administrators
essentially concluded United Water had low-balled its bid and would
be unable to provide the service at the price it stated based on
current expenses.
</P>
<P>
   As the front-runner for the work, OMI, which manages the waste
water systems in Rockdale and Forsyth counties, has been the target
of behind-the-scenes sniping by some of its competitors. They have
questioned several aspects of the selection process, but none of
them will talk about it on the record for fear of losing future
county work.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints center largely around cost and why OMI ranked
higher than United Water although United Water's bid was lower.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism also was leveled at the county for demanding bidders
to submit a best and final offer, then throwing the offers out
after receiving them.
</P>
<P>
   The move raised suspicion among some vendors that county
staffers favored one firm over the others and didn't want to
require the favored firm to meet the rock-bottom price offered by
the other vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton Public Works director Terry Todd said the offers were
thrown out because of an unfounded suspicion that vendors may have
found out what their competitors were offering.
</P>
<P>
   OMI faced similar charges of favoritism when bidding for the
Atlanta job in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Groselle, an OMI regional vice president, said, ``This is
a very competitive industry. There is always a loser that's never
satisfied with the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
