</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-MARKET-1015(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE STOCK STRENGTH DEFIES BAD NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japan's languid economy slid into another recession late
last year, companies are struggling to overhaul themselves, the
government's debts are piling up and the prime minister is comatose
with a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   None of that news seems to have fazed the Japanese stock market,
which has outperformed the U.S. market over the last year. On
Monday, even with word that the condition of Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi was grave, investors bid up share prices, and the benchmark
Nikkei index reached the highest level since late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The market demonstrated its resilience again Tuesday, retreating
only modestly despite the political uncertainties. And much of that
weakness was attributed to the carryover effect of the Nasdaq stock
market's severe drop Monday in the United States. [At midday on
Wednesday, stocks were a little more than 1 percent lower. The yen
weakened against the dollar.)
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese market's recent strength does not necessarily
signal a better future for this country's economy, the world's
second largest, which has been struggling for years to recover from
the bursting of the speculative bubble a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   The forces that have been driving the market higher reflect some
trends that have not been seen before. A flood of new Japanese
mutual funds, for example, has reversed a prolonged contraction in
the industry. Mutual fund activity, in turn, has spurred buying by
momentum investors, who hope to profit by purchasing shares that
big investors are buying.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, people have been moving their money into stocks that
reflect a modest boom in information technology, telecommunications
and the Internet, at the expense of traditional Japanese companies.
</P>
<P>
   Their moves are intensified by a shortage of stocks in those
sectors; only 12 Japanese stocks are pure Internet investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the feeling that the worst of the economic news is
behind us,'' said Ichizo Takeuchi, marketing director at the
Kokusai Asset Management Co., which supervisors 11 trillion yen in
assets, currently $105 billion. ``Investment in information
technology is growing,'' he said, ``and the structure of the
economy is changing.'' Takeuchi added that the market this year has
been driven by Japanese investors, rather than the foreigners who
piled in last year, and by more individual investors than in the
recent past.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese are among the world's great savers, so any
indication that they are beginning to risk some of that money in
the stock market, where many had been badly burned in the early
1990s, could represent a new source of demand for shares. ``Because
of the large pool of savings here,'' Takeuchi said, ``once
households begin to share risks in the capital markets, that will
in turn contribute greatly to improvement of the Japanese corporate
sector in which they are investing.''
</P>
<P>
   His opinion is not necessarily shared by other money managers
here. Some worry that individual Japanese investors may be stepping
back into the market just in time to be wiped out again, as was
their experience when the asset bubble burst. ``My sense is that
those hurt when the bubble popped are not part of this thing,''
said Craig Chudler of Nikko Salomon Smith Barney. ``But new
companies that are listing and seeing their shares bid up very,
very rapidly _ you hear the `bubble' word come out of their mouths.
They're dumbfounded by the rise in stock prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Just in the last few weeks, a bit of air has come out of the
market. While the benchmark Nikkei index of 225 issues is up 8.77
percent since the beginning of the year, the Topix index, a much
broader piece of the market, is off 0.9 percent after having been
up 2.3 percent less than a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Evans, strategist at HSBC Securities here, said: ``I asked
two of my analysts the other day to tell me how the market had
performed without looking at their numbers, and both of them said
it was up somewhere in the range of 15 percent. That's not the
case, but their perception is one that is widely shared by many
investors, who are enthusiastic about Japan and its future.''
</P>
<P>
   That is most apparent in the mutual fund industry. The funds,
known here as investment trusts _ having been net sellers of stocks
for much of the last decade _ have been piling into the market.
From the beginning of the year through the second week of March,
funds made net stock purchases of 671 billion yen. They were
exceeded only by foreign investors, who were net purchasers of 991
billion yen in stock, though most have been investing in Japan at a
much slower pace than last year.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that mutual funds account for a large part
of recent investment in the equity market, since there are so many
new ones. The most prominent so far is Nomura Securities' Big
Project N, the largest Japanese fund ever. Its success in
attracting 1 trillion yen to the stock market, a good chunk of it
from Nomura's own bond funds, helped expedite the creation of other
stock funds. From mid-January through mid-March, 62 new stock funds
have been introduced, according to Morningstar, the mutual fund
research company.
</P>
<P>
   And that does not include three new funds announced a few weeks
ago by Fidelity Investments. ``We've seen a significant increase in
our business almost across the board,'' said Robert H. Auld, chief
investment officer at Fidelity Investments Japan. Like others, Auld
sees differences between the stock market and the economy.
``Certainly, Japan has stumbled about from a macroeconomic policy
point of view, and everyone knows that,'' he said. ``But a lot of
companies are starting to restructure their businesses and in ways
that are independent from what the government is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   This makes it easier to distinguish winners from losers.
``There's a little more divergence in the fortunes of individual
companies,'' Auld said. ``Where historically all companies tended
to rise and fall with the overall movement of the tide, there are
now companies able to determine their own fortunes independent of
whether the tide is moving in or out.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ahead of the funds are the momentum buyers, who seek to exploit
the links between the funds and the indices they use as benchmarks.
Trading volume exploded earlier this year after Nomura announced
Big Project N, and momentum investors rushed to buy shares ahead of
the fund, hoping to profit from its need to hold certain stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Among those must-have stocks are NTT DoCoMo, Japan's largest
mobile telephone company and the first company anywhere to
commercialize Internet access over a phone, and Sony, which has
sought to convince investors, with some success, that it is
transforming itself from a consumer electronics manufacturer into
an Internet company.
</P>
<P>
   As had been the case in the United States, the most tenuous
connection to the Internet has commanded a high premium in the
market. Thus, shares of the Itochu Techno-Science Corp., the
company that developed a wildly popular system for tapping the
Internet using a mobile phone, have risen 425 percent since they
were first floated in December on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   CJK , which sells and services imported information-processing
and telecommunications equipment, has risen more than 250 percent
since its shares were offered about a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Meikyosha Co., a retailer that sells games, software
and electronics, is up more than 50 percent over its offering price
since it went public in February.
</P>
<P>
   The voracious appetite for these stocks and others like them,
combined with their limited availability, has created risks for
investors. Of the 70 companies with the biggest market
capitalizations, the seven largest funds devoted to investing in
the domestic market hold shares in only 27, and only three are not
related to technology or information services: the Bank of
Tokyo-Mitsubishi; Takeda Chemical Industries, a pharmaceuticals
company; and Seven-Eleven Japan, modestly higher because of its
plans to link its business to cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Evans said he thinks that concentration is too heavy and has
probably hurt the funds' performance so far. Of the 10 stocks that
have risen the most this year, half are old-line electronics
companies, like Mitsubishi Electric and Sanyo Electric, or
pharmaceutical companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
