<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-TELECOMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TRADE REPRESENTATIVE MAY TAKE ACTION AGAINST MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The U.S. trade representative, Charlene
Barshefsky, said Tuesday that Mexico was failing to support
competition in telecommunications and warned that she might take
action against Mexico before the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Mexico, it appears that progress towards a level playing
field for telecommunications carriers is now stalled,'' Barshefsky
said, calling the situation ``extremely serious.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States will decide by July 28 whether to lodge a
formal grievance against Mexico with the WTO, the Geneva-based
group that makes the rules for global commerce. If the WTO were to
rule in favor of the United States, Mexico could face punitive
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The notice to Mexico was part of an annual U.S. review in which
Barshefsky also threatened to file WTO complaints against South
Africa because its telecommunications monopoly had refused to
provide high-volume private circuits to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and MCI WorldCom have pressed the trade representative to
take Mexico to the WTO, arguing that Telefonos de Mexico SA has
abused its advantages as a former monopoly to suppress competition
in the Mexican telecommunications industry. Telmex stopped
providing dedicated lines for Internet and business service to
competitors and charges high rates to complete long-distance calls
carried by other companies, the competitors said.
</P>
<P>
   Between them the two international telecommunications giants
have invested more than $2 billion in building new networks in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The trade representative also criticized Mexican regulators for
not bringing Telmex into line. On March 27, only days before the
U.S. report was due, the Mexican regulatory agency announced new
rules to force Telmex to bring down costs and provide services to
its competitors. But Barshefsky's report noted that ``Telmex has
frustrated similar efforts over the past two years.'' Telmex has
vowed to challenge the regulator's new rules.
</P>
<P>
   The report also criticized Israel for imposing extra charges on
calls to the United States and Canada that it did not charge for
any other country. Israel has announced that it would cancel the
surcharges by Dec. 31, 2001. The trade representative said she
could go to the WTO if Israel did not eliminate the charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
