<SLUG> BC-NABISCO-ICAHN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICAHN OFFERS $5.2 BILLION FOR ALL OF NABISCO GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Carl C. Icahn stopped nibbling around the edges of
Nabisco Group Holdings on Tuesday and made an offer to buy the
entire company _ A1 Steak Sauce, Planters peanuts, Oreo cookies and
all.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn, the New York financier, said he would bid $16 a share, or
about $5.2 billion, for the holding company that owns as its only
possession about 80 percent of the Nabisco food company. Shares in
the holding company, which had been trading at about $9 before
Icahn sought to buy a 30 percent stake last week and force a sale,
closed Tuesday at $14.50, up $2.125. Icahn now owns about 9 percent
of Nabisco Group Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   His announcement came one day after the company's board rejected
an earlier offer from Icahn to buy an additional 30 percent of the
company for $13 a share. But in a concession to his demands, the
board also said it had hired two investment banks to review its
options, including a sale of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn's latest offer amounts to the opening bid in an auction
that most analysts expect will end at a higher price. Icahn said he
agreed, so long as any takeover is not hostile. ``Nabisco alone is
a great company; it's just undervalued,'' he said in an interview.
``It's got so many good things that another food company would love
to have.''
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco's core brands, which also include Chips Ahoy!, Life
Savers and Ritz, have been performing well recently, said Eric R.
Katzman, an analyst at Merrill Lynch. The stock has barely budged,
however, largely because of investors' disinterest in consumer
goods stocks and fears about liabilities Nabisco may face from its
years as a corporate sibling to R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. RJR
bought Nabisco in 1986, and the parent company spun off the tobacco
business last year.
</P>
<P>
   Nomi Ghez, an analyst at Goldman, Sachs, said she thought the
holding company could fetch about $33 a share, based on its assets.
Even if investors decided that the potential for tobacco liability
required a large discount, Icahn's $16-a-share bid still appears
low, she added. The most likely buyers are other large food
companies.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Nabisco's directors Tuesday, Icahn took a
confrontational tone, chiding them for rejecting his earlier bid as
too low even though they had not bought a large number of shares
for themselves when the stock was trading at less than $9. He also
asked that the company open its books to him and his financial
advisers. Otherwise, he wrote, the company's announcement that it
was considering a sale would look like an attempt to ward off his
effort to replace the board. .
</P>
<P>
   Henry A. Sandbach, a Nabisco spokesman, said the company had
received Icahn's letter and would respond to it ``in due course.''
</P>
<P>
   Icahn and Nabisco have been battling for years. In the
mid-1990s, he and Bennett S. LeBow, another financier, tried to
take over RJR Nabisco and force a spinoff of the food unit. They
failed and, when the stock climbed in 1997, Icahn sold his stake
for a large profit. When it dipped in 1998, he invested again and
continued to press management to shed the food unit.
</P>
<P>
   The company instead spun off the tobacco business, in part
because Steven F. Goldstone, then the chief executive, thought it
would leave the two units in better shape to handle tobacco
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Icahn began another proxy fight and also made his
$13-a-share offer for 100 million shares, saying he wanted to
replace the current board with directors who would sell Nabisco.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in the holding company have fallen sharply since the 1999
spinoff, dropping from $20 in March 1999 to less than $9 before
last week. Its market value of $4.7 billion remains only 57 percent
of the value it would appear to have, based on the price of shares
in Nabisco Holdings. Shares of Nabisco Holdings closed at $39
Tuesday, up $6.625.
</P>
<P>
   (BL)
</P>
</TEXT>
