u f BC-TV-SOAPS-WEBSITE-NYT &LR;      04-04 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SOAPS-WEBSITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIMEDIA AND SONY PICTURES TO CREATE SOAP OPERA SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking to find new ways to take advantage of the loyal
following attracted by television soap operas, Primedia and Sony
Pictures have reached agreement on a joint venture to create a new
online site for soap fans.
</P>
<P>
   Executives for the two companies said they expected the new
venture to generate revenue through everything from sales of items
of apparel worn by soap opera stars to pay-per-view telecasts of
episodes of shows that fans might have missed.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas S. Rogers, the chairman of Primedia, said his company's
two magazines that cover the soap opera world, Soap Opera Digest
and Soap Opera Weekly, would combine with the Sony Web site
SoapCity.com, which is built around the two network soap operas
produced by Sony's Columbia television studio, ``Days of Our
Lives'' and ``The Young and the Restless.''
</P>
<P>
   The result will be a newly branded Web site, which, Rogers said,
will expand greatly after broadband technology becomes widely
available, making possible such options as streaming video of
highlights of the day's soap episodes and features built on pieces
from the magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Both he and Yair Landau, the president of Sony Pictures Digital
Entertainment, said they anticipated significant revenue from
e-commerce related to the soaps. ``The core audience for the soap
is intensely passionate about their shows,'' Landau said. He said
items like clothing and jewelry worn by soap stars would be
available for sale to fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking to create  &UR; the &LR;  place for the hard-core
demographic interested in soap operas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said his strategy for Primedia, which publishes a wide
range of magazines for those with specialized interests, from
brides to hog farmers, is to ``become the biggest company for
enthusiasts.'' He added. ``This is a way to play to the passionate
viewer of soaps.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement should be completed in four to six months, Rogers
said. Sony has already moved its plans for building a secondary
revenue stream for its two soap operas away from a soap opera cable
channel, which would compete with the Soap Channel already started
by Walt Disney Co., and toward a plan to provide daily episodes as
a pay-per-view offering.
</P>
<P>
   A Sony executive said the company was ``a couple of months
away'' from offering the day's episodes to fans on DirectTV and
other pay-per-view outlets. The fee is expected to be small, as
little as a dollar or two.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, episodes could be retransmitted through video
streaming on the broadband Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Landau emphasized that Sony would still create ``far more
revenue from the network play of the soap operas than we can off
these new areas for a very long time.'' So he added, ``We have no
interest in endangering the core showing on the networks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Primedia does not want to undermine its publications either,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers stressed, however, that the new joint venture would open
``enormous opportunities for cross-promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   (BL)
</P>
</TEXT>
