<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bullpen chilled by Rockies
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Braves bullpen experiment Day 2 failed, as the
countdown to the return of John Rocker and Rudy Seanez continues.
</P>
<P>
   John Burkett saw his Braves debut spoiled on a bases-loaded
double by Jeff Cirillo in the seventh inning for a 5-3 Rockies win
on Tuesday night as the Braves' record evened at 1-1. He'd given up
a couple of soft singles and a walk to stir up trouble before
Cirillo sent his first pitch down the left-field line.
</P>
<P>
   That tarnished the Braves debuts of Bobby Bonilla and Rafael
Furcal as well, and the 400th start of Tom Glavine's career.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla had spotted the Braves a 2-0 lead with his first homer
and Glavine had survived one poor inning to leave with a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   From good guy to supposed bad boy, deep duties Tuesday night
fell to Bonilla, who followed Andres Galarraga's Monday heroics
with a two-run homer to right field in the fourth inning and his
first Turner Field ovation from a chilled crowd of 26,132.
</P>
<P>
   That, along with the Chipper Jones' double before it, was the
first noise off Rolando Arrojo, who was making his first visit to
Georgia since he defected from Cuba while playing for its national
team in Albany in the summer of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He made this trip memorable for his first major league hit in
his National League debut. The former Devil Ray helped even the
game 2-2 with a double off Glavine on a two-out 0-2 pitch in the
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, who became only the second pitcher to make 400 starts
for the Braves along with Phil Niekro (689 games), got his season
off right, holding the Rockies to two runs in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine cruised through four scoreless innings, but he lost his
2-0 advantage in the fifth after a leadoff walk and a stray
two-out, 0-2 pitch to Arrojo that was hit over Reggie Sanders in
right field, scoring Neifi Perez. That and a Tom Goodwin triple
past Bonilla in left evened the game 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves got a breath of fresh air from 19-year-old Furcal,
who came away with his first major league hit on a single to right
in the sixth inning in his third at-bat. He stole second and
advanced to third on an errant throw from catcher Scott Servais.
</P>
<P>
   In what's now speedy Furcal fashion, he made an impression in
his very first trip to the plate. He fought Arrojo for 12 pitches,
fouling off eight in a row at one point before striking out on an
offspeed pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Furcal added his first major league assist with a rifled throw
to first to get Cirillo in the fourth inning and got his first
major league putout on a Cirillo liner an inning later to strand
two runners.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
