<HEADLINE>
ATTORNEY GENERAL TO OFFER OLIVE BRANCH TO SILICON VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   by JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a speech at Stanford University and in
subsequent talks with executives of technology companies, Attorney
General Janet Reno will extend an olive branch to Silicon Valley
companies Wednesday over issues like digital surveillance and will
offer the government's support in fighting computer crime.
</P>
<P>
   During the last five years, strategies for fighting computer
crime and strengthening network security have been flashpoints
between the government, and high-technology companies and civil
liberties and privacy groups. The Justice Department has infuriated
those groups by demanding broad new authority and technologies to
conduct electronic surveillance while trying to weaken encryption
programs intended to protect individual privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials said the attorney general was
traveling to the nation's high-technology heartland in an effort to
build new trust and at the same time offer the department's support
in protecting against attacks on computer networks.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's outreach effort follows a spate of attacks
on the nation's largest e-commerce companies earlier this year. In
response to the attacks, which brought down the Web sites of
companies like Etrade, eBay, Yahoo and others, the Clinton
administration held an Internet security summit meeting in February
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the officials said, the attorney general will
spend the day searching for common ground and new ways to build
trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some lingering concern among high-technology
executives about the government's role,'' said a federal official
who is involved in planning the meeting and who spoke on the
condition of anonymity. ``We're trying to address those concerns by
building trust and finding out how industry and law enforcement can
work together while protecting privacy and civil liberties.''
</P>
<P>
   The official added that similar meetings were planned with
privacy and civil liberties groups.
</P>
<P>
   After Reno speaks, law enforcement officials and corporate
executives will break up into working groups on subjects like
reporting incidents, conducting investigations and sharing
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Industry has been leery about being too close to government,''
said Harris Miller, president of the Information Technology
Association of America. ``Particularly an industry like ours which
has been so worried about government control.''
</P>
<P>
   He said, however, that Reno's visit and subsequent meetings will
help build trust between law enforcement officials and corporate
executives. ``This is an educational process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, the attorney general plans to visit a
``digital clubhouse'' in Sunnyvale, where she will meet with a
group of teen-agers to talk about computer ethics.
</P>
<P>
   (BL)
</P>
</TEXT>
