<SLUG> BC-NY-FISCAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANY'S LEADERS REACH AGREEMENT ON SPENDING PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki and leaders of the Legislature
agreed Tuesday on the outlines of a roughly $77 billion spending
plan that generously finances education, heath care, transportation
and tax cuts, clearing the way for one of the earliest budgets in a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   With the state running a large surplus, the accord sets the
boundaries for a budget that is all but certain to include an array
of programs that the governor did not call for in his original
budget proposal _ from expansion of prekindergarten classes and
reductions in class size to low-cost prescription drugs for the
elderly. And state leaders also agreed to let voters decide in
November whether to spend $3.8 billion on a host of transportation
projects, including a new subway line on Second Avenue in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for spending $1.4 billion more than the governor
proposed in January. It propels the budget talks further along than
they have been at this date in most recent years, and it places
Pataki and the Legislature on a course to enact a final budget by
the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   The deal also calls for $1.2 billion in new tax cuts. But the
cuts are not expected to have a significant impact on this year's
final budget because they will be structured to take effect in
future budget years, legislative aides said.
</P>
<P>
   The budget was due on April 1, but for the 16th consecutive
year, the governor and the Legislature failed to meet that
deadline. Last year's budget was adopted on Aug. 4, 126 days
overdue. With Tuesday's agreement, the action shifts to the
Legislature, where rank-and-file members of both houses will have
to negotiate the final details publicly in conference committees.
</P>
<P>
   The swiftness of the budget negotiations this year has been
propelled by the legislators' desire to get home early to campaign
for re-election, and by a continued surge in tax revenue that
allows lawmakers to avoid having to make many of the hard choices
of the past. It has also helped that Medicaid spending,
traditionally one of the most contentious areas of the budget, was
determined in a separate agreement in December.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers and their leaders faced another incentive for a timely
budget: a 1-year-old law that withholds their pay for as long as
the budget is late.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Bruno, the Republican majority leader of the Senate,
predicted Tuesday that the budget, the main business of Albany,
would be completed in slightly over a week.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The accord announced Tuesday calls for $1.2 billion in new tax
cuts to be phased in over the next five years, including tax
credits for low-wage New Yorkers, as well as a reduction of a tax
that adds several dollars a month to the average gas and electric
bill.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, agreement on how much to spend above the governor's
proposal has been the most difficult part of the budget
negotiations. But with tax revenue streaming into the state's
coffers, it was hard for Pataki to resist the Legislature's call
for more spending. Pataki had proposed spending $76.8 billion in
the budget he released earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Pataki has promised that he will not
attempt the sort of widespread vetoes he made in 1998, when he cut
more than $1 billion in programs, mostly Democratic, from the
budget that the two houses sent to him. But Pataki has privately
warned Bruno and Silver that he will abide by the agreement only if
they do not spend any more than the $1.4 billion that they agreed
to add to his original budget proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The deal reached Tuesday by Pataki, Bruno and Silver settles the
main issue that had held up negotiations for weeks: an overall
spending figure that all sides could accept. But aides to Pataki
and legislative leaders cautioned that some details still had to be
worked out before the budget was completed and then submitted to
lawmakers for approval. Conference committee hearings to consider
the budget will start convening as early as Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
