<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7370 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GUN-DEALER-ART-NYT &LR;      04-04 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-DEALER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELLING GUNS: A TRADITION AND A DILEMMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT44 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Considering the setting for the following interview _
a big, bustling gun factory in Brooklyn _ what comes next may be
hard to believe. But Anthony F. Imperato and his family have never
really been all that crazy about guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guns were just not a part of our lives,'' he said. ``Other
than the fact that we sold them.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, the business that supports the Imperato family seems
about as out of place in New York City as a kosher deli would be in
West Texas: The family owns both the gun factory, the only such
factory in the city, and a gun shop, the oldest in the city, in
Little Italy.
</P>
<P>
   But growing up in Bensonhurst, Imperato said, he and his father,
Louis, never once went hunting. ``We didn't shoot at targets. None
of our hobbies ever involved guns. Guns were a job.'' He reaches
for an apt analogy: ``Maybe the guys who run Lobel's meat market
are, you know, vegetarians. You never know.''
</P>
<P>
   So over the last several years, as New York's gun laws have
become among the most restrictive in the country, and especially
over the last several weeks, as the national debate over gun
control has grown even more polarized, Imperato, 42, has become a
man in a strange spot.
</P>
<P>
   When the workday is over, he would much rather talk about food
than firearms. In a three-hour interview that started on a desolate
industrial street near the Gowanus Canal, continued through the
Brooklyn-Battery Tunnel and ended in Little Italy, he did not once
mention the Second Amendment. But he is a member of the National
Rifle Association. And he is a businessman _ ``a very responsible
businessman,'' he said _ who has watched his livelihood come under
assault even though he feels he has never done anything wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``My viewpoint on the right of people to own guns is the same as
it has always been,'' he says. ``But like anything else, the more
you're attacked, the more you think about whether to fight or
flee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And we're not going to flee,'' he adds resolutely. But the
family is certainly finding it more difficult to hold its ground.
</P>
<P>
   The Imperatos' storied Manhattan gun shop, with its famous
wooden pistol sign aiming due west, has seen better days. Called
John Jovino after its founder, a former Italian leather smith who
moved the shop to its address on Centre Market Place in 1911, it
was once in the middle of a block of busy gun shops that catered
mostly to the gun-toting men who worked across the street, at the
old Police Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I would go there as a kid with my father,'' Imperato
recalled, ``it was a sea of blue. It smelled like holster
leather.''
</P>
<P>
   He got into the business without thinking much about it. He grew
up wanting to play either center field for the Yankees or the piano
for Bruce Springsteen, ``but somehow that didn't happen.'' He
studied business at New York University, thinking vaguely about the
restaurant trade because he had always been something of a gourmet.
</P>
<P>
   But then his family gave him an apartment above the gun shop,
where he lived from the late 1970s to early 1980s. And so, he said,
smiling broadly and quoting from a character in ``The Sopranos''
who was quoting Al Pacino in ``The Godfather, Part III,'' ``Just
when I thought that I was out, they  &UR; p-u-l-l &LR;  me back in.''
</P>
<P>
   But by the time Imperato got into the business, it was a
different world on Centre Market Place. The police moved south in
1973. The city's gun laws gradually became tougher, requiring
buyers to wait anywhere from six to nine months for a permit. And
mostly for the first reason, but also for the second, said Imperato
(pronounced Im-per-AH-to), he and his father, who is now
semi-retired, were looking for a way to stay afloat by the late
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   They ended up looking into the past. In 1993, hoping to
capitalize on the growing interest in Civil War memorabilia, they
opened the Brooklyn factory, which now makes newly issued Colt
pistols and cap-and-ball revolvers, first manufactured in the
mid-1800's, along with reproductions of Henry rifles, first used in
the Civil War. (Henry's motto: ``Load on Sunday and shoot all week
long!'')
</P>
<P>
   The powder guns made do not require a permit, luckily. Like the
modern guns beneath the glass case in the store, they can still be
used to kill someone, of course. But the shooter first must learn a
whole lot about black powder, percussion caps, wadding, lead balls
and hand-strengthening exercises. ``The revolvers have a pretty
good kick,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Imperato spends most of his time at the factory, which
cranks out about 5,000 guns a year. ``This is where we put the
butter on the bread now, is right here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He speaks of trying to keep the Manhattan store open at least
until its centennial, in honor of his grandfather, Frank Albanese,
who bought it from Jovino. But these days the store is mostly in
the hands of its manager, a friendly Chinese man who is known
around the neighborhood simply as ``Gun King Charley.''
</P>
<P>
   Imperato never apologizes for his work. ``Over the years,'' he
says, ``we know we've sold lots of guns to people who have used
them to protect their lives, and that's a good feeling.'' But he
adds that he sometimes worries about what his three children, 14,
11 and 8, will end up thinking of his career. ``Honestly, it occurs
to me. They don't ask about it, but I know they probably hear about
the issues in school, about how gun dealers are bad. And I don't
want them to think their father is bad.''
</P>
<P>
   (BL)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
