<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-CHAMPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARTANS ADD SYMMETRY TO THE CHAOS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Magic Johnson watched from the floor, barely a
one-handed bounce pass away, as Mateen Cleaves stood on a
stepladder and snipped down the nets. There they were, two Michigan
State point guards separated by 21 years, but connected by a common
accomplishment: They took national championships to East Lansing,
Mich.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tenuous line, but about the best you can do in trying to
link this National Collegiate Athletic Association basketball
tournament with those of the past. Johnson, after all, cut down his
souvenir as a sophomore in 1979, headed to the National Basketball
Association draft as the overall No. 1 pick and then changed the
professional game forever.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaves is a senior. He will be drafted somewhere in the first
round, but odds-on it will be behind some high-school player no one
but hoops newsletter writers, scouts, agents and their surrogates
have heard of. Still, at least for 40 minutes on Monday, Cleaves
and two senior and two junior teammates made sense of a tournament,
of a college basketball season, that did not make much sense at
all.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans were more experienced, played better defense and
thoroughly handled a young Florida team, 89-76, here at the RCA
Dome. They were the lone No. 1-seeded team standing in the field of
64 _ two others, Arizona and Stanford, did not even make it out of
the first weekend. Michigan State had won an ugly contest, 53-41,
in the semifinals Saturday against a Wisconsin team that
transported basketball aficionados back in time _ to 1941, to be
exact, when the Badgers' deliberate style sedated Washington State
and, you have to believe, anyone who was watching, 39-34.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin was the biggest surprise in a tournament full of them.
Its coach, Dick Bennett, wears a red sweater vest and has earned a
reputation as a genius among his peers after 35 years of taking
players who would be hard pressed to make an All Ivy team of any
year and turning them into giant killers.
</P>
<P>
   To borrow a term from the business world, this ``old economy''
team may not have been fun to watch on the basketball ticker, but
Wisconsin earned its way here.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State earned the national championship in much the same
fashion. It was more talented than Wisconsin, but nearly as short
of marquee names. After Cleaves, who scored 18 points to go with 4
assists in the championship game, the Spartans were carried by two
other seniors: Morris Peterson, whose 15 second-half points buried
the Gators, and A.J. Granger, who had an unobtrusive 19 points and
9 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Florida, the ``new economy'' team, managed to generate
all the buzz before and, to some extent, after the Spartans made
them 2000's NCAA runners-up. Their 34-year-old coach, Billy
Donovan, lured a collection of seven blue-chip freshmen and
sophomores first to Gainesville, Fla., a football stronghold, and
then to the title game.
</P>
<P>
   They pressed full court, they bombed from 3-point territory and
one of them, Udonis Haslem, banged inside for a career-high 27
points on 10-of-12 shooting. Afterward, there was plenty of talk
about next year, as well as next week.
</P>
<P>
   That is when perhaps Florida's sophomore forward Mike Miller
will decide whether he will return to school or turn professional.
On the eve of the Final Four, Miller confirmed what documents
reviewed by The New York Times had shown, that he had spoken
extensively with a sports agent who was unregistered in Florida and
who did not inform university officials of the conversations, as
the state's strict agent law requires. The NCAA said the player had
done nothing wrong, but the agent, Andy Miller, is now under
investigation by Florida law-enforcement authorities.
</P>
<P>
   It was yet another strange twist in a strange season that,
unfortunately, perhaps upstaged Michigan State's title run. In the
weeks leading up to the tournament, a series of NCAA investigations
and player suspensions for everything from who paid prep school
tuition to improper contact with agents, prompted some of the
biggest names in college coaching to call college sports' governing
body names.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, such disparate people and institutions as a
basketball enthusiast implicated in a recruiting scandal at
Syracuse nearly decade ago, a Manhattan lawyer, a church with a
distinguished history earned in the civil-rights era and a famed
modeling agency have all been mentioned in connection with Erick
Barkley and a continuing investigation of St. John's basketball
team.
</P>
<P>
   That is only one part of the tattered mosaic of college
basketball that turned the NCAA president's state-of-the-game
address here into a bitter call for change. The president, Cedric
Dempsey, barely concealed his disdain for ``the culture'' of
college basketball and vowed to ``wipe it out.''
</P>
<P>
   So what should have been a celebration of coaches in sweater
vests with overachieving players and a senior-laden team
persevering to achieve a goal, or even a young, exciting troop full
of possibilities, was broken up even before it got started.
</P>
<P>
   Magic the person might have been on the court when Cleaves and
his Michigan State teammates cut down the nets, but little was
magical throughout the final months of the college basketball
season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nk
</P>
</TEXT>
