u k BC-EDIT-MARKETS-NYT &LR;      04-04 0405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MARKETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MERCURIAL MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Wednesday, April 5: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Volatility was redefined on Wall Street Tuesday. First the Dow
fell more than 500 points by 1:15 p.m. Then, miraculously, it
gained back all but about 57 points by the 4 p.m. closing. The
Nasdaq dropped 574 points before it too roared back to end down 74.
Comparing start and finish, there was not that much change. But for
investors already jittery after Monday's biggest point drop ever,
349, on the Nasdaq, Tuesday's whiplash market was jarring.
</P>
<P>
   At their low ebb, stocks had by one estimate lost about $1
trillion of value. That is a stunning amount of money for investors
to lose, even if temporarily. But of course no one knew at midday
that bottom had been reached. Some no doubt feared the revenge of
Alan Greenspan had come, three years after Greenspan, chairman of
the Federal Reserve Board, had warned of the markets' ``irrational
exuberance.''
</P>
<P>
   By many calculations stocks are overvalued, with prices about
twice their historical average when compared with corporate
earnings. Prices continue to rise faster than earnings. In the
high-tech sectors, it almost seems that the more a company loses,
the more attractive its stock becomes to investors. One eminent
economist recently predicted that the market would fall by a third,
even though it might take a decade or more. But who wants to be the
first to bail out?
</P>
<P>
   Given the uncertainty, it is not hard to understand why stock
prices swing wildly. The flimsiest rumors spook investors who are
guessing when other investors will take flight. Even a predictable
event like Monday's antitrust verdict against Microsoft appears to
send stocks into a tailspin.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, a school of thought that says stock prices
are actually a bargain and will almost certainly soar over the next
few years. This view rests on the assumption that contrary to
conventional wisdom, stocks are no riskier than bonds over the long
haul. Though popular formulations of this theory have been
questioned by economists, some investors seem not to doubt its
wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   So experts are sharply divided. Prices appear irrationally high
to some, temptingly low to others. A new breed of traders has
entered stock markets with an investment horizon measured in
seconds. No wonder stock prices roar up and down. (af)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 2335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
