<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: BUDGETING FOR NEW YORK STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Wednesday, April 5: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With unexpected speed, Gov. George Pataki and the New York State
Legislature have agreed on a framework for a new $77 billion
budget. Producing a framework does not mean the legislature has
actually produced a budget on time _ a feat that has not been
achieved in Albany for the last 16 years. This budget was
officially late last Saturday. But the agreement on a budget
outline is definitely a sign of progress for legislators prodded by
an election this fall and the loss of their paychecks until the
budget is officially finished. Last year the legislature reached
this point in its budget negotiations in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   At press conferences in Albany, state leaders promised an
enticing list of possibilities such as reduction of school class
sizes and low-cost prescriptions for the elderly. Still, this
general agreement must be greeted cautiously until the details
emerge in the coming weeks. Despite the surge in state revenues,
primarily from taxes on Wall Street profits, the governor, the
Senate majority leader, Joseph Bruno, and Assembly Speaker Sheldon
Silver must be careful not to endorse either tax cuts or
obligations that would expand the deficit later.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders have identified an additional $1.4 billion available
for spending since the governor announced his budget, and want to
apply some of this to $1.2 billion in new tax cuts phased in over
the next five years. Some of the newly identified money is expected
to be used to cut the gross receipts tax on energy, which falls
heaviest on struggling upstate businesses, especially as energy
costs increase. There are also promises of earned-income tax
credits, an important way to help the working poor.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of a separate agreement on transportation is a
proposed $3.8 billion bond issue for next November, half going for
highways and the other half for mass transit. The bond issue has
been seized upon by state leaders as their part of the capital plan
of the Metropolitan Transportation Authority, particularly a $3
billion proposal to build a full Second Avenue Subway and a link
between the Long Island Rail Road and Grand Central Terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Bond issues have been a tough sell in recent years, and voters
in November may well be concentrating more on senate and
presidential races than on increasing the state's debt. They will
certainly be skeptical of authorizing more borrowing by the state
without a full explanation of how the money will be spent and when
these projects will be finished. Meanwhile, serious questions
remain about where the MTA will get the remaining funds _ whether
from city or state coffers, the Port Authority of New York and New
Jersey or perhaps even an unpopular fare increase.
</P>
<P>
   This fat-year budget wisely offers at least some cushion against
leaner times, adding a reserve fund of $750 million as a hedge
against an economic downturn. Such measures will help shore up New
York's budget status even more than this sudden surge of
timeliness.  &QL; 
(af)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 2346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
