<DOCNO> NYT20000404.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7383 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-GIULIANI-SOFTMONEY     04-04 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-SOFTMONEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONITORS ACCUSE MRS. CLINTON AND GIULIANI ON SOFT MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two advocacy groups charged on Tuesday that Hillary
Rodham Clinton and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani have illegally collected
the largely unregulated donations known as soft money for their New
York Senate campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The groups, Common Cause and Democracy 21, which both contend
that the campaign finance laws need to be tightened to reduce the
influence of money in politics, asked the Federal Election
Commission and the Justice Department in a formal complaint to
investigate the two candidates' soft money fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   ``These illegal schemes, unless they are stopped, threaten to
inject millions of dollars of federally illegal campaign
contributions into the New York Senate race,'' said Fred
Wertheimer, president of Democracy 21.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who was campaigning Tuesday with Sen. John McCain of
Arizona, a leading proponent of campaign finance reform, brushed
aside a question about whether his soft-money fund raising was
illegal. A spokesman for the Clinton campaign, Howard Wolfson, said
Clinton had not violated finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Election Commission and the Justice Department both
declined to comment on the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Each candidate has raised nearly $1 million in soft money in the
New York contest. Those amounts are dwarfed by the totals they have
collected for their official campaigns _ $19 million for Giuliani
and $12 million for Clinton. But soft money could play a crucial
role in the final weeks of the campaign, when money becomes scarce,
and candidates seek ways to harvest large sums quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money contributions are raised in unlimited amounts by
party committees, which are legally barred from using them to help
candidates directly; instead, the money is supposed to be used for
so-called party building activities, such as voter drives. Many of
the contributions come from corporations and unions that are
otherwise prohibited from giving political funds.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, soft money has become a gaping loophole in the
regulatory system, with parties increasingly using it in ways that
appear to assist candidates _ by, for example, running
advertisements that promote or attack candidates' views without
explicitly urging viewers to vote for or against the candidates
themselves. Federal regulators have been reluctant to crack down on
the practice.
</P>
<P>
   The two advocacy groups Tuesday focused their complaint on
special fund-raising committees that both Giuliani and Clinton
established in conjunction with the party committees run by the
Republicans and Democrats in the Senate. Other candidates around
the nation have set up similar committees.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates solicit soft money donations for the special
fund raising committees _ New York Senate 2000 for Clinton and the
Giuliani Victory Committee for the mayor. Under the law, the party
committees control the money in the special fund raising
committees, and cannot pledge to use it in the New York race.
</P>
<P>
   But the two advocacy groups asserted that in reality, the party
committees will spend all the money in New York, buying
advertisements that legally should come from the campaigns
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Tuesday about the criticism from the two groups, Giuliani
said no soft money had yet been spent to assist his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only person in this campaign that has spent soft money is
my opponent,'' he said. ``We've raised it and we're holding it, but
we haven't spent it. All of the ads that so far have been on
television for me have been paid for by my campaign. All of the ads
for her have been paid for by the Democratic National Committee
soft-money fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson, the Clinton campaign spokesman, said, ``All of our
fund-raising has been perfectly legal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
