<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-04 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7385 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-GIULIANI-MCCAIN-AR     04-04 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-MCCAIN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN RIDES AGAIN, THIS TIME TO SUPPORT GIULIANI  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHPORT, N.Y. _ Sen. John McCain was back on a campaign bus
Tuesday, but this time in support of the U.S. Senate candidacy of
his friend, New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who happens to be
in pursuit of the same independent and Democratic vote that made
McCain such a phenomenon in the presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the mayor and the senator tried to turn what even
Republicans say is Giuliani's biggest problem _ his temperament _
into a positive interpretation of character.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that Rudy, like me, will be elected Miss
Congeniality in the United States Senate,'' McCain said at a Town
Hall meeting with Giuliani in Suffolk County, where McCain beat
George W. Bush in the March 7 New York primary. ``But I do believe
that he will be an instant star.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also said at the meeting, at the Northport American
Legion Hall: ``We need more mild-mannered, even-tempered
individuals like Rudy and myself'' _ and was interrupted by
laughter _ ``who will never rock the boat or say anything that's
controversial in nature. So, I'm looking forward to having a soul
mate in the United States Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's appearance, his first on a campaign trail since
suspending his presidential bid in March, was clearly welcomed by
Giuliani, whose campaign has suffered from the mayor's aggressive
attacks on Patrick M. Dorismond, the unarmed black man shot dead in
March by police.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, of Arizona, seemed to have a positive effect on the
mayor. Giuliani laughed frequently throughout his morning on Long
Island, was cheerful with reporters and even made fun of himself
when a participant at the Town Hall meeting asked why Hillary
Rodham Clinton, the mayor's opponent, says that the mayor cannot
get along with anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did she say I can't get along with anybody?'' the mayor
shouted back, stalking toward the participants in mock rage. ``Sit
down! Shut up!''
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd laughed and cheered, Giuliani predicted that his
performance would be used by his opponent. ``I can be in a Clinton
campaign commercial!'' he exulted. ``Paid for by soft money!''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani was frequently dogged Tuesday by questions about his
own fund raising, which reached $19 million in March, particularly
since he was traveling with the man who made overhauling the
campaign finance system a centerpiece of his presidential campaign
and who vowed to renounce unregulated soft-money donations if he
became the Republican presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   But as he has in the past, Giuliani said he was raising money as
a defensive tactic against the historically prodigious fund-raising
of the Clinton administration, even though Clinton has raised only
$12 million in this race and now expects the mayor to outspend her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a fool,'' Giuliani said over a campaign-stop
breakfast. ``And I don't intend in October to have them pour in
$10, $20 million, have the unions spend $10, $20 million, and be
virtually defenseless against that.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, McCain said that he was grateful for Giuliani's support
of his campaign finance bill, McCain-Feingold, but ``I understand
that when you are in this kind of a race, you have to raise
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani remained in buoyant spirits all morning, particularly
during an unusual _ for the mayor _ relaxed and open session with a
small group of reporters on a bus that Giuliani shared with McCain.
</P>
<P>
   For McCain, it was a day of what he called ``very warm
memories'' of his old campaign bus, the Straight Talk Express,
where such sessions with reporters were constant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been on a bus this nice before,'' Giuliani marveled
of the Peter Pan VIP coach with sofas and tables, suitable for a
touring rock band. ``This is terrific. The campaign bus that we
used in the past was like a truck.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani supported Bush in the New York primary, but kept a
much-remarked-upon distance from him as he simultaneously praised
McCain and refused to engage in the tough state Republican Party
tactics used to defeat him. McCain publicly thanked Giuliani at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans said the mayor would far prefer to have McCain
at his side than Bush, whose appeal to conservatives could alienate
the independents and Democrats Giuliani needs to win the race.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor acknowledged as much on the bus. ``He has proven that
he can put the good of the country as he sees it ahead of partisan
politics,'' Giuliani said of McCain. ``And I think that's very
appealing as it should be to independent voters, to Democrats who
are willing to consider voting for a candidate of the other party.
So I think having his support means a great deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd at the Town Hall meeting , composed of invited
Republicans, legionnaires and enthusiastic walk-ins, asked
questions about home heating oil, gun control and Elian Gonzalez,
the 6-year-old Cuban boy whose mother drowned at sea while bringing
her son from Cuba to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Clinton, Giuliani said he supported legislation
granting Elian permanent resident status. ``His mother gave her
life so that this boy would not grow up in tyranny,'' the mayor
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the bus, Giuliani and McCain also talked about the mayor's
favorite television show, ``The Sopranos,'' about a mafia family in
New Jersey. ``How authentic is it?'' said the mayor, a former
prosecutor. ``I mean, this is where I really spent my life. It is
very, very close.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you the picture,'' Giuliani said, ``of a group of
people that aren't very different than everybody else but for the
pathological way in which they conduct their business. And
therefore, they can be totally horrible and totally evil, or they
can be these enormously complex people who love their children,
love their friends, but then every once in a while go out and kill
one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   (BL)
</P>
</TEXT>
