u s BC-GLF-MASTERS-NYT &LR;      04-04 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL SAYS IT'S HIS TIME; NORMAN IS RUNNING OUT OF TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ As the start of the Masters drew closer Tuesday,
so did the anticipation among the players. Greg Norman, preparing
for his 20th Masters, is running out of time to win a green jacket.
David Duval, the world's No. 2-ranked player, has been blunt about
his intentions to win a major this year. Tiger Woods, with three
victories and three second-place finishes in his last seven starts,
has never entered a major with more momentum.
</P>
<P>
   So while practice rounds continued at Augusta National Golf
Club, thoughts drifted toward Thursday, when the tournament will
begin, along with the drama.
</P>
<P>
   For Duval, waiting for the Masters has been difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of pressure on me, because I put it on myself,''
said Duval, who vowed in January to win a major this year. ``I've
worked very hard, and I hope everything falls into place. We've
been talking about it for a few months. We're going to find out
very soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The players will also find out about the impact of course
alterations that will give some of the holes a different feel. Some
fairways have been narrowed, new pin positions have been added at
Nos. 10, 12, 13 and 16. Most players expect the course's degree of
difficulty to increase, particularly if conditions are windy.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' record-setting winning score of 18 under par in 1997
appears safe. When asked about the course changes, Woods said
players may have to take a more cautious approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest adjustment is going to be the fairways,'' Woods
said. ``They're smaller. Some of the rough lines are different.
It'll make it very interesting, I'll tell you that. You can't go
out there and take driving for granted like you used to around
here. It's going to be quite a challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   For Norman, a return to Augusta means revisiting an assortment
of memories, including heartbreaking defeats. In 1987, Larry Mize
chipped in from 140 feet to defeat Norman in a playoff. In 1996, in
one of the most stunning final rounds, Norman squandered a
seemingly insurmountable six-stroke lead on Sunday, collapsing with
a final-round 78 and losing to Nick Faldo. Then last year, Norman
stormed into contention again, playing brilliantly before finishing
third, three strokes behind the winner, Jose Maria Olazabal.
</P>
<P>
   With six finishes in the top three at Augusta, but no victories,
Norman thought he would have a green jacket by now. When asked if
he thought much about his disappointments, he shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I thought about that, I'd go crazy,'' said Norman, who
turned 45 years old in February. ``To come up with a logical answer
is not logical. Of the 20 years being here, it has just been a huge
emotional roller coaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman won the British Open in both 1986 and 1993, but he
expects to be competitive in only a few more majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reality is reality,'' Norman said. ``When you start hitting
45, 46, it's a little hard to get out of bed. There's a few more
cricks and pains.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many players, however, Norman said he always feels better
once he arrives at Augusta. Olazabal was struggling heading into
last year's tournament, yet found his game and captured a memorable
victory. When Mark O'Meara won in 1998, he shot an opening-round
74, but found his putting stroke in time to win his first major at
age 41.
</P>
<P>
   Those kind of memories help make the Masters special, and
starting Thursday, the latest chapter will start to unfold. Duval,
along with many others, was glad that the wait was almost over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether there's rough or not, whether the greens are hard or
fast, whether they make alterations to the course every year, it
doesn't matter,'' Duval said. ``There's still going to be a Masters
champion come Sunday. And I'm very much looking forward to this.''
</P>
<P>
   (nk)
</P>
</TEXT>
