u s BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     04-04 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TALL TEXAN MUST LEAD THIS DRIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ As an imported New York Yankee, Roger Clemens
has worked hard to fit into their championship cast, to be himself,
the down-home Texan and hard-throwing Rocket. Now if only Cy Young
will revisit his right arm and make him whole.
</P>
<P>
   He was not himself last season, or at least not the pitcher he
was in Toronto the previous two. In the final box score and
analysis, it didn't matter. Clemens left to a standing ovation in
Yankee Stadium the night this most famous franchise won the World
Series for the 25th time. A year of pitching dangerously had quite
the climactic ending, even if it came without the rest of the
storybook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to the ring ceremonies when we get back
home,'' Clemens said before pitching against the Angels here
Tuesday night, and following a familiar Yankee formula _ strong
starting pitching plus timely hitting equals another save by
Mariano Rivera _ in the season opener Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens redeemed himself against Atlanta for his modest
performance last season (14-10, 4.60 earned run average), or at
least that was the spin on the postseason pitch. He was forgiven
for impersonating, or being, an aging power pitcher. He earned the
ring. Now comes what could be a trickier process, deserving a
raise.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't talk about next year, and neither do the Yankees, but
it is out there, the belief that George Steinbrenner made an
agreement with Clemens' agents, Randy and Alan Hendricks, to extend
his contract upon acquiring him last spring. Steinbrenner is not
likely to treat two leveraged player agents from the powerhouse SFX
the way he would the politicians who are trying to get his
commitment to remain in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Boss has been known to employ other methods of
dealing with star players (see Winfield, Dave) who have him backed
into a financial corner but whose performances have not met his
level of expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Like any sure-fire Hall of Famer, Clemens has flattering goals
for himself, another 20 victories that would accelerate his pace to
300, from the 247 he began with Tuesday night. But he's also tasted
Champagne now, got high on Yankee success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've won 20 numerous times and five Cy Youngs,'' he said. ``If
it means 15-15 and having the opportunity to pitch in the World
Series, that overrides any individual achievements.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't a bad pitcher last season, just not the same one who
was selected to baseball's All Century team. The Yankees sure made
their share of excuses for Clemens. He was trying too hard and he
was struggling with location and pitching to a new set of catchers.
The truth was, as David Cone said last night, ``We didn't see his
good splitter and slider last year.''
</P>
<P>
   There never was an urgency for the Clemens of old. Even in the
three postseason series, by the time he pitched, the Yankees had
their claws around the opposition's throat.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, in the last game of the 20th century, that was Cy
Young Clemens out there against the Braves, and his mother, Bess,
who suffers from emphysema, traveled to see him pitch, and back
home in Houston, his winter days were filled with more
``way-to-gos,'' than ever.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't watched the tape of Game 4, because the off-season, he
said, is about family, about fatherhood. ``I'm not the Rocket to
them,'' he said of his four children. Then again, they are named
Koby, Kory, Kacy and Kody, so down-home dad likely has more
invested in Rocket-hood than he lets on.
</P>
<P>
   Cone called him ``the greatest pitcher of our generation,'' and
remarked how strange it was to hear him booed in Boston, in Texas,
and when he struggled in New York. ``It was like he didn't have a
home,'' Cone said.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston last week, Clemens had the whole team out to his
house. Cone has sensed a larger leadership role for Clemens this
spring. That said, it could get hot and sticky if Clemens doesn't
pitch with a vintage flourish this summer. For one thing, the
Yankees might actually find themselves in a pennant race. For
another, Cone, also 37, could have as good a year or better and not
be extended an invitation to return. And Cone has merely been a
pillar of support on three title teams, not to mention one of New
York's most engaging voices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing unusual _ I've got the same target dates every year,''
Clemens said, making this one out to be like any other on the eve
of his 2000 debut.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't. Clemens rode a bandwagon last season, and took a big
bow at the finish. This time around, beginning Tuesday night, he
has to help steer.
</P>
<P>
   nk
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
