A7394 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-BOSNIA-NYT &LR;      04-04 0413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BOSNIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE PURSUIT OF JUSTICE IN BOSNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Wednesday, April 5: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the arrest this week of Momcilo Krajisnik, the
international war crimes tribunal is closing in on the architects
of the mass killing of Muslim civilians during the 1992-95 Bosnian
war. For the past four and a half years, NATO troops have kept the
guns of Bosnia silent. But NATO has been hesitant to pursue the top
officials responsible for the slaughter, fearing reprisals or even
a renewal of ethnic warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Krajisnik was indicted by the tribunal earlier this year for a
grim list of atrocities. These include the expulsion of hundreds of
thousands of Muslims and Croats from some 40 villages and towns,
the massacre of hundreds of civilians, and criminal activities at
11 prison camps where Muslims and Croats were tortured and executed
on his orders. He is the highest-ranking wartime leader brought
before the tribunal, and his trial will lend added authority to the
court. During the war, Krajisnik was the second most powerful
political leader on the Bosnian Serb side, subordinate only to
President Radovan Karadzic, who has been indicted for many of the
same crimes but is still at large. Also indicted but still
uncaptured is Gen. Ratko Mladic, the Bosnian Serb military
commander.
</P>
<P>
   Bosnia now has perhaps its best chance since the Dayton
agreement to begin the difficult process of ethnic reconciliation.
Franjo Tudjman, the Croatian president who encouraged violent
separatism among Bosnia's Croats during the war and then worked to
undermine the federation between Croats and Muslims after the
peace, died late last year. His successors in Zagreb favor
constructive cooperation between Bosnian Croats and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the arrest of Krajisnik and others indicted for war
crimes rightly assigns accountability for the horrors of 1992-95 to
leading policy makers rather than to the entire Bosnian Serb
population. It may now be possible to arrest Karadzic and Mladic
without provoking a revival of ethnic conflict or exposing NATO
troops to retaliatory attacks. France's willingness to move against
indicted Bosnian Serbs _ Krajisnik was captured by French commandos
_ is especially encouraging. The risk to NATO forces must be
carefully weighed, but the alliance can serve the interests of
justice in Bosnia if it can arrest other indicted Bosnian Serb
leaders. &QL; 
(af)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 2355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
