<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON HOPES KOBE WILL COOL IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ When Kobe Bryant took a retaliatory swing at the
Knicks' Chris Childs on Sunday, Lakers coach Phil Jackson said it
was a ``natural reaction.'' But he also hopes Bryant's first career
fight will be his last for awhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times in any game, in any season, that players will
do this,'' Jackson said. ``Even Michael Jordan took a swing at
(Indiana's) Reggie Miller. God knows he deserved it, but it still
doesn't mean it's right. Or it still doesn't mean he could get away
with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this game, you get suspended. From that standpoint, with
the playoffs on our heels here and just a few games left in the
regular season, you've got to put your mind in a certain sense of,
`Hey, this could cost my team a game in the playoffs if I retaliate
like this.' It's a good reminder of how to keep your cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates saw Bryant's return fire as a good sign that the
21-year-old would stand up for himself and wasn't afraid to get
physical.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson, who lectured Shaquille O'Neal after he was
suspended earlier this season for fighting, made it clear that he
doesn't want to see a repeat performance from Bryant either ``No, I
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said defenders are grabbing him more lately. Jackson said
that's a response to the Lakers' league-best record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's not Kobe so much as every team wants to beat the
Lakers right now, because we're on a tear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to test on what level you'll play at, how far
you have to take (us) down to play at this level. So coaches are
probably animated, encouraging teams to get tough and play physical
and do all these things. So it's probably going to escalate from
here through the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   NO REST: Jackson confirmed that he's unlikely to place veteran
Ron Harper on the injured list, although he wouldn't rule it out
entirely. The combination of Bryant's suspension and Harper's
steady play of late made Jackson reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could do it (today) if we wanted to (when Bryant returns),
but we don't feel like as much that it's necessary, perhaps,
because the end result, the rhythm he's playing with, being in
stride, all those things, takes a player a couple games to get back
into (it),'' Jackson said. ``If a guy misses too many games, he
needs enough games to play to get back in speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Jackson will give Harper's tendinitis-stricken knees a
rest by cutting back his minutes and possibly holding him out of a
game or two once the Lakers clinch home-court advantage throughout
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He works very hard weight-wise, he knows what conditioning
level he has to stay at with his strength in his leg,'' Jackson
said. ``He's playing great. I think he just put a little burst on
because he thought he was going to have a couple days off.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-04-00 2358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
